<SLUG> BC-NY-BILLS-PASSED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY LAWMAKERS PASS DNA AND CLINIC BILLS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, New York _ The state Senate gave final legislative
approval to four major bills Thursday, including one that expands
the state's DNA database for tracking criminals and another that
increases penalties for blocking access to abortion clinics and for
stalking.
</P>
<P>
   The bills were passed by the Democratic-led Assembly in August
as its members rushed to adjourn a legislative session marked by
fierce partisanship. But by then, Republican leaders in the Senate
had broken off negotiations with Democrats and ordered their house
closed for the session. The Senate later agreed to return this
autumn to take up the measures.
</P>
<P>
   The other two bills adopted Thursday stiffen penalties for
making false bomb threats and allow the construction of power
plants in the state. All four measures now go to Gov. George
Pataki, who has said he will sign them into law.
</P>
<P>
   The DNA bill is considered the most far-reaching. It calls for
the collection of DNA ``fingerprints'' from people convicted of
many felonies. Just as fingerprints taken from criminals can be
matched to prints at crime scenes, a DNA database would allow law
enforcement officials to match blood, skin or hair samples found at
a crime scene against samples from convicted criminals in the
database.
</P>
<P>
   The state already collects DNA information, usually from a
saliva sample, from people convicted of certain violent crimes,
including sex crimes. The bill would expand the database, allowing
the state to gather samples from all violent felons and people
convicted of several other kinds of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Another major bill passed Thursday creates new criminal
penalties for blocking access to abortion clinics. The new law is
similar to federal legislation in that it makes it a crime to
harass or physically attack either abortion-clinic employees or
people seeking services from them. The state law, unlike the
federal version, can be enforced by local law officers, but it does
not allow victims of the prohibited activities to seek civil
damages in state courts against someone convicted of harassing or
attacking them.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic-access bill also includes a provision that does not
exist in the federal law, creating stiff penalties for the crime of
stalking. The measure was intended to provide victims, often women,
greater protection from harassment Another bill that the Senate
approved Thursday increases penalties for people convicted of
making false bomb threats to schools and other institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The other significant legislation passed Thursday allows for the
construction of power plants in the state for the first time in two
decades. Energy companies have begun applying to the state for
permission to build plants, mostly in the Hudson Valley. But
because of changes in federal law since then, no state agency
currently has the authority to issue permits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
