<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST ENCEPHALITIS DEATH IS REPORTED IN SUBURB OF NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ A 76-year-old Mineola woman has become the first
Long Island resident to die of the West Nile-like encephalitis
virus, Nassau County health officials announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, whose name was withheld because of patient
confidentiality, was one of two new cases of the virus reported on
Thursday by Nassau County officials, bringing the total to six.
There were also additional cases reported on Thursday in New York
City and Westchester County, and New Jersey officials reported the
first suspected case of the illness there.
</P>
<P>
   Officials could not say whether the Nassau woman, who died on
Oct. 4, contracted the virus here or in Queens, where most of the
cases have been reported. County Health Commissioner Kathleen A.
Gaffney said the new cases and the death of the Mineola resident
demonstrated the urgency with which the county needed to go forward
with its long-delayed plans to spray pesticide by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   The aerial spraying was to have begun last Friday, but it was
delayed by rain, cold, too much wind and a lawsuit. The suit was
rejected by the courts, but the rain, wind and cold have persisted,
blocking spraying efforts not only in Nassau County, but in Suffolk
and Westchester Counties and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials in New York City, where four people have died
of the virus, reported on Thursday that an additional case had been
confirmed, bringing the total for the city to 39, of which 27 were
in Queens, 9 in the Bronx, 2 in Manhattan and 1 in Brooklyn. That
latest case of the virus in the city was a 56-year-old woman from
Queens, who was said to had been released from a hospital in good
condition.
</P>
<P>
   An additional case, a woman in her 40s, was also reported on
Thursday in Westchester, where one person has died of the virus,
bringing the total number of cases in the county to nine, officials
said. As in other areas, officials said they hoped to resume
spraying on Friday and to continue through the weekend, weather
permitting.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, health officials said they were awaiting the
results of tests by the Centers For Disease Control and Prevention
to determine whether a resident of Lakewood had contracted the West
Nile-like encephalitis virus. The man is a patient at the Jersey
Shore Medical Center in Neptune, where a spokeswoman, Christine
Scott, said his condition was critical.
</P>
<P>
   If the cold, windy weather continues to inhibit spaying, there
is concern that enough mosquitoes now infected with the virus might
survive through the winter to enable the cycle to start again in
the spring. The mosquitoes could also continue to bite and feed on
birds, animals and people until most of the insects are killed by a
frost. Some, however, could survive the winter among warm damp
leaves in the underbrush, especially if it is a mild winter, health
officials have said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
