<SLUG> BC-BORDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER PATROL PLANS CRACKDOWN NEAR DOUGLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
The Immigration and Naturalization Service plans to launch a major
crackdown on illegal immigration in southeast Arizona during the
next few months, while at the same time easing travel restrictions
in the bor der zone.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The double-barreled program is to be announced Oct. 8 in Tucson,
where INS Commissioner Doris Meissner and Mexican Ambassador Jesus
Reyes Heroles will reveal broad proposals to improve safety and
commerce along the Arizona-Sonora frontier.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol will soon hit Douglas and Naco with Operation
Safeguard, an enforcement blanket that already covers most of the
U.S.-Mexico line, said Virginia Kice, an INS regional spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Border Patrol will use spotlights, fences,
sophisticated technology and extra agents to com bat the flood of
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mexican and U.S. au thorities plan to expand a
25-mile zone on both sides of the border. On the Arizona side, open
territory would extend 65 miles north to encompass Tucson. That
means for eign tourists, shoppers and business people visiting the
United States will not have to hassle with the paper work now
required.
</P>
<P>
   Kice said the idea is to create ``a border that works'' with
policies that promote commerce while preventing illegal
immigration. ``The border shouldn't divide us,'' she added. ``It
should bring us together.''
</P>
<P>
   The beefed-up enforcement _ simi lar to programs deployed in
Nogales _ drew mixed reviews from Douglas residents who have
complained for months that it is funneling illegal immigrants and
smugglers to Co chise County.
</P>
<P>
   During fiscal 1999, which ended last month, Border Patrol agents
from Nogales to New Mexico appre hended 470,449 undocumented immi
grants _ more than double the number picked up in 1995. &QL; 
Will it stem tide?
</P>
<P>
   ``They can line 'em up side-by-side from the Pacific to Del Rio,
Texas, and it's not going to stop the problem,'' said Douglas Mayor
Ray Borane, who was scheduled to meet with Meissner on Oct. 9.
``The problem is Mexico _ their economy and their poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of filling his town with uniformed agents, Borane said
the Clinton administration should pres sure Mexican authorities to
stop the immigrant-smuggling cartels and the corruption that thrive
in northern Sonora.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's making our town a militarized zone,'' Borane said of
Operation Safeguard.
</P>
<P>
   Thelma Vance, who lives about a mile from the border and
routinely watches groups of immigrants sneak past her home,
welcomes the federal crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything's worth a try,'' Vance said. ``They have to control
the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas residents met this year with congressional leaders and
held com munity meetings to bemoan the glut of immigrants, as well
as the trash and crime that comes with them. At the same time, many
worried about the danger faced by desperate illegal immigrants who
trek through deserts and mountains to avoid Border Patrol agents.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government began a gradual escalation of U.S.-Mexico
border enforcement about five years ago when Mexico's economy bot
tomed out, leading to a dramatic rise in illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Agents swarmed to El Paso and San Diego first, building fences
and using helicopters to stem the tide of immigrants. Those efforts
moved many of the migrants, and smug glers, to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Border Patrol launched Operation Safeguard in
Nogales, trying to blockade illegal immigra tion there. The result:
a dramatic rise in apprehensions, followed by an other shift of
economic refugees and ``coyotes'' _ smugglers of illegal immigrants
_ into the Naco-Doug las area.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with limited forces, the Border Patrol made 202,868
appre hensions in Douglas _ four times the number in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Gavin, an INS spokeswoman, said Cochise County is one of
the last gaps in the enforcement wall. ``We're closing down on
it,'' she added. &QL; 
Boosting border business
</P>
<P>
   Kice said the expanded visitor zone _ which begins Dec. 1 _ will
allow Mexicans with border crossing cards to visit Tucson for up to
72 hours without filing registration forms. It will be employed as
a one-year experiment, and affects only entrants via U.S. ports at
Nogales, Douglas, Naco and Sasabe.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Echols, a research assistant with the Tucson City Manager's
Office, said officials expect a mini-boon in tourism _ estimated at
more than $53 million a year. She noted that more than 500,000 Mexi
cans from Sonora and Sinaloa have border crossing cards.
</P>
<P>
   The new visitor zone is not expected to affect Border Patrol
enforcement, Kice said, and will not require checkpoints to be
closed or moved.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.S. citizens would also be allowed to travel farther
south into Mexico without going through customs or filling out
visitor registra tion forms.
</P>
<P>
   When Meissner and Reyes Heroles announce the new policies this
after noon, they are to be accompanied by Gus de la Vina, chief of
the Border Patrol; Johnny Williams, western regional director of
the INS; and David Aguilar, Tucson's Border Pa trol chief.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 9, Meissner is expected to visit the border in Douglas
and Naco, touring facilities and meeting with residents. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
