<HEADER>
A0385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT     10-08 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE KEEPS YANKEES IN CONTROL OF RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Yankees may not own the Texas Rangers,
but they seem to have a seasonal rental agreement. Every October,
the Yankees use the Rangers for playoff fodder.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte and two relievers became the latest pitchers to
shackle the Rangers, as the Yankees defeated Texas, 3-1, at Yankee
Stadium Thursday night in Game 2 of the American League division
series.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who have scored two runs in their last 51 playoff
innings against the Yankees, now return home for Game 3 and _ they
hope _ Game 4 on Saturday and Sunday, and on those days the Yankees
are scheduled to start pitchers with 427 career victories combined,
Roger Clemens and David Cone, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers led, 1-0, in the fifth, had runners at second and
third and nobody out. But Pettitte turned the game around there,
retiring the next three hitters and holding the runners in place,
and then in the bottom half of the fifth inning, Scott Brosius
doubled home Tino Martinez with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez walked with one out in the seventh. And with Texas' Lee
Stevens holding Martinez at first, Chili Davis skipped a ground
ball through the first-base hole, Martinez moving to third. It was
at this point that the Rangers' lack of left-handed relievers hurt
them.
</P>
<P>
   With the left-handed-hitting Ricky Ledee coming to bat and Texas
manager Johnny Oates intent on saving his one good left-hander,
Mike Venafro, for the likes of Paul O'Neill, weary starter Rick
Helling stayed in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee capitalized, dumping a double between the outfielders in
center and right, Martinez scoring the go-ahead run. Tim Crabtree
relieved Helling at that point and shut down the Yankees' rally
without more runs scoring, but the Yankees had what they needed in
their eighth consecutive playoff victory against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored their last run in the eighth, when Venafro
walked Jim Leyritz with the bases loaded to force home a run.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte allowed just the one run in 7 1-3 innings, striking out
five.
</P>
<P>
   T-shirts and shorts have given way to jackets and sweaters at
Yankee Stadium. The temperature dipped to 47 degrees by game time
and players on both teams were warming their bare hands between
pitches, Pettitte blowing on his clenched fist as he looked in for
the sign, Chuck Knoblauch stuffing his right hand into the back
right pocket of his pants.
</P>
<P>
   But Helling, of Fargo, N.D., took the mound in short sleeves;
the temperature was well above freezing, after all, and Helling
looked entirely comfortable, his approach simple. He threw
fastballs. Lots and lots of fastballs. High fastballs and low
fastballs, and every once in a while, he would bounce in a
curveball, just to be different.
</P>
<P>
   In midsummer _ when fans were wearing T-shirts and shorts _ he
might have got in trouble, but with the cold exacerbated by a
swirling wind, fly balls were not carrying well. Brosius smashed a
high fastball to straightaway center and the air seemed to freeze
the ball, which Roberto Kelly caught 50 feet or so short of the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi, the next batter, tomahawked a fastball toward the
wall in left. It appeared as if Girardi had hit just his third home
run of the season. But the ball settled in the mitt of left fielder
Rusty Greer well in front of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good night for pitchers to challenge hitters, and this
is what Helling did, and he retired the first 10 batters he faced,
throwing fastballs with 41 of his first 44 pitches, striking out
five. Derek Jeter was the first Yankees base runner, in the fourth,
when he doubled with one out.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were a little tougher on Pettitte. Rafael Palmeiro
and Todd Zeile hit singles to open the second inning before
Pettitte struck out Kelly with high fastballs and Stevens hit into
a double play. But in the fourth inning, Juan Gonzalez reached far
across the plate for a fastball _ low and outside, a great pitch _
and pulled a line drive into the left-field stands. With that, the
Rangers took a 1-0 lead and ended their streak of 25 consecutive
scoreless playoff innings against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly singled to center leading off the fifth and Stevens
bounced a double into the stands, a break for the Yankees. Kelly
would probably have scored if the ball had skipped low off the
wall, but the ground-rule double forced Kelly to stop at third.
Texas had second and third and nobody out. Ramiro Mendoza, a
right-hander, warmed up hurriedly in the Yankees' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching deliberately, Pettitte fell behind Mark McLemore, three
balls and one strike, and he might have been one pitch away from
being yanked. The switch-hitting McLemore, after all, had batted
.163 as a right-handed batter, and walking him would have been a
crime. But Pettitte threw a strike, then flipped a breaking ball
off the outside corner _ and McLemore, in a classic example of the
Rangers' reckless aggressiveness, swung and missed. One out.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte fell behind to Royce Clayton, two balls and no strikes,
the crowd murmuring tensely. Helling was pitching wonderfully, and
preventing the Rangers from scoring any more runs seemed
imperative.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte fired a strike, came back with another low fastball,
and Clayton topped a grounder to Brosius. The runners had to hold
as Brosius threw to first. Two out.
</P>
<P>
   Now Pettitte had to deal with Greer, who fouled off two pitches,
running the count full. Pettitte breathed warmth into his left
hand, looked for the sign: breaking ball. He spun the curveball
into the dirt, Greer flailed wildly and missed. Pettitte whirled on
the mound and pumped a fist, overcome by emotion. He and the
Yankees had escaped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
