u a BC-OBIT-GRAAFF-NYT &LR;      10-08 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GRAAFF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE VILLIERS GRAAFF, 85, EX-LEADER OF SOUTH AFRICAN CENTRIST
OPPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIC PACE   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sir de Villiers Graaff, who led South Africa's weak and troubled
parliamentary opposition for two decades during the apartheid era,
died Oct. 4 at his farm outside Cape Town. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Graaff, who was nicknamed ``Sir Div'' and ``Div,'' had an
``impeccable Afrikaner background,'' as The Daily Telegraph put it
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A burly six-footer, he succeeded to his baronetcy in 1931 after
the death of his father, Sir David Graaff, a well-to-do businessman
who had been made a baronet by King George V for his services in
helping to form the Union of South Africa, which was created in
1911. The family surname is pronounced ``grahf.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir de Villiers studied at Cape Town University and Oxford,
became a lawyer in South Africa and was decorated for his military
service in World War II. He was a member of South Africa's
Parliament from 1948 to 1977, representing a constituency in Cape
Town for most of that time.
</P>
<P>
   From 1956 to 1977 he was the leader of the centrist United
Party, the official opposition in the all-white Parliament, which
was dominated by the National Party of John Vorster, who was prime
minister from 1966 to 1978.
</P>
<P>
   But as The Cape Times put it, ``The bare facts'' of Graaff's
``career as leader of the opposition offer little encouragement to
the most admiring biographer.''
</P>
<P>
   In that role, he condemned the National Party's program of
forcing blacks by the millions into enclaves called homelands.
Still, as The Times of London reported, ``He upheld racial
segregation and white supremacy.'' And after the Sharpeville
massacre of 1960, he came out in favor of the government's steps to
ban the African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped down as the United Party's leader in June 1977, and
the party was dissolved after years of decline. By then the number
of seats it held in the Parliament had dwindled to only 24, from 41
in 1974, after defections to the left and the right. By June 1977
the party had split four times and had been defeated in five
general elections.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure as leader, he got mixed reviews in South
Africa. David Welsh, senior lecturer in African government and law
at the University of Cape Town, wrote in a 1975 book that Graaff
had ``shown strength and resilience in riding out storms within the
party, but he has come under fire from left and right for
equivocation and ambivalence.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, nearly five years after South Africa's exit from the
British Commonwealth, National Party members had great fun asking
why Graaff had not renounced his baronetcy. The Times of London on
Thursday reported that the baronetcy would pass to Graaff's elder
son, David, unless that son disclaimed it.
</P>
<P>
   Graaff is also survived by his wife of 60 years, the former
Helena Voigt; another son, and a daughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
