<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WIN OR LOSE, ONCE AGAIN, YANKS RULE PRIME TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is easy to tell a Mets fan this week _ the one
looking like a tropical fish, with expressionless eyes and a gaping
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Quite sadistically, baseball is turning them into guppies, what
with its staggered and staggering late games.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, you say, that's what Mets fans look like normally. That's
cold. You must be a Yankee fan.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, those darlings of the ratings, are two-time
champions and deserve their place in the choice television hour of
8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, they beat Texas, 3-1, to open up a two-game
advantage in this short series. Young fans were surely sent to bed
before the end, but at least adult fans had a crack at watching
Jeff Nelson and Mariano Rivera save the victory for the gallant
Andy Pettitte in the late innings, the right of every baseball fan.
</P>
<P>
   For cruel and unusual punishment, however, baseball really must
have it in for Mets' fans, putting games on after 11 p.m. on
Tuesday and Wednesday nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great watching baseball, especially when you know every
game is so important,'' said Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, who
said he stayed up to watch the Mets' 7-1 loss Wednesday night _
``right to the bitter end,'' rooting for Todd Stottlemyre, the
winning pitcher and son of Torre's pitching coach, Mel Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know every player talks about it, and I know my staff
watches,'' Torre said of the television exposure. ``It's fun
watching it because you know everybody's going to watch us
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The players are entertainers, and love to know they are being
watched by their peers as well as their fans. But Mets fans were
treated callously in their first post-season games since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were back home on Thursday on an alleged off day,
trying to catch up on their sleep after an overnight run to
Cincinnati, followed by two games in Arizona, followed by a
daylight landing in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes make these cross-country flights all the time, and
their charter flights are not as crowded as the coach torture
chambers the average flier must endure.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are not going to have a lot of sympathy for million-dollar
entertainers, but fans should not be surprised to see athletes
stumble around after playing so late in the West and then rushing
back East.
</P>
<P>
   The networks rationalize the late, late games by saying that the
Yankees deserve star billing, but Bud Selig and his cohorts long
ago sold out any pretension of integrity in regard to the networks.
</P>
<P>
   The fans support the team all year, buying expensive tickets,
splurging on all the trendy junk baseball markets, and just plain
caring about these guys, and then baseball turns around and says,
``The heck with you people, we're putting other games on in the
late afternoon and evening. If you want to watch the Mets, take a
nap and stay up late.''
</P>
<P>
   How contemptuous. Baseball is trying to serve two masters here _
the networks, and the calendar. By squeezing in three rounds of
playoffs, baseball is already defying the laws of nature that
dictate it is going to get colder and colder as this month drags
on.
</P>
<P>
   The weird thing about going to a third round is that baseball
officials have this morbid fear of playing a World Series game in
November. This year, the seventh game of the World Series would be
held on Oct. 31 _ Halloween. Those won't be fright masks you will
see. Those will be the faces of hitters jammed on the fists with
fastballs in 30-degree weather.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there was the totally ridiculous situation of the
Yankees having a day off on Wednesday in crisp early October
weather. This was to avoid saturating the airwaves, what with games
in Atlanta after 4 p.m., Cleveland after 8 p.m. and Arizona after
11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   They could not have moved up each game by an hour or two? So
what if Arizona fans had to get to the ball park by 5 or 6 p.m.?
What else do they have to do in Phoenix?
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry Colangelo, the Diamondbacks' owner, wanted two games
in prime time in the Pacific time zone _ so where's the ocean? _
and Jerry Colangelo got them. Nice to know who's got clout in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the late starts worse is the plodding pace of the
games. Including Thursday night, the first eight games of the
playoffs ran an average of eight minutes longer than baseball's own
record-setting trudge of 2 hours 53 minutes for the past season.
</P>
<P>
   The starting times should have been adjusted. All it would have
taken was respect for the loyal Mets' fans. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 0026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-CLINTON-1STLD-WRIT     10-08 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT SETS BRISK PACE IN NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS 10th, 11th grafs with Clinton quote; ADDS amount of money
made in fund-raiser in 14th graf.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 47 of Clinton shaking hands with James P.
Hoffa is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY and STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton came to New York Thursday to pay
tribute to two political constituencies that had proved central to
his electoral success _ labor unions and gay rights advocates _ and
now loom as critical to the political future of Clinton's wife and
his vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of two hours, and in the space of two city blocks,
Clinton spoke at a dinner in honor of James P. Hoffa, the president
of the teamsters' union, and moved on to a fund-raiser for New
York's most prominent gay rights group, the Empire State Pride
Agenda. In both places, Clinton drew an exuberant reaction from
audiences that have, as often as not, been viewed as a political
liability by candidates and officeholders over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for making New York the biggest, strongest union
city in America,'' Clinton declared to the cheers of labor leaders.
And when Clinton mentioned the guest of honor's name, he was
overwhelmed by shouts of ``Hoffa, Hoffa, Hoffa!''
</P>
<P>
   Labor and gay rights organizations have proved to be reliable
parts of Clinton's political base. But given the extent to which
those groups have been the subject of Republican attack over the
past 10 years, Clinton's appearances suggest the freedom he feels
as he approaches the end of his second term, and his evident
interest in helping Vice President Al Gore, who is running for
president, and Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is all but running for
the Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton left the dinner, Hoffa told the audience, ``I got
a good idea speaking to the president: Why don't we all get
together and back Hillary Clinton as senator for the state of New
York?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance at the Hilton Hotel at the tribute to Hoffa
was the first time that a president had appeared so publicly with
the much investigated teamsters' union since Franklin D. Roosevelt
spoke at one of its conventions more than 50 years ago. Clinton
drew cheers from the audience as he shook hands with Hoffa, who has
been a leading opponent of an immediate endorsement of Gore in the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that I wanted to do when the vice president
and I came into office was to change the way that America thought
about labor,'' Clinton said. ``I was so sick and tired of more than
a decade of people trying to make unions the whipping boy of
whatever it was that was wrong with America.''
</P>
<P>
   One issue of particular concern to his labor audience was the
North American Free Trade Agreement and its call to allow Mexican
trucks to drive freely in the United States. Clinton indicated that
he shared their concern because American officials have found that
two-thirds of Mexican trucks are not safe.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Clinton moved a block west to the annual dinner of
the Empire State Pride Agenda at the Sheraton. Clinton is one of
several candidates who have, over the years, turned to gay rights
organizations for campaign contributions. But in this case, the
president was the draw rather than beneficiary of a dinner that
organizers said would raise $1 million for lobbying and political
candidates sympathetic to gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   He was escorted to the stage by Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y. to
a three-minute standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am indebted to you because I happened to be president and
seek this job at a time when you are raising these issues, and you
gave me a chance to make a contribution,'' Clinton said. ``You made
me a better president and you made me a better person.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech to the Empire State Pride Agenda was his third
appearance as president in a public setting before a gay rights
group. His attendance was testimony to the growing influence of gay
voters in New York elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``At our second annual dinner, we were wondering if David
Dinkins would show up,'' said Jeff Sorof, the co-chairman of the
organization, referring to New York's former mayor. ``This is quite
a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also did what he typically does on his frequent visits
to New York: raise money for the Democratic Party. In this case, he
was the featured speaker at a $500,000 fund-raiser Thursday for the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The president appeared in New York alone. Mrs. Clinton was in
Italy. Gore was in New York, but he and Clinton did not cross
paths.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton attended the dinner for Hoffa just four days before the
AFL-CIO, which includes the teamsters, holds a convention in Los
Angeles, where several union leaders are urging an endorsement of
Gore over Bill Bradley, the former senator from New Jersey. It is
far from certain that Gore's supporters can command the two-thirds
majority needed to endorse him.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa has urged other labor leaders to hold off on an
endorsement to see whether the administration will give assurances
on trade barriers and other matters. Among Hoffa's concerns is
persuading the government to end its decade-long supervision of the
union, which has been imposed to end corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner was sponsored by the Labor Research Association, a
consulting group that advises unions. For decades, presidents have
shied away from the union because of its history of corruption. But
federal officials said that the 1.4 million-member union is
significantly cleaner after a decade of supervision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 0029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-LEDEE-NYT &LR;      10-08 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-LEDEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: LEDEE TAKES TORRE'S WORDS TO HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS.: this story, eliminated earlier, is now restored)  
 (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ricky Ledee was a few feet from Joe Torre when the
manager gathered the Yankees together in the clubhouse before the
division series against the Texas Rangers started Tuesday. Torre
reminded his players to appreciate where they were. Torre rarely
raises his voice, but his soothing words are powerful words. Ledee
listened closely.
</P>
<P>
   Torre pointed to Derek Jeter and mentioned how the 25-year-old
shortstop had been on five straight post-season teams and reminded
everyone that Jeter's wonderful journey had been abnormal. Just
study my career, Torre said. It took Torre 32 years as a player and
a manager to be involved in his first World Series game, so he
knows how to describe exasperation in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Joe said really made me think,'' Ledee said. ``I wasn't
even supposed to be on the team last year and look what happened.
You have to enjoy this, but you can't expect it's going to happen
every year. That's what Joe was trying to tell us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee heard Torre's words and appreciated Thursday night even
more after he looped a double into right-center field off Rick
Helling in the seventh inning to break a 1-1 tie and help the
Yankees defeat the Rangers, 3-1, and take a 2-0 lead in the
three-of-five-game series. Ledee's hit symbolized the differences
between the Yankees, who expect to beat Texas, and the Rangers, who
expect to succumb to New York and did for the eighth straight time.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know why the Yankees smacked the Rangers again
Thursday night and basically turned their weekend in Arlington,
Texas, into a formality, find a videotape of the game and watch the
fifth and eighth innings. Those two innings aptly explain why the
Rangers were the Washington Generals and the Yankees were the
Globetrotters. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte wriggled through a jam with runners on second and
third with no outs to keep the Yankees' deficit at 1-0 in the top
of the fifth. In the bottom of the fifth, the Yankees tied the
score when Scott Brosius lined a double off the left-field fence to
score Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was not that simple. Rusty Greer, who lost Ledee's
liner in the lights in the opener, played Brosius' blast as if he
were a skateboarder trying for degree of difficulty points. Greer
rushed back to the warning track, lost sight of the ball, then
climbed the wall and flung his glove toward where he thought the
ball might be. He missed it by a foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so tough to play out there,'' said Ledee, the Yankees'
left fielder. ``You're always looking into the lights and trying to
find the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Rangers are about to have their season ended by
the Yanks for the third time in the last four seasons. Ledee, who
was a World Series hero with two months of major league service
last season, will continue scooting along with the Yankees. Like
Jeter, Ledee is the anti-Torre in October.
</P>
<P>
   After striking out in his first two at-bats against Helling,
Ledee calmly batted with runners on first and third in the eighth.
He roped a 2-2 pitch down the right-field line that tailed to the
right of the foul pole and missed being a three-run homer by about
10 feet. But Ledee exhaled and came back with a huge double that
dropped between Roberto Kelly and Juan Gonzalez, who both
approached the ball lackadaisically.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee listened to Torre before Game 1 and again after the
Yankees beat the Rangers, 8-0. Torre announced an optional workout
Wednesday but told Ledee it was not optional for him. Ledee knew
why.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Yankees played the Cleveland Indians in Game 6 of the
American League Championship Series last October, Torre held an
optional workout at Yankee Stadium. It is supposed to be an option
for veterans like Paul O'Neill, but Ledee recalled how Shane
Spencer missed the workout and Torre seemed upset.
</P>
<P>
   Torre asked Ledee if he had seen Spencer and Ledee shrugged. The
manager told Ledee, who had not started any post-season games, that
he would start in left field in Game 6. Ledee said he asked Torre
if he was starting because he was perturbed with Spencer and Torre
said, ``I don't know'' and walked away. The strategy worked as
Ledee went 6 for 10 with four runs batted in against San Diego,
remembering each word Torre uttered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Ledee said, ``I still don't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is still a fan inside Ledee, which is why he initiated a
discussion about the possibility of a Subway Series and said he
would love to play the Mets. He wore his Mets' T-shirt around
Salinas, P.R., until it became thinner then a paper towel. Without
provocation, Ledee reeled off the names of the 1986 Mets and said
he rooted for them because ``they were the team of the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was mentioned to Ledee that he is part of the current
team of the moment, he remained silent for a few seconds. Ledee
pondered the description of the Yankees and said: ``I guess we are.
We should appreciate this.'' And he meant it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
