<HEADLINE>
HACKETT FLOATS ARIZONA QB RUMOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Arizona has done its best to avoid a quarterback
controversy by alternating Keith Smith and Ortege Jenkins, so USC
coach Paul Hackett injected himself into the situation Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big rumor is they're going to play one guy,'' Hackett
said. ``They're going with (Smith).''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett didn't say where he heard the rumor, but relished the
idea that the Wildcats would play only one quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great. It will disrupt the team,'' Hackett said.
``Half of the guys will be upset.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether any of it was true was dubious. The rumor to go with
one quarterback certainly hadn't reached Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Thursday night, Jenkins said he had not heard of any
change at the quarterback position, and that Wildcats coach Dick
Tomey never announces any decisions before the team meets at its
hotel on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky No.8: Someone in the USC secondary will have the
unenviable task of defending Arizona wide receiver Dennis
Northcutt, who has had a pair of 10-reception games and has 38
catches in five games. He is one of the leading candidates for the
Biletnikoff Award, which goes to the nation's top receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of placing one cornerback on Northcutt, however, USC
will stay in its normal defense. Northcutt will be defended by
whomever's side he lines up on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to play on Sundays,'' cornerback Kris
Richard said. ``He's going to be a challenge for us. A lot of the
offense is geared toward him. We're prepared for them to go to him
no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Secondary coach Dennis Thurman said that for the second straight
week, true freshmen Darrell Rideaux and Kevin Arbet will be part of
the regular rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not afraid to play them,'' Thurman said.
</P>
<P>
   Rideaux and Arbet have moved ahead of senior Tanqueray Clark and
sophomore Eric Reese on the depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Precautionary measure: USC has hired a communications specialist
to take to Tucson and make sure there are no problems with the
headphones after they malfunctioned last week against Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've hired a whole team of people,'' Hackett joked. ``We're
going to need two vans to take everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill out: Sophomore safety DeShaun Hill will not make the trip
after experiencing problems with his back. Defensive tackle Ryan
Nielsen rested Thursday but is OK.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Windrell Hayes continued to make strides in
practice and should be near 100 percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher to tailback? It appears sophomore Miguel Fletcher of
Alemany High may be going back to tailback after playing most of
last season at cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher has been operating at tailback for several weeks on the
scout team.
</P>
<P>
   The white stuff: With a 12:30 p.m. kickoff and an expected
temperature of 95 degrees, USC will be fortunate to wear its white
road jerseys. Arizona will wear its navy blue jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, there's the edge,'' Hackett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
