<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ERICKSON, CORVALLIS BEST STOP AFTER FORGETTABLE SEATTLE
TENURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Dennis Erickson was a little testy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have time to talk about that,'' the Oregon State coach
said, responding to a reporter's press conference question Monday
about his time in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson was on a conference call from Corvallis, where the
Huskies play the Beavers Saturday but enough ice came through the
wires to put out a navigation warning to boats on Lake Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis, Dennis, Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   Folks here are OK with you.
</P>
<P>
   Calm down. No need to feel defensive.
</P>
<P>
   True, it wasn't a storybook departure last December, getting
fired with a year left on your contract as Seahawks coach. But even
though the decision was justifiable, your major flaw merely was
having mediocre results (OK, one other thing, but what's a DUI
among friends?).
</P>
<P>
   But as you and your 'bro from Snoho, Jim Lambright, discovered
two days later, mediocre just doesn't cut it anymore in these
parts. This is Microsoftburg, and if you're not out trampling the
world, you will be trampled.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Seahawks and Huskies went out in one week and
spent more on football coaching than China spends on birth control
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Scoreboard, baby.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the tepid record, Dennis, there was also the law of
averages. Having hightailed it out of four previous jobs (Idaho,
Wyoming, Washington State and Miami), it was only a matter of time
before a job beat you out the door.
</P>
<P>
   But that's nothing to feel bad about, particularly since it was
an NFL job. Lots of college coaches get sideways in the pros,
compared to the few (such as Jimmy Johnson and Tom Coughlin) who
thrive.
</P>
<P>
   The problem often seems to be one of command presence. Erickson
didn't have much of one.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the sole reason for success in the NFL. But after
observing the demeanor of Mike Holmgren, as well as his most
successful Seahawks predecessor, Chuck Knox, not to mention NFL
stalwarts Bill Parcells, Mike Shanahan, Bill Cowher, Bill Walsh and
others, the words of one Seahawks player rang true:
</P>
<P>
   ``He never seemed comfortable here, never seemed in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   After a long career spent in college coaching, Erickson moved to
the Seahawks expecting that the players would be men, and therefore
disciplined, self-motivated, organized and responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   The main difference between pro football players and college
football players is the pros have million-dollar contracts that
give them the incorrect impression that they are more bulletproof
than James Bond.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, it takes a formidable, Goldfinger-like personality to
hose that idea. Erickson was a little too deferential, failing to
treat his players as the overgrown youngsters they often are.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Erickson had some reasons for never getting his,
pardon the expression, Behrings.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise nearly took away the primary reason for accepting
the Seahawk job _ its Seattle address. The relocation travail
screwed up his first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Although Paul Allen ended that, the franchise sale brought in
president Bob Whitsitt, who regarded Erickson as overmatched. His
ouster was plotted for most of two years before the come-from-ahead
flop last season made it easy.
</P>
<P>
   But Erickson's career crisis lasted all of two weeks. Although
many were surprised that he would allow himself to fall from the
NFL to Corvallis _ a distance previously covered only by NASA
spacecraft _ it was the ideal fit.
</P>
<P>
   College kids are typically intimidated by the head coach, who
has total control. The mere weight of the office gives Erickson all
the authority he needs.
</P>
<P>
   At Oregon State, he has a program more like his first three
head-coaching jobs _ on the fringe, dripping with despair. Because
of his success, the Beavers never cared that his fourth coaching
stop ended with the NCAA federales chasing him out of Miami, nor
that Cougars fans still haven't forgiven him for his 1988 walkout
the residue of which included a team grade-point average of 1.94.
</P>
<P>
   He won national championships with the Hurricanes in 1989 and
1991. Those rings are all the dazzled Beavers need to see. As they
say in Corvallis these days: There's nothing wrong with probation
that a bowl-game appearance can't fix.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview before OSU's game last week against USC,
Erickson admitted the Seahawks job was a mistake for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to do it over again,'' he said, ``I probably wouldn't
have taken the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. The Seahawks might say the same thing about their
coaching offer. Then again, he never failed to keep Joey Galloway
happy, never traded Shawn Kemp for Vin Baker, never blew an
eighth-inning lead and didn't recruit Huskies during a quiet
period.
</P>
<P>
   His time here wasn't so bad. Nor was it especially good.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to stay mad at a beige wall. Sort of welcome back,
Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8009
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
