<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ERICKSON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE, ERICKSON SHINE ON OREGON STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. _ It's Thursday morning and, fittingly, the sun
is trying to break through the clouds and shine on the football
program at Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   For the longest time, anguish was the only thing that hung in
the air here. Saturday it will be replaced by optimism and
enthusiasm as well as orange and black balloons rising from the Van
Buren bridge and parking meters along Fourth Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon State Beavers are 3-1 and have Dennis Erickson as
their leader, which means they also have hope.
</P>
<P>
   stars
</P>
<P>
   At the Big O restaurant on the corner of Fourth and Adams
streets, Floyd Hutchins has just polished off his daily muffin
while continuing to drain another cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock to us,'' Hutchins says, referring to the hiring
of Erickson last January. ``We never expected anybody of that
stature.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big O is where you will find pancakes and omelettes and true
Beavers believers. If you stop in Saturday before the game against
Washington, most of the waitresses will be in orange and black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for Margie,'' says Sharon Stewart, who has been here
since 1990. ``She's blonde and says it doesn't match her
complexion.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart whips out her scrapbook, which features a picture of
seven Beavers piling onto the Oregon ball carrier, Ricky Whittle,
during the 1994 Civil War. Naturally, however, Oregon State lost
that game, 17-13.
</P>
<P>
   If you're talking about the Beavers, Stewart wants to be in the
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Erickson,'' she says. ``The electricity he ignites in
the team is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart goes on in detail about her favorite Beavers
paraphernalia, which includes a big orange parka and a pin that
shows a Beaver choking a Duck.
</P>
<P>
   Then she refers to Jess Lewis, explaining his impact on one of
Oregon States most memorable games, a 3-0 victory over USC in the
mud in Parker Stadium in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the man,'' Stewart says. ``He is the man.''
</P>
<P>
   stars
</P>
<P>
   Jess Lewis is the man, all right, a very big man. He is
currently driving a white Dodge van, pulling a trailer with two
workers who are putting out garbage cans at Reser Stadium in
preparation for Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a black Oregon State football sweatshirt, Lewis gets out
of the van and relates what the Beavers' resurgence has meant to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been fun,'' he says. ``A lot of people hadn't given up on
Oregon State. But you can only take so many hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was the defensive lineman in 1967 who made a game-saving
tackle on O.J. Simpson after the Juice had broken free.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are different versions of that story,'' Lewis says. ``I
was playing against Ron Yary, and he had me blown off the line so
far, all I had to do was fall in front of O.J. and he tripped over
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis went on to play professionally with the Houston Oilers,
New Orleans Saints and Winnipeg Blue Bombers. He developed an
addiction to metha-amphetamines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a recovering drug addict,'' he admits. ``I've been 10
years clean and sober.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to handling operational duties around Reser Stadium,
Lewis counsels student athletes and teaches a health class called
Drugs in Sports. Growing up in nearby Aumsville, he has come back
to give back, and now the Beavers are rewarding Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is real exciting,'' he says. ``We needed some change to
make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   All around him, change is evident. The Valley Football Center
houses a weight room and state-of-the-art coach. Reser Stadium has
a new artificial surface.
</P>
<P>
   He points to the softball field where an indoor practice
facility will start being constructed in January. In another
direction are 900 orange parking curbs with nameplates for donors
and other Very Important Beavers.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares to field another call on his cell phone, Lewis
says: ``I love this place.''
</P>
<P>
   stars
</P>
<P>
   Outside Gill Coliseum, Dee Andros is waiting for his ride to an
Oregon Hall of Fame luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Just behind him is the ramp that Andros used to run down,
leading the Beavers onto the field. His big orange outfit and ample
frame prompted sportswriter Harry Missildine to call Andros ``The
Great Pumpkin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it,'' Andros says. ``People didn't know who Dee Andros
was, but they knew who The Great Pumpkin was.''
</P>
<P>
   They knew who the Beavers were, too. Andros coached during the
Beavers' glory years, the 1960s, a decade in which Oregon State
never had a losing season and went to the Rose Bowl in 1964. He
also coached in the '70s, when all of the awful began.
</P>
<P>
   For 28 consecutive years, the Beavers have been losers. Decades,
coaches, time _ they all changed, but the Beavers never have. Until
now, after Mike Riley lit the match and Erickson stoked the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we made the announcement of Denny, it gave us
instant recognition,'' Andros says. ``I've never seen spirit any
higher than it is right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides having an energetic new coach, Andros says facilities
are the key to building and sustaining a winning program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't mean that much when I was having my heyday,'' he
says. ``In 1974, I had a great athlete (recruit) come in here who
said: ``Coach, I think the world of you and your town, but we have
better facilities at my high school.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Beaver booster Bert Babb drives up in his Lincoln Town Car and
Andros hops in. Babb was at that game in '67, sitting six seats
away from California Governor Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``With about three or four minutes left, he walked out,'' Babb
says. ``Everybody was really giving him the raspberries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have fun in those days,'' Andros says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have fun again,'' Babb replies.
</P>
<P>
   stars
</P>
<P>
   At practice Thursday afternoon, Erickson runs the Beavers
through a series of drills, looking fit and ready himself in his
black hat, black top and black shorts.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't talking today, having already spoken earlier this week
about Seattle, Seattle, Seattle and the Seahawks, Seahawks,
Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   So everyone else talked about the coach's state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to win,'' says his mother, Mary, from her home in
Everett. ``I know he tries hard. He seems to be happy now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen Dennis happier,'' says offensive coordinator
Tim Lappano. ``To go from where you weren't wanted to where you
are, well, it does a man good.''
</P>
<P>
   But will he stay? Signs say yes. Erickson bought a
half-a-million-dollar home in the Lewisburg Hills overlooking the
Willamette Valley and put $100,000 of improvements into it.
</P>
<P>
   On his way home, athletic director Mitch Barnhart offers his own
opinion on the car phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me: `I'm a Northwest guy and I want to stay in the
Northwest. I also want to put my signature on a program,'''
Barnhart said. ``There is no better story in college football than
Oregon State getting this thing turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Erickson, Barnhart has had a major influence on Oregon
State athletics. He is marketing the teams and finding big
supporters like Al and Pat Reser, renaming Parker Stadium after
receiving a $5 million donation.
</P>
<P>
   He raised ticket prices, wanting to ``create value to the
program,'' believing people should pay more to watch the Beavers
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That told the student athletes it was worthwhile for them to
be trying,'' Barnhart says.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the Andros era, Oregon State drew 12,803 fans for
its game against Stanford in 1975. Nearly that many fans traveled
to Oregon State's first game this year at Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Reser Stadium has not been sold out for a non-Civil War game
since 1984 against Washington. Every seat will be taken Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart also helped introduce ``Fan Fair,'' which precedes
every Beavers home game on Parker Plaza. It's a family event with
games, structured to appeal to youngsters who eventually will make
up the new fan base.
</P>
<P>
   Apathy can't be found in Corvallis anymore. Most of the
rejuvenation is credited to the man in the black outfit who was
unacceptable in Seattle before being embraced here.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Bowl anyone?
</P>
<P>
   ``This place would be rocking,'' says Stewart back at the Big O.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are just waiting,'' Lewis says. ``He's the kind of guy
who can make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Moore can be reached at 206-448-8013
</P>
<P>
   or jimmoore &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 0043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
