<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS MAY BE TARGETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ In a fluke bit of scheduling, ring announcer Michael
Buffer will introduce the Mighty Ducks before tonight's home opener
against Dallas at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   After the events of last Saturday's season opener in Dallas,
which resulted in the suspension of Ducks Ruslan Salei, Pascal
Trepanier and Jim McKenzie, and the verbal response of the Stars,
Don King might have promoted the game as Blood Feud III.
</P>
<P>
   Teemu Selanne says he understands Dallas' emotional reaction to
the injuries to Mike Modano and Darryl Sydor, but he doesn't think
the two teams are getting ready to rumble.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne, along with Paul Kariya, could be a target if the Stars
are looking for revenge, but the winger believes calmer heads will
prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be just another game,'' said Selanne, who took
a vicious elbow from former Dallas defenseman Craig Ludwig that led
to a wild brawl late in the 1997-98 season. ``The league will have
its eye on it. If guys do anything stupid, they are going to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock and winger Brett Hull have been
outspoken about the Ducks' perceived dirty play, and Anaheim coach
Craig Hartsburg has made it clear that's hardly the reputation his
team wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be known as a team that's hard to play against,''
he said. ``But we don't want to be known as a cheap or dirty team.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even former Ducks defenseman Jamie Pushor, now a member of
the Stars, took a shot at his ex-teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what kind of message they were trying to send,''
he told a Dallas newspaper. ``(But) it's not going to scare us. To
me, it was just a message that they didn't want to win the hockey
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim goalie Guy Hebert says the Ducks can't worry about what
Dallas thinks and said he believes they might be able to use the
Stars' anger to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully that will work as a distraction to them,'' he said.
``We have to get back to playing our system. That is a more
important issue for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Ducks have yet to score a goal in losses to Dallas
and Phoenix and are in the midst of continuing a disturbing October
trend. Anaheim is 14-34-11 in the first month of the season since
joining the NHL in 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why we've had slow starts,'' said Selanne. ``It's
something I'd like to know too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to think positive, we need one good game to get our
confidence back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg expects to see a different (Ducks) team against
Dallas, but only if it is willing to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work ourselves out of it (the slump), not hope
ourselves out of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim coach said he isn't concerned with the lack of
scoring _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the mindset is to score, you end up getting less,'' he
said. ``If you go out and check... (and are) a good solid team, the
chances will come. You have to worry about the process.''
</P>
<P>
   With only 20 players on the roster _ the suspended players can't
be replaced by minor-league callups _ Hartsburg's flexibility is
limited, so much so that he joked he was going to play.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg doesn't plan on changing the forward lines, but he is
planning to reunite Jason Marshall and Kevin Haller on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to establish a pair to play against the other team's
top lines,'' he said. ``We got away from that, but we've got to get
back to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall and Haller were the Ducks' top defensive pairing last
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
