<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON PERKS UP CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Representing the people of L.A. for at least one
season is Derek Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   In unwittingly promoting a litigious theme, Anderson has
encouraged his new Clippers teammates and coaches to refer to him
as ``DA.''
</P>
<P>
   It serves, because the burden of proof is his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just here to play hard, help the team win and put up a lot
of numbers,'' said Anderson, an explosive, 6-foot-5 shooting guard
acquired Aug.4 from Cleveland in what seems like the bonanza half
of Lamond Murray's sign-and-trade deal.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, chosen by the Cavaliers with the 13th pick in the 1997
NBA draft, averaged 11.3 points in 104 games over two seasons in
Cleveland. But the right knee that disrupted his senior year at
Kentucky conspired with a logjam of high-priced Cavaliers shooting
guards to strangle some of his pro production.
</P>
<P>
   The leg is sound now, but the Cavaliers thought the
contract-extension goal of Anderson and his agent Tevester Scott of
rapper Master P's No Limit Sports agency was a bit pricey.
</P>
<P>
   When they traded him, he didn't exactly land on ``The Price Is
Right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My thing is to change that,'' said Anderson of the negative
vibe that surrounds the Clippers. But perhaps even more ferocious
than the franchise's history of losing is its tradition of being
stingy with a buck. It is assumed that even a spectacular season
from Anderson would be insufficient to hold sway with owner Donald
T. Sterling's checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not my decision,'' Anderson said. ``But I can't just
say I'm going to play here one year and then leave. A lot of things
can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very good,'' coach Chris Ford said of Anderson. ``He's
very athletic, he makes good decisions with the ball and can play
multiple positions.''
</P>
<P>
   The appreciation is reciprocal so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this a lot,'' Anderson said of his first week with the
Clippers. ``Everyone has a willingness to work. There's a lot of
quickness and speed and a new philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way it's supposed to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
