<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FLOP, HOPE FOR HITS OFF BROADWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The game was a thriller, a pitching duel taut with
suspense and drama from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The result, however, was the same and the Rangers, despite Rick
Helling's performance, are going back to Arlington on the brink of
elimination.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees pushed them to that point because Andy
Pettitte pitched just a little bit better than Helling in shutting
down the Rangers. Not that stopping the Rangers' offense is rare in
the playoffs, but Pettitte's performance gave the Yankees a 3-1
victory Thursday night in Game 2 of their American League Division
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick couldn't have pitched a better game, and we couldn't do
the things we needed to do to pick him up,'' Rangers shortstop
Royce Clayton said. ``It's an indescribable feeling. You go out, do
all you can, and it wasn't enough. It's a terrible feeling; no
other way to describe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss left the Rangers down 2-0 in the best-of-five series.
Game 3 is scheduled for Saturday night at The Ballpark in
Arlington, where the Rangers begin their quest to be the fourth
team in history to rally from two games down to win a best-of-five
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just outpitched us and outplayed us,'' Helling said.
``They got the big hit when they needed it, and Andy made the big
pitch when he needed to. It was a tough loss. If we win, we have
them right where we want them, going home tied 1-1 and the
home-field advantage. Now we have to win three in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling held the Yankees to one run on three hits through six
innings but faltered in the seventh. Tino Martinez drew a
five-pitch walk with one out then raced to third on a full-count
hit-and-run single through the right side by Chili Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee followed with a fly ball into right-center, and
center fielder Roberto Kelly couldn't run it down. Instead it fell
for a double, bringing home Martinez with the go-ahead run. Helling
was lifted at that point, having thrown 124 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt better in the seventh inning than I did in the sixth
inning,'' Helling said. ``Like I've said, if you get tired in a
game like this, something is wrong with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers did get a run Thursday night, on Juan Gonzalez's
fourth-inning home run, giving them a 1-0 lead. But the rest of the
game was just an extension of the offensive miseries that have
beset the Rangers in five consecutive Division Series losses to the
Yankees going back to last year.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you scoring at home, it's now two runs in 45
innings, and eight consecutive playoff losses to the Yankees, going
back to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating and disappointing,'' outfielder Rusty Greer
said. ``We just have to get more hits with runners on base, simple
as that.''
</P>
<P>
   The most painful memory from this game will be the fifth inning
when the Rangers blew a great chance to add to their lead. Kelly
led off with a single, and Lee Stevens lined a ground-rule double
over the left field fence, putting runners on second and third.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers failed to score. Mark McLemore, after getting
ahead 3-0 in the count, struck out on a 3-2 pitch, Clayton bounced
out to third baseman Scott Brosius and Greer struck out on a 3-2
cut fastball in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hurt, right there,'' McLemore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get the job done,'' Clayton said. ``There's no
reason for it. He wasn't dominating. He wasn't even around the
strike zone. We helped him out. We just couldn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The second inning was another wasted opportunity. Rafael
Palmeiro and Todd Zeile led off with singles, but Kelly struck out
and Stevens hit into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're better than us,'' Helling said. ``I
think we're as good as anybody in baseball. They've just executed
better. It's as simple as that. They get the big hit when they have
to, and they make the big pitch when they have to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
