<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELMONT-TESTIMONY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUSD SUPERINTENDANT TESTIFIES BEFORE COMMITTEE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BETH BARRETT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Los Angeles Unified Superintendent Ruben Zacarias
told an independent commission he would consider a scaled-down
Belmont Learning Center if environmental problems persist and
cleanup costs climb too high.
</P>
<P>
   But Zacarias also said he favors completing the nation's
costliest high school atop the former oil and gas field, if it can
be done safely for students, staff and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the completion and eventual opening of the project,
but only if one critical condition is met: The Department of Toxic
Substance Control must declare the site safe for occupancy by
students and staff,'' he told the Belmont Commission Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected to take months for those tests of potentially
explosive methane and deadly hydrogen sulfide gas in the soil to be
completed.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is scheduled to recommend to the school board
whether to proceed with the $200 million school on Oct. 20.
Zacarias appeared before the commission as one of dozens of
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias said he is now considering whether to use ``only a
portion of the property where it appears there is less toxicity.''
He said his approach to the site is being shaped by continuing
preliminary probes that show high readings of hydrogen sulfide in
the soil in some locations. He also said he is unwilling to spend
unlimited amounts of funds to safeguard the entire 35 acres.
</P>
<P>
   A source said Zacarias has been talking with top district
officials about completing only a portion of the school, which is
just over half finished, as an annex to the current Belmont High
School.
</P>
<P>
   ``By narrowing the scope, the remediation of a smaller portion
might be less costly and easier to monitor,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Another option being discussed by district officials is to build
a smaller high school or middle school where administrators are now
lodged at a downtown site known as ``The Hill,'' and to move those
1,500 staff members to Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Belmont have complained that while acceptable
exposure rates for toxics such as hydrogen sulfide have been
determined for adults, they have not been set for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in time, I believe we must be flexible,''
Zacarias told the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Beckman said Zacarias' testimony underscored
the remaining uncertainty in judging the fitness of Belmont for a
school site.
</P>
<P>
   The latest in a series of tests reported Wednesday by the Daily
News showed elevated levels of hydrogen sulfide in some monitoring
wells in the ground. Zacarias said the test series confirm ``that
environmental conditions at Belmont are dynamic, not static.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckman said the commission will have to make its decision
taking that environmental uncertainty into account.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's executive director Ira Reiner, who requested
Zacarias' testimony, criticized the superintendent for his
responses, saying they did not address major concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Reiner said he believes the district's staff is paralyzed when
it comes to making decisions on Belmont, and he is worried they
will not be able to properly monitor the site if the project is
completed. Reiner cited bills from an environmental consultant he
said the district delayed paying for months as evidence of
ineptness.
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias said he was unaware of any billing problems, but said
he has put in place a new team to oversee Belmont's environmental
reviews and any future construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``An extraction system and a membrane barrier are only as
effective as the people who ensure that they are maintained
properly on an ongoing basis,'' he said, adding the district and
state toxics officials will guarantee the site will be monitored
for the life of the school.
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias said that if the school or any portion of it opens,
parents and students will be fully briefed on the toxic situations
and what steps are being taken to remediate them.
</P>
<P>
   And while opposing granting a blanket waiver for students who
wanted to attend another school because of health concerns, he said
such waivers would be considered on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
