<HEADER>
A0415 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN--FRANBLINEBURY-HN     10-08 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--FRAN </SLUG>
 BLINEBURY-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE good news is that the Braves can't run Kevin Millwood out there
every game.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that Ken Caminiti probably can't keep up his
one-a-day homer pace, either.
</P>
<P>
   Which means that if the Astros are going to score enough runs in
the rest of this Division Series to overcome Atlanta's trophy case
full of Cy Young Awards, it will require at least an appearance by
the two biggest cogs in the machine.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio and Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   Same song, third verse.
</P>
<P>
   This is starting to sound as familiar as a Christmas carol.
Silent Night
</P>
<P>
   Two games in, and the numbers are eerily similar to 1997 and
1998. Biggio and Bagwell are a combined 2-for-16 at the plate _ one
hit apiece.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Killer Fleas.
</P>
<P>
   In nine playoff games against the Braves and Padres, they are
8-for-65. Bagwell is hitting .121 and Biggio .125 Which are nice
numbers if you're a supermodel on an eating binge.
</P>
<P>
   For the Astros, they have become the Killer Breeze, an icy wind
blowing through a gaping hole at the top of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   At least this is one problem nobody can blame on Derek Bell.
He's not even on the field, and to date his offer of cash bonuses
for big hits has not awakened the biggest _ and most critical _ of
all the Astros' bats.
</P>
<P>
   If Biggio doesn't get on base, there isn't much for Bagwell to
drive in. If Bagwell isn't driving the ball and collecting RBIs, it
is far less threatening for the Braves to deal with Carl Everett
and Caminiti down below.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure isn't hard for me to write their names in the lineup
every day and send them out there,'' said manager Larry Dierker.
``Biggio and Bagwell are who they are, and you don't question their
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the course of the long season, we would, of course, never
get to where we are without them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, things can and do change in a short series. But it stands
to reason that if we are ever going to go where we want to go in
the playoffs, well, yes, we need them.''
</P>
<P>
   Like an alcoholic goldfish needs to swim in a bowl of vodka.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of big hits, one huge inning. Would that break the dam
and ease the pressure?
</P>
<P>
   It is a painful dilemma. All season long, the Astros are nothing
at all without them. Now, in the postseason, they are nothing
special without them. Not a team that can make a World Series run.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say they haven't contributed to the 1-1 split.
After struggling with his glove down the stretch, Biggio has been
solid at second base. And Bagwell made a couple of big defensive
plays in Game 2 alone.
</P>
<P>
   But they don't point the cameras at Cameron Diaz for her ability
to recite the multiplication tables, and if the Astros are ever
going to get the playoff monkey entirely off their backs, the
Killer B's will have to at least inflict a few bruises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can win some games without them,'' Dierker said. ``But when
they're hitting, they give us the ability to win games easily,
without having to depend on all the rest being perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   There have always been players who thrive in the postseason.
Reggie Jackson was Mr. October. Caminiti's bat comes around as
regularly as Halloween. But there also have been big names who have
struggled in the spotlight. Dave Winfield was Mr. May.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the difference, of course, is in the pitching. It is
consistently better at this time of year. If you're not facing Greg
Maddux, Tom Glavine, John Smoltz or Kevin Brown, then it's a
Millwood stepping up to carve out a one-hitter with surgical
precision. In other words, there are few gimmies and it is up to
the hitters to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the course of the long regular season, guys can put up
big numbers by hitting bad pitches off bad pitchers,'' Dierker
said. ``But sometime or another in the playoffs, you've got to
start hitting good pitches from good pitchers. It can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   If the hitter doesn't tie himself up in mental knots.
</P>
<P>
   For all of his cliches and low-key demeanor in public, Biggio is
outgoing and vocal within the confines of the team. When he
struggles at the plate, he becomes overaggressive, lunging at the
ball. He has not drawn a walk or tried a bunt to get himself on
base, where his speed is a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell is always controlled and stays with his own program when
trying to find his way out of a slump _ gritting his teeth,
swinging harder, yet remaining the stoic.
</P>
<P>
   However, both can be tortured souls. Both internalize
everything. Both become emotional Krakatoas. What works for them
most of the time can also work against them when things get tight.
</P>
<P>
   This is more than just a few good pitches from a few good
pitchers. It's a trend and a disturbing one that again threatens to
keep the Astros from getting past the doorstep of October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
