<HEADER>
A0416 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS     10-08 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The road to the World Series is hardly an HOV lane. It's more like
the West Loop at rush hour _ slow progress, but progress
nonetheless.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just ask the Atlanta Braves, who have just one World Series
championship to show for seven consecutive previous trips to the
playoffs this decade. Odds are if the Astros keep reaching the
postseason, they eventually will reach the ultimate goal, too.
</P>
<P>
   But until they do, there will be doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life when your playoff resume doesn't include a single
series victory.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the Astros are in control of their best-of-five
National League Division Series, which is tied at a game apiece.
The next two games are in Houston, and the Astros will send their
best pitcher, Mike Hampton, to the mound today in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   But conventional wisdom doesn't seem to be on the Astros' side
in this instance. The prevailing commentary regarding the remainder
of this series has revolved around the Braves' extensive playoff
experience and their history of playing well at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   There's also talk about how easily the Braves could reel off a
pair of victories behind former Cy Young Award winners Tom Glavine
and John Smoltz over the next two days, and pitcher of the decade
Greg Maddux is available if Game 5 is necessary Sunday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, there is little talk about the Astros and
their chances of pulling off a first-round upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because we're playing the Braves,'' Astros first
baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``We're playing the Braves and their
mystique. The Braves obviously have a great team, and they've been
in this situation a lot more than we have. No one expects us to
beat them except us, and we really believe we can do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go back and look at the newspapers from 1997 (when the
Astros were swept by the Braves in a Division Series), and I know I
said I thought we could beat the Braves back then. But to be
honest, deep down inside, I didn't feel like we were good enough to
beat them. But we're a different team now _ a better team _ and I
really believe we can beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won one of the first two games against the Padres in
their 1998 Division Series, but the next two games were in San
Diego and the series never returned to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Astros have a chance to make the home-field
advantage work for them.
</P>
<P>
   A near-sellout crowd is expected today at the Astrodome, where
the Astros haven't played since clinching the NL Central Division
title Sunday behind a strong effort from Hampton and a vocal crowd
that made the atmosphere uneasy for the competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros no doubt would take a repeat on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fans are going to be fired up,'' second baseman
Craig Biggio said. ``This time of year is a lot of fun. We're
excited to have come out of Atlanta with a split and to have the
next two games at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever has an advantage when they're playing against the
Braves. They're a great team; there's a reason they keep winning
year after year. But there are going to be two great pitchers out
there (today). It's going to be another good game, and hopefully
we'll come out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   That's usually the case when Hampton pitches. The Astros won 29
of his 34 starts this season, and he led the majors with a
remarkable .846 winning percentage. In other words, Hampton is the
man the Astros want on the mound when they most need a victory.
</P>
<P>
   But because neither team is in position to eliminate the other,
today's game is more pivotal than critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the playoffs, so obviously every game is a big game,''
closer Billy Wagner said. ``But as far as I'm concerned, there's no
reason to put any extra pressure on ourselves, and to me, that's
where pressure comes from.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans can't put pressure on you; the media can't put
pressure on you; no one can put pressure on you except yourself. We
just need to relax and play the way we know how to play. If we do
that, we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the expectations, there's no reason for the underdog
Astros to be anything but relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody figured we would be in this situation anyway,'' center
fielder Carl Everett said. ``I guess it's because we haven't done
too well in the playoffs the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what we've done in the past doesn't mean anything right
now. The only thing that matters is winning two more games. If we
do that, who cares about the past?''
</P>
<P>
   Having been down that road before, the Astros are more
interested in charting a new path.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
