<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE RUN WAS ALMOST ENOUGHT FOR HELLING
</HEADLINE>
 -TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
NEW YORK _ This Rick Helling is one lucky fellow. Once a year, the
Rangers come to the Bronx and score a run in the baseball
postseason. But they only score it for Rick.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No other pitcher is so honored. Helling gets his run and his
thrill. Everybody else gets a taxi ride with the foreign cabbie who
has a fake passport, no Mapsco and an apparent death wish.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, however, is not exactly appreciative. Doesn't he
realize that one run is better than none? And none is the norm for
the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Economic riches appear to be rather sparse in the Bronx, unless
you happen to own a razor-wire company or be a pitcher for the
Yankees. It doesn't matter what kind of pitcher, just be fortunate
enough to have manager Joe Torre send you out against the Rangers.
Like the razor-wire tycoon, you are guaranteed to cash.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Andy Pettitte was the chosen one last night.
Pettitte must live with the disgrace of allowing one run a year to
the Rangers in the postseason. But the trade-off is that Pettitte
has now been the winning pitcher in consecutive Game 2s of the
American League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   These Game 2s have crushed the Rangers, since they also happened
to have lost the Game 1s.
</P>
<P>
   Another playoff exit was assured for the Rangers last night in a
3-1 defeat. The only hanging question is will it be Sweep II. A
trip to Texas, an off-day today, then a Saturday-night encounter at
The Ballpark in Arlington will determine that.
</P>
<P>
   But besides being gifted with his traditional one run, Helling
also pitched his guts out last night. Unfortunately, the
right-hander has been down this dead-end road before.
</P>
<P>
   Helling lost, 3-1, last night. A year ago in Game 2 at Yankee
Stadium, he lost, 3-1. Pettitte bested him both times. Pettitte did
not outpitch him either time. But Pettitte has the support of a
batting order that is manly, and even when not overly productive,
still gets the job done.
</P>
<P>
   There is always overwhelming concern in North Texas precincts
about the Rangers being mismatched against the Yankees in the
rotation department. But that was not the case last night, nor was
it a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Helling again gave his team every opportunity to come out of New
York with a split, and head home with renewed hope in the series.
But against the Yankees, the Rangers' batting order continues to be
hopeless and homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The next guy from Keller or Lake Worth who says the Rangers just
don't have the pitching, slap him right across the teeth. There is
no truth to what seems to pass as the truth. Just like there is no
chance for the Rangers to have postseason survival against the
Yankees, not with the lightweight hitters who freeze up in the
October spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know in our hearts we can play with those guys, but until
we start doing it, there is going to be doubt,'' said manager
Johnny Oates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doubt,'' of course, is putting it way too mildly.
</P>
<P>
   All Helling needed to do last night was throw a shutout. And he
actually had that kind of stuff, and was that kind of bulldog. But
nursing a 1-0 lead against the patience of the New York hitters
makes for a long, hard evening.
</P>
<P>
   While being in command, Helling's pitch count also kept climbing
and climbing. The Yankees' hitters made him work for every out, and
every strikeout, which totaled eight in the first five innings.
</P>
<P>
   With a leadoff runner at first, Helling had two strikeouts in
the fifth before going to a full-count on Scott Brosius. The next
pitch to Brosius came in fat, and he drilled it off the left-field
wall, scoring Tino Martinez from first.
</P>
<P>
   Helling took the 1-1 deadlock into the seventh, having thrown
101 pitches. A one-out walk to Martinez invited trouble, and was a
sure sign Helling was tiring. Oates, however, had more faith in
Rick than his bullpen, and that's understandable. Chili Davis,
however, singled Martinez to third, and then Ricky Ledee popped a
double into right center, giving the Yankees all they needed _ a
2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-luck Helling departed at that point, having to know
privately there was no chance for his offense to rally.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that Ledee and Brosius did the damage to Helling
was yet another flashback to a year ago. In that 3-1 defeat in
1998, Brosius had two runs batted in, and the No. 8 batter in that
game (Shane Spencer) drove in the other run.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom-of-the-order blues low-lighted last October's exit by the
Rangers. Same old story, and same old lack of runs this time,
except for Helling getting his usual one. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
