<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0419 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-H     10-08 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANNY ROBBINS  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They got a fine effort from their starting pitcher.
They scored a run and actually had a lead. And then, of course, the
wheels came off for the Texas Rangers. Eight games into one of the
cruelest losing streaks in postseason baseball, can there be any
other way?
</P>
<P>
   Failing to hit with men on base, the Rangers went down again to
the New York Yankees on Thursday, losing Game 2 of their American
League Division Series at Yankee Stadium 3-1. The series now shifts
to Arlington, for games Saturday and possibly Sunday, with the
Yankees leading the best-of-five series 2-0 and the Rangers facing
the prospect of having to beat both Roger Clemens and David Cone to
force a fifth game.
</P>
<P>
   In losing to the Yankees for the eighth consecutive time in
postseason play, the Rangers wasted the effort of starter Rick
Helling, who gave up two runs and five hits in the 6 innings he
worked.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers broke a 25-inning postseason scoreless streak when
Juan Gonzalez homered off Yankees starter Andy Pettitte in the
fourth to give the Rangers a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were able to win by scratching out runs off Helling
in the fifth and seventh innings, Ricky Ledee's single bringing in
the go-ahead run, and added another when reliever Mike Venafro
walked in a run in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   In 7 innings, Pettitte allowed seven hits, didn't give up a walk
and pitched out of serious trouble in the second and fifth innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (Pettitte's performance) is what I remember about Andy,''
Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``He makes big plays, big pitches.
He walked that tightrope in '96. He got into jams and got out of
them. You talk about hitching it up. ''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to juice up their offense, which produced only two hits
in Game 1, the Rangers made several adjustments Thursday. Manager
Johnny Oates tinkered with the top of his lineup, making Royce
Clayton and Rusty Greer his Nos. 1 and 2 hitters, and tried to give
his players a new mindset at the plate as well.
</P>
<P>
   Oates thought Rangers hitters, normally free swingers, had been
too selective at the plate in Game 1, taking pitches they usually
can hit, as if they were trying to emulate the heralded patience of
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some hits, got some hits early,'' Oates said after
Thursday's game, ``and just weren't able to back it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, in the second inning, the Rangers found
themselves in Game 1 mode. After Rafael Palmeiro and Todd Zeile
opened the inning with back-to-back singles, Roberto Kelly struck
out and Lee Stevens dribbled a broken-bat grounder up the middle
that Derek Jeter turned into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the fourth, the Rangers broke through. With one out
and nobody on, Gonzalez took a 1-2 pitch from Pettitte and lined it
into the lower deck in left. After 25 scoreless innings of Division
Series play against the Yankees, a streak dating to the fifth
inning of last year's 3-1 loss in Game 2, the Rangers had a genuine
run and a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees got their first hit of the night in their half of
the inning, Jeter's one-out double to right-center. With the
stadium energized for the first time since the beginning of the
game, Paul O'Neill battled Helling from 0-2 to 3-2 before grounding
to Clayton, the Texas shortstop, whose throw beat Jeter at third.
Helling then struck out Bernie Williams to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers again had Pettitte on the ropes in the fifth. Kelly
started the inning with a single. Stevens followed with a double to
left. But Pettitte was able to battle his way out of it, striking
out Mark McLemore after falling behind 3-0, getting Clayton to tap
to third and striking out Greer, swinging, on a 3-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees then made it a 1-1 game. Tino Martinez opened the
New York fifth with a single. Helling struck out the next two
hitters, Chili Davis and Ledee, but couldn't get past Scott
Brosius, the Yankees' No. 8 hitter, who brought in the run with a
double off the wall in left.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' wasted opportunities loomed large when Helling finally
ran out of gas in the seventh and the Yankees moved ahead on
Ledee's run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez walked with one out, the only walk issued by Helling,
and moved to third when Davis grounded a single to right. Ledee
then golfed one to right-center that fell in for a single and
scored Martinez with the go-ahead run.
</P>
</TEXT>
