<HEADER>
A0420 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     10-08 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' HELLING HAS NO HELP IN LOST CAUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
NEW YORK _ The Lone Ranger showed up at Yankee Stadium last night,
ready and willing to ride to the rescue. His trusty sidekick Tonto
was a miserable no-show again. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Outmanned and outgunned, our hero went down fighting. But down
he went just the same. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All Rick Helling needed was a little help from his friends. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Someone to watch his back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Someone to give him a little moral support. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Someone, for crying out loud, to contribute a clutch hit, drive
in a critical run. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His, however, was a lonely one-man stand in the cold Bronx
night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, this October nightmare will soon be over. The
Yankees' 3-1 victory gives them a 2-0 lead in this best-of-five
Division Series, which makes a brief stop in Texas on Saturday
night before the Yanks once again move on to bigger and better
things. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, as usual, have been no more annoying than a
meaningless pimple on the Yankees' pinstriped behinds, practically
invisible to the naked eye and soon forgotten. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' futility has become a baffling mystery, even to the
Yankees and the arrogant provincial New York media that never
misses an opportunity to stroke the home team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A ticking time bomb,'' Yankees outfielder Paul O'Neill says of
the Rangers' offense. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Great. Maybe it'll go off next March, when it really matters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can't do better than this,'' a New York columnist
snidely wrote yesterday, ``they don't get invited back.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Insert gnashing of teeth here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what can you say? The Rangers have left those of us who
believed that this would be the year they would finally put an end
to the Yankees' curse as defenseless as Helling was last night with
only Juan Gonzalez's solo home run in the fourth for support. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is impossible,'' Helling said. ``We have a good
ballclub. It can be done. We've won three games in a row this year.
I'm sure the Yankees have lost three in a row this year.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trying to conceive those two scenarios coming together at this
point, however, is beyond the most fertile imagination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates shook up his lineup, moving Royce Clayton
to leadoff, Rusty Greer to the two hole and hitting Pudge Rodriguez
third. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got good vibes tonight,'' Oates confided before the
game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Must have been coming from that one lonely run. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You always try to put zeros on the board,'' Helling said. ``It
would have been nice to throw a 1-0 shutout, but I don't think you
expect that to happen.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's home run snapped the team's streak of consecutive
scoreless innings at 25. His line drive barely cleared a left-field
billboard advertising a popular camera and film company, a true
Kodak moment, if you will. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully someone snapped a picture, because it's not like these
things come along every day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were a pitiful 0-for-5 with runners in scoring
position, and their inability to break the game open in the fifth
after they put runners at second and third with no one out was the
contest's lynchpin moment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Kelly had lined a leadoff single to center, and Lee
Stevens drove an Andy Pettitte fastball on a slicing arc to left
field, where it caromed off the warning track and into the
left-field seats for a ground-rule double. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So who's due up? Second baseman Mark McLemore, the one guy Oates
tried to hide in his lineup by dropping him to ninth, thanks to a
postseason batting average (.104) so low you couldn't buy a cup of
New York coffee with it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But McLemore worked the count to 3-0, building hope in the
hearts of Rangers faithful. A base hit could score two runs and
give Helling, pitching well, a 3-0 lead. A walk would load the
bases for the top of the order with no one out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We get the guy \RMcLemore\S 3-0 and runners at second and
third and you're feeling good,'' Oates said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dream on. McLemore struck out flailing at Pettitte's backdoor
cutter. Clayton chopped an easy one-hopper to third baseman Scott
Brosius as the runners held. Greer struck out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Misery descended on the Rangers once again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good feeling when he struck McLemore out, especially
coming back from 3-0,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``Getting
out of that inning and getting that third run in the eighth was
huge.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fired up, the Yankees would tie the score in the bottom of the
fifth, and a tiring Helling, who started theseventh having thrown
104 pitches, finally coughed up the lead run in the seventh on
Ricky Ledee's run-scoring double to right center. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Torre's right. The Yankees did add a third run in the eighth,
but huge? That's giving the Rangers way too much credit.
Essentially, they were dead after the fifth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were no Texas base runners in the final three innings.
Zero. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's frustration,'' a dejected Oates said. ``We know in our
hearts we can play with these guys, but until we start doing it,
there's always going to be doubts.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't even begin to start covering it, Kemo Sabe. &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
