A0422 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-CLUTCH-TE     10-08 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-CLUTCH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SQUANDER OPPORTUNITIES IN CRITICAL FIFTH INNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1996 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Right-hander Rick Helling provided the Rangers an
opportunity to return to The Ballpark in Arlington with the
best-of-five Division Series against the Yankees square at a
victory apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' potent lineup whiffed on the potential breakthrough
and doomed the American League West champions to a 3-1 loss
Thursday night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore, shortstop Royce Clayton and left
fielder Rusty Greer failed to produce with runners aboard second
and third during the critical fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Those three at-bats would be the last the Rangers managed with a
runner in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was certainly a key inning of the ballgame,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``That was probably the best opportunity
to have a big inning other than the first. You think you've got a
good shot at getting something going.''
</P>
<P>
   It began with such promise after a leadoff single by center
fielder Roberto Kelly and the ensuing double by first baseman Lee
Stevens. Despite no outs, neither crossed the plate.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore, who hit .163 this season against left-handers, stepped
into the batter's box hitting right-handed against Yankees
left-hander Andy Pettitte. Yankees manager Joe Torre played third
baseman Scott Brosius and shortstop Derek Jeter at normal depth and
pulled in the right side of his infield.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore took three consecutive pitches before Pettitte threw a
strike, and Oates gave his switch-hitting infielder the ``green
light'' on 3-1. McLemore fouled that pitch down the first-base line
to run the count full, and he swung through Pettitte's 3-2 delivery
for the inning's first out.
</P>
<P>
   It would be an ominous sign.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte induced a one-out ground ball on a 2-1 pitch from
shortstop Royce Clayton, who hit leadoff for only the third time
this season. Oates did not signal for the ``contact'' play, whereby
Kelly would break as soon as Clayton put the ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees third baseman Scott Brosius fielded the ball cleanly and
retired Clayton at first base, and Kelly and Stevens remained in
scoring position for left fielder Rusty Greer. Pettitte again fell
behind in the count before working it full, and Greer swung through
a 3-2 breaking ball in the dirt to end the threat. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0026 </DOCNO>
