<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0424 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      10-08 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ Shandon Anderson had been told the Rockets planned to run
more. He believed it, too.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was one of the reasons he had been attracted to the Rockets.
And it made sense. With a potential backcourt of Anderson and Steve
Francis, and with Cuttino Mobley likely to command minutes, you
run.
</P>
<P>
   But the image of the plodding Rockets remained. Fair or not, the
Rockets were regarded as a half-court, slow-down, post-up team. No
matter how convinced Anderson was the Rockets were ready to change
_ and he was convinced enough to sign with the Rockets as a bargain
free agent _ the image remained.
</P>
<P>
   It is gone now. After three days with Rudy Tomjanovich pushing
hard on the accelerator, Anderson and the Rockets know how serious
Tomjanovich was when he said he would pick up the pace on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew when you were playing the Rockets, they would throw
the ball to Hakeem (Olajuwon) or (Charles) Barkley and beat you
with the 3, and they're not going to hide it,'' Anderson said of
his previous three seasons in the NBA with the Jazz. ``With the
rule changes, you can't sit there and pound the ball. Rudy told me
he wanted more movement in the offense. But I didn't know he meant
this much running. Now I know he was serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we'd go up and down a little bit. But he wants us to
get up the floor every time. Every time. We can always set up in
the half-court. But we're going to get up the floor and try to get
the easy basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich always intended to get the Rockets in the open court
and to get them used to getting up and down the floor. But he began
camp by emphasizing the need to run to make it a habit. Players
always will run if they see a dunk waiting on the other end of the
court. Tomjanovich wanted them in flight before they had a chance
to look.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of talk about the running game,'' he said.
``There's a lot of talk, but you have to consistently get up and
down the court. A split-second hesitation could take away a break.
We're trying to get them conditioned to push it down every time. We
can always slow down later in a tight game. We've made great
progress in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   The other benefit of quickly establishing that part of the
offense is it can then offer a better gauge of the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a 50/50 deal,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We have to
put in our offense so we can have some offense we have to defend.
If you're running terrible offense, you're going to think you're
playing good defense. You get into that situation: `Are we that
good on offense or terrible on defense? Are we that good on
defense, or terrible on offense?'''
</P>
<P>
   Now that they are running, Tomjanovich wants the Rockets to be
able to quickly call on an ``early offense,'' a part of the game
that in recent seasons has all but disappeared from the NBA. When
the break does not generate a fast-break basket, Tomjanovich would
like the Rockets to quickly shift to a half-court set without
having to stop and call a play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why nobody in the league does that,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``It's been either a fast break or a set play. It's something
that's been talked about. You have some sort of pattern as you
break. If the break is not there, you get into some sort of
pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, the Rockets believe the break will be there, if only
because they have the players to turn even a small opening into a
chance to outnumber an opponent on the other end of the court. If
the Rockets can keep up with Francis, he has shown he can get the
ball from one end to the other faster than anyone can backpedal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to run as hard as you can to keep up with him,''
forward Don MacLean said. ``That's good. You want a point guard
that pushes it up and gets you a few easy buckets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to play to your strengths. In the past, Dream
needed 25 shots a game. Dream isn't looking for that. You play with
your personnel. Steve Francis is going to be a great player.
Shandon Anderson is a proven scorer. You want those guys involved,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that the guys weren't involved before, but they were
dominant inside. Now, we're taking advantage of the other strengths
the Rockets have.''
</P>
<P>
   The inside strength offered no complaints. Olajuwon said ``it's
just basketball.'' The details, he said, do not matter if a team
leans on what works.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was ready for the Rockets to no longer lean so heavily
on him. If the image of Barkley is not of him filling a wing on the
break, he said he is ready to move away from the punishment that
comes with hand-to-hand combat in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't bring Steve Francis and Shandon Anderson in here to
walk the ball up the court,'' Barkley said. ``It helps everything
to run. Also, I don't want to have that pressure of having to bang
the whole game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to be up-tempo, get the running game going. What
we're going to have to really work on, when the break isn't there,
is a quick transition into offense, instead of slowing it down and
going to the half-court and having to bang the whole game. We
(Barkley and Olajuwon) don't want to be as productive as we have
been in the past. We can't be. This is going well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets who live to run were only too happy with the change.
For Anderson and Francis, the running Rockets are the only Rockets
they have known firsthand. For Mobley, a half-court point guard
with full-court finishing skills last season, the change is a
revelation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real nice,'' he said. ``We've got Bryce Drew, Matt
Maloney and Steve Francis pushing the rock; myself, Shandon, Walt
(Williams) and Stacey (Augmon) on the wing. It will cause a lot of
problems for a lot of teams. Any young player doesn't want to stand
around. We have too much energy. We want to play. I'm just loving
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the Rockets, it might say more that they don't have to
be ``any young player'' to see so much potential in the change.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets made a healthy 46.2 percent of their shots last
season, ranking third in the NBA. Their average of 94.2 points per
game ranked seventh. But for the second consecutive season, the
Rockets had a first-round playoff exit.
</P>
<P>
   The quickness on the perimeter could improve the defense, but it
can also boost the Rockets' scoring and, Olajuwon said, their
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an advantage to have guys who can run and post up,''
Olajuwon said. ``You don't (pre)determine the style of basketball
until the players are in sync together, play good defense, get the
rebound, outlet pass, run the fast break, post up. That's
basketball. People try to separate the post-up game from the
running game. You need to do both. That wins championships.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
