<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-PETTITTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT ESCAPES BY PETTITTE SECURED WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A free agent when the season ends, Andy Pettitte can
name his price after his performance in Thursday night's victory.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte had trouble with his curveball and relied on his
two-seam fastball, working in and out of some tight jams that could
have sent him to the showers early. But, when he needed the big
out, he found more escape hatches than Houdini.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big game,'' said Pettitte, who won his sixth career
postseason game. ``Sometimes you are going to be good. We had a lot
of little things happen that a lot of people don't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether by his own ingenuity or courtesy of the continuing
futility of the Rangers' offense, Pettitte dodged two key, no-out
jams as the Yankees went on to win 3-1 and take a commanding 2-0
lead over the Rangers in the American League Division Series at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He walked that tightrope,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said.
``When he was in jams, he didn't look like he would get out of,
he'd get out of them. You talk about hitchin' it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Two innings, the second and fifth, were crucial to Pettitte's
survival on a night when Rangers starter Rick Helling kept the
Yankees' offense as cold as the Bronx night air.
</P>
<P>
   In both innings, Pettitte brushed off back-to-back leadoff hits
to get out of danger with no runs scoring. The fifth was the key
inning when the Rangers started by putting runners on second and
third with no outs. Pettitte, once again emerging as a big-game
pitcher, set down the Rangers and gave his offense a chance to win
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte allowed only a fourth-inning solo home run to Juan
Gonzalez. He left in the eighth inning to a standing ovation. It
was just earlier this season when Pettitte was booed out of Yankee
Stadium and his name was often heard in trade rumors. This night,
he reassured everyone of his ability, going 71/3 innings and
allowing one run on seven hits. He walked none and struck out five.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was awesome. There were a couple of jams he got out of,''
right fielder Paul O'Neill said. ``Then we were able to squeak out
a couple of huge runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees tied the score at 1-1 in the fifth on Scott Brosius'
double off the left-field wall and then scored the winning run on
Ricky Ledee's seventh-inning double, his second run-scoring double
of the series.
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, the defending champions are one game away
from sweeping the Rangers on a night when the Rangers got a strong
outing from starter Rick Helling.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will force the Rangers to beat Roger Clemens in Game
3 on Saturday, David Cone on Sunday, if necessary, and Orlando
Hernandez, who pitched an eight-inning, two-hitter in Game 1, in
what would be the decisive Game 5 back at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, Pettitte made the difference between leading 2-0
and handing home-field advantage over to the Rangers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
