<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0426 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN--ROBERTSON-HNS &LR;      10-08 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN--ROBERTSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHAT Bob McNair's group has done in gaining ownership of the NFL's
32nd and, in all probability, last new franchise of our lifetime is
tantamount to winning the Super Bowl with a John Elway drive in the
game's final moments.
</P>
<P>
   There is one striking difference, though. When a team wins the
Super Bowl, it gets drunk, then goes on vacation for about six
months. In contrast, McNair and his weary associates were
essentially back in full pads preparing for two-a-day practices
Thursday, less than 24 hours after the NFL offered its blessing to
their record $700 million bid.
</P>
<P>
   A celebratory welcome-home news conference was held at noon, but
by midafternoon they were in meetings with investment bankers.
There's so much work to be done in a ridiculously short time it is
staggering. For example, the structural steel for the stadium and
its retractable roof must be ordered in less than two months, if
the building is to be completed by Aug. 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my wife I'd see her in about four years,'' joked Steve
Patterson, the former Rockets and Aeros general manager who has
been McNair's only full-time executive-level employee throughout
the 2{ years he spent pursuing the franchise against what most
believed were impossibly long odds.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, by gosh, the Houston (fill-in-the-blanks) are up and
running, with a toll-free phone number and a Web site online.
Regarding the latter, there were 200,000 hits the first hour. And
Houston, the more skeptical NFL owners would have had us believe,
lacks a passion for pro football?
</P>
<P>
   The McNair victory over LA's zoo full of 800-pound gorillas
stands as a tribute to the operation's preparedness, thoroughness
and, perhaps most important when it came to closing the deal,
mental toughness. The sorest of losers on the Left Coast are
calling McNair a fool for overpaying, but this was not a desperate
act by a desperate man by any means.
</P>
<P>
   The figures, however preposterous they appear, crunch nicely,
thanks to a clever financing structure in combination with the
NFL's license-to-print-money economics. Although McNair was in no
position to drive a hard bargain as he fended off California's
front-running dreamers, he got what he needed to get _ a guaranteed
future Super Bowl for Houston included _ when he needed to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Heeding the advice of his inner circle of associates, he
demanded an answer Wednesday, not in November or March. That's why
it was decided a week ago to stop the haggling and put $700 million
on the table, take it or leave it.
</P>
<P>
   The new Cleveland Browns, working with prearranged terms, needed
six weeks to properly tweak their franchise agreement. McNair and
his people took only six days, and they were negotiating on the
fly.
</P>
<P>
   The document, by the way, is almost a foot thick. And it wasn't
handed over in full to the expansion committee until a half-hour
before it convened. McNair, not yet dressed for the day and groggy
from lack of sleep, according to witnesses, signed off on it
shortly before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   What wasn't immediately handed over was the $70 million letter
of credit, the down payment the NFL had insisted upon. That was
given to commissioner Paul Tagliabue only after the expansion
committee formally had endorsed Houston's ironclad proposal over
the pie-in-the-sky LA schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, it wouldn't be an open-ended assurance of the
seriousness of Houston's intent, either. The letter of credit was
expressly written to expire at midnight Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't going to let them drag the process out any
longer,'' one of McNair's closest advisers said. ``The offer was
coming off the table if they hadn't reached a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The offer almost had come off the table around midnight Tuesday
when an attempt was made to remove the Houston-hosted Super Bowl
from the equation, a key element that had been negotiated into any
potential agreement during McNair's meeting at the NFL's offices
Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   An unnamed league official claimed _ bogusly, for some reason _
a huge convention scheduled for the city in January 2004 would make
it impossible for the necessary number of hotel rooms to be
available for the ticket holders. Documents confirming Houston's
capacity to handle every fathomable requirement for a Super Bowl
hurriedly were faxed to Atlanta, and the storm blew over.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could have been a deal-breaker for sure,'' said a McNair
associate.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Billy Shakespeare told us, all's well that ends well.
Apparently, the only thing with which McNair didn't leave Atlanta
was a guarantee from the NFL his football team would be a
participant in Houston's Super Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
