<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0428 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-APPLEWHITE-HNS &LR;      10-08 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-APPLEWHITE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Some may think of it as trauma-induced amnesia.
</P>
<P>
   Major Applewhite calls it a short memory.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it is what keeps the 6-1, 205-pound sophomore coming
back strong.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas quarterback was under siege the entire afternoon last
Saturday against Kansas State, and it was obvious to all that he
would be harried by the Wildcats every time he dropped into the
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   But Applewhite wasn't fazed. No fear, no happy feet, no ducking
his head and pleading for mercy no, not Major.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I was getting hit doesn't mean I wasn't going to
stand in the pocket,'' Applewhite said. ``I was going to stand in
there strong and try to complete the ball. So what if I get hit?
That's part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was particularly part of the Kansas State game. Applewhite
was sacked five times and took untold hits in the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Because of K-State's defense, Applewhite had his worst college
game. He completed 19 of 37 passes for 271 yards and threw three
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, standing fearlessly in the pocket led to three
fumbles. All told, the Wildcats turned six turnovers by Applewhite
into 26 points in a 35-17 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite's take on the game: ``Forget about it. Get ready for
OU.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll see how well he heeds his own advice when the Longhorns
face Oklahoma on Saturday in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have such a short-term memory,'' Applewhite said. ``That's
what you have to do as a quarterback. I don't even remember most of
the games last year. I remember some of them, but I don't remember
a whole lot about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People on the field that have to have the shortest memory are
the quarterbacks and the cornerbacks. If a cornerback gets beat on
a 40-yard bomb, he's got to turn right back around on the next play
and play man-to-man coverage again. You can't think about it (being
beaten). That's what separates good ones from bad ones.''
</P>
<P>
   In just over a year on the job (16 starts), Applewhite has
proved to be one of the good ones.
</P>
<P>
   At his current pace, he will shatter every Texas passing record.
</P>
<P>
   He already holds or shares 19 school records, including average
yards per game (248.0), passing yards in a single game (408) and
longest pass play, a 97-yard touchdown toss to Wane McGarity in
last year's Red River Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   He has thrown for at least 200 yards and one touchdown in each
of his 16 starts (another record). But the last game on that list
was a subpar performance. It was so bad, in fact, that Applewhite
had trouble recalling one similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in seventh grade I had a bad game like this, but it
didn't make the papers,'' Applewhite joked, though he later would
say he never played that poorly in seventh grade. ``I would
consider it (Kansas State) my one bad game. There were some games
where I didn't play excellent but I didn't play bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was my one bad game, but you can't have bad games. That's
the way I look at it. I can't have bad games if we want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   A thinking man's quarterback because he has to be, thanks to
average size and arm strength, Applewhite hit the film room for
nearly three hours early Sunday morning after the K-State loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sick; I didn't sleep,'' Applewhite said. ``It's
disappointing because you let yourself down. It's disappointing
because fans are upset, and that bothers you. You can't avoid that
as a player. You try to avoid listening and try to hope that all
the voices are benign, but they're not. You just kind of get over
it, and I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it a lot, and the only thing that kept coming
to my head was, You can't play that game over again, so shut up.
And I did. You'll never get that one back, so get ready for OU.
That's the only way to redeem ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to bouncing back, teammates believe Applewhite
accomplishes that from play to play, let alone game to game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's character in the way he's able to come back and regroup
and have control over the huddle and just keep it positive when
things aren't going well,'' split end Ryan Nunez said. ``Looking at
the film and some of the shots that he took, I got a lot of respect
for him and the things he goes through. The abuse that he gets on
and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll bounce back this week, and he'll be raring to go against
Oklahoma. So will everybody, but him in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   The ability to bounce back is but one thing that makes
Applewhite special. He intently breaks down every defense and knows
its tendencies. He's rarely caught off guard by a formation.
</P>
<P>
   Even Kansas State, which brought a multitude of blitzers from
all angles, could not surprise Applewhite. The biggest problem for
Texas was its offensive line didn't block well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we give him time to throw the ball he's deadly, lethal back
there,'' Nunez said.
</P>
<P>
   And a shoddy memory makes him even more deadly. Last week is
over. On to the Sooners.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team, you can't let K-State beat you twice,'' Applewhite
said. ``You have to get up, grow up and go out and play. And that's
what we're going to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
