<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE'S HAT TRICK LIFTS KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ Luc Robitaille knows Andy Murray can only say so much.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie coach's buzzword for this season is accountability,
but without his top players buying into the program, Murray knows
there would be meltdowns along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, who lived through one in Wednesday's brutal loss to
Florida, responded Thursday with three power-play goals in a 5-2
victory against the Tampa Bay Lightning.
</P>
<P>
   It gave him an NHL-leading six goals in just four games and
helped raise the Kings' record to 3-1 on their season-opening,
seven-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   But it only tells part of the story.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, Murray, who was better known as a former high
school coach than the respected longtime assistant he really was,
went to Robitaille and captain Rob Blake to say they held the real
power.
</P>
<P>
   Murray needed them in better shape than ever and carrying a
positive message to younger teammates who became fractured last
year under former coach Larry Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, once one of the league's premier scorers, had
rebounded from several down years in Pittsburgh and New York to
score 39 goals last season, including the 500th of his career. The
reason was his commitment to conditioning, which blossomed under
strength coach Joe Horrigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way the team has played all around, but there is no
question of the weight Luc carries around here,'' said Blake, who
also scored a power-play goal. ``The guys see what he is doing on
the ice and it sets a tone. When you work that hard to get better,
other players follow.''
</P>
<P>
   As with the Kings' second line, which still does not have a
point in the first four games but which pressured Lightning goalie
Darren Puppa all night. Donald Audette hit the post late in the
second period with a ring that awoke the crowd of 10,614 at the Ice
Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Or Stephane Fiset, who was in goal Wednesday night when the
Panthers scored two goals in a 20-second stretch during the final
two minutes, then added an empty-netter to hand the Kings an
embarrassing 4-2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset, who started the first three games of the season, was
given Thursday night off, but entered a tie game to start the
second period after Jamie Storr strained his right groin.
</P>
<P>
   Blake scored 24 seconds into the period for the eventual winning
goal and Fiset stopped all 17 shots he faced the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   There were others, such as rookie defenseman Frantisek Kaberle,
who recorded two assists for his first NHL points. Even assistants
Dave Tippett (power play) and Mark Hardy (penalty killing) received
credit from Murray for pulling the team together after the coach
held a lengthy meeting earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, they helped erase the dismal memory from the night
before. But leading the way was Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goals are the result of the hard work,'' Robitaille said.
``We have a good thing here, but we have to stay focused. Nobody
wanted to see what happened (Wednesday), but it was important to
see the team put it behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen right away.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were flat for the first 10 minutes against Tampa Bay,
even trailing 1-0 on a goal by Stan Drulia, who hadn't scored an
NHL goal since Nov. 23, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   On the play, veteran defenseman Garry Galley bumped into Storr
just before Drulia's shot.
</P>
<P>
   Galley redeemed himself with his first goal of the season and
Robitaille made it 2-1 with 8:10 left in the first when he
rebounded a shot by Ziggy Palffy.
</P>
<P>
   Blake got his goal in the first minute of the second period and
Robitaille added his second by jamming the puck past Puppa late in
the period.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille completed the hat trick with 3:09 left in the game
when he attempted a pass to Palffy in front of the Lightning goal.
Palffy swung and missed because the puck hit Puppa's stick and
trickled in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luc isn't always on the ice, but he has had a great start and
that has had an effect on everybody,'' general manager Dave Taylor
said. ``A couple of years ago, Luc was getting booed and he decided
to make a change. That is now the team's plan, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0430 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-08 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
JOSE Lima's personality hits you like one of his favorite baseball
pranks _ a smack in the face with a shaving-cream pie.
</P>
<P>
   Lima wiggles and gyrates. He talks loudly, makes bold
predictions, slide-steps and barks back at the opposing bench when
they start talking trash. Lima stares boldly at the camera with
those dancing, mischievous eyes of his and shouts his favorite
saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``Be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Mike Hampton. The anti-Lima.
</P>
<P>
   While Lima wears his personality on his sleeve, Hampton tucks
his away in his shoe like a kid hiding lunch money.
</P>
<P>
   The mischief certainly is there, and you can count on it. But
usually it shows itself only when Hampton feels the need to break
the tension or set the tone.
</P>
<P>
   Before a recent big game, Astros closer Billy Wagner was talking
to the media and lamenting his recent lack of save opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who drafts me in their fantasy baseball league is
stupid,'' Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton walked by as Wagner spoke and without breaking a stride,
or a smile, quietly uttered, ``No kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lima can express an opinion or tell it like it is in
25,000 words or less, sometimes Hampton doesn't need any.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday in Atlanta after the Astros' 5-1 loss to the
Braves, someone pointed to a sportswriter who has a Cy Young Award
vote and told Hampton, ``He didn't vote for you. He voted for Randy
Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, straight-faced, said nothing, but as he walked away
mockingly acted as if he was pulling a knife out of his back.
</P>
<P>
   It also was Hampton who, at an exhibition game in San Antonio
last April, finally had had enough of San Antonio Missions mascot
``Henry the Puffy Taco'' running through the Astros' dugout. As the
mascot ran past the bench one too many times, Hampton exploded from
his seat and blindsided the mascot, taking the Taco to the ground
and making the Taco not just puffy but probably swollen, too.
</P>
<P>
   Before the mascot regained his senses enough to get up and see
who had smacked him, Hampton already was back on the bench _
straight-faced _ watching the game as if nothing had happened.
Teammates practically bit through their bottom lips, laughing,
trying not to identify the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the puffy tackle, Hampton responded through
that dead-serious stare of his: ``It wasn't me. It was a
conspiracy. Someone was wearing my jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton also coined the popular clubhouse phrase ``Killer
Fleas,'' after Bagwell and Craig Biggio struggled at the plate in
the Division Series against the Braves two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the most significant thing about that last quote:
Hampton got away with it. Anyone else, and the veterans might have
been agitated.
</P>
<P>
   But this team respects Hampton as much as any player in the
clubhouse. They know what he is.
</P>
<P>
   He is every bit the sly one, every bit the spirited one, but his
delivery is like his pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Clever. Quiet. Devilish. It's what the Astros need now more than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton is understatement to Lima's overstatement. He is the
well-placed one-liner to Lima's prop comedy.
</P>
<P>
   We mention all of this only because today at the Astrodome it
can only be called Hampton Time.
</P>
<P>
   If you think the Astros have begun a typical postseason slide
with their one-hit loss that left this series tied at one game
apiece Wednesday, well be careful.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton knows the score. He figures to be the bulldog on the
mound, as always. He figures to be sly, quiet, clever. Nibble on
this corner. Toy with that corner. Throw a breaking ball when
they're expecting a fastball. Take the cutter outside when they're
expecting something inside.
</P>
<P>
   He figures to give the Astros what they need more than ever. If
there is one pitcher the Astros need as this Division Series is
perilously close to slipping away, it is Hampton. And there he will
be for the 3 p.m. start at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Lima often has called himself the ``stopper'' for this Astros
team _ the guy who turns around a bad trend. But really, while this
is not to cast any aspersions on Lima's superb season, the real
stopper for the Astros has been the real prankster.
</P>
<P>
   By having to start Hampton today because they needed him to
clinch the division title on the last day of the regular season,
it's as if the Astros have hidden their lunch money in their shoes.
They know where to find their meal ticket _ behind those
deceptively steely, serious eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton won a league-leading 22 games this season, but did you
know 10 of those victories came the day after an Astros loss?
</P>
<P>
   Looks can be deceiving. He is the sly, clever and cunning one on
the field and off. He is the Astros' stopper. And if Hampton cannot
turn this series back in their favor today, probably no one can.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the Killer Fleas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
