<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ For as long as Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas has been describing himself as a ``compassionate
conservative,'' Republicans and Democrats alike have wondered
whether the phrase was a call for a flexible new ideology or an
attempt to put a friendlier face on an essentially unchanged
philosophy. But as he starts to set out specific positions,
particularly on taxes and economic policy, Bush is by no means
abandoning the basic conservative principles that have defined the
party. He is clearly attempting a delicate balancing act. By
Richard W. Stevenson with Frank Bruni.
