<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-OFFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOMING RANGER BATS ARE SURPRISINGLY SILENT
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During the regular season, the Texas Rangers had a
.293 team batting average that led both leagues, their 945 runs
ranked second behind the Cleveland Indians, and they led both
leagues in hits, total bases and slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   But in this American League division series with the Yankees,
they're the Texas Impostors. They're hitting .148.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees holding a 2-0 lead in the three-of-five game
series that resumes on Saturday night in Texas, the Rangers have
scored one run _ Juan Gonzalez's fourth-inning homer in Thursday
night's 3-1 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates, the Rangers' manager, shuffled his batting order,
moving shortstop Royce Clayton to leadoff and left fielder Rusty
Greer to the second spot ahead of catcher Ivan (Pudge) Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, they,'' said Oates, alluding to Clayton and Greer,
``can get on base in front of Pudge and Juan.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton and Greer not only never got on base, but didn't deliver
in the fifth with runners on third and second.
</P>
<P>
   With Roberto Kelly on third and Lee Stevens on second with none
out and the Rangers leading, 1-0, Mark McLemore worked the count to
three balls and no strikes, but then struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get it done,'' McLemore would say later. ``It was
key. It hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton bounced to Scott Brosius as Kelly stayed at third, then
Greer fanned.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the game,'' Clayton said. ``On a 2-1 count, you think
you're in a good situation. I had laid off two faders away. I
thought the third pitch was low. The 2-1 pitch was a breaking ball,
and sometimes the bat head rolls over the top. I didn't get a good
enough pitch to hit to the other side or in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Every so often with microphones and notebooks in front of him,
Clayton would say, ``I'd give anything to get that at-bat back.''
</P>
<P>
   So would Greer, who had drawn two walks in Tuesday night's
opener but has yet to get a hit in this series in 6 official
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``On 3 and 2, he threw a pitch I wasn't expecting,'' Greer said,
alluding to Andy Pettitte, the Yankee left hander. ``I was
expecting something harder. I was way out in front of it and just
waved at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Oates talked about how he wanted the Rangers to
swing with what he called ``controlled aggressiveness,'' as opposed
to their ``passive patience'' Tuesday night in a two-hit, 8-0 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at tapes, we didn't have a whole lot of bat speed in
our swings,'' Oates said. ``We were too passive.''
</P>
<P>
   At least on Thursday night the Rangers had seven hits, including
two by Rafael Palmeiro, their designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a better chance of being successful swinging
the bats like we did in this game,'' Oates said. ``We had more
hits. I'm not sure we made more outs on pitches out of the strike
zone, but I know that we looked like we had a chance to do
something with the baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
