<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0459 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-MCCLAIN-COLUMN-HN     10-08 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCCLAIN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John 
McClain
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
When Houston football fans are distributing credit for helping our
city blow away Los Angeles for the 32nd franchise, they should not
overlook Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, the Dallas Cowboys' owner, is Houston's newest best
friend. He was instrumental in helping Houston get the expansion
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   So, as the song goes, ``All you Cowboys fans stand up and
cheer.'' This week, at least, we should all be Cowboys fans. And
that's blasphemy for some of us.
</P>
<P>
   Jones used his considerable influence and public-relations
skills to stump for Houston. His goal was to convince the owners
and NFL executives that he knew what was best financially for the
league in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Jones may be from Arkansas, but he had in mind what was best for
Texas as well as the NFL. Thankfully, 28 other owners lined up
behind him when it came to selecting Houston or Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 11 years, the owners have learned enough about
Jones to know that when he preaches to them about money, they'd
better grab their wallets or call their investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones turned a $180 million investment in 1989 into the most
valuable franchise in professional sports. If he put the Cowboys
and Texas Stadium on the market, they might go for close to $1.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous, you say? In what some say is closer to a $900
million deal, Daniel Snyder bought the Redskins and Jack Kent Cooke
Stadium this year. He says he will put another $50 million into the
stadium, parking and roads.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if the Cowboys and Texas Stadium were available. Just
think of the ego massage a multibillionaire could get by buying
them. Of course, Jones has no interest in selling. He's having way
too much fun, especially when he wins a long, difficult battle for
Houston, which he knew all along would be best for the league.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Jones was a tireless worker behind the scenes. There
were two things he wanted to achieve, and he's halfway there.
</P>
<P>
   Jones watched Houston win the 32nd franchise. Now, he wants to
help the Raiders return to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Jones believes that if the Raiders move back to LA, it will end
lawsuits that could cost the league more than $1 billion. He
doesn't think the Bay Area needs two teams. And it would put a
franchise in the nation's second-largest city and television
market. But the Raiders issue is a long way from being solved.
</P>
<P>
   First, Jones had to help take care of Houston. He knew Houston's
plan was solid. He knew Houston was an NFL hotbed that was hungry
for another franchise to replace the Oilers. He understood that the
Oilers' move to Tennessee had nothing to do with fan support on
Sundays and everything to do with their feelings for owner Bud
Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Jones studied Houston's stadium financial plan. He reminded
others that the $195 million in public money committed by Houston
and Harris County showed the strong commitment on the part of the
fans and politicians. He pointed out that Los Angeles had no public
money and probably wouldn't get any, no matter how long the league
waited.
</P>
<P>
   Jones became a Bob McNair fan. He knew McNair had the resources
and the drive to become ``one of the five best owners'' in the
league. Jones was looking for a new partner who had a vision like
his, a vision that would help the NFL become even more popular and
powerful worldwide and, ultimately, an even bigger money maker for
32 owners.
</P>
<P>
   Once Jones went public in August about the importance of the NFL
selecting Houston over Los Angeles, people began to take Houston
more seriously. Jones beat that drum so hard that many actually
began to change their opinion about the necessity of having Los
Angeles back in the league.
</P>
<P>
   For the next two months, Jones favored Houston so strongly that
he did everything but douse himself with gasoline and set himself
on fire to get attention so people would listen to him.
</P>
<P>
   Jones told everyone who listened that Houston would get the
expansion team, and he was happy to explain why it should. He
always said having the expansion team in Houston was best for the
league. When he got around the owners, he rubbed elbows and twisted
arms. Fortunately, none broke.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they would still be playing in the NFC and AFC,
Jones wanted Dallas and Houston to play every year under a new
realignment and scheduling plan that is supposed to take care of
natural rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Jones knows that the Cowboys and Oilers set attendance records
in Tokyo, Mexico City and El Paso. And those were preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the expansion process, Jones' critics predicted there
was no way he would be in Houston's corner. They said when Jones
looked at our vacant market, he saw Silver and Blue. He may have,
but when he wanted to see more green, he knew Houston needed
another team.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Cowboys are already America's team. And Japan's
team. And Mexico's team. And Texas' team, too.
</P>
<P>
   Jones knew that Texas needed another team, and he saw the
endless marketing possibilities with a successful franchise
operated by a popular owner with deep pockets. In Jones' mind,
McNair was ideal.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Jones was quietly working to help return the
Raiders to Los Angeles. Talk about a hard sell. When owner Al Davis
bolted Los Angeles for Oakland, he left behind a lot of bad
feelings on the part of fans, media, politicians and business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   After commissioner Paul Tagliabue announced Houston as the 32nd
franchise, he said he didn't believe another team would move for a
while. Jones said just the opposite. He said the Houston decision
cleared the way for Los Angeles to get an existing team.
</P>
<P>
   And sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is getting Los Angeles to let bygones be bygones
with Davis, who had a deal for a new stadium at Hollywood Park. His
lawsuit claims the NFL interfered with his deal at Hollywood Park
and cost him millions, perhaps billions. League sources say there's
a good chance he might win the suit.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones needs help, McNair should volunteer. That's the least
he can do. After all, Davis refused to abstain when the Houston
vote was taken. Davis voted yes. And Davis would rather wear a
turquoise Raiders jump suit than do anything but abstain in voting
on most league issues. Even if that issue was in his best
interests.
</P>
<P>
   John McClain covers the NFL for the Chronicle. His column
appears on Fridays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
