<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAJPAYEE-INDIA-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAJPAYEE: BULLDOG BRAHMIN WITH CHURCHILL'S TOUCH  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This timely 425-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By PETER POPHAM  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 52 years, India has at last found a leader it likes who is
not a member of Jawaharlal Nehru's family.
</P>
<P>
   Atal Behari Vajpayee, who is likely to start his third term as
Prime Minister in the next few days, is an amateur poet, a Hindu
romantic, a parliamentarian for more than 40 years, a lyrical
orator, a Brahmin and an honest man.
</P>
<P>
   He is, his opponents allege, ``a good man in the wrong party'';
a ``mask'' for the fanatics and fascists who make themselves amply
at home in the Hindu nationalist family.
</P>
<P>
   To his party before the last election one and a half years ago
he was ``the man India awaits.''
</P>
<P>
   Against great odds, Vajpayee has justified the trust his party
has placed in him, though as much by luck as good judgment.
</P>
<P>
   He began his term last year in dramatic fashion by staging five
nuclear tests and drawing down the wrath of the world. Delhi's
diplomatic grapevine has been humming with speculation that they
might do some more tests on winning this election.
</P>
<P>
   By the time his parliament was defeated in parliament in April,
thanks to the defection of an ally, he looked like a blundering old
man _ he is 74 _ and way out of his depth.
</P>
<P>
   He could make India a nuclear power, but could not control the
price of onions _ let alone his coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
   When he had been relegated to the status of ``caretaker prime
minister'' Vajpayee got lucky. His luck took an unlikely form.
Pakistani troops infiltrated deep into Indian territory above
Kargil in Kashmir, and seized strategic positions high in the
mountains. By the time they were discovered in early May they were
practically unassailable.
</P>
<P>
   That was a great embarrassment for India, but Vajpayee turned
this debacle into a diplomatic and military triumph. The
infiltrators were met by massive Indian force, but the government
resisted powerful military persuasion to end the conflict quickly
by crossing the cease-fire line, the so-called Line of Control.
</P>
<P>
   This restraint won international applause, and was followed by a
massive diplomatic effort to persuade world leaders that Pakistan
was the aggressor, which left Pakistan isolated.
</P>
<P>
   Reckless enough to try to bomb his way to the top table; but
calm under heavy pressure: that is the paradoxical impression
Vajpayee made.
</P>
<P>
   There has long been something Churchillian about him. The Kargil
crisis reinforced the image of a bulldog brahmin. His popularity
now transcends party and regional lines. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 425-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
