<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2577 -- Sept. 23, 1999 &QR;  We are
offering the following articles for sale. Please contact us for
availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. STYLE OF THE NILE In Egypt in the 14th century B.C.,
Nefertiti was a paragon -- her name meant ``the beauty has come.''
Yet she did not rely on her natural looks alone. She applied makeup
in bold strokes, outlining her almond-shaped eyes in black and
darkening her brows. So did her husband, the pharoah. This article
describes how the ancient Egyptians created the chemistry and
cosmetics that marked their unique look. By Robert Kunzig. From
Discover magazine. 1,200 words + photos.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
SEEKING HELP FOR THE DOLLAR SIDE OF DIVORCE In the world of
no-fault divorces, a new financial expert has evolved - the
certified divorce planner. Women, in particular, need the help of
an advisor who understands the long-term implications of various
financial settlements. By Diane Lacey Allen. NYT Regional
Newspapers. 1,000 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
FOOD ALSO MEANS IDENTITY The French have a new word for it, ``la
malbouffe.'' While it means approximately ``bad chow,'' it is
coming to express all the irritation, resistance and fear of
vulnerability that is directed against America, as the leader and
leading menace of globalization. By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
FROM NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A France and Spain)
</P>
<P>
   (a) Cool Running A simple idea could make flying much safer.
Tests in the US have shown that cooling fuel before it is put into
aircraft prevents explosive fumes building up in the fuel tanks. By
Paul Marks. 500 words. (b) Unchain Your Mind Not getting enough
sleep? Then you are cheating your brain out of the eight hours it
needs to learn properly. Helen Phillips eavesdrops on the
night-long seminar inside your head. 1,800 words. (c) Follow My
Leader Why build giant space telescopes when a few small spacecraft
flying in formation could do a better job for a fraction of the
cost? By Catherine Zandonella. 1,800 words.
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   5. FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES BOOK REVIEW :
</P>
<P>
   (a) The Fall of Man Men, Susan Faludi says, can now be men only
by pretending to be men. Their plight awakens in her a tender
sympathy for a sex she now suspects is in greater need of
liberation than her own. 1,200 words. (b) Liquid Asset Esther
Williams, whose all-American good looks and swimming talent turned
her into a Hollywood star, has now written her memoirs. 1,200
words. (c) Still Nothing To Wear A fashion writer explores how
marketing has changed the rag trade. 1,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
THE SHADOWS OF THE FIRST WORLD Hurricane Floyd seemed to expose the
deep weakness of the American empire, showing that the First World
is, sometimes, as brittle or more so than the Third World. Natural
catastrophes may happen anywhere and it is not the storms that
expose the weakness of the First World, but rather the resources
and capacities of the human beings to face them. By Tomas Eloy
Martinez. 1,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   (a) Male Contraceptive Millions of men may be taking a male
contraceptive pill without knowing they are doing so. Calcium
channel blockers (commonly prescribed for high blood pressure,)
also act to prevent fertilization by a man's sperm. 500 words. (b)
Snoring Disrupts Partner's Sleep A study performed by the Mayo
Clinic found that people who sleep with a partner who snores lose a
good amount of sleep each night. Successful treatment of snoring
and obstructive sleep apnea resulted in better quality and longer
sleep periods for the partner. 500 words. (c) Children Get
``Bedtime Pass'' To Good Behaviour A new behavioural technique that
prevents children from crying out and leaving their bedrooms after
bedtime may allow children and parents to sleep easier. 500 words.
