<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0511 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HMOS08-COX     10-08 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMOS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House HMO reform bill is triumph for Norwood
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House approved a massive overhaul of the
managed health care industry Thursday that gives patients broad
rights to sue their health insurer for denying care and to choose
their own doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was a significant political victory for Rep.
Charlie Norwood (R-Ga). As the bill's chief architect, he handily
de- feated the wishes of his own party's top leaders, who favored a
far more limited legal recourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now on top of Hamburger Hill,'' said an ebullient
Norwood immediately after the 275-151 vote. He was referring to a
Vietnam War battle in which U.S. troops withstood 11 bloody
assaults before prevailing.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood's bill, co-authored by Rep. John Dingell (D-Mich.), won
the support of 67 Republicans and 206 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Georgia delegation, Norwood was joined by Republicans
Bob Barr and Saxby Chambliss and Democrats Sanford Bishop, John
Lewis and Cynthia McKin- ney. ``The final victory was larger than
anyone predicted,'' said Rep. Mark Foley (R-Fla.), an early backer
of the Norwood-Dingell plan. ``The employers may not like it, but
the employees will love it.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote drew an intensive lobbying campaign, with President
Clinton personally calling lawmakers from Air Force One and
Republican leaders making their own rounds in an effort to avoid an
embarrassing defeat for House Speaker Dennis Hastert (R-Ill.).
</P>
<P>
   ``The passage of this bill represents a major victory for every
family and every health plan,'' Clinton said. ``It shows that
America is no longer willing to allow unfeeling practices of some
health plans to add to the pain of injury or disease. It proves
that America is committed to putting patients first.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in New York, Clinton said he was pleased the House had
rejected a ``watered-down'' measure put forth by Republicans Tom
Coburn of Oklahoma and John Shadegg of Arizona. That bill, which
had the blessing of Hastert and other Republican leaders, went down
238-193.
</P>
<P>
   Georgians voting for the defeated GOP alternative were Chambliss
and fellow Republicans Mac Collins, Nathan Deal, Johnny Isakson,
Jack Kingston and John Linder.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwood-Dingell bill allows patients to sue for damages if a
health insurance company denies or delays care at any point.
Patients can also seek remedy from an external review panel.
</P>
<P>
   The defeated Coburn-Shadegg bill would have required patients to
exhaust all administrative appeals before taking a managed health
care company to court. And then lawsuits would have been restricted
to federal courts, where monetary damages are usually lower, unless
the patient lived in a state where such lawsuits are permitted.
</P>
<P>
   As well as giving patients the right to choose a doctor, the
Norwood-Dingell bill would allow women to seek care from
obstetricians and gynecologists and children to see a pediatrician
without going first to a primary care physician.
</P>
<P>
   Health insurance plans would be required to pay for emergency
room care, and doctors would be allowed to talk to patients without
worrying about violating managed care rules.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was passionate and fiery. Democrats portrayed
Republicans as protectors of the health insurance industry;
Republicans painted Democrats as protectors of the trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the final vote, Rep. Greg Ganske (R-Iowa) wheeled
7-year-old James Adams of Atlanta to the floor of the House to show
what can happen under a managed care company's rules.
</P>
<P>
   Adams lost his forearms and legs to gangrene after his insurance
company ordered his parents to take him to a hospital about 60
miles away for treatment of a 104-degree fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had a finger and you pricked it, it would bleed. He's
not an anecdote,'' said Ganske, as Adams sat playing in the front
row of the House chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The right to sue was at the heart of arguments on both sides. A
1974 federal law intended to protect employee health and pension
plans had the unintended effect of granting liability protection to
managed care companies.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert and other Republican leaders said their plan would keep
frivolous lawsuits to a minimum. Norwood and Dingell ar- gued it
created so many obstacles that the patient might be dead by the
time they finished appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert even went to the floor to appeal to lawmakers. ``We've
got a solid, balanced approach that I urge you to support,'' the
speaker said. ``The difference in these bills is how far you go,
how far you give license to the trial lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats argued that the GOP plan did not go far enough.
``It fails to hold health care providers accountable. It lets them
off the hook,'' said Minority Leader Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.).
</P>
<P>
   When his son had terminal cancer in 1972, Gephardt said, he was
fortunate to have insurance that allowed him to go to a specialist
who could find a special treatment. Under today's health care
system, his son would be denied that opportunity, Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the final vote, Norwood made a final, emotional
plea: ``I did everything I could do to get the Republicans to take
this issue. I realized for us to change the law in this country, we
have to do it in a bipartisan
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
