<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Two fates are sealed by a slap in
the face
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches From Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, at
least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   (A photo of Bronzie and Clyde R. Ray taken 20 years ago is
available by calling CoxNet at 404-526-5456.)
</P>
<P>
   By Clyde R. Ray
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ It was a beautiful balmy Sunday afternoon in June
1935 when I first met Bronzie Lee Harris.
</P>
<P>
   For about a year before that, a friend of mine who dated
Bronzie's sister had been trying to ``fix us up.''
</P>
<P>
   Although I didn't tell this to my friend, I was reluctant to
date Bronzie because I thought she was a redhead like me, having
decided that Bronzie was a nickname for a red-haired girl.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, was I in for a shock.
</P>
<P>
   Then came that fateful afternoon when a group of us boys drove
out to Fowler's Lake, a favorite swimming hole for our younger set.
</P>
<P>
   Lo and behold, Bronzie and some of her girlfriends had the same
idea. So, finally, I was introduced to Bronzie, and I mentally
castigated myself for my previous stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   To grossly understate the case, Bronzie was a living doll. Her
hair was a satiny, coal-black halo framing a face so beautiful that
she could well have been the model for Leonardo da Vinci's ``Mona
Lisa.''
</P>
<P>
   As you may judge, I was badly smitten, a true case of love at
first sight.
</P>
<P>
   I went to church with her that night. After church, several boys
and girls got together at a friend's home. We had homemade freezer
ice cream and cake. Then we gathered around the piano and joyously
sang Christian and love songs.
</P>
<P>
   I was standing next to Bronzie. The magic of her ethereal beauty
suddenly overcame me. Impulsively, I reached out, put my arms
around her and kissed her full on the lips.
</P>
<P>
   Her reaction was quick and meaningful. She sharply slapped my
face.
</P>
<P>
   I apologized but told her that she was so attractive and
irresistible that I simply couldn't help myself.
</P>
<P>
   Bronzie accepted my apology and during the course of the evening
implied in so many words that I might call on her. I respected her
so much for that slap that from then on she was the only girl for
me.
</P>
<P>
   We had a wonderful year of courtship, and it's been the same
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   On July 26, 1999, we celebrated our 63rd wedding anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Bronzie had one of the finest careers in our society: That of
housewife and mother of our two children.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Bronzie, for the more than 60,000 meals you've
cooked, besides all those good cakes, and for the washing and
ironing you've slaved over for more than six decades.
</P>
<P>
   That trip to Fowler's Lake in June 1935 turned out to be the
most important journey of my life.
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches From
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville
stories, visit http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
