<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Printing the good news
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The good news came the other day in the form of a phone call. My
second grandchild will be a little girl. And, thanks to the
miracles of modern medicine, there she was on videotape, unnamed
and a bit more than a tadpole, swimming around in her mother's
belly. Perfectly formed, notably active, said the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Mira, my 3-year-old granddaughter, was wonderfully happy. She
has been lobbying, vociferously, for a baby sister. Mira has been
learning the facts _ well, a fact or two _ of life. She has been
hugging and kissing her mommy's somewhat pregnant belly.
</P>
<P>
   I had a talk with Mira a few days before the arrival of the good
news. Do you want a baby brother or a baby sister? I asked, the way
adults do in their most boring manifestations. Baby sister, she
said. You know, Mira, I said, hoping to drop in a bit of education,
it could be a baby brother, and that would be just as good. She
looked at me peculiarly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What're you worried about?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   You can't even patronize a 3-year-old these days.
Whippersnapper.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
