A0559 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LATHAM-COLUMN09-COX     10-08 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We may be paying for our neglect of the arts in school
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ I don't remember much about prayer in school,
though I can remember being the student selected to read the prayer
over the loud speaker more than a few times.
</P>
<P>
   I think school administrators kept picking me because they hoped
that the message would eventually sink in. Those of us who acted
most like heathens got selected the most.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the word ``amen'' I don't remember a single word of a
single prayer ever uttered in school and I am not among those who
believes that it is of much worth to read a prayer over the
intercom.
</P>
<P>
   I think prayer _ one student to one God _ is of great worth, of
course, and that can be done anytime, anywhere without anyone ever
knowing.
</P>
<P>
   So I don't really buy it when people say that the problems with
school violence stem from taking God out of school. Indeed, God is
much more a part of school today than it ever was when I was a
student.
</P>
<P>
   Back in my high school days, the few students who would have
admitted to being religious were called ``Jesus freaks'' and were
mostly derided by other students. Unlike Marshall High School, you
never would have had enough people to encircle a flagpole before
school to pray.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike the days when God's part in school was mostly rote,
these students have real feelings and beliefs and they let them
show.
</P>
<P>
   God out of school? That's nonsense. Those who say that haven't
been around schools lately.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other things we've taken out of schools in the
last two decades that haven't had such a revival.
</P>
<P>
   The arts, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   It may strike some of you as implausible that taking the arts
out of school could lead to problems down the line, but it seems a
real possibility to me.
</P>
<P>
   William Shakespeare said ``Music hath charms to soothe the
savage breast,'' and he was right. A pet peeve of mine is when
people _ who obviously have missed instruction in the arts _ change
the last word of that line from ``breast'' to ``beast.''
Shakespeare wasn't talking about calming dogs and cats, he was
talking about humans.
</P>
<P>
   The arts isn't completely out of school and local schools have
some fine arts instructors, but society _ this is happening
everywhere _ has slashed the arts to save money and to meet that
goal of ``getting back to the basics.'' Kids do have to learn to
read, write and do math, but, beyond that, little is more basic
than the arts.
</P>
<P>
   The guess here is that most people over 40 remember sitting in
art class every day going over little postcard-sized pictures of
the great works of art. This was real school work. In a test, you
had the picture and you had to give its correct title and tell who
created it. Likewise, you had to listen to a work of music and do
the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   So, as a sixth-grader, I could identify ``The Last Supper,'' or
``An American Gothic.'' I knew that it was really the ``William
Tell Overture,'' and not the theme from ``The Lone Ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not a deep knowledge of the arts, mind you, but it is
much deeper than we are allowing schools to teach today.
</P>
<P>
   I asked each of my children to describe ``An American Gothic''
for me, perhaps the most recognizable piece of American art ever.
None of them could do it, including the two who have been enrolled
in gifted and talented programs for years.
</P>
<P>
   My oldest son, bless him, first said American Gothics were
people who wore black leather jackets. At least when I described
the painting to him, he knew what I was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   As with all kinds of education, arts instruction can and should
be done in the home.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it strikes me as amazing that we would be willing to pay
for classes pleading with teens not to have sex _ something that
darn sure ought to be done in the home _ while cutting arts
funding.
</P>
<P>
   We'll never know if spending more time on the arts would have
prevented some of the tragedies that we've already faced, but it is
never too late to work to prevent the next one.
</P>
<P>
   As long as we are casting about for ideas, why not try one that
doesn't involve skirting around the First or Second Amendments? An
idea doesn't have to be controversial to work.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (Texas) News
Messenger. His email address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
