r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN09-COX     10-08 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ventura's controversial interview nevertheless honest
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ American voters are like the lass who will not
share her favors until a suitor professes his love, whether he
means it or not.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Gov. Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura is not about to
breathe sweet nothings into the ear of the electorate to court
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura stirred up a hornet's nest with his interview in Playboy
magazine in which he offered candid opinions on a variety of
hot-button subjects.
</P>
<P>
   His answers and observations offended many Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But did Ventura lie?
</P>
<P>
   Did Ventura equivocate?
</P>
<P>
   Did he parse his words?
</P>
<P>
   Did he redefine words?
</P>
<P>
   Did he later say he was misquoted?
</P>
<P>
   Did he claim his comments were taken out of context?
</P>
<P>
   Did he blame the press?
</P>
<P>
   Did he change the subject by claiming a vast conspiracy was out
to get him?
</P>
<P>
   Did he try to excuse his behavior by pointing out that other
politicians in the past also have made inflammatory remarks?
</P>
<P>
   Did he duck any of the questions he was asked?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to all those questions is no, no, no and a thousand
times no.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, people are saying that Ventura is a lousy
politician.
</P>
<P>
   The former professional wrestler has a lot to learn about
politics if he hopes to get elected again, say political pundits.
</P>
<P>
   All it takes to be a political pundit is the willingness to
admit your inability to perform useful labor. The qualifications
are similar to those of an artist.
</P>
<P>
   As an admitted political pundit, I agree with my fellow pundits.
Ventura has a lot to learn about politics _ at least the way
politics have evolved in America.
</P>
<P>
   Today's traditional politicians go out of their way to insert
religious piety into their political campaigns. They talk about
their private religious beliefs and conversions. They do their best
to show the religious trappings of America's main religious
dominations.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they are true to their own pious murmurings in word and
deed is an open question. At least they are playing the political
game as voters have come to expect it to be played.
</P>
<P>
   When Ventura called organized religion ``a sham and a crutch for
weak-minded people who need strength in numbers,'' he definitely
went outside traditional American politics.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's concern with organized religion as practiced in the
United States is that it ``tells people to go out and stick their
noses in other people's business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's concern with organized religion gaining the political
clout needed to get laws passed to restrict individual behavior is
in keeping with his belief that individual Americans should have
sole dominion over their own lives so long as they do not forcibly
interfere with the equal right of others to live as they choose.
</P>
<P>
   This is a view held by the Libertarian Party even though Ventura
is a member of Ross Perot's Reform Party, which is nothing if not a
refuge for nontraditional political beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's views on decriminalizing drugs and prostitution are
consistent with his other nontraditional positions.
</P>
<P>
   When asked his opinion of the Navy Tailhook scandal, Ventura's
response infuriated many Americans even though he said he did not
condone the behavior of the aviators and that the guilty gropers
deserved to be court-martialed.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura is an off-the-wall politician. He tells you what's on
his mind, take it or leave it. I'll take the honesty part.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
