<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0567 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINTER-COLUMN1009-COX     10-08 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN1009-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Today's journalism suffering from colorblindness
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ One thing I learned when I was hired as
editor of a daily newspaper is that you can't be conservative
enough for conservatives or liberal enough for liberals. Certainly
a native Southerner working for a Southern newspaper can't be
liberal enough to suit journalists from other parts of the country
who equate anything below the Mason-Dixon line with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   I had to admit a bit of perverse pleasure when I heard from Bob
Christian, my personal Washington correspondent. Bob is a native of
Tate, Ga., who worked his way from The Atlanta Journal sports
department through high office with Delta and Eastern airlines to
retirement in northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   He sent clippings of a headline and story from the Washington
Post along with the comment that they had caused a big controversy,
prompting a flood of telephone calls, e-mail, and letters to the
Post. Accused of racism, the Post naturally was quick to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   The story began this way:
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE, Sept. 14 _ Martin O'Mallory, a white City Council
member, won the Democratic mayoral nomination today in this
black-majority city. His biggest challenge came from two black
candidates, but he easily outdistanced them.'' The story quickly
explained that a Democratic nomination is tantamount to election in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The offending headline said: ``White man gets mayoral nomination
in Baltimore.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters are taught to cover the ``W's'' in the first
paragraph: Tell who, what, when, where and then get to the why.
Headlines capsule what a story is about. I think my old journalism
professor, Tyus Butler, would give an ``A'' to the Post reporter
who wrote the story and to the copy editor who wrote the headline.
Although we might wish otherwise, race certainly is a part of 1990s
politics. A white mayor following a black mayor in a two-thirds
black city is news.
</P>
<P>
   The Post would now have us believe the candidate's skin color
was no more significant than the fact he plays guitar in a Celtic
band. Somewhere along the way, media folk came up with the foolish
idea of colorblindness, although I keep reading about how white
mayors are succeeding black mayors in New York and Los Angeles, and
are not likely to in Atlanta. Getting color out of today's news is
like pumping water out of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Being colorblind isn't always enough. Cliff Baldowski was about
as close to colorblind as anyone I've known, and it got him in
trouble. Sitting in his church on Cascade Road in South Atlanta,
surrounded by colors quite different from Buckhead, and listening
to the eulogies, I thought about that, and how his bosses at the
newspaper let him down in the twilight of his brilliant career.
</P>
<P>
   In his early years at The Atlanta Constitution, he worked in
harness with Ralph McGill at a time when, as Hal Gulliver reminds
us, ``it took guts to have guts.'' Many a day McGill and Baldy had
to breach a line of Ku Kluxers when they went to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   His cartoons had at least as much impact on Georgia and the
South as the words of prize-winning columnists. He missed some of
the glory that came to others because he was an humble man who
often passed up national subjects to do his skewerings of local
crooks, fat cats, fools and pompous jerks. His hilarious treatment
of ``The Shag Cates Gang'' and their Fulton County courthouse
shenanigans deserved a Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Editorial cartoonists exaggerate features of people they draw.
FDR was characterized by his chin and cigarette holder, Jimmy
Carter by his teeth, Richard Nixon by his nose. Baldy gave Gov.
Lester Maddox, who differed sharply with The Constitution on racial
issues, oversize ears.
</P>
<P>
   When African-American politicians began to hold public office in
Atlanta, they interpreted Baldy's technique as racist. They wanted
all politicians of color to have light skin and Caucasian features.
Troubled by this, Baldy consulted Dr. Martin Luther King. ``Just
draw us like you've been drawing white folks,'' King advised. With
King gone and changes at the newspaper, pressure mounted to make
all African-Americans look like Julian Bond.
</P>
<P>
   When Baldy drew a cartoon of a black city councilman with a hand
in a cookie jar, The Constitution, in what was not that great
newspaper's finest hour, published an apology. The last time I
looked, the gentleman apologized to was serving a jail sentence for
accepting bribes.
</P>
<P>
   If I were colorblind, I wouldn't have noticed that about half
the mourners and one of the preachers at Baldy's funeral were not
white. If the preachers and eulogists had been colorblind, they
wouldn't have talked about how Baldy never succumbed to white
flight, never left his South Atlanta neighborhood, and how he stuck
with his church when the congregation no longer reflected the face
he saw in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Baldowski was a great man. What a fantastic city Atlanta
would be if it had more like him.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
