<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0583 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD09-COX     10-08 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking a flight of fancy on a plane
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sometimes I wonder what a stranger to our craft might
think if he got into the middle of a conversation betwen
woodworkers.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a fellow on the Internet posts a message headed:
</P>
<P>
   ``Need a frog for a No. 8 Stanley plane - help!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, perhaps a No. 8 Stanley is sort of an offshoot of the old
Stearman, you know, the sort of biplane they still use for
crop-dusting, or maybe it's one of those early World War II
fighters. They had some pretty strange craft there at the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was a French aircraft, and this guy is being
extremely insensitive and politically incorrect and is demanding a
French national to fly his antique French airplane.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, maybe it's just some sort of wind-up thing
he's made with room for an amphibian inside, and he's trying to
prove the old adage about how if frogs could only fly, they
wouldn't be bumping their little bottoms all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive me. Sometimes I have these seizures. For those still
with me, Stanley is a trade name, a plane is, of course, a bench
plane used for smoothing and leveling wood, and a frog is the
device that holds the plane iron in place. I cannot imagine why
it's called a frog, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, now, folks, from the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   ``I just finished gluing up a fairly good sized coffee table top
(34 by 53 inches) of 4-inch poplar boards about 3/4 inch thick. The
top is cupped about 1/2 inch. Do I start over with new boards,
being more careful this time (how can I prevent this?) Do I add
some cross boards underneath to try and flatten it by using
screws?''
</P>
<P>
   Preventing it is a lot easier than curing it. Assuming his wood
was dry, I suspect excessive clamp pressure was the problem. He
doesn't say whether the grain was running in the 34-inch dimension
or the 53-inch, but in either case that's too many boards to glue
up at once. The more pieces that are being laminated, the more
there is a tendency for the entire thing to cup under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The thing to do, of course, is to take the nine boards _ if
we're talking about the grain running in the longer direction _ and
glue them up in three sets of three boards each. When they're dry,
glue the three sets together.
</P>
<P>
   As for fixing it, I'd just cut it up again, add another board,
and reglue as above.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
