<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0589 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SCHIZOPHENIA-COX     10-08 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHIZOPHENIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schizophrenia, other diseases require much more than medicine
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The benefits of psychotherapy and social support,
long recognized in treating depressive disorders, also are gaining
acceptance as an essential element in treating schizophrenia and
other mental illnesses that involve psychoses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that people with severe mental illness need more than
a pill and a doctor's visit,'' says Laurie Flynn, executive
director of the National Alliance for the Mentally Ill (NAMI).
Vicki Lynn Bentley of Dayton, founder of the area's Schizophrenics
Anonymous (SA) support group chapter, has known that for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medication is like a Band-Aid,'' says Bentley, explaining
the value of her psychotherapy at the VA Medical Center. ``A person
has symptoms _ hearing voices, anxiety, whatever _ and medication
alone is just like sticking a Band-Aid on a cut without adding any
medicine to it. The cut will take a lot longer to heal, if it ever
does heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Schizophrenia is a disorder characterized by delusions and
hallucinations, according to University of Florida researchers who
reported last month on brain structure differences that could lead
to tools for diagnosing or predicting the illness. The roughly 2.5
million schizophrenics in the United States might hear voices no
one else hears or sense they're being spied on or persecuted, but
they do not have the multiple personalities that pop culture often
erroneously attributes to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's marked by a feeling of: `I don't belong,''' says
psychologist Dennis O'Grady, who treats schizophrenics individually
and works with SA. ```And you're telling me by how you're treating
me that I am correct.'''
</P>
<P>
   Therapy helps schizophrenics see that the world isn't as
threatening and dangerous as their instincts tell them, O'Grady
says. It also can teach them how to cope with everyday stresses,
says Bentley, ``how to think of alternatives rather than suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   From cooking to people skills, she says, the mentally ill need
to learn life fundamentals that others take for granted. ``I don't
know why society thinks if you're mentally ill, you can't learn
anything. Nothing could be farther from the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, NAMI has tried to make support and knowledge
more available for those with psychoses by establishing what it
calls COPE, for Caring, Outreach, Partnership and Education. The
resource program, also directed toward family members, includes a
consumer guide about patient empowerment, a housing guide, a family
guide with productive ways of coping and a resource directory.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
