<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Friday, Oct. 8, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence
at 202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SAT-MINORITIES (Colonie, N.Y.) _ For more than two years, the
Educational Testing Service has been fine-tuning a formula under
which students in certain socioeconomic categories could be labeled
as ``strivers'' and qualify for additional points on the SAT. Some
minority students find the proposal _ which is unlikely to move
beyond the proposal stage _ repugnant, adding to the stereotype
that they are underachievers. By RICK KARLIN.
</P>
<P>
   UFO-MEETING (San Francisco) _ An upcoming meeting between
Silicon Valley high-tech executives, NASA scientists and a
high-profile UFO enthusiast has sparked an investigation by a
government agency. At that meeting, attendees, including scientists
from the NASA Ames Research Center in Mountain View, will discuss
propulsion technologies. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   VISITING-DEER (San Francisco) _ It was sort of a macabre
wildlife marriage of ``Animal Farm'' and ``The Night Before
Christmas'' and it has changed Maggie Clark's whole way of looking
at her friendly neighborhood deer. By LARRY D. HATFIELD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-HEARTS (Undated) _ In the mood for a big, glossy,
super-star-wattage Hollywood romance that goes ... nowhere? If so,
you'll be glad to learn of ``Random Hearts,'' a sleek zero of a
movie that asks whether two gorgeous people can get it on. By AMY
BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-LIMEY (Undated) _ There are no maracas and nary a
wah-wah guitar riff or smacked-up cymbal to speak of, but director
Steven Soderbergh and writer Lem Dobbs' ``The Limey'' is
atmospheric Champagne funk that holds you under its spell long
enough to make you believe Curtis Mayfield is still in the
soundtrack business. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-SUPERSTAR (Undated) _ ``Superstar,'' an odd,
hysterically pointed movie chapter in the ``Saturday Night Live''
heroine's screwball life, offers Mary Katherine Gallagher as a
lunatic manifestation of teenage lust and better role model for
girls than certain multiplatinum pop stars. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-HARSH-REALM (Undated) _ Chris Carter has never been easy on
his audience. The creator of ``The X-Files'' and the late, bizarre
``Millennium'' is a master of wild turns in plot, daring viewers to
try to keep up with him, let alone guess ahead. Carter is at it
again with ``Harsh Realm,'' a Byzantine mind game that after the
first episode will leave you confused but intrigued. By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WASTELAND (Undated) _ ABC now has a semi-decent
twentysomething show (``Wasteland'') to go along with an excellent
new fortysomething show (``Once and Again''). If only it could
offer something for 30-year-olds. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARAGE-DOORS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The manual garage door is almost a
thing of the past. There's nothing like the convenience of an
automatic door and being able to drive into the protection of the
garage. Recent improvements to sensors and door openers have
increased their usefulness. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS. (For release
Sunday, Oct. 10.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LAS-VEGAS (Las Vegas, Nev.) _ The Vegas experience captivates
people in a variety of ways. Some come here to see the bright
lights, glittering celebrities and architectural excesses. Some
come here determined to view it as merely a monument to schlock and
glitz and then go home to tell their friends and neighbors how
tacky it all is. Some come here to get rich quick (a brief list of
the successful ones' names available upon request). By WILLIAM M.
DOWD. (For release Sunday, Oct. 10.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DUCK-HUNTING (Whitehall, N.Y.) _ Wednesday was opening morning
of the first half of the waterfowl season on both the Vermont and
New York sides of Lake Champlain, an incredible habitat for ducks
that I'd witnessed with my own eyes, but only in the off-season. As
promised, it was a phenomenal duck hunt, Champlain-style. By FRED
LeBRUN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ There were the best-received
panhandlers in the history of San Francisco. On Thursday, a dozen
teachers stood on the median strip in front of City Hall, begging
drivers for help and holding signs such as ``Got paper?'' and ``Got
pencils?'' By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Bolton Landing, N.Y.) _ Throughout the 1990s, New
York state has ranked 49th in job creation and No. 2 in combined
state and local per-capita taxes. Cut taxes? Sure, everybody wants
to. But until New Yorkers grasp the true nature of the problem and
submit to combining local governments and school districts to save
money, then nothing much will change. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN-MUSEUM (New York) _ After seeing the controversial
``Sensation'' exhibit at the Brooklyn Museum of Art, I'm inclined
to continue believing that the First Amendment is superior to the
opinion of a mayor. But maybe they should change the name of the
show to ``Sensationalized,'' because that's what it seems to have
become. By BILL LUCIA.
</P>
</TEXT>
