<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-SUPERSTAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC SCHOOL SATIRE OFFERED IN `SUPERSTAR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For anyone who's ever wondered what's the opposite of Julia
Roberts, it's Mary Katherine Gallagher (Molly Shannon), that
awkward teenage girl with the horn-rimmed glasses and a too-short,
parochial-school uniform living inside almost every woman, that
socially deformed woman who lives in some girls.
</P>
<P>
   She has a hundred-dollar smile and, to quote Hal Hartley, is a
nymphomaniac who's never had sex. She just likes to simulate it on
trees and stop-sign poles _ only Wayne and Garth seemed
simultaneously more real and not of this Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superstar,'' an odd, hysterically pointed movie chapter in the
``Saturday Night Live'' heroine's screwball life, offers Mary
Katherine Gallagher as that lunatic manifestation of teenage lust
and better role model for girls than certain multiplatinum pop
stars. She's literally boy crazy and desperate to be the eye of the
storm of attention, even when she's working as the rewind girl at
the video store.
</P>
<P>
   Her sense of romance is outdone only by her sociopathic need for
fame. And her virginity would be on an eBay auction block if she
lived in a techno world. Instead she exists in a Catholic school
neverland that seems to be a distilled composite of 1982-1993, and
cool truly is a state of Shannon's mind.
</P>
<P>
   The film was directed by Bruce McCulloch, a ``Kids in the Hall''
guy who evidently was using the comically challenged,
blink-so-you'll-miss-it ``Dog Park'' as practice for this
infinitely more confident effort. And his basic goal here is to let
Shannon and the rest of ``Superstar's'' madly funny cast slapstick
themselves silly.
</P>
<P>
   The story, by Steve Koren, is simple: Mary Katherine wants to be
noticed by the curiously heterosexual Sky Corrigan (``SNL's'' Will
Ferrell), who's the best dancer in her Catholic school. (``He's the
Swayziest,'' swoons Mary Katherine's boyish pal, Helen, played by
Emmy Laybourne as Jan Brady on hormones.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sky has a bitch girlfriend named Evian (Elaine
Hendrix looking like Alicia Silverstone with a Britney Spear
through her heart), and the silent hunk in the bad leather jacket
(Harland Williams) from Mary Katherine's special-ed class has a
crush on her.
</P>
<P>
   Against her grandmother's (Glynnis Johns) better judgment, she
auditions for her school's ``Fight Against Venereal Disease''
talent contest, the winner going to Hollywood to star in a movie
with positive moral values _ what, like Pax's ``Little Convent on
the Prairie?''
</P>
<P>
   McCulloch arranges the film to feel like one long ad-lib crammed
with spontaneous musical numbers, the best of which busts out in
the cafeteria with Mary Katherine and Sky doing ``the robot'' with
the rest of the cast to ``Gonna Make You Sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   And when they're bored at Mass, Mary Katherine and Helen play
``Supermodel Documentary Hour.'' As part of ``Superstar's'' silly
riffing on kids'-eye-view of Catholicism, Ferrell also plays Mary
Katherine's personal Jesus, who visits her in her bedroom, and Mark
McKinney plays neurotic Father Ritley. (And what's Canadian obnoxio
Tom Green doing here, just screaming at Mary Katherine?)
</P>
<P>
   It's Shannon who's at the center of the contagious nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   There's an unstable genius in the mild psychopath brewing
beneath Mary Katherine's scarlet headband. As ``SNL'' women go,
only Gilda Radner seemed as willing to rib so much of herself for
our pleasure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0636 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-LIMEY-HNS     10-08 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-LIMEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LIMEY' IS STEVEN SODERBERGH'S LATEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are no maracas and nary a wah-wah guitar riff or
smacked-up cymbal to speak of, but director Steven Soderbergh and
writer Lem Dobbs' ``The Limey'' is atmospheric Champagne funk that
holds you under its spell long enough to make you believe Curtis
Mayfield is still in the soundtrack business.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Saber is behind most of the film's hollowed-out
jazz-tronica. But it's Soderbergh's Visine-clear vision and
unconventional skill at killing several narrative birds with a
single stylistic stone that elevates a relatively simple noir flick
into an ingeniously atavistic work of art, in which even the
editing is a slave to the rhythm. All this, despite the fact that
Soderbergh is after two divergent film moments from the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   With dueling smolder and self-doubt, Terence Stamp plays Wilson,
a small-time thief who's been in and out of jail and has just been
released into the L.A. wild after his latest nine-year stint. The
character is the older, more contemplative incarnation of the thug
Stamp played in Ken Loach's ``Poor Cow'' from 1967.
</P>
<P>
   It was a smallish part in a film that serves as ``The Limey's''
textual blueprint, providing actual flashbacks akin to old one-reel
home movies that are visual reminders of what a striking presence
Stamp was.
</P>
<P>
   In '67 Loach was figuring out the working-class assassin living
in his head, and Soderbergh has grown exceptionally at ease
exploring the super-fly, fun-lovin' criminal in his.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's looking to serve payback to the party responsible for
the death of his estranged daughter and all the signs point to his
daughter's last lover, a record producer named Valentine (Peter
Fonda). He's a guy who ``took the whole '60s Zeitgeist thing and
ran with it,'' as he's described to Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda, who's somehow finding himself as an increasingly less
empty screen presence, is playing a shady, comically Bizarro shadow
of his former self.
</P>
<P>
   An unusually striking Lesley Ann Warren is in the cast. And
Nicky Katt and Barry Newman are excellent as a pool-hall thug and
Valentine's right-hand bastard who hires him to kill Wilson, both
of whom get to stretch out extended sub-plot-ish sequences.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh was a writer-director who became a filmmaker under
our noses, like that girl who, as a party trick, removed her bra
without the exhibition of flesh but with the requisite modicum of
grace. He did this with a limited amount of fanfare as if after his
``sex, lies, &AMP; videotape'' breakthrough, he broke down, blinded by
the Sundance in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   When he made 1994's ``The Underneath,'' an under-seen remake of
1949's ``Criss Cross,'' the fulgent palette and stylistic devices
seemed like a break in form. ``Out of Sight'' was further proof of
Soderbergh's assertion that noir needn't be. Now, with ``The
Limey,'' he's reconfigured the genre with Crayolas that fill in the
washed-out documentary overtones in Loach's first non-TV feature
just as it makes a term like neo-noir seem like a fatuous catch
phrase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0639 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-08 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY NEW YORK ISN'T SHARING IN JOB GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOLTON LANDING, N.Y. _ Throughout the 1990s, New York state has
ranked 49th in job creation and No. 2, just behind a statistical
anomaly called Alaska, in combined state and local per capita
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The question was asked: Did anybody perceive a relationship
between those two figures.
</P>
<P>
   This was a few weeks ago at the annual meeting of the Business
Council of New York State. Virtually everybody in that large
meeting room at the Sagamore on Lake George saw a direct and
disturbing relationship between those numbers. That seemed
especially true of the high-powered business people engaged in a
panel discussion of the state's economic future.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the stage were William F. Allyn of Skaneateles,
president of a successful company that makes medical and imaging
gear; Stanley J. Grubel of Hopewell Junction, the chief executive
of a semiconductor manufacturing operation; advertising agency
proprietor Eric Mower of Syracuse; Heidi A. Nauleau, who runs
several manufacturing companies in Jamestown; and Hector Hyacynthe,
of the Packard-Frank Organization in Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   All agreed that New York's tax load is too heavy. All agreed
that it needs weight reduction. So did the audience. Tax-cutting,
after all, is a Business Council priority.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, where do you trim? Where are tax dollars being
gobbled up needlessly? Realistically speaking, where can New
Yorkers save public money without creating disaster and fostering
misery? Everybody had an idea or two. And ideas are desperately
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the rhetoric from the Pataki administration about
how wonderfully the Empire State is doing economically, the Federal
Reserve last month released a report documenting a rather startling
``brain drain'' from New York, especially upstate. Well-educated
New Yorkers in their 20s and 30s are leaving skid marks as they
flee to the South and West, where job opportunities for skilled
workers exist in relative abundance.
</P>
<P>
   How bad is it? Here are some dreary numbers on New York's
economic performance in the 1990s: New York job growth averaged 1
percent. National Average: 2.5 percent. You can argue that New York
already has the jobs while Arizona is still developing, and that's
true as far as it goes. But New York's job growth in the 1990s has
been only half that of Massachusetts and the rust belt states of
the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   The industries that lost the most jobs in this state during this
decade _ manufacturing, for example _ paid wages that topped the
statewide wage average by 53 percent. The industries that added
jobs, mainly the retail and service industries, pay wages that run
8 percent below the statewide average wage. The situation is
especially grim upstate. Upstarters are 37 percent of the state's
population, but New Yorkers north of Westchester enjoyed only 25
percent of the limited job growth. Bankruptcies are more common
upstate than downstate. New York mortgage foreclosures run 50
percent above the national rate.
</P>
<P>
   Energy costs and towering state energy taxes play a role in the
loss of manufacturing jobs in particular. But New York ranks in the
middle of the pack in per-capita state tax load. It ranks first in
local per-capita tax load. It's easy to see where much of the
problem lies _ in an old, outdated system of local government that
gives Albany _ a metropolitan area of less than a million people _
770 separate taxing units to support.
</P>
<P>
   Where Florida administers education at the county level, New
York clings to more than 850 separate school boards, each with its
own administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   Cut taxes? Sure, everybody wants to. But until New Yorkers grasp
the true nature of the problem and submit to combining local
governments and school districts to save real money, then nothing
much will change.
</P>
<P>
   And the jobs will keep going elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
