<HEADLINE>
THE MYSTERIES OF AUTOMATIC GARAGE DOORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 10)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The manual garage door is almost a thing of the
past.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like the convenience of an automatic door and
being able to drive into the protection of the garage.
</P>
<P>
   Recent improvements to sensors and door openers have increased
their usefulness.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, automatic garage doors have featured an invisible
backup light beam. The door's direction reverses if the beam is
disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   To check the safety of a garage door, place a small block of
wood in the area where the door closes. The door should go into
reverse upon contact with the block.
</P>
<P>
   If your garage door doesn't stop, call for a service check by a
reputable technician. Should you not have a safety reversing
feature, you may want to upgrade your opener with a new one that
meets all safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   Follow a regular maintenance routine, even if you have a newer,
self-lubricating, automatic garage door.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to have the hardware in top working
condition,'' stressed Joe Greene, owner of Greene Overhead Door of
Waterford, N.Y. ``Perhaps they may need to be repaired or replaced
since they were installed or last checked. The last thing you want
is for something that weighs several hundred pounds and moves over
your head to not be in excellent working condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Regular maintenance includes making sure the door remains
properly balanced, tightening hardware, such as hinges, lubricating
metal rollers, pulleys and cables, and spring adjustment. Safety
cables will keep the springs from flying out of control if they
should break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Springs stretch and eventually wear out or get rusty from lack
of care,'' added Greene. ``Lack of maintenance can make your garage
door wear out faster than normal. By servicing it once a year, you
can extend the life of your door.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are buying new, look for a good warranty and service
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warranties vary,'' said Tom Murphy, owner of Murphy Overhead
Doors in Albany. ``Most manufacturers offer a lifetime warranty
against rust-through on all steel doors. Some just cover rust. Look
for a warranty that covers rust, period. Otherwise, you need to
have a hole through the door caused by rust for the warranty to
kick in.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Boers, owner of Ed's Overhead Doors in Niskayuna, N.Y.,
said that you shouldn't have to buy a service contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look to a warranty where the parts and labor are guaranteed
for the first year,'' said Boers.
</P>
<P>
   Some manufacturers offer a lifetime warranty on the paint finish
and one to five years on the hardware. Shop around before deciding
on the make of door you are going to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Today, you can get a garage door to complement your home's
architectural style. Wood doors are traditional, but require
painting and can warp, crack or split over time. A custom-installed
wood automatic garage door costs approximately $500 to $2,500,
which includes removal of your old door.
</P>
<P>
   Steel insulated doors cost approximately $400 to $1,000 for a
standard size (7 feet high by 8 or 9 feet wide) single bay door.
The price depends on whether the door is strengthened with raised
panels or windows.
</P>
<P>
   John Meichtry, owner of Leo's Overhead Garage Doors in Troy,
said steel doors don't need painting, are lighter than wood and not
prone to dry rot. They can be insulated, which adds rigidity, or
uninsulated. Murphy said that the gauge of steel varies, and it
isn't listed in most literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lower the number, the thicker the gauge,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Another option for residential doors is vinyl, which can feature
2-inch-thick foam insulation, won't rust or dent, said Boers. A
standard size costs approximately $180 to $340.
</P>
<P>
   Automatic garage doors must have an emergency release that
allows the door to be operated manually.
</P>
<P>
   A permanent ``press'' button or key pad should be installed on
the garage door jamb out of the reach of small children. A wireless
keypad ($38 to $48) opens and closes the garage door when a
four-digit security code is entered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
