r a BC-NTSB-AZR &LR;      10-08 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NTSB-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMWEST FAILED TO FIX DEVICE TIED TO MISHAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - An accident that in jured four flight attendants last
month is being blamed on a faulty warning system that America West
knew about but had not corrected, according to federal
investigators.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board is continuing its probe
of the Sept. 20 in-flight accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at why the problem persisted,'' said Bob
Crispin, a safety board investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots who flew the Boeing 757 aircraft before the accident
reported problems with the ground-proximity warning system.
Mechanics tested the device but did not find out what was wrong,
said Steve Johnson, America West chief administrative officer.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear what exact problems the pilots reported with the
computer warning system, but there had been no previous injuries on
America West as a result of a false warning, Crispin said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the injured flight attendants, Celinda Levno, said she
hopes that the investigation improves safety at America West for
passengers and crew members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pain and suffering is worth it if it makes the airline
safer,'' said Levno, who broke her left leg and foot in the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   The board is examining what main tenance America West performed
to repair the warning system and whether the problems were beyond
the scope of what the airline could have been expected to solve,
said Crispin, who is heading the investi gation.
</P>
<P>
   He would not say how long America West had been having trouble
with the warning system, but the board is checking maintenance
records of the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a stack of paperwork 4 or 5 feet tall to go through,''
Crispin said.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board is researching whether there have been similar
problems on the warning systems for the worldwide fleet of Boeing
757s, Crispin said.
</P>
<P>
   Two flight attendants were seriously injured and two suffered
minor injuries in the sudden evasive maneu ver, according to the
board's prelimi nary accident report.
</P>
<P>
   An aircraft operation that results in a death, serious injury or
substantial damage to the plane is considered an accident by the
board.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was not damaged and none of the 170 passengers was
injured on Flight 2208, which was en route from Los Angeles to
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots Franklin Etter and John Spriggs reacted as they were
trained to do under the circumstances, Cris pin said.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft was descending through clouds at a rate of about
4,000 feet per minute when the warning system sounded. Etter and
Spriggs pulled up on the aircraft at an altitude of 22,000 feet and
increased the engine power to maximum thrust. The plane's nose
pitched upward about 8 degrees, and the aircraft began to climb at
a rate of 3,400 feet per minute, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants in the back galley fell about 8 feet when
the cabin floor dropped out from under them, Crispin said, adding
that it's fortunate that the injuries were not more serious.
</P>
<P>
   America West spokeswoman Patty Nowack said one of the flight
attendants fractured her leg, another broke her ankle, a third
suffered a badly sprained knee and the fourth was badly bruised and
had neck and back injuries.
</P>
<P>
   None of the injured flight attendants has returned to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't return to work until they're healthy and ready to
fly again, and we don't know when that is,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The ground-proximity warning sys tem, which alerts pilots if
they are flying too close to mountains or other terrain, is linked
with a plane's collision-avoidance system, which warns of nearby
aircraft, Crispin said.
</P>
<P>
   That system had alerted the America West pilots of a plane
passing 1,000 feet below them just before the ground-proximity
warning system sounded.
</P>
<P>
   America West has replaced the warn ing systems since the
accident and the plane was returned to service after an extensive
check by company mechanics, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the 13-year-old aircraft was grounded for scheduled
maintenance to examine the entire aircraft and its avionics, the
electronic and computer systems that control the plane, John son
said.
</P>
<P>
   That work is being done at a contract maintenance facility in In
dianapolis operated by United Air lines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers of the warnings systems, AlliedSignal and
Rockwell Collins, are testing the devices that were removed after
the accident, Crispin said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has been found wrong with the systems, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The board expects to issue a final accident report within six
months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration in its initial accident
report cites improper maintenance as a factor but did not include
specifics.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing 757 involved in the accident had a previous
mechanical failure, when the hydraulic system failed on July 4,
1997. The plane, which is painted with the Diamond backs logo, made
a safe emergency landing in Phoenix after circling for more than an
hour to burn fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe-based America West, the na tion's ninth-largest airline,
has never had a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   However, the carrier was fined $5 million in July 1998 by the
FAA for maintenance violations, one of the largest fines ever in
commercial-aviation history.
</P>
<P>
   America West paid half that fine immediately. FAA administrators
in Washington agreed to waive the remaining $2.5 million on July 14
after deciding that the Tempe-based carrier had complied with the
re quired corrective actions.
</P>
<P>
   But that decision went against the recommendation of Phoenix FAA
inspectors, who did not believe America West had complied.
</P>
<P>
   Local inspectors wanted to extend the compliance deadline and
use the remaining $2.5 million fine as lever age, but were
overruled. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
