<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUCK-HUNTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKE CHAMPLAIN OFFERS A PARADISE FOR HUNTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED LeBRUN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITEHALL, N.Y. _ ``This will be the hardest duck hunt you've
ever loved, I promise,'' guide Brad Plummer said in a strained
whisper between shoves and lurches on our hung-up canoe.
</P>
<P>
   He surely didn't have to convince me how hard it would be. Here
it was 4:05 a.m., pitch black, and it really was slow going trying
to pull, push and tug a 14-foot Old Town Osprey loaded with
shotguns, decoys, and gear of all type about 100 yards through
thick cattails and reeds where one step you were above the water
line on sort-of solid ground, and the next you sank into mucky ooze
to your waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing great, we're doing just great,'' Plummer kept
saying between lurches, although I wasn't sure who he was trying to
convince.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet you $1,000 that when we get set up we will have the
place to ourselves and the hunting will be unbelievable. You will
see more ducks than you've ever seen in your life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This very statement is what got me hooked on this hunt, and at
this point I was wondering just what I'd gotten myself into.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was opening morning of the first half of the waterfowl
season on both the Vermont and New York sides of Lake Champlain, an
incredible habitat for ducks that I'd witnessed with my own eyes,
but only in the off-season. I had never actually put a gun to it,
so I was definitely inclined. Plummer promised a classic Lake
Champlain-style duck hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's none of your heated blind, motor the boat right to it and
wait for the birds to fall out of the sky elite duck hunt. It's a
little more exercise than that, and you might get a little muddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad is some salesman. Throw the physical challenge stuff at me
and I'll bite every time.
</P>
<P>
   So Plummer and his boat and I met at a fast-food shop at 2:30
a.m., then we drove 15 miles north of Whitehall along Champlain. At
a small, private dock, we launched his 16-foot Grumman Ranger with
an 18-hp Go-Devil designed to churn through the thickest duck weed
and swamp grass. After a half-hour in that salad, we suddenly
veered on the New York side into a broad, shallow bay jammed with
decoys. Aha, I thought. This must be it. Piece of cake.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Somebody else's decoys.
</P>
<P>
   This was only the first leg, so to speak, because we unloaded
everything into the canoe and did what canoes don't do that well _
skated over land. The short of it is, after 5,000 calories we
finally crossed the reeds to Plummer's own favorite sink hole, a
hidden gem about 50 yards across, out of sight between two major
shooting galleries.
</P>
<P>
   We set the canoe on the sturdiest clumps of cattails we could
find back off the shore 10 feet and parallel to it with the wind to
our back. Plummer rigged a makeshift blind between us and the
water. We stood in the canoe, saw it was good, and got out our
shotguns and shell boxes. It was 5:30, an hour before shooting
time. Hmmm, I thought, this is going to work out great after all.
</P>
<P>
   Then, within 10 minutes, the temperature dropped to within a few
degrees of freezing, the wind whipped up and it started to rain. At
the same time, a flashlight suddenly bobbed 30 feet away, attached
to another hunter and his faithful Labrador. I could hear Plummer
groan, ``I can't believe this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take that $1,000 in small bills,'' I muttered quietly.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour before sunrise, if there had been a sun, the
remarkable stillness in all directions was shattered with gunfire
from 30 different unseen blinds. Then I remembered what Plummer had
said about Lake Champlain duck hunts.
</P>
<P>
   This is mostly a public shoreline, and these duck hunters are
not apt to be Orvis-decorated. This is the people's duck hunt, and
there are a lot of them. These folks love their ducks. Then again,
there also are an incredible number of ducks to love. In the
thousands. Wave after flock, singles and doubles came at us from
every direction, with never more than a three- or four-minute break
in the action.
</P>
<P>
   Woodducks, blue and green-winged teal flying in their
characteristically low, fast and erratic manner. Bigger black ducks
and mallards doing their B-52 imitations higher up, out of range
except for the big 10-gauges, which we did not have.
</P>
<P>
   I was used to river duck hunting, and this was a different game.
Along a river, the ducks generally fly up or down stream. In
Plummer's sink hole, they came at us like a three-dimensional
arcade game, from every point of the compass and at full speed,
right out of the cattails. A shot-shell manufacturer's dream.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, we were in the ideal position thanks to
Plummer's guiding, and the other hunter got off only a few shots at
our rejects. Both Plummer and I maxed out on our limits of six each
by 9 a.m., mostly teal, which I adore. We easily could have doubled
that if it were legal, or halved the shooting time.
</P>
<P>
   Except Plummer's rule applied. He allowed us to shoot only at
ducks that would fall in the sink hole in front of us. We had no
dog, and the only retrieving we could do was with the canoe.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, each of us shot a bird that accidentally fell not 15
feet into the rushes. We looked for an hour and a half and found
neither one, a bitter lesson. We both felt bad enough over losing
those birds that neither of us shot anymore. Enough.
</P>
<P>
   A warm sun came out, the wind abated. I looked down at two empty
boxes of shotgun shells and spent hulls in all directions, and a
boat full of ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, you can keep your money,'' I told Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   It was everything he said it would be, a phenomenal duck hunt,
Champlain-style. Which also means on the way out we discovered the
wind had pushed the water right out of the bay where we'd beached
the big boat, and we had all we could do, after expending another
5,000 calories, to get out of there without a tow.
</P>
<P>
   He warned we'd get a little muddy. He was right about that, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
