u a BC-EYE-SURGERY-$ADV11-HN     10-08 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYE-SURGERY-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLEAR CHOICE: WRITER SHARES HER EXPERIENCE WITH POPULAR EYE
SURGERY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Monday, Oct. 11) 
 
By LORI RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If you have always struggled to see, then you have
always known me.
</P>
<P>
   I was the kid the teacher thought was slow because I couldn't
see the blackboard; the geek in the Coke-bottle glasses that
everyone called four eyes; the one who went from hard contacts to
gas permeable to soft and finally back to glasses, this time,
bifocals.
</P>
<P>
   If you have struggled to see forever, then you know why I spent
more than $4,300 five months ago to fix what, for most of my life,
has been unfixable.
</P>
<P>
   Myopia, or nearsightedness, is caused by eyes that are too long
from front to back. Astigmatism, caused by an irregularly curved
cornea, blurs vision as well. I had both, and badly, when I decided
to undergo LASIK, short for laser in-situ keratomileusis and
currently all the rage for restoring normal vision.
</P>
<P>
   At the onset, you should know this: LASIK is not for the faint
of heart. Consider the informed consent agreement I signed: ``I
understand it is possible that a perforation of the cornea could
occur, causing devastating complications, including the loss of
some or all my vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Other daunting warnings include the possibility of
``starbursting'' around lights, resulting in a halo effect,
increased difficulty focusing at night and permanent
over-correction from nearsightedness to farsightedness.
</P>
<P>
   I pressed on; some understandably do not.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``flap and zap'' in the industry, LASIK treats the
middle layers of the cornea to correct nearsightedness,
farsightedness and astigmatism. Numbing drops are administered to
prevent pain. A vacuum ring props the eyelids open. A thin flap is
sliced on the cornea with a device called a microkeratome and
folded back. Microscopic layers of the exposed tissue are vaporized
with an excimer laser to slightly reshape the cornea.
</P>
<P>
   The actual application of the laser takes 10 to 90 seconds, and
the hinged flap is gently returned to its original position. In the
best-case scenario, the eye heals without incident and the chance
of seeing 20/40 or better (the legal vision to drive without
glasses) can exceed 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the patients' perspective, it's a miracle. It's an
extraordinary transformation of their vision,'' says Dr. Douglas
Koch, professor of ophthalmology with Baylor Laser Vision at
Houston's Baylor College of Medicine and the physician who
performed my procedure.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, the demand for LASIK surgery has skyrocketed,
from 200,000 procedures in 1998, to an expected 800,000 this year.
Dallas Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman, race-car driver Bryan Herta
and a legion of professional sports players have bared their
eyeballs for the laser.
</P>
<P>
   Ophthalmologists' offices are mobbed with people who want to
toss their glasses and see the world in all its peripheral glory.
They want to water-ski and workout without prescription goggles.
</P>
<P>
   Vanity certainly plays a part, but most want the simple
pleasures: waking up in the morning and reading the alarm clock;
falling asleep on the couch while watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   That was me. I've awoken so long to dimness and stumbled around
in a world full of blobs, I just wanted to sharpen some edges. I
did a massive Internet search and considered the options, the
surgeries, the risks and benefits, the clinics and the doctors. By
the time I walked into Baylor's Alkek Eye Center a year ago, I was
a go.
</P>
<P>
   At least from my end.
</P>
<P>
   My first ``screening'' to determine if I was a good LASIK
candidate was a bust. According to Koch, a pioneer in the field, I
have what are called ``trace'' cataracts in the center of both
eyes. If the cataracts were growing, they could require surgery as
soon as a year or two, Koch said; it would be imprudent to subject
each eye to two surgeries in that short space of time.
</P>
<P>
   Now that was a devastating complication.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, a second screening four months later showed
that the cataracts were stable, not growing, and could be decades
away from being a problem. Now I was a go.
</P>
<P>
   Of the actual surgery, I can tell you this: I was trembling and
given a Valium (thank you, laser team). I got a running
play-by-play (thank you, Dr. Koch). It was over in a flash and
didn't hurt (thank you, God).
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to say I awoke the next morning to a brand-new world,
but that's not the way it went.
</P>
<P>
   One eye was good from the get-go; my vision so bright and clear,
I drove that afternoon. The other was bad from the start; my vision
pained and blurred from debris (dead cells, deposits and the like)
that had ended up beneath the corneal flap.
</P>
<P>
   The next month was hell. The bad eye was as bad as the good eye
was good. It hurt, kept me up at night, interfered with work,
worried me no end. No matter what combination of drops the doctors
prescribed, the debris didn't go away, and neither did the pain. I
felt fragile, blind.
</P>
<P>
   Koch kept telling me they had ways of getting me to where they
wanted me. In the end, that way was lifting the corneal flap,
scraping away the debris and irrigating the heck out of it. That
was longer than the initial surgery and, since I was now less
confident, it was scarier. But it worked.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, I finally awoke to that brave new world, and my
life has not been the same since. I see the alarm clock in the
morning. I see the leaves on the trees outside, in all their
dazzling detail. I see my mom's needlepoint on the wall, not just
the pink of the flowers and the green of the leaves, but the actual
dots of the thread. I see all this, and I am profoundly grateful.
</P>
<P>
   At Baylor, Koch and his partner, M. Bowes Hamill, turn away
perfectionists who will be disappointed with anything less than
contact-lens clarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``That level of expectation is too high,'' says Koch. ``This is
elective surgery. You have to be twice as careful with this. The
stakes are much higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamill, an ophthalmologist for the Houston Astros, discouraged
two professional baseball players who were seeking LASIK surgery.
The men wore contact lenses only during games, and Hamill told them
the slight risk inherent in LASIK wasn't worth the convenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pretty careful about it. This is not a mill,'' says
Hamill. ``Our goal is not high volume.''
</P>
<P>
   LASIK normally costs $2,000-plus per eye. It's not usually
covered by health insurance, doesn't always work and, when it
doesn't, your vision could be worse for life.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter McDonnell, chairman of the American Academy of
Ophthalmology's Refractive Surgery Interest Group, says about 1
percent of his patients have had worse vision; Koch and Hamill put
their complication rate at 1 percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   I was a temporary member of that 1 percent club. But last week,
still in the six-month healing period, I read the eye chart
somewhere between 20/20 and 20/16 with both eyes. That varies
depending on how tired I am, how long I've stared at the computer
and how dry my eyes have gotten. I still need reading glasses; that
loss of focusing is caused by age and is not surgically
correctable. I still sometimes strain to see. I still worry about
the cataracts and the long-term health of my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond three years, the consent form plainly tells you, the
effects of LASIK are not known. Your vision could regress, your
nearsightedness could return. But then I knew, even as they were
throwing all those different drops at my bad eye, that, to a
degree, these doctors are charting new territory.
</P>
<P>
   I don't really care.
</P>
<P>
   At midlife, I won't be around to catch a fraction of what the
millennium brings in the way of medical miracles, and I envy all
those who will.
</P>
<P>
   But I have lived long enough to see a lifetime of blurriness
snap into shocking clarity, and I'll take that.
</P>
<P>
   I'll awake to my mom's needlepoint in the morning, walk out the
door in my high-toned sunglasses, look at the day in all its
brilliance and, for however long it lasts, I'll say a grateful
prayer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
