<HEADLINE>
GIVING EXTRA POINTS TO MINORITIES ON SAT EXAMS IS STILL DEBATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RICK KARLIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ Ask J.J. Harvey if he should get extra points on
his SAT score because he's African American and you'll get a
puzzled look followed by a brief show of indignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose idea was that?'' asked the senior at Colonie Central
High School. Automatically adding points to the Scholastic
Assessment Test scores of minority students, Harvey said, would
simply reinforce the stereotype that blacks are poor students.
</P>
<P>
   Said Shontell Smith, another black member of the school's class
of 2000: ``I'd like the extra points but not that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding points for minority or disadvantaged students, though, is
exactly what the Educational Testing Service (ETS), which designs
the SAT, has considered. For more than two years, ETS has been
fine-tuning a formula under which such students in certain
socioeconomic categories could be labeled as ``strivers'' and
qualify for additional points.
</P>
<P>
   It's based on the idea that some disadvantaged students will
score higher than predicted, and those students, because they show
promise, should get a leg up in the college admissions game.
</P>
<P>
   A disadvantaged student who scored 1,000 of a possible 1,600
points on the combined math and verbal test, for instance, is
probably scoring about 200 points better than expected, according
to ETS researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the strivers concept, several socioeconomic factors in
addition to race would be plugged into the equation. Variables such
as the education levels of a student's parents and even the number
of books in the student's home could come into play.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the strivers concept is only that: a tentative idea that
ETS has put forward. It is not likely to be enacted anytime soon.
The College Board, the association of colleges that hires ETS to
write and score the SATs, quickly rebuffed the idea, saying the
college admissions process is too full of subtleties to be reduced
to a formula.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that ETS has looked at a strivers category
underscores the thorny issue of how college admissions officers
balance measurable academic achievements such as grades and
standardized test scores, against intangible characteristics such
as the drive or motivation that a student needs in order to
overcome barriers to scholastic success.
</P>
<P>
   That's an issue that has become as perennial as the SATs
themselves, which will begin being administered Saturday in
selected schools across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   SATs are a fall ritual for thousands of students, especially in
the eastern states, where the test is used as a yardstick by most
colleges and universities. They are offered several times
throughout the year, with many of the October participants taking
the test again in hopes of raising their scores.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that students may go through the test process twice
speaks to the importance that SATs play in college admissions.
</P>
<P>
   There is an entire industry devoted to preparing students for
the test, and some high schools, including Colonie Central, have
developed their own after-school test-prep programs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet guidance counselors like Colonie Central's Jack Cramer
stress that the SATs aren't the only measure of a student. ``I
would pretty much expect that they take into account a student's
background and extenuating circumstances,'' Cramer said.
</P>
<P>
   Like admissions counselors at most schools, those at Skidmore
College in Saratoga Springs, N.Y., recognize that students from
different backgrounds have unique characteristics that can't be
measured with an SAT number, said Mary Lou Bates, who heads the
school's admissions office. ``There's no hard and fast number,''
Bates said when asked if there is an SAT cutoff score for admission
to Skidmore.
</P>
<P>
   The imprecise nature of what SAT scores mean, however, is
precisely the problem with these tests in the first place, critics
say, adding that the strivers concept proves their point.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the issue of strivers marks ``the first time on record a
very senior person at ETS has said a combined score of 1,000 on the
SAT is not always 1,000,'' said Robert Schaeffer, public education
director for Fair Test, a Cambridge, Mass.-based group that is
critical of standardized tests like the SATs.
</P>
<P>
   Hartwick College is one of a handful of schools that will accept
applications without SAT scores, if a student thinks they aren't
reflective of his or her true abilities. About 11 percent of the
roughly 2,000 students seeking admission to the Oneonta, N.Y.-based
school leave out their SAT scores in their applications. Still,
despite those obvious doubts about the SAT's effectiveness,
Hartwick Dean of Admissions Susan Dileno says a strivers category
would at least provide a tool for quantifying socioeconomic
factors. ``From my discussions with other admission colleagues,
there seems to be a real interest in it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like others, however, Dileno stressed that good admissions
officers will look at a variety of factors, including the rigor of
courses a student takes in high school. Most admissions officers,
she said, are more impressed with tougher courses, such as those on
the honors or advanced-placement levels, than a high SAT score.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
