<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WASTELAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE ARE THE SHOWS FOR THE 30-SOMETHINGS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you are a gay guy, and are compelled to tell a straight buddy
from college whom you haven't seen in a while that you are
homosexual. You are not exactly sure how he is going to react, so
you break the news:
</P>
<P>
   _ In a bar, so both of you at least can get hammered if he can't
hack it.
</P>
<P>
   _ At home, so you can have a thoughtful discussion if one is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the shower at the health club.
</P>
<P>
   If you are Kevin Williamson, the man behind ``Dawson's Creek,''
``Scream'' and now ``Wasteland,'' it's a no-brainer. Hand me a
towel, will ya?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasteland,'' a new ABC drama chronicling a group of friends in
their mid-20s living in Manhattan, debuted Thursday night. And yes,
that coming-out scene is in there.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario is ridiculous, but the pilot episode at least rises
to mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   Dawnie (Marisa Coughlan) is a 26-year-old grad student doing her
thesis on how people in their 20s undergo ``a second coming of
age.'' Whatever. She is also a virgin.
</P>
<P>
   And her whole gang has baggage. Dawnie titles the life of people
in their 20s as ``The Wasteland.'' Single, 20-year-olds living in
New York City who have disposable income _ no, who are not living
in an old Maytag box _ should not whine. Ever. In fact, message to
Hollywood: You are not making us feel empathy toward the
complainers. You are making us ticked off. Teen angst? Sure.
Twenties angst? Shut up.
</P>
<P>
   The network now has a merely semi-decent twentysomething show
(``Wasteland'') to go along with an excellent new fortysomething
show (``Once and Again''). If only it could offer something for
30-year-olds. Yeah, Something for 30s. Nah, never happen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
