<SLUG> BC-HOMECOMING-QUEEN-ART-$ADV10-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TEXAS TOWN GOES ALL OUT FOR HOMECOMING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Oct. 10) 
 
(Moved in ``a'' and ``s'' categories) 
(Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAUMONT, Texas _ Forty queens at one homecoming might seem like
wretched excess, but excess is what homecoming is all about in
Vidor, a town of 11,000 just east of here.
</P>
<P>
   There will be 39 previous homecoming queens to greet the 1999
queen when she is crowned at halftime during Vidor High School's
football game Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The flashing black and gold of the Pirates band will be mirrored
by golden fireworks flashing through the dark skies. The stadium
will go dark while twirlers perform, not with batons, but with
flaming torches. Earlier in the day, Main Street will be shut down
for a big parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we go all out for homecoming,'' said Diana Walles Pierce,
the 1968 queen. ``We do it right. We don't always win the ballgame,
but we do have the best homecoming.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tradition that's been going on for half a century, and
this year the school invited all 50 previous queens to come home
again. Thirty-nine accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Taylor of the class of '56, who took on the job of tracking
down the former queens, figured 20 of them would come back for this
year's extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed at the response,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty of the former queens still live in Vidor. Most of the
others live across Texas, but some live as far away as Ohio. Many
are in business; some are educators. One, Tammy Hext, the 1980
queen, went on to win the Miss Texas pageant.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago Taylor took on the job of inviting the 102
football captains from the previous years to homecoming. All but
five showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those football captains were later married to Pierce, who
is now a divorced grandmother living in Beaumont and operator of a
massage therapy studio in Vidor.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce and the other queens will gather for a noon luncheon in a
Vidor tea room Friday and then ride down Main Street in
convertibles in a big parade that starts at 2 p.m. CST. Most of the
cars are being provided by the Corvette Club of Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   And while Taylor wasn't a homecoming queen, she did write the
school fight song back in 1954 that is still sung at football
games. ``Every time I hear it,'' she said, ``I get a thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
