<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO CONTROL THE PESKY DIALUP BOX: KEEP WINDOWS CLOSED TO PROTECT
PC 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: I upgraded to Windows 98 Second Edition on my
computer, and now it's doing the most irritating thing. Whenever I
start my computer, a box pops up that wants to dial my Internet
provider. I can't figure out how to make this go away.
</P>
<P>
   A: This is an annoying side effect to a useful feature that's
included in Internet Explorer 5, the browser that is put on your
system when you install Windows 98 SE.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that IE5 can do is to better manage multiple
dialup accounts. With earlier versions of Windows 95/98 and
Internet Explorer, it was difficult to keep different dialup
settings from conflicting with each other.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you needed to have one set of settings for your
Internet provider and another for getting onto your company's
network, you might find you had to manually put them in each time
you wanted to dial in.
</P>
<P>
   With this latest version of both the operating system and the
browser, there's now an area in the browser that lets you keep
connections separate. However, it also adds a layer of complexity
that results, for some folks, in this dialog box popping up when
it's not wanted.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening is that some component of Windows is trying to
get to the Internet. It could be the Windows Update Notification
feature, which checks the Windows Update Web page for fixes and
patches to the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   When it tries to connect to the Net and finds no pathway, it
launches this Dialup Networking box automatically. What you want is
to tell the system not to do that.
</P>
<P>
   To turn off the box, go to the Internet Options module in the
Control Panel (or right-click on the Internet Explorer icon and
choose Properties). Click on the Connection tab.
</P>
<P>
   You'll see three choices in that window: Never dial a
connection, Dial whenever a network connection is not present, and
Always dial my default connection. To turn the box off, click the
first item.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, you may still get that box. In that case, you'll
have to change one more setting.
</P>
<P>
   Go to the Dialup Networking folder in My Computer, and choose
Connections, then Settings. Make sure Don't prompt to use Dialup
Networking is checked.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With the weather starting to cool off, my wife and I again
are having our ages-old argument _ do we have to keep the air
conditioning on to keep out the humidity, or can we turn it off and
throw open the windows? I argue that because we have a home
computer network, we need not only to keep it cool, but also dry.
She doesn't buy it. Who's right?
</P>
<P>
   A: You would think I'd know better than to step into this one,
but I'll take a shot at it. You are right, but mainly because you
live in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is known for its high humidity, and that can indeed
shorten the lifespan of a PC. When it's hot outside, you definitely
want to have the air conditioning on, particularly if you have a
modern-era PC with its superfast chips that run hot. Extreme heat
is a major enemy to PC components.
</P>
<P>
   However, even when its cool, there's a danger that the humid air
could cause condensation on the metal parts of a PC when you turn
it off. Water on the internal components of a PC is even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean you should always run your air conditioner? Not
necessarily. Heaters also dry the air, so no need to try to run the
AC when it's chilly. However, if the humidity level gets to the
point where you feel physically uncomfortable in mild temperatures,
it's probably best to close the windows and turn down the
thermostat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
