<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0652 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-08 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE ARE MANY GOOD CHOICES FOR IMAGE EDITING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Digital image editing, once the domain of professional graphics
artists, is going mainstream. Once your mom starts scanning your
embarrassing baby pictures, the next logical step is for her to
alter them in some way, particularly if she's going to post them on
her home page and invite your friends to come see.
</P>
<P>
   To change those picture files, she'll need software. Programs
that can be used to work with digital images _ whether they're
canned, scanned or snapped with a digital camera _ vary from the
simple and slick to the complex and powerful. Fortunately, you have
many choices.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at three new versions of some of the most popular
image editors, with choices for dabbling novices, those who need
less hand-holding and, finally, those who are serious about working
with graphics.
</P>
<P>
   _ PhotoSuite III Platinum Edition, $50, MGI Software: Like its
primary competitor, Adobe PhotoDeluxe, PhotoSuite III groups the
most common tasks used in working with digital pictures into
specific categories. This includes getting pictures, editing them,
organizing them into groups, composing them in projects and sharing
them with others.
</P>
<P>
   But PhotoSuite III also lets you browse images on the Net and
pull them easily into the editor. The Windows software includes a
version of Internet Explorer, which essentially turns the entire
Web into your own personal photo album.
</P>
<P>
   I like PhotoSuite's interface, which puts the image you're
changing in the middle of a three-paned window. On the left are the
tools you use to make the changes, and on the right are more images
to choose from, grouped into photo albums.
</P>
<P>
   There are the basic set of image-editing tools for selecting and
altering parts of a picture _ such as painting, cropping, rotating
and so on _ and another set of fun special effects. My favorite is
Mirage, which can make part of your picture appear ghostlike.
</P>
<P>
   There are only two truly new features here as compared with the
previous version. The best one, Auto-Stitch, lets you join images
to create panoramas. Let's say you wanted to take a picture of your
house, as well as the homes on either side of yours. You could take
a photo of each, and then let the program piece them together into
one wide-angle image.
</P>
<P>
   The second new feature, called PhotoTapestry, is primarily a
snazzy special effect. It takes your image and recomposes it using
thousands of tiny, smaller pictures. How well this works depends on
the image you're working with _ larger pictures with less detail
are best. Intricate images tend to come out looking like mud.
</P>
<P>
   While PhotoSuite III has lots of features, you're fairly limited
because its design is primarily aimed at novices. In other words,
you're protected from the nitty-gritty of photo editing by the
friendly interface. If you're a little more experienced at working
with images, you may want to consider this next choice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paint Shop Pro 6.0, $109, Jasc Software: What began as a
humble shareware image editor has been developed into the best
Windows-based software for middle-level users. And even some pros
love Paint Shop Pro, preferring its intuitive interface over
higher-powered products such as the venerable PhotoShop.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this is my image editor of choice. I use it to do the
graphics at my personal Web site at www.neosoft.com/dwights/.
</P>
<P>
   With version 5.0, Jasc added the ability to do layers _ you can
alter one part of a picture without affecting the rest of it _ and
6.0 further refines this. It also now comes with vector drawing
tools, which make it easier to draw pictures with Paint Shop Pro.
Vector-based images are stored differently than the traditional
images created with Paint Shop _ called raster images _ and can be
manipulated differently. This gives the program more flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Jasc also has added features designed just for images to be used
on the Web. Tools let you fiddle with the attributes of GIF and
JPEG graphics files so they are smaller and load faster on a Web
page.
</P>
<P>
   The interface has been slightly reworked, so that some menu
items have icons that clue you in on what they do. And the floating
toolbars and palettes now roll up, window-shade style, when you're
not working with them.
</P>
<P>
   You can download a fully functioning version of Paint Shop Pro
6.0 at www.jasc.com.
</P>
<P>
   In beefing up its capabilities, though, Paint Shop Pro is
starting to become a bit harder to use. It's not quite as simple as
it once was, though it certainly remains easier to use than the
next choice on this list.
</P>
<P>
   _ PhotoShop 5.5, $649, Adobe Systems: No professional graphics
artist worth his or her trackball is going to be without PhotoShop.
This program, available for both Windows and Macintosh systems, is
the ultimate tool for working with images and getting them into
print or onto the Web.
</P>
<P>
   You can do almost anything you want to with PhotoShop. The tough
parts are paying for it and then figuring out how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   With version 5.5, Adobe has added features designed to make it
easier to produce images for online use. PhotoShop began life aimed
at getting images onto paper. However, as the Web evolved, artists
also found it was great for online work. Adobe's now giving those
artists tools they've been asking for.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you've probably seen cool Web sites with rollovers
_ graphics or text that change when you move your mouse over them.
PhotoShop now automates the process of making them, generating the
Javascript coding that's necessary for the effect.
</P>
<P>
   It also now has a slick feature that, like Paint Shop Pro, lets
you adjust the size and colors used in graphics so they load faster
on the Web. You can compare the same graphic rendered in several
different ways to get a balance of speed and visual quality.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite new features is an automated contact-sheet
creator. Just tell PhotoShop what images to include, and it will
arrange them on a virtual contact sheet. You can even include
captions. This also can be used to generate a Web page of
thumbnails that link to bigger images.
</P>
<P>
   While PhotoShop's interface remains daunting, Adobe has improved
the tutorial and help files. This helps the learning curve a bit,
but PhotoShop remains a program aimed at _ and priced for _
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   A demo version of PhotoShop for both Windows and Macintosh is
available at www.adobe.com/products/photoshop/demodnld.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
