<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS GO BEGGING FOR THEIR STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ These were the best-received panhandlers in the
history of San Francisco. On Thursday, a dozen teachers stood on
the median strip of Van Ness Avenue in front of City Hall, begging
drivers for help and holding signs such as ``Got paper?'' and ``Got
pencils?''
</P>
<P>
   Like hundreds of other motorists, the driver of a tour bus
tooted his horn in support. But what would the tourists think of
San Francisco, Money magazine's choice as the best place to live in
America, knowing our teachers have to spend their own money on
pencils for students?
</P>
<P>
   In the Great Depression, people sold pencils. In the Golden Age
of initial public stock offerings and the Internet, teachers are
begging for pencils.
</P>
<P>
   They did get some paper. The driver of a Kinko's truck
spontaneously dropped off a carton of copying paper. The teachers
scurried to get packs of it to take back to their classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't even know we're spending our own money on
supplies for our kids,'' said Mark Sanchez, a fourth-grade teacher
at Paul Revere School, who spends about $600 a year on art paper
and supplies of all kinds. ``The administration never acknowledges
it, much less thanks us.''
</P>
<P>
   You've never seen panhandlers like this. You'll see them again.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be back every month on that median strip in front of
City Hall, publicizing other teachers' issues, like oversize
classes and lack of prep time. And they'll continue begging for
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Gina Rothman, a fifth-grade teacher at Paul Revere, says she
spent $700 on her kids last year. One of Rothman's former students,
11-year-old Gregory Howard, arrived on roller skates to pass out
leaflets for the teachers in front of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came to support her,'' he said. ``She buys pencils,
paper, crayons, glue _ all the things to do all kinds of
projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Susie Siegel, a kindergarten teacher at Yick Wo School, kept
running into stopped traffic to hand out leaflets to drivers. ``I
risk my life every day for the kids,'' she joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most years I spend over $4,000,'' said Siegel, who says she
deducts it from her income taxes. ``That's almost 10 percent of my
$45,000 salary. When I need to buy snacks for my kids, I buy it,
because they need it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not activists,'' Sanchez said. ``We're teachers. We're
fed up.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his fellow panhandlers have started a group called
Teachers4Change and a Web site. ``When we started our Web site, we
wanted a conduit,'' Sanchez said. There's so much wealth out there.
There's so much largess. We eventually want our own warehouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez and the other teachers are begging for pencils, crayons,
markers, paper of all kinds, educational games, posters, books,
computers, printers, everything that the school district and the
state should be supplying to classrooms, but aren't.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked him if that didn't relieve the school district of
its responsibilities, Sanchez said, ``I'm a realist.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of these teachers are regular customers of Mike Ghiorso's
store, the Educational Exchange on 35th Avenue. This former teacher
sells school supplies to teachers, right now dealing in a lot of
Halloween materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of buying back your time _ literally,'' said
Ghiorso, referring to purchasing materials in his store rather than
making them. ``It's much more productive to be doing lesson plans
than to spend your time drawing squares.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez and the other panhandlers weren't aware of it, but the
administrators' union has a proposal before the Board of Education
to raise the amount of money allocated to each school for supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Principal Judy Coenen of Robert Louis Stevenson School calls her
union's proposal a ``cost-of-learning adjustment.'' For as long as
Coenen can remember, at least 12 years, each elementary school has
received $19.80 for each student from the school district. Middle
schools get around $25 per student and high schools $30.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's your basic bread-and-butter money for paper, pencils,
glue, toners, and all the new things we didn't have 12 years ago,
like printers and ink cartridges,'' Coenen said. ``You name it, and
it covers it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it doesn't cover it. Coenen says the money only covers
half the year. All Coenen and other principals are asking is an
extra $5 per pupil per year.
</P>
<P>
   When are we going to stop subtracting the cost of their pencils
and paper from the already meager salaries of teachers?
</P>
<P>
   Katie Sedgwick, a fourth-grade teacher at Paul Revere School,
said, ``We don't have enough books to go around, so we end up
photocopying our supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   Sad to say, but no panhandler ever grabbed a quarter as
gratefully as these teachers clutched their packs of Kinko's paper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
