u f BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-08 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIAS TAKES TOLL ON HEAVY PEOPLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Kendra Kennon is a large woman who weighs 100 pounds
more than her ``ideal'' weight.
</P>
<P>
   Kennon is also charming, attractive and lively _ everything that
most companies would want in a customer service representative.
</P>
<P>
   But Southwest Airlines doesn't want her because she can't fit
into a size 18 uniform _ the largest size the airline will allow
for its customer service agents.
</P>
<P>
   Kennon said the problem surfaced when she arrived at a job
interview. After the Southwest recruiter cleared the basics _ that
everyone getting interviewed that day must go to Dallas for
training, that everyone must be available to work on holidays _ the
issue of size came up.
</P>
<P>
   Kennon, who wears what's known as a ``plus size'' 22-24, said
she was told in front of a dozen people there for the interview
that the airline doesn't provide large-size uniforms, but perhaps
the airline had a job ``in the back'' for her away from the public
view. Southwest doesn't have a uniform-size standard for jobs out
of the spotlight such as reservation sales agents.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear, said Kennon, who has two years of college and four
years of customer service experience, that Southwest was sending a
message that heavier people aren't good enough to work out front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors tell you to accept your body size and be healthy and
happy and live a normal life,'' Kennon said. ``But it's hard to
accept yourself when you can't get a job when you're heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines is adamant that it hasn't broken any laws.
</P>
<P>
   Appearance standards, including a restriction on uniform sizes,
are legally acceptable, said Melanie Jones, spokeswoman for
Southwest Airlines in Dallas. Unlike race, sex or national origin,
large size is not a protected class, she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MARGINALIZED GROUP &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's true, said Bettye Travis, president of the National
Associaton to Advance Fat Acceptance. And that won't change until a
law is passed making it illegal to discriminate based on body size,
just as there are rules that forbid discrimination based on race or
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Fat people are the last group of marginalized Americans, said
Travis, who also is the co-owner of Spun Sugar, a cake decorating,
candy-making and coffee shop in Berkeley, Calif. People don't feel
embarrassed humiliating heavy people.
</P>
<P>
   Talk-show hosts would never make fun of someone's race, but they
often joke about body size, she said.
</P>
<P>
   And, there is little to no education on size acceptance, Travis
said. Some overweight children commit suicide because of the
humiliation by their peers. However, if a child were getting
tormented because of his race or national origin, the schoolteacher
would certainly step in, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest has a long-held belief that appearance counts. In
1971, the ``Luv'' airline argued to a federal judge in Dallas that
its flight attendants must wear hot pants and go-go boots because
the airline catered mostly to businessmen then.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the argument the airline made that it had a business
necessity to require the sexy garb, the court ruled the airline was
in the transportation business and had no legitimate business
reason to deny men flight-attendant jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The same people running the company today dictated the hot pants
and go-go boots, said Scott Pawgan, the lawyer who is representing
Kennon. They're still focused on attractiveness.
</P>
<P>
   And Pawgan says there may be a problem with race and gender,
claiming black women tend to be overweight compared to other racial
groups. And, men's uniforms are based just on waist sizes (between
27 and 42), so if a man has a huge chest, he wouldn't be denied the
job.
</P>
<P>
   If a taller-than-average woman applied for the job, she might
require a size larger than 18 even if she were relatively trim,
Pawgan said. And, though it sounds strange, a man who is unusually
tall could fit into a woman's uniform because Southwest considers
only waist size. He'd get the job, but she wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SIZING UP THE ISSUE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based Continental Airlines doesn't have a size limit for
its customer service agents, spokeswoman Sarah Anthony said. Its
standard uniform size goes up to 28, and if someone is larger, the
airline will make a uniform to measure.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission ruled
Southwest Airlines had discriminated against Kennon on a perceived
disability claim. But the agency reversed itself last month,
contending that it made a mistake and has referred the issue to
mediation.
</P>
<P>
   Kennon, meanwhile, has taken a job as a bill collector to pay
her own bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want big people to know that Southwest Airlines doesn't
want us to work in the front lines where the customers might see
us,'' she said. ``So maybe they won't want to fly with them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
