<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0667 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-HARSH-REALM-HNS &LR;      10-08 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HARSH-REALM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HARSH REALM': HARD TO CONQUER, BUT WORTH A SECOND LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Carter has never been easy on his audience. The creator of
``The X-Files'' and the late, bizarre ``Millennium'' is a master of
wild turns in plot, daring viewers to try to keep up with him, let
alone guess ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is at it again. Now comes ``Harsh Realm,'' a Byzantine
mind game that after the first episode Friday night will leave you
confused but intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, just what Carter fans want.
</P>
<P>
   But is it really worth the intellectually masochistic
satisfaction? To be honest, I don't know yet, since I haven't
exactly figured out this Fox fantasy drama. But it did get better,
and a lot more focused in my mind, when I watched a tape of the
pilot a second time.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Thomas Hobbes (Scott Bairstow), an American Army hero in a
1994 Sarajevo skirmish, is a short-timer in 1999, getting ready to
leave the military and move from New Jersey to California with his
fiancee, Sophie (Samantha Mathis). But he is unexpectedly called in
by a superior (Lance Henrickson of ``Millennium'' in a cameo) to
play what the officer calls a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harsh Realm ... It's a simulated war game, a virtual-reality
game used to teach situational war strategy,'' the officer tells
the less-than-philosophical Hobbes. ``The Pentagon developed it,
kept it under wraps. We got it on line looking for a crackerjack
soldier who can beat our high score: Sergeant Major Omar
Santiago.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, the game is more than a game _ it can affect our
real world _ and Santiago (Terry O'Quinn of ``Millennium and ``The
X-Files'' movie) has hijacked the alternate reality and created the
military junta that rules it. Dozens of soldiers have been sent
``into'' the game to ``take out'' _ that is, kill _ Santiago, a
retired soldier who was the most decorated combat veteran in
Southeast Asia and now is reigning Lord of the Realm.
</P>
<P>
   So who else is in the game? Us _ at least copies of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using the 1990 Census, satellite cartography and other
classified data, the creators of Harsh Realm have simulated a
virtual reality, where landscapes and people are identical to our
world, down to every man, woman and child,'' an offscreen narrator
(Gillian Anderson, uncredited) in a video tells Hobbes before he
unwittingly is sent into the game. What he finds is another world
populated by ``copies'' _ and other soldiers and mercenaries sent
in before him to kill Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   Question: If the game copied everybody, and you are sent in to
take out Santiago, wouldn't there then be two of you? (See what I
mean?) By the way, if you die in the game, you die in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Now does everybody understand this show based on a comic book?
Don't worry, it even took one of the stars some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much understood the show when I read it, but I had a
hard time visualizing it,'' O'Quinn said. ``I'm kind of computer
illiterate. So I had a tough time seeing it. The fact that Carter
is doing it is a good starting point.''
</P>
<P>
   But will the audience get it? ``I guess there is some concern,''
O'Quinn said. ``There might be some things if you miss the first
one you won't know what is going on. They are going to have to find
a good one- or two-minute intro that explains things.''
</P>
<P>
   Or you can watch it twice. It works.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
