<HEADER>
A0675 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-HEARTS-HN     10-08 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-HEARTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RANDOM HEARTS' CHARMS BUT HAS TOO LITTLE SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the mood for a big, glossy, super-star-wattage Hollywood
romance that goes ... nowhere? If so, you'll be glad to learn of
``Random Hearts,'' a sleek zero of a movie that asks whether two
gorgeous people can get it on.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is, of course, yes. But we knew that. We also knew
that Harrison Ford can carry anything, and we don't mean Samsonite.
This helps, considering that his chemistry with the fascinating but
cool Kristin Scott Thomas fails to spark firestorms of desire, and
that Sydney Pollack's direction runs at two speeds, slow and stop.
</P>
<P>
   When something happens to kick the thing into gear _ i.e., when
one character assaults and/or emphatically kisses another _ the
effect is altogether jarring, like waking from an afternoon nap to
the sound of a car horn.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Ford plays ``Dutch'' Van Den Broeck, a Washington,
D.C., internal-affairs cop whose wife, Peyton (Susanna Thompson),
goes down in a Boeing 737 bound for Miami. In the same crash dies
Cullen Chandler (Peter Coyote), husband of Kay Chandler (Thomas), a
New Hampshire politico who's running for Congress. Kay and Dutch
are initially unaware that their spouses have died, because _ as
fate and infidelity would have it _ Kay and Dutch don't know that
their respective spouses were heading to Florida for a little
hanky-panky by the beach.
</P>
<P>
   When the news hits, nobody cries. Nobody collapses. Nobody
heaves shuddering sobs of grief. Instead, Dutch's response to his
wife's death is to become obsessed with her adultery, tracking down
information on the couple's hotel, their trysts, their love nest.
</P>
<P>
   In his pursuit he ticks off Kay, who just Vants To Be Alone, at
least until she changes her mind about Dutch and starts necking
with him violently in an airport parking lot. And so it goes: The
gorgeous people get it on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Random Hearts'' is lovely to look at, and it boasts a few nice
character turns (from Charles S. Dutton and Pollack himself), but
the film suffers from a fatal lack of plot. Nothing much happens.
Despite Dutch's investigation, we never learn anything substantive
about the cheating spouses. How did they meet? How long had they
been fooling around? Was some vast governmental conspiracy behind
their affair? Were they drug-runners? Terrorists? Cuban
nationalists? Time-travelers?
</P>
<P>
   Based on a novel by Warren Adler, ``Random Hearts'' splits its
writing chores between Darryl Ponicsan (``Murder in the First,''
``School Ties''), who gets credit for the adaptation, and Kurt
Luedtke (``Out of Africa,'' ``Absence of Malice,'' both Pollack
pictures), who gets credit for the screenplay. The fine points of
such divisions of labor are probably lost on anyone outside
Hollywood, but the results are the same: a plot that droops, a
subplot (involving a corrupt cop) that's more interesting than the
central romance, and dialogue that trades in hesitant aphorisms.
</P>
<P>
   Pollack's last directing effort was his unfairly maligned remake
of ``Sabrina,'' in which Harrison Ford made a good-faith effort at
playing Humphrey Bogart to Julia Ormond's Audrey Hepburn. In that
film, at least, a gaping age difference stood between the comely
couple and a happy future; in this one, nothing stands between them
beyond a pair of adulterous dead spouses (who are never properly
mourned, anyway) and a desire to duck some really nasty gossip.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, it's an election year. Kay has that congressional seat
to consider.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Random Hearts'' charms, and it does here and there, it's
invariably thanks to Ford's worn-in charisma _ a reassuring mix of
vulnerability and take-charge, buckwheat guyness. Ford's best
scenes are at the start of the film, as Dutch fumblingly learns of
his wife's death and infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Van Den Broeck, I don't think you should be alone right
now,'' says a solicitous airline official who visits Dutch's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah?'' Dutch snaps. ``I was alone when you got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who sports a near-perfect American accent, brings her
crisp, authoritative presence to the film but never quite explodes
with Ford the way she did with Robert Redford in ``The Horse
Whisperer.'' There's no danger here _ no suspense, no nagging doubt
about the fate of Kay and Dutch. We assume all along that they'll
follow the tale to its end. The question is, will we?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
