<HEADER>
A0693 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-HNS &LR;      10-08 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI MAKES EXHIBIT A SENSATIONAL HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL LUCIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last Sunday, as we rode down Broadway on our way to
the ``Sensation'' exhibit at the Brooklyn Museum of Art, the
cabdriver warned us of what was to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to go yesterday, but the line of people was out in
the street,'' he said. He suggested we visit the botanical gardens
next door to the museum instead. ``I'll go see it in December,'' he
said of the controversial show.
</P>
<P>
   We disregarded the advice and took the subway to Brooklyn, which
was complicated a little by the fact that the stop right in front
of the museum was closed. After a three- or four-block walk, we
came to a line of people maybe 1,000 strong stretching the length
of the museum, along the sidewalk and almost into the street.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoned protest signs lay on the lawn, and the police made
their presence apparent, as about 20 officers milled around in
small groups in front of the building.
</P>
<P>
   The waiting line was surprisingly diverse, ranging from families
with young children, to turtleneck-clad artists, to the elderly
most lured, like my classmate and me, by the media frenzy. The
mellow crowd outside buzzed with conversation about the
circumstances surrounding the show inside.
</P>
<P>
   One teen-age girl, seething with pseudo-intellectual comments,
asked a cop, ``What do you think of the whole Giuliani thing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a public servant. I have no opinion,'' he replied, before
going after a woman trying to scalp a ticket. (Ticketholders were
admitted immediately, skipping the line.)
</P>
<P>
   After a week of religious outcries, repeated condemnations by
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and inescapable hype about elephant dung on
religious icons, a classmate and I had headed to New York to see
what all the squabbling was about.
</P>
<P>
   After a half-hour, we finally made our way inside, and once we
passed through the metal detector and the bag check we joined the
ticket line, where we waited 10 more minutes to gladly pay our
$9.75 admission and at last enter ``Sensation.''
</P>
<P>
   The saga did not end there.
</P>
<P>
   It continued with an overflowing elevator ride and another line
on the fifth floor. Then, right when I was beginning to feel that
the process was more difficult than applying to college, we entered
the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   It was evident that the crowd of about 5,000 lacked serious art
viewers; many visitors wandered aimlessly, glancing quickly at a
piece before moving on, often appearing bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I'm an art critic. My museum experience includes only
the Metropolitan Museum of Art, also in New York, and the
Smithsonian, in Washington. I was, however, finding ``Sensation''
interesting and educational, regardless of the fact that some of
the work was rather unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one artist used mannequins _ some dismembered and
hanging from trees. Another work portrayed children with genitals
on their faces. It was bizarre, and I could see why some might find
it disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   One of the works that I found fascinating was a fiberglass male
face, about 5 feet tall and 4 feet wide. The artist had paid an
amazing amount of attention to detail. Every eyelash and nose hair
was strategically placed. The face had blemishes, there was a
little wax in the ears, and there was an expression in the eyes
that seemed to stare right through you. We moved on, doing our best
to interpret and react to each work. And finally we encountered the
reason we came, ``The Holy Virgin Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christopher Ofili painting at the heart of the controversy
clung to the wall, protected by a plate of clear plastic and two
security guards.
</P>
<P>
   We slipped through a crowd of about 20 people surrounding it to
get a close look. I stood there, almost wanting to laugh. If the
cartoonish image did not have the words ``Virgin Mary'' under it,
the average passer-by probably never would have figured out that it
was supposed to be her. A lacquered piece of elephant dung covered
one breast, and photographic cutouts of buttocks that looked like
wings surrounded the image.
</P>
<P>
   After a moment, we escaped the group of onlookers and took in
the rest of ``Sensation.'' Ofili, who painted ``Mary,'' had three
other paintings in the show, two of which involved elephant dung.
Not to say that the paintings looked crappy _ they actually were
very intricate, and more intriguing than the work that had caused
the ruckus.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the exhibit, I'm inclined to continue believing
that the First Amendment is superior to the opinion of a mayor. But
maybe they should change the name of the show to
``Sensationalized,'' because that's what it seemed to have become.
Only Giuliani could provoke so many people to pay 10 bucks to see
elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I'd like to thank the mayor for enticing me to go see
an interesting art show. I'm sure the people who run the museum
would like to thank him, too, for such wonderful free advertising.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Lucia is a senior at Schalmont High School in Rotterdam,
N.Y.)
</P>
</TEXT>
