<HEADLINE>
NASA PROBES MEETING OF SCIENTISTS, EXECS AND UFO ENTHUSIAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An upcoming private meeting between Silicon
Valley high-tech executives, NASA scientists and a high-profile UFO
enthusiast has sparked an investigation by a government agency.
</P>
<P>
   Special Agent Keith Tate, an investigator with the Long Beach
branch of NASA's Office of Inspector General, has been calling
Silicon Valley sources, including the San Francisco Examiner,
seeking information about a planned meeting next Tuesday between
research scientists and Silicon Valley high-tech executives.
</P>
<P>
   At that meeting, first reported by the Examiner, attendees,
including scientists from the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's Ames Research Center in Mountain View, Calif.,
will discuss propulsion technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to determine if any proprietary information will
be talked about at that meeting,'' said Tate. ``We're very
concerned about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Staging the meeting will be the International Space Sciences
Organization. Its founder is Joe Firmage, a 28-year-old, high-tech
executive who made headlines late last year when he published a Web
site and book in which he recounted his beliefs in space aliens. On
the ISSO site, he claims to have been visited in his bedroom one
night by such an alien.
</P>
<P>
   Firmage also has stated that some of the high technology of
today was obtained from the legendary alien space craft crash that
allegedly occurred in Roswell, N.M., in 1947. Firmage stepped down
from his post as CEO of the giant Santa Clara-based USWeb Internet
consulting firm following his revelations because of shareholder
concerns about his extra-terrestrial pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   An ISSO spokesman had no comment on the NASA probe.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several years, NASA has been researching an array
of exotic propulsion technologies through a small program dubbed
Breakthrough Propulsion Physics.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these techniques thumb their noses at Albert Einstein's
theory of relativity, which postulates that nothing can travel
faster than the speed of light _ 186,000 miles per second.
</P>
<P>
   These include using technologies familiar to science fiction
fans: worm holes and warp drives.
</P>
<P>
   Firmage, according to his Web site, says that ``there is
stunningly good evidence that UFOs are real starships.''
</P>
<P>
   He writes that ``whatever did or did not happen at Roswell in
1947 will ultimately prove to be a rounding error when the
implications of this phenomenon become widely known.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0721 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-VISITING-DEER-HNS &LR;      10-08 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISITING-DEER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISORIENTED DEER DROP IN ON WOMAN FOR NIGHTTIME VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was sort of a macabre wildlife marriage of
``Animal Farm'' and ``The Night Before Christmas'' and it has
changed Maggie Clark's whole way of looking at her friendly
neighborhood deer.
</P>
<P>
   While others in Clark's area have been building higher and
higher fences to keep out deer, she's been feeding them and naming
them. Until now.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 47, a business calendar saleswoman, was watching ``Animal
Farm,'' based on the George Orwell novel about animals revolting
against humans, last Sunday night when on her rooftop, she heard
such a clatter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard this big crashing noise outside my bedroom window and
I assume it's the big bucks who are always hanging out in this
neighborhood and crashing into things,'' she said. ``Two minutes
later, my whole house starts shaking. I'm freaking out, thinking,
`My God, they're ramming my front door.'''
</P>
<P>
   Telling a friend who had just called that she'd better check
things out, Clark said, ``I looked out the door into the hallway
and they're walking toward me. They could've been ambling, they
could've been charging. I don't remember. I screamed and slammed
the door shut. My friend, of course, thinks I'm being murdered.''
</P>
<P>
   The deer, both male, one older and one younger, apparently had
jumped from a hill onto her ranch home's roof, then tumbled through
latticework over the patio and, panicked, tore through a screen
door into the house.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Clark's screams alarmed the beasts. The bigger one
fled back outside. ``He had to turn his entire head sideways to get
his rack out of my now-torn up screen door,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   But the other dashed into the living room. ``He's going berserk,
freaking out,'' Clark said. Although she said Thursday that there
are still hoof marks all over, the frantic buck miraculously
avoided breaking any wine glasses, a huge glass cocktail table or
several plate glass windows.
</P>
<P>
   During the mayhem, Clark was able to call 911. As the frenzied
deer dashed to the other end of the house, the 911 dispatcher kept
yelling, ``Are you OK? Are you OK?'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The animal went down to her office, Clark added, ``tearing
things up. (But) he didn't go near my computers. Actually, he was a
very careful deer for (being) as frantic as he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, police arrived and, after assessing the scene in
amazement, they coaxed the deer back outside.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rampage, Clark said damage to her house wasn't all
that much _ maybe $500 _ but she's looking at deer differently
these days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0733 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     10-08 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERMANNED TEAM MISSING WHAT IT TAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Every player who entered the clubhouse saw the
pictures Thursday. They were framed, hanging eerily on the walls of
the Red Sox' temporary quarters at Jacobs Field. To the left: An
advertisement for ``Field of Dreams'' _ autographed by Kevin
Costner. To the right: An ad for ``Angels in the Outfield'' _
accompanied by the appropriate disclaimer: You gotta believe.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox saw that prophetic artwork as they trudged the route
from their showers to their lockers. Talk of angels and dreams is
perfect for them because it is obvious that they need to rely more
on the spiritual, magical, and mystical rather than the physical.
To paraphrase Jack Nicholson, they can't handle the physical. And
it's not entirely their fault. In two Division Series games here,
this is what happened when the Sox tried to be physical: Indians
14, Sox 3. They tried Thursday and lost, 11-1.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after walking by those photos, Sox reliever Derek Lowe
was asked about the team's fans. He was asked if he thinks anyone
has abandoned the Sox and opted to leap from a local bridge
instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may not have jumped yet,'' Lowe said, ``but they may be
hanging on by an arm.''
</P>
<P>
   As for those who already jumped? It's too bad, because they
missed the point. The Sox do not trail their best-of-five series
because they choked or were haunted by ancient Curses. They are on
the verge of losing to the Indians for the third time in five years
because the entire organization hasn't learned what it takes to win
in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously that includes the players. Bret Saberhagen, a man who
walked 11 batters all year, walked three in the third inning
Thursday. The day before, John Valentin could have thrown out Manny
Ramirez and gotten Lowe out of the sixth inning. His throw was low.
The next batter, Jim Thome, hit a home run that tied the game.
There have been errors, bad at-bats, and bad pitching. But
regardless of what happens in the next three days, Dan Duquette and
his staff will have to upgrade their off-the-field plans in the
offseason, which could start as soon as Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox general manager has shown that he knows how to take a
couple premium materials, combine them with random discarded parts,
and produce a playoff team. No one can question Duquette's ability
to get his team there. He should be given props for that,
especially since many GMs are fired before ever assembling a
playoff team. But the next step is to produce a team that can win
in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Boston has played Cleveland in the playoffs nine times since
1995, winning only once. The Sox may be able to handle the powerful
Tribe in the regular season, when teams don't nitpick nearly as
much as they do in the playoffs. So it's not that the Indians know
something the Sox don't. It's just that they have the ability to do
something the Sox can't: They can be physical any time they want.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, after all the talk of mistakes and errors and bad
pitching, we should come to the conclusion that the Indians are
simply the better team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll say that,'' Valentin said. ``They have a
lot of talent over there. A whole lot of talent. When they play
well, it is hard to beat them. But we've got a plan of how we like
to do things. And if we follow it, we should win. But sometimes you
can follow it and lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Really, that is the major difference between the Indians and the
Sox. One team leans on its abundance of talent; the other leans on
its strategy. When the venue is a classroom, the intellectuals can
beat out the brutes. But when you are trying to go to the World
Series, the men with the most muscle usually win. The Sox can still
win this series and advance to the American League Championship
Series. Here's the only condition: They can't make any mistakes. No
matter what your profession, that's a terrible way to live.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Sox catcher Jason Varitek sat in a clubhouse chair and
talked about the mistakes he thought he made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I made a bad pitch selection to (Harold) Baines,'' the
catcher said. With the Indians leading, 3-1, in the third, Baines
hit a three-run homer that secured the win. ``We can't let Harold
beat us there,'' Varitek said. ``I probably should have gone to the
mound and slowed the pace of the game. That's what I mean by a bad
selection. I'll take the blame there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was mentioned to Varitek that since the Division Series
format began in '95, only one team _ the Mariners _ has come back
to win after being down 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why there is history,'' he replied. ``And that's why
they keep records.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question the Sox have been enjoyable to watch this
season. In the bloated stat world known as the American League, the
Sox actually won with decent pitching and by perfecting
hit-and-runs. But there are reasons that many fans will feel more
like Sox pallbearers when they attend Saturday's game. They
understand that the players, coaches, and manager maximized what
they had. They also understand it is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   And that's how Duquette becomes part of this. He needs to
acquire more premium parts. The Indians are Saks Fifth Avenue. The
Sox are T.J. Maxx. This has to change. If not, the playoff results
will remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
