   CLINTON-CANADA ( Ottawa) _ President Clinton inaugurates new
U.S. embassy in Ottawa, meets with Canadian prime minister. By
James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Dateline to Come) _ There are reports of a
Chechen counterattack against Russian forces. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With locator map.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TRAINCRASH (London) _ A preliminary report says use of
warning device system could have prevented the London train crash
that killed more than 40 people with 70 others still missing. By
Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (category ``w'' &LR; )
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH-CARE (Washington) _ Exploring what happens next
following the House's passage Thursday of legislation to overhaul
health care regulations _ a bill much at odds with the measure
passed earlier by the Senate. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-BAN-TREATY ( Washington) _ Senate debate on test-ban treaty
opens. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (category ``a'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-DANCE-BAND (Miami) _ Hostilities are at a peak once again
here with the announcement that Los Van Van, Cuba's most popular
dance band and one that has performed all over the United States,
but never in Miami, is coming to town. The band is scheduled to
play the Miami Arena on Saturday night in what promises to be a
test for both freedom of expression in this city and the shifting
views within Cuban Miami itself. 1,400 words. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-FREEWAY (Los Angeles) _ At one level, the latest fight
over a South Pasadena freeway is a classic, parochial conflict,
pitting one community against another. But in a broader sense, the
battle of Highway 710 is an example of the biggest question
bedeviling a region that is again expanding explosively after a
deep recession: How to accommodate growth in Southern California
without destroying the very qualities of life that drew masses of
Americans here in the first place. 1,600 words. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FIDDLE-REVIVAL (Nicut, West Va.) _ Many young people
traditionally must leave this state to find promising careers,
rarely mastering and passing on the Appalachian folk ways of their
elders. But lately, young people searching out uncommercialized,
authentic old music have been showing up on Heritage Center
scholarships at the cabin doors of the aging masters learning how
to fiddle. 1,100 words. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-SWEENEY (undated) _ The head of the AFL-CIO, John Sweeney,
is leading a revival of organized labor in both the workplace and
in politics. 1,300 words. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-MEXICO-SCHOOLS (Albuquerque) _ The New Mexico Board of
Education votes to teach evolution in state schools, in contrast to
Kansas, which has deleted all mention of evolution in its
guidelines for teachers. 1,000 words. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FLOOD-AID (Newark, N.J.) _ Flood victims and lawmakers around
the Northeast are clamoring that they're not getting their fair
share of disaster aid. By Ronald Smothers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (category ``f'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY (Undated) _ The number of workers on U.S. payrolls fell
by 8,000 in September, the first drop since January 1996, as
Hurricane Floyd caused flooding and shut businesses. While job
growth slowed, average hourly wages posted their biggest gain in
more than 10 years, rising 7 cents, to to $13.37. The jobless rate
remained at 4.2 percent, a 29-year low. The Dow was up 73 points at
2 p.m. 1,100 words. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   LAGARDE-LAWFIRM (Chicago) _ Christine Lagarde becomes the first
woman to lead Baker &AMP; McKenzie, one of the world's largest law
firms. Her election, by an overwhelming majority of the Chicago
firm's 548 partners on Thursday night, of whom 91 percent are men,
is a sign that women are finally moving into power at some major
law firms, which have been behind even their clients in corporate
America at promoting women into management's upper echelons. 1,800
words. By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   FCC-CABLE (Washington) _ The FCC relaxes significantly the rules
governing cable ownership concentration, just two months after
relaxing similar rules on broadcast ownership. Friday's step will
allow AT&AMP;T to complete its takeover of Mediaone with only marginal
divestitures. 1,000 words. By Steven Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   XEROX-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Xerox warns that third-quarter
profits will be sharply lower than expected and that revenue will
be little changed because of weak sales and increased competition.
700 words. By Claudia Deutsch.
</P>
