<HEADLINE>
BCS REMAINS AN INEXACT SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of you probably think the coaches' and writers' polls
decide the front-runners for the Bowl Championship Series title
game in the Sugar Bowl Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   This logic would suggest that Florida State and Penn State are
in line for New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Think again. As part of the BCS selection process, eight
computer rankings will be a factor _ along with the two major
polls, team record, and strength of schedule _ ranging from the
popular Sagarin and Dunkel rankings to the obscure Billingsley and
Rothman rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State is No. 1 in only three rankings _ Dunkel,
Billingsley, and Sagarin.
</P>
<P>
   In the California-based Rothman rankings, Penn State is ranked
just 16th.
</P>
<P>
   Even more startling is the top five of the Rothman rankings: 1.
Virginia Tech, 2. Marshall, 3. Florida State, 4. Clemson, and 5.
Nebraska. Also ahead of Penn State are Virginia, Minnesota,
Mississippi State, and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   We are in the no-harm, no-foul stage of the season, with the
first BCS ranking scheduled to be released at the end of the month,
but please. How in the name of Bear Bryant can anyone take this
process seriously if a ranking as off-base as the Rothman is
considered?
</P>
<P>
   Using those rankings as the definitive measuring stick, we would
have a national championship game of Virginia Tech vs. Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Rothman rankings, Penn State and Tennessee would fight
for the last spot in a 16-team playoff format.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the criticism of the BCS last year was that there were
too few rankings with too much weight. Now it appears eight is more
than enough, but in a negative way.
</P>
<P>
   All of this goes back to the issue of having a playoff system to
decide a national champion.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS was formed to preserve the bowl system but also to
implement a formula to decide who would play in a rotating national
championship bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   What was flawed last season _ and what appears to be flawed this
season _ is the method of selecting which teams get to New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   As subjective as the coaches' and writers' polls are, they still
involve humans making decisions based on what they see and feel.
</P>
<P>
   With these computers, one wonders about the mind-set of the
programmers. The Rothman rankings list 1-AA Troy State at 44th,
ahead of Auburn and Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   The eight computerized rankings count for one-fourth of the
total of the BCS rankings, which will determine the No. 1 and No. 2
teams.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS was criticized last year, so the system was ``tweaked,''
as BCS chairman Roy Kramer put it.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through a season which has yet to take a defining turn,
the system may need to be tweaked again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bowling for BC
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not too early to start talking about Boston College's bowl
chances. Two more wins _ probably against Temple and Pittsburgh _
get the Eagles a bowl game in Hawaii. Three more will get them to
the Music City Bowl in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   The Big East has arrangements for three BCS slots: the Gator
Bowl, the Insight.com Bowl, and the Music City Bowl. The X-factor
is Notre Dame. If the Irish qualify for a bowl bid, the last
bowl-eligible Big East team will be displaced, and that could be
BC.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish can't go back to the Gator Bowl this season (they were
there last season), but they could take the slot in the Music City
or Insight.com Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   With three early-season losses and Tennessee, USC, Arizona
State, Stanford, and BC still on the schedule, the Irish need to
win five of their last seven (they play 12 games this season) to
qualify with a 7-5 mark.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Top 25-bound?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of BC, the Eagles are one of the 13 unbeaten Division
1-A teams. The other 12 are ranked in the Top 25 . . . Rutgers
coach Terry Shea is winless in odd-numbered years. Shea took over
in 1997, a winless season, won five games last year, and is 0-4
this season . . . The Florida State situation involving wide
receivers Peter Warrick and Laveranues Coles, in which more than
$200 worth of merchandise allegedly was purchased at a department
store in Tallahassee while less than $25 was rung up on the cash
register by a friendly clerk, drew this response from Warrick, who
felt the whole thing was blown out of proportion by the media.
``It's not like I killed the president,'' he said. It will be
interesting to see if Warrick's Heisman Trophy chances are
affected. So far he is the leading contender, with Georgia Tech's
Joe Hamilton a close second, followed by Alabama running back Shaun
Alexander, Wisconsin running back Ron Dayne, and Purdue QB Drew
Brees . . . There's turmoil at Alabama as well, where several
players and administrators had speeding tickets fixed. ``What's the
big deal?'' asked coach Mike Dubose. When you are a coach who is
under siege, as he is, any turmoil isn't good . . . Auburn punter
Damon Duval had words with coach Tom Tuberville during last week's
loss to Tennessee after Duval's pass on a fake punt was overthrown.
No big deal, but they were shown on national television and when
the redshirt freshman was sent to the locker room by Tuberville to
cool off, the cameras picked up Duval flashing a smile and a peace
sign. That did it. Duval is no longer the Tigers' No. 1 punter.
``We don't condone that type of behavior,'' said Tuberville . . .
Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez had knee replacement surgery this
week and is recuperating at the Mayo Clinic. That won't slow
Alvarez, however. He will watch the Badgers' game against Minnesota
on a big-screen television and have a phone hookup to the sidelines
. . . Florida State coach Bobby Bowden signed a five-year contract
extension. The reason it was announced in midseason was that other
schools were using Bowden's age (he turns 70 next month) against
him in recruiting battles . . . One of the better turnarounds of
the season has been Hawaii's 4-1 start under new coach June Jones.
In recent years, the Rainbows have ranked as one of the worst teams
in Division 1-A, but Jones has watched his team roll to four
straight wins after a season-opening loss to Southern Cal . . .
Watch out for East Carolina. If they get past Southern Mississippi
Saturday, the Pirates could go 11-0 . . . Fans are in an uproar in
Columbus, Ohio, because Ohio State had the audacity to lose two of
its first five games. Could this truly be a rebuilding year for
coach John Cooper, who has lost enough pro prospects in the past
three years to supply a legitimate NFL franchise? . . . Virginia
Tech plays winless Rutgers Saturday, which is bad enough for the
Scarlet Knights. But the Hokies have also won 21 of their last 27
road games.
</P>
</TEXT>
