<HEADLINE>
SINGLE WOMAN, 67, SHOULD USE NESTEGG TO REDUCE MORTGAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October 10, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a single woman, 67 years old. I have $55,000 in a money
market account, $25,000 in a CD maturing in December, $13,000 in an
IRA maturing this month, and $7,000 in a checking account. My
monthly income from Social Security and retirement is $1,650, and I
am able to save $200 to $300 of this. I have a $75,000 mortgage on
my condo and no other bills. I also have $3,000 in Vanguard Windsor
II fund, and a $6,500 stock portfolio, which has lost $600 at this
time. Id like to be able to leave my daughter as much as possible.
Can you suggest some relatively safe funds, bonds, etc.?
</P>
<P>
   J.C., La Jolla, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, since you now have more than 90 percent of your money
invested in absolutely secure instruments such as the money market,
CD, and other bank accounts, Im going to assume that your appetite
for risk is pretty limited.
</P>
<P>
   It strikes me that you are probably paying more in interest on
your mortgage than most of your investments are earning, so it
might make sense to use some of your current nest egg to prepay the
mortgage, and subsequently to add whatever you are able to save to
your mortgage payments. This will increase the net worth of your
estate at a more rapid rate than adding funds to the money market
or CD accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Heres what I suggest. If the money market account is with a bank
rather than a mutual fund, transfer $20,000 of that money to a
mutual fund money market account, which will probably pay about
twice as much as most banks do on their money market accounts. Ill
suggest Vanguards Prime Money Market fund, since you already have
an account there and its easiest to keep all your fund holdings
within one family.
</P>
<P>
   Id then move $20,000 of the money market account to Vanguard
GNMA fund, which invests in government-guaranteed mortgage
securities and should bring you a yield in the 6.5 percent range.
But read the prospectus and annual report carefully before you do
this, because over short time periods this and other GNMA funds can
be quite volatile. This is a good investment only when held for the
long run, in which the upswings and downturns (caused by changes in
interest rate climates) tend to cancel each other out. Look
carefully at performance figures over the last decade, and youll
see the short-term volatility I describe; if youre uncomfortable
with this risk, or if you feel you might have to call upon these
funds in an emergency, this is not a good fund for you.
</P>
<P>
   Id then move $5,000 of the money market cash to Vanguard Star
fund, which is a conservative balanced fund, dividing its assets
between stock and bond holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I would use the remaining $10,000 from the money market
account balance to prepay the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   If you are comfortable with that strategy and if you feel that
having $20,000 in the money market fund plus $7,000 in your
checking account is enough in the way of liquid assets to protect
yourself from emergencies, you might also add the proceeds of the
CD that matures this month to the mortgage prepayment. If you feel
that having more money in liquid accounts is best, you could simply
roll the CD over into a new issue. Or you could roll over some of
the money into a new CD and use the remainder to add to the
mortgage prepayment.
</P>
<P>
   I think these moves would have the effect of increasing the
potential for growth within your savings, without dramatically
increasing the risk level.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are 29 and 27 years old respectively, with
no plans to have children. Our current savings consist of $15,500
in a Roth IRA account invested in Putnam Voyager fund, Class B.,
and my 401(k) plan now worth $27,000 evenly divided among Fidelity
Blue Chip Growth, Fidelity Fund, Fidelity Magellan and Fidelity
Contrafund. We also have $2,000 each in Invesco Financial Services,
Invesco Health Services, and my companys stock. We have $4,000 each
in SIT Large Cap, Janus Worldwide, and Fidelity Cash Reserves
funds. Finally, we have $6,500 in Fidelity Equity Income II fund. I
contribute $500 a month to my 401(k) and $200 a month to my
companys stock purchase plan. My husband will begin contributing
$200 a month to his companys 401(k) plan once he becomes eligible
in a few months. Our current debt and obligations consists of two
car payments and rent. Our investment goals are to purchase a home
in the next three to five years and retirement. Do you have any
suggestions on our current portfolio to help us meet our goals?
</P>
<P>
   N.H., Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think youre doing reasonably well with your retirement
portfolio, although a little more diversification away from the
large-cap stocks would doubtless help in the long run. But for the
life of me, aside from the $4,000 money market account, I cant find
the savings for your anticipated purchase of a new home. Since all
of your ongoing savings are going into either tax-deferred accounts
or your companys stock, Im going to presume that you are thinking
of the $18,500 which is in stock mutual fund accounts, plus the
money market position, as the source of your down payment. To my
thinking none of the stock funds are appropriate for money which
you will likely be calling upon in 36 to 60 months. The stock funds
represent too much risk for such a near-term goal. So my first
suggestion is to decide how much of your total savings is to be
used for the down payment on your first home, and to move that
money to appropriate vehicles, such as the money market fund, CDs,
or perhaps a short-term bond fund at the riskiest. In addition, you
should decide if any of your ongoing savings should be earmarked
for the down payment, and if so to put it in similar vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   As for your retirement accounts, all of the funds yopu hold
concentrate their portfolios in large-cap domestic stocks. I would
begin by looking at the options within your 401(k) program, looking
for attractive offerings in the mid-cap and small-cap arenas, plus
perhaps an international and a health care fund. If there are no
such options available, you could at least achieve some
diversification by moving the money in the Roth IRA to funds in
those categories. Once your husband joins his companys 401(k) plan,
I suggest he make his investment choices with diversification in
mind. My advice would be to look a all the retirement accounts as a
single portfolio, and then to put 50 percent to 60 percent in
domestic large-cap funds, and then to divide the rest, more or less
evenly, among a mid-cap, a small-cap, an international, and a
sector fund. In the latter category, I tend to find health care and
technology the most attractive sectors for long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why would it not be better for a 75-year-old interested in
income to have a major portion of his portfolio in a Fidelity or
Massachusetts tax-free fund rather than a GNMA?
</P>
<P>
   H.N., Westwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, in some tax circumstances, it might be advantageous,
but dont think that tax-exempt funds and Ginnie Mae offerings have
no differences beyond their different tax status. As this is
written, Vanguards Massachusetts Tax Exempt fund offers a 5.17
percent yield, and Vanguards GNMA fund offers a 6.84 percent yield.
Certainly somebody in a substantial tax bracket would be better off
with the fund that is free of both federal and state income taxes.
But the tax-free fund -- like most municipals -- holds a long-term
portfolio, in contrast to the intermediate-term holdings of he GNMA
fund. You can see this right away when you look at year-to-date
results for the two funds. This has been a pretty tough year for
bond funds of all stripes, but the 3.73 percent year-to-date loss
for the Vanguard Massachusetts Municipal fund is a long way from
token .18 percent gain for Vanguard GNMA. Whenever you have a
fixed-income fund with a long-term portfolio, the risk level is
greater than that of a fixed-income fund with an intermediate-term
portfolio. In this case, the difference is more than enough to
erase any advantage in yield. And if you went to an
intermediate-term Massachusetts tax-free fund, the yield would
decline accordingly, until the advantage over the GNMA fund would
be erased for all but the wealthiest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
