<HEADER>
A0737 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-CLEMENS-BOS &LR;      10-08 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEMENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS TO REVEAL HIS TRUE STRIPES SATURDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Will the real Roger Clemens step forth? A lot of
people have been asking that since he donned Yankee pinstripes in
February.
</P>
<P>
   With his first postseason start since 1995 a day away, Clemens
is going about his business. Long runs along the nearby parkway.
Exhausting exercises, performed mostly in private at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens flew to Texas Thursday to prepare for his start against
the Rangers in Game 3 of the American League Division Series
Saturday night. ``Too much to do,'' he said in a brief encounter
Thursday. ``Can't talk. Got some people to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   He probably does. Certainly, Clemens is focused on the job at
hand. Now 37, he has become a very private person. To many, he is a
hired gun, even though he had no control over being traded from
Toronto to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was an insurance policy for a team that won 114
regular-season games last year and maintained the best record in
the American League this year. The Yankees have a four-man rotation
that includes David Cone, Orlando Hernandez, and Andy Pettitte. Is
it a sin to have only a 14-10 record for such a squad? If the
Yankees don't repeat, it might be. Yankee manager Joe Torre says he
has four guys who can be No. 1 starters, and for the Division
Series, Clemens fits in well at No. 3. In the next series he might
be No. 2 or No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see Roger bringing to the table is his preparation,''
said Torre. ``Also his history of the number of games he's won and
how dominant he's been. Experience is big with me. For the most
part, Roger's stuff has been good, but his command hasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not the way people are used to describing Roger Clemens.
He has won five Cy Young Awards, none of them as a No. 3 man. This
is a change that happens when you get older.
</P>
<P>
   In his Red Sox days, they talked about his immense pitching
ability and his leadership qualities. As a kid out of the
University of Texas, he was confident on the mound and almost as
skinny as Pedro Martinez. He challenged hitters with his fastballs.
In winning his first three Cy Youngs, he was the pride of New
England and seemed to enjoy the role. But that has changed, and so
has Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens left Boston after posting a 10-13 record in 1996. He
complained about the way he was treated by general manager Dan
Duquette. Even worse, he was stunned by the criticism from Red Sox
fans, who were quick to point out that he was only 40-39 in his
last four seasons in Boston. Even now, just the mention of his name
at Fenway incites the boo-birds.
</P>
<P>
   The trip from Beantown to Toronto was good for Clemens, and it
gave him another chance to win new fans and two more Cy Youngs. But
his frequent barbs at the Blue Jays (specifically the quality of
his teammates) revealed another side. Clemens wanted to leave
Toronto because he felt the organization no longer wanted to win.
Thus he had no trouble with the trade to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The trade was suppose to help both teams while giving Clemens a
change to achieve his only remaining goal _ a World Series ring.
The Blue Jays got David Wells, Homer Bush, and Graeme Lloyd in what
was called the biggest trade since Babe Ruth was acquired from the
Red Sox. Clemens posted a 14-10 record in 30 starts with a 4.60
earned run average. He won't win the Cy Young, but if the Yankees
repeat, no one _ including Clemens _ will care.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fit in with the team well,'' said Yankee coach Don Zimmer,
who as a bench coach with the Red Sox in 1992 observed Clemens on a
daily basis. ``I know he would have liked to have a better year
pitching. There were times when he was the real Roger that
everybody knows. There were other times when he struggled. He's
been no different here than he was when I was in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does a lot of work on his own. Lots of times you won't see
him on the field, but it's not because he's not working. The guy
comes out on the bench. He roots for pitchers. He roots for
hitters. There's no problem with Roger. One thing about it, he
gives you what he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre, ``I think a lot of it is we're getting to know each
other. At times we gave him more rest than he was used to having.
Sometimes that's a hinderance to a power pitcher who goes at a
certain rhythm. He likes to be a little tired, maybe. We took a
little edge off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked with him the last few days, and he's got his plans
for Game 3 already mapped out. He seems very relaxed. He is very
mindful of what his job is. You just hope he doesn't get too pumped
up. When that happens, he can't control it on the mound. David Cone
has the same problem. He goes out there and all of a sudden you
have your arm trying to catch up, and you're all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre added that Clemens is No. 3 in the rotation by design.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great as a manager when you have those marquee
pitchers,'' he said. ``Clemens could have pitched No. 1. But again,
I'm big on experience, and David Cone has done so well in the
postseason pitching in the middle of the rotation. Having the two
guys who have the most experience is a big plus for us. You can't
get caught up in all the distractions. What if you don't? What if
you can't? You've got to think in terms of what you're going to do
and not what you can't do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
