<SLUG> BC-TAX-LOTTERY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EVEN FOR LOTTERY WINNERS, DEATH AND TAXES UNAVOIDABLE
 &HT;    By JERRY MOSKAL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Life for Gladys J. Cook was a gamble that finally
paid off big _ really, really big. On July 8, 1995, Cook and and
her sister-in-law Myrtle N. Newby won the Texas Lottery, sharing a
$17 million jackpot to be paid over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the elderly Cleburne, Texas, women did not have much time to
enjoy their multimillionaire status. Cook died Nov. 6, 1995, less
than six months after picking the winning numbers, and Newby died
last year.
</P>
<P>
   And now Cook's winnings are the target of an Internal Revenue
Service claim seeing an additional $1.04 million in federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS took aim at a partnership Cook and Newby formed to pool
their winnings and losses from their gambling ventures. Instead of
the $1.52 million that MG Partners Ltd. had said Cook's half-share
was worth, the IRS valued it at $3.22 million if borrowed against
or sold.
</P>
<P>
   But the estate is fighting back. It filed a petition asking the
U.S. Tax Court here to overturn the IRS ruling of deficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The petition and Walker Arenson, an Austin tax attorney for the
estate, contended that the IRS valuation was flawed because anyone
buying the estate's share of the remaining winnings would confront
a huge IRS tax bill as well.
</P>
<P>
   Arenson said borrowing against Cook's share was equally
unrealistic, because a lender would probably demand double-digit
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't sell something, then it's not worth what they
claim,'' Arenson said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that in a similar case involving a winner of the
California Lottery, a judge ruled against the IRS. Arenson said he
anticipates similar results in the Cook estate's case.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Thursday, Arenson blamed the IRS tax
assaults for the downturn in lottery revenues realized by the
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people see the big winner in the lottery as the
Internal Revenue Service,'' he said. ``I think that's the reason
the lotteries are falling off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRS sees a bunch of money in these cases and is taking the
easy way out,'' Arenson said. ``If the IRS was successful, 75
percent of all lottery prize money would go to the IRS in taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   While Arenson said he did not represent Newby's estate, he
expected that the IRS would also try to collect additional taxes
from it.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS issued its notice of deficiency June 25, and has 60 days
to respond to the estate's Sept. 21 petition. If the IRS and estate
fail to negotiate a settlement, the case could go to trial before a
tax court judge.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
