<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON OF PLENTY IN THE NORTH COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURG, N.H. _ Reasons for heading north in the fall are not
hard to list. Just string together ``fish,'' ``mountains,''
``leaves,'' ``air,'' ``rivers,'' ``moose'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   In this northern corner of New Hampshire, just below the Quebec
border, all these items come together to make autumn one of the
best seasons to head for New England's high country. We take them
one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The big season in landlocked salmon came to a statutorial end
Thursday. Month's end also closes out lake fishing in the state,
but not so river and stream fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Also, fishing such ponds as Round Pond and Back Lake (which
qualifies as a pond) narrows the focus a good deal, though if you
hook a salmon in the Connecticut River it must be released.
</P>
<P>
   The trout fishing in the streams, though, is fair game and there
is plenty of river, especially the inlet at First Connecticut Lake
and Second Lake _ both accessed easily from Route 3, which runs
along the west shore. Back Lake lies to the south, with the same
highway running along the east shore. Round Pond is an off-road
trek on Route 3 just after the French Wildlife Refuge.
</P>
<P>
   This hilly country makes for terrific hiking, largely because
it's so far off the well-worn trails of the White Mountains. And
while the trails through Connecticut Lakes State Forest are not the
highly groomed pathways maintained by the AMC on and around Mount
Washington, they are nevertheless challenging in this hill country,
with treks up Covell Mountain out of Brundege Forest _ across Route
3 from First Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Foliage was no doubt damaged by the remains of Hurricane Floyd
as it stalled in this country for nearly a day with high winds and
heavy rain. But if the foliage is off-peak, the walking and
streamside fishing remain among the best escapes, especially in
early fall before snowshoes become a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire's way north is also a pleasant drive this time of
year, when the roads are free of summer tourists. Travel Route 93
through the White Mountain National Forest, then pick up Route 3 at
Franconia Notch and drive up to Lancaster, where the road picks up
the Connecticut River and stays alongside up to Colebrook.
</P>
<P>
   This is a land of green hills, thick forests, and bright water _
some of the prettiest land in the north even if it lacks the
dramatic heights of the White Mountains. And for moose, the
watchword _ as motorists see often on oversize yellow traffic signs
_ is watch out for the huge brutes. Collisions are numerous. On my
visit this fall, I had driven no more than a quarter-mile past the
warning sign when I saw my first (of many) moose. It was a
youngster about 7 feet tall, shambling along the left lane of Route
3.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for moose,'' says fishing guide Leon St.
Onge, ``you won't have to look too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, according to Fish and Game spokesman Mark Latti, even
though the season for trout and salmon closed, there are enough
special regulations to keep the stream and lake fishing going at
least through mid-October, in some cases longer.
</P>
<P>
   The late-summer storms did a number, as many of the streams
upcountry rose and began to churn so wildly that the water became
discolored and the stream beds scoured so that holding fish were
displaced.
</P>
<P>
   But the fishing is returning to the western Maine hills around
the Rangeley lakes district, and particularly the Kennebago River,
where ``The Screen'' outlets Rangeley Lake into the Rangeley River.
</P>
<P>
   Here, anglers are still talking about one of the best salmon
seasons in recent memory, and the river and upper dam will remain
open for catch-and-release fly fishing only through October. Lake
fishing is generally closed here.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the hiking in the region is truly of the back
country variety as wilderness prevails between Rangeley and the
Canadian border. The Appalachian Trail comes through the Rangeley
region on its last 40 miles to its terminus on Katahdin, Maine's
mile-high mountain in Baxter State Park.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, for serious hikers, early fall is prime time for
Katahdin, best approached this time of year along the Hunt Trail.
Plan on a full day's hike and pack warm clothes for the possible
change in climate at the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the region, check out the South Branch of the
Dead River, which runs between Rangeley and Stratton. The trout
fishing along this stretch is terrific in the pools, and about half
the length of the river, between Saddleback Lake and Flagstaff
Lake, is easily accessible from Route 16.
</P>
<P>
   Jumbo landlocked salmon are still fishable in the Crooked River,
which we also visited last spring when the fishing season was off
at a roar as the warm weather hit in April. Since then, locals
around East Sebago say fish to 10 pounds are possible in the next
two weeks. The special regulation closes the Crooked Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the Sebago area, where there are some huge togue in the
lake, though landlock season has closed, there is a special
regulation season open until Nov. 30. Anglers may fish the lake at
Sebago Station with barbless hooks, fly only, catch and release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
