<HEADLINE>
NOT MUCH TO TALK ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 11-1 rout of the Red Sox by the Indians wasn't much of a
workout for ESPN's Jon Miller and Joe Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland has so many weapons there's not too much you can
do,'' Morgan said after Cleveland's Harold Baines hit a three-run
homer in the bottom of third. ``A team's defense is constantly
under pressure with the Indians lineup. You have to play a perfect
game to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight game, a Red Sox miscue opened the door
for the opportunistic Indians. Wednesday night's Game 1 saw third
baseman John Valentin blow a routine throw to first. The next
batter, Jim Thome, cranked a two-run homer. At least Morgan was
kind. ``One play doesn't always win or lose a game,'' Morgan said
in Valentin's defense. ``The home run only tied the game. If they
had a little more hitting, who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's goat was Jose Offerman, whose failure to turn a
double play helped extend the third, giving Baines the chance to
boost Cleveland's lead to 6-1 and knock Saberhagen out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Offerman makes that play, Saberhagen would have been
pitching from a windup as opposed to a stretch,'' Morgan said.
``The Indians always take advantage of every little mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN reporter Rick Sutcliffe sensed Saberhagen's demise earlier
in the third. ``Saberhagen's day is almost over,'' Sutcliffe said,
explaining that he needed 14 pitches to get two outs and required a
total of 37 in the third before finally being pulled.
</P>
<P>
   Miller had the line of the day after John Wasdin came in out of
the bullpen. ``He is coming in one pitch too late,'' Miller said.
``Saberhagen had one of those hellacious innings.''
</P>
<P>
   The good thing about both Miller and Morgan is that they made
their points without making it personal or being nasty. They both
praised Saberhagen and the Red Sox for having remarkable seasons.
Morgan pointed out that Saberhagen hadn't walked a leadoff batter
in 111 innings. But Miller said after the first that Saberhagen had
thrown 20 pitches and that he only had ``85 or 90 in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller pointed out that Saberhagen had had three surgeries on
his shoulder, two on his elbow, and another one on his knee. ``The
only thing that hasn't happened to Saberhagen is that they haven't
named a surgery after him,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan heaped loads of praise on the Indians, particularly Kenny
Lofton, Omar Vizquel, and Roberto Alomar. Morgan said the
acquisition of second baseman Alomar from Baltimore made the
Indians ``almost perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller added that Lofton, Vizquel, and Alomar _ at the top of
the Cleveland order _ are ``all fast, and all get on base all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan and Miller also spent time recapping Game 1 and Pedro
Martinez's injury. ESPN showed Martinez throughout the first three
innings, dressed in a wool cap, laughing and joking in the Red Sox
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Fox analyst Tim McCarver, who called Game 1, said in an
interview what everybody knows _ ``the Red Sox are a totally
different team without Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarver said Martinez should win both the Cy Young and MVP
awards. ``Everybody knows that Pedro is the most dominant pitcher
in the game and the most important person on the Red Sox team,''
McCarver said, pointing out that other teams, such as the Yankees
and Indians, have a number of solid replacements for their
starters. The Red Sox don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not closing the casket entirely,'' McCarver said before
Thursday's game. ``They've still got games to play. If Ramon
Martinez can give them six strong innings . . .''
</P>
<P>
   McCarver might be the last remaining optimist.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
