<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S MAKE PRIVATE EQUITY PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rich are different from us in so many ways. One is their
access to the world of private equity.
</P>
<P>
   The democratization of capital markets has come a long way,
advanced most forcefully by the mutual fund industry for decades
now. The more recent efforts by brokerages to chip away little
pieces of some initial public stock offerings for their individual
clients is hardly as impressive in practice, but still another step
in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Private equity remains one of the last corners of the investment
world virtually inaccessible to the average Joe or Jane. Leveraged
buyout firms like Thomas H. Lee Co. and scores of venture capital
firms go to institutions and very wealthy individuals when they
want to raise money for a new fund.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt that venture capital is the hot spot of the
equity world these days, funding start-ups that hope to be little
building blocks of the new information age. Some turn out to be
duds, but occasionally one become a public stock blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   This week we wrote about the upcoming IPO from Sycamore Networks
Inc. of Chelmsford, which has the potential to be another hot
telecommunications networking stock right out of the box. Lots of
people called or wrote in vain for tips to achieve the near
impossible: to get a piece of stock at the offering price that is
currently estimated to be $18 to $20 per share.
</P>
<P>
   We have no idea if that will really turn out to be a good deal
or not, but Sycamore's venture capital backers certainly secured
better terms. Existing shareholders, which include company insiders
and venture funds, paid an average of 83 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt private equity, especially venture capital, is
a relatively high-risk proposition. But when we see those
individual investors winning, we usually see very wealthy people
getting even richer.
</P>
<P>
   Good for them, but what about us?
</P>
<P>
   In the city of mutual funds, aren't there a few smart people who
can hurdle the problems (there are lots of them) and open some
private equity doors for the rest of us?
</P>
<P>
   There has been progress. So-called funds of funds, which invest
in several private equity pools, are available at brokerages and
trust departments with a $100,000 minimum ante in most cases.
Investors have to have a net worth of at least $1 million to
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue that a push to get into private equity is a kind
of foolish grab for more big returns in the twilight of a bullish
stock market. Another point of contention: that risk and lack of
liquidity make private equity unsuitable for most public
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   It's true private equity isn't for everyone. Money can be tied
up for years _ a big drawback _ and it's more complicated than your
average mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   Our response: So what? Just because private equity isn't for
everyone, why should smaller investors who know what they're buying
get boxed out completely?
</P>
<P>
   If pension funds dedicate small slices of their portfolios to
venture capital, why is it inappropriate in moderation for a 401(k)
plan of someone who will work for another 10 or 20 years?
</P>
<P>
   Seligman Advisors, best known for its technology mutual funds,
raised $580 million in August for a new closed-end fund that comes
closest to the point.
</P>
<P>
   The Seligman New Technologies fund plans to invest up to 35
percent of its money in later-stage venture capital deals. Unlike
most closed-end funds, its shares don't trade on any exchange but
investors can redeem up to 5 percent of their shares per quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, which was sold through brokers, required just a
$10,000 minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous appetite for these types of
investments,'' said Steve Hodgdon, president of Seligman Advisors.
``The big issue for us is just capacity'' to invest the money. The
fund's list of shareholders includes lots of investors who put up
just $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgdon said Seligman will consider creating another fund, but
not before the original vehicle puts more of its money to work in
venture capital investments.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam Investments in Boston teamed up with Thomas Lee this
summer to jointly prepare private equity investments for
institutions and wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Maxwell, a Putnam managing director who oversees his
company's relationship with Lee, isn't predicting specific products
for less-than-wealthy investors.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't rule them out either, and emphasized that Putnam's
relationship with brokers who could screen customers for private
equity suitability would be essential.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments has made a fortune for itself with its own
in-house venture capital firm. Why can't it find a way to manage a
little venture money for its customers, too?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
