u f BC-ATL-FASHION-RED     10-08 0228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-FASHION-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hot Hues from Burgundy to scarlet are guaanteed to stop traffic
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fashion-conscious people are seeing red this fall, and it's not
necessarily in their bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Red is in. Big time. Whether it's garments or accessories, the
color has become so huge that it's quickly replacing black as the
``must-have'' in the wardrobe department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a millennium thing,'' says Anita Finkelstein,
regional fashion stylist for Women's Wear Daily in Atlanta. ``All
of a sudden, it's a brave new world. Everybody's in this very
celebratory mood, and all this black has gotten way too
depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   People have always worn red, particularly for holidays, intimate
occasions and on sweetheart's day. But these days, red is cool
anywhere, anytime.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many hues to choose from, including scarlet, brick
and burgundy, that almost anyone can wear it without looking like a
vixen. Men can pull the look off too, especially with deeper tones
in blazers and shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm selling it a lot as a layering piece,'' says Shannon
Marler, owner of Sage Clothing Co. in Dunwoody, Georgia. ``And
we're selling a lot of the burgundy because it's something
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
