<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0767 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-KOCH-FAMILY-COX     10-08 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOCH-FAMILY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: W/KOCH-TRIAL
 &HT;    Family business ranks high on 'Forbes' 500
 &HT;    By Fred Cohen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULSA _ Based in Wichita, Kan., Koch Industries is the
second-largest privately held company in the United States, after
Cargill. According to a December article in Forbes magazine, it is
a $35 billion business with estimated profits of $700 million. The
company ranks 18th on the Forbes 500, right behind Chevron, Procter
&AMP; Gamble and DuPont.
</P>
<P>
   The company's main business is oil and gas. It has refineries in
Corpus Christi, Texas, and near St. Paul, Minn., and is among the
world's largest oil traders. It is also produces chemicals, asphalt
and building materials. Koch Beef Co has 12,000 head of cattle on
450,000 acres. Last year Koch Industries bought Purina Mills Inc.,
which had $1.2 billion in sales of animal feed.
</P>
<P>
   Koch Industries employs 16,000 people worldwide and practices a
philosophy it calls Market Based Management.In contrast to
traditional military style command-and-control management, this
system encourages employees to think like business owners _ with
bonuses that can reach seven figures, according to Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes article said all voting stock in the company is held
by two of Fred Koch's four sons _ Charles of Wichita, the company's
chairman and CEO, and David of Palm Beach, its executive vice
president _ and by Houston investor E. Pierce Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Koch Industries was founded by Fred C. Koch, who, in the 1920s,
invented a process for increasing the amount of gasoline that could
be extracted from crude oil. Refiners with competing technologies
filed 40 suits against him alleging patent infringement. Although
he won them all, he could not do business in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He went to the Soviet Union, where he helped modernize 15
refineries _ and witnessed Stalin's purges, in which several
Russians he had worked with were killed.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the United States a staunch anti-communist and
became a founding member of the John Birch Society. He founded the
Rock Island Oil and Refining Co. in 1940 and turned control of the
company over to his son Charles in 1961. After he died in 1967,
Charles renamed the company Koch Industries.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
