   &UR; NATIONAL (category ``a'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-DANCE-BAND (Miami) _ Hostilities are at a peak once again
here with the announcement that Los Van Van, Cuba's most popular
dance band and one that has performed all over the United States,
but never in Miami, is coming to town. The band is scheduled to
play the Miami Arena on Saturday night in what promises to be a
test for both freedom of expression in this city and the shifting
views within Cuban Miami itself. 1,400 words. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-FREEWAY (Los Angeles) _ At one level, the latest fight
over a South Pasadena freeway is a classic, parochial conflict,
pitting one community against another. But in a broader sense, the
battle of Highway 710 is an example of the biggest question
bedeviling a region that is again expanding explosively after a
deep recession: How to accommodate growth in Southern California
without destroying the very qualities of life that drew masses of
Americans here in the first place. 1,600 words. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FIDDLE-REVIVAL (Nicut, West Va.) _ Many young people
traditionally must leave this state to find promising careers,
rarely mastering and passing on the Appalachian folk ways of their
elders. But lately, young people searching out uncommercialized,
authentic old music have been showing up on Heritage Center
scholarships at the cabin doors of the aging masters learning how
to fiddle. 1,100 words. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-SWEENEY (undated) _ The head of the AFL-CIO, John Sweeney,
is leading a revival of organized labor in both the workplace and
in politics. 1,300 words. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-MEXICO-SCHOOLS (Albuquerque) _ The New Mexico Board of
Education votes to teach evolution in state schools, in contrast to
Kansas, which has deleted all mention of evolution in its
guidelines for teachers. 1,000 words. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FLOOD-AID (Newark, N.J.) _ Flood victims and lawmakers around
the Northeast are clamoring that they're not getting their fair
share of disaster aid. By Ronald Smothers.
</P>
