<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN11-CO     10-08 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Truth is ... you can't handle the
truth
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor ol' Pat Buchanan and Jesse Ventura. They let some truth
leak out of their lips. Boy! They're in trouble now.
</P>
<P>
   I say ``truth.'' It's the truth as they believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, in his new book, says America should have avoided war
with Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, in an interview with Playboy magazine, says religion is
a crutch for the weak.
</P>
<P>
   Here's good advice. Don't do a Playboy interview. It never turns
out well for the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Remember poor ol' Jimmy Carter admitting that he had lusted in
his heart? If they can pin down something prurient about Jimmy
Carter, the rest of us wouldn't stand a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I admire Buchanan and Ventura for saying what they
really think. More politicians should do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it might take a little prodding.
</P>
<P>
   Best deal would be whenever a candidate for president was
assigned Secret Service agents, he or she would have a polygraph
operator allocated as well.
</P>
<P>
   How recent history could have been changed by truth in
campaigning:
</P>
<P>
   _ Had Clinton told the truth about his philandering.
</P>
<P>
   _ Had Bush told the truth about his opinion on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Had Reagan told the truth about what he knew of the
Iran-Contra affair. (Reagan has forgotten more about Iran-Contra
than we'll ever know.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Had Carter told the truth when he said he'd never lie to us.
</P>
<P>
   _ Had Ford told the truth that he had trouble distinguishing up
from down.
</P>
<P>
   _ Had Nixon ... oh, well. The list is endless.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine if voters could know the truth of George W. Bush's
alleged cocaine use in his youth, or Al Gore's use of Buddhist
campaign contributions during the current administration.
</P>
<P>
   Who do you think we'd feel better about: Bush, Gore, Buchanan or
Ventura?
</P>
<P>
   The Scriptures tell you that ye shall know the truth and the
truth shall set you free. I don't argue with the Scriptures.
</P>
<P>
   But my personal observation is that if people know the truth
about you, it can set your britches ablaze _ i.e., ``Liar, liar,
pants on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   I remember when the Civil Rights Act of 1964 passed Congress,
Time magazine quoted an unnamed politician as saying, ``If we could
have turned out the lights and voted, it never would have passed.''
</P>
<P>
   I know for a fact that the worst trouble you can get into
running a newspaper is to let a little truth slip in by accident.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to suggest that newspapers lie.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly what they do is just quote other people.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is _ which is as good an opening for a lie as there is
_ the public doesn't want to know the truth.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't want to know about Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't want to know about Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't want to know about Iran-Contra.
</P>
<P>
   The list is endless, and growing.
</P>
<P>
   The truth? You can't handle the truth.
</P>
<P>
   That's a quote from a Jack Nicholson movie. It may not be
Scripture, but it's the gospel truth.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
