<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0802 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-KOCH-TULSA09-COX     10-08 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOCH-TULSA09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: With KOCH-FAMILY
 &HT;    Tulsa's middle name is 'oil'
 &HT;    By Fred Cohen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULSA, Okla. _ From not long after oil was struck here in 1901
through the first half of the century, Tulsa was the center of one
of the world's leading oilproducing regions. The city soon became
known as the ``Oil Capital of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Although oil production in Oklahoma has slowed and the industry
is just now recovering from its collapse in 1985 _ when the price
of a barrel plummeted from $25 to $9 in a single day _ Tulsa still
considers itself the world's oil capital. To find out why, all you
have to do is pick up the Greater Tulsa phone book _ specifically,
the Yellow Pages.
</P>
<P>
   They're like Yellow Pages everywhere until you get to the letter
``O.'' Then, right after Office Supplies, the listings of
oil-related businesses begin _ hundreds of them.
</P>
<P>
   No fewer than 154 businesses are engaged in Oil &AMP; Gas
Exploration and Development. After that, the oil business gets
pretty compartmentalized.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to meet Tulsans' oil drilling-related needs are businesses
in the straightforward category of Oil Welling Drilling (nine) and
such specialties as Oil Well Directional Drilling (one), Oil Well
Casing Pulling (one) and Oil Well Drilling Mud &AMP; Additives (eight).
</P>
<P>
   In the realm of equipment, there are companies in categories for
Oil Field Equipment (66), Oil Field Pumping Equipment (four), Oil
Well Logging &AMP; Perforating Equipment (one) and, for roustabouts who
can't make a commitment, Oil Field Equipment Rentals (two).
</P>
<P>
   There are even three companies that provide Oil Well Fishing
Tools. That's for when your drill bit falls off and you have to
fish it out of the well bore.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever been to Oklahoma, you've seen lonely oil rigs out
on the plain pumping away without apparent human intervention.
Looks easy, right? Get yourself a lease, drill a well, and stuff
your savings account at the Oil Capital Federal Credit Union with
royalty checks.
</P>
<P>
   The Greater Tulsa Yellow Pages indicates it's not so simple. If
oil wells were low maintenance, would there be 67 businesses under
the category of Oil Field Services?
</P>
<P>
   Their names suggest some of the services needed in the oil
fields: American Tank Cleaning Co., Protective Coating and
Sandblasting Co., Cherokee Hose &AMP; Supply, Hudgins Co. Pipe Testing.
Some of the suggestions are a bitoblique: J B Hot Oil &AMP; Steam Co.,
Blue Star Acid Service, International Blenders Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The names of tank-truck companies indicate they're often needed
urgently; if Quickdraw Tank Truck Service can't get there fast
enough, try Lightning Tank Trucks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to drill in the Tulsa area, expect lots of
competition _ the Yellow Pages lists 71 Oil Producers. Luckily, 27
Oil Marketers are there to sell the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of a disaster, call one of the two businesses
listed under Oil Spill Clean-Up &AMP; Control.
</P>
<P>
   When your well runs dry, don't leave the well bore open; a child
could fall in. Call the oil-well undertaker listed under Oil Well
Cementing to eliminate the safety hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
