<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT-METRO _ CAIRO, Egypt _ Above ground, Cairo is one of the
noisiest, most polluted and congested cities in the world. Under
ground, the gleeming, air-conditioned, trains of Africa's only
subway offer efficient comfort. The newest line opened this summer
and tunnels under the Nile. Common Egyptians, now regular riders of
the Metro, consider the $7 billion marvel comparable to the
pyramids. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tuesday, Oct. 5 in (i) International and (t) Travel
categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FUNDRAISING _ MEXICO CITY _ It makes Bill Clinton's
alleged irregular campaign donations look tame. In Mexico, corrupt
bankers have been accused of funneling millions of dollars into
political campaigns here. And despite prohibitions, candidates are
still accused of taking illicit donations, breaking spending rules
and usurping public funds to buy votes. The race to choose Mexico's
next president _ supposedly the most democratic election yet here _
will test whether electoral reforms can prevent wholesale political
scams from being repeated in this country. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday, Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY _ DES MOINES _ Bill Bradley, who was a consistent critic
of farm subsidies as a senator, unveils his agricultural program in
Iowa, where subsidies are a potent issue. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TREATY-EXPLAIN _ WASHINGTON _ An explanation of how the nuclear
test ban treaty would work and how it would be verified. (Cox News
Service).
</P>
