<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0811 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     10-08 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER'S SUNDAY-SCHOOL LESSONS, BOOK DRAW FROM HIS LIFE'S WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former President Jimmy Carter has been teaching Sunday school
since he was 18. He even taught in Washington, D.C., when he was
president. And he's still at it.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, Carter prepares a lesson, using his Bible and
Scripture references recommended by his denomination. Then he goes
to his home church in Plains, Ga., to teach a Sunday class for
adults.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, it is a typical Sunday-school class.
</P>
<P>
   But when he arrives at the Maranatha Baptist Church, about 200
people are usually waiting to hear him teach. The Secret Service is
there as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some come out of curiosity about seeing a politician teaching
the Holy Scriptures,'' Carter said last week in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   His class attendees outnumber church members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only have about 35 or 40 families in our little church in
Plains,'' he said. ``But our visitors come from everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday, 28 nations were represented in his class.
``We have Mormons, Quakers, Jews, Catholics and also Protestants
and nonbelievers,'' he said. ``I love discussing the different
perspectives we have on the Scriptures.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's Sunday school lessons, in shortened form, have become a
bestselling book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took 52 of those lessons that seemed most interesting and
pertinent _ some humorous and some serious _ and put them in a
book,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   The book ``Sources of Strength: Meditations on Scripture for a
Living Faith'' has been on ``The New York Times'' bestseller list
and was recently released in a $14 paperback by Times Books.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons include some of Carter's recollections about his
personal experiences as president and as a worldwide peacemaker in
his role as founder of the Carter Center in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In the book's preface, Carter picks up on the title, ``I have
thoroughly enjoyed recapitulating the lessons I've taught over the
years. ... I hope they will be for you, as they have been for me,
sources of strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Some chapters in the book indicate the content: ``Who Among Us
Is Superior''; ``The Art of Forgiving''; ``Woman and Man Equal
Before God''; ``Are the Ten Commandments Enough?''; ``The Laughing
Jesus''; ``We Underestimate Ourselves and Others''; and ``Take a
Chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter is one of our most honored ex-presidents.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Rosalynn, each recently received the
Presidential Medal of Freedom, the nation's highest civilian honor.
</P>
<P>
   His faith is deeply integrated into his everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I was a little child, I have been a believer,'' he said.
``It's like breathing to me. It is as much a part of me as being a
Georgian, or a Southerner or an American. For me, religion is
pre-eminent.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean he doesn't have problems. He sometimes
overlooks God, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm struggling with some issues, I frequently forget
about my faith,'' he said. ``I have to realize I'm not
all-powerful. I do need help. I need to re-examine the priorities
in my own life.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said having faith means individuals can reinvent
themselves for the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant learning process,'' he said. ``Constant
self-education. With God, we can become more gentle and we can have
a more exciting, more adventurous and gratifying existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Such candor and clarity about deep spiritual matters is one of
the reasons, I'm sure, that people from across the world show up to
sit at Carter's feet on Sunday mornings to hear him speak.
</P>
<P>
   All of us are looking for some answers. And this man of faith,
very humble in his own way, seems to be on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0812 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     10-08 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHERWOMAN'S GIFT WAS WORTH MORE THAN MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The deadline for this column was well past when I opened up the
paper last week and read that Oseola McCarty had died.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't the kind of news you want to read with your morning
coffee, but McCarty's death was especially hard to avoid. It made
the front page.
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, McCarty is the Mississippi washerwoman
who gave away her life's savings _ $150,000 _ to the University of
Southern Mississippi, my alma mater, so others wouldn't have to
work as hard as she did.
</P>
<P>
   And so, just as I was moved by her story four years ago, I was
moved by her passing. The story said that she had been told she had
liver cancer just three weeks ago, about a year after she had
surgery for colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Had it not been for her gift, none of us might have heard of
McCarty or her selflessness, and certainly not in such a public
way. That is as much a tragedy, I think, as her death.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, people such as McCarty go through life
virtually unnoticed. I don't know whether that's good or bad. I'm
happy that in this case, we didn't have to find out.
</P>
<P>
   Reading about McCarty again, I was struck by the number of
people _ 600, the story said _ who had added some $330,000 to the
original scholarship fund; and the billion-dollar gift her giving
prompted Ted Turner to make to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   McCarty and Turner both gave generous gifts, but I couldn't help
but wonder which meant more in the sight of God. The one who gave
all she had, or the one who gave a billion from his
multibillion-dollar bank account.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, it occurred to me that the thing that made Oseola
McCarty different was not her gift. People all over this country
give of their time and money to institutions and causes.
</P>
<P>
   But while they give out of the abundance of their wallets,
McCarty gave out of the abundance of her heart, so that other
people's ``children won't have to work so hard like I did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bible promises us three score and 10 years of life. At 91,
McCarty lived considerably longer. I suspect that she lived well,
too, realizing that it is far better to store up treasure in heaven
than here on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   When she decided in the summer of 1995 to give away most of her
life's savings, McCarty said there was nothing in particular she
wanted to buy and no place she wanted to go.
</P>
<P>
   The things that we hold dear, that we spend our money on, were
of no significance to her. She must have understood that where
one's treasure is, there his heart will be also.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let me hasten to say that treasures are not all material.
In any position of privilege there is the danger that status and
power, for instance, become primary.
</P>
<P>
   T.S. Eliot would know what I'm talking about. In the play
``Murder in the Cathedral,'' he wrote: ``They who serve the greater
cause have the danger of the cause serving them.''
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, a company will lay off hundreds of workers to
protect one executive salary; and another company will employ tens
of thousands of children, some as young as 4, to work in
exhausting, and even hazardous, conditions just to save a buck.
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder how many people took advantage of McCarty's
washing and ironing skills, withholding what her work was really
worth.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder Jesus said, ``It is easier for a camel to go
through the eye of a needle than for a rich man to enter the
kingdom of God?''
</P>
<P>
   McCarty's gift brought her worldwide attention and more than 300
awards. She gave us so much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of talk about self-esteem these days,'' she was
quoted as saying once. ``It seems pretty basic to me. If you want
to feel proud of yourself, you've got to do things you can be proud
of.''
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
