<HEADLINE>
TEXANS SHOULD EXERT SOME PRIVACY PRESSURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congressional representatives had commendable motives when they
passed the Driver's Privacy Protection Act as part of the Omnibus
Crime Control Act of 1994. They were trying to keep your vital
statistics out of the hands of people who may have less than
honorable intentions for their use.
</P>
<P>
   The federal legislation directs states to block the release of
personal information contained in state motor vehicle records. The
privacy concern was sparked by the 1989 murder of TV actress
Rebecca Schaeffer, whose stalker/slayer found her California
address by using motor vehicle records.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists typically must provide a litany of details about
themselves before they can obtain a driver's license: name,
address, telephone number, Social Security number (you can try to
opt out of giving that information in Texas, but expect a wrestling
match), height, eye color, thumbprints and photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of some of this information _ by most state laws, only
names, addresses, birth dates and driver's identification numbers _
to individuals and marketing firms means real money, particularly
in heavily populated states. According to the U.S. Department of
Justice, New York's motor vehicle department raked in $17 million
in one year by selling driver records.
</P>
<P>
   The federal act has run into legal problems, however, and is the
focus of a Supreme Court challenge this fall. South Carolina
officials are contending that Congress violated the 10th Amendment
of the U.S. Constitution by passing a law that forces states to run
a federal program.
</P>
<P>
   The berobed justices will decide if Congress overstepped its
bounds in 1994 by telling sovereign states what they can and cannot
do with state-controlled records. In the meantime, the Texas
Legislature passed a statute in 1997 to give Texans more control
over who has access to personal information given to state
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Although no overt constitutional problems have arisen from the
state program, it has run into its own difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Texans, at the time they get or renew a driver's license or
vehicle registration, may request that their personal information
not be sold to marketing firms that buy lists from state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The law applies to information collection by the state
departments of Transportation and Public Safety. The Department of
Parks and Wildlife, which collects similar information for boat
registrations and hunting and fishing licenses, wasn't included in
the law but has adopted the restrictions anyway.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report last month in ``The Wall Street Journal,''
the Texas Department of Transportation sells its lists without
removing the names of people who have opted out. The department
just makes a notation on the names whose owners have requested
deletion and leaves it up to the marketing firms and list buyers
not to use them.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Public Safety and the folks at Parks and
Wildlife have found ways to eliminate the names of people not
wishing their information to be sold. But of at the state's
Transportation Department contend that removing the names would
necessitate keeping two separate databases and that this is a less
than ideal or efficient way of operating.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by the ``Journal'' reporter why some agencies can
accomplish this but they cannot, transportation officials declined
to explain, saying only that the department is complying with the
law.
</P>
<P>
   The law, as amended by the Texas Legislature in 1997, requires
that ``persons are provided an opportunity, in a clear and
conspicuous manner, to opt out and prohibit the use'' of their
information. It does not specify how each agency will carry out
that provision.
</P>
<P>
   According to a spokesman for the Transportation Department, it
is up to the companies that buy the lists to police themselves to
make sure they don't use names that are flagged for nondisclosure.
If a marketing company does use such names, it would be in
violation of its contract with the state and risk the ability to
buy weekly updates or future lists.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that, according to the ``Journal,'' the
Transportation Department has never canceled a buyer's contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Transportation is perpetrating a sham on the
people of Texas every time someone checks off the box asking that
personal information not be released.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative pressure is needed on this agency to do what elected
officials promised the people of Texas in 1997: protect their
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
