<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ALI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHAMP'S DAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERONA, N.Y. _ Razor Ruddock has been around boxing long enough
to know that just because a marquee says you're the main event
doesn't mean you're ``The Main Event.'' That is why he showed up
more than a half-hour late for his press conference Thursday at the
Turning Stone Casino knowing no one would care a bit, if they even
noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologize for being late but I see you had someone to
entertain you,'' Ruddock said, nodding to a pretty young girl in
the corner. ``You're not here for me anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   A room packed with more than a dozen photographers and an equal
number of TV cameras from as far away as Europe made that clear the
moment the pretty young girl strode into the room. As Laila Ali
sauntered through the door with the regal carriage of Zena the
Warrior Princess, flashbulbs exploded.
</P>
<P>
   The flashes persisted until long after common sense would argue
they had all the shots they needed. They persisted even after she
had finally settled down on the dais to await the inevitable
questions she knew were coming at her.
</P>
<P>
   When the 21-year-old daughter of Muhammad Ali began to speak, it
was clear no one else was in the room. Even though it was jammed
with bodies, no one else mattered now that she'd arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Same as it was for her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people are wondering, so many people have questions,''
she said. ``But I wouldn't be up here talking all this mess if I
was going to go in the ring and do nothing. I'm the one you all
gonna watch. I'm the one you all gonna follow. I'm the one.''
</P>
<P>
   She may well be the one, but somehow the words sounded hollow.
Just as her skill in the boxing ring she enters for the first time
will be measured against that of her father, so too will her words.
</P>
<P>
   This is not fair when you are talking about the greatest boxer
in history and the biggest name in sports in our lifetime, but it
is no less fair than a rich kid from Los Angeles with no experience
stealing the thunder from a guy who twice fought for the
heavyweight title of the world. So what's fair and what isn't fair
isn't what this is all about, as Laila Ali seems to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad never had this much attention on him when he was first
fighting,'' she said. ``There are so many expectations. There is so
much pressure on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised. I grew up around this. I saw it coming
before anyone else did. My father's Muhammad Ali, so at this point
I don't feel people are just here for me. That's not going to
happen until I do something. I had to decide if I wanted to deal
with that. I'm here dealing with it.''
</P>
<P>
   What she's dealing with is prurient interest far out of
proportion to her accomplishments in a boxing ring, because until
now Laila Ali has none. Until she steps into a ring jammed into a
casino ballroom and faces a pudgy challenger from Michigan City,
Ind., named April Fowler, Laila Ali will be nothing more than a
sideshow, a carnival act trading upon the reputation of boxing's
greatest name the way Buffalo Bill Cody traded on his own
reputation at corny Wild West shows long after the West had been
won.
</P>
<P>
   The young Ali knows this, just as she knows the stunning good
looks she inherited from Ali and his third ex-wife, the beautiful
model Veronica Porsche, are all part of the attraction. Although
this fight is about her, the crowd she will attract is more about
her father, the greatest boxer who ever lived in the eyes of most
who ever saw him fight.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is more about her than it is about Ruddock, who will box
a familiar journeyman named Jose Ribalta in an attempt to keep his
search for a world title fight going on a night when few will
notice the outcome. Of that much Ruddock was not the only one who
was sure. So, too, was the quiet waitress from Indiana, fodder for
a new Ali.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a waitress at Ye Olde Benny's,'' said Fowler, who has lost
her only professional fight but won three Tough Person (is that a
gender?) contests before deciding to become a true prize fighter.
``I like my job as a waitress better than boxing, but the
pressure's not on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to prove. I'm not getting into the ring with
her father. I'm getting in the ring with her. She's just a name to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. She's just a name to everybody, which is why the room
was jammed Thursday and why it will be overflowing. Not because
Laila Ali can fight, because no one knows if she can or can't,
including herself.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the continuing story of Razor Ruddock's comeback either
and certainly not for the second professional fight of April
Fowler's career.
</P>
<P>
   No, the room will be jammed to see if a 5-foot-10-inch,
168-pound rich girl has the right stuff. The stuff that made her
father someone who not only could call himself ``The Greatest'' but
could back it up. The stuff to be called Ali in a boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   Is she the exception to boxing's rule that you don't discover
boxers in Beverly Hills or is she just another Hollywood fiction
weaved out of thin air and hype?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she has a great amount of courage and character to do
this,'' said Mike Acri, a small-time promoter from Eire, Pa., who
is handling her career for now. ``She's going into the ring with
big expectations in the shadow of the greatest fighter who ever
boxed. She could be doing a ton of other things. She already owns
her own business. But she's here.''
</P>
<P>
   She is, and because she is, so are some of the biggest
newspapers and television networks in America, although the fight
will not be televised live. So, too, are representatives from
London's tabloids and Germany's national TV network.
</P>
<P>
   Here not because she's a kid who grew up well-to-do in Hancock
Park, went astray for a while, and got busted for shoplifting and
spent three months in juvenile hall, owns her own nail salon and
decided a year ago to try her hands at boxing. No one is here to
tell that story.
</P>
<P>
   They are here for a simpler reason and a bigger story. They are
here to see how far the apple falls from the tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to knock somebody out!'' Ali shouted at one point,
her eyes glowering before she smiles the kind of smile that comes
from $15,000 worth of dental work as a teenager. ``My friends feel
this is right down my alley. I think I'll be a great boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not trying to be like my father. I'm just at the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but of what? Of a boxing career? Or, as some including her
mother have theorized, at the beginning stage of some long walk to
find the father who left her when she was 8?
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Porsche will there to support her daughter and rumor is
her father may come in by private jet. Both have made clear they
are against this idea, yet they support it in the way parents of
21-year-olds must. Because they have no other choice.
</P>
<P>
   Laila Ali understands that too, understands that while she is
fighting for herself others are involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I want to do something I just do it,'' she said. ``I want
to do this. I started this to stay fit but I liked it. I feel at
home in the ring. I don't care what anyone else has to say about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dad has never said he's against it but he's made it known.
I think he's pleased I'm an independent thinker, but if he could
program my brain not to be a fighter I think he would.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never told me flat out not to box, but like any father he
doesn't want his daughter to get hurt. He brought up all the
negative things so you get the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, Ali did more than that. While his daughter and her
trainer/boyfriend, cruiserweight Johnny McClain, were visiting him
on his farm in Michigan, he went over to watch her train. As she
moved, he slowly began to move as well, his body a shadow of what
it had been before boxing and Parkinson's syndrome slowed it to a
crawl.
</P>
<P>
   The 57-year-old Ali offered to spar with his daughter. She
agreed, assuming she knew what was coming. She did not, which was
her father's point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel I could hit him that hard and he ended up
popping me,'' she recalled. ``It sort of surprised me.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Laila Ali's first surprise in boxing. If she stays for
long, it won't be her last.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
