<HEADLINE>
NEW WELD PLOT POSES A MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
BIG UGLY 
By William F. Weld 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, 232 pp., $23. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Weld's at it again. No, not running for office, but writing
novels. His second Terry Mullally suspense novel, ``Big Ugly,'' is
out. (The first one concerning the up-from-poverty Irish
prosecutor-turned-pol, ``Mackerel By Moonlight,'' was published
last fall.)
</P>
<P>
   It's set in the swirling cutthroat world of contemporary
presidential politics, so naturally, the horse-race question comes
immediately to mind: Is it a winner? But since we speak of Weld the
writer of prose fiction, and not the political office-holder or
-seeker, the outcome can't be so readily calibrated.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with well-earned praise, because the former
Massachusetts governor is manifestly a very able writer: a slick
creator of character; author of brisk, crisp dialogue; and imaginer
of fully entertaining, and often flavorfully eccentric, vignettes.
Mullally is a colorfully faceted protagonist and as nicely
ambiguous a centerpiece as you tend to find in good genre fiction.
In this book, the one-time Democratic district attorney in
Massachusetts has scrapped his way to the US Senate and now is
savoring the fearful heights of power. As the waggish Weld-Mullally
observes in one of the book's pithier gibes, ``The difference from
regular roller coasters is, in Washington at least somebody gets
thrown to their death on every ride.'' Mullally is bright,
charming, and deeply tarnished, likable as much for his private,
deprecating self-doubt and humanizing guilt as for his silvery
sociability.
</P>
<P>
   Two other major players Weld brings vividly to life in ``Big
Ugly'' are Happy Gilliam and Vivian Anson, older, smoother
Democratic senators vying for the 2000 presidential nomination and
for freshman Mullally's support. Gilliam is literally outsize, a
giant philandering Texan as crude and congenial as Lyndon Johnson,
but less than half as smart and twice as corruptible. His homespun
speech _ ``prass spoats'' for price supports _ reveals Weld's sharp
ear for dialect.
</P>
<P>
   Anson is an even nicer piece of work, a populist West Virginian
Weld richly appoints with endearing Southern idiosyncracies. The
scenes involving Mullally and his wife's visit to Anson's home in
Big Ugly, W. Va., are the best in the book, sharply observant of
the snake-infested natural world, and often hilarious. The most
outrageous one concerns another West Virginian, a gifted,
hippie-haired Washington-lawyer friend of Anson who is also a
park-bench wino. Hung over after a night of revelry, he addresses a
goofy Sunday sermon to Anson's muddy hogs while tossing them slop.
</P>
<P>
   This is what keeps us reading: the full-bodied humor, snappy
chatter, curious specimens.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   The real mystery here is the whereabouts of a plot. It wouldn't
be accurate to say that Weld is troublingly digressive _ because
there just isn't any discernible narrative path from which to
wander. Yes, Mullally has a deeply stained past that might whiplash
his life and career, and present corruption in high places also
threatens to topple him (and the vice president). But Weld treats
these actions, which should be throttling the story forward, as
minor props, as, at best, bright swatches of local color.
</P>
<P>
   Especially in his truncated second term as governor, Weld was
accused of losing interest in the job, of lacking focus and
commitment. It's perhaps glib to say, but true nonetheless, that
his second book betrays a similar lack of close attention and
follow-through. Otherwise, it would surely tell a story instead of
merely, if very inventively, creating intriguing political scenery
and spicing it with his rogues.
</P>
<P>
   This is all too bad, because if ``Big Ugly'' worked better as a
novel, it might also have been a more convincing riff on the
intoxication of political power and its almost inescapable tendency
to corrupt. Light genre fiction can be, and often is, a splendid
vehicle for social ideas and political commentary, but the binding
contract the author makes with the reader is primarily to tell a
good story.
</P>
<P>
   Because ``Big Ugly'' doesn't, it can't be voted a winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
