<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBING HER PSYCHE WITHOUT POWER CHORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; From surface impressions, Melissa Etheridge enjoys a very
successful romance. She and life partner Julie Cypher (a
writer-director in Los Angeles) are sharing the upbringing of two
children and are regularly seen at high-powered entertainment
events, posing blissfully for photographers.
</P>
<P>
   So why does Etheridge's new album ``Breakdown'' have dark, moody
songs about love?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought people might think everything is fine and dandy, but
nothing is ever totally that way,'' says Etheridge. ``You have to
really work at a relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Released this week, the album is her first in nearly four years.
It's another high-quality effort from Etheridge, but doesn't revel
in the anthemic, Springsteen/Mellencamp-like rock songs for which
the Kansas native (and onetime Berklee College of Music student)
has been known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come from a simpler place, a smaller place, a more
vulnerable place,'' Etheridge says from her Los Angeles home. ``The
album was born from not being on the road or rocking with an
audience. It came from going inward and from raising children and
from soul-searching questions to myself of `What is life all
about?' and `What are my demons?' I didn't want to force the
rockers this time. The song `How Would I Know' was supposed to be
big and up-tempo, but it didn't end up that way. My management
said, `Where is the rocker?' And I said, `Well, you may not get one
this time.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to take it texturally one step farther than anything
we've done before, but I wanted the vocals to still be strong and
serious and real,'' says Etheridge, who coproduced the album with
her guitarist, John Shanks.
</P>
<P>
   There's the fascinating ballad ``Enough of Me'' (``I give you my
soul . . . I give you my skin and my Original Sin''), a song about
an unrequited romantic crush (``Angels Will Fall''), the touching
``Into the Dark'' (``There's a place we must go _ into the soul,
into the heart, into the dark''), and the laid-back,
mandolin-coated ``Truth of the Heart.'' There also are two
transfixing songs about her childhood, of which ``Mama I'm
Strange'' stands out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a direct sentiment of my childhood and my
adolescence,'' she says. ``I still don't feel I dress right or am
as fashionable as the next person. . . . As a child, I'd have
nightmares about waves coming over my house or of falling down
stairs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scarecrow'' (not the Mellencamp song by the same name) was
inspired by the late Matthew Shepard, who was killed because he was
gay. Overall, it's not always an easy album to absorb, but she has
taken a quantum leap in probing her own psyche without resorting to
the power chords of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Etheridge is generally quite happy these days. She and Cypher
have two children _ Bailey, 2, and Becket, 1 _ as the result of
Cypher's pregnancies with a male friend whose identity has not been
revealed. Being a parent has made Etheridge appreciate life all the
more _ another reason that Shepard's death hit her so hard. ``It
made me focus on life and why it's so precious,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NetAid to relieve poverty: Saturday's NetAid concerts in
London's Wembley Stadium and Giants Stadium at the New Jersey
Meadowlands will be part of the world's largest Webcast. Internet
users can call up www.netaid.org starting at noon for the London
concert and at 5 p.m. for the US event. Meadowlands performers
include Sheryl Crow, the Black Crows, Wyclef Jean, and Bono, Puff
Daddy, Jewel, and Sting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bits and pieces: Erik Lindgren and Ken Field, two members of
Birdsongs of the Mesozoic, have formed sFz Recordings, with a goal
of releasing music that is ``substantive, and serious, but also
relevant, interesting, and appealing to a broader public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
