<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SUPERSTAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUPERSTAR' HAS WHAT IT TAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
SUPERSTAR 
Directed by: Bruce McCulloch 
Screenplay by: Steven Wayne Koren 
Starring: Molly Shannon, Will Ferrell, Elaine Hendrix, Harland
Williams, Mark McKiney, Glynis Johns, Emmy Laybourne 
Running time: 90 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (sex-related humor and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's one thing to trip over chairs and be funny for 10 minutes
on a ``Saturday Night Live'' sketch. It's quite another to bring
off a 90-minute claim on an audience's attention in a feature film.
But Molly Shannon's endearing ball of parochial school anxiety
named Mary Katherine Gallagher, with her too-short plaid skirt and
her face screwed into an expression of perpetual intensity behind
her horn-rimmed glasses, beats the odds and makes the jump in
``Superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   We laugh at her because she's so relentlessly serious, and
although the story is so slight as to be virtually nonexistent in
``Superstar,'' it does give her two things to be intense about. She
desperately wants to win a talent contest sponsored by Catholic
Teen Magazine with a first prize of a trip to Hollywood and a
chance to be an extra in a movie with positive moral values. She
also wants to cop a big, long smacking-wet Hollywood kiss from the
school dreamboat.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she goes around hugging trees. Shannon is so
closely identified with her character that she's funny even when
she's playing opposite a tree in a scene of one-way romance. Not
that Will Ferrell, her SNL co-star, is playing a character that's
much more sparkling than a tree. What makes his character named Sky
so funny is Sky's vacancy. He could be thought of as a tree with
dancing ability. His out-of-itness gives Shannon just the
springboard Mary needs to push off from.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the comic surehandedness is the obvious
chemistry between Shannon, Ferrell, and director Bruce McCulloch,
who recently teamed up with Ferrell to demonstrate their rapport
and also their shared mastery of comic dimness by giving us a
hilarious take on Woodward and Bernstein in ``Dick.'' Harland
Williams is a plus, too, as the mysterious Harley-riding school
loner and so is Emmy Laybourne as Mary Katherine's klutzy but loyal
sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   They all know exactly how to play this material out, and the
script gives Shannon just the extra measure of sweetness she needs
to stave off two-dimensionality and keep us from feeling sheepish
about laughing at Mary Katherine because we know her tenacity will
eventually get her what she's after. The secret of Mary Katherine's
success is that she isn't afraid to risk looking foolish by trying
too hard. The secret of Shannon's success is that she knows just
how hard to try.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
