<HEADER>
A0839 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-RANDOM-BOS &LR;      10-08 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RANDOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RANDOM HEARTS' BEATS TOO TEPIDLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
RANDOM HEARTS 
Directed by: Sydney Pollack 
Screenplay by: Kurt Luedtke 
Starring: Harrison Ford, Kristin Scott Thomas, Charles S. Dutton,
Bonnie Hunt, Dennis Haysbert, Richard Jenkins, Paul Guilfoyle,
Susanna Thompson, Dylan Baker, Peter Coyote, Kate Mara, Ariana
Thomas 
Running time: 133 minutes 
Rated: R (brief violence, sexuality and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Random Hearts'' is A-list soap opera, high-class and
high-gloss. Maybe it would have been better if it had dipped into a
few B-movie moves. Rare and admirable as reserve may be in
Hollywood movies, it's a bit too reserved, too detached for its own
good, such decorousness having been imposed on it, one assumes, by
the presence of Harrison Ford and Kristin Scott Thomas. To their
credit, neither is likely to be associated with anything cheap. But
in a way, this works against them because the way of the movie
world also demands that there be a romantic interlude between them
as characters suddenly thrust into each other's lives after they
learn that their respective spouses have been sleeping with each
other.
</P>
<P>
   The affair comes to light after the cheating spouses die in a
plane crash. They were flying to Miami for a weekend after
carefully setting up cover stories. As Ford's D.C. cop glumly says
to Scott Thomas's perhaps too-poised congresswoman from New
Hampshire, ``Sooner or later, everybody knows everything.'' What
hurts Ford's cop named Dutch Van Den Broeck is that while he prides
himself on being an ace investigator who makes his living noticing
things, he was the last to know. Thomas's pol reacts differently.
Her impulse is to slam the door on the hurt arising from her
betrayal, and move on. She finds, however, that it's easier said
than done.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Ford's cop spends most of the film losing a fight
to stay in control, while Scott Thomas's congresswoman spends most
of the film winning one. A credibility problem arises because each
character clearly is a keep-the-lid-on type who may feel things
deeply, but operates from behind some pretty formidable defenses.
Although the film will be attacked for taking its time getting to
their romantic convergence, I liked the gradualness of the
revelation each experiences. Given the shocking unexpectedness of
their mates' reciprocal unfaithfulness, the details shouldn't fall
into place too readily.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, when they do finally throw themselves at each
other, the moment is unconvincing because we don't see them as the
impulsive people the scene tells us they are. In other words, we
feel they're being thrown together because the script needs them
to, not because we feel it's what they would do. Even though we
believe in the precarious, vulnerable, and even explosive emotional
state each is in, we believe it only cerebrally, not as felt
knowledge. Ford does better at letting emotion work its way around
the edges of Dutch's attempt at control. Scott Thomas's character
seems more intrinsically cool and distancing, even though she
softens appealingly in the film's last third. But for all its
handsome, careful craftsmanship, there's a vital spark missing from
the core of the tepid ``Random Hearts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
