<HEADLINE>
BLACKS FIGHT BACK ON SCHOOL SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In July Boston School Superintendent Thomas Payzant, Mayor
Thomas Menino, and the Boston School Committee rolled over and
thrust their hooves to the sky in racial rigor mortis. Mortally
gored by the 1995 suit that abruptly ended affirmative action at
the elite Boston Latin School, the city's powers were finished off
by the June lawsuit by four white families that sought to end
racial balancing in the rest of the system and return us to the
good old days of neighborhood schools. Those days, of course, were
good only for white families.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of fighting with whatever strength was left, the powers
took one look at the new suit and called for the gravedigger. On
July 14, the night the School Committee ended race-based busing,
there were at least 75 parents, both white and black, who tried to
remind the committee that without such busing, white families would
ghettoize themselves into Latin-ready schools in whiter
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the desires of two white parents meant more than the
scores of children at Latin who benefited over the years from
affirmative action, the demands of four white parents in the new
lawsuit meant more than the testimonies of these 75.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to pick our battles,'' Payzant said in a sugary
excuse. ``And the battles ought to be coalescing people around the
teaching and learning agenda . . . rather than believing that this
one change in the student assignment plan will work against our
commitment to high standards for all students, equitable allocation
of resources, choice for parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Payzant knew this was absurd since neither the McLaughlin nor
Wessmann families at Latin, nor the four white families in the new
suit were ``coalescing people around the teaching and learning
agenda.'' All they cared about was maximum white gerrymandering of
a system that is 85 percent children of color.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was transparent. Payzant and the powers caved in
to white noise because they fear no deafening roar from black and
brown families. Even though African-American and Latino sixth
graders in the Boston public schools face Las Vegas odds _ 1 in 100
_ of going to Latin, the powers assume that families of color have
their own hooves to the sky in political apathy.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that Payzant, Menino, and the School Committee
may be wrong. Late last month, a rainbow coalition of groups filed
a brief in US District Court to oppose the suit by the white
families. The coalition includes groups such as the local NAACP,
the American Jewish Congress, and the Greater Boston Civil Rights
Coalition, and well-known individuals like Mel King,
desegregation-plan veterans Charles Willie of Harvard University
and Michael Alves of Brown, and METCO director Jean McGuire.
</P>
<P>
   Though not in the brief, Cheryl Garrity, president of the state
chapter of the National Organization for Women; Peggy Wiesenberg, a
board member of the Citywide Parents Council; and Tom Louie,
director of Mass English Plus have all vehmently denounced the
lawsuit. Other groups, such as Community Change, Affirmative Action
Voices, and the new Campaign to Defend Desgregation are saying the
clock will not be turned back.
</P>
<P>
   Wiesenberg is angry over her years of going to School Committee
meetings, and arguing for an expansion of advanced work slots to
little avail. Leonard Alkins, head of the Boston NAACP, and two
attorneys connected with the brief, Joel Eigerman and Michael
Weisman, warned that the brief was only a beginning. They are not
only fighting to stop the current suit, but they are considering
whether the system, like the state a few years ago, can be sued for
providing unequal education. They said the Latin situation is
symbolic of Menino's and Payzant's acceptance of inequality.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, let's assume there is something to be said for
having to qualify for exam schools,'' Eigerman said. ``But instead
of having this divisive battle over scarce resources, why on earth
are there not enough places for the kids who qualify? Why not give
all the kids who qualify places?''
</P>
<P>
   Alkins and King said the brief was a beginning, not just of
legal action, but of civic action. He said the complaints of
parents has been increasing and growing louder in volume, reflected
in part by activist Chuck Turner's advance to the final in the race
for the District 7 seat of the City Council. The volume, they said,
is getting loud enough where soon it might make Menino and Payzant
awaken from their racial rigor mortis.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting the message that Menino is standing for
white privilege and white preference in the schools,'' King said.
``People are getting the message that the School Department is so
hellbent on getting white people back in school, they will throw
black people down the drain.''
</P>
<P>
   Alkins said, ``I don't think people will accept a full circle
backwards. But it is going to take some dramatic action. Going to
School Committee meetings is not enough, since the committee is
picked by the mayor. It's clear that Payzant and Menino won't
respond to a critical mass unless it's a voting mass.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
