<SLUG> BC-TV-GUMBEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUMBEL'S GAMBLE, PART II 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's one thing to be haunted by something done wrong,
but as Bryant Gumbel returns to morning television, he will
confront the specter of something he did right.
</P>
<P>
   That something is the powerhouse known as NBC's ``Today'' show,
which Gumbel anchored for an unrivaled 15 years, hiring many of the
program's key players and driving it to the top of the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, he works for CBS now, and ``Today'' 's utter
dominance of the morning poses the biggest _ though not the only _
obstacle to the success of Gumbel's ``The Early Show,'' which
enters the breakfast battles Nov. 1 with Jane Clayson as coanchor.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Boston this week, Gumbel, who was accompanied
by Clayson, expressed the hope that his ``Today'' past will serve
as prologue to his new venture. He pointed out that ``when I
started in '82, things went south before they went north.'' When he
was named ``Today'' anchor, he recalled, skeptics wondered whether
Gumbel _ ``a black guy, a sportscaster, and a 32-year-old'' _ could
win the loyalty of a national audience. He noted that though it
took a year and a half, he proved them wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Now another 32-year-old, Clayson, seeks the acceptance of a
national audience. A former ABC News correspondent who covered the
O.J. Simpson trial, the 1996 presidential campaign, and the
conflict in Kosovo, Clayson was chosen as Gumbel's coanchor only a
month ago, following a lengthy search that CBS insiders dubbed
``Operation Glass Slipper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of pressure, and there are a lot of
expectations,'' acknowledged Clayson in an interview at WBZ-Ch. 4.
With a nod toward Gumbel, she added: ``I've decided that sitting
next to this guy is a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Their on-camera rapport is what counts and cannot be judged
until Nov. 1, but off-camera, the two project an easy
companionability after an acquaintance of three months. Gumbel
joked, ``She reminds me of another Jane'' (referring to onetime
``Today'' cohost Jane Pauley); Clayson called him ``my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   But will they continue singing in harmony? Gumbel's relationship
with Katie Couric on ``Today'' was reportedly chilly; he is reputed
to have a prickly side. ``I know that's my reputation,'' he said.
``I've long since stopped baying at the moon about it.'' But he
insisted that ``I never yell,'' and maintained that he remains
``good friends with almost everybody I've ever worked with.'' For
her part, Clayon said she has found Gumbel to be ``a very gracious,
warm, caring guy. That's the Bryant I know and am eager to work
with.''
</P>
<P>
   As he and Clayson try to pull CBS out of third place in the
morning, Gumbel's friends at ``Today'' aren't likely to cut him a
break, given how cutthroat the competition has become in morning
television (the only time period where network audiences are
growing). Nor is ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' enjoying its own
resurgence thanks largely to the presence of Diane Sawyer on the
anchor desk.
</P>
<P>
   But Gumbel seems confident he can once again make his own breaks
_ and he may have reason for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   He has few peers when it comes to conducting live TV interviews,
blending imperturbability with a slight edge of unpredictability
when quizzing newsmakers, and his range encompasses politics,
sports, history and show business. After nearly three decades on
TV, he brings his own large network of contacts to ``The Early
Show''; in fact, he refused to concede that ``Today'' or ``GMA''
will have an advantage when it comes to booking major guests _ the
so-called ``gets'' on which morning shows rise or fall. ``I don't
think we'll be No. 3 on the call-back list,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though reluctant at first to return to morning TV, it is an
arena he has mastered, and in which viewers have embraced him _
unlike prime time, where his newsmagazine ``Public Eye with Bryant
Gumbel'' was canceled last year after just one season due to low
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel, who makes a reported $5 million a year, has been on the
CBS sidelines since then. When he returns to the air, a certain
tune-in curiosity among viewers seems likely; the power of marquee
names was illustrated by the ratings spike for ``GMA'' once Sawyer
and Charles Gibson agreed in January to coanchor the show.
</P>
<P>
   But Gumbel prides himself on a ruthless candor, and it surfaces
when he is asked whether his fans will still be loyal after he has
bounced from NBC to CBS and from mornings to evenings and now back
to mornings. ``I honestly don't know,'' he replied. Though the show
will clearly bear his stamp, he said he doesn't intend it to be
``drastically different'' from the traditional morning format of
news, features, and interviews.
</P>
<P>
   A lot is riding on his drawing power. In the past year, CBS has
become the top-rated network in terms of total viewers, but there
remains what Gumbel called ``a hole in its schedule in the
morning.'' In fact, due to the weakness of ``CBS This Morning,''
which ``The Early Show'' will replace, many CBS affiliates
preempted its first hour to air their own morning news programs.
</P>
<P>
   Once Gumbel was lured back to the morning, there ensued what he
termed a ``difficult dance'' of persuading them to yield the time
to the network show. Some have refused. ``It's a sore point,''
Gumbel admitted, saying he was hoping all the affiliates would get
aboard. In Boston, however, Channel 4 readily sacrificed the third
hour of ``News 4 This Morning,'' which has placed a weak third in
the ratings, so ``The Early Show'' can air from 7 a.m. to 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he looks ahead to Nov. 1, Gumbel can't help looking back
two decades and marveling at the changes in the once-sleepy world
of morning television. ``Back in 1982, the morning was seen as a
rehash of the evening news,'' he recalled. ``Now, people operate on
a 24-hour clock.''
</P>
<P>
   And once again, Bryant Gumbel will occupy two of those 24 hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
