<HEADLINE>
KLEIN SHOPS AROUND FOR MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calvin Klein Inc. is shopping for a good deal.
</P>
<P>
   The New York fashion house, which became legendary in the '70s
and '80s for its provocative advertising and signature designer
jeans, announced that it is considering a merger or strategic
alliance as a means to bolster its international business and brand
name.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes amid a flurry of such deals in the fashion world.
Prada recently bought a controlling interest in Jil Sander and
Helmut Lang. Gucci was recently acquired by Pinault-Printemps
Redoute of Paris, and now Fendi is reportedly being wooed by
several industry suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the mergers are coming at a time when brand names
are less relevant to many consumers who aren't willing to pay top
dollar for clothing. ``Today, most shoppers feel that they can be
very well dressed without going broke in the process,'' said Kurt
Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report, a New Jersey
forecasting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big companies like Calvin Klein are realizing that to make
themselves more competitive, they have to prune and pare their
overhead to become more affordable . . . The way to do that is to
merge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Calvin Klein brand has matured beyond its heyday
in the 1980s _ when racy ads such as the ones with model Brooke
Shields (``Nothing comes between me and my Calvins'') had everybody
talking. These days, competitors like Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, Banana
Republic, FUBU, Ralph Lauren, and Tommy Hilfiger are dominating the
sportswear market.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his jeans business, Calvin Klein has lost market share to
Ralph and Tommy over the last two years,'' said Josie Esquivel, an
apparel analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in New York. ``Tommy
and Ralph have also been very aggressive (in their) women's
business. I haven't seen that with Calvin Klein.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the challenge for Klein and every other fashion house,
she said, is that operating in the industry has become much more
expensive. Many retailers are requiring suppliers pay for
advertising and in-store shops as well as take back or pay for
merchandise not selling. What's more, retailers aren't increasing
the square footage they give to design houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your product isn't the one that consumers are running
after, it becomes very tough,'' she said. ``If you're going to
grow, you have to find another channel of distribution to sell into
or open a bunch of stores. But that takes a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to comment, but in a statement released
this week said, ``We have made tremendous progress in recent years
in building our brand . . . now is the ideal time to consider
strategic alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the outcome of this review may be, the company will
continue to build on its powerful competitive position in its
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein is a private company that doesn't release financial
figures but industry sources estimate its annual revenues are more
than $2 billion, including sales of apparel, cosmetics, and home
furnishings. Klein founded the company in 1968 with a childhood
friend from the Bronx named Barry Schwartz, who is now its chairman
and chief executive. Their combined initial investment was $10,000.
Klein and Schwartz each own 43 percent of the company, with the
rest held in a family trust.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources said numerous companies could be interested in
buying or investing in Calvin Klein, including a competitor, a
retailer, or even a high-tech firm or an entertainment or media
conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   Said Tom Julian, a fashion trend analyst for New York ad agency
Fallon McElligott, ``The brand is globally recognized. The image is
well maintained. I think the business has a lot of potential to
grow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
