<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-RAILS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITONS SAY PROFIT, NOT SAFETY, RULES RAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As he left St. Mary's Hospital Wednesday night, a
bitter Steve Jones ruefully concluded that he and the rest of those
killed and injured in Tuesday morning's rush-hour train crash near
Paddington Station had been sacrificed for profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a case of money,'' said Jones, 38, a management
consultant from Cheltenham who was treated for burns to his face,
arms, and hands. ``The people that died need not have died. The
technology is there.''
</P>
<P>
   The grim task of recovering bodies from the charred wreckage of
the worst rail accident in Britain in more than half a century is
not yet complete. But for 2 million Britons who take the trains
every day, perhaps most disturbing is the realization that their
lives have been judged not worth the expense of installing
state-of-the-art safety equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Many f them agree with Jones. But others say that while the
anger he voices is understandable, there is not an unlimited supply
of money that can be pumped into safety devices. Besides, they
argue, rail travel remains much safer than the roads, where an
average of 3,500 people die in accidents each year in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're 15 times safer being in a train than in a car, and five
times safer than being on a bus,'' said Lucy Twitchin, a
spokeswoman for the Association of Train Operating Companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Louise Christian, a lawyer for victims of a similar accident
just a few miles west of Tuesday's crash, said it is inexcusable
that railroads have not put in the most sophisticated equipment
when they know it can save lives.
</P>
<P>
   As public outrage grows, there are indications that the
government, which has been trying to persuade more people to ride
trains, is changing its mind about the cost factor. John Prescott,
the deputy prime minister in charge of transportation, said
Thursday that if an inquiry into Tuesday's crash recommends
installation of safety devices that the government and train
operators rejected as too expensive, it will be done.
</P>
<P>
   All this comes too late for at least 70 people known to have
died, and more than 150 who were injured, when a commuter train
apparently ran a red signal and veered into the path of an express
carrying 500 people two miles west of Paddington. The collision was
nearly identical to the last major rail accident in Britain two
years ago, when seven people died in a collision at Southall, a few
miles west of Tuesday's disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike two years ago, ruptured fuel tanks erupted in flames
Tuesday, dramatically increasing the death toll. By Thursday night,
authorities had recovered only 30 bodies, and some 120 people
remained unaccounted for. The recovery process is expected to take
several more days.
</P>
<P>
   Against this gruesome background, the debate over safety is
growing daily. That this should happen in the country that
pioneered railways, and as the popularity of rail travel is
increasing, makes it an issue that goes right to the national
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Anthony Hidden, the lawyer who led the investigation into a
collision at Clapham in which 35 people were killed, recommended in
1989 that all trains be fitted with Automatic Train Protection, or
ATP, systems, which automatically apply the brakes when a driver
ignores a red signal light, as happened at Clapham, Southall and,
apparently, on Tuesday. But the more than $1 billion cost to
install that system was rejected by train operators and the
government as too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's accident, the industry had calculated, based on
the average number of rail passenger deaths in recent years, that
installing the ATP system would cost $23 million per life saved,
and that it couldn't justify spending more than $3.25 million per
life. Since Tuesday, that kind of calculation, routine in
cost-effectiveness analysis, has sent a collective chill down the
spines of many Britons.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Prescott said an alternative Train Protection
and Warning System designed to prevent collisions would be
installed nationwide by 2004. Its advocates say it provides 70
percent of the protection of the ATP system at 20 percent of the
cost. But Christian and other critics say it is not as reliable.
</P>
<P>
   In the three years since Britain's 20,000 miles of railway were
privatized, ridership has increased 20 percent. But so have delays,
overcrowding, and passenger complaints. Critics say privatization
has created a fragmented system in which a comprehensive approach
to anything, including safety, is more difficult than in countries
where rail systems remain under state control.
</P>
<P>
   While everything used to fall under British Rail, privatization
has seen the rail system carved up into 100 components. The tracks
are owned and managed by Railtrack. There are three rolling stock
companies that lease locomotives and passenger cars, five freight
services, seven maintenance companies, 25 companies that operate
passenger services, and dozens of subcontractors.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the system, by which most of the 25 passenger
carriers hold the rights to a line for seven years, does not give
companies enough incentive to invest in safety.
</P>
<P>
   Since privatization, Railtrack and passenger carriers have
posted healthy profits. But too many of the profits have been going
to stockholders, not back into the system, critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privatized railway companies make huge profits,'' Christian
said.
</P>
<P>
   But while Railtrack is pulling in profits of more than $1.5
million a day, Lesia Kozlowsky, a Railtrack spokeswoman, said much
of that profit is being put into the infrastructure. She said the
company will spend $45 billion over the next 10 years on
maintenance and improving tracks and signaling.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget Hutter, a professor at the London School of Economics
who has studied the railway industry, takes more than a
professional interest in the debate. Her husband was supposed to
take the doomed train on Tuesday but missed it.
</P>
<P>
   She said the scale of this disaster, and the government's
reaction, could lead to safety improvements once considered too
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a cost-benefit analysis,'' she said. ``But
the emotion in this debate could change everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
