u k BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-08 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNALIST ON JUNKET AT POSH MOUNTAIN SPA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ASPEN, Colo. _ The hot tub got them really steamed. It wasn't
the water temperature. It was just that I got to try it and they
didn't. They said they didn't dare, because someone from the press
_ someone like me _ might see them soaking and dismiss their
high-minded conference as a junket.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was something of a junket. But then again, it wasn't.
The truth about the Leadership Institute for the National
Conference of State Legislatures, held earlier this week, lies
somewhere in the middle _ like so much else that we report on and
write about.
</P>
<P>
   I went there to talk about the press. I had to fight for every
word, because my audience, made up of state legislators and
lobbyists, had a lot to say and very little of it was flattering.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly news that people today hate the media. But this
group also fears it and worries about it more than the average
soul, because it is more at risk for being harmed by it.
</P>
<P>
   What was sad was how equally cynical they are about journalists.
They assume the worst about each of us, perhaps the way many of us
assume the worst about each of them.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter offered plenty to think about on the plane ride
home. For instance: If I didn't participate in this gathering and
only heard about it from others, how would I write about it? Would
I write about serious sessions that ran from 9 a.m. to 4 or 5 p.m,
with a break for lunch? Or would I dwell on the stunning setting,
pampered atmosphere and fine cuisine available at any number of
pricey Aspen restaurants? Is there a way to write about both?
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt the conference, held at the Aspen Institute,
conjured up standard junket adjectives like ``posh'' and
``privileged.'' In October, the mountains are golden and so
beautiful you have to stop yourself from constantly looking up. The
air is cold in the morning, but warms up so much you will find
snakes lolling in the sun if you take a mid-day trek along the
river.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the tremendous natural beauty, there is an unnatural
concentration of wealth. Huge, sprawling houses ring the mountain,
rising higher and higher to capture the most commanding view. One
homeowner, you learn, is paying $4 million to tear down a structure
that irks him because it interferes with the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   The Aspen Institute, which hosted the conference, is described
in a brochure as an ``international nonprofit educational
institution dedicated to serving leaders throughout th world.''
Presidents and prime ministers have been there, and weighty topics
are discussed and debated. But then again, there is that hot tub!
</P>
<P>
   Conference participants attended from all over the country.
There were no legislators from Massachusetts. House Speaker Thomas
Finneran was supposed to attend, but apparently decided against it
in light of the longrunning state budget saga.
</P>
<P>
   Junkets and misuse of public money are, of course, fair game for
journalists. But are we treating people fairly and honorably as we
pursue them? When they think we got something wrong, do we talk to
them about it afterwards, or leave them to vent via our voice mail?
</P>
<P>
   If it turns out they are partly right and we are partly wrong,
do we admit it, even to ourselves? If we just expose the elephant's
trunk, do we honestly believe we have drawn an accurate picture of
the entire elephant? And finally, why doesn't anyone ever write a
story headlined: ``Journalist on junket at posh mountain spa?''
</P>
<P>
   Those were the kinds of questions asked at the Aspen Institute.
Some were hard to answer. Typically, we are quick to dismiss such
questions, especially when they come from elected officials. We
have the First Amendment and they have to live with it.
</P>
<P>
   That is an arrogant view and an odd one, given the times.
Traditional print media are clawing to find and keep a niche in a
new communications world. Yet we continue to dismiss the consumers
of our product in a way that would not be tolerated if we produced
something like razor blades.
</P>
<P>
   We think we are listening to them more. But I think we are
listening less to our most loyal readers, ignoring them in search
of a new market that may never materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between the single-minded ``gotcha'' and the mindless
fluff are real stories that real people will read if we write them.
They don't necessarily want happy news, they want honest news. They
can take tough stories, if they are obtained fairly and put in
context.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny how you can come face to face with reality in a spot
beautiful enough to be a fantasy-land: Whether or not we step into
a jacuzzi, we are already in plenty of hot water.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
