<HEADLINE>
`LIMEY' HAS STYLE, BUT NOT ENOUGH SUBSTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE LIMEY 
Directed by: Steven Soderbergh 
Screenplay by: Lem Dobbs 
Starring: Terence Stamp, Peter Fonda, Lesley Ann Warren, Luis
Guzman, Barry Newman, Joe Dallesandro, Nicky Katt, Amelia Heinle 
Running time: 90 minutes 
Rated: R (violence and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's not that much to ``The Limey,'' but its moody visuals
and performances do a lot to compensate for its story shortfall.
Still, all of its style can't altogether conceal that director
Steven Soderbergh doesn't have as much to work with here as he did
in his career-rejuvenating last crime movie, ``Out of Control.'' In
place of that film's charming waywardness, this one offers a grim
linearity as Terence Stamp's recently sprung British career
criminal journeys to Los Angeles to go gunning for the man behind
his grown daughter's death. The biggest thing he has going for him
at first is that in youth-driven, body-image-obsessed LA, nobody
takes him seriously because his hair is gray and he talks funny.
</P>
<P>
   A few corpses later, however, he's on everybody's radar. After
he guns down a few underlings and spends time brooding in a cheap
motel room, reading and rereading clippings detailing his
daughter's death while he was serving time, he zeroes in on her
lover, Peter Fonda's rich, tarnished record producer. Until the
foreordained convergence of these two aging angels of death, the
film passes the time with a few fairly entertaining set pieces, but
most of its interest stems from Soderbergh's realization that LA is
a great staging area for several kinds of alienation. He and his
cinematographer, Ed Lachman, tell us all we need to know about the
limey's fish-out-of-water feeling when we see him in a long shot,
parading in profile down an LA street against a huge windowless
wall aggressively sunlit with a surrealistic brightness.
</P>
<P>
   The film's architecture, in fact, says more than its characters.
Fonda's way of looking wiltingly elegant in the producer's showy
Hollywood Hills house makes him seem about to implode, isolated
despite being surrounded by party guests, trying not to crumble as
he senses life catching up with him. The presence of both actors,
of course, resonates with the '60s and their respective places in
that turbulent era. They impart an elegiac quality. ``The Limey''
even includes shots of Stamp from the 1967 Ken Loach film ``Poor
Cow,'' looking heartbreakingly innocent and hopeful. In this case
the device works, even if it leaves us to do the work of providing
some badly needed back story to a film that never satisfactorily
establishes exactly what particular surge of paternal feeling sets
Stamp's character in motion.
</P>
<P>
   We're never clear on whether Stamp's character is driven by
paternal love and a need to square himself with the daughter he so
often disappointed, or merely by macho bravura. To his credit,
Stamp projects a regret that keeps the first alive as a
possibility. Fonda, too, projects regret in a dozen ways, from the
way he holds a glass to the way he takes a phone call. It's the
regret of a selfish, shallow man, too smart not to see that his
life is arcing downward. One reason ``The Limey'' seems so
undersupplied is that the secondary characters are scant,
particularly Lesley Ann Warren as the dead daughter's sympathetic
acting teacher and Luis Guzman as a man trying to live down his own
criminal past. Stamp and Fonda give us a muted, rueful, and highly
watchable duet in ``The Limey,'' and Soderbergh's resourcefulness
will have producers standing in line hoping he can make their
underwritten scripts look as good. But ``The Limey'' can't outrun
its very visible limits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
