A0848 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV1     10-08 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV10-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SELECTIVE BLEACHING' JUST MIGHT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October 10, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My brick walks get moldy in the shade. How can I kill the
mold without killing the moss and grass? Some moss is on the brick
and looks very nice, but the mold is ugly.
</P>
<P>
   JEAN DURRY, Marblehead, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. By selective bleaching. It might work. Make a mix of one part
bleach and five parts water; this is weaker than the handyman's
usual mix (one bleach, three water), but it should kill the mildew,
and if it gets on moss or grass, it is less likely to damage it,
especially if you hose it off immediately.
</P>
<P>
   By selective bleaching, I mean brushing the bleach on the mold,
and nowhere else. Brushing with a paint brush (buy one for
exclusive use with bleach) will make this easier, certainly better
than trying to spray on the mix. You can let this solution dry,
then hose off everything with a fine spray. Or, spray when you see
the mold disappear. The diluted bleach will turn into a harmless
element when it goes into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am cleaning our flagstone patio that was just installed.
Spic and Span cleaned them a little, but there is a lot of
ground-in dirt on these old, used flagstones. What else can I do?
</P>
<P>
   JOE ESSEGIAN, Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try power washing. Have it done by a pro, or rent a
power-washing generator at a rental store and do it yourself. One
good thing about power washing is that you don't have to add
detergent or any other cleaner to the power spray. Another trick is
to add a cup of bleach to the Spic and Span solution if you do not
power wash. This will kill any lurking mold or mildew, which can
last on a stone for years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I heard about your story telling of some sort of needle board
called Nicolet to keep pigeons and other birds away from my house.
I looked everywhere without success. People never heard of it. So
maybe I should come to you, the source. What is that material and
where can I get it?
</P>
<P>
   JOANNE BLAND, Hull, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, you came to the right place, finally, but it is amazing
how the word of mouth can distort things. There is nothing like the
printed word, if you can find it. The needle boards are made by
Nixalite of America, not Nicolet, 1025 16th Ave., Box 727 Dept. PN,
East Moline, IL 61244, 309-755-8771 and 800-624-1189. It is not
sold in stores, that I know of.
</P>
<P>
   A company that makes a similar product is Ecopic, 725 South
Adams Road, Suite 270, Birmingham, MI 48009, 313-647-0505.
</P>
<P>
   You say people never heard of it? You talked to the wrong
people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a small deck, only 4 by 8 feet, of mahogany
floorboards. I have not sealed them or done anything to them yet,
but the installer butted the boards tightly together. What can I do
in a case like that? The boards are square-edged, not tongued and
grooved.
</P>
<P>
   CLAUDIA CALDERHEAD, Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If the deck slopes ever so slightly for water to run off, you
have two choices: 1. Apply a clear sealer to make the boards water
resistant. Apply this sealer once a year. 2. Apply a
semitransparent stain of the color of your choice. This will do the
same as the clear sealer, but will last three to five years. If the
deck does not slopes, your option is to trim each board with a
rotary saw to create a gap of 1/4 to 3/8 inch. If you create this
gap, you still want to seal or stain the deck.
</P>
<P>
   Another option: Have the installer take up the boards and relay
them with gaps. I think the drainage is most important, and I think
it is important that you get the installer to do it, because he did
it wrong, especially if there is no roof over this deck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My plastic Spring Ram America kitchen sink is four years old
and has developed rust stains. I was told to use Clorox, but it
didn't work. My friend's sink, similar to mine, is also bad. We
were told that maybe the finish was removed. I tried Soft Scrub,
also without success. No one ever suggested sanding.
</P>
<P>
   After all this, is there something that can clean up those
sinks?
</P>
<P>
   ETHA INDECK, Beverly, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Have you checked the manufacturer? Can you find the
manufacturer, or is he out of business? It sounds as if the sinks
are simply not very good products, and you are the unwilling
victims, especially if the company is out of business or is
unwilling or unable to help.
</P>
<P>
   Try this before you give up, an old cleaner: Apply hydrogen
peroxide to the sink, then sprinkle cream of tartar on the wet
finish. Leave for an hour, then scrub and rinse. If the sink cleans
up, apply a thin coat of Gel-Gloss. The handyman offers no
guarantees that this will work, and warns that there is a chance
that the treatment will make things worse.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing to try: Smear on Ivory shampoo, let it sit an
hour, then scrub and rinse. Again, no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
