<HEADER>
A0849 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-HAPPY-BOS &LR;      10-08 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HAPPY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HAPPY TEXAS' LIVES UP TO ITS TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
HAPPY, TEXAS 
Directed by: Mark Illsley 
Screenplay by: Ed Stone, Illsley, Phil Reeves 
Starring: Jeremy Northam, Steve Zahn, Ally Walker, Illeana Douglas,
William H. Macy 
Running time: 104 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (language, sexual content and some violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every season needs its crowd-pleasing screenful of populist
froth, and this year's is ``Happy, Texas.'' Mark Illsley's
directing debut yields a disarming film of which Al Franken might
say: It's clever enough, it's eccentric enough, and doggone it,
people like it. Part of the reason it's going to be popular is that
it never attempts to be more than it is, which is a small comedy
that never tries to boil when it can bubble. This it starts doing
almost immediately as convicts Steve Zahn and Jeremy Northam escape
when their Texas prison van rolls into a ditch with M.C. Gainey's
bad-tempered hulk right out of a Chaplin silent. You know this big
bad guy is going to turn up later, just when things are going well
for the escaped pair.
</P>
<P>
   And things do go well. For a while. We feel as liberated as they
do when they lose their prison jumpsuits, steal a Winnebago that
belongs to a gay couple who make a living staging beauty pageants,
and roll into the apocryphal little Texas town of Happy, which, it
turns out, has become pretty unhappy over the years because its
schoolgirls never get anywhere in talent contests. So the town pays
the pair $1,000 to turn the willing but raw elementary schoolers
into a parade of little winners, assuming they're the experts
they've been expecting, too innocently pure-hearted to suspect that
they're fakes.
</P>
<P>
   Northam is the handsome one, which means he gets to woo the
town's eminently wooable banker, Ally Walker's smart, earthy woman
tired of living the single life. Zahn is the funny one, though, the
one who's going to send you away feeling you've had a good time.
After making his presence felt around the edges of a couple of
hits, he's found his breakthrough role here. If you don't find
yourself laughing when he lunges and twinkletoes his way through a
schoolroom of preteen girls relying on this cellblock Baryshnikov
to get them to the finals in the face of their rapidly escalating
skepticism, check your circulation.
</P>
<P>
   He never lets his runtiness stop him from taking on anybody in a
fight or screwing his face into some pretzelly twists as he shapes
up the dancing tots and romances their teacher, played with bedroom
eyes, yet mostly for laughs (with the aid of impeccably bad
clothing choices), by Illeana Douglas. That rubber-faced gold
standard of independent comedy, William H. Macy, also chips in
mightily as the town's soulful sheriff, who bravely takes a few
bullets, then surprises himself when he even more bravely follows
the vagrant call of his own heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy, Texas'' doesn't represent the last frontier in
enlightened gay portrayals. But there's lots of generosity and no
meanness at all in its more-than-slightly dated gay characters. Its
bustle, color, and off-kilter writing more than carry the film past
the less-than-inspired patches, including a need to tie everything
up into a package. Walker, Macy, and Zahn _ especially Zahn _ take
the characters much further than you think they're going to go. I
can't imagine anyone not feeling entertained by ``Happy, Texas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0851 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-HEPPNER-BOS &LR;      10-08 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HEPPNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEN HEPPNER REACHES BEYOND `TRISTAN UND ISOLDE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hottest ticket in New York this season is for one of the
Metropolitan Opera's performances of Wagner's ``Tristan und
Isolde'' with Ben Heppner and Jane Eaglen in the title roles. Even
the Met has been caught off guard by the feeding frenzy at the box
office, although it shouldn't have been _ for more than 50 years
the company has been presenting ``Tristan or Isolde'' and sometimes
even ``Neither of Them.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the frenzy is that Heppner has no more
intention of devoting the rest of his life to singing Tristan than
his great Canadian predecessor Jon Vickers did once he had reached
the summit of this Himalayan part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a full-fledged helden guy,'' Heppner genially said
over the phone recently before going off to sing Schoenberg's
``Gurrelieder'' with the Pittsburgh Symphony. ``And I am content to
be what I am. I think of myself as a large lyric. When I look at a
score, I try to think of phrases as lyric rather than dramatic.
From the way I look at it, that's the healthy way. I can't sound
like some of those other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Heppner makes his Boston debut as a recitalist next Friday
night, singing a program in Jordan Hall for the BankBoston
Celebrity Series. He's a relative newcomer to the recital circuit,
but he says he's learned to enjoy the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when I was in the university, I did some recitals because
I had to. Back then, there was always a sense of voluntary
incarceration, even when I went to recitals by other people. I
believe that recitals should have both entertainment and musical
value, so I try to find music that meets both of those critera.
Once my career got underway I got so busy doing opera and an
orchestral piece once in a while, there wasn't any time for
recitals. But two seasons ago I started singing recitals again. It
was a little tricky at first, and I felt awkward, but I've learned
to like this kind of intimate contact with the audience. And, from
what I hear, the reviews came out pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Heppner's program, with Craig Rutenberg at the piano, begins
with Beethoven's ``Adelaide'' and continues with Berlioz's ``Nuits
d'ete.'' After intermission there's a group of powerful
Rachmaninoff songs, and then, unexpectedly, a nosegay of parlor
songs like ``Bird Songs at Eventide'' and ``Roses of Picardy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite thrilled by these old songs; it's an absolute joy to
sing them. I've made a parlor song CD which will be out in
November, and people are hoping it will become a popular crossover
disc for me. These are the songs my mother, who is 88, always
wished I would sing. There's a sense in which she doesn't think
opera is at all nice, but she can relate to music like this. And it
will be fun to sing them in Boston, where people must think the
only piece I know is Mahler's `Das Lied von der Erde'!'' (Heppner's
only previous local performances were with the Boston Symphony
Orchestra in the Mahler cycle in two different seasons.)
</P>
<P>
   Heppner grew up in British Columbia and studied at the
University of British Columbia; 20 years ago, fresh out of school,
he won the Canadian Brodcasting Company Talent Festival. At that
time, he sang the lyric tenor repertory, although he was clearly
headed for bigger things. Over the last dozen years he has
developed his technique for heavier roles through studying with the
tenor William Neil and hs wife Dixie Lee Neil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Dixie just before I left the apprentice program at the
Toronto Opera. I was brought in to replace another singer in a
group of arias that couldn't be changed, lyric things, including
`Un aura amorosa' from `Cosi fan tutte.' Actually in my youth, that
one used to get me letters under the door from girls after I sang
it! We went through it and then Dixie took the score, closed it,
and said, `You've got to promise me one thing _ that you'll never
sing this again,' and I've taken her up on that!''
</P>
<P>
   Heppner warms to the theme of the affinity he feels between
Mozart and Wagner. ``I can still sing Mozart arias like `Il mio
tesoro' from `Don Giovanni' and Tamino's aria from `The Magic
Flute' _ although I do it without the sanction of the Lyric Tenors
Association! And then I can turn around and sing `Die
Meistersinger.' OK, lyric tenors, try that one! Actually I think
Walter in `Meisterrsinger' and Mozart's Don Ottavio are for the
same kind of voice, and Lohengrin should sound like Tamino.''
</P>
<P>
   He had sung Wagner's Walther and Lohenrin for years, and
recorded ``Die Meistersinger'' twice, before he finally accepted
the challenge of Tristan in Seattle two years ago. ``I can get
through it; that kind of suprised me! What you need to do in the
rehearsal period is to work through all those emotions that Tristan
has to experience, and that's not an easy thing. I found the first
rehearsal process to be quite hard on me in a lot of ways _ the
piece itself, the things I bring to it that make my own problems
worse, the mountain of mythology that surrounds the part, the huge
expectations of the audience, which is something I hadn't even
thought about. But now I have 15 of them under my belt. In Seattle
I ended up singing the part with cuts because I just wasn't coping
with it, and I had to sing it every third day. But I have since
done it it full-length in Florence and in Berlin.''
</P>
<P>
   Heppner says he met Jon Vickers only twice. ``When the Canadian
soprano Lois Marshall received a lifetime achievement award, Jon
presented the prize and I sang in her honor. Later, at her memorial
service, when we were receiving instructions about how to move
forward, he came up to me and said, `So are you singing too much?'
`Why do you say that?' I asked. `Every time I open a magazine,' he
said, `you're in it.' I told him it was smoke and mirrors. I try
not to sing more than 40 or 50 times a year. This year I know I've
overbooked myself for Tristans; there are more of them than I ought
to sing. But I know my voice is healthier and stronger for having
done it. Still, I maintain a healthy fear about the piece; I know
you can't take anything for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Heppner also knows there is more to life than singing; he knows
that his life outside his profession nourishes his singing. He
lives in Toronto and his family is very important to him (his
children are 18, 15, and 13). ``I had the chance to go sing
`Turandot' in the Forbidden City in Beijing, but after I finished
`Tristan' in Seattle, the only thing I wanted to do was go home. I
don't want to spend eight months of the year on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Heppner's recording of ``Tristan'' with Deborah Voigt was
cancelled when conductor Sir Georg Solti died. Sony plans to record
the opera with Jane Eaglen, but with another tenor as Tristan _
Placido Domingo. Heppner is wistful about this lost chance.
``Recordings of `Tristan' don't come along every day. What I would
love would be a movement from one of the record companies to record
the Met performances this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Heppner is looking to move his operatic repertory into different
directions. ``When I did `Pagliacci' a while back, a couple of
things struck me. I was too young and needed more miles on this old
frame _ you have to know what you're about to sing that opera. I
needed to develop a sense that I could do whatever I wanted with my
voice and know I won't hurt it. In another six or seven years when
I'm hitting my 50s I want to try it again. By then, I'll have
something to bring to the role. And I'm planning to sing Verdi's
`Otello.' Watch this space for further announcements. . .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1549EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
