   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VIEQUES-BOMBING (Washington) _ The government's premier
cancer-monitoring agency agrees to investigate claims that 58 years
of Navy and Marine Corps bombing practice on the Puerto Rican
island of Vieques has caused the high cancer rate among residents
there. The agency's action may complicate President Clinton's
decision on Navy demands that the target range be reopened. It was
closed after a Puerto Rican civilian was killed by a bomb that went
astray. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ Kendra Kennon is a large woman,
weighing more than 100 pounds than what her ``ideal'' weight should
be. Kennon is also charming, attractive and lively _ everything
that most companies would want in a customer service
representative. But Southwest Airlines doesn't want her because she
can't fit into a size 18 uniform, the highest size the airline will
allow for its customer service agents. By L.M. SIXEL. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Digital image editing, once the
domain of professional graphics artists, is going mainstream.
Here's a look at three new versions of some of the most popular
image editors, with choices for dabbling novices, those who need
less hand-holding and, finally, those who are serious about working
with graphics. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader asks, ``I upgraded to
Windows 98 Second Edition on my computer, and now it's doing the
most irritating thing. Whenever I start my computer, a box pops up
that wants to dial my Internet provider. I can't figure out how to
make this go away.'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ Pitcher Mike Hampton tries to give the
Houston Astros a lead in the best-of-five divisional series in an
afternoon game between the Astros and the Atlanta Braves. The
series is tied at 1. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN and BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOMECOMING-QUEENS (Beaumont, Texas) _ Forty queens at one
homecoming might seem like wretched excess, but excess is what
homecoming is all about in Vidor, a town of 11,000 just east of
here. There will be 39 previous homecoming queens to greet the 1999
queen when she is crowned at halftime during the upcoming Vidor
High School football game. By RICHARD STEWART. (Photo available on
NYT database.) (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-MURDERS (Los Pajaros, Venezuela) _ The execution-style
slayings of three U.S. humanitarian workers by the FARC, this
nation's largest rebel group, outraged Washington, shocked
Colombians and threatened to derail a fragile peace process
designed to end a 35-year-old civil war. A look at events leading
up to the slayings sheds much light on Colombia's lethal triangle
of hell-bent revolutionaries, multinational oil companies and newly
enfranchised indigenous groups. By JOHN OTIS. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Warren Beatty's possible bid for
the presidency cannot be kissed off lightly. If he could garner the
votes of all his former girl friends, he could probably win hands
down. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
<P>
   For Monday:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EYE-SURGERY (Houston) _ If you have always struggled to see,
then you have always known me. I was the kid the teacher thought
was slow because I couldn't see the blackboard; the geek in the
Coke-bottle glasses that everyone called four eyes; the one who
went from hard contacts to gas permeable to soft and finally back
to glasses, this time, bifocals. If you have struggled to see
forever, then you know why I spent more than $4,300 to undergo a
laser procedure to fix what, for most of my life, has been
unfixable. By LORI RODRIGUEZ. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
