<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0862 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TRAVEL-SCAMS09-COX     10-08 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SCAMS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET USERS WARNED ABOUT TRAVEL AUCTION SCAMS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (t) travel categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The thought of relaxing on a palmy beach, cool
drink in hand, is enticing to many stressed-out Americans. In fact,
it's so tempting that thousands are turning to the Internet to seek
out travel bargains. Unfortunately, in many cases, would-be
vacationers are relearning that oldest consumer lesson: when a deal
sounds too good to be true, it is.
</P>
<P>
   Even when your money is not stolen outright, you may find that
the ``luxury hotel and cruise'' package advertised is really ``a
trip to the roach motel... on a barge,'' said Phillip C. McKee III,
founder of the Internet Fraud Watch project of the National
Consumers League.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Friday to the American Society of Travel Agents,
McKee said that during the first half of 1999 complaints to the
watchdog group jumped 600 percent compared with the first half of
1998. The huge increase was driven primarily by the growing
popularity of online auctions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The typical auction scam works like this: A con artist goes
online to say he has purchased a non-refundable vacation package,
but can't travel because his grandmother has just died. Bidders
offer to send him money, thinking they are helping out another
person while helping themselves enjoy some low-cost travel. But the
fraud perpetrator takes the bidder's money and mails out nothing.
If he does send something, it's a travel voucher issued by a phony
company that never books the trip.
</P>
<P>
   In another version of that scam, the crook claims he has
thousands of airline frequent flier miles that he must sell before
they expire. Of course, no such miles exist.
</P>
<P>
   Another travel trick is based on the old-fashioned pyramid
scheme. In this scenario, a fraudulent company offers the gullible
individual a chance to earn a free travel voucher. To get the free
trip, the victim must sell 18 vouchers to friends and family
members. The vouchers are either worthless, or provide
accommodations in grubby hotels with ``stained mattress and barbed
wire,'' McKee said.
</P>
<P>
   Still another scam involves the offer of both income and
discounted travel through the miracle of becoming a travel agent,
McKee said. Online companies offer to send you a kit of information
and credentials that will instantly turn you into a travel agent.
The victim sends in several hundred dollars, and the con artist
mails out a slim packet of largely worthless information. The
package contains none of the computer equipment or software needed
to enter the travel business. The agent credentials, which are
supposed to provide travel discounts, are not recognized by any
reputable hotels, cruiselines or airlines.
</P>
<P>
   McKee gives travelers this advice: ``free'' travel is never
free; it's a con. Never send money directly to someone selling
goods or services through an online auction. Instead, go to a
reputable auction site that allows you to send money to an escrow
account, which will hold the money until you receive what you
bought. Get every aspect of the deal in writing. Check references.
Pay with a credit card rather than cash or check. And never forget
that the Internet, with its fancy Web pages and invisible sales
representatives, can offer ``a perfect environment for fraud,''
McKee said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1610EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
