<HEADER>
A0864 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-COWLES-FLAIR-$ADV10-A     10-08 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWLES-FLAIR-$ADV10-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEUR COWLES MAKES LIFE A BED OF ROSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: England )  (For release Sun., October 10) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By PENELOPE GREENE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She was tiny and dapper in a trompe l'oeil ``jacket''
she had designed herself, its buttons and lapels coyly imagined in
needlepoint. She wore her signature amber-colored sunglasses; her
lipstick was rose pink and fresh. There were roses everywhere _
another signature _ blowsy ones clambering up the chintz chairs and
the pillows on the slippery green silk-damask love seat; sterner
ones nodded from bowls and a huge glass vase. You could smell them
with every breath. She took your hands and squeezed hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``So pleased,'' she said, her voice low and a little flat. ``At
last!''
</P>
<P>
   Fleur Cowles, the legendary editor of the legendary Flair
magazine, is very, very good at meeting people. If you don't get
the point immediately, refer to her 1996 memoir, ``She Made Friends
and Kept Them'' (HarperCollins), which is a daunting assemblage of
cozy reminiscences of her famous pals, which include just about
every news maker in the last half century: heads of state, movie
stars, major and minor royalty, artists, writers, socialites. Ms.
Cowles appears suddenly and ubiquitously in the newsreels of
history, chatting and squeezing hands and mixing it up with the
great ones from the front lines of Korea to the Shah of Iran's
palace. Ms. Cowles collects people as an avocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to put it down to the fact that I was born to make
friends,'' she said, in the suite named for her at the Lowell Hotel
on in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cowles and her doting husband, Tom Montague Meyer, a retired
British timber tycoon, were in town last week for the publication,
and the attendant celebrations and signings, of ``The Best of
Flair,'' a $250 boxed and bound album put together by Ms. Cowles in
1996 and reissued this year by Rizzoli.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost exactly a half-century ago that Gardner Cowles
Jr., the founder of Look magazine, published an extraordinary
confection of type and talent called Flair. Ms. Cowles, who
happened to be married to Cowles at the time, was its editor, and
quite infamous for her efforts at Look magazine, which she had
transformed from ``something quite vulgar, a barbershop magazine,''
as she put it, into a vibrant general interest magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But Flair was something altogether different, a delicious new
form of magazine, with marvelous thick paper that folded this way
and that, pop-up pictures, flip-books, books-as-inserts, scented
pages and a windowed cover _ die-cut in different shapes each month
to reveal a tantalizing image from the page behind it.
</P>
<P>
   There were stories by Colette, Tennessee Williams, Katherine
Anne Porter. You could see the work of Salvador Dali and a young
painter named Lucian Freud. ``The best things, the first things,''
it promised, ``uniting its readers in an aristocracy of taste.''
</P>
<P>
   After 12 issues and losses of almost $3 million (``It was a
fortune then,'' Ms. Cowles said), Cowles pulled the plug, breaking
his wife's heart. Four years later, she married Montague Meyer, and
left New York for London.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Lambert, the elder stateswoman of fashion publicity, has
known Ms. Cowles since the 1930s, ``when we were both just starting
out in New York,'' she said. ``Fleur had a column at The New York
Telegram or something like that, and I was representing a hotel in
Atlantic City. She's just gone from strength to strength. Part of
her charm is the extravagance of her luck, and the puzzlement of
how she has gotten along in life.''
</P>
<P>
   You won't learn how old Ms. Cowles is by asking her. ``The
Financial Times says I'm 83, but I'm not,'' she said, turning away
from the question. She's been ill, she said, and had some falls,
but then she has never been a robust person. At lunch Monday in her
hotel suite, Ms. Cowles dutifully ate cold pancakes, urged on by
her husband, while he drank his soup bowl dry and gazed at his
wife. They talked about Flair fans they've met around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just had my 56th one-man show,'' Ms. Cowles said with
characteristic aplomb. Ms. Cowles makes naive paintings of flowers
and animals, the sales of which are usually donated to her favorite
charity, the World Wildlife Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asked to show all over the world,'' she said,
delivering her lines with a freshness and sincerity that belied the
fact she's said this same thing in magazines, and in other
interviews, many times before. ``At every one of those shows,
someone, a young person, comes up to me with a copy of Flair to
sign. I made the magazine as an expression of me. I didn't want
yachts, I didn't want race horses, I already had enough jewels. And
then I made ``The Best of Flair'' for these young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooke Hayward bought herself a complete collection of original
Flairs a decade or so ago. Ms. Cowles saw them arrayed on a table
in Ms. Hayward's apartment, in a photograph in a decorating
magazine. ``She actually wrote me a divine little note telling me
how thrilled she was,'' Ms. Hayward said. Does Ms. Hayward see a
comparison between Ms. Cowles and Tina Brown?
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't possibly compare her to Tina Brown,'' she retorted.
``Her magazines are vulgar. Talk is vulgar. Tina is after something
else, she's after buzz. Fleur is different. She is an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cowles said she doesn't read contemporary magazines. ``I
don't think magazines have any great power anymore,'' she said.
``They send them to me, you know, but I'm not interested. They're
just shopping guides or travel brochures and I find them very
strange shopping guides. I get so angry when I see a dress, a
fantastic photograph, and all you see is the neckline. But people
still buy magazines to see what's in fashion. I don't care what's
in fashion. I never buy anything. Never. I don't want to look like
other people.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades, Ms. Cowles' clothes have been made
exclusively for her by a retired French couturier named Philippe
Lempriere. ``I send his children to college, and he designs only
for me,'' she explained. ``That's our quid pro quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cowles is a mid-century modernist with that American can-do
spirit. ``I have an idea a minute,'' she declared. ``I'm very
creative.''
</P>
<P>
   She extended her hand and showed off the asteroid of diamonds on
her pinkie, a Cowles design. She talked about her plans to bring
out a Flair guide to life; her book-in-progress about flowers, and
her collaboration with an animator to make two of the children's
books she has illustrated _ ``Tiger Flower'' and ``For the Love of
Tiger Flower'' _ into movies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, S.J. Perelman skewered Ms. Cowles' un-self-conscious
immodesty in a satirical piece in The New Yorker, which concluded:
``Hyacinth switches on her reading lamp, picks up a box of paper
clips, and patiently begins constructing a linotype machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Point made, but I'll bet Ms. Cowles could easily construct a
linotype machine out of paper clips. Could you?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
