<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LONDON REVIEW OF BOOKS: A MAGAZINE FOR THE INTELLECTUALS OF
YESTERYEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: England, Calif., N.J.) (EDS: Wendy Lesser, author of ``The Amateur'' and other books, is
the editor of The Threepenny Review, which will soon celebrate its
own 20th anniversary.) 
(DW) 
 By WENDY LESSER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anybody with enough money and connections can give a good party
celebrating a magazine; what's much more difficult is to produce a
magazine worth celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   On the Thursday before last, at London's monumental Mall
Galleries, The London Review of Books gave a 20th-anniversary party
for itself. There was nary a movie star or a political celebrity in
sight. This was a party for the magazine's writers, and those in
attendance included Frank Kermode, Bernard Williams, Alan
Hollinghurst and a host of other British luminaries.
</P>
<P>
   Like most bookish people of my time and place, I feel stranded
in the gap between huge glossy magazines and tiny literary
publications. The former seem to care too much about a mass
audience that does not include me; the latter rarely care about
audience at all.
</P>
<P>
   Where are the mutually conversant, well-educated,
general-interest intellectuals of yesteryear? I find their
equivalent _ to the extent one can find them at all _ in the pages
of The London Review of Books.
</P>
<P>
   I probably didn't see the very first issue of The LRB, which
came wrapped in the British copies of The New York Review of Books
on September 27, 1979. But by the time it became an independent
biweekly, in May of 1980, I was certainly aware of The New York
Review's younger sibling, which borrowed the American magazine's
tabloid look. The London Review of Books' founding editor was Karl
Miller; he was replaced in 1992 by his deputy editor, Mary-Kay
Wilmers, who has carried on the job ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Just as The New York Review of Books famously draws on English
writers, The London Review of Books reaches out to America. In my
own home town of Berkeley, Calif., its contributors include Thomas
Laqueur, Michael Rogin, Martin Jay and (very occasionally) myself.
On the other coast, the magazine taps Michael Wood and Alexander
Nehamas _ and that's just the Princeton contingent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a broad circle of people who speak to one another through
its pages, a circle that's always shifting,'' says Nehamas, a
philosopher who recently wrote for The London Review on Iris
Murdoch. `It's a journal that's serious when it needs to be
serious, irreverent when it makes sense to be irreverent, and
always witty.''
</P>
<P>
   The wit can be found even in the personal ads: for example,
``Socialist with a beard. Mid-40s. Would like to meet similar
female (facial hair optional).'' But this is trimming. What I
really like about The London Review of Books is that it preserves,
even in its lengthiest essays, the sound of the individual voice.
People who write for The Times Literary Supplement and The New York
Review of Books sound smart, informative, grammatically correct _
and, for the most part, just like the TLS or The New York Review of
Books. The very same people writing for The London Review of Books
sound like themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The editing is absolutely brilliant _ it's an education,''
says Adam Phillips, a British psychoanalyst whose article on Hart
Crane appears in the anniversary issue. ``And the magazine sustains
some idea of the common reader.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how many of these readers there are is the subject of
some debate. The London Review of Books' publisher, Nicholas Spice,
sets the total circulation at 33,276 (of whom nearly 10,000 live in
the United States). `That's only about a thousand less than The
TLS,'' he proudly announces.
</P>
<P>
   But Ferdinand Mount, the editor of The Times Literary
Supplement, insists that many of The London Review's subscriptions
are heavily discounted: ``They're giving it away and we're selling
it.''
</P>
<P>
   To American readers, all this will seem like a tempest in a
teapot. After all, both The London Review of Books and The TLS have
smaller circulations than little magazines like Doubletake and
Granta. But the literary influence of The London Review can't be
measured in subscriptions alone. It's there in the literary quality
of the pieces and the responses those pieces evoke in readers; it's
there, too, in the way the magazine fosters nonfiction writers.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Bennett is widely known in Britain as a playwright. But he
is equally famous, since the publication of his collection Writing
Home, as an author of nonfiction prose. Bennett would probably not
be writing such prose if it were not for The London Review of
Books' diminutive, soft-spoken, but extremely forceful editor, Ms.
Wilmers. Bennett's unforgettable essay ``The Lady in the Van,''
about the homeless woman who lived in his driveway, first appeared
in The LRB 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary-Kay knew I'd got notes on it, so she made me write it
up,'' Bennett told me at last week's party, where he was hiding
with characteristic shyness behind his trademark brownish-gray
bangs. I turned the conversation to his delicate memoir in the
current issue, which deals with his mother's eight-year
institutionalization for depression and her lifelong fear of
seeming ``common.'' But he deflected me into a discussion of the
essay's tenses.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilmers, when I asked her about editing Bennett, was equally
chary of addressing content. ``It is incredibly difficult because
he doesn't have any punctuation,'' she murmured. ``A lot of writers
hear their sentences to themselves, but he's gone way beyond that.
I heard someone in the office saying, `How many commas did you put
in?'''
</P>
<P>
   Tenses and commas may seem beside the point, but they are not.
As Nehamas put it, ``Though they are willing to edit your prose,
they do not edit your thought.'' That alone, these days, seems
worth a toast or two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
