<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of Mon., Oct. 11, 1999
and anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New York
Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE NUCLEAR ACCIDENT NO SURPRISE &LR;  _ Japan's Tokaimura
nuclear plant was an accident waiting to happen. The world now
knows that its workers breached safety procedures. But even if they
hadn't, the plant's processing method was inherently risky. New
Scientist's enquiries indicate that, aside from Japan, only
Kazakhstan has in recent years processed highly enriched uranium
using a ''wet'' process. This is hazardous because water makes a
criticality accident many times more likely. 900 words By Peter
Hadfield, Rob Edwards, and Justin Mullins.Slugged:
BC-JAPANESE-NUCLEAR-ACCIDENT-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   CONCRETE-CHOMPING BACTERIA COULD CLEAN UP NUCLEAR SPILLS &LR;  _ A
bacteria-infected yellow gel that eats through concrete could soon
help engineers to clean up radioactive contamination at nuclear
sites. British Nuclear Fuel plans to put it to the test in the next
few months at the Sellafield nuclear reprocessing plant in Cumbria.
. 550 words. By Ben Crystall. Slugged:
BC-CONCRETE-CHOMPING-BACTERIA-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   ARTIFICIAL LIPS TESTING PHYSICS OF TRUMPETS &LR;  _ A pair of latex
lips is helping to reveal what brass players do with their lips to
make a brass instrument sound the way it does. The European
researchers who made the artificial lips hope they will lead to
trumpets and trombones that are easier to play. 550 words. By Paul
Marks. Slugged:
BC-ARTIFICIAL-LIPS-TEST-INSTRUMENTS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   OCEAN HOT SPRINGS CAUSING MERCURY CONTAMINATION &LR;  _ Hydrothermal
vents on the ocean floor release mercury into the sea, geologists
from Canada have found while analysing samples from vents in New
Zealand. This finding raises the question about whether this
``natural pollution'' contaminates fish and eventually moves up the
food chain to reach humans. 350 words. By Jeff Hecht. Slugged:
BC-MERCURY-CONTAMINATION-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
