<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0888 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-EXTREME-FASHION-$ADV1     10-08 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTREME-FASHION-$ADV10-ART </SLUG>
 - 2NDTAKE-NYT 
NEW YORK: aspirational ideal.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Esoteric sports that were once strictly participatory have
become spectator events watched by millions. ESPN 2 covers
competitions that would once have been viewed only by nervous
friends and relatives: off-road skateboarding, sky surfing,
chain-saw championships. Web sites like Quokka.com and
MountainZone.com hook up climbers and long-distance desert runners
with digital cameras, pulse monitors and communications equipment.
E-mail messages to Quokka describe hours spent staring at computer
screens as daredevils scaled the Great Trango Tower, a 6,000-foot
sheer rock wall in Pakistan, in July.
</P>
<P>
   The newest magazine aimed at this market is National Geographic
Adventure, edited by John Rasmus, a former editor of Outside and
Men's Journal. ``We want to capture the purity of what's implied by
the name adventure,'' said Rasmus, whose National Geographic
spinoff was started in April. His pages may contain features on
``exploraphernalia,'' but Rasmus, himself a hiker and kayaker,
takes his adventure seriously. He said his magazine's approach is
``not about irony'' and is careful to refer to the Himalaya
Mountains by their local pronunciation: ``the hee-MAL-yah.''
</P>
<P>
   Rasmus said focus groups indicate that his audience is ``very
active'' and was reluctant to acknowledge an armchair contingent.
Hal Espen, the editor of Outside, took a more realistic view. A
recent reader survey showed that about 15 percent of subscribers
``have tried some level of fairly ambitious mountaineering,'' he
said. ``Far more than 15 percent of our readers are as fascinated
with vicariously participating in stories about mountaineering.''
</P>
<P>
   An overdue parody of the genre appeared in the men's magazine
Details in the August issue. Wil Hylton wrote of training for a
serious climb in South America by drinking and smoking beforehand
and then continuing to do so on the way up.
(OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</P>
<P>
   There are cultural antecedents for our obsession with these
kinds of stories. From the middle of the last century into the turn
of this one, an industrializing America devoured the literature of
adventure, risk and physical danger in penny-dreadful accounts of
men driven to cannibalism, the great novels of Herman Melville and
the wilderness stories of Jack London. The view of nature had
ceased to be redemptive (the Romantics' idea) and become Darwinian,
as George Stade, a professor of English at Columbia University,
observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the last century there was a fusion of adventure
with literalism and realism and London and instrument of that,'' he
said, recalling a Jack London story in which a man caught in a
winter storm kills his dog and puts his hands inside the animals'
body to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Hemingway kept the man vs. nature tradition alive long
after the rest of literature had left it to Hollywood. There is a
George Clooney movie in production of ``A Perfect Storm,''
Sebastian Junger's novel of a sailor's losing battle with the sea.
But for the most part, the current armchair adventurism has
remained a literary, not cinematic, form. Rosenthal suggested that
``people are so used to being transfixed by visual imagery, there
may be some desire to conjure things up in the mind's eye again and
put the imagination to some test.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, that can be tested at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
