<HEADER>
A0894 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-ARISTOCRATS-BOS &LR;      10-08 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ARISTOCRATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARISTOCRATS FOUNDED ON `MASTERPIECE THEATER' HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ARISTOCRATS 
Producers: David Snodin, Christopher Hall, Kevin Menton and Nigel
Warren Green 
Director: David Caffrey 
Starring: Serena Gordon, Jodhi May, Anne-Marie Duff, Geraldine
Somerville, Alun Armstrong and Ben Daniels 
On: Channel PBS, Sunday, Oct. 10, 17 and 24, at 9 p.m.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, ``Aristocrats,'' a historical three-part series
beginning Sunday night on PBS, represents the best aspects of its
``Masterpiece Theater'' lineage. Its detailed visual account of
aristocratic Georgian England and Ireland _ the palaces, country
homes, gilded and chandeliered interiors, elaborately layered
fashions, dining tables groaning under the weight of roasts and
glistening silver _ is stunning. And, at times, and often when it
counts, equally polished and finely wrought performances give this
chronicle of four sisters of royal heritage a robust and poignant
immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   Grandchildren of Charles II and his French mistress Louise de
Keroualle, the Lenox sisters were privileged and fascinating
creatures of a rapidly changing world. ``Aristocrats,'' based on
the widely acclaimed book by Stella Tillyard, attempts to frame
their various intimacies _ sisterly, maternal, marital, and, in two
cases, adulterous _ with epic history. Their lives were touched,
sometimes quite directly, by surging democratic philosophies and
rebellions in the colonies and in France and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   It might be helpful to describe ``Aristocrats'' as a portrait of
four strong women and numerous strange or sappy men. Of course,
there are exceptions. But, for example, eldest sister Caroline,
well-read and willful, elopes with Henry Fox, a dourly intellectual
political animal, decent but notoriously odd and, finally, publicly
despised. Prolific Emily (22 children by two husbands) originally
mates with Irish Lord Kildare, dashing and amorous, and perhaps an
exception. Emily is smart, a deeply affectionate mother affected by
the new educational ideas of Rousseau, but cautious until her
second, and socially daring, marriage. Louisa marries a dopey
nonentity of fabulous wealth. Sarah, a darling tot in Part 1 whom
bizarre King George II playfully stuffs in a huge vase, later comes
close to marrying his son, George III, pictured as blandly
peculiar. The public humiliation of her near miss leads Sarah _
sensual, needy, outrageous by the standards of the day _ first to a
union with a nasty cold fish, then a scandalous affair with a
near-nutcase, followed by exile from high society.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters' emotional lives _ the powerful relationships to one
another, to their spouses and lovers and children _ are often
evoked with sublime artfulness and urgency. At its best,
``Aristocrats'' offers us daily life as it was experienced and felt
by these extraordinary, articulate and surprisingly engaged and
candid women.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``Aristocrats'' starts slowly, tilting our attention
toward its shiny production values rather than the rich human drama
they should illuminate. Except for the striking fact that many
years pass in Part 2 without anyone showing signs of aging, the
odyssey hits its stride there and in the early moments of Part 3.
Then, this multi-generational saga almost as full of begats as the
Bible, pulls the rug out from under viewers grown attached to its
dynamic main characters. Instead of cosmetically graying and
wrinkling by now familiar and generally excellent actors, the
producers disorientingly inserted new performers into several
principal roles.
</P>
<P>
   One effect is simple who's-who confusion. Worse, moments of the
finale seem like a goofy ``Saturday Night Live'' version of
``Masterpiece Theater,'' seriously diminishing but not defeating
this sweeping and sometimes spellbinding drama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
