<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     10-08 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Saturday, Oct. 9. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-EXTRADITE (London) _ A London court ruled Friday that
Gen. Augusto Pinochet can be extradited to Spain to stand trial on
torture and conspiracy charges. By Warren Hoge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSY-BOMB-ARREST (Undated) _ Federal officials on Friday
announced the first arrest of one of the nine fugitives who have
been charged in the bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Tanzania in
August 1998. The suspect, Khalfan Khamis Mohamed, 26, was captured
in Cape Town, South Africa, on Tuesday, flown to New York, where he
was arraigned Friday morning in federal district court in
Manhattan, and jailed pending trial. By Benjamin Weiser. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEST-BAN-TREATY (Washington) _ As the Senate opened debate on a
treaty to ban nuclear testing, President Clinton acknowledged
Friday that he lacked the votes to ratify the treaty and pleaded
with Senate leaders to delay action on the global pact. By John M.
Broder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH-CARE (Washington) _ The chief lobbyist for the
nation's health maintenance organizations said Friday that her
group would support federal legislation allowing patients to take
their grievances to an independent panel of medical experts, as an
alternative to letting them sue HMOs for the denial of care. This
represents a shift by the industry, which until now has opposed new
federal standards for managed care. The change was prompted by the
stunning House vote in favor of ``patients' rights'' legislation on
Thursday. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   N.Y.-GIULIANI-SENATE (New York) _ For months Rudolph W. Giuliani
has said that the best way to run for U.S. Senate is to be a good
mayor, without distractions from a campaign apparatus. But in the
weeks since Labor Day, Giuliani's unannounced race against Hillary
Rodham Clinton has entered a new stage as City Hall and the mayor's
closest aides quietly build the foundation of an aggressive, very
Republican campaign. By Elisabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-FREEWAY (Alhambra, Calif.) _ At one level, the latest
fight over a South Pasadena freeway is a timeless, parochial
conflict, pitting one community against another. It has gone on so
long that the son of the federal judge who presided over the last
big freeway fight in Los Angeles is now presiding over this one.
But in a broader sense, the battle of the 710 is an example of the
biggest question bedeviling a region that is again expanding
explosively after a deep recession: How to accommodate growth in
Southern California without destroying the very quality of life
that drew masses of Americans here in the first place. By Todd S.
Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-MEXICO-SCHOOLS (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ The New Mexico Board of
Education votes to teach evolution in state schools, thumbing its
nose at Kansas, which has deleted all mention of evolution in its
guidelines for teachers. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FCC-CABLE (Washington) _ The Federal Communications Commission
decided Friday to substantially loosen the rules that have limited
one company from controlling too much of the cable industry,
clearing the way for AT&AMP;T to own more than a third of the nation's
franchises offering subscribers television, telephone and high
speed Internet se &UR; r &LR; vices as well as being partners with a number
of major video producers and television programmers. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   PARROT-POWER (Undated) _ Do parrots think cognitively? Dr. Irene
Pepperberg, a scientist at the University of Arizona, says they do.
Assertions like hers are at the center of a highly emotional debate
about whether thought is solely the domain of humans or whether it
can exist in other animals. Is animal behavior the result of
reasoning and choice, or is it just instinct or sophisticated
mimicry. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
</TEXT>
