</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0926 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-GREECE-OLYMPICS-$ADV1     10-08 1491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREECE-OLYMPICS-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATHENS, HOST TO THE 2004 OLYMPIC GAMES, PREPARES TO AGAIN BE THE
CENTER OF THE WORLD
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (s) sports and (i) international
categories
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ Francois Carrard glowered through the dim light
at the 20 or so reporters gathered in the cavernous auditorium for
a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee's director general, an
imposing Swiss lawyer accustomed to being treated with deference _
if not fear _ said something.
</P>
<P>
   But almost no one could hear him because the microphones were
turned off.
</P>
<P>
   And many of the reporters wouldn't have understood Carrard
anyway because there weren't any translators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were supposed to have the lights, technicians and
interpreters,'' Carrard said in an un-amplified apology to the
front row of foreign journalists. ``But this is Saturday night _
and this is Athens.''
</P>
<P>
   And in five years, Athens once again will be at the center of
the known world. After being snubbed in its frantic campaign to
host the 1996 Centennial Games, Athens finally has what it coveted:
the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Still not completely recovered from its bitter loss to upstart
Atlanta in 1989, Athens is a city with something to prove with the
2004 Games. At the dawn of the next millennium, Athens wants to
prove to the world that the presumptions underlying Carrard's quip
are out of date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show that Greece is not just a country that lives
in the past but is a dynamic, effective, productive, competitive
place capable of organizing the Olympic Games,'' said Panagiotis
Thomopoulos, who was recently appointed president of the 2004
organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
   The city's performance in staging the Games is also seen as an
opportunity for Greece to prove it is worthy of holding its own
with fellow members of the European Union, many of whom regard the
country as a junior partner.
</P>
<P>
   When the new European monetary union and single currency _ the
euro _ debuted at the beginning of the year, Greece was left
waiting in the wings because it failed to meet economic minimums
for entry.
</P>
<P>
   And while its NATO allies were happily pounding Belgrade over
Kosovo, Greece stood by wringing its hands, unable to appear
decisive because of its sympathies for the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   While no one thinks a two-week sporting event will instantly
elevate Greece to the status of France, Britain or Germany, the
Olympics are seen as an important ticket to the partners' table.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the obvious challenges facing Games organizers
there is an air of complacency at the Olympics offices. Indeed,
even as reporters and IOC members who gathered in Athens last
weekend for Olympic meetings groused about the city's notorious
traffic, dodgy hotels and aura of chaos, top IOC officials were the
picture of tranquility.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Rogge, the Belgian physician who heads the IOC's
coordination commission for the 2004 Games, told reporters he has
''no concerns whatsoever'' about the state of Athens' preparations.
IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch echoed this sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the surface, however, senior IOC members and executives
expressed much deeper concerns. The IOC late last month decided
suddenly to switch its meeting from Baden-Baden Germany to Greece
to see for itself if whether there was trouble in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   The local media _ never a friendly lot for Olympic organizers _
have fueled speculation that the organizing committee was rife with
delays, mismanagement and internal bickering.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has endured a number of staff changes _ including
the resignation of its capable former chairman Stratis Stratigis,
who left following a scrap with the president over Stratigis' plans
to attend the wedding of a relative of the deposed Greek king.
</P>
<P>
   It is also widely speculated that Costas Bakouris, the
committee's popular managing director, is on the verge of being
dismissed, a rumor he only partially dispelled during the IOC
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The construction program has been taken over by the government,
and the organizing committee still is struggling to issue its first
serious budget for spending about $1.6 billion to stage the Games _
substantially less than the $1.8 billion spent by Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps an even bigger problem will be finding a place to house
the spectators. Athens has about 30,000 hotel rooms of reasonable
quality _ about 20,000 fewer than Atlanta _ and about 20,000 of
those have been snapped up for IOC members, their families,
sponsors, officials and other Games regulars. There are discussions
of pulling cruise ships into the harbor, converting dormitories and
assembling private housing to accommodate spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the IOC is unconcerned, people on the street are worried
by what they see as a lack of progress. Their pride at winning is
tempered by the enormity of the challenges facing the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``So where are the construction cranes building the stadiums,''
sand Kostas Triantafyllides, a merchant selling Athens 2004
T-shirts in the touristy Plaka district. ``I'm very nervous. We win
the Olympics two years ago and then they disappear. In Athens, five
years is a blink.''
</P>
<P>
   Triantafyllides is among those who have softened their views
toward Atlanta's winning the 1996 Games. ``I didn't drink Coca-Cola
for two years after they bought the Games for Atlanta,'' he said.
``Now they buy the Games for Athens, maybe I think again.''
</P>
<P>
   While about 75 percent of the venues were in place before Athens
was selected to host the Games, the city must build an Olympic
Village to house 16,000 athletes and a few smaller venues such as
those for baseball and softball. And the organizing committee still
is undecided about where to place six venues, an issue normally
resolved much more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have been late in waking up to the problems,'''
Thomopoulos, the new organizing committee chief, said last week.
``But I think now we are fully aware of the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the problems that plagued Athens when it was
competing with Atlanta in the late 1980s remain today. It is still
considered to be Europe's most polluted city, although the
government says stringent controls on car usage have produced a 30
percent improvement in air quality.
</P>
<P>
   The country's perennial political instability remains, but the
country is generally regarded as settling down into at least a more
stable mode. The economy, with low deficits and inflation rates, is
performing well enough to put the country on course to become a
full member of Europe's unified economy.
</P>
<P>
   A fresh concern is earthquakes. The city was stricken by a
substantial tremor just a few weeks after the devastating quakes
that hit Turkey. A mild quake caused a rumble during the IOC visit
and raised a number of questions about whether the city would be
safe during the Games. The organizers said, more or less, that they
would do what they could but earthquakes happen.
</P>
<P>
   Athens is undergoing massive transformation, with a new metro
system that will serve much of the city opening its first large
phase before the end of the year. A new airport in the heart of the
Attican peninsula is expected to be completed by 2001 with a new
highway leading to it by the time the Games arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Work has begun on parking garages in Kolonaki Square and central
Kaningos Square _ public places now choked by cars. Eleftherias
Park is being expanded to give the sometimes cluttered city a much
needed expanse of green. Even the Parthenon is getting a face lift:
eight columns along the temple's north side will be dismantled and
reconstructed.
</P>
<P>
   Athens organizers are going for the kind of makeover and
indulgent attention of TV broadcasters that permanently elevated
Barcelona to join the big players in Europe after the 1992 Games.
</P>
<P>
   ''You cannot compare today's Athens with Athens in 2004,'' said
Thomopoulos, referring to the improvements scheduled to come on
line before the start of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   It won't come a minute too soon for Johnny Yannakopoulos, the
most recent member of his line to hold the officer's rank at
Captain Johnny's restaurant in the seaside district of Mikrolimono.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent night, tourists strolled down the sidewalk above the
string of restaurants that sit right on the water. The air was
filled with the smell of charred fish and shrimp. Yannakopoulos was
one of the proprietors working the crowd of passers-by, tempting
them with his fresh seafood.
</P>
<P>
   Business has been lousy. ``You had the war and the earthquake,''
he said. ``The tourists canceled by the thousands and went
somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   In his view, the Olympics may be the one event big enough to
compensate for such extremes of man and nature. ``They are five
years away, but what a five years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1702EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
