<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL'S TOP GAMES THIS WEEK  
 EDITOR: RATINGS BY THE NEW YORK TIMES COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SATURDAY'S KEY GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 Michigan 5-0
</P>
<P>
   No. 6 at Michigan State 5-0
</P>
<P>
   This is Michigan's weekly Big Ten crisis game. The Wolverine
defense has stopped everyone so far, and Michigan State's defense
ranks first in the nation against the run (42.8 yards a game). The
Spartans can move the ball, too.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia 4-0
</P>
<P>
   No. 13 at Tennessee 3-1
</P>
<P>
   Two good teams struggling on offense. In beating Auburn last
Saturday, Tennessee couldn't punch the ball in. After Georgia's
second straight 1-point victory, Coach Jim Donnan said, ``We were
our own worst nemesis.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 24 Miami 2-2
</P>
<P>
   No. 5 Florida State 5-0
</P>
<P>
   Peter Warrick, the Florida State receiver and perhaps college
football's best player, has been suspended indefinitely after his
arrest on charges of underpaying for department-store clothing.
Still, the Seminoles have too many weapons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No. 24 Air Force (3-1)
</P>
<P>
   vs. Navy (2-3)
</P>
<P>
   at Raljon, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Run, run, run. Air Force ranks second in the nation in rushing,
Navy fourth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUTH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No. 11 Florida (4-1)
</P>
<P>
   at Louisiana State (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   Against Georgia, LSU couldn't run and couldn't stop the run.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina (1-3)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 9 Georgia Tech (3-1)
</P>
<P>
   Easy for Georgia Tech's offense, the most productive in the
nation (517.2 yards a game).
</P>
<P>
   No. 16 Mississippi State (5-0)
</P>
<P>
   at Auburn (3-2)
</P>
<P>
   A long day for Jeff Klein, Auburn's young replacement
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Mississippi (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   at East Carolina (5-0)
</P>
<P>
   If East Carolina wins this tossup game, an unbeaten season
awaits.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIDWEST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No. 3 Penn State (5-0)
</P>
<P>
   at Iowa (1-3)
</P>
<P>
   With all its perceived shortcomings, Penn State keeps winning.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas (2-3)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 7 Kansas State (4-0)
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State has the defense, and the Kansas runners aren't
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin (3-2)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 8 Minnesota (4-0)
</P>
<P>
   This game may show if Minnesota's defense is that good.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue (4-1)
</P>
<P>
   at Ohio State (3-2)
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State can't be as bad as it looked in the second half
against Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 20 Notre Dame (2-3)
</P>
<P>
   In beating Oklahoma, Notre Dame's Jarious Jackson passed for 276
yards and ran for 107.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUTHWEST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma (3-1)
</P>
<P>
   vs. Texas (4-2)
</P>
<P>
   at Dallas
</P>
<P>
   Two good teams that sometimes yield too many yards and
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAR WEST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No. 12 Southern California (3-1)
</P>
<P>
   at Arizona (3-2)
</P>
<P>
   Another tough-to-figure game in the underachieving Pacific 10.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada-Las Vegas (2-3)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 15 Wyoming (3-1)
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming's blitzing defense should have little trouble.
</P>
<P>
   California (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 17 Brigham Young (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Feterik is a passer in the Brigham Young tradition.
</P>
<P>
   No. 18 Missouri (3-1)
</P>
<P>
   at Colorado (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's defense should handle this ranked opponent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MISMATCHES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 Virginia Tech (4-0)
</P>
<P>
   at Rutgers (0-4)
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers's Mike McMahon, tender throwing arm and all, faces the
best defense around.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State (3-1)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 4 Nebraska (5-0)
</P>
<P>
   This should prove too tough for Iowa State's big rushing game.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor (1-4)
</P>
<P>
   at Texas A&AMP;M (3-1)
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies' flawless rushing defense, flawed last week, should
get well.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
