<HEADLINE>
OK, I'LL DO WINDOWS, BUT JUST THIS ONCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I've heard that you can copy a file from the
Windows installation disk to your hard drive to keep a program
being installed from asking you to insert the Windows disk. Which
file do I copy?
</P>
<P>
   _ Slipped Disk
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SLIPPED: I could tell you, but it's more fun to think about
you scrabbling through all your junk CDs from AOL and Earthlink and
Mindspring, hoping against hope that you didn't toss your Windows
CD the last time you cleaned out your desk, and that, if you
didn't, it's not scratched beyond repair. No, really, I have this
great mental picture of you breaking out in a cold sweat. It's
really funny.
</P>
<P>
   But, because my therapist says that's really disturbing behavior
for a help columnist, I suppose I can let you in on the secret.
Everyone who needs this info better write it down, though, because
I'm not repeating myself, regardless of what that quack says.
</P>
<P>
   Use Windows Explorer to browse your CD and look for a folder
called Win98 (or Win95). Drag the folder over to any place on your
hard drive. It doesn't matter where. Now, the next time Windows
needs a file that didn't get installed during the original setup _
such as a network or printer driver _ and it prompts you to stick
the CD in, you'll be able to browse to the folder on your hard
drive instead. Some versions of Windows will make you type in the
directory, but it works the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the big question is why Microsoft didn't add this as an
installation option. Maybe it likes the idea of you frantically
searching your house, too.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Someone is sending out a very desirable screen
saver, the Budweiser frogs _ ``Buddylst.zip.'' If you download it,
you will lose everything!!! Your hard drive will crash and (more
apocalyptic silliness). This information was announced yesterday
morning from Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   _ Easily Hoodwinked
</P>
<P>
   DEAR EASILY: No, it wasn't. Did you even check Microsoft's
security site (www.microsoft.com/security)? C'mon, people! Never,
ever trust anything you read in e-mail, no matter who it comes
from. First of all, Microsoft is only going to announce things that
can go wrong with its own products. Second, if you want information
about any potential virus, go to somebody you can trust, like
Symantec (www.symantec.com/avcenter/hoax.html) or McAfee
(www.mcafee.com).
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am forwarding this because the person who
sent it to me is a very good friend and does not send me junk.
Microsoft and AOL are now the largest Internet company (blah, blah,
blah). When you forward this e-mail to a friend, Microsoft can and
will track it. For every person that you forward this e-mail to,
Microsoft will pay you $245 and (more ridiculous tripe).
</P>
<P>
   _ Get Rich Quick
</P>
<P>
   DEAR RICH: That loud sound you just heard was me slapping my
forehead. Microsoft and America Online are pretty close to being
mortal enemies. That should be your first clue. And Microsoft
doesn't give money away without years of nasty litigation. Stop
spreading this fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   I'm very disappointed. In fact I'm almost as depressed as those
actors in the Gap commercials, although I believe their depression
is rooted in the fact that A.) they're too old to be playing
teen-agers; B.) they lack sufficient hand-eye coordination to comb
their hair; and C.) they have to wear those clothes.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay dresses only in attire from Eddie Bauer,
unless you count that beaded Versace gown he puts on every
Halloween. Reach him at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via
snail-mail at Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101; or fax: (817) 390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael
Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
