A0933 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-LADYBIRD-BIOGRAPHY-TE     10-08 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADYBIRD-BIOGRAPHY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOGRAPHY TELLS A LOT ABOUT LADY BIRD JOHNSON, BUT NOT THE FULL
STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady Bird''
</P>
<P>
   By Jan Jarboe Russell
</P>
<P>
   Biography
</P>
<P>
   Scribner, $26
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   When author Jan Jarboe Russell sat face to face with Texas' most
revered first lady, she asked how the widow of Lyndon Baines
Johnson had endured her husband's well-known indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   It was a legitimate, if indelicate, question. Lady Bird had a
quick, cold answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people ask me these sort of things,'' she said, ``I just
say, `Look to your own lives. Look to yourself, everybody. Fix
yourselves, and keep your problems to yourself.'''
</P>
<P>
   That answer sets the tone for this biography. It gives notice
very early on that the former Claudia Alta Taylor isn't about to
spill any personal or political beans; that she has spent a
lifetime protecting her family from public scrutiny, and this
effort by Russell will probably not get past her guard.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   We get a brief look at Lady Bird before there was a Lyndon in
her life, but only a brief one. The majority of this book is really
a biography of two people and their lives together.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way to separate us and our roles in each other's
lives,'' Lady Bird once wrote to Russell. The author agrees,
calling this biography ``a love story. A book about a marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Lady Bird was raised by her Aunt Effie Pattillo, a prototypical
Southern spinster, following the death of Lady Bird's mother in
1918. Effie was a dreamer, a delicate flower, with infirmities that
forced her to live her life vicariously through her young niece.
She wanted the strong-willed Bird to become a journalist for The
New York Times perhaps, or maybe The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   If not a journalist, then a ballerina.
</P>
<P>
   But Bird's father, Thomas Jefferson Taylor, was the richest man
in Harrison County. He got that way by working hard and dreaming
little. He wanted his daughter to stay in the small East Texas town
of Karnack where she was born, and work in the family business.
</P>
<P>
   The opposing forces accounted for Lady Bird's pragmatism at the
University of Texas at Austin. She graduated cum laude with degrees
in history and journalism, but also earned a teacher's certificate
and learned how to take shorthand.
</P>
<P>
   She had, already, learned to be flexible.
</P>
<P>
   But she was far less practical when she met a tall, outspoken
U.S. congressional aide named Lyndon Johnson on a blind date on
Aug. 1, 1934. Within days, he was daring her to marry him. Within
months, she did.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a storybook romance, but it was an enduring one that
cast LBJ in the stark, ugly light of an oppressive husband, and
Bird in the shadowy darkness of the oppressed wife.
</P>
<P>
   That was not entirely true, not entirely fair.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was brutish at times. He often mocked his wife in front
of others, scolded her for her looks, dressed her as though she was
his own personal toy. But, Russell also notes, there were times
when he was tender and loving. Times when he needed her strength.
Times when he could not go on without her.
</P>
<P>
   In the deeply dark days of the John F. Kennedy assassination, it
was Lady Bird who breached the cavernous gap between the Kennedy
and Johnson camps. She mothered the stricken Jackie Kennedy. She
tutored LBJ through the quarrelsome meetings with Bobby Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, she and Jackie remained distant, but gracious and
friendly to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Bird was often compared with Eleanor Roosevelt, another
strong first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eleanor was also a motherless child. Lady Bird lost her mother
when she was 5 years and 9 months old, and Eleanor's mother died
when she was 8,'' Russell points out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were also similarities between the two women's
marriages. Both of their husbands were unfaithful, and both women
endured the betrayal by looking the other way and becoming involved
in inspirational projects that had the effect of lifting them out
of the depths of their own private misery.''
</P>
<P>
   Lady Bird clearly had the business brains in the Johnson family.
While LBJ could wrangle a bill through Congress, she could squeeze
dollars from a failing radio station in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   She built a communications empire for her family, one that
financially fed her husband's political ambitions and provided for
her own independence.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Bird was no frail Southern flower like her beloved Effie.
She was _ and is _ strong, passionate and forever a Texas icon,
revered and loved for her graciousness and civility.
</P>
<P>
   It has, as Russell points out, been a difficult road for her.
She fought to keep her marriage intact, and decades after LBJ's
death, she continues to fight to keep her life with her husband
private.
</P>
<P>
   And she prevails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years,'' Russell writes, ``the way Lady Bird would
sustain herself in the hard periods of her marriage was to perform
a solitary, private ritual. When she was alone, at night or in the
early morning, she would take out her Episcopal prayer book, read
the vows, and recommit herself to love Johnson. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``She trained herself not to think about or notice whether he
was honoring his vows.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman is a columnist and writer for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
