A0937 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-INFINITI-A     10-08 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-INFINITI-ART-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000 INFINITI I30: AN OLD FAMILY RECIPE WITH NEW INGREDIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ A decade ago, when Nissan gave birth to its Infiniti
luxury division, the baby's future seemed clear: Infiniti was
destined to be the BMW of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The other new luxury brand of 1989, the Lexus division of
Toyota, copied Mercedes-Benz. Lexus cars had a similar vault-like
feel and cocoon-like isolation; the big LS400 even looked like a
big Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   But Infiniti's first car, the Q45 sedan, had distinctive styling
along with the kind of exhilarating performance that had been the
forte of BMW. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soon, however, Infiniti drifted from the high-performance
concept, and its place in the market grew hazy. The styling became
more conservative and predictable, and Infiniti emblems appeared on
pedestrian cars that were sold as Nissans overseas. The
second-generation Q45 seemed watered-down. It had a smaller engine,
smaller dimensions and, yes, a smaller price.
</P>
<P>
   Customers took note of this less-is-less formula, and Infiniti
suffered. While Lexus sales doubled in 1995-98, and Honda's luxury
division, Acura, gained 15 percent, Infiniti had an increase of
just 8 percent after some roller-coaster years. With Nissan in
financial trouble, Infiniti's future was in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are signs that Infiniti is taking baby steps to
recapture the territory it staked out a decade ago. The latest
evidence is the 2000-model I30, the second generation of its
midsized car. The I30 is smooth and polished, it performs well, and
it holds its own in a very competitive class.
</P>
<P>
   The first I30, introduced in 1996, was a Band-Aid over a gaping
hole in Infiniti's lineup. Sales of what the industry calls ``near
luxury'' cars _ sedans priced in the low-$30,000 range _ were
growing quickly. Indeed, this is still the fastest-growing segment
of the car market.
</P>
<P>
   Infiniti used the Nissan Maxima's drivetrain and body, grafted
on its own grille and rear end, dressed up the cabin and added
insulation to lower the noise level. The resulting car was pleasant
but hardly a standout.
</P>
<P>
   Although that car used much of the Maxima's sheet metal, the new
I30's body shares only its basic shape and roof line with the less
expensive Nissan. The styling is still unlikely to turn heads _ but
few cars in this class do.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the I30 looks better in subtle ways. I appreciated this
most when I saw a previous-generation car parked near my
millennium-jade test car. The old car looked more boxy and plain;
the 2000 model has sweeping, more elegant lines; more steeply raked
glass, and more dressy taillamps. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new I30 is 4 inches longer and 2 inches wider, and the added
size is evident inside. The cabin feels airy, with a particularly
spacious back seat. The trunk is among the largest in the class, at
14.9 cubic feet, and the split rear seats fold for cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Infiniti wants to establish that the I30 really is a luxury car.
The base model has been discontinued; leather upholstery is now
standard. Inside, only the glove box is shared with the Maxima.
</P>
<P>
   The instrument panel has been revised, with perfectly placed
controls that are larger and easier to use. It is still a
conservative design; some competitors have come up with more
contemporary dashboards, even gauges that look like holograms. The
centerpiece of the I30 dash is a gold analog clock with delicate
hands; that clock, an Infiniti signature, was unwisely dropped in
the second-generation Q45, but executives say it will appear in all
Infinitis from now on.
</P>
<P>
   All four windows can be raised or lowered with a single touch of
a button. There are five cupholders and a foot parking brake.
</P>
<P>
   The new I30 continues to use the front-drive architecture of the
Maxima, which was also redesigned for 2000. Both are powered by
Nissan's smooth and powerful 3-liter V6, an engine that often
appears on the lists of the world's best.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The I30 comes only with an electronic four-speed automatic
transmission; the five-speed manual was dropped for lack of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Modifications have raised horsepower by 37 from last year, to
227; the I30s engine was tweaked to produce 5 horses more than the
Maxima's. Because the I30 is heavier, though, and its gearing is
different, the Maxima is actually quicker. Torque has increased by
12 foot-pounds, to 217.
</P>
<P>
   The car accelerates briskly, and though the interior has been
quieted further by thicker window class, one can still hear the
engine's pleasant guttural tone. A stiffer body and suspension make
for more responsive handling and enhanced safety. The brakes have
been beefed up.
</P>
<P>
   The I30's safety equipment includes antilock brakes, four air
bags, active front head restraints that move to prevent whiplash,
and seat-belt pretensioners that take up slack in a collision.
Traction control, standard on many competitors, costs $300 extra.
</P>
<P>
   Other standard features include air-conditioning; a Bose stereo
with CD and cassette players; power windows, mirrors, locks and
seats; remote locking; automatic headlights and fog lights. The
I30t _ for touring edition _ adds Xenon headlights, larger wheels
and tires, a firmer suspension and quicker steering, memory
settings for the seats and auto-dimming mirrors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One cool feature, literally, is a power sun shade in the rear
window, like those in high-end cars like the BMW 7-Series. It is
optional on the base model for and standard on the I30t. It keeps
direct sunlight off rear-seat passengers, reduces the cabin
temperature by as much as 9 degrees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Infiniti Communicator, a sophisticated communications system
that uses cellular phone technology and Global Positioning
technology, is a $1,599 option. It connects the car to a 24-hour
response center similar to General Motors' Onstar that can provide
help in emergencies and offer travel information.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of Infinitis is generally above reproach, and the
test car was no exception. The engine is excellent, tried and true.
Infiniti's pampering dealerships are rated among the best in the
business.
</P>
<P>
   The base I30 model starts at $29,990 and the touring edition is
$32,065. A fully equipped car would run about $35,000. These prices
are roughly the same as the original I30 of four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Infiniti's closese competitor, the Acura 3.2TL, may
be a better deal. Acura offers similar package of
performance-oriented luxury for $28,855, very well equiped. Even if
hou add on the Acura's only factory option, a $2,000 navigation
system, the TL costs less than the I30.
</P>
<P>
   But compared with its predecessor, the I30 has more horsepower,
more interior and trunk space, more features, more distinctive
styling. That is the formula Infiniti plans to use on future
models.
</P>
<P>
   These include a restyled, more powerful QX4 sport utility that
arrives in March. (The next-generation QX4 will have an even larger
engine and seating for eight.) A new Q45, which goes into
production next year, will have more than 300 horsepower and
distinctive styling.
</P>
<P>
   The small G20 sedan will trade its four-cylinder engine for a
V6. And Infiniti executives promise to take on the very popular
Lexus RX300 with a new sport utility that will have ``the spirit of
a sports car.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
