<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If willpower doesn't exist, why do some people eat vegetables?
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Scientists who study weight loss have concluded
that there is no such thing as willpower.
</P>
<P>
   I'm no scientist, but I beg to differ despite the fact that I
haven't invested a single minute on the study of willpower.
</P>
<P>
   If the scientists are right, then they have spent perhaps years
studying something that isn't there.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I have spent no time studying this subject.
So who's smarter?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no magical stuff inside of you called willpower that
should somehow override nature,'' Dr. James C. Rosen, a professor
of psychology at the University of Vermont, told the New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently the scientists have been searching for something they
could weigh, measure or analyze.
</P>
<P>
   I see willpower more as mind over matter, when your mind gives
in to temptation no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when confronted with a bag of soft-baked
Pepperidge Farm Chocolate Chunk cookies sitting on a supermarket
shelf, I can either buy the cookies or not. It's all a matter of
willpower.
</P>
<P>
   I happen to really like these cookies. But if I had willpower, I
would not buy the cookies.
</P>
<P>
   After all, I know that a 14-year Harvard study of 76,000 female
registered nurses and 39,000 male doctors and other medical workers
found that the risk of stroke was cut by nearly a third among those
who consumed a diet rich in fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than buy a bag of eight big soft-baked Pepperidge Farm
Chocolate Chunk cookies, I should push my shopping cart over a few
more aisles and load up on kale, bok choy, collard greens, brussels
sprouts and broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   I know this.
</P>
<P>
   I consider the Harvard study and also recall the repeated
admonitions of my mother and several wives regarding my need to eat
more vegetables. I drop a bag of the cookies into my cart.
</P>
<P>
   I am not a female registered nurse, nor am I a male doctor or
other medical worker.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, I've always suspected that the women in my life
were just trying to cut their grocery bills. I can't recall when
they suggested that I eat something more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Grocery store items that are green and cheap as grass likely are
close grass relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what the weight-loss scientists say, my purchase of the
Pepperidge Farm cookies is proof that I lack willpower. Other
shoppers see the same cookies and keep going. That proves it
exists.
</P>
<P>
   To make up for the Pepperidge Farm cookies, a few aisles over
I'll fill flimsy plastic bags with kale, bok choy and brussels
sprouts. Weeks later I'll dig this slimy mulch out of my
refrigerator's vegetable bin and regret my lack of willpower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willpower was a kind of all-embracing theory that was used all
the time to make doctors feel good and patients feel bad,'' Dr.
Albert Stunkard, a professor of psychiatry at the University of
Pennsylvania told the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Stunkard, who has been studying weight loss for five decades,
must be old. ``Willpower doesn't have any meaning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It means something to me. Confronted with some temptations, I
have amazing willpower. With others, I have none. I think everyone
is the same.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when tempted to experience pain, I invariably
display an energetic determination to resist. More often than not,
I succeed.
</P>
<P>
   When confronted with a slice of fresh-baked apple pie, I have no
willpower.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than try to disprove the existence of something that
obviously is there, scientists should find a way to manufacture
more of it.
</P>
<P>
   Once it has been bottled, sort of like Pepto-Bismol, people
could take quick swig when needed.
</P>
<P>
   Just before grocery shopping would be a good time for a shot of
willpower. More willpower might even solve the world's
overpopulation problem.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(AT)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
