<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LOVE09-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   `Love &AMP; Money' not worth your time
</P>
<P>
   By Kevin D. Thompson
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Pop quiz: You're a network programmer. Some hotshot writer
barges into your office with this premise: Rich girl is about to
marry rich guy. But rich girl really loves poor guy. Rich girl
dumps rich guy for poor guy. Rich girl's snooty parents aren't too
keen on poor guy. Let the yuks begin.
</P>
<P>
   What do you do?
</P>
<P>
   Shoot him, of course.
</P>
<P>
   That premise is as dated as rabbit ears. But CBS hopes to milk
as many laughs as it can out of it in ``Love &AMP; Money,'' yet another
routine sitcom. Are fresh ideas really that rare in Hollywood? They
must be, because we've seen this comedy over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Allison Conklin (Paget Brewster) is a well-to-do socialite who's
about to marry some Princeton grad who bought her a $45,000 ring.
The problem is, she's in love with Eamon Roach (Brian Van Holt), a
former hockey player who toils as a super at Allison's high-priced
New York City apartment building. The guy actually _ gasp! _ lives
in the basement with his gruff dad (Brian Doyle-Murray), who looks
like former New York Mayor Ed Koch.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell Allison and Eamon (what kind of name is that?) are
from different worlds. She wears fancy Vera Wang wedding gowns. He
wears moderately priced tool belts from Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   While Allison and Eamon are cute, so are cocker spaniels. There
isn't much hot chemistry between them, either. And that includes
when they're making out in a freight elevator in next week's
episode. It doesn't help that both Allison and Eamon look like
they're in the third grade.
</P>
<P>
   The most laughs actually come from David Ogden Stiers and
Swoosie Kurtz, who play Allison's super-rich folks. Kurtz is
particularly funny as the martini-guzzling mom. But even those
characters are strictly one-dimensional and cartoonish. And so is
this show.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin D. Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: kevinthompson(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
