</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REALM09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `X-Files' creator plunges viewer into murky new `Realm'
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ITALIC)War . . . what is it good for? Absolutely nothing.(END
ITALIC)
</P>
<P>
   Well, don't tell that to Chris Carter. Despite what Edwin Starr
sang on War, his 1970 top-10 single, Carter knows that war can be
good for one thing on television: telling dramatic stories. That's
why ``The X-Files'' creator is using it as a backdrop for ``Harsh
Realm,'' his intriguing, though maddeningly murky, sci-fi series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harsh Realm'' is a typical Carter show. There's a sinister
government conspiracy at work. The tone is dark and brooding.
There's a dense mythology, and nothing is what it appears to be.
``Harsh Realm'' actually refers to a top-secret virtual-reality war
game designed during the Cold War to simulate various combat
scenarios. The game was supposed to be scrapped after the Cold War
ended, but Harsh Realm had other ideas as it took on a life of its
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to do a TV show that had elements of some
of my favorite movies, 'Paths of Glory,' 'Platoon,' 'Blade Runner'
and a lot of really good early war movies,'' says Carter, who based
the show on an obscure '90s comic book with the same title. ``I was
affected by 'Saving Private Ryan' and 'The Thin Red Line.' This was
an opportunity to take some of the things I liked best about those
movies and use some of the elements of virtual reality to create a
really good science-fiction show.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen, however, how good ``Harsh Realm'' will
be. Tonight's opening episode is definitely intriguing and leaves
you wanting more. Scott Bairstow (''Party of Five'') stars as
Thomas Hobbes, a be-all-you-can-be type of Army lieutenant. After
seeing some of the horrors of war in Sarajevo, Hobbes decides it's
time to settle down with his fiancee, Sophie (Samantha Mathis). But
the government has one more job for him to do: test Harsh Realm and
find a rebel soldier named Santiago (''Millennium'''s Terry
O'Quinn).
</P>
<P>
   After all, ``it's just a game,'' Hobbes is told.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than that. Once inside, Hobbes finds that the game
is very real and that he can't get out. It's a world in which there
are no rules, no God and no mercy. It's a world in which people
evaporate when they die, so, as Carter notes, ``there is no
reverence for the dead.'' Hobbes is forced to form an uneasy
alliance with a veteran soldier named Pinocchio (D.B. Sweeney), who
believes the young lieutenant can save all the virtual characters
stuck in the Realm.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say ``The Matrix?''
</P>
<P>
   Hobbes learns that Santiago actually hijacked the program and is
using the game to create his own kingdom. He also discovers that
his fiancee is another character who doesn't know him in this
parallel universe.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ``Harsh Realm'' is basically a metaphor for
totalitarian states. ``I wanted to take a godless world where there
is no morality, where there is no standard or code of behavior and
see what the world would be like if it were like that,'' he says.
``That gives us a chance to comment on society and certainly on a
lot of contemporary issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter has a lot riding on this series. Hollywood insiders are
already whispering he may be a one-hit wonder. Remember, the always
dreary ``Millennium'' flopped miserably. It doesn't help that ``The
X-Files'' is entering what will probably be its last season. Carter
has hinted, however, that he may develop a series starring ``The
Lone Gunmen'' characters.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Harsh Realm is Carter's chance to prove he can do more
than ``The X-Files.'' But if ``Harsh Realm'' is going to succeed,
Carter must create characters viewers care about and he can't
afford a drawn-out mythology that yields little answers. That's
what sank ``Millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   The always candid Sweeney, however, doesn't think Carter should
give away too much too soon. ``If it's pat, if everything's
answered for you, like the way it was in the ``Dharma &AMP; Greg''
pilot, I don't know why you'd want to watch the show.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll probably want to watch the second episode, just to figure
out what the heck is going on. Why is the government still
operating Harsh Realm? What impact does the virtual world have on
the real world? Who are the good guys? Who are the bad guys? Can
Hobbes get his fiancee back?
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate question is, will it all work?
</P>
<P>
   Carter thinks so. ``This has a tremendous love story and has a
great mythology potential as well,'' Carter says. ``I think this is
a great chance to tell allegorical stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin D. Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: kevinthompson(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
