<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-RODENTS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oh, Rats! How to keep your house from being a rodent haven this
season
 &HT;    (EDS: Rat facts and tips on keeping rodents out are at the
bottom of this file.)
 &HT;    By Amy Kincheloe
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Fall is here and you could be getting some
unexpected houseguests _ and that's not a reference to the annoying
family members who show up around the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   These unwanted guests are rodents, which include rats, mice and
squirrels, and they often like to hole up in your home during the
fall and winter months.
</P>
<P>
   According to Steve Jones, owner of Ladybug Termite and Pest
Control, the Waco area is already experiencing a rodent problem,
and some of it is drought-related.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their instincts are kicking in, and they're looking for winter
nesting spots in and around the home,'' Jones said. ``Rats and mice
are bad in the rural areas like China Spring right now. In Waco
proper, squirrels are living in attics. They're looking for
moisture, warmth, a hiding place for safety and food.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Poche, owner of Genesis Laboratory in Fort Collins,
Colo., which has specialized in pest control research for the past
30 years, said mice and rats are looking for an area to nest where
they normally won't be disturbed by humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll go under the stove, the refrigerator, under the sink,
the attic,'' Poche said. ``They're looking for a dark, warm area.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said rodents get into homes through small holes and
cracks. Poche added that mice can squeeze through areas as small as
a nickel, and rats can squeeze through areas as small as a
half-dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Once in your home, rodents can be very destructive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been known to chew through lead pipes to get a
drink,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Poche said rats and squirrels can also chew through wiring,
which can lead to fires.
</P>
<P>
   Rodents are unhealthy guests to have living in your home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They carry diseases, they carry fleas and they leave waste,''
Jones said. ``Their hair is also unhealthy _ it can cause people's
allergies to act up.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Centers for Disease Control, hantavirus, a lung
disease, is carried by rodents.
</P>
<P>
   Although the disease is rare, it is easy to contract, according
to the CDC. Hantavirus is contracted primarily by inhaling airborne
particles from rodent droppings, urine or saliva left by infected
rodents or through direct contact with infected rodents.
</P>
<P>
   Poche said good sanitation is the first step to keeping rodents
out. He advises putting your pet's food and water up at night and
storing the food in metal or thick plastic containers with
tight-fitting lids. Also, clean up debris in and around the home.
</P>
<P>
   The next step in keeping rodents out of the home is ``excluding
them with entry,'' Poche said.
</P>
<P>
   He advises putting steel wool in cracks and holes in the
exterior of the home.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing he advises is an old-fashioned method.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use good snap traps,'' Poche said. ``Place them along the
walls, because rodents tend to follow along the walls. Also, bait
the trap with peanut butter.''
</P>
<P>
   Poche said rodents like the smell and taste of peanut butter and
it also takes more of an effort to eat it off of the trap, giving
the trap more of a chance to catch the rodent.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Poche recommends using baits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep EPA-approved baits out,'' Poche said. ``Place them in
cabinets, under the sink, under the workbench, behind the stove,
and under the refrigerator. But place them where kids and pets
can't get to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Poche said when it comes to rodents, be proactive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't wait until you see one, because if you see one, you
usually have more lurking behind the scenes,'' Poche said.
</P>
<P>
   MOUSE AND RAT FACTS
</P>
<P>
   _ The U.S. Food and Drug Administration destroys approximately
400,000 tons of food yearly that is contaminated by rodent
droppings.
</P>
<P>
   _ As frequently as every three weeks, rats can bear eight to 12
offspring.
</P>
<P>
   _ The teeth of rats are harder than iron and their jaws can
exert pressures of 24,000 pounds per square inch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rats can swim up to a half of a mile and tread water for up to
three days.
</P>
<P>
   _ The fear of mice is the third most common fear among
Americans, right behind fear of public-speaking and fear of going
to the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   _ While rodents do carry many diseases, contrary to popular
belief, rats are not a common transmitter of rabies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mice are the ``rabbits of the rodent world'' _ a single pair
of mice can produce descendants numbering 15,000 in one year. In
just six months, one pair of mice can deposit as many as 18,000
droppings.Mice have been a pest to man for thousands of years and
they will probably continue to coexist with us for many more. Since
rodents may be able to smell nuclear fallout, they may even outlast
humans.
</P>
<P>
   Source: d-Con
</P>
<P>
   KEEPING CRITTERS OUT
</P>
<P>
   _ Seal up potential entrances to your home _ Using sheet metal,
steel wool or concrete, seal up any holes larger than one-quarter
inch in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Remove items that are potential nesting sites _ Remove stacks
of newspapers, storage and cardboard boxes from
</P>
<P>
   shelves and floors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep high risk areas, such as garages, attics and storage
areas, free of accumulated litter _ Mice are attracted to
undisturbed areas within the house and in and around stored
objects.
</P>
<P>
   _ Food and garbage storage _ Keep all food, water and garbage in
metal or thick plastic containers with tight-fitting lids. Never
leave food and water out overnight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep a clean house _ Wash dishes and cooking utensils, and
clean spilled food from counters and floors immediately. Also,
dispose of any trash and clutter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use rodenticides _ Keep a supply of baits and traps on hand
and use them regularly as a preventative or to stop a little
problem from becoming an infestation. In addition, use
EPA-registered rodenticides, such as bait pellets, on an ongoing
basis inside the home.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Kincheloe writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: akincheloe(AT)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
