<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE-LABOR-$ADV10-COX     10-08 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LABOR-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE FIGHTING TO AVOID A REBUFF AT AFL-CIO CONVENTION
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories for release
Sunday, Oct. 10.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore faces an uphill battle this
week to win the endorsement of the AFL-CIO labor federation and
avoid another blow to his struggling presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign chairman Tony Coelho, scheduled to arrive here
Sunday for last-minute negotiations with the federation's leaders,
said the rules at its convention make it difficult for Gore to win
an endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   A two-thirds vote of the convention's 700 delegates is required.
And while former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Gore's only
opponent for the Democratic presidential nomination, may not have
enough support to win the endorsement himself, he might muster
enough votes to block the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get two-thirds, and all Senator Bradley has to get
is one-third to stop us,'' Coelho said in an interview. ``So the
odds are weighted against us. But we're working hard. We feel
good.''
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO President John Sweeney is reluctant to force an
endorsement on his organization, even though he has sent signals
throughout the year that he favors Gore. His top lieutenant,
Richard Trumka, marched at Gore's side in a Labor Day parade in
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   But Sweeney also is determined not to allow recent electoral
gains by organized labor to be jeopardized by a lackluster effort
in next year's election, which will determine control of both the
White House and Congress, and ultimately the balance on the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   A united front is what the labor leader hopes to achieve when
representatives of the federation's 68 unions gather here Monday
for their three-day convention.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that includes an endorsement of Gore ``boils down to
John Sweeney and whether he will push it through,'' said Mike
Mathis, political director of the teamsters union.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has banked dozens of union endorsements in recent weeks in
an effort to pry an endorsement out of the AFL-CIO. On Friday, he
got the biggest yet from the National Education Association, the
nation's largest teachers' union, with 2.8 million members.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, who has surpassed or pulled even with the vice
president in some state public opinion polls, has furiously lobbied
union leaders to hold off endorsing anyone before the first voting
in Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Some powerful union leaders were already arguing in favor of
delaying the AFL-CIO's endorsement, most notably James P. Hoffa,
president of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa, who began his tenure earlier this year by declaring that
the Teamsters ``will not be an ATM machine for the Democratic
Party,'' has raised concerns that the administration-backed North
American Free Trade Agreement will open the Mexican border next
year to low-wage truckers.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, following a private meeting with Hoffa in New
York on Thursday, promised to prevent any changes in NAFTA trucking
rules until Mexican trucks meet U.S. safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor has largely objected to the free trade policies
of the Clinton-Gore administration. But Bradley, too, is a
free-trader, and his voting record in the Senate on union issues
was virtually the same as Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   It helps Gore with unions that the economy under the Clinton
administration has produced the lowest unemployment in 29 years.
And the administration has delivered on such issues as family
leave, a rise in the minimum wage, education reforms and tax
credits for low-income working families.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gore's lackluster performance thus far in his pursuit of
the 2000 Democratic nomination has given some labor leaders doubts
about bestowing the AFL-CIO's blessing so early in the nominating
process. An endorsement this week would be the earliest the
federation has intervened since 1983, when it backed Walter Mondale
in the midst of a tougher-than-expected primary challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is just too early in the process,'' said
Teamsters spokesman Chip Roth.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO's endorsement would help Gore make the case that his
campaign is rejuvenated, ready for the challenge not only from
Bradley but from Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the GOP
front-runner. For the convention to end without the long-sought
endorsement ``would be a setback'' for the vice president, said
David Axelrod, a Democratic consultant with ties to Gore and the
union federation.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
