<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING: LESSONS AT A SCHOOL WHERE THE WORM CLUB RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 10)  
 (bl)  
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Worms seem unlikely ambassadors for a troubled world,
but they were popular members of the after-school garden club I
helped start last year at Public School 15 _ the Patrick Daly
School, named for the principal who was shot while searching for a
pupil seven years ago _ in Red Hook, Brooklyn. These worms were
teaching us to be good stewards of the earth, until their ecosystem
crashed _ due to their own global warming, I think _ but we're
going to try again.
</P>
<P>
   Our club is small: about 10 kids, fourth- and fifth-graders, and
four grown-ups, though sometimes the grown-ups act like kids and
vice versa. We started out last fall, planting bulbs in the
school's central courtyard, which had a forgotten, overgrown look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to this school, and I never knew this was here,'' said
Enily Mieles, a volunteer for the Americorps program, standing
under the drifty branches of a weeping white birch. We gather here
every Thursday after school to weed, and prune and plant things.
Half the time we just look at stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Like catkins dangling from a hazelnut tree. Or the empty shells
of the nuts discarded by the squirrels that ate half our tulip
bulbs last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that!'' shouted Mercedez Delgado on one clear, chilly
afternoon, opening her arms to a sugar maple ablaze with orange
light. We looked up its name _ ``Acer saccharum'' _ in our tree
book, and noticed how the shape of the leaf is different from that
of A. rubrum, the red maple. Then somebody, who will remain
nameless because he repented, smashed a worm. ``Why did you do
that?'' I asked, deadpan. He shrugged, grinning. His pals giggled.
</P>
<P>
   So, we talked a bit about what earthworms do, like churning and
aerating the soil, and how red worms, another species, could turn
our garbage into gold for the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Desmond Hill rolled his eyes, as if I were kidding, which is his
favorite activity. But the next week, I brought in two pounds of
red worms from the Lower East Side Ecology Center, along the East
River in Manhattan, where worms turn garbage to compost. And that
afternoon, Lower East Side worms began eating Red Hook garbage _
chopped up lettuce, carrots and the like _ and making compost for
our garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we should call ourselves the Worm Club,'' Desmond said,
as we got the worms' habitat ready: shredding newspaper and
sprinkling it with water, tossing it like spaghetti into a rubber
bin about the size of a laundry basket. The worms like it damp, but
not too damp.
</P>
<P>
   We weighed their first meal: old lettuce, coffee grounds,
eggshells, banana peels and cantaloupe rind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worms love melon rind,'' I told them. ``But they don't like
cabbage. It's hard to digest, so it sits in the box and starts to
smell.'' So, it's best to stay away from cabbage and onions, and
meat, of course, which attracts critters other than worms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worms are nasty,'' Mercedez said, giggling happily.
</P>
<P>
   Questions tumbled out: If you cut a worm in half, will it die or
grow into two worms? Do worms have bones? Eyes? Teeth? Blood? How
long do they live? ``Does a worm go through an aging process,''
Jesse Horenstein asked, ``like being a baby, and then a kid, and
then a teen-ager?''
</P>
<P>
   And how do they mate? (Or marinate, as Luiz Miranda asked, which
is apt, because they lie there, two together, with this slime
wrapped around them.) We watched ``Wormania,'' a video made by Mary
Appelhof, a biologist and worm-maniac in Kalamazoo, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could remember the word ``hermaphrodite'' _ something to
do with being male and female at the same time. But if a worm has
both eggs and sperm, why didn't it make its own babies?
</P>
<P>
   Harriet Chichester, the school's science teacher, gave a talk on
genetics. Luiz turned philosophical. ``I think if you made your own
babies, you'd never get to know anybody,'' he said. ``Even if you
went to heaven, you wouldn't know anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's a scary thought. But to get back to the
nitty-gritty, if a pound of worms can eat a half-pound of garbage
in one day, how much can two pounds of worms eat? A wave of math
anxiety washed through the room, until Michael Pagan, staring
solemnly at the ceiling, intoned, ``one pound.'' We weighed out a
pound, and put it in one corner of the bin, which has plenty of air
holes. Then we sprinkled handfuls of worms over the shredded paper
and watched them wriggle away from the light (worms hate light)
toward their first meal.
</P>
<P>
   By then, even Mercedez was holding a worm in her hand. Desmond
named his new friends Kevin, Josh and Frank. However, Ms.
Chichester, who screamed when she first held a worm, asked me to
keep the bin at my house, and to bring it back on Thursdays. Over
the weeks, the kids fed them and looked at them under magnifying
glasses _ to find their ``five hearts,'' or circulation system; the
clitellum, or band through which they exchange sperm; the egg cases
that look like gold beads.
</P>
<P>
   Then, all of a sudden, something went haywire: most of the worms
died. Maybe we gave them too much food, or water, or not enough
newspaper, or maybe my apartment got too hot. So, I dumped them in
the composter in my backyard (where a few survivors have apparently
procreated big time). And this year, we'll try again, with
Christina Datz Romero, the compost queen on the East River, as our
worm coach. It's a can-do club: Luiz says we're going to solve New
York's garbage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   More information on worms and gardening in the schools is
available from the Lower East Side Ecology Center, (212) 420-0621;
Worm Digest, (541) 485-0456 (www.wormdigest .org); Mary Appelhopf,
Flowerfield Enterprises, (616) 327-0108, or the National Gardening
Association, (800) 538-7476. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   THIS WEEK: THINK ABOUT THE NEXT DRY SUMMER
</P>
<P>
   By PATRICIA JONAS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Even a wet fall will not reverse the drought's effects on
foliage. That makes this a perfect time for unsentimental
evaluation: which plants did you water all summer and yet are
bedraggled?
</P>
<P>
   Unless they're at water's edge, fringe tree (Chionanthus
virginicus), sweet pepperbush (Clethra alnifolia) and queen of the
prairie (Filipendula rubra) might not belong in a garden with water
restrictions in summer. Look for plants that tolerated the drought
and thrived, like native bearberry (Arctostaphylos uva-ursi) and
witch hazel (Hamamelis virginiana), rugged Rosa rugosa, hybrid
epimediums and penstemons, and free-flowering bush clover
(Lespedeza thunbergii).
</P>
<P>
   Finish planting trees, shrubs and perennials by October's end,
so that roots can establish before the ground freezes hard. Pull up
spent annuals, but don't dig tender bulbs or tubers for storage
until foliage is blackened by first frost (nutrients are being
stored till then).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
