<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Oct. 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains are possible Saturday over the Ohio, Tennessee and
lower Mississippi valleys as a slowly evolving low pressure system
draws a steady, uninterrupted stream of moist air northward from
the Gulf of Mexico. Given the available moisture and the
sluggishness of the system, the risk of flash flooding will rise in
areas where repeated downpours produce rainfalls in excess of two
inches. Behind the system, clouds will linger across parts of
Oklahoma and northern Texas, with spotty showers and isolated
thunder affecting a few areas.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northeast, dry air will rush eastward on the heels of a
cool front across the eastern Great Lakes into upstate New York and
western New England. The sky will clear during the day, with
clearing eventually commencing along much of the New England
Seaboard as breezes from the west dry on descent from the
Appalachians. Showers with the front will end over Maine before the
sky starts to brighten later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the northern and central Plains will bask in
unseasonable warmth, though a cool front will tamp down
temperatures across eastern Montana and parts of North Dakota.
Behind the cool front, showers will develop over parts of Idaho's
Bitterroot Mountains as relatively moist Pacific winds impinge on
west-facing slopes.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Southwest will be rather hot as a sprawling pool of
warm air centered over the deserts of southern California and
southeast Arizona holds steady. Unseasonable warmth will extend to
the southern California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Copious Rains &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly an inch of rain fell in Colorado Springs on Thursday.
This raised the tally for 1999 to 26.17 inches, exceeding the
previous record for a year of 25.43 inches set in 1965. With nearly
three months remaining, it is certain that this record will
increase. The average annual rainfall is 16.24 inches, based on the
most recent 30 years. This year has been unusually wet in Colorado
Springs for a variety of reasons. Upslope rainstorms have been
frequent as were the late-day thundershowers this past summer. It
will be several days before showers return to this region. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
