<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0953 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     10-08 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERFUL EXPOSE REMINDS US `THE CHILDREN ARE WATCHING'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A quick glance at 17-year-old Miranda shows a sensitive girl
aching for simple goals in life: to be happy and healthy, educated
and successful, to love and be loved. But as ``The Children Are
Watching'' unfolds, little is simple when it comes to her life.
</P>
<P>
   Designed as a kind of ``Scared Straight'' for grown-ups (it's
courtesy of the same producer, Arnold Shapiro), this special
report, airing at 9 p.m. CDT Sunday on PBS, exposes how parents'
bad examples have often-unintentional, but highly destructive,
effects on their children's behavior and life choices.
</P>
<P>
   Four families are featured, and the hand-me-down behavior is
made quite clear as cameras zero in on their everyday lives,
including a five-hour bathroom tussle between a father and teen-age
son over a drug test. Before it's over, there's a huge hole in the
bathroom wall and the son is declaring hatred for the father who
has re-entered his life. ``I want you to die,'' the teen-ager sobs.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with subjects and therapists, along with generic
commentary from narrator Jane Seymour (don't let this throw you off
or lower your expectations), help put the stories in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda, for instance, is a pretty girl disgusted with the
number of men her mother brings home, sleeping with them even after
they've become physically and verbally abusive. Miranda watches
these situations play out like a bad dream from which she can't
awaken. No wonder her teary mother (Nina) is both concerned and
frustrated that her daughter ``has a lot of negative thoughts about
men.''
</P>
<P>
   Which explains why Miranda is in a clingy, self-destructive
relationship with a teen-age boy. Jesse looks nice enough, but in
one scene, Miranda finds drugs and throws him out, even as she
questions whether she can go on living without the guy. He returns,
of course, and resumes his nightly sleepovers in Miranda's bed.
</P>
<P>
   Nina won't object because her daughter is happy when Jesse is
around and suicidal when he isn't. ``She took some scissors and
slashed up her arms the last time he said he'd leave her,'' Nina
says, shaking her head.
</P>
<P>
   But Miranda's choice is a carbon copy of the ones made by her
mother, who is needy, insecure and a terrible judge of character.
We learn that Nina was abused by her mother, who, not surprisingly,
also had a terrible track record in choosing men.
</P>
<P>
   The same mother-to-daughter pattern emerges with 14-year-old
Antonette, who is going through anger therapy to keep from smacking
her younger siblings in fits of rage. But is it her fault she's
been saddled with helping raise them as her parents spend all their
time running the beeper service store they own?
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Vanessa, has her own sordid history. She was sent to
jail on drug charges when Antonette was 2, and after she got out,
resumed a life with many men (there are four other children, most
with different fathers). She talks to them all in an angry, almost
growling tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how she does with me, now,'' Vanessa says of Antonette,
looking disgusted at the thought. ``Even her voice inflections are
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   The special also looks at a well-educated, middle-income family
and how they deal with a father whose aggressive driving and macho
behavior are passed down to his son (the son nearly causes a car
accident while speeding in his new sports car, and then balks at
the thought of atoning for his actions). And it examines what
happens when an estranged father re-enters the life of a son who
spent his formative years with a drugged-out mother. ``I see hatred
in his eyes,'' the father says, almost surprised. Why should he be?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Children Are Watching'' pushes the rather common-sense
notions that our children basically become what we raise them to
become, and that we're not spending enough time with them. And when
we do, their needs are second to our own.
</P>
<P>
   This report puts faces on what will become even more of a
concern as we continue our harried quest to obtain more, bigger,
better, to the detriment of our kids. Yet we're shocked when they
shoot up schools.
</P>
<P>
   Something can be said of parents who work like mad to, they say,
provide for their children, forgetting that time is far more
valuable than a new Ford Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder how many parents actually think about how their
behavior _ from something as simple as handling a dispute in a
retail store to running a red light because no police are around _
is processed by impressionable young minds.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Children Are Watching,'' the adage of actions being louder
than words is serious stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Also worth watching this week:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice'' (9 p.m. CDT Sunday, ABC) _ Well, well. Look
who's back. Judge Kittleson (Emmy winner Holland Taylor) drops her
gavel _ not to mention a few other things _ in a, well, revealing
episode, that also includes threatening notes, illegal handguns and
chloroform. See to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear America: So Far From Home'' (6:30 p.m. CDT Thursday, HBO)
_ Tells the story of Mary Driscoll (Laura Bertram), an 18-year-old
Irish immigrant in 19th-century Massachusetts, where she works at a
textile mill in the hope of earning money to pay for the passage of
her parents. This is another installment of the splendid historical
series for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' (9 p.m. CDT Thursday, NBC) _ Alan Alda arrives for his
guest stint as a newly hired physician with legendary credentials
in emergency medicine. Rebecca De Mornay made her entrance last
week, showing that the producers of TV's No. 1 series aren't
sitting around waiting for the drama to get stale. Good move.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
