<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0954 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-PARIS-FASHION-$ADV10-     10-08 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-$ADV10-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS IN PARIS FASHION: AMERICAN SPORTSWEAR MEETS FRENCH
GLAMOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 10) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Michael Kors' affection for the jet set, whether in Palm
Beach or St.-Tropez, might have produced the most hilariously
atrocious results (tiaras in the afternoon, white mink in the
cabana) if this American designer weren't such a practical dreamer.
</P>
<P>
   In his version of St.-Tropez glamour _ ``Jennifer Lopez meets
Jackie O,'' as he put it before his spring show for Celine on
Thursday _ the ideal woman wears a white denim jacket instead of
mink. But she still has fun. Her mile-high stiletto mules are made
of ultra-tacky Lucite. ``She's got energy, she's got ...'' Kors
said, looking for the right word as he stood amid the preshow chaos
backstage. He seemed to consider a few more buzzwords, then waved
them away. ``Enough with depressing fashion, right?'' he said.
``Time to crank it up!''
</P>
<P>
   So he did, sending out a smart collection of American sportswear
separates enlivened with French glamour. There was Giselle in an
aqua leather jean jacket, a clingy white tank top, and tight denim
pants that looked tie-dyed but were, in fact, bleached. Kors caught
the upbeat, feminine mood sweeping through the French collections,
which end on Saturday, as coolly as Marc Jacobs had in his Louis
Vuitton show. For Kors that might mean cute cashmere tops,
chrome-studded bathing suits and sarong skirts, or maybe a shirt
dress in bleached aqua suede that evoked passing clouds in a summer
sky.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the old Gene Kelly ``American in Paris'' story, but
both Kors and Jacobs have made the most of their deals with LVMH,
the French luxury conglomerate. They have found a way of mixing
their American sensibility for clean sportswear with French kitten
glamour, chiefly by drenching their shows with great, over-the-top
accessories. Kors had the biggest beach bags around. But, as he
said of his Jennifer-meets-Jackie prototype, ``She's not traveling
light.'' In other words, she's still a big spender.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as seven or eight years ago, when Ann Demeulemeester
was making those sensationally plain dresses and aprons that served
as a kind of refuge from 1980s materialism, and Martin Margiela was
projecting a similar bunker mentality through recycled clothes, you
could see how the avant-garde was digging into the establishment.
It was one of those us-against-them things that have always
flowered in Paris. But with this difference: the new style was
coming from Belgians, who hadn't been on anyone's radar.
</P>
<P>
   But now that many of their ideas, like fraying hems and
thrift-shop chic, have been absorbed by the mainstream and no
longer shock, the avant-garde has hit an impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Margiela seemed to be mocking the fashion world's preoccupation
with labels and proportions in his show, presented on Thursday on
round tabletops in a room that looked set up for a Rotarian dinner.
For one thing, he had his models wear the kind of clothes you'd
find in a budget department store _ a loose-fitting men's jacket
over a white cotton shirt, a navy sweatshirt over a white slip, a
haggard-looking trench coat that a guy running for the 5:45 train
to Greenwich might be dragging after him.
</P>
<P>
   For another, the models' shoes all had the heels hacked off, and
some of the clothes had green price stickers or antitheft sensors
on them. Apparently, among young people, walking around with a
plastic sensor hanging from your jacket is considered a status
symbol, announcing that you'd ripped off the system.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was all very amusing to look up at clothes that you
wouldn't pay attention to for half a second if they weren't at a
fashion show. But Margiela's point was too obvious, besides being
heavy with condescension. He needs to think of something new to
say.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Demeulemeester has kept a very individualistic approach, and
her show on Wednesday evening in an old church was beautiful, with
models in white shirts and low-slung trousers that were often
veiled with black tulle. Yet even Ms. Demeulemeester seemed stuck.
Inspired once again by the poetry and style of Patti Smith, she
took lines from a poem that Ms. Smith had recorded for her show's
soundtrack and had them embroidered on the tulle or strips of bias
tape that wrapped around the models' arms.
</P>
<P>
   Between the fragmented lines and Ms. Smith's reading, the show
seemed overwrought with significance. There is scarcely anything
more for Ms. Demeulemeester to say about Ms. Smith's outlaw-poet
style (the white shirt, black pants business) that doesn't
compromise her own integrity. The long black aprons printed with
Jim Dine's black-and-white photographs of birds were a better
marriage of art and fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Prada show, which swept the runway clean of
ruffles and precious adornment, it's been impossible to look at
girlish peasant dresses with gathered necklines without thinking
they look dated. That was the trouble with Peter Speliopoulos'
collection for Cerruti. There were many pretty elements, like short
cotton skirts and sleeveless tops sprouting with embroidered
flowers or striped with rows of buttons or shells. But even though
the Riviera lavenders and greens were enticing and the cuts
feminine, Speliopoulos seemed out of step with fashion's pendulum.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
