<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0958 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RELIGION-AUDREY09-COX     10-08 2188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-AUDREY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audrey Santo: Healer, miracle worker or saint?
 &HT;    By Doug Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ When Linda Santo was pregnant with her fourth
child, she didn't pray her baby would become a doctor or a movie
star or a millionaire. She prayed she would give birth to a saint.
</P>
<P>
   Now she knows how difficult raising a prospective saint can be.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Santo hasn't sat down to a home-cooked meal, played on a
jungle gym or proclaimed, as she often did, ``I'm gorgeous,'' since
she was 3 years old. She has been in bed for 12 years now, with a
feeding tube in her belly and a nurse by her side to make sure she
doesn't choke on her own spit.
</P>
<P>
   In August of 1987, Audrey fell into the pool in her back yard
and floated face down in the water long enough for most of the
cells that formed her consciousness to die. The doctors called it
massive hypoxia. Only her brain stem was left intact.
</P>
<P>
   And while the brain stem keeps her lungs inflating and her heart
pumping, Audrey has, according to Dr. Edward Kaye, the pediatric
neurologist who treated her for six years, probably not had a
conscious thought since she was pulled from the water. And she
probably never will.
</P>
<P>
   Her life is circumscribed by the pink and lace of her bedroom
and dozens of pictures of Jesus and Mary and the Apostles. She is
15, her skin alabaster and unblemished, her long, dark brown hair
carefully gathered at the crest with a white ribbon. Her hazel eyes
move back and forth, seemingly seeing nothing. Her mouth is open,
her tongue lifeless, her brow soft and warm and still.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for the translucent, yellow oil that has been
dripping from religious statues in the Santo home for years, if it
weren't for the blood that appeared on the communion wafer and the
stigmata that have risen like red welts on her hands and feet and
forehead, Audrey Santo would probably be another anonymous file in
a government social welfare cabinet. A sleeping beauty who will
never wake up.
</P>
<P>
   But something is happening at the Santos' _ either very
sophisticated fraud or highly supernatural phenomena. One or the
other, either/or.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people have chosen to believe it is God
working through a little girl. The result: Audrey Santo has been
canonized, if not by Rome, then by the faithful and the desperate
who travel the world seeking miracles from intercessory spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Day in and day out, the pilgrims come to this mostly Jewish
middle-class neighborhood believing the prayers Audrey's mother
sent to heaven 15 years ago were answered.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Santo is a tiny woman _ 4 feet, 11 inches _ and like a lot
of small women, she never seems to stop moving. She tucks her legs
underneath her in an overstuffed arm chair, then rearranges them a
moment later. She begins telling a story, gets up to pick at a
Halloween bowl of candy corn and starts again.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened to her daughter is not so mysterious, really,
Santo explains. God is using Audrey as an instrument to get our
attention. We live in a throwaway society where death is pervasive:
executions, abortions, homicides, suicides. Audrey is telling the
world that, even though she's not a cheerleader or president of the
French Club, she is useful. Her life has meaning. God does not make
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audrey,'' Linda Santo declares with authority, ``makes people
uncomfortable.'' That, in the end, is her destiny.
</P>
<P>
   And if ever a ``victim soul'' were born into an ideal family,
this would be it. Stephen and Linda Santo have four children and a
marriage grounded in faith. It wasn't always that way. Stephen is a
blue-collar worker with a past his neighbors whisper about. After
his youngest daughter's accident, he walked out on all of them. He
returned a few years later, drawn back, he has said, by his wife's
strength. And there is Linda, who once studied to be a nun but
married at 18, and who says of her belief: ``Very Catholic, very,
very Catholic. The whole nine yards.''
</P>
<P>
   There are nominal Catholics, and there are devout Catholics, and
there are Catholics who breathe their Lord. Count Linda Santo among
the latter. Everything in the Santo home speaks to her devotion.
Jesus will never desert Linda Santo _ his likeness is on virtually
every wall, his words embroider almost every pillow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prayed Audrey would be a saint because I can give my child
life, but I couldn't give her eternal life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no self-righteousness to Linda Santo. She may be
a baptized Catholic, but she was born a townie, a product of an old
mill city an hour's drive west of Boston that calls itself
``Woostah'' and revels in the Yankee virtues of provincialism and
self-deprecation.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Santo simply knows what she knows: God is in her house,
and her daughter is in God's hands, on his lap, whispering in his
ear. Proof is not a problem. In a garage transformed into a chapel,
cream-colored walls are stained with the same clear, yellowish oil
that drips from paintings of the Last Supper and the Virgin Mother.
Statues of the crucified Christ have plastic cups attached to them
to capture the oil that flows from his eyes, his ears, his hair.
</P>
<P>
   When Audrey fell into the family's above-ground pool, her mother
screamed in blind panic. Gigi, a sister, flew down the stairs. Her
brother Matthew leapt frantically into the water. Acknowledging the
cynicism and disbelief of the outside world with her smile, Linda
Santo is steadfast in her belief of what happened: Audrey's soul
rose to heaven and she had a job interview with Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew pulled Audrey out of the water. The EMTs resuscitated
her. The doctors drugged her. The therapists massaged her. But
Audrey never regained consciousness. It didn't matter, Linda Santo
says.
</P>
<P>
   Little Audrey had answered yes to God, she would be his child.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic Church is not as sure as Linda Santo. It has
traditionally been slow to acknowledge claims of the supernatural
or even to investigate them for fear of lending credence to the
claims. When the church does investigate, most claims fall apart
under scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, on the 10th anniversary of Audrey's loss of
consciousness, some 5,000 people crowded the football field at Holy
Cross College in Worcester to attend Mass _ and see Audrey, resting
in her specially-made air-conditioned glass box. The miracle on
South Flagg Street could no longer be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Worcester Bishop Daniel Reilly commissioned an investigation.
Released in January after 14 months of study, the church report
says, in part, that Linda Santo is doing God's work by caring for
her daughter with such devotion. It also says there is no evidence
of either miracle or fraud.
</P>
<P>
   A second, more technical and in-depth investigation began a few
months ago, but investigators are not allowed to discuss their work
until they have finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to play the devil's advocate,'' said Worcester
Diocese spokesman Ray Delisle. ``We are not out to deify her, we
are here to dig deeper into this issue and try to account for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, before Audrey could be considered to take a step toward
official sainthood _ which requires the candidate to have been dead
for five years _ it would have to be proven she has some cognitive
powers. To be an intercessor and speak to God on a supplicant's
behalf, she must be aware of the requests, Delisle said.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey's family and friends are certain she is aware of
everything that goes on around her. But proving that to the
satisfaction of the church remains tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kaye, the neurologist who treated her: ``She has very
little cognitive or thought processes. It's a possibility (she can
hear people), but I never saw any evidence that she can.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever is happening in the Santo household started in 1991
when oil started dripping from a painting of Our Lady of Guadalupe.
Panicked, Linda Santo called the Rev. Emmanuel Charles McCarthy, a
family friend whose daughter had overdosed on Tylenol and was saved
by the miraculous intercession of Edith Stein, according to the
church. Stein was later canonized because of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy is an Eastern Rite priest; he has 13 children and the
practicality of fathering a family that large. He's 58 and believes
the paranormal circuit can do as much harm as good. When he arrived
at the Santo home, he pulled the frame off the painting and looked
for any evidence of tampering. He found none.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her if this is from God, he'll let you know. If it's
not, don't worry about it,'' McCarthy said. Despite his own
skepticism, McCarthy _ who has had sinus problems for years _ said
the smell of roses was pervasive. Roses are the sign of Our Lady of
Guadalupe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is that people are going to this house and
they come away not with a yes or a no, but with a good feeling, a
feeling of faith,'' McCarthy said. A few weeks after McCarthy saw
the oil on the painting of Our Lady of Guadalupe, blood appeared on
an image of St. Rita of Cascia at the Santo hom then, one
after another, religious paintings and statues began to weep and
bleed. Eventually, the reports of the supernatural grew to include
virtually everything in the Catholic repertoire: stigmata on
Audrey, bleeding communion wafers, statues moving by themselves,
the Virgin Mary appearing in clouds.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there is the oil _ which has been tested several
times. Published results have varied. Some labs have shown it to be
chicken oil and corn or soybean oil. Others have said it contains
``unidentifiable'' elements.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its content, cotton balls are dipped into it, tucked
into plastic baggies and given to the faithful. Much to the
distress of the church, the oil is often called holy and has been
used to treat everything from cancer to shingles.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, you might say, ``Aha! They sell the oil, the
money trail starts here.'' But no one has been able to document
that any money is passing hands. Books and videos are sold at cost,
and volunteers around the house work for free. A small bucket in
the corner of the garage/chapel accepts donations, which are used
to care for Audrey (the state pays for the nurses).
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors, who have had to deal with traffic for years, are
cynical. Some believe the family is exploiting Audrey for profit.
Others marvel at what they see as the gullibility of the pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess people have so much faith that they can't help
themselves,'' said Bill Kennis, who has lived on South Flagg Street
for 35 years. ``But I'll tell you this, she's not going to cure
cancer. She's not going to cure a broken foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the lines grow. The waiting list is more than a year. A
small bureaucracy has been erected around Audrey. Journalists are
asked if they have any anti-Catholic sentiment before being allowed
to see her. Several have been denied access. But Linda Santo turns
no pilgrim away.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need this,'' she says simply.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the routine was simple: Pilgrims would
arrive, often in buses from out of state, and be taken first to the
chapel, then to a window cut into the wall in Audrey's bedroom. A
blind would be opened, and for five minutes the faithful would
beseech, pray, drop to their knees, rub their rosaries, cry.
Occasionally, the terminally ill were allowed into the bedroom to
touch Audrey.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Audrey is no longer displayed for her public.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were cutting up pieces of the rug, the grass, the
towels, anything to take with them,'' said Mary Cormier, who moved
from New Hampshire two years ago to be a full-time organizer at the
Church of Little Audrey, which is formally called the Apostolate of
a Silent Soul, Inc. ``It just got too much.'' Many are like Valerie
Kroeft, who came from North Carolina to pray for her brother-in-law
in June of 1997 after she heard about Audrey. Her brother-in-law
had had a tumor removed from his brain, and doctors said they
couldn't remove it all. It was malignant, and he surely would die
by Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   There are only two ways to live your life, Albert Einstein once
said. Believing everything is a miracle _ or nothing is. Kroeft and
the tens of thousands who have traveled from as far away as South
America to the Santo home have all chosen to believe in miracles.
</P>
<P>
   Worcester was not a first for Kroeft. She has been to Conyers,
Ga., to hear Nancy Fowler relay messages from the Virgin Mary. She
has been to Jerusalem and seen Jesus walk with the Cross. She has
seen miracles. She has felt God.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have faith, God is going to (take care of) you,''
Kroeft said. ``You have to be open.''
</P>
<P>
   Kroeft's brother-in-law is cancer-free and has survived more
than two years, though he said he isn't sure if God saved him.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Kroeft knows. She said her prayers. She made a
pilgrimage to see Audrey. She has no doubts. It was a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: dougbelkin(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
