<HEADER>
A0960 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RELIGION-GUSHEE09-COX     10-08 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-GUSHEE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Ventura can't wrestle religions to the matBy Steve
Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura claims that organized religion is a sham. As a
former professional wrestler, he knows a great deal about bogus
organizations. But, as governor of Minnesota, he cavalierly
dismisses what is arguably the most powerful force on earth. Still,
he could be right.
</P>
<P>
   By definition, religious belief is a gamble. Organized religions
ask the faithful to bet their lives on the power of a God who
cannot be empirically tested.
</P>
<P>
   But if, as Ventura insists, organized religion is a placebo,
most human history is built on a lie.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the evil done and most of the good that men and women
have accomplished is rooted in religious traditions Ventura
ridicules.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed his disdain for religious institutions in an
interview published in the November issue of Playboy magazine. He
called them a sham and a crutch for weak-minded people.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Ventura joins a long list of characters who have
unwisely dismissed the power of organized religion. Among them,
Karl Marx called it the opiate of the people. Comedian George
Carlin always gets laughs ridiculing the church.
</P>
<P>
   But the naysayers substitute the buffoonery of television
evangelists for the blood-drenched witness of saints.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, religious institutions are often cowardly and
wrong-headed in catering to the very culture their God would
transform. But many, if not most, of the world's great reformers
were unapologetic for their profound religious belief.
</P>
<P>
   The pilgrims bravely sailed to this land to forge a new nation
in which they might practice their faith in an organized manner.
John and Charles Wesley raised the consciousness of 18th-century
England and America to an active concern for the poor. They started
the Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Nobel Peace Prize winner Archbishop Desmond Tutu, the head of an
organized religion in South Africa, was instrumental in defeating
apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. found strength to fight for
civil rights through his belief in the God preached from the
pulpits of organized religion. He and countless others paid with
their lives for a faith Ventura calls a crutch.
</P>
<P>
   Their commitment to the promise of another world gave them the
courage to change this one. They challenged the power structures of
their day through the power of the God Ventura belittles.
</P>
<P>
   Josef Stalin also ridiculed organized religion. Warned against
offending the power of the pope, Stalin cynically asked how many
military divisions the pontiff had at his command.
</P>
<P>
   He had none, of course. But many believe Pope John Paul II was
largely responsible for the downfall of communism in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For him and millions of others, the God of organized religion is
not a crutch but a backbone.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gushee writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: stevegushee(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
