<HEADER>
A0963 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     10-08 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD INTRODUCES DRASTICALLY REDESIGNED TAURUS FOR 2000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a case of back-to-the-drawing-board for vehicle designers
at Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   The result: a drastically redesigned Ford Taurus for 2000, part
of an all-out effort to recapture the momentum this car lost when
it received a radical redesign in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   You might recall that until the redesign, the Taurus was
America's best-selling car, an honor the vehicle had won several
years in a row. The original Taurus, introduced in the mid-80s, had
a cutting-edge design for the U.S. market, with its flying-wedge
shape (not original, but borrowed from an Audi sedan).
</P>
<P>
   That design worked for more than a decade. Taurus dominated the
midsize sedan segment, beating out challenges from the Honda Accord
and Toyota Camry. General Motors never came close with its midsize
products, including the like-sized and like-priced Chevrolet
Lumina.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, Ford redesigned the Taurus, giving it another
cutting-edge look, almost like something from another planet.
Accented by a strange oval rear window that decreased rearward
visibility and rear-seat head room, the car's popularity dropped.
</P>
<P>
   People either loved it or hated it; there appeared to be no
in-between. Many stalwart Taurus owners of the past, people who for
the most part aren't into radical changes in their lives, stood
back and blinked at the new design and bought something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taurus owners are the quintessential good neighbors, people
who pay their bills on time,'' Rick Crossland, brand manager for
the new Taurus, said at a recent media program to introduce the
2000 model. As salt-of-the-earth folks, they really aren't into
anything radical.
</P>
<P>
   To come up with the latest design, which looks modern but not
radically so, Ford asked former Taurus owners and other potential
buyers in focus groups what they would like to see changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `How do we need to change the car to appeal to you?'
said Dave Marinaro, chief program engineer for the 2000 model.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting product, which does away with the oval rear window
(which actually underwent an emergency modification for 1998 to
make it much-less radical looking), comes closer to the marketing
goal for cars that are intended to sell in high volume. They
``delight the few and attract the many,'' said George Murphy,
Ford's general marketing manager. He believes the new Taurus will
delight more than a few, however, on its way toward attracting the
many.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the current Taurus hasn't led the midsize
segment, it hasn't been a slouch in the marketplace. It's No. 3
behind the Camry and the Accord, and it posted its best August
sales in the brand's history this year, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford plans a December launch for the 2000 Taurus, which goes
into production next month. Prices haven't been announced yet, but
expect to see them almost identical to last year's. For 1999, base
prices ranged from $17,560 to $19,560.
</P>
<P>
   Although underneath, the 2000 Taurus is still much the same,
there are 900 new parts. ``We touched nearly every piece of the
car,'' Marinaro said.
</P>
<P>
   On the outside, the only parts that carry over from 1999 are the
windshield and the doors.
</P>
<P>
   Changes include larger headlights and a wider grille opening; a
higher and wider rear deck lid, with larger taillights; and a
traditional rectangular rear window.
</P>
<P>
   Body-panel revisions have made the car look bigger, but it's
more than an illusion. The car is taller and wider than before, and
it sits on larger wheels and tires (16 inch wheels are standard).
Rear head room has increased 1.9 inches, and front head room is up
nearly an inch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective for the surface detailing was simplicity and a
straightforward nature,'' according to Ford press literature
describing the changes.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, there are new seats, a new instrument panel, new door
panels with six map pockets, and redesigned consoles. The car can
seat five or six people, depending on whether the front seat is a
bench or two buckets. The rear seat comfortably holds two adults
and a child, or three children.
</P>
<P>
   A first for a passenger car are the power-adjustable brake and
accelerator pedals. If you have short legs, you won't have to scoot
the seat up toward the dashboard just to reach the pedals. With a
push of a button, the pedals can be raised to bring them closer to
your feet. Ford also has introduced this feature on some of its new
sport-utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The changes aren't all visual. The car has been redesigned to be
safer than before (even though last year's model was the only sedan
under $20,000 to earn a top five-star rating in both frontal- and
side-impact crash tests).
</P>
<P>
   Front air bags are standard, but optional side air bags are
offered to help protect the driver and front passenger in a
side-impact crash. This is an option previously offered only on
luxury cars.
</P>
<P>
   There is an emergency trunk release inside the trunk, so anyone
who is accidentally (or otherwise) trapped in there can get out
without help. Energy-absorbing interior trim helps lessen injury
during a crash, and the armrests are designed to collapse in a side
impact to absorb energy and protect the occupants. Child-seat
tether anchors are provided above the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   The new Taurus comes in two trim levels: the base LX and the
uplevel SE. There also is a wagon version, offered only in the SE
trim.
</P>
<P>
   The base engine is a 3.0-liter Vulcan V-6 with the standard two
valves per cylinder, rated at 155 horsepower and 185 foot-pounds of
torque. That's up from 145 horsepower and 170 foot-pounds of torque
last year.
</P>
<P>
   To boost performance, consumers can choose the optional
3.0-liter Duratec engine, which uses four valves per cylinder to
crank out 200 horsepower and 200 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   Standard is a four-speed automatic transmission with overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the Taurus is fun. It feels rather sporty for a family
sedan when equipped with the Duratec engine, and the car has a
solid feel in tight turns on curvy roads. Ride is smooth and comfy,
but not overly cushy. Steering response is excellent, which gives
the driver a good sense of control.
</P>
<P>
   The trunk is larger and has a more usable shape. And in keeping
with the vehicle's intended use as a family car, Ford has installed
hooks inside the trunk to hang plastic grocery bags on so the
groceries don't spill all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 17 miles per gallon in the city and
26 mpg on the highway for the Duratec engine, and 20 mpg city/28
highway for the base engine. The tank holds 16 gallons of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is transportation writer and
automotive columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Contact him
at 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76022; telephone
(817) 685-3810; e-mail chambers(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FELICIA-FILM-REVIEW-7     10-08 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELICIA-FILM-REVIEW-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FELICIA'S JOURNEY': A SURREAL AND SUBTLE THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(lb) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To call Atom Egoyan's surreally atmospheric screen
adaptation of William Trevor's novel ``Felicia's Journey'' a genre
movie would be a little like describing ``Moby-Dick'' as a fishing
manual.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Trevor's insidious thriller about a lost Irish
girl adrift in England's industrial Midlands and the homicidal
catering manager who ``rescues'' her has epic pretensions. It's
that Egoyan, Canada's most gifted filmmaker, brilliantly bends this
Gothic-flavored fable to express his own tricky cinematic vision.
</P>
<P>
   That vision, to put it a bit grandly, is the contemplation of
human fate in a universe that throws out tantalizing portents of
meaning and purpose while paradoxically appearing to be absurd.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of Felicia (Elaine Cassidy), a young woman who
travels across the Irish Sea in search of the man who impregnated
her, and Joseph Hilditch (Bob Hoskins), a stout, beady-eyed
bachelor whose head swirls with '50s pop kitsch, represents a
bizarre collision of two self-enclosed universes.
</P>
<P>
   Felicia's world, which we glimpse in flashbacks (the movie is
continually roaming around in time), is a dreary working-class
existence redeemed by her schoolgirl passion and her naive faith in
a lover who departed without leaving an address.
</P>
<P>
   In her quest to find him (she mistakenly believes he works in a
lawn-mower factory), Felicia suggests a modern-day equivalent of
one of Thomas Hardy's solitary pilgrims traipsing across a
magnificently bleak industrial landscape. Ms. Cassidy captures the
character's youth and determination with a convincing mixture of
vulnerability, blankness and a kind of stubborn radiance.
</P>
<P>
   Where Felicia's emotional world is defined by mournful Irish
ballads and by Kate Bush's throbbing recording of ``The Sensual
World,'' Hilditch surrounds himself with the syrup of Mantovani and
tinny sentimental ballads like ``My Special Angel,'' a song that
assumes a creepy resonance as the movie goes along.
</P>
<P>
   A fastidious head chef in a factory, Hilditch returns each night
to his large empty house with its gigantic, gadget-filled kitchen.
Here he prepares elaborate gourmet meals under the videotaped
supervision of his dead mother, Gala (Arsinee Khanjian), who used
to be the host of a French cooking show and whose programs he
reruns obsessively while cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Egoyan directs these scenes for a slightly ghoulish, campy
comedy. The music is garishly tacky, and the cooking show a funny
parody of '50s-style ersatz French chic. In video flashbacks, we
see the chubby preadolescent Hilditch dragged onto the program by
his unflappably ebullient mother, who dispatches him on minor
chores (which he invariably muffs) and feeds him morsels (which
make him gag.)
</P>
<P>
   Here and elsewhere (especially a startling moment in which
Hilditch gazes conspiratorially into the camera), we have the
feeling of being toyed with in the same way Alfred Hitchcock
delighted in tweaking film audiences with little pranks.
</P>
<P>
   As Hilditch, Hoskins _ who has specialized in crude, ruddy-faced
blokes _ reins in his bluster to give a remarkably restrained and
compassionate portrayal of a repressed middle-aged mama's boy with
a streak of psychopathic violence.
</P>
<P>
   When he first encounters Felicia in a chance meeting in his
small green car, he appears to be a good Samaritan helping out a
woman in distress. But even here, there are subtle warning signals:
The character is a little too intent, a little too carefully
spoken.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, like the book, teases us by withholding information.
It isn't for a while that we learn Felicia is not only lovelorn but
pregnant. Although we suspect that Hilditch may be up to no good,
his violent history is leaked only gradually. Videotaped fragments
(they're either memories or actual tapes, the movie doesn't say) of
conversations in his green car with grateful young women he has
befriended and helped begin punctuating his thoughts. As their
gratitude shades into terror, it becomes clear that they are his
murder victims. But the movie never shows his actual crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the story threatens to turn into a predictable
cat-and-mouse game in which Hilditch lures the innocent Felicia
into a lethal trap, the movie throws in a Bible-thumping
missionary, Miss Calligary (Claire Benedict), who shelters Felicia
after she has been robbed.
</P>
<P>
   At first Miss Calligary appears to be a stock movie caricature
of an obnoxious religious proselytizer. But in the film's
transcendent final scenes, she appears as a vehicle of fate,
another rescuer, whose disturbing mixture of the crazy and the
benign mirrors that of Hilditch.
</P>
<P>
   In exploring notions of fate, chance, coincidence and timing in
people's lives, ``Felicia's Journey'' has many of the same
preoccupations as ``The Sweet Hereafter,'' Egoyan's 1997
masterpiece, which examined the reactions of a tightly knit
community to a tragic school-bus accident that took the lives of
many of the town's children. Burrowing into the town's grieving
soul, ``The Sweet Hereafter'' posed deep, anguished questions about
blame and liability, faith and causality in human affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicia's Journey,'' which closes the New York Film Festival
on Sunday evening, is a smaller film, restricted by its genre and
by the limitations of its two main characters. Neither the
tight-lipped Felicia, who is locked in her own romantic dreams, nor
Hilditch (who may not even remember his crimes) is emotionally
accessible in conventional screen terms. That's one reason the
movie occasionally loses its grip and appears to be an immensely
clever exercise in genre expansion.
</P>
<P>
   But once viewed, ``Felicia's Journey,'' like most of Egoyan's
mature work, is hard to forget. Visually and in its soundtrack of
overlapping voices, the film sustains a mood of heightened
consciousness, implying a world of surreal, only half-discernible
connections in which weather, music, landscape, media and the
chance encounters of strangers all suggest an enticing, if slightly
ominous sense of a grand design.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FELICIA'S JOURNEY'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Atom Egoyan; based on the novel by
William Trevor; director of photography, Paul Sarossy; edited by
Susan Shipton; music by Mychael Danna; production designer, Jim
Clay; produced by Bruce Davey; released by Artisan Entertainment.
Running time: 116 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Elaine Cassidy (Felicia), Bob Hoskins (Joseph Ambrose
Hilditch), Claire Benedict (Miss Calligary), Brid Brennan (Mrs.
Lysaght), Arsinee Khanjian (Gala) and Peter McDonald (Johnny
Lysaght).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
