<HEADER>
A0968 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CAR-SMART-VOLKSWAGEN-     10-08 0351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-VOLKSWAGEN-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `PEOPLE'S CAR' FOR A NEW CLASS OF PEOPLE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM DIEM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Volkswagen won't be keeping many manufacturing secrets when it
begins making a new luxury car late next year. The factory in
downtown Dresden, Germany, will have walls of glass, allowing
customers and passers-by to watch the cars being built.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has VW hidden its ambitions. As along ago as June 1997, the
company's chairman, Ferdinand Piech, talked publicly about his plan
to build a high-end Volkswagen in addition to the Audi line of
luxury cars. Many people thought he was dreaming, but even as he
spoke Mark Lichte was at work on the design.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started on this project from the first day on the job two
and a half years ago,'' Lichte said as he hovered over the Concept
D, a show-car version of his baby that was unveiled at the auto
show here last month.
</P>
<P>
   The production version does not yet have a name. Concept D
alludes to the ``D segment'' of the German market, comprising large
cars like the Mercedes-Benz S-Class. Unusual for that class, the
Concept D has a fastback shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the history of VW there are a lot of fastbacks,'' Lichte
said, ``but there are none in the D class. We thought to have an
alternative.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The all-wheel-drive car will have a 5-liter, turbo-diesel V10
engine rated at 313 horsepower. Volkswagen said it might offer
other engines, including a new 12-cylinder gasoline engine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People no longer think Piech is dreaming. Last year, VW bought
control of the Bugatti, Lamborghini and Bentley brands. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``VW is probably the only volume manufacturer that could pull
this off cost-effectively,'' said Simon Miller, an automotive
analyst with Credit Lyonnais in London. ``It also has a
quasi-premium brand status that it has built up over the last 10
years or so.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VW executives say the new car will be exported to North America;
the factory can build 40,000 a year. The price is expected to
undercut the Mercedes-Benz S-Class, which starts around $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
