<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0969 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-MANAGERS-2TAK     10-08 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-MANAGERS-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIMMING AGAINST AN EBB TIDE 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass., Md., N.C., Ga.)   (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a lackluster, disappointing third quarter for most mutual
funds, but there were notable exceptions _ many of them helped by
investments in innovative companies in the telecommunications,
semiconductor and biotechnology industries.
</P>
<P>
   And smaller growth stocks in general outpaced bigger,
value-oriented issues in the three months ended Sept. 30, helping
those funds that tilted in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   Here, stock-pickers of three top-performing funds for the
quarter look back at what made their funds such standouts _ and
offer a glance ahead. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Disciple of Growth &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New technology created the winners in the $145.2 million Strong
Enterprise fund, a mid-cap growth fund. It returned 19.5 percent
for the quarter, taking the No. 1 place among domestic diversified
equity funds. ``We try to identify the leading companies in rapidly
growing industries,'' said its manager, Andrew S. Cupps, 29,
``companies that can capitalize on opportunities in a changing
world.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his biggest winners was Sandisk of Sunnyvale, Calif.,
which makes what is in effect the film used in digital cameras _
the chips on which images are stored. Two million digital cameras
have been sold since their commercial introduction in 1998, said
Cupps, adding that sales of 28 million units are forecast for 2002
_ ``and every one goes out with a Sandisk chip.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, he added, also makes chips that enable portable
music players like the next-generation Sony Walkman _ due in
January _ to play music downloaded from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no market at all for these several months ago,''
Cupps said, ``and now they should sell several million units.''
Sandisk, whose stock rose 44.9 percent in the quarter, also makes
chips that are built into personal digital assistants designed by
Compaq Computer and Hewlett-Packard, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another winning stock was Broadvision, of Redwood City, Calif.,
a maker of software for companies doing business on the Internet.
Its stock rose 80.4 percent in the quarter. Broadvision software
lets companies like American Airlines offer personalized Web sites,
Cupps said, by helping them identify individual customers and then
offering special deals geared to their spending patterns.
</P>
<P>
   He also made money in Millennium Pharmaceuticals, a
biotechnology company in Cambridge, Mass., that specializes in
genomics. Its stock rose 80.6 percent in the quarter. The company's
research on human genes ``can help pharmaceutical companies
discover drugs more quickly and in a more targeted fashion,'' Cupps
said. Millennium is currently focusing on the genetic roots of
obesity.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, he remains optimistic. ``A small group of big
technology stocks and next-generation stocks have been very strong,
but a whole generation of software stocks are down because of Y2K
and other concerns.'' he said, adding that the market could resume
its upward move ``if the economy slows down, and there's some
indication that this is happening.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Monster Bet on Chips &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How did the $265.1 million Northstar Special fund, a small
growth fund, earn its No. 5 place among domestic diversified equity
funds for the quarter? Through investments in semiconductor stocks,
which made up 20 percent of the fund's portfolio, and contributed
mightiliy to its 17.4 percent return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Semiconductor companies are secular growth vehicles that went
through a slowdown last year, partly because of the Asian crisis
and global recession, and began to come out of it this spring,''
said the fund's manager, Mary Lisanti, 43. ``What's helping now is
the strong demand for personal computers because of the Internet,
cheap PC pricing and personal digital assistants.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of her biggest winners was PMC-Sierra, a Burnaby, British
Columbia, manufacturer of semiconductors used in telecommunications
equipment; its stock rose 56.9 percent. The company is highly
profitable and is ``always considered one of the class acts in the
business,'' Ms. Lisanti said, adding that it weathered the recent
downturn better than most of its competitors did. ``It's a
value-added player as opposed to a commodity provider,'' she said,
due to the specialized nature of its chips.
</P>
<P>
   Another hit was Harmonic Inc., a Sunnyvale, Calif., company that
makes fiber optic systems for delivering voice, data and video over
cable satellites and wireless networks. The company, whose stock
rose 127.7 percent in the quarter, uses a technology called wave
division multiplexing that lets it expand fiber capacity by
splitting light waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows you to make a 2-lane road into a 10-lane road,'' Ms.
Lisanti said.
</P>
<P>
   She also made money in Applied Micro Circuits, a San Diego
designer and maker of semiconductors used in broadband
communications. ``It has leading-edge chip-manufacturing technology
that it developed for the military, which always sent tons of data
around the world,'' she said. ``Now they're producing it
commercially at a competitive cost.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock rose 38.6 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   What's ahead for the market? ``This year is the exact opposite
of last year, when you wanted to own the big safe havens,'' Ms.
Lisanti said. ``Now you want the opposite _ more industrially
oriented companies, to benefit from the economic recovery
overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   She expects an inflation rate in the 2 percent to 3 percent
range through year-end and long-term interest rates of 6 percent to
7 percent. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thinking Small, Really Small &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to identify the most dynamic companies in the microcap
universe that are also exhibiting above-average relative price
strength,'' said Tom Callan, 39, co-manager with Bill Wykle, 62, of
the $141.9 million Blackrock Microcap Equity Portfolio. In the
third quarter, he found those stocks among emerging biotechnology
and wireless communications companies.
</P>
<P>
   The fund returned 17.7 percent in the quarter, earning it the
No. 4 place among domestic diversified equity funds.
</P>
<P>
   Among his biggest winners was United Therapeutics, a
biotechnology company in Silver Spring, Md., that produces UT-15, a
new version of a hypertension drug. UT-15 is administered
intravenously, using a tiny portable pump instead of the awkward
refrigeration unit that its predecessor required, Callan said.
``It's a big step up in ease of delivery,'' he added. He originally
bought shares in the June initial public offering. The stock was up
143.2 percent for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   He also made money in Trimeris, a Durham, N.C., company that is
developing a new class of AIDS drug, called T-20, that blocks the
HIV virus from entering T-cells, Callan said, adding that it can be
used when combination therapies and protease inhibitors are
ineffective. The stock was up 15.1 percent for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Another winner was Price Communications, a New York company that
provides wireless service, mainly in Georgia and the rural South,
and which benefited from accelerating growth in its number of
subscribers. ``The average revenue per user has remained stable,
even though rates have dropped dramatically across the board,''
added Michael Carey, 30, senior analyst on the fund. The stock rose
75.4 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, ``the market is trying to find a new level of
equilibrium,'' Callan said. He is cautiously upbeat. ``In the
best-case scenario,'' he said, ``third-quarter earnings, which
should be strong, will dominate the news and that should lead a
rally through year-end.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
