u s BC-FBN-49ERS-FOOD-NYTR &LR;      10-08 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-FOOD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 49ERS TRADITION: WINNING THROUGH EATING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEVIN LYNCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Pizza in the afternoon smells like ...
victory.
</P>
<P>
   And the wafting aroma of catered barbecue lunches elicit the
warm glow of winning.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, football fans, the way to a football team is through its
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it? Just ask the 49ers, who have developed a
culinary reward/punishment system that puts old Pavlov to shame.
When the team wins, players can anticipate a week of Epicurean
delights and positive reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
   But after a loss? Well, there haven't been many losses in the
past decade or so. When they do happen, the week is bleak: no food,
no fun, just work.
</P>
<P>
   It's just possible that the San Francisco 49ers manage to stay
successful year after year in part because they've surrounded
themselves with routines and traditions that kick in only after a
win.
</P>
<P>
   This year, those conventions may have helped steady the 49ers'
ship after a horrendous start. The 49ers were thumped in their
opener, 41-3 by Jacksonville, which seemed to confirm the preseason
predictions of the dynasty's demise.
</P>
<P>
   However, the team rattled off three straight wins, yet again
affirming the 49er legend. While other teams flounder after serious
injuries, San Francisco keeps going. The 49ers started the season
with their 1,570-yard rusher from last season, Garrison Hearst, on
the bench. Then they played without quarterback Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams, like Atlanta and Denver, are a combined 0-8 without
their established offensive threats. The 49ers are 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   How do they do it? Some might say it's because of winning
tradition, veteran leadership and consistently unbeatable game
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The real reason?
</P>
<P>
   Food.
</P>
<P>
   Pizza is trucked in Monday following wins. Players mill around
the large square boxes in their lounge just off the locker room.
Eyes get big and stomachs are filled as players pop open the boxes
and indulge in their victory pie.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers also have a midweek tradition of catered barbecue
suppers after Thursday practice. The silver trays of slathered ribs
and chicken are displayed on red-clothed tables. The meals are
replete with rolls, corn bread, cole slaw, salad and fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest payoff occurs Saturday night when the team gathers
at a hotel, whether home or away. Cartons of ice cream are broken
out along with chicken, hamburgers and pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches then award T-shirts for special teams' exploits. The
``hammer'' shirt goes to the special teams' player who recorded a
big hit. The ``Gut Buster'' shirt is for the special teams' player
who exhibited exceptional hustle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good for team chemistry,'' said cornerback
Darnell Walker. ``It helps us jell.'' The club then settles in for
a video presentation pieced together by head coach Steve Mariucci
and the organization's video crew of Keith and Robbie Yanagi.
</P>
<P>
   Video of the previous week's network broadcast are spliced with
clips from movies for humorous effect. Terrell Owens pounded his
chest after snaring a touchdown pass in the 49ers first win of the
season, a 28-21 defeat of New Orleans. His move was captured on
video and then quickly followed by an old clip of Tarzan beating
his chest.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers were playing the Cardinals that week, so the video
ended with scenes from the remake of the Alfred Hitchcock movie
``The Birds.'' It showed birds exploding in mid-air.
</P>
<P>
   The food rewards might seem a bit obvious, but hey, it works.
It's all part of the culture of winning exuded by the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are always sore and grumpy,'' said Mariucci, who
instituted the video gimmick. ``There's expectations and there's
ups and downs. Somewhere along the line you got to enjoy the
journey ... When we show that film, they are just bouncing off the
walls. It's good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers win enough that the victory traditions are routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can cause some domestic disputes,'' joked guard Ray Brown.
He said his wife rarely fixes dinner on Thursday because she knows
her husband has his barbecue at the team facility.
</P>
<P>
   During a losing week, Brown has arrived home to an empty house
and no dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The Thursday spread cuts both ways _ reward and pain. That's
because one player or a group of players has to pick up the $3,000
tab.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's expensive,'' said Brown, who picked up the bill for a
supper last year. ``And if no one volunteers, then coach (Mariucci)
will pick someone. But, hey, you got to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Rosa, Calif., Press Democrat is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
