<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-PORTFOLIOS-ART-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM FIVE RETIREMENT PORTFOLIOS, ANOTHER VOTE FOR DIVERSIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of how the five stocks pickers are doing is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A volatile stock market was particularly punishing to big growth
stocks and value issues in the third quarter, while many small
stocks and overseas investments fared better. That gave an edge to
investors with diversified portfolios, including the five money
managers who have assembled hypothetical retirement portfolios for
The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Though all five portfolios lost ground over the three months,
each beat the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, a benchmark that
has largely been unbeatable in the last few years but that lost
6.25 percent in the quarter. By contrast, the average diversified
domestic equity fund tracked by Lipper Inc. lost 5.37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The winning manager for the quarter was Jack A. Brill, a San
Diego investment adviser who has built a ``socially responsible''
portfolio. Over all, he lost 2.13 percent. His two stakes that held
up best were MMA Praxis International, which rose 5.48 percent, and
IPS Millennium, a growth-and-income fund, up 5.05 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe it is more important than ever for long-term
investors to be well-diversified in stock size and across mutual
fund style,'' Brill said. And he does not expect the market to
stabilize anytime soon. ``As we get closer to year-end and
potential Y2K problems,'' he said, referring to widespread concerns
that some computers will malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, ``we may very
well see a continuation of third-quarter action into the fourth
quarter, with continuing high volatility.''
</P>
<P>
   For more diversification, he is trimming his position in Ariel
Appreciation, which owns small- and mid-cap value stocks, to 10
percent from 15 percent, and using the proceeds to increase his
stakes in two index funds, Domini Social Equity and Citizens Index,
to 15 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the managers' hypothetical portfolios is
tracked each quarter by Lipper, of Summit, N.J. Figures exclude
sales charges, transaction costs and taxes because most retirement
money is held in tax-deferred accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The five managers may choose any funds open to new investors and
may shift money quarterly. From the outset of the competition, in
July 1993, they were asked to pick portfolios intended to grow for
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Jacobs, who edits the No-Load Fund Investor in
Irvington, N.Y., retains the overall lead among the five managers,
with a gain of 144.6 percent since the contest began.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, the five portfolios have risen an average of
123.92 percent, compared with a 228.74 percent return for the
Vanguard 500 Index fund, which mimics the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, Susan Dziubinski, who edits the Morningstar
Fund Investor, placed second, with a loss of 2.31 percent. She was
helped largely by international holdings _ Founders Passport, which
rose 6.92 percent, and EuroPacific Growth, up 5.74 percent. ``Just
a year ago, people were asking why they should bother with
international investing,'' she said. ``Here's why: International
investing is alive and kicking, thanks to the long-beleaguered but
now-reviving Japan and rebounding emerging markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dziubinski also held the fund that performed best in the
quarter among those held by the five managers: Oppenheimer Real
Asset, which owns commodity-linked investments and which gained
16.69 percent. ``It won't give consistent overperformance _ more
fits and starts,'' she said. ``But as a portfolio hedge, it seems
to be working fine for me. Over the long term, it should help to
smooth out the bumps in the portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   She is selling her stake in Founders Passport, she said, because
the fund's manager, Michael W. Gerding, left in July. She is using
the proceeds to increase her holdings in a core position, TIAA-CREF
Growth and Income, to 30 percent from 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Eric M. Kobren, president of Kobren Insight Group and editor of
Fidelity Insight in Wellesley, Mass., came in third for the
quarter. His all-Fidelity portfolio lost 3.47 percent. As did Ms.
Dziubinski, Kobren benefited from investment overseas: One of his
funds, Fidelity International Value, gained 6.43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   His big loser was Fidelity Value, down 11.18 percent. But he
plans to stay with the fund. ``The setback could be attributed to
cyclicals moving too far, too fast, in April and May,'' he said.
``At this point, we believe the value correction has run its
course, and Fidelity Value remains very well poised to profit from
the continuing strong economy and potential rising commodity
prices.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is reducing his position in Fidelity Contrafund II to 15
percent, from 25 percent, and using the proceeds to start a 10
percent position in Fidelity Aggressive Growth. The manager of that
fund, Erin Sullivan, ``has proven to be very adept at maneuvering
in the volatile high-tech and health care arenas,'' he said. ``But
we've been even more impressed by the controlled losses this fund
has sustained during the inevitable dips.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold R. Evensky, an investment adviser in Coral Gables, Fla.,
took fourth place for the quarter, with a loss of 4.87 percent. He
was hurt by his stakes in Matthews Pacific Tiger, an
emerging-markets fund, down 13.49 percent, and Vanguard Value
Index, a growth-and-income fund, down 9.24 percent. But he plans no
changes in his portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``My managers in the international developed, small-cap growth
and value sectors continue to outperform the S&AMP;P 500,'' he said.
``Unfortunately, the same can't be said for the recent high-flying
emerging markets. Still, the game plan is to manage risk as well as
return.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs finished last in the quarter, with a loss of 5.17
percent. He is dropping two laggards, Vanguard Windsor II and Baron
Growth (each 10 percent of his portfolio), and starting a 15
percent position in Janus Olympus and a 5 percent position in T.
Rowe Price Science and Technology. The changes shift his exposure
toward large cap-growth and technology stocks and away from smaller
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although certain small-cap funds have done quite well
recently, small-cap indexes such as the Russell have performed only
as well as the S&AMP;P 500 in the third quarter,'' Jacobs said. ``And
if we do get a major correction or bear market, the small caps will
decline more than the large caps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
