<HEADER>
A0974 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-UGA-VOLS09-COX     10-08 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-UGA-VOLS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulldogs look to end 'The Streak'
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Georgia has done its best to play down its
current losing streak to Tennessee. But the Bulldogs' eight
consecutive losses to the Vols have been brought up to them
continuously _ and not just this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm aware of (the losing streak),'' Georgia quarterback
Quincy Carter said glumly. ``Our fans remind us of it every
offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10th-ranked Bulldogs (4-0, 2-0 SEC) will do their best to
reverse their fortunes tonight when they meet No. 6 Tennessee (3-1,
1-1) in a nationally televised game played before 107,000 at
Neyland Stadium. Even though Georgia is undefeated and in first
place in the SEC's Eastern Division, Tennessee is favored by 11
points.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bulldogs lose tonight, it will be their longest losing
streak against any team in their 107-year history. Despite such
external pressures, Georgia seems a relatively loose bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be scared against Tennessee; the flight's already
booked,'' junior Jonas Jennings cracked.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time Georgia has taken a 4-0 team against
the Vols. The Bulldogs have been 4-0 each of the last two times
they faced Tennessee. The Vols won each of those contests handily,
38-13 in Knoxville in '97 and 22-3 last year in Athens
</P>
<P>
   But after consecutive one-point wins over Central Florida and
LSU, the Bulldogs come here with a considerable amount of humility.
And Georgia coach Jim Donnan sees the attitude as a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Bulldogs were undefeated and sky high coming off
a 28-27 upset of sixth-ranked LSU in Baton Rouge. Meanwhile,
Tennessee had lost starting tailback Jamal Lewis to a season-ending
knee injury the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we spent a little too much time letting people
congratulate us, rather than thinking about what we had to do to
win the game,'' Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the defending national champions had their 14-game
winning streak ended by Florida 23-21 on Sept. 18 in Gainesville,
and they needed a long pass play in the final minute to defeat
Memphis 17-16 a week later. However, Tennessee appeared to get its
offense untracked in a 24-0 win over Auburn last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been perfect and they haven't been perfect,''
Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer said. ``I don't know of anybody who
has. Georgia's been good enough to be 4-0, and that's good
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The game has several subplots. Three of the Vols' star players _
Cosey Coleman, Deon Grant and Jamal Lewis _ are Georgians. Two
coaches, Rodney Garner and Kevin Ramsey, defected from the
Volunteers to join Georgia's staff the last two years. An academic
fraud controversy hovers over Tennessee, a story broken by ESPN,
which is televising the game.
</P>
<P>
   And the two head coaches have been cool to each other since
Donnan accused Fulmer of running up the score two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the main story line is the one that involves the
Southeastern Conference Championship. With Florida and Tennessee
already having lost in the conference, a Bulldog victory would push
them a long way toward their first SEC title since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to be in the SEC championship picture, this is a
critical game for us,'' Garner said. ``It's going to be no place
for the mild or the meek. It's going to be a war.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
