<HEADER>
A0977 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-PARIS09-COX     10-08 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PARIS09-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Karl Lagerfeld a innovator for Chanel, not a follower
</P>
<P>
   By A. Scott Walton
</P>
<P>
   FASHION EDITOR
</P>
<P>
   Paris _ Fashion Week began winding down to a close here on
Friday, with two of this city's most formidable designers
punctuating the most popular trends for spring/summer 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In each of their shows, Chanel's Karl Lagerfeld and Christian
Lacroix sent out clothes in a rich range of colors and wide
assortment of shapely silhouettes. But that's where the
similarities between their collections end.
</P>
<P>
   Lagerfeld's themes were stylish, sexy, and, by this city's
standards, sensible. Lacroix's looks, on the other hand, were
indecipherably complex.
</P>
<P>
   Though he's far passed the point of having to prove his creative
prowess, Lagerfeld still strives to make strong statements. Friday,
the German-born genius flaunted the financial might that allowed
him to employ nearly 100 models and staged a fast-paced preview
that featured a medley of R&AMP;B music. The chorus of the soundtrack
was the James Brown lyric Lagerfeld could justifiably sing himself:
``I've got soul, and I'm super bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Some designers are hired to maintain the status quo for a design
house; but Lagerfeld, always an innovator, this year shredded the
Chanel suit's mystique. The items in this collection invoked the
spirit of things being separate, but equal.
</P>
<P>
   Lagerfeld left no doubt that quilted stretch synthetics can
carry as much weight in a woman's wardrobe as quirky snakeskins;
that knee-length skirts matter as much as ankle-grazing pants; that
floral prints are as important as solids; and that accessories are
as key to being well-dressed as coats.
</P>
<P>
   The floral prints _ rendered in chiffon, and often accented with
the brand's interlocking ''C'' logo _ looked more abstract than
natural. The snakeskins looked slathered in semi-precious stones.
The skirts were fluted or gathered into pouches at the hem. The
jeans, with three zippers down the front , molded to models' legs.
</P>
<P>
   Colors ranged from black and white to peach, pink and perky
blues. Handbags were compact and quilted, Lagerfeld said, to look
like ''chocolate bars.''
</P>
<P>
   No Chanel show would be complete without a least a few felted
wool pieces, this time in the form of angular torso wraps held up
under the bosom with shoestring-thin belts.
</P>
<P>
   Lacroix losing it?
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the Chanel show, Lacroix's preview made it appear
the designer was holding onto his sanity by a thread, a fancy one
at that: maniacal pattern mixes and florals looking like
fruit-colored amoebas under the lens of a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   Only the florals in black-and-white woven silk and the
hand-painted palm patterns were easily discernible.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, it seems Lacroix has staged his show in an effort to
shock, rather than sell. And this was no more evident than in
ensembles typified by diagonally striped black pants paired with
something like a polka-dotted top _ with an arrow poking out a
model's hair as an added flourish. Undoubtedly, there were
precious, masterfully-made items in the collection. But it's never
easy to appreciate what's special about Lacroix's designs when he
conceals them with such distracting color combinations.
</P>
<P>
   On other runways
</P>
<P>
   Film screens showed clips from Kenzo's life and old friends
paraded as mannequins during the ``This Is Your Life''-style bash _
including motorcycles, a white horse and a whirling dervish onstage
_ celebrating his last collections before retirement. Kenzo, 61,
the first Japanese couturier to conquer Paris is stepping down from
the company he founded 30 years ago and is looking forward to
travel and artistic projects after his successor Gilles Rosier
takes over.
</P>
<P>
   The women's clothes for the coming season featured blousy belted
suits, skirts to the knee and short tunic dresses _ all showing
plenty of color along with some interesting crinkled fabrics in
neutrals and grays.
</P>
<P>
   The beige dress with a pleated skirt and the full,
pastel-striped skirt were wonderful, as were the trouser suits in
yellow, lavender or pink and the bright print shorts out of a
Caribbean fantasy. Men walked along with the women in squarish
linen suits.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Kenzo, known for his cheerful clothes, went back to his
roots with beautiful kimono ideas, huge obi-style bows at the waist
or shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The audience boasted plenty of designer stars, Sonia Rykiel and
Alber Elbaz of Yves Saint Laurent among them. ``It was colorful,
dazzling, marvelous,'' Elbaz said afterward. ``And sort of like
seeing the end of an era, the last of a kind of very independent
designers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOG / Staff
</P>
<P>
   Boldword Text for the cutline goes here on so many lines and
about four lines deep.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOG / Staff
</P>
