   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0978 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-POPMUSIC-COX     10-08 2342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It all started with the blues
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, OCTOBER 10. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN.
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a reason they call it the blues.
</P>
<P>
   Blues, plural. Blues, as in there's a lot of them. Blues, not a
specific color or tone but a spectrum. A continuum. An American
continuum that was born with the century, evolved over its course
and will usher it out. Blues scattered across a far-reaching arc
that has its origins in field hollers, sanctified shouts and the
coded polyrhythms of West Africa. Blues that connect the dots
between ragtime and hip-hop, and form the spine of rock,
rockabilly, gospel, rhythm and blues, jazz, bluegrass and country
music.
</P>
<P>
   Blues that come raw and electrified, like the music Muddy Waters
recorded for Chess Records in his 1950s Chicago heyday _ with his
mojo woikin' _ and blues that are gleaming and opulent, like the
music Duke Ellington composed for his great orchestras. Blues that
rip through the fabric of time like they were a cheap bedsheet and
leave the listener spellbound by their power, which is why Robert
Johnson continues to haunt us. Blues appropriated, quoted, latched
onto as a mask that allows performers to reveal more than they ever
could in a bare-faced confession, which is what gives 1990s rock
singer Polly Jean Harvey her bewitching focus.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no matter how many variations it seeds or seasons, no matter
how complex or abstract or tucked away or thrust forward its
influence, the blues are always elemental _ a natural fact. It's
the most vital strand in the DNA of American popular music.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Johnny Shines says, the blues are the pillars of the
piers,'' says Peter Guralnick, author of the two-volume biography
of Elvis Presley, ``Last Train to Memphis'' and ``Careless Love.''
Taking a cue from the country bluesman, Guralnick emphasizes the
way the blues gave license to musicians, black and white, who heard
it. ``As much as musically, it offered an emotional spontaneity, a
structure in which people could express emotion straight out.''
</P>
<P>
   You may think the following example preposterous, but to get a
handle on what this means, think of the blues as the single degree
of separation between the most unlikely pieces of music. Imagine
this: The blues are what link the metropolitan grandeur of George
Gershwin's ``Rhapsody in Blue'' (1924) to the primordial
sludge-rock of Black Sabbath's 1970s heavy-metal anthem ``Iron
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin, who was influenced by the pre-blues ``coon'' songs of
the 1890s, looked to vernacular forms as a way to color the tunes
he composed on Tin Pan Alley. He borrowed from African-American
musicians, and then they borrowed back. Bebop, the mathematically
complex form of jazz that emerged right after World War II, took
the kind of show tunes Gershwin wrote and briskly improvised on
their chord changes. Later, Gershwin's 1935 folk opera ``Porgy and
Bess,'' was recast by Miles Davis and his arranger Gil Evans in
1958 as a cool orchestral showcase for the jazz legend's sublimely
melancholy trumpet. It's the kind of cultural exchange that America
was built on.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Black Sabbath frontman Ozzy Osbourne can't claim the
same artistic pedigree, but like Gershwin, his particular genius as
an entertainer couldn't have existed without the blues to back him
up. His band's brutally rudimentary rock songs developed out of the
same British blues-rock sources as the Yardbirds and Cream. Except,
where Gershwin looked to the blues as the source of a populist art
music, Osbourne heard distortion and an id-driven frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the blooze, and look ahead a decade to a teenage Kurt
Cobain entranced by its thunderous beats and glacial tempos. The
furious melodies of Nirvana _ and the mainstreaming of alternative
rock _ were just around the bend.
</P>
<P>
   The connections to the blues aren't always obvious. Sometimes
they wiggle and blur. Not long before he committed suicide, Cobain
made it explicit, paying homage to the 1930s troubadour Leadbelly
on ``MTV Unplugged'' with a version of ``Where Did You Sleep Last
Night?'' Also known as ``In the Pines,'' it's actually an old
Appalachian murder ballad _ exactly the kind of material that the
blues existed to transform.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to soar
</P>
<P>
   To borrow a phrase from the black church, popularized by
rhythm-and-blues visionary George Clinton on Funkadelic's 1978
album, ``One Nation Under a Groove,'' the influence of the blues is
``so high you can't get over it, so low you can't get under it, so
wide you can't get around it.''
</P>
<P>
   George Clinton isn't strictly a blues musician. He's a former
doo-wop guy from Detroit who fused elements of acid rock, James
Brown's propulsive funk grooves and his own outrageous cosmic
fantasies into a subversive hybrid of sci-fi and hard-core R&AMP;B. If
a 12-year-old has heard Clinton these days, it's probably because,
after James Brown (or Brown's celebrated ``funky drummer'' Clyde
Stubblefield), Clinton's music is sampled ubi-
</P>
<P>
   quitously by hip-hop record producers. But Clinton is part of
the cultural line, and he knows exactly what novelist and critic
Albert Murray was talking about when he wrote the following words.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blues as such are synonymous with low spirits. Blues music
is not,'' Murray says in his 1976 study, ``Stomping the Blues,''
his vibrant introduction to music, and the ways that jazz developed
from it. When Murray describes ``the most miserable moaning and
groaning, the most excruciating screaming and howling'' as the
focal point of, say, a boisterous Saturday night at a juke joint or
dance hall, he might be echoing generations of naysayers who have
dismissed the blues and its progeny _ all those wailing saxophones,
all those loud guitars _ as so much noise. But he's actually saying
that the extreme passion of the music liberates those who embrace
it. Murray defined swing, the insistent rhythmic element that
underpins most traditional jazz, as ``the velocity of
celebration.'' It's one of the grooves, as Funkadelic shouts, that
has taught a nation how to dance its way out of its constrictions _
even if only for a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnomusicologist Robert Farris Thompson has called that
alchemical property ``the flash of the spirit,'' and it speaks
through improvisation. Hear the way B.B. King bends his guitar
string to emphasize feeling, or how generations of slide guitarists
_ from seminal force Blind Willie Johnson to latter-day acolyte
Stevie Ray Vaughan _ have used the sawed-off neck of a bottle to
conjure otherworldly effects. Hear how rock demigod Jimi Hendrix
ignited the painfully amusical ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' into a
breathtaking meteor shower, or how saxophonist John Coltrane remade
the treacly ``My Favorite Things'' into an epic mantra. Blues has
the power to crack the shell of the ordinary so that it becomes
surreal. Listen to Billie Holiday sing even the blandest show tune,
and she turns it into a seance with the subconscious.
</P>
<P>
   It can be incantatory, this power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raunchy, revolutionary, out there,'' says Dianne McIntyre, a
New York-based choreographer who has based much of her work on
collaborations with blues and jazz artists, such as Olu Dara and
Ornette Coleman. ``It makes you feel you can soar.'' It's what the
bravest pop and rock singers do, even when they're not as vocally
gifted as the melismatic Whitney Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In their classic albums of the 1970s, punk-rock poet Patti Smith
and Irish soul man Van Morrison visit the slipstream of the blues
continuum. They speak in tongues to say what can't be said in plain
speech, conversing with demons and angels. Smith's ecstatic reading
of ``Gloria'' (a song of testifying desire that Morrison wrote with
Irish rock group Them) or the entirety of Morrison's beatific
``Astral Weeks'' radiate with blues feeling _ the notion that sense
can yield to sound and convey a profound truth. Even when, as
Murray told us, that sound constitutes ``the most miserable moaning
and groaning, the most excruciating screaming and howling.''
</P>
<P>
   A commanding sound
</P>
<P>
   Robert Johnson, the most legendary of all blues singers, heard
that noise, too. He sang of having a ``Hellhound on My Trail.''
Johnson, of course, provided the blues _ and American popular
culture _ with its own Faust saga. Popular blues lore has it that
he sold his soul to the devil at the crossroads in exchange for
uncanny mastery over his guitar. A few years later, according to
myth, he died mysteriously in a juke joint, down on all fours
barking like a dog, poisoned by a jealous lover. The story has
produced a body of work that is vast compared to the hour's worth
of songs Johnson recorded in 1936 _ songs that have continuously
cycled through American pop life, as successive generations pillage
or prize a ``Hellhound on My Trail,'' or a ``Cross Roads Blues'' or
a ``Love in Vain,'' looking for secrets between the lines of those
satanic verses.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's legacy has inspired genius and hokum. You can hear him
conjured in the best music the Rolling Stones ever made (the
shambling dread of ``Exile on Main Street'') and in a stunning
track by the Houston gangsta rap group Geto Boys called ``Mind
Playing Tricks on Me.'' He's what the Red Hot Chili Peppers and
Cassandra Wilson have in common. While a devotee and fellow Delta
native nicknamed Muddy Waters would make the transition from
country blues in the 1930s to forge the dynamic Chicago blues sound
of the 1950s and stage a comeback in the 1970s, Johnson became a
kind of phantom. But a phantom who could materialize everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Robert Johnson's first album came out in 1961, it may not
have sold a lot of copies, but it made a huge impact on people like
Eric Clapton, Mick Jagger, Keith Richards and Brian Jones,''
Guralnick says, citing the direct influence Johnson commanded over
1960s rock. ``The myth appealed to people but it wasn't myth that
sustained his influence. It's the way his songs enter the language.
You hear it everyday whether you know it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson inspired dumb movies, such as Walter Hill's
``Crossroads,'' in which ``Karate Kid'' Ralph Macchio takes on the
powers of darkness, represented by a poofy-haired heavy-metal
guitarist, in a musical duel.
</P>
<P>
   And he eventually ended up on a postage stamp, based on a rare
photo-booth snapshot. The cigarette that had dangled from his lips
had been thoughtfully airbrushed away _ not unlike the trebly vinyl
scratches that were cleaned up when Columbia released its two-CD
Johnson
</P>
<P>
   box set in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Music and society
</P>
<P>
   And yet, that feeling Johnson tapped into can never be erased.
It's always floating around, waiting to be evoked. As the audience
for traditional blues has long been predominantly white, the music
often can't escape from its own museum: a place of false nostalgia,
good times and overpriced beer. Think of ``The Blues Brothers''
movie or the heavily merchandised hoo-haw of the House of Blues
chain. John Lennon once called the blues ``the first chair,'' but
its survival as a commercial genre has often relied on its becoming
just another theme park.
</P>
<P>
   That is, in itself, nothing new. ``The commercialization of
black culture has allowed it to be much more permeable than the
people themselves,'' says Dwight Andrews, professor of music at
Emory University and a composer who has frequently collaborated
with playwright August Wilson. Wilson draws deeply on blues culture
in his work (``Ma Rainey's Black Bottom,'' ``Seven Guitars'').
``When white audiences were flocking to hear Duke Ellington play
his `jungle music' in the 1920s, they went because it was the hot
new product, not necessarily because they wanted the band to come
home for dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   As Andrews views it, the blues is as contemporary as it is
historic. It's an almost generic influence on 20th-century American
music because it condenses the basics of Western harmonic practice.
We're so used to it, it's second nature. But Andrews also suggests
that the blues abide, even if you don't recognize them as such,
because the social conditions that fostered them 100 years ago
still exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason hip-hop is an extension of the blues is that many
of its aspects are shaped by racism and oppression _ there are
still reasons to sing the blues,'' Andrews says. Rap music _ ``the
CNN of black America,'' declared the pace-setting rapper Chuck D of
Public Enemy _ has become, in many respects, what blues once was:
black popular music whose narratives express and protest aspects of
existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even as we look at hip-hop today, the ultimate expressions
of hip-hop are not what we hear on the radio,'' Andrews continues.
``It's all driven by commerce, just as it was when (pioneering
women blues singers) Ma Rainey and Bessie Smith were performing 80
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, to hear where the blues has traveled, you have to
look where it's not advertised. You would have to have seen PJ
Harvey on the first part of her 1995 tour, when the British singer
was promoting her new album, ``To Bring You My Love.'' The music
Harvey and her band played wasn't really blues, but its eerie,
discordant pulse and voodoo-queen gestures were unimaginable
without the blues. The blues, which Harvey heard as a child,
listening to the Howling Wolf albums in her parents' record
collection, told her how to do what she did. And that was reach
back to that mythic, moonlit Delta crossroads and grab a fistful of
Robert Johnson's bedeviled dust.
</P>
<P>
   There's a line to a 1970s Rolling Stones song that goes, ``Your
old-time religion is just soul possession.'' Harvey embodied that
in a way that is terrifying and thrilling, self-consciously
theatrical and uncannily real. Time was running out on the
century's clock, but Harvey had something stronger than time.
Something so low, so high, so wide that there was no point in
contesting it. And even if you could, you wouldn't want to.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
