<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0979 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-POPMUSIC-TIMELINE-COX     10-08 1650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-TIMELINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POP MUSIC: A Century in the Arts
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, OCTOBER 10. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN.
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1901
</P>
<P>
   Innovative jazz trumpeter and singer Louis Armstrong is born,
but not on July 4 as he claimed.
</P>
<P>
   1905
</P>
<P>
   The year Jelly Roll Morton claims to have invented jazz. The
noted pianist, singer and band leader would have been about 20
years old.
</P>
<P>
   1912
</P>
<P>
   Memphis band leader W.C. Handy, ``the father of the blues,''
publishes sheet music for
</P>
<P>
   ``Memphis Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   1914
</P>
<P>
   Sheet music for Handy's ``St. Louis Blues'' is published.
</P>
<P>
   1917
</P>
<P>
   Original Dixieland Jazz Band, a group of white musicians playing
a style originated by black
</P>
<P>
   performers, is the first band to make a record.
</P>
<P>
   1923
</P>
<P>
   Ma Rainey, ``the mother of the blues,'' cuts first 78s for the
</P>
<P>
   Paramount label in Grafton, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   1925
</P>
<P>
   Bessie Smith, the vocalist known as the ``empress of the
blues,'' meets up with Armstrong to record ``St. Louis Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   1926
</P>
<P>
   Morton records ``Dead Man Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke Ellington records ``East St. Louis Toodle-ooo.''
</P>
<P>
   Blind Lemon Jefferson records ``That Black Snake Moan.''
</P>
<P>
   1928
</P>
<P>
   Leroy Carr records ``How Long _ How Long Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Red and Georgia Tom (Dorsey) record ``It's Tight
</P>
<P>
   Like That.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong records ``West End Blues'' and ``Weather Bird.''
</P>
<P>
   1933
</P>
<P>
   John and Alan Lomax, father and son folk song scholars, record
Leadbelly (real name Huddie Ledbetter) in the Louisiana State
Penitentiary at Angola. Leadbelly, a singer-guitarist, gets his
name from his deep bass voice.
</P>
<P>
   1936
</P>
<P>
   Robert Johnson, the most celebrated of the Delta bluesmen,
records ``Cross Road Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   1938
</P>
<P>
   ``Spirituals to Swing'' concert at Carnegie Hall features Big
Bill Broonzy, the top-selling male blues singer of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Morton is recorded for the Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   1938
</P>
<P>
   Robert Johnson dies of poisoning and passes into American myth.
The event confirms, for many, that the stunning guitarist sold his
soul to the devil in exchange for blues mastery.
</P>
<P>
   1943
</P>
<P>
   McKinley Morganfield (Muddy Waters), one of the last of the
great country blues singers, arrives in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   1945
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Parker, aka ``Bird'' or ``Yardbird,'' records ``KoKo''
and ``Now's the Time.'' His specialty: the alto saxophone.
</P>
<P>
   1947
</P>
<P>
   Prison songs at Parchman
</P>
<P>
   Penitentiary in Mississippi are recorded using a new technology:
the portable tape recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Thelonious Monk, a jazz pianist from North Carolina, makes his
recording debut for the Blue Note record label, material later
collected as ``The Genius of
</P>
<P>
   Modern Music.''
</P>
<P>
   1948
</P>
<P>
   Columbia Records releases the first longplay recording, a
12-inch vinyl disc to be played at 33 1/3 revolutions per minute.
</P>
<P>
   1949
</P>
<P>
   Black businesswoman Carrie ``Mama'' Cunningham purchases the Top
Hat Club on Auburn Avenue in Atlanta and rechristens it the Royal
Peacock. The club becomes a mecca for every important blues,
rhythm-and-blues and jazz artist of the era.
</P>
<P>
   RCA releases the first 7-inch
</P>
<P>
   ``single'' recording, playable at 45 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   Saxophonist Ornette Coleman, touring Mississippi with an R&AMP;B
roadshow led by Silas Green, is beaten up after playing an
</P>
<P>
   unconventional solo. An angry mob throws this tenor off a
</P>
<P>
   hillside. He recuperates in New Orleans _ and switches to alto.
</P>
<P>
   1952
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthology of American Folk Music,'' a collection of lost
blues, country, gospel and Cajun music, is released on Folkways
Records. Recordings by now-canonized bluesmen such as Blind Willie
Johnson, Mississippi John Hurt and Blind Lemon Jefferson are among
those compiled by filmmaker, archivist and self-styled
``alchemist'' Harry Smith. The
</P>
<P>
   six-album anthology capitalizes on the recently introduced LP
format and lays the groundwork for the folk and blues revivals of
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Phillips launches his Sun label in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   1954
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-born singer-composer-pianist Ray Charles records
</P>
<P>
   ``I Got a Woman'' in the studio of radio station WSB in Atlanta
(now the site of Georgia Tech's WREK-FM).
</P>
<P>
   Elvis Presley records ``That's All Right'' at Sun studios in
Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   James Brown, one of the most significant figures in black pop
music, begins his singing career
</P>
<P>
   in Macon with the Gospel
</P>
<P>
   Starlighters.
</P>
<P>
   1955
</P>
<P>
   Bebop innovator Parker, 34, dies at the Hotel Stanhope in New
York, watching jugglers on the Dorsey Brothers' televised
</P>
<P>
   variety show. Overnight graffiti declares that ``Bird Lives!''
</P>
<P>
   Billie Holiday records ``Lady Sings the Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Richard, ``the Georgia Peach,'' hollers the phrase,
</P>
<P>
   ``A wop bop alu-bop a wop bam boom,'' in a New Orleans recording
studio.
</P>
<P>
   1957
</P>
<P>
   Ellington's orchestra performs at Newport, R.I., and nearly
incites a riot with a historic performance of ``Dimuendo and
</P>
<P>
   Crescendo in Blue,'' during which saxophonist Paul Gonsalves
solos for 27 consecutive choruses. Ellington's career achieves
renewed popularity.
</P>
<P>
   1959
</P>
<P>
   Recordings by John Coltrane (``Giant Steps''), Miles Davis
(``Kind of Blue'') and
</P>
<P>
   Coleman (``The Shape of Jazz to Come'') are released.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday dies at age 44.
</P>
<P>
   1964
</P>
<P>
   The Beatles conquer America with appearances on ``The Ed
Sullivan Show.'' Pop music's British Invasion begins.
</P>
<P>
   The Rolling Stones, who take their name from Muddy Waters'
``Rollin' Stone,'' record at Chicago's legendary Chess Studios.
Waters drops by.
</P>
<P>
   1965
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dylan achieves a commercial breakthrough with ``Like a
Rolling Stone,'' which also takes its title from ``Rollin' Stone.''
Later, it's also the name
</P>
<P>
   of the first major rock music magazine, founded by Jann
</P>
<P>
   Wenner and Ralph J. Gleason.
</P>
<P>
   1966
</P>
<P>
   The band Cream is formed, featuring guitarist Eric Clapton's
explosive versions of the blues classics ``Crossroads'' and
``Spoonful.''
</P>
<P>
   1967
</P>
<P>
   Blues-rock guitarist Jimi Hendrix, one of the tragic figures of
'60s pop music, sets his guitar on fire at the Monterey Pop
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   1968
</P>
<P>
   Led Zeppelin records its first album. The group would become one
of the biggest supergroups of the 1970s, melding Delta and Chicago
blues sources to Celtic folk music and hyperbolic rock
amplification. Years later,
</P>
<P>
   songwriter Willie Dixon would sue the band for royalties.
</P>
<P>
   1971
</P>
<P>
   The Allman Brothers Band records ``At Fillmore East,''
</P>
<P>
   perhaps the greatest evocation of the blues ever staged by white
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Sly and the Family Stone release ``There's a Riot Goin' On.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Armstrong dies at age 70.
</P>
<P>
   1972
</P>
<P>
   The Rolling Stones release ``Exile on Main Street,'' which
features a stomping version of Robert Johnson's ``Stop Breaking
Down (Blues)'' and Slim Harpo's ``Shake Your Hips.''
</P>
<P>
   Saxophonist Archie Shepp, a leader of the jazz avant-garde,
records ``Attica Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   1973
</P>
<P>
   Alligator Records releases its first title, ``Hound Dog Taylor
and the Houserockers.''
</P>
<P>
   1974
</P>
<P>
   Ellington dies of cancer at age 75.
</P>
<P>
   1976
</P>
<P>
   Waters records ``Hard Again'' with guitarist/disciple Johnny
Winter. The album's raw and vibrant performance sparks renewed
success and wins Waters a new generation of fans.
</P>
<P>
   1980
</P>
<P>
   Saxophonist David Murray, leader of jazz's so-called
</P>
<P>
   ``gutbucket avant-garde,'' records ``Ming.''
</P>
<P>
   1983
</P>
<P>
   Waters dies at age 78.
</P>
<P>
   1988
</P>
<P>
   Living Colour, led by guitarist and Black Rock Coalition founder
Vernon Reid, releases its first album, ``Vivid.''
</P>
<P>
   1989
</P>
<P>
   President Bush jams with B.B. King at a White House luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   The rap group Public Enemy releases ``It Takes a Nation of
Millions to Hold Us Back.''
</P>
<P>
   1990
</P>
<P>
   Robert Johnson's ``King of the Delta Blues Singers'' is reissued
as a two-CD set. Reviews are mixed _ the digital transfer sanitizes
too much grit _ but sales of more than 250,000 copies put Johnson
on the pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   1992
</P>
<P>
   Fat Possum Records is founded in Oxford, Miss. Release of
recordings by R.L. Burnside and Junior Kimbrough renew interest in
the music of Mississippi's northern hill country. The subsequent
release of the documentary ``Deep Blues'' puts Kimbrough's juke
joint in Chulahoma, Miss., on the international map. U2's Bono,
Iggy Pop and members of Sonic Youth begin dropping by for the
marathon jam sessions and powerful corn liquor.
</P>
<P>
   1993
</P>
<P>
   Cassandra Wilson's ``Blue Light 'Til Dawn'' is released on Blue
Note. The album includes slyly feminized versions of two Robert
Johnson songs _ ``Come on in My Kitchen'' and ``Hellhound on My
Trail.''
</P>
<P>
   1994
</P>
<P>
   Robert Johnson appears on stamps issued by the U.S. Postal
Service. The image, based on a rare photo booth snapshot of
Johnson, is doctored to erase the cigarette dangling from his lips.
</P>
<P>
   1995
</P>
<P>
   ``To Bring You My Love,'' by the British rock singer Polly Jean
Harvey, is released. Though not strictly a blues album, its songs
are steeped in Delta lore.
</P>
<P>
   1996
</P>
<P>
   The Clarksdale, Miss., cabin of Muddy Waters is dismantled and
reconstructed for display during the Summer Olympics at the House
of Blues in Atlanta. The chain of music clubs, which
</P>
<P>
   features busts of blues legends and $5 beer, closes its Atlanta
franchise after the Games.
</P>
<P>
   1997
</P>
<P>
   Jazz and classical trumpeter Wynton Marsalis wins a Pulitzer
Prize for ``Blood on the Fields.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthology of American Folk Music'' is reissued by Smith-
</P>
<P>
   sonian/Folkways in a six-CD box set.
</P>
<P>
   Guitarist/record collector John Fahey and Nashville lawyer Dean
Blackwood launch the Revenant label. Devoted to ``raw musics,'' the
company releases collections by banjo player Dock Boggs and
pre-World War II black gospel singers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blind Willie McTell,'' recorded by Dylan during the sessions
for the 1983 album ``Infidels,'' is finally released as part of
Dylan's ``Bootleg Series'' box set.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
