<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0980 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGION-ORISA-COX     10-08 1498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-ORISA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Followers of Ifa pray to ancestors and depend on divination for
help in everyday life.
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The festive rattle of seeds against gourd, the clap of stick
hitting stick, the deep vibration of fingers against drum _ these
rhythms transform a Sunday afternoon in a Piedmont-Lindbergh
apartment clubhouse into an African worship experience.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, voices chanting _ sometimes soft and slow,
sometimes high-pitched and fast _ break through. Neighboring
children, used to the weekday sounds of the clubhouse's day care
center, often stop to watch, their faces pressed against the glass
wall.
</P>
<P>
   This is the weekly religious service of the Ile Ori Ifa Temple.
Several dozen African-American adults and about 10 children come to
sing and dance and hear lessons in Ifa (EE-fay) _ a religion built
around a reverence for ancestors and spiritual beings known as
orisa.
</P>
<P>
   Many were raised in various denominations of the Christian
faith, but consider Ifa, which originated with the Yoruba peoples
of West Africa more than a millennium ago, the faith of their
forefathers.
</P>
<P>
   A basketball net on a pole has been pushed aside. Against one
wall, plants and candles sit on a low altar over a grass mat. A
half-circle of orange stacking chairs marks the sacred space,
inside which women in bright flowing dresses and head wraps and men
in loose African-inspired suits move their bare feet on the dingy
tile floor to the rhythm of African instruments. The slapping of
their feet blends into the percussion, and the dance seems almost
involuntary.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny boy sways gently as he stares wide-eyed at his family. A
baby girl in bright yellow rocks sleepily to the rhythm in her
mother's arms.
</P>
<P>
   Temple founder Oguntolu Akinlana, 45 _ who carries the title
babalawo, or high priest _ notes that Ifa has become more accepted
in the United States, taking its place alongside Santeria and
Vodun, or voodoo, which blend elements of Catholicism with
traditional African religious practice. He believes Ifa _ which
continues without obvious Catholic influence_is closer to the form
of faith the ancestors practiced.
</P>
<P>
   Raised Roman Catholic in Baltimore, Akinlana vowed to become
familiar with African culture and spirituality after missions to
Johannesburg in the 1970s with the U.S. Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to meet African priests and get readings from
them,'' he said. ``Part of my destiny was that I was to be a
messenger for the ancestors and to make available the information
to African-Americans who are unsatisfied in their religious life.''
</P>
<P>
   He left the Air Force in 1983, became a jeweler in Florida, and
continued to study African traditions. In 1992, he traveled to
Nigeria, where he was initiated as an Ifa priest. He moved to
Atlanta in 1994 and founded the temple here.
</P>
<P>
   Ifa is ``a beautiful religion,'' said J. Lorand Matory,
professor of anthropology and Afro-American studies at Harvard
University. ``More and more, people of color seek solace in a
religion that shows their own image.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that a lot of people who migrate look for ties to the
place from whence they came, to their roots,'' said Sandra Barnes,
professor of anthropology at the University of Pennsylvania. Barnes
became interested in orisa worship while living in Nigeria. ``I saw
various ritual and religious practices, and I thought I should know
about them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ifa teaches that to be fulfilled, people must integrate the
practical with the spiritual, says Philip John Neimark, a convert
who wrote ``The Way of the Orisa'' (HarperSanFrancisco, 1993).
</P>
<P>
   According to Neimark, there are three main facets of Ifa:
</P>
<P>
   -- Ancestor worship, which taps into the ``energy and wisdom''
of deceased blood relatives. Ifa practitioners have ancestor altars
in their homes, with photographs, candles and flowers, and offer
prayers daily to deceased kin.
</P>
<P>
   -- Orisa worship. Ifa is essentially monotheistic but recognizes
orisa, or different aspects of the one god. In Ifa, Osun represents
money, love and conception; Sango controls thunder and lightning;
and the warrior Ogun is over all metals, for example. Each person
also has an ori, or individual orisa, that serves as a guardian
angel.
</P>
<P>
   -- Divination, through which followers of Ifa can learn their
futures. Most everyday divination is done with an opele, a chain of
shells that, in how it falls, leads the divining priest to a
particular odu, or sacred story, with a message for the
practitioner. Once handed down orally, these teachings are now in a
sacred text made up of 16 major books and 240 minor ones, each with
hundreds of verses. When larger issues are involved, the babalawo
uses ikin, or special palm nuts, to ascertain the right odu.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in I Ching or astrology, Ifa divination of an event does
not mean it is inevitable. An Ifa reading foretells what will
happen if nothing is changed, according to Neimark.
</P>
<P>
   One way to change the future is to call upon the ancestors and
orisa for intercession. Gaining their assistance can involve
preparing offerings of money, plants and other kinds of gifts. When
major issues are involved or when someone is being initiated into
the faith, this may involve blood sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Specific animals are used for specific problems or desires,
according to Neimark. To get a wife, a man should sacrifice a hen
or female goat; a woman should sacrifice a rooster or male goat to
get a husband. Pigs, guinea fowl and fish encourage prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Local adherents buy animals from outlying farms and have outdoor
ceremonies of sacrifice on appropriate occasions, leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   In modern America, the practice may be controversial, but
Akinlana maintains it is simply a recognition of the transfer of
energy in the cycle of life. It is similar to Jewish and Muslim
dietary laws governing the preparation of meat, he said, since
animals ritually killed are treated with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go to Kentucky Fried Chicken every day. They don't ask
how these chickens are killed or whether somebody prayed over
them,'' Akinlana said. ``Chickens are not born in (supermarkets).''
</P>
<P>
   When the ritual is over, the sacrifice is shared and becomes
dinner. ``It's a spiritual barbecue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For some African-Americans whose families came to the United
States as slaves, the practice of Ifa represents a kind of
reclamation of their roots.
</P>
<P>
   Before he became auainted with Ifa, Robert Jones had an ancestor
altar of sorts. He had photographs of deceased family members on a
table with flowers and a candle.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, he was Father Robert, a Catholic priest in the
Capuchin order, ordained by Atlanta's late Archbishop James Lyke in
1991. Today, he is Ifadero Ifadoyin _ a name that means ``Ifa is as
sweet as honey,'' and Aug. 1 he was ordained a priest in Ifa.
</P>
<P>
   Ifadoyin, 43, was raised in a nonreligious home and converted to
Catholicism in his 20s, attracted by the social work of the
Catholic Church and the sacrifices of modern-day martyrs. He was
serving St. Anthony's church in Atlanta's West End when he attended
a lecture on ``Orisa Consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought the lecturer made a lot of sense _ especially
when she talked about the significance of ancestors. ``It makes you
realize that what you got from those who went before you is more
than DNA,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When his religious order asked him to move to the Bronx, he left
the priesthood and began working in various retail jobs. He
remained Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Through word-of-mouth and the Internet, he continued to explore
Ifa.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he heard of the opening of the Ile Ori Ifa Temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the singing and dancing and just the whole spirit kind of
pulled me in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ifa priests do not proselytize, and the faith teaches that there
are many roads to God, he said. But many American converts from
other faiths, like himself, consider Ifa to be the best route for
their own journey.
</P>
<P>
   Osunleye Ayobunmi Asake, 33, who was raised a Holiness
Christian, was visiting her hometown of Savannah two years ago when
she ran across a book about Ifa. She was so impressed, she skipped
the family's Thanksgiving dinner to drive home to Atlanta to build
an ancestors' shrine.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, she and her husband visited Nigeria to be initiated
into the priesthood at the Idin Ileke Temple in Osogbo, the mother
temple of the Atlanta congregation.
</P>
<P>
   When she tried to talk about what her new faith means to her,
she broke into sobs. ``It's like I've found myself with my
spiritual family,'' she said. ``It's like all my life I was lost
and I've finally found a home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ile Ori Ifa Temple will hold its 2nd Annual Ifa Festival on
Sunday, beginning at noon at Camp Truitt-Fulton campground, 4300
Herschel Road, College Park, Ga. For information, call 404-691-6509
or 404-830-7996.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
