<HEADER>
A0981 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GATECH-HEELS09-CO     10-08 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-HEELS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech putting up impressive numbers
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thanks to Georgia Tech's rise into the Top Ten, mere
victories might not be enough for the No. 7-ranked Yellow Jackets.
Suddenly, they have national-championship and major-bowl dreams.
</P>
<P>
   And as the season moves on, winning big becomes important, in
non-playoff, major college football.
</P>
<P>
   When Tech (3-1, 1-1 ACC) entertains North Carolina (1-1, 0-3)
for homecoming today, most attention will be focused on the
offensive numbers. The Jackets' 45.3 points a game lead the nation.
</P>
<P>
   And the more Tech scores, the more attention will be directed
toward quarterback Joe Hamilton, the NCAA leader in pass efficiency
whose race for the Heisman shortens with each nationally televised
highlight.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, however, eagerly would trade Heisman hardware for a
national-title trophy.``That is what you come to college for,'' he
said before the season.
</P>
<P>
   So, for some viewers, those who vote in the Top 25 polls and
crunch numbers for computer rankings, how many points the Jackets
surrender will be as important as how many they score.
</P>
<P>
   That combination helps formulate the convoluted Bowl
Championship Series rankings that will determine who will get to
play for the national championship. Or at least, who gets to go
bowling for the big New Year's Day dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, margin of victory is part of the BCS equation,
and Tech's young defense, which has shined at times but is still
allowing 24 points a game, will be called upon to carry its end of
the load.
</P>
<P>
   Challenge accepted. ``You want to be at a place like this,''
defensive coordinator Ted Roof said, ``where people really care how
you perform.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jackets have improved. The defense could not make enough
stops to give the offense more chances to beat Florida State. But
it did firm up enough to avoid being upset by Maryland, forcing the
Terrapins to go three-and-out on 10 of 17 possessions.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, though, the Jackets defense _ an enthusiastic
bunch with a penchant for over-reacting -- faces a hungry team with
a quarterback, Ronald Curry, who is as explosive but erratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to continue to be aggressive,'' coach George
O'Leary said. ``That's the only way to play defense. But they have
to remember (that), when something bad happens, the next play is
the most important ''
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Clemons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
