<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0985 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV10-B     10-08 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV10-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POOL REPORTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October 10, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   White House reporters and war reporters before them long ago
evolved the custom of the pool report. When something interesting
is happening, yet there is not enough room for all to go along, one
or several representatives of the press corps are chosen to witness
the event close up, then write accounts from which all the others
are free to draw for their own reports.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these pool reports have become underground classics over
the years. Written as they are for a small audience of news
professionals, they often demonstrate a sharp eye for precisely the
sorts of illuminating details and judgments that cannot be printed
in a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Something of the sort has occured with Edmund Morris, whose book
``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan'' has been getting clobbered on
nearly every hand by reviewers who have trouble discriminating
between the parts about himself (many of which Morris made up) and
the parts about Reagan (none of which he made up). Despite what you
cannot escape having heard, ``Dutch'' is a wonderful book, at least
if you are interested in what happened in America during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It also is a superlative read, a page-turner (a first cousin to
Doris Kearns Goodwin's ``The Fitzgeralds and the Kennedys'') whose
airport sales will keep it going long after the pecksniffs, rivals,
and self-interested pleaders against it have returned to their day
jobs. It is beautifully illustrated as well.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ``Dutch'' employs several novelistic devices that makes you
glad to read and think, beginning with its dedication to the
short-lived Christine Reagan, infant daughter of Reagan and his
first wife, actress Jame Wyman. The most famous of these artifices
is a semi-fictional narrator named Edmund Morris, who, thirty years
older than the author, turns out to have gone to college with
``Dutch'' (Reagan's boyhood nickname), to have folowed him to
Hollywood and who, only on the last page of the book, discloses a
momentous secret about their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   True, it is a daring technique. It produces occasional moments
of vertigo, until you discover that it is the sensibility of the
storyteller that matters, not his biographical situation. As Morris
says, ``Everything that the narrator tells is true.'' So what does
it matter that when the writer wants to draw to the reader's
attention a particularily apposite passage from the radical
sociologist C. Wright Mills it is the narrator who says he has read
the book, rather than the writer himself?
</P>
<P>
   The fictional Morris is no more than a convenient proxy for the
biographer's access to eyewitness testimony or the best available
Educated Guess, then and now. So the effect is of a pool reporter
plunging in and out of the details of Ronald Reagan's early life,
his years in Hollywood and as a pitchman for General Electric, as
governor of California, then settling down in its last third to an
account of the presidency itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dutch'' is not a biography in a conventional sense, in other
words, but rather an interpretative account of a life by a
crackerjack student of character. Dozens of historians and
biographers in the coming decades will work over the Reagan years.
Many will be policy wonks, well-equipped to interpret what happened
and why. None will come closer than Morris to the man himself, both
literally and figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   (For all the accusations of bad faith, he is scrupulous to
describe his actual relationship to his subject. In fact he begins
his book with an account of the trio of dinners that led to his
engagement as ``authorized biographer'' _ a rhetorical ploy whose
effect is to remind the reader of the complexity of the world of
presidential biography.)
</P>
<P>
   I have long been among those who have thought that 1980 was a
great turning point in US politics, comparable in many ways to 1932
and the advent of the New Deal. What happened wasn't simply that
Reagan was elected, or that the Republicans won leadership of the
Senate, but rather that a watershed had been reached. Rivers flowed
the other way on the far side. To attribute this to Ronald Reagan
(or worse, to Margaret Thatcher) is simple-minded. And yet what
Reagan (and Thatcher) did and said mattered greatly.
</P>
<P>
   Morris sums up his view this way: ``But for his reluctance to
boast, he might already be considered great, on the achievements of
his first term alone. An overnight resurgence of American
patriotism and positivity; a rethinking of old attitudes toward the
government as provider; an assertion of popular rights on the
federal shop floor, and on the federal bench; a declaration of
moral war on the Soviet Union, plus a perfect willingness to
bankrupt it by force of military spending; a rebalancing of
executive power against the legislature; and a transferral of
`compassion' from welfare to the womb.''
</P>
<P>
   But Morris is also better aware than most that the problem of
audience lies at the heart of the Reagan presidency. As the Globe's
Mark Feeney has written, ``To some he is one of the century's
giants, to others a laughable doofus.'' Morris' achievement is to
set Reagan fairly and firmly in context that the reader once again
can judge for her or himself, at a distance of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   So Morris doesn't spend as much time on tax cuts as Robert
Bartley of The Wall Street Journal editorial page would prefer. He
doesn't devote enough attention for my taste to the ``yellow rain''
episode of the first term, in which the State Department formally
accused the Soviet Union of conducting biological warfare in Laos,
presenting samples that turned out on closer examination to be bee
excrement.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what Morris succeeds in communicating is a crucial
aspect of Reagan's approach to these matters, as when he describes
the peroration of the first inaugural address _ in which a young
doughboy of the American Expeditionary Force in 1917 vows to work,
save, sacrifice, endure, ``as if the issue of the whole struggle
depended on me alone,'' only to wind up buried in Arlington
National Cemetery across the Potomac. It's another example of
Reagan's ``Daliesque ability to bend reality to his purposes,''
Morris writes. In fact the soldier is buried in Bloomer, Wis., but
``Nobody who knows Reagan doubts that young Treptow lies forever in
some Arlington in his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the image of Reagan which Morris seeks to convey is
not the second-class Hollywood movie star, not the union politician
or corporate mouthpiece but rather the summer lifeguard who as a
young man pulled no fewer than 77 swimmers from the tricky currents
of Illinois' Rock River. ``Someday,'' concludes the fictional
Edmund Morris, ``I hope, America might acknowledge her . . . debt
to the Old Lifeguard who rescued her in a time of poisonous despair
. . .'' The lifeguard's trade is in fact a curious mixture of
posturing punctuated by daring. This is a wonderful book.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
