<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PRISONERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE OVER WHO SHOULD BE FREED DELAYS PRISONER RELEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Peace efforts hit a snag Friday when Israel delayed
a release of Palestinian prisoners after a dispute with the
Palestinians over who should be freed.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the latest Israeli-Palestinian accord, signed
last month, Israel was supposed to have released 151 prisoners
Friday, after a joint committee of Palestinians and Israelis had
agreed on their names.
</P>
<P>
   But a meeting between the two sides on Thursday night reached an
impasse when negotiators failed to agree on a prisoner list that
the Israelis drew up.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to avoid the release of long-serving prisoners who have
killed or seriously wounded Israelis, the Israeli team submitted a
list that included some prisoners who were serving short terms or
whose terms have nearly ended.
</P>
<P>
   Among those are Muslim militants from the Hamas and Islamic Holy
War movements and people who committed offenses after Sept. 13,
1993, when the Oslo accords were signed in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Israel had previously resisted freeing Islamic militants, and
the agreement ruled out the release of prisoners who had committed
offenses after the Oslo accords had been signed. But Israeli
officials said they were compelled to include such prisoners to
meet the required quota of 151 without releasing people ``with
blood on their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are avoiding releasing prisoners whose offenses are
particularly serious,'' said Public Security Minister Shlomo
Ben-Ami.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis whose relatives have been killed by Palestinians or who
have been wounded by Palestinian attacks have been lobbying the
government not to release prisoners who have killed or maimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a separation between freeing prisoners and
peace,'' said Shlomo Kalmanovich, a Jewish settler whose face was
disfigured by a firebomb thrown at his car in the Palestinian
uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians say the Israelis are violating the latest
agreement by seeking to free prisoners who committed offenses after
the Oslo accords. They insist that the freed prisoners should
include 47 longer-serving inmates from the ranks of the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people carried out attacks but are now enthusiastic
supporters of the peace process,'' Ziyad Abu Zayyad, a Palestinian
lawmaker, said in a radio interview. ``Are we going to be prisoners
of the past?''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over the release caused the second delay this week
in carrying out the new agreement. A safe-passage route through
Israel between the Gaza Strip and the West Bank was supposed to
have opened last Sunday, but disagreements on security
arrangements, which were finally resolved, have delayed the opening
until next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
