<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1001 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS09-COX     10-08 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hasek, Sabres call on Atlanta
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Late November should be a wonderful time of year for a
hockey team to be in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly when that team is based in Buffalo. Bad opponent.
Warm sun. Good combination.
</P>
<P>
   But to say Darcy Regier's day was ruined on a Sabres' trip to
sunny Florida early last season would be like saying a 100-mph
slapshot to the forehead could sting a little. Goalie Dominik Hasek
told the Buffalo general manager he was going to retire after this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself not to get too close to the water,'' Regier
said. ``The next thing I thought was, `Why?' I was just trying to
understand the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Regier now has a better understanding of why Hasek, the world's
best goaltender, will retire. He merely is relieved he was able to
talk the Czech native into playing one more season this year. The
Sabres, who visit the Thrashers tonight at Philips Arena, reached
the Stanley Cup finals last year before losing in six games to
Dallas on a disputed goal in triple overtime. They were that close
to a Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Logically, Hasek gives them the best chance to get back to the
finals. Some Buffalo players don't deny the perception that the
team has a one year window of opportunity. ``Some of our guys have
it in their minds that if we don't win this year we're not going to
have the opportunity because Dominik's gone,'' right winger Rob Ray
said. ``But I don't believe that. It would nice to win this year
for him. I just hope people don't think that we can't win next year
without Dominik.''
</P>
<P>
   Regier doesn't want his players to believe that and says he
doesn't believe it himself. While Hasek's retirement is potentially
traumatic, the Sabres are better equipped than most to handle it.
The roster is blessed with speed and youth and there are two touted
goalie prospects in the system: Martin Biron and Mika Noronen, a
first-round pick two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they want to do as well as they can while Hasek is
there, but they have a very good team,'' said Thrashers right
winger Nelson Emerson, whose Ottawa team was frustrated by Hasek in
the playoffs last year. ``When you go to the Cup finals, you can't
say it's just because of the goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   Regier said, ``We were going to try to win it this year whether
Dom was here or not. But I think we've positioned ourselves very
well the last few years to prepare for this. When we took Noronen,
I think we all had a sense that Dom wasn't going to play more than
a few more years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people who expect that we're going to drop off the
face off the earth when Dom retires are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, who desires to kick back and raise his kids in the Czech
Republic, was in goal Friday night when the Sabres had their home
opener against Washington. Coach Lindy Ruff would not tip his hand
on whether the goalie would play consecutive nights, but Regier
said, ``All you have to do is look at how many games he played last
year. If I were guessing, I'd say he'll play'' tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek started 64 of the Sabres' 82 regular-season games last
season. Backup Dwayne Roloson didn't make his first start until
Jan. 2. With five Vezina trophies, two MVPs, a gold medal and the
NHL's leading saves percentage for six straight years on Hasek's
resume, there's no reason for the team to save him.
</P>
<P>
   With the Thrashers struggling to score goals, there are other
faces they would rather stare at tonight. Atlanta defenseman Darryl
Shannon, who played for Buffalo for three and a half seasons, said,
``The thing I'll always remember most is not so much a particular
save but the other team almost laughing and shaking their head in
disbelief how the puck didn't go into the net.''
</P>
<P>
   For one more year, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
