<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1002 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-EXTREME-FASHION-$ADV1     10-08 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTREME-FASHION-$ADV10-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION FOR ARMCHAIR ADVENTURERS IN THE EXTREME 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 10) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Did you ever order the ``Extreme Carver'' sandwich at
Boston Market? Have you pre-ordered from Amazon.com one of the new
books about that Australian yacht race caught in the 1998 storm
that killed six people? Does your wardrobe include any of Ralph
Lauren's RLX ``technical'' athletic gear, Donna Karan's Ducati line
of motocross-inspired men's wear or a Timex Expedition watch, which
looks remarkably like a regular Timex except it has the word
``expedition'' on it?
</P>
<P>
   A ``yes'' to any or all these questions could mean that you are
one of those high-octane outdoorsy types who compete in extreme
sports, race expensive foreign motorcycles and relish testing their
mettle against the forces of nature.
</P>
<P>
   More probably, it means you've thought about doing these things.
You've read best-selling books about inclement weather (``A Perfect
Storm,'' ``Isaac's Storm''), maybe got a subscription to Outside
magazine or once wore hiking boots to work on casual Friday. You've
stood beneath soul-sucking fast-food fluorescent lighting and said
to yourself, I may be a consumer of processed poultry products, but
I identify with tattooed, body-pierced, physically imperiling,
limit-pushing extreme life styles.
</P>
<P>
   For every thrill-seeking weekend warrior, countless more
armchair adventurers are romanticizing risk-takers when their own
lives have never been more risk-free.
</P>
<P>
   Designers are engaged in an extreme competition of their own,
rushing to load up their waterproof, coldproof, heatproof
active-wear with trademark high-tech fabrics. Through an endless
supply of nonfiction nail biters and extreme-sports Web sites
literally wired into the athletes' heart rates, almost everyone can
live vicariously on the edge in the comfort of their own La-Z-Boys,
where the severest hardships are a dim halogen bulb or a slow
modem.
</P>
<P>
   More than 140,000 visitors will have trekked through the
American Museum of Natural History to see ``The Endurance:
Shackleton's Legendary Antarctic Expedition'' by the time it closes
Monday. The show chronicles the intense hardships experienced by
the 28-man crew of Sir Ernest Shackleton's failed voyage to the
South Pole in 1914. Many of the museum's trustees had opposed
``Shackleton,'' saying that the voyage yielded no significant
scientific discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an adventure story, and there was very little science
in it,'' Dr. Ross McPhee, a co-curator of the exhibition, said.
``It was a disaster. They never got to Antarctica.'' McPhee
admitted the show had very little to do with natural history and
likened it to a B-movie, complete with pulse-quickening silent
cinematography. ``By the end of it, you really feel kind of
thrashed,'' he continued. ``You've gone from climax to climax. And
you may not have known what the ending was, so there's that release
of tension when you find out.''
</P>
<P>
   The 130-year-old museum has never sounded so sexy.
</P>
<P>
   Books on similarly doomed expeditions, both past and present,
keep on coming. Four books on the Sydney-to-Hobart yacht race that
left six sailors dead. Five next year on George Mallory, the
legendary English climber who disappeared on Mount Everest in 1924
and whose body was found, in May, preserved high on the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Of this mania for adventure narratives, the president of Simon &AMP;
Schuster's trade division, David Rosenthal, said: ``I think people
are looking for a dose of reality in their lives. These books do
deal with life and death, and not like `ER' or a disaster movie.
There's a lot of, `There but for the grace of God go I.'
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of folks are in sedentary careers and have not had time
between college and work to traipse off and climb a mountain. These
books are the best antidote to finding yourself married with two
kids at 32 and living in Chappaqua.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal has been publishing this kind of stuff for years,
starting with the gonzo journalism of Tim Cahill and Hunter
Thompson in the 1970s to the harrowing Everest saga of Jon
Krakauer's ``Into Thin Air,'' the book credited with setting off
the late-1990s avalanche of ``extreme'' nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion has come a little late to the campfire, but appears to
be making up for lost time.
</P>
<P>
   A recent cover of Women's Wear Daily, with the headline ``Going
to Extremes,'' showed a model in orange overalls and a white down
vest clutching a snowboard _ all made by Burton. The inside pages
displayed clothing by Prada and Ralph Lauren fabricated with
technical-sounding materials: Teflon, Primaloft, Tactel, Supplex,
Colmax and those old standbys of the urban pioneer, Gore-Tex and
Polarfleece.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Wand, vice president of RLX, an offshoot of Polo Ralph
Lauren, said his was ``primarily a performance line,'' designed for
biking, snowboarding and the likes, and is sold at sporting goods
stores. That won't prevent nonbikers and nonsnowboarders from
wearing it, though.
</P>
<P>
   Wand added, ``The reality is that they might also be getting
great use out of these products just walking around or because they
think something looks amazing because it's a technical piece.''
</P>
<P>
   At Donna Karan, there is less concern with projecting an image
of authenticity. The DKNY Ducati line, with its motorcycle-theme
pants ($900) and jackets ($1,200) in stretch Kevlar, is ``primarily
a fashion statement,'' said Fraser Conlon, a senior director of
men's wear at the company. (Ms. Karen's husband, Stephan Weiss, has
long raced Ducatis.)
</P>
<P>
   Burberry has also gone rugged. The label has moved beyond
draping supermodels in its trademark tartan to celebrating the
company's roots in colonial-era outerwear. A sepia-toned booklet
from the Burberry public relations department includes reprints of
advertisements extolling the invention of gabardine inn 1879 by the
company's founder, Thomas Burberry, and a letter of praise for the
material by Roald Amundsen. Next to that kind of endorsement a Gap
ad saying ``James Dean wore khakis'' sounds pretty lame.
</P>
<P>
   So what if the new Burberry styles aren't worn for anything more
dangerous than an assault on the north face of Madison Avenue?
</P>
<P>
   A central tenet of marketers and ad agencies is that consumer
behavior is ``aspirational.'' A 9-year-old girl watches television
shows about teen-agers because she wants to be one. Walker Smith,
the president of the market research firm Yankelovich Partners,
said, ``Driving an SUV, you're saying I have an extreme attitude
and those are things that resonate with me.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent Yankelovich poll asked people to respond to the
statement, ``I like to imagine myself doing something I know I
wouldn't dare do.'' The number who agreed was 53 percent, up from
45 percent in 1995. Another question asked people if they like to
engage in activities regarded as dangerous. That number was up,
too, but only 2 percentage points (from 23 to 25) over the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``In broad strokes,'' Smith said, ``this push toward extremity
is one manifestation of the absence of the middle as an
aspirational ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Esoteric sports that were once strictly participatory have
become spectator events watched by millions. ESPN 2 covers
competitions that would once have been viewed only by nervous
friends and relatives: off-road skateboarding, sky surfing,
chain-saw championships. Web sites like Quokka.com and
MountainZone.com hook up climbers and long-distance desert runners
with digital cameras, pulse monitors and communications equipment.
E-mail messages to Quokka describe hours spent staring at computer
screens as daredevils scaled the Great Trango Tower, a 6,000-foot
sheer rock wall in Pakistan, in July.
</P>
<P>
   The newest magazine aimed at this market is National Geographic
Adventure, edited by John Rasmus, a former editor of Outside and
Men's Journal. ``We want to capture the purity of what's implied by
the name adventure,'' said Rasmus, whose National Geographic
spinoff was started in April. His pages may contain features on
``exploraphernalia,'' but Rasmus, himself a hiker and kayaker,
takes his adventure seriously. He said his magazine's approach is
``not about irony'' and is careful to refer to the Himalaya
Mountains by their local pronunciation: ``the hee-MAL-yah.''
</P>
<P>
   Rasmus said focus groups indicate that his audience is ``very
active'' and was reluctant to acknowledge an armchair contingent.
Hal Espen, the editor of Outside, took a more realistic view. A
recent reader survey showed that about 15 percent of subscribers
``have tried some level of fairly ambitious mountaineering,'' he
said. ``Far more than 15 percent of our readers are as fascinated
with vicariously participating in stories about mountaineering.''
</P>
<P>
   An overdue parody of the genre appeared in the men's magazine
Details in the August issue. Wil Hylton wrote of training for a
serious climb in South America by drinking and smoking beforehand
and then continuing to do so on the way up.
(OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</P>
<P>
   There are cultural antecedents for our obsession with these
kinds of stories. From the middle of the last century into the turn
of this one, an industrializing America devoured the literature of
adventure, risk and physical danger in penny-dreadful accounts of
men driven to cannibalism, the great novels of Herman Melville and
the wilderness stories of Jack London. The view of nature had
ceased to be redemptive (the Romantics' idea) and become Darwinian,
as George Stade, a professor of English at Columbia University,
observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the last century there was a fusion of adventure
with literalism and realism and London and instrument of that,'' he
said, recalling a Jack London story in which a man caught in a
winter storm kills his dog and puts his hands inside the animals'
body to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Hemingway kept the man vs. nature tradition alive long
after the rest of literature had left it to Hollywood. There is a
George Clooney movie in production of ``A Perfect Storm,''
Sebastian Junger's novel of a sailor's losing battle with the sea.
But for the most part, the current armchair adventurism has
remained a literary, not cinematic, form. Rosenthal suggested that
``people are so used to being transfixed by visual imagery, there
may be some desire to conjure things up in the mind's eye again and
put the imagination to some test.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, that can be tested at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
