<P>
   KOCH-FAMILY _ TULSA _ Based in Wichita, Kan., Koch Industries is
the second-largest privately held company in the United States,
after Cargill. According to a December article in Forbes magazine,
it is a $35 billion business with estimated profits of $700
million. The company ranks 18th on the Forbes 500, right behind
Chevron, Procter &AMP; Gamble and DuPont. The company's main business
is oil and gas. It has refineries in Corpus Christi, Texas, and
near St. Paul, Minn., and is among the world's largest oil traders.
(Cohen, Palm Beach Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOCH-TULSA _ TULSA _ Although oil production in Oklahoma has
slowed and the industry is just now recovering from its collapse in
1985 _ when the price of a barrel plummeted from $25 to $9 in a
single day _ Tulsa still considers itself the world's oil capital.
To find out why, all you have to do is pick up the Greater Tulsa
phone book _ specifically, the Yellow Pages. (Cohen, Palm Beach
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-WORLD _ NEW YORK _ The world, according to experts is
all going to be connected to the Internet. But what will be
connected to what? We'll take a look at the gadgets, phones,
kitchen appliances that are all the rage at InternetWorld in New
York this year. (Cocks, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   FORD _ ATLANTA _ Talking to local Ford unions about their
preparations for a possible walkout tonight over Ford's desire to
spin off its Visteon parts-making unit. UAW fears the move would
lead to lower wages and lost jobs. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
