<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-575&AMP;A     10-08 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW GENERATION OF HUMANISTIC JUDAISM ;  CHURCHES BACK NUCLEAR
TEST BAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A big test faced by voluntary organizations is whether they can
pass their convictions to a second generation. If not, they
probably face extinction, at least until someone comes along to
revive their core ideas.
</P>
<P>
   So it should not have been surprising that Rabbi Sherwin Wine,
in an interview this week, voiced satisfaction in looking forward
to an event at his temple in suburban Detroit. The movement he
launched, a Judaism focused on human ``power and responsibility''
without reference to God, was about to ordain its first rabbi, a
woman who grew up in the movement and was formally trained in its
principles.
</P>
<P>
   Educated in Judaism's Reform branch, Wine struck out on his own
to found the Birmingham Temple in Farmington Hills, Mich., in 1963.
It is now a cornerstone of the Humanistic Judaism movement.
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, is a Judaism based on two premises, that Judaism
is the historic culture of the Jewish people ``and therefore is
more than a religion,'' and that its power is ``not to be found in
an external source, but in human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, preparations were under way to ordain Tamara
Kolton, a 29-year-old licensed clinical psychologist who was bat
mitzvahed in his congregation. Ms. Kolton, the congregation's
associate rabbi, is the first graduate of a rabbinic program run by
an institute affiliated with a federation of secular humanist
Jewish groups. (A brochure defines a humanist rabbi as a teacher,
counselor, pastor and ``expert'' in Judaism.)
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony on Friday night had been designed to include Jewish
poetry and music, reading of philosophical reflections and a
statement of Ms. Kolton's commitment to the community.
</P>
<P>
   Wine, 71, drew widespread attention after he founded the
Birmingham Temple. News coverage of the controversy his views
provoked could sometimes be bold. A newspaper headline identified
him as ``the atheist rabbi.'' He was flooded with speaking
invitations from the curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that first year, I must have gone out at least 100 times''
to lecture outside Detroit, he said. ``I was invited by groups who
were interested in the controversy,'' he said. ``And then I was
invited by people who were interested in forming groups of their
own.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, he established the Society for Humanistic Judaism,
which has about 35 affiliated congregations in the United States
and Canada. About 20 other local groups belong to a sister
association, the Congress of Secular Jewish Organizations. There
are independent groups in Israel, Russia, and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of community is a function of the need of people to
feel connected to other people who share their convictions,'' Wine
said. ``We above all as humanists need communities. We don't have
God to rely on.''
</P>
<P>
   A New York affiliate is the City Congregation for Humanistic
Judaism, which holds a monthly Sabbath meeting, and Sunday programs
of Torah study and adults' and children's education, at the Village
Community School, 242 West 10th St. The congregation now has 70
households affiliated, said Myrna Baron, its past president. When
it was begun eight years ago, it had only six people, who met in a
living room.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baron went to Michigan to participate in a meeting at Wine's
temple called Colloquium '99, a program of discussions among
members of the humanist Jewish movement. Ms. Kolton's ordination
was timed to occur during the event. ``It's a wonderful milestone
for us,'' Ms. Baron said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Churches Back Nuclear Test Ban
</P>
<P>
   Before the U.S. Senate opened debate Friday on whether to ratify
a controversial treaty that would ban underground nuclear tests,
several religious leaders, representing Protestant, Roman Catholic,
Jewish and Quaker organizations declared their backing of it.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, half a dozen of them, originally scheduled to join
Republican Sen. James Jeffords of Vermont at a Capitol Hill press
conference, went instead to a White House gathering organized to
show support for the measure, the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
Clinton signed the document in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Among those declaring their organizations' support were the Rev.
Joan Brown Campbell, general secretary of the National Council of
Churches; Bishop John Glynn, auxiliary bishop of the Catholic
church's Military Archdiocese, and Mark Pelavin, associate director
of the Religious Action Center of Reform Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   But the treaty faces stiff opposition in the Senate, where
critics have said its provisions might threaten the safety and
reliability of U.S. nuclear stockpiles. Six former Republican
defense secretaries have come out against it, although it is
supported by Defense Secretary William Cohen and Gen. Henry
Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, Archbishop Theodore McCarrick of Newark, N.J.,
chairman of the Catholic bishops' International Policy Committee,
sent a letter to senators, saying the bishops favored ratification.
``The moral credibility of the United States in urging other
nations to forgo nuclear weapons depends on its ratification of
this treaty,'' he wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
