A1011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-TRAINCRASH-NY     10-08 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-TRAINCRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF WARNING SYSTEM CITED IN REPORT ON TRAIN ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ALAN COWELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Moving with unusual speed after Britain's worst train
crash in decades, a government panel confirmed Friday that a
commuter train had caused the crash here by running a red signal
light straight into the path of a speeding intercity express.
</P>
<P>
   Four days ago, police initially said that at least 70 people
died in the crash. But Friday they said that 30 fatalities had been
confirmed and that 64 people remained unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   The accident on the approaches to Paddington Station horrified
the millions of Britons who commute by rail each day and fueled an
emotional debate over safety three years after the state sold its
railroad system to private investors.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary government report from the Health and Safety
Executive found that the accident could have been avoided if the
track operators had installed a special warning system at the
now-notorious signal 109 near Ladbroke Grove in western London, the
crash site.
</P>
<P>
   Signal 109, known among rail engineers as difficult to see, had
been due to be fitted with the warning system, but not until
December 2003, the report said. The agency ordered Railtrack, the
company that owns tracks, signals and stations, to upgrade the
signal before using it again.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether private companies have trimmed safety
budgets in their pursuit of profit goes to the core of a debate
that has consumed newspapers, television talk-shows and ordinary
conversation since the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The government report did little to comfort travelers abruptly
confronted with a sense that public safety comes second to profit
in what Philip Stephens, a columnist in The Financial Times, called
``a culture that has ceased to weigh carefully the public against
the individual interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Britain has grown accustomed to public squalor,'' Stephens
wrote. ``Until, that is, something like this happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The report seemed just as damning. It said the Automatic Train
Protection system, which is widely used in continental Europe, had
been installed on the First Great Western intercity express that
was heading into London at 8:11 a.m., but was switched off because
it was ``not operational.''
</P>
<P>
   The equipment would not have prevented the crash, the report
said, but should have been functioning. First Greater Western was
accused of a similar lapse in an crash on that stretch two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since the accident, railroad executives have been accused of
shying from the cost of installing special devices across the
network, saying that the devices are unreliable and expensive and
that they are quite likely to cost some $3.3 billion to install.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, rail operators have begun to install the
technologically different _ and cheaper _ Train Protection Warning
System. Both systems are designed to brake trains automatically if
they run into danger.
</P>
<P>
   Raising another safety question, the report said both trains
were carrying diesel fuel in tanks that apparently ruptured,
spreading what rescuers have termed an inferno from the point of
impact. Even Friday, rescuers had still not searched through a
first-class buffet car on the intercity express described by
rescuers as being knee-deep in ash after a fireball incinerated it
and the people inside.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, official inquiries into rail accidents take
months or even years to complete. But Friday's findings were
released quickly in response to a public clamor for explanations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has experienced anything worse,'' said Vic Coleman,
Britain's chief inspector of railways, ``Everyone has been deeply
affected and there's been a sense of deep shock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
