<HEADER>
A1013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-HAWKS09-COX     10-08 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HAWKS NOTEBOOK: Small forwards among walking wounded
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. _ You can't be too thin or too wealthy _ or
have too many small forwards.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks can add the last part to an old axiom after LaPhonso
Ellis and Chris Crawford spent the morning practice on stationary
bikes. That left second-year player Roshown McLeod as the only
healthy member of the team's most competitive position.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis aggravated a calf strain he suffered a few weeks ago and
stayed out as a precaution. ``He felt a twinge,'' trainer Chris
Tucker said, ``so we're being cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford was taken for X-rays Friday morning after banging his
right hand in Thursday night's scrimmage. The X-ray showed no
evidence of a fracture at the tender spot at the base of his thumb,
but Tucker said he might seek another opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Fans will remember Crawford scoring 26 points against the Knicks
in the playoffs even though he had a separated shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   He had a similar reaction to this injury. ``Shoot it,'' he told
Tucker, referring to a pain-killing injection. ``Shoot it, and I'll
get back out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough kid,'' Lenny Wilkens said. ``That's what we love
about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford signed a six-year contract in August worth about $18
million.
</P>
<P>
   The staff is impressed with Ellis' work ethic. He was the
hardest-working veteran during the summer, seeking a quicker
release for his jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Practice notes
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens shortened practices Thursday night and Friday morning so
players could get the spring back in their legs.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, he threw the ball to Dikembe Mutombo. If Mutombo
could make two free throws, the team could skip sprint drills.
Calmly, the big man dropped in one and then the other, becoming
very popular.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Hawks went 90 minutes in the morning to prepare for
a hard evening scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks will hold a free public scrimmage at 6 p.m. today at
UT-Chattanooga's Roundhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll divide up into competitive teams and go four 10-minute
quarters,'' Wilkens said.
</P>
<P>
   They will finish here Sunday morning, practice at Philips Arena
on Monday and fly to Albany, N.Y., for the first exhibition,
against New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Short shots
</P>
<P>
   Alan Henderson was among several Hawks veterans surprised by
Isaiah Rider's questions about the team's ability to contend in the
East. ``I think we've got just as good a chance as anybody,''
Henderson said. ``This is a good team.'' . . . When fatigued,
rookie center-forward Cal Bowdler still has tightness in his back.
The problem surfaced in summer camp when the team's rookies and
free agents practiced twice daily and then played three games in as
many nights. . . . At the moment, center Mutombo and power forward
Henderson are the only two who are guaranteed a starting position,
and Lorenzen Wright is forcing Henderson to play better. Ellis
holds an advantage at small forward. Jim Jackson is ahead of the
late-arriving Rider at shooting guard. And rookie point guard Jason
Terry has shown brilliance, particularly with a withering spin move
from the top of the key, but nine-year-man Bimbo Coles makes fewer
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
