<HEADER>
A1025 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY09-COX     10-08 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Farming issues has Bradley rethinking past stances
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLISLE, Iowa _ Democrat Bill Bradley continued Friday to put
some distance between himself and his Senate record on farm issues,
telling farmers here he would support new federal subsidies to aid
distressed family farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Gazing out on gently sloping corn fields, the former New Jersey
senator called America's family farms part of the ``productive
beauty'' of the American landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we ever lose that, we are going to lose something that is
as deep in America as Thomas Jefferson,'' said Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Farm policy is perhaps the thorniest issue for Bradley as he
seeks to transform himself from a former senator into a national
candidate for president. In the Senate, Bradley voted against
increasing price supports for farmers and for the reduction or
elimination of loans to farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Bradley said he would commit an additional $1.2 billion
to put 5.6 million acres of farm land under the federal
conservation reserve program, which pays farmers not to use
environmentally sensitive land.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also proposed a new system of cash payments to farmers
tied to the market price of crops and agriculture products. When
prices dipped below farmers' cost of production _ feed, fertilizer
and maintenance _ farmers would be entitled to subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   After his chat with farmers, Bradley said that he now regretted
voting for the Freedom to Farm Act in 1996, which phased out some
price supports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't have passed it until they put a safety net in
place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His own proposals were not a reversal of his record, he said,
but a ``re-thinking of the issue.'' He noted that his proposals do
more than return subsidies for farmers, by targeting aid to small,
family producers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in his campaign, Bradley also did an about face on
federal subsidies for ethanol, the corn-based fuel additive that
annually consumes some 200 million bushels of corn in Iowa and
accounts for 14,000 state jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley sponsored legislation to phase out the ethanol subsidies
in the Senate, but now he is in favor of continuing them.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore's campaign immediately seized on Bradley's
latest proposals as a ``blatant political attempt to curry
political support in Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For 18 years as a United States senator from New Jersey, Bill
Bradley voted against the interest of farmers,'' said Gore
spokesman Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the decisiveness with which he has advanced other
proposals, such as providing universal health insurance, Bradley
was decidedly more cautious in dealing with the farm issue.
</P>
<P>
   He freely conceded that he didn't know ``a whole lot'' about
agriculture when he began his campaign and that campaigning in Iowa
had been an education. ``I had no sense of what the farm economy
was all about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is offered modestly, but it's offered sincerely,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Bradley was asked a question about soy beans. Unable to
answer, he simply shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's host for the day, Joe Dunn, who farms 200 acres and
leases 1,000 acres to other farmers, said he found Bradley sincere
but wasn't ready to commit to the East Coast Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time I've ever met him,'' said Dunn, whose
farm has been in his family for 140 years. ``I want to follow this
a little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
