<HEADER>
A1026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-4     10-08 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHENS RECLAIM PART OF AREA OCCUPIED BY RUSSIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ Chechen fighters have repulsed Russian forces
from villages along the Terek river in northern Chechnya, in their
first serious resistance since fighting began two weeks ago, a top
Chechen commander said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechens started a coordinated attack on several places
along the Terek on Thursday afternoon, said Aslanbek Izmailov,
deputy chief of the cabinet of ministers and a senior commander.
</P>
<P>
   More reinforcements were sent in overnight and secured at least
two villages that had been occupied by Russian forces: Isherskaya,
in the northeast, and Chervlennaya, almost directly north of the
capital, Grozny, Izmailov said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians only control the steppe now, we control the
villages,'' he said. The Russians had withdrawn as soon as they
came under attack and lost four armored vehicles in the process at
Chervlennaya, and small arms fire was continuing Friday evening,
said Izmailov. He added that Chechen fighters were digging in.
</P>
<P>
   Now ranged on the steppe north of the villages on the Terek, the
Russian troops have shelled Chechen positions. Heavy ripple
explosions from multiple rocket systems could be heard clearly from
Grozny, some 15 miles away, Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Izmailov estimated that 20,000 Russian troops were now
positioned north of the Terek. They swept into Chechnya two weeks
ago without meeting much resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians said little Friday about the fighting in Chechnya,
but conceded that their casualties are mounting, according to a
Russian general, Valery Manilov, who said some 20 to 30 Russian
soldiers had been killed in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians invaded Chechnya in 1994 to crush a bid for
independence. They withdrew in humiliating defeat 21 months later,
agreeing to defer any decision on Chechnya's status for five years.
Negotiations continued but Chechnya became engulfed in a wave of
crime that has aggravated relations with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians renewed military action in recent weeks, spurred by
a violent uprising in neighboring Dagestan and bombings that killed
hundreds of people in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians had occupied all the land down to the Terek,
roughly a third of the republic, earlier this week, forcing Chechen
fighters to withdraw south across the river.
</P>
<P>
   Izmailov said the Chechens would try to hold the villages,
especially Chervlennaya, which commands the heights over the city
of Grozny, but he expected heavy bombing. ``The men can stand the
shelling, they are digging in,'' he said. ``If it gets too heavy,
then we either have to go forward or back. We can move our
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   He said most civilians had left the area, but the Chechen
government estimated that some 5,000 people, of a population of
50,000, were still in the area north of the Terek.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Chechen leadership was determined to prevent Moscow from
annexing the northern area and setting up its own administration,
he said. Part of Moscow's plan was to enable two Chechens loyal to
Moscow to run for seats in parliamentary elections in December from
the region. The man named to lead the new administration in the
annexed northern part of Chechnya, Malik Saidullayev, was a
traitor, Izmailov said, adding that the Chechen authorities had
confiscated his apartment in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, he said, Russian forces had not advanced from
positions poised on Chechnya's eastern and western borders. The
Russians have concentrated 40 percent of their forces north of the
Terek, Izmailov said. Nevertheless, he remained convinced that
Russia intended to eventually take the whole province.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just checking to see if we would resist,'' said
Izmailov. ``If they see we are weak, then they will move in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
