<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-SALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLISHER SAYS SALE OF WORCESTER TELEGRAM IMMINENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sale of the Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette, the third largest
daily newspaper in Massachusetts, could be announced as soon as
next week, its publisher said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Telegram &AMP; Gazette publisher Bruce S. Bennett said indications
are there are three finalists for purchasing the paper, whose
history stretches back 115 years. They are the Journal Register
Co., of Trenton, N.J., Media News Group Inc. of Denver, and the New
York Times Co., which owns The Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has told me it is these three, but that is what the
indications are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett would not say which company is to be the buyer of the
newspaper, but Newspaper Guild officials have said staffers expect
the Times Company to be the winning bidder. The purchase price is
expected to be between $200 million and $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Guild is preparing for a sale to the New York Times,''
said Kathleen Shaw, chairwoman of the Worcester unit of the
Providence Newspaper Guild. In September, the Worcester Telegram &AMP;
Gazette reported that seven potential buyers _ the three finalists
as well as Fidelity Investments' Community Newspaper Co. of
Needham, Mass.; Pulitzer Inc. of St. Louis, Gannett Co. Inc., of
Arlington, Va., and Copley Press Inc. of La Jolla, Calif. _ toured
the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two or three weeks ago, architects representing the New
York Times Co. visited the building, taking photographs, in a
precursor to a possible building renovation, said Shaw, leading to
speculation among staffers that the Times was to be the paper's
next owner.
</P>
<P>
   Times Co. spokeswoman Nancy Nielsen declined to comment, saying
the company has a long-standing policy of not discussing potential
acquisitions, divestures or investments.
</P>
<P>
   One reason to believe a sale of the T&AMP;G is imminent is Tuesday's
announcement by Pulitzer Inc. that it was purchasing The
Pantagraph, the T&AMP;G's sister paper in Bloomington, Ill., for $180
million from the Chronicle Publishing Co. of San Francisco, which
owns the Worcester paper, and put them both up for sale, along with
the San Francisco Chronicle, three television stations, two book
publishing companies, a Web site and a cable news outlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that with the pace of the situation, something
will happen within next seven days,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Worcester is New England's second largest city with a population
of 162,000. The Telegram &AMP; Gazette has a daily circulation of
107,405 and 134,067 on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NM-EVOLUTION-EDUC-600     10-08 1035
