<HEADLINE>
GENENTECH ANNOUNCES STOCK SPLIT AND PUBLIC OFFERING BY PARENT
COMPANY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Switzerland)   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Genentech Inc. said Friday that Roche Holdings
Inc., its parent company, intends to sell 20 million shares of
Genentech common stock as soon as possible, reducing its ownership
of Genentech to 65 percent from 82 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech also announced a 2-for-1 stock split at a date yet to
be determined. The split and the public offering by Roche both
reflect the substantial gains in Genentech shares. Since they were
first offered to the public in July at $97, Genentech shares have
traded as high as $179.50. In June, Roche exercised its option to
buy the 33 percent of Genentech it did not already own for $82.50 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the sale will be for the sole benefit of Roche,
which is based in Basel, Switzerland. Roche also intends to issue
dollar-denominated bonds exchangeable with Roche for up to
approximately 5.5 million shares of Genentech common stock owned by
Roche. Genentech, based in South San Francisco, will not receive
any proceeds from the transaction, but Genentech executives said
their shareholders will benefit from increased liquidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had some frustration on the part of investors, that
with the low trading volume, it can be difficult to get in and out
of the stock without moving the market,'' said Arthur D. Levinson,
Genentech's chairman and chief executive. He said the offering,
coupled with the split, would quadruple the number of shares
available for trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a softer realm, this sale of the shares is in part a
reflection of Roche's confidence that we're doing a good job
managing the company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech shares closed Friday at $157.75, down $15.0625, on the
New York Stock Exchange. Analysts said that Genentech has benefited
both from its own strong execution and from the general run-up in
the shares of the larger biotechnology companies this year, and
that Friday's stock movement represented profit taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's brilliant,'' said Viren Mehta, an analyst with Mehta
Partners. ``Even Roche could not have anticipated it would go so
well.'' Although Genentech's financial results have been positive,
the share price represents the anticipation of even stronger future
growth, he said. ``Investors are not so much focused on the current
earnings, but on the potential of Genentech to surprise us,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Genentech Friday also reported earnings that
exceeded Wall Street estimates. For the third quarter, exclusive of
special and recurring redemption related charges, Genentech earned
$66.9 million, or 51 cents a diluted share, topping the 39 cents a
share expected by Wall Street analysts surveyed by First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Including the charges, Genentech reported a loss of $62.8
million, which compared with earnings of $63.4 million, or 49 cents
a share, in the period a year ago. Revenue grew by 10 percent to
$345.3 million from $313.9 million in the same quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech attributed the revenue growth primarily to sales of
Herceptin, a treatment for some cases of metastatic breast cancer,
and Rituxan, a treatment for some types of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
