<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-NATWEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL WESTMINSTER SHAKE-UP FOLLOWS TAKEOVER BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Desperate to thwart a $34 billion hostile takeover by
the Bank of Scotland, National Westminster PLC dismissed its
discredited chief executive on Friday and hired an outside salvage
expert.
</P>
<P>
   Sir David Rowland, Natwest's chairman, will replace the chief
executive, Derek Wanless, and Ron Sandler, the former chief
executive of Lloyds of London, will join the bank as chief
operating officer. Sir David and Sandler had worked at Lloyds
together and are credited with rescuing its insurance business from
near-ruin.
</P>
<P>
   The management shake-up was the first aggressive move by
Natwest, the No.3 bank in Britain, as it tries to repel the
takeover attempt announced by the Bank of Scotland two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The move did not come as a surprise to most analysts, who said
the departure of Wanless was needed to regain the confidence of
investors unhappy with his management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose it was inevitable that they had to get rid of
Derek,'' said Robin Down, a banking analyst at ABN Amro in London.
``He had no credibility with the investment community over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanless lost the support of investors after a string of bungled
deals including an attempt to create a leading investment banking
unit and, most recently, a failed $17.2 billion bid for Legal and
General Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors had opposed that deal, saying Natwest was
offering too much money for the company, a British insurer.
Natwest's stock price fell as a result, and that was considered one
reason the Bank of Scotland was emboldened to make a bid on Sept.
25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you preside over a couple of disasters, people lose
faith,'' Down said of Wanless. ``The final straw came with the
Legal and General deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Natwest said Wanless would remain a consultant to the bank. But
it was apparent that his dismissal occurred amid tension with Sir
David, who said Natwest made the management changes because ``what
we wanted was people who eat red meat for breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir David made the remark in an interview with Bloomberg News,
and the statement was later confirmed by a Natwest spokesman. Sir
David and Wanless declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Natwest is also said to be considering a plan to sell 5 billion
pounds ($8.3 billion) in assets to strengthen investor confidence
even further. Executives close to the company said the bank was
considering a plan to sell its fund-management unit, Gartmore
Investment Management; its bond-trading operation, Greenwich
Natwest; and Ulster Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really digging in their heels for a fight,'' said Tom
Rayner, a banking analyst at SG Securities in London.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Natwest's new management could also help in an
effort to find a friendly buyer to help it escape the Bank of
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it easier for a potential white knight to come in if
they keep the chief executive slot open,'' Down said. ``They are
looking for a rescue team.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Natwest are still trading over the Bank of Scotland's
original bid, partly in anticipation that another suitor may soon
emerge. The Royal Bank of Scotland PLC and Abbey National PLC are
said to be considering bids.
</P>
<P>
   Any possible bidder will probably wait for the Bank of Scotland
to issue its official offer document, expected as soon as early
next week. On Thursday, the Bank of Scotland said the acquisition,
if completed, would create 1 billion pounds, or nearly $1.7
billion, in savings per year through cost-cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Burt, chief executive of the Bank of Scotland, said he
believed his bank could squeeze more savings out of Natwest than
any possible counterbidders.
</P>
<P>
   Natwest's anti-takeover moves on Friday did little to convince
investors one way or the other. Shares of Natwest increased 2
pence, to 1,442 pence ($23.94) while shares of the Bank of Scotland
dropped 4.5 pence, to 725 pence ($12.03).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think getting rid of Wanless will make much of a
difference to the overall outcome of the takeover battle,'' Rayner
said. ``It's not much a defense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
