<P>
   TEST-BAN-TREATY (Washington) _ As the Senate opens debate on a
treaty to ban nuclear testing, President Clinton acknowledges that
he lacksthe votes to ratify the treaty and pleads with Senate
leaders to delay action on the global pact. By John M. Broder.
1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   FCC-CABLE (Washington) _ The Federal Communications Commission
decides to substantially loosen the rules that have limited one
company from controlling too much of the cable industry, clearing
the way for AT&AMP;T to own more than a third of the nation's
franchises offering subscribers television, telephone and high
speed Internet services as well as being partners with a number of
major video producers and television programmers. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Undated) _ An in-depth look at the state of Vice
President Al Gore's campaign, following the recent decisions to
streamline and move its headquarters to Nashville. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   PARROT-POWER (Undated) _ Do parrots think cognitively? Dr. Irene
Pepperberg, a scientist at the University of Arizona, says they do.
Assertions like hers are at the center of a highly emotional debate
about whether thought is solely the domain of humans or whether it
can exist in other animals. Is animal behavior the result of
reasoning and choice, or is it just instinct or sophisticated
mimicry. By Dinitia Smith. 2,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-FREEWAY (Alhambra, Calif.) _ At one level, the latest
fight over a South Pasadena freeway is a timeless, parochial
conflict, pitting one community against another. But in a broader
sense, the battle of the 710 is an example of the biggest question
bedeviling a region that is again expanding explosively after a
deep recession: How to accommodate growth in Southern California
without destroying the very quality of life that drew masses of
Americans here in the first place. By Todd S. Purdum. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   REEFERS:
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-EXTRADITE (London) _ A London court rules that Gen.
Augusto Pinochet can be extradited to Spain to stand trial on
torture and conspiracy charges. While there have been a number of
dramatic court decisions since Gen. Pinochet's arrest a year ago,
this is the first to be based on the crimes he is accused of rather
than simply on the legality of his arrest. By Warren Hoge. 1,300
words.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-ASSESS (New Delhi) _ News Analysis: Something amazing
happened in Indian politics in the elections that just concluded.
In the large southern state of Andhra Pradesh, the party that
promised the freebies lost. And the politician who warned there's
no free lunch won. The larger question for India now is whether the
winner's strategy for economic growth will catch on in other
states. By Celia W. Dugger. 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS (New York) _ Game 3 of NL division series.
By Judy Battista.
</P>
