<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1046 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-VIEQUES-BOMBING-HNS &LR;      10-08 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-BOMBING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCY TO STUDY WHETHER NAVY BOMBING CAUSES CANCER ON VIEQUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government's key disease-monitoring agency
agreed Friday to investigate claims by residents of the Puerto
Rican island of Vieques that nearly six decades of Navy and Marine
Corps bombing practice caused a high rate of cancer there.
</P>
<P>
   The action by the Atlanta-based Agency for Toxic Substances and
Disease Registry (ATSDR) threatens to complicate President
Clinton's already delayed decision on Navy requests to resume
live-fire combat training at the Atlantic Fleet's 58-year-old
target-practice range.
</P>
<P>
   The range has been closed since April 19 when a Marine pilot
mistakenly dropped two 500 pounds bombs on a range observation post
more than a mile from his intended target, killing a Puerto Rican
security guard and injuring four other civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The accident sparked demands by Puerto Rico's political leaders
and allies in Congress for the Navy to permanently end the bombing
and withdraw from the picturesque island that is home to almost
9,400 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Williams, the assistant surgeon general and director
of the ATSDR's division of health assessment and consultation,
notified Gordon Rumore, a resident of Vieques, of the agency's
decision in a letter mailed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rumore, a retired Pennsylvania state environmental health
specialist and a public health nurse who settled on Vieques in
1998, petitioned the ATSDR on May 14 to make ``an investigation and
assessment of a clear, immediate and profound risk to the health''
of island residents from toxic chemicals in bombs, rockets and
naval gunfire rained down on the 899-acre site since 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Rumore claimed that the thousands of tons of explosives
detonated in that period created clouds of toxic dust that were
carried by trade winds over populated areas 10 miles away and that
contaminated the residents.
</P>
<P>
   Williams wrote Rumore Friday that his request ``for a public
health assessment of the population subjected to toxic chemicals
from the detonation, deflagration and decomposition of military
ordnance ... meets the ATSDR criteria for conducting'' the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The health monitoring agency has started to gather ``relevant
environmental sampling data and exposure information'' from federal
and local authorities and has formed a site team to evaluate the
data, Williams added.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Skipper, spokeswoman for the ATSDR, an arm of the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta, said the
investigation could ``take a year or more.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency launched the probe, Skipper said, because ``there are
enough issues of public health significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Vieques have complained about the incidence of
cancer there for years. A study of health statistics during the
1980s by Dr. Diego E. Zavala, director of the Central Cancer
Registry of Puerto Rico, concluded in October 1997 that the number
of cancer cases per capita on Vieques during the five-year period
ending in 1989 was 26.9 percent higher than in any other Puerto
Rican community.
</P>
<P>
   Rumore, who had worked with the ATSDR on hazardous sites during
his 12 years with the government of Pennsylvania, said he welcomed
the agency's decision.
</P>
<P>
   He charged that the Navy had ``shown a depraved indifference to
human health'' by failing to ``monitor the health of the people of
Vieques through epidemiological surveys, water sampling and air
testing.''
</P>
<P>
   Navy Cdr. Karen Jeffries, a Navy spokeswoman at the Pentagon,
said the Navy and Marine Corps welcome the ATSDR study because it
will settle the question of whether Vieques' high cancer rate stems
from live-fire training.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these operations were proven to be harmful or cause cancer,
we would cease and desist,'' Jeffries said, adding: ``But there are
currently no studies anywhere that suggest our military operations
are harmful to the residents.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffries reiterated the Navy's contention that it needs to
resume the live-fire training on Vieques immediately to prepare
Atlantic-based Navy and Marine forces for possible combat before
deploying on routine missions to the Mediterranean and Persian
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, a deputy White House press secretary and spokesman
for the White House National Security Council, said Clinton will
consider the ATSDR decision to investigate the cancer charges as he
ponders the future of the bombing range.
</P>
<P>
   A four-member Pentagon review panel appointed in June at the
president's request had been expected to make recommendations on
the range by Aug. 31 to Defense Secretary William Cohen. But the
panel didn't issue its initial report until Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   At that time it recommended that live-fire training should be
resumed on a limited basis for the next five years and that the
Navy should withdraw from the island by 2005. The panel also
recommended an immediate and comprehensive study of the incidence
of cancer on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen then asked the panel to rework its recommendations. Leavy
said Friday that ``the recommendations are still being worked
out.'' He added that Clinton ``understands the passions and
emotions on both sides of this controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
