</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL UP TO PEDRO'S BROTHER RAMON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He is fragile and well-rested. He is experienced and
poised. He is 6 feet 4 inches and weighs only 184 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   He's not heavy. He's Pedro's Brother. And Ramon Martinez is all
that stands between the Red Sox and the winter of 1999-00.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro (back) is hurt, Nomar (wrist) is wounded, and after two
days of agony and annihilation, the Sons of Jimy Williams have come
home to die. But before they expire, there is at least one more
game to be played, one more loss to package and carry into the next
century with all the others. Big Brother Ramon, a man who has
pitched in exactly four major league games in the last 16 months,
gets the ball at Fenway Saturday at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Weird. After all that's happened, who would have guessed that
Ramon would be the healthy Martinez for this suddenly disappointing
playoff ride?
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the Red Sox didn't have this luxury back in 1967 when
they had to throw Cy Young Award winner Jim Lonborg on two rest for
the seventh game of the World Series. Alas, Eric Lonborg was never
a big league pitcher. And think about how cool it would have been
if Randy Clemens could have pitched Game 7 in '86, the day after
Cy-designee Roger left with a blister on his index finger. Imagine
if Oil Can Boyd had a brother (Chainsaw Boyd, perhaps) who could
have rescued the Sox every time the Can got hurt or lost his way?
</P>
<P>
   Pedro has a brother and he is more than capable of winning.
Thirty-one-year-old Ramon was in the majors long before Little
Pedro came along (the Dodgers signed Ramon when he was 16) and won
20 games for Los Angeles in 1990. He is a two-time All-Star, has
thrown a no-hitter, struck out 18 batters in a game, and pitched in
two postseason contests (0-1, 5.84 ERA). But it somehow seems
unfair that he should be the last line of defense for the 1999
Boston baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Indians) have a great lineup,'' acknowledged Ramon.
``What I've got to do is go out there and try to beat it. I'm going
to try to do that (today). I'm not 100 percent yet, but I'm getting
close. What I have now, I can pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought he could throw more than 100 pitches, maybe
even toss a complete game. It seems too much to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days ago, we were all assuming the Sox would win Game
1 behind Pedro and then try to steal one of the next three games
hurled by veterans Bret Saberhagen, Ramon, and Kent Mercker. That
was before Pedro got hurt and Saberhagen went wild and Thome
Thunder struck twice at the Jake.
</P>
<P>
   And now it is left to Ramon to prevent Boston's fourth playoff
sweep in five tries, AB (After Buckner). A loss would make Boston a
hideous 1-19 in postseason play since Game 5 of the 1986 World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has pitched in the playoffs before,'' said Williams. ``He
has pitched well in his last couple starts. The big thing for me,
watching him pitch, is his foundation, his legs. He carried his
legs well beneath him those last two games, and I don't believe he
was tired coming out because of the conditioning he's been through.
I look forward to watching him pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon's shoulder was rebuilt in June 1998, and in the summer of
'99 he pitched in Lowell, Sarasota, and Pawtucket before returning
to the majors Sept. 2. He lasted only three innings in that first
start at Fenway and was dropped from the rotation, only to return
and win his final two starts _ lasting seven and six innings in
victories over the moribund Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramon Martinez beat us the last time he pitched against us (he
actually pitched 4 2/3 innings in a 14-3 Sox win),'' said Cleveland
manager Mike Hargrove. ``We know what we're in for. We know what
his pitches are. It's not that he's an unknown. We know we've got
to be very good to beat him. Last time we weren't very good, and he
beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my second outing,'' recalled Ramon. ``I was very
pleased with the way I pitched against the Indians. I was a little
wild (four walks). I'm going to try to do a little better than
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they took me out of the rotation, I wasn't thinking I'd
make it to the playoffs. But they've given me an opportunity to
pitch and I've taken advantage, and I feel better and better every
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro will be at Ramon's side in the dugout, going over the
Cleveland batters, and maybe talking about the hungry years in the
Dominican when they had no money for baseballs and learned to throw
curveballs using rolled-up balls of tape and the heads of their
sisters' dolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he will give me any advice,'' said Ramon. ``He
might be a little nervous. We will probably talk a little bit about
some of the batters.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to compare his personality with Pedro's, Ramon smiled and
said, ``We're a little different. I mean, he . . . that's all I'm
gonna say. We're a little different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is too skinny,'' said Pedro. ``My other brother, Jesus, is
too skinny. And my brother Nelson is too short. I am just right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon said he thought Pedro could pitch Game 5 Monday if the Sox
win the next two games. Too bad the Sox didn't win Game 1 and let
the Brothers Martinez take the whole series.
</P>
<P>
   The best pitching brother tandem in postseason history was St.
Louis's Dizzy and Paul Dean, who won all four games of the 1934
World Series against the Detroit Tigers. Theoretically, Ramon and
Pedro could set the standard this year.
</P>
<P>
   Or next.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
