<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEVELAND BATS LEAVE RED SOX UNFOCUSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They knew it before, but they know it even better now. They know
it in 0-2 reality. On the verge of being swept out of the American
League's Division Series, the Red Sox return for Game 3 at Fenway
knowing all too well the depth, talent, and persistent
determination of the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're swinging the bats well,'' said Sox outfielder Darren
Lewis, following the 11-1 hammering the Indians put on the Sox
Thursday afternoon at Jacobs Field, lifting Cleveland's advantage
to 2-0 in the best-of-five series. ``You've got to give them
credit. Now we've got to get ourselves refocused.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have been seeking to regain their senses ever since
losing a 2-0 lead in Game 1, an advantage erased by a two-run Jim
Thome bomb over the right-field wall in the sixth inning. Three
innings later, Manny Ramirez scored the winning run, setting the
Sox up the next afternoon for their worst thrashing in postseason
history. The 10-run margin was even worse than the Sox' 12-3 loss
to the Cardinals in Game 4 of the '46 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, Cleveland's combination of Bartolo Colon on the mound
and Thome's blast over the moon was too much. In Game 2, a rehabbed
Bret Saberhagen couldn't come close to matching Charles Nagy, and
the mighty Cleveland lineup amassed all 11 runs by trotting 17
hitters to the plate across the third and fourth innings.
</P>
<P>
   The big hits were a three-run blast by Harold Baines in the
third and a grand slam by Thome (you were expecting maybe Travis
Fryman?) in the fourth. Adding to the feeding frenzy, Saberhagen
and reliever John Wasdin issued a charitable motherlode of six
walks in those two innings. The Indians beat them with their bats
and with their patience for good pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time of the year, you're facing good pitching,'' said
Lewis. ``(In Game 1) it was Colon, and then Nagy kept us off
balance. I think it's good for us to get home and have the
home-field advantage. No one at this point is done. Sure, we would
have liked to have done better, but at the same time, you've got to
give them credit.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Sox have struggled to cobble together a pitching
rotation beyond Pedro Martinez, the Indians have methodically
trotted their starters to the mound. While the Red Sox have sought
more pop than a Nomar Garciaparra-Mike Stanley combination (they
paired up for Boston's five hits in Game 1), the Indians have nine
reliable hitters, all of whom carry an air of offensive
assuredness.
</P>
<P>
   For two games, the Sox have appeared and played like so many
disassembled links in a chain, only to be lashed by the Indians'
bullwhip consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know you don't win any sort of race without having
all your components,'' said Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove.
``Whatever team is out there usually is noted for one or two strong
points, and even if all of their components are solid and strong,
there's a tendency for some to be overlooked. We scored over 1,000
runs this year in the regular season and, you know, everything has
a tendency to be overlooked, you know, beyond that. So we feel like
we've got good, solid starting pitching and we've got a good, solid
bullpen, and really that's the way it's gone for most of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, this Indians team is a far more solid and consistent
bunch than many in Red Sox Nation believed this time a week ago.
Perhaps the Sox were better matched this time, especially in a
short series, but that perceived edge was built solely around Pedro
Martinez's right arm. He was penciled in for two wins (remember?),
but when those went up in the fire that burned in his back muscle
in Game 1, and all the smoke quickly cleared, the Indians were left
standing as the monolith too easily overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our backs are against the wall,'' said third baseman John
Valentin, unduly scorched for a Game 1 error that set the stage for
Thome's destructive two-run homer. ``Nagy pitched well . . .
they've got a great lineup . . . Saberhagen was doing his best to
shut 'em down there . . . but the bottom line is, we have to score
some runs. We've got to be aggressive and take it to them the best
we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear for the Sox is that even a familiar Fenway outburst
might not be enough against the balanced, confident Indians. It may
not be a classic power-hitting assemblage in the Cleveland dugout,
but 1,000 runs in six months, roughly six runs a game, speak for
power and consistency. Whatever the game, they stick around, and
usually win.
</P>
<P>
   Their diversity is a true quality, emphasized Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we catch the ball well, we run the bases well, and
we've got people who hit the ball out of the ballpark,'' he said.
``I think that it's as evenly divided as any club that we've had,
offensively and defensively.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
