<SLUG> BC-CABLE-HOUSEHOLDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS EASE RESTRICTIONS ON CABLE COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal regulators announced revised rules Friday that AT&AMP;T
officials said will allow them to complete their $58 billion
takeover of MediaOne Group by next winter without requiring any
divestment of MediaOne franchises.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission move should also allow
AT&AMP;T to pursue plans to offer local telephone service through
upgraded cable systems to 50 to 55 percent of all American
households, competing with the Baby Bells it was forced to divest
in 1984 and other local phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   And the FCC move could also make it easier for AT&AMP;T-MediaOne to
make a bid to buy or swap franchises elsewhere for the Cablevision
franchises in Boston, adjacent Brookline and 37 Massachusetts
communities. Cablevision has said it plans to sell them by
mid-November to focus on its New York region, and MediaOne, with
1.1 million Bay State customers, has been widely seen as the most
logical buyer.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T owns a 33 percent stake in Cablevision and has 9 percent
voting control. Swapping Massachusetts Cablevision properties for
some of the ownership stake would apparently be one way for AT&AMP;T to
enhance its already densely clustered Bay State operations while
staying within federal ownership guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's long-awaited ruling, the FCC said it would maintain
its 30 percent cap on the number of television homes a single
company can control.
</P>
<P>
   But the FCC voted to change the way that number is calculated,
measuring actual customers rather than homes passed by cable
service and including in the total homes served by satellite dishes
and other wireless systems. That effectively raises the limit on
the share of cable customers AT&AMP;T could control to 36.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with reporters, AT&AMP;T chairman C. Michael
Armstrong said the company understands that the FCC is not counting
toward the cap MediaOne's 25.5 percent stake in Time Warner
Entertainment, which has 11 million customers. As a result,
Armstrong said, AT&AMP;T will be under the 30 percent overall cap even
after adding MediaOne customers to the former TCI franchises it
bought earlier this year for $55 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, however, would not say how close AT&AMP;T thinks it is to
the 30 percent figure. Even though it poses no obstacle to the
MediaOne deal, Armstrong's top lawyer, Jim Cicconi, said AT&AMP;T
continues to oppose the 30 percent figure as ``artificial and
arbitrary'' and will appeal it to the FCC or in court.
</P>
<P>
   The old rule is being challenged in federal appeals court by
Time Warner, with arguments scheduled for December. Cicconi said
AT&AMP;T thinks 40 percent is a more realistic cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new cap permits us to proceed with the MediaOne deal. This
very much adds to the certainty of that deal completing,''
Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AT&AMP;T and MediaOne, which had sunk recently amid Wall
Street uncertainty the deal would ever close, rallied Friday. AT&AMP;T
rose 1/2 to 47 7/16, while MediaOne jumped 1 3/4 to 73 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   FCC chairman William E. Kennard said his agency wants to make it
easier for cable companies to compete for local telephone business
and Internet access. ``The cable industry is a logical provider of
those services, and we want them to move aggressively,'' Kennard
said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong and Cicconi also voiced confidence that the terms of
the FCC ruling will not require the company to sell Liberty Media
Group, a cable channel operator formerly affiliated with TCI that
trades as a separate tracking stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no interest in programming,'' Armstrong said. ``Our
interest is in distribution and extending our local exchange
competitiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gene Kimmelman of Consumers Union, which has strongly
opposed the AT&AMP;T cable deals, said, ``The control of so many wires
into the home as a sole provider, irrespective of how much
programming you own, gives you enormous influence and power over
the programming decisions'' and represents another downside for
consumers to the MediaOne takeover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
