<HEADER>
A1117 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-UN-ROBINSON-BOS &LR;      10-08 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-ROBINSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN'S ROBINSON RECALLS `TERRIBLE STORIES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bless Mary Robinson for all that she hears.
</P>
<P>
   As the United Nations' high commissioner of human rights for the
past two years, Robinson has traveled the world, choosing a path of
misery, listening to tales of great sorrow from Indonesia to Sierra
Leone to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   She was presented Friday with the 1999 J. William Fulbright
Prize for International Understanding Friday at the State
Department, the last in a recent series of plaudits for her ability
to elevate the issue of human rights around the world, to expand
its definition to include economic and social rights, and to stand
up to bullies, on their turf.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the former president of Ireland said in an interview that
the job, while richly rewarding, has been exceedingly difficult.
``It took the first year to turn the office around from a
management point of view to focus on issues of great concern,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   And in two years of travel, she said, the stories have taken an
emotional toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the burden of listening,'' she said. ``The burden
should be shared. I've listened to so many terrible stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they came tumbling out: ``I sat in a mosque in Sierra Leone
where I listened to a husband and wife tell me how their six
children were killed right in front of them. In Pristina, I met
several human rights activists that I had read extensively about,
and one widow told me the exact details about how her husband was
killed on the 24th of March, just as the NATO bombing started, and
how the killers tried to get her son to kill the father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw pregnant women, and children, with arms amputated in
Sierra Leone. In Darwin (Australia), I met people from East Timor
who didn't know what had happened to their families,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates have found some fault in Robinson's
careful handling of China, wishing that she were more
confrontational. And some believe that she could have more
skillfully applied pressure on Rwanda, instead of pulling out her
UN mission to protest the restrictions Rwanda had imposed.
</P>
<P>
   But most offer praise, especially when they compare her to the
UN's first high commisioner for human rights _ her predecessor,
Jose Ayala Lasso of Ecuador _ who was described as ``practically
invisible'' by Curt Goering, deputy executive director of Amnesty
International USA.
</P>
<P>
   ``She calls things as she sees them,'' Goering said Friday.
``She's not hesitant to criticize anyone, including the United
States over its use of the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed Brody, advocacy director for Human Rights Watch in New
York, cited Robinson's work on East Timor. She was the first to
call for a commission of inquiry into atrocities committed by
militias following East Timor's vote for independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not afraid to describe the atrocities there, which is
very difficult when you are talking about the fourth most populous
nation in the world,'' Brody said. ``She earned herself a lot of
enemies because she is so forthright.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington over the past two days, Robinson met with White
House and State Department officials and members of Congress on a
broad range of topics, including the need for the United States to
pay its $1.6 billion debt to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fulbright award ceremony Friday, Robinson focused on what
was most dear to her. Borrowing the words of Eleanor Roosevelt,
Robinson noted that ``human rights begins in small places, in the
world of individual person.'' And, she said, ``it must be
understood that all human rights must be equally championed and
protected.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of education for millions around the world especially
``works against young girls, who account for two-thirds'' of
dropouts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson spoke about sending out representatives who focus on
the right for education for all. And she spoke about funding small
efforts to encourage learning, such as one in Nepal in which a
teacher walks to 15 high schools to talk about human rights or one
in Burundi where copies of the Universal Declaration of Human
Rights are handed out in refugee camps, including one recent
session for 200 women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see my job as a voice for the victims, someone who can stand
up to the bullies, confront foreign ministers, even prime
ministers,'' she said in the interview. ``And when I hear about
extreme poverty, I immediately think of the impact on women and how
vulnerable it makes them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
