<SLUG> BC-XEROX-EARNINGS-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XEROX WARNS OF LOWER EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Xerox Corp., reeling from inroads that competitors are making
into its markets even as its own sales force is in disarray, warned
analysts Friday that its third-quarter results would be dismal.
</P>
<P>
   The document processing company, which is based in Stamford,
Conn., said its revenue would not top the $4.61 billion it reported
in the same quarter last year, and its earnings could be as much as
12 percent below the 53 cents per diluted share that it earned in
the third quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That comes to less than 47 cents a share, way below the 58 cents
a share that analysts had been predicting. Analysts rushed to
downgrade their earnings estimates for this year and next, and to
pull their ``buy'' recommendations off the stock. Xerox shares
plunged $10.25, or 24 percent, to close at $32.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was more than just fine-tuning estimates; this was a sign
of a really big disappointment,'' said Charles Hill, director of
research at First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks analysts'
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Xerox, Richard Thoman, held a conference
call for analysts at 2 p.m. to reiterate his confidence in Xerox's
strategies. But he did not take questions, and few analysts seemed
appeased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously they are shell-shocked, but they did not say
anything new,'' said Peter Enderlin, an analyst at First Albany
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Enderlin and others hung up wondering whether Xerox would try to
bolster earnings with more job cuts or a stock buy-back. Both
scenarios are unlikely. Xerox has already cut more than 6,000 jobs
this year. ``They're pretty much tapped out on restructuring in
terms of cushioning the top line,'' said Jonathan Rosenzweig, who
covers Xerox for Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Since Xerox last month agreed to buy Tektronix Inc.'s
color-printing business for $950 million in cash, it would be
difficult to budget for stock buy-backs soon. Some analysts
question whether that purchase itself was a sign of internal
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have been able to bring their own color product to
market,'' said Alexander Henderson, an analyst with Prudential
Securities Research.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Xerox is battling problems on all fronts. It is plagued
with weak sales in Brazil and Europe. It imports many of its
engines and other parts from Fuji Xerox, so the strong yen has been
a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Xerox's super-fast digital copiers, which command
prices as high as $250,000 and have virtually no competition, have
been slow. And fierce competition for the lower-margin, midpriced
market, particularly from multifunction devices that double as
printers and copiers, has kept Xerox from raising prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Staking out the very high end has always paid off for Xerox,
but now customers are getting their needs met by less than
top-of-the-line product,'' said Hadley Reynolds, director of
research for the Delphi Group, a consulting firm in Boston.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Customers are choosing the solutions they find most
acceptable, and increasingly that means us,'' said Nolan Sundrud, a
spokesman for Hewlett-Packard Co., which offers several
multifunction products.
</P>
<P>
   Canon Inc., meanwhile, introduced a new line of digital copiers
in March that sell for as much as $20,000 less than comparable
Xerox products.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's name is good enough to justify a $20,000 price
difference, and we're winning business that we've never been able
to compete for in the past,'' said Dennis Amorosano, assistant
director of networked office systems for Canon USA.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox's sales force is in poor condition to fight back. Xerox is
about to rejigger its sales territories, now organized by
geography, around particular customer industries instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realigning the sales force is probably a good long-term move,
but it is certainly creating instability now,'' said Benjamin
Reitzes, who follows Xerox for Paine Webber. Xerox acknowledges the
problem. ``It's been more disruptive than we anticipated, and our
execution was less than we wanted,'' said Judd Everhart, a Xerox
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the debacle left Xerox with one powerful thing going for
it: It is now a very cheap stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the selling was a bit overdone,'' Reitzes of Paine
Webber said. Nonetheless he removed his ``buy'' recommendation on
the stock. In contrast, Gibboney Huske of Credit Suisse First
Boston is suggesting that investors snap up Xerox shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock's cheap, it offers good risk return, and there's not
a lot more downside,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
