<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-EDITOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JAMA EDITOR SAYS SHE HAS PROTECTION BUILT INTO DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the American Medical Association fired the editor of its
esteemed journal last January over a dispute about editorial
judgment, an editorial board member named Dr. Catherine D. De
Angelis angrily denounced the decision to AMA executive vice
president Dr. E. Ratcliffe Anderson, the axe-wielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gave an impassioned speech about how much damage they had
done to medicine and journalistic integrity, and how important this
journal is to American medicine,'' said a fellow editorial board
member.
</P>
<P>
   Friday the AMA named De Angelis editor-in-chief of the
Chicago-based Journal of the American Medical Association,
customarily known as JAMA, the world's largest-circulation medical
journal.
</P>
<P>
   The 59-year-old De Angelis, a dean and pediatrics professor at
Johns Hopkins University, is the first woman to hold the editor's
post in JAMA's 116-year history _ not to mention the first
pediatrician and the first nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Her appointment, combined with the recent ascension of Dr.
Marcia Angell to the editor-in-chief's chair at the rival New
England Journal of Medicine, means that two of the world's top
medical journals are in the hands of women.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the significance of that, De Angelis made word-play
on her name and Angell's: ``It means that the devils are gone and
the angels are in...I'm joking!''
</P>
<P>
   Angell, asked the same question, shot back: ``There goes the
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the unusual confluence of female editorial
leadership may not last long. Angell holds an interim position at
the New England Journal, which she took last summer after the
Massachusetts Medical Society, its publisher, fired editor-in-chief
Dr. Jerome P. Kassirer in a dispute over the medical society's
intent to exploit the journal's name for commercial gain. The
medical society has just begun to look for a permanent replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect her life expectancy'' as editor ``will be longer
than mine,'' Angell said of De Angelis.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Angell and De Angelis find themselves at the twin
peaks of medical publishing at a moment when many are wondering if
any editor can hold the line against pressures that arise when
physician-interest groups are publishers of lucrative, influential
journals.
</P>
<P>
   De Angelis swears she can, and will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about that at all,'' she said in an interview.
She pointed to a new seven-member Journal Oversight Committee that
the AMA set up in June to protect the JAMA editor (who also
oversees nine other AMA journals and its website) from future
interference by AMA management.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new AMA ``editorial governance plan'' issued in
June, the new committee, which will contain only one AMA official,
must vote on ``any proposal to dismiss the editor-in-chief for any
reason'' and pass its recommendations on to the AMA board of
trustees. It will take a two-third majority of the trustees to fire
the next JAMA editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``AMA management recognizes and fully accepts the necessity of
editorial independence for the editor-in-chief at all times,'' the
``editorial governance plan'' declared.
</P>
<P>
   If that pledge is broken, De Angelis said Friday, ``there will
be no more JAMA, I can assure you.''
</P>
<P>
   The prognosis among observers is somewhat guarded.
</P>
<P>
   The new AMA policy ``offers quite a bit of protection, if it
works as advertised,'' Angell said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Blendon, a Harvard University health policy expert who is
on JAMA's editorial board, predicted that De Angelis would be able
to stand up to AMA pressures. ``They didn't pick her because she is
quiet on editorial independence,'' Blendon said. ``When George
Lundberg was fired, there was no one more vociferous, more angry,
and more eloquent.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Blendon said De Angelis will likely ``be a
little bit more cautious'' than Lundberg, ``because that's her
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tom Delbanco, chief of general medicine at Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center and a JAMA columnist, remained skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, no matter what firewalls are put up or safeguards
there are on paper, I'd be surprised if over time the goals of the
AMA big boss and the goals of a first-class editor will be in
sync,'' Delbanco said.
</P>
<P>
   De Angelis made one clear distinction between herself and
Lundberg, who often said he was ``a journalist first, then a
doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded of Lundberg's self-characterization, De Angelis
replied: ``I am a physician first, last, and always. I'll make
news, but in my own way _ as one of the keepers of the educational
and scientific flame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
