<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1128 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CLINTON-TESTBAN-BOS &LR;      10-08 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TESTBAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SENATORS SCUTTLED TEST-BAN TREATY, CLINTON SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ President Clinton Friday conceded defeat on his fight
to ratify a global nuclear test-ban treaty and lashed out at Senate
Republicans he charged were playing politics with international
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've treated this like a political document. This whole
thing is about politics,'' Clinton said during a joint news
conference with Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien.
</P>
<P>
   ``This treaty was never treated seriously,'' said Clinton, in
Canada to dedicate the new American Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the treaty has huge implications for both nuclear
testing and for US foreign policy. But in his most direct attack on
Republican handling of the treaty issue to date, Clinton insisted
the matter had come down to simple, partisan politics at the
expense of international non-proliferation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about, `Burn us in 1999, because we're against the treaty
that 80 percent of the American people support, but please don't
burn us again in 2000,' '' Clinton said, referring to Senate
Republicans who are insisting that Clinton formally withdraw the
treaty and promise not to bring it up again for the remainder of
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   While the president said he hoped the Senate would delay acting
on the document, he wasn't committing to keeping it out of Congress
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signed the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty in 1996 before
the United Nations, calling it one of the most important steps
toward achieving world peace. Ratification of the treaty would add
a key historic footnote to Clinton's troubled legacy as president.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty would ban underground and above-ground nuclear
testing, an agreement proponents say would curtail the behavior of
rogue nations who have or are working toward nuclear capability.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the treaty worry that the verification technology
is not sophisticated enough to keep other signers in line. Other
foes of the treaty take a fundamentalist, isolationist view that
the United States should not limit its military capability by arms
control.
</P>
<P>
   When Senate Republicans abruptly pushed for a ratification vote
_ after the treaty had sat dormant for two years _ the Clinton
administration mounted a heavy lobbying effort, including a White
House dinner for wavering senators and personal calls from
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright and Defense Secretary
William S. Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the votes,'' Clinton said bluntly Friday. White
House officials believe to be 15 or more votes short of the 67
necessary to ratify the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   It's still unclear whether the vote will be put off. Senate
Democrats were trying to convince Republicans to delay the vote,
tentatively scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican push for a vote is ``pigheaded,'' said Senate
minority leader Thomas Daschle. ``Our allies in Europe, they are
lobbying today saying what the Senate is doing is nuts, it is
wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the major nuclear testing treaty, then, has come
down to procedural sparring. The White House says scheduling the
vote is not in its hands but in the power of Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats say they might try the unusual tactic of
calling for a procedural vote to halt the treaty vote, a strategy
that would require a simple majority of senators, instead of the
two-thirds needed to ratify the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   That idea, in turn, ruffled Senate Republican leader Trent Lott,
who noted that such scheduling changes were traditionally made by
the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get an agreement'' to delay the vote, ``we will
oppose'' the Democratic procedural effort to stop it, Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse
Helms of North Carolina, an outspoken Clinton foe, says Clinton
indeed has the power to stop the vote _ providing the president
makes the politically humiliating move of asking in writing.
</P>
<P>
   Helms also wants Clinton to promise not to bring the treaty up
again for the remainder of his presidency, a deal that would
deprive Clinton of his long-desired foreign policy credit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton at first indicated he would refuse. ``So they want me to
give them a letter to cover the political decision they have made
that does severe damage to the interests of the United States and
the interest of nonproliferation around the world? I don't think
so,'' Clinton said defiantly.
</P>
<P>
   But later, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart softened Clinton's
statement. ``It was not a blanket, sermonesque statement, `I will
not send a letter.' The intention there, I think, was conciliatory,
to say, ``Let's work together,' '' Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he is reluctant to agree not to bring up the treaty
again next year, since world events might make it necessary to
consider it again.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff is likely to continue over the weekend, as
Democrats search for a way to protect their president from a floor
vote, which would certainly result in a rejection of the treaty. If
there is a vote, it would be the first time since the League of
Nations vote during the Woodrow Wilson administration that a
foreign policy treaty was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is going to be a resolution until the last
minute on Tuesday,'' said a Democratic Senate aide close to the
talks. ``Feelings are running pretty strong on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the treaty are concerned that an out-and-out
rejection of the document would embarrass the United States. As the
world's only remaining superpower, the United States would look
arrogant by voting down a standard it has pleaded with the rest of
the world to adopt, analysts in support of the treaty say.
</P>
<P>
   Some nations are already irritated at the United States' refusal
to participate in the International Criminal Court, or to join the
international ban on land mines, noted Lawrence Korb of the Council
on Foreign Relations.
</P>
<P>
   Without the treaty, ``the notion of being able to control this
stuff, and to manage the international system, is pretty much
shot,'' said Dan Doure, deputy director of political and military
studies at the Center for Strategic and International Studies in
Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
