<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1132 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-PINOCHET-EXTRADITE-BO     10-08 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-EXTRADITE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET EXTRADITION TO SPAIN GETS BRITISH OK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In the latest twist to a yearlong legal saga, a
magistrate cleared the way Friday for the extradition to Spain of
Augusto Pinochet, Chile's former military dictator, on charges that
he tortured political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in Bow Street Magistrates Court, Metropolitan Magistrate
Ronald D. Bartle ruled that 35 charges of torture and conspiracy
against Pinochet were legally sound and should be resolved at a
trial in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's lawyers have 15 days to file an appeal, and it could
be months before the case is finally resolved. The final decision
to extradite Pinochet rests with Home Secretary Jack Straw, who
will rule after all legal appeals are exhausted. But just when that
will be is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said Bartle's decision makes it likely that
Pinochet's only chance at avoiding extradition is to ask Straw to
let him return to Chile on humanitarian grounds because of failing
health.
</P>
<P>
   Bartle had excused the 83-year-old Pinochet from attending
Friday's hearing after being told the former dictator had suffered
two minor strokes recently at the mansion in Surrey where he is
under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   But, apparently expecting the decision to go against him,
Pinochet prepared a defiant statement which his lawyer, Clive
Nicholls, read out in court after Bartle's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not guilty of the crimes of which I am accused,''
Pinochet wrote. ``Spain has not produced a single piece of evidence
which shows that I'm guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet said Spain's attempts to extradite him for alleged
crimes that took place after Pinochet led a coup against the
democratically elected president Salvador Allende in 1973 amounted
to a violation of Chile's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The events in Chile have nothing whatsoever to do with
Spain,'' Pinochet wrote. ``It has long been clear that my
extradition is politically motivated and being pursued purely for
political reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   But while acknowledging that the Pinochet case has aroused
political passions in which left-wingers see Pinochet as ``the arch
devil'' and right-wingers see him as ``the savior of Chile,''
Bartle insisted his decision was based on a dispassionate
interpretation of extradition law.
</P>
<P>
   Bartle rejected defense arguments that 33 of the charges should
be thrown out because they were not included in the original
charges filed by Spanish authorities. He also rejected the defense
claims that Spain did not have jurisdiction over crimes committed
against non-Spaniards, accepting the argument by lawyers acting for
the Spanish authorities that an international convention outlawing
torture gives jurisdiction to all signatories.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's ruling triggered celebrations outside the court, where
several hundred Pinochet opponents gathered under the imposing
columns of the newly refurbished Royal Opera House to await the
verdict. Their hands daubed in red paint to symbolize the blood
they say is on Pinochet's hands, they sang songs and chanted
slogans against Pinochet and former British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, who earlier this week voiced a spirited defense of
Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling prompted cheers in Chile among hundreds of
anti-Pinochet protesters, who also chanted ``Pinochet, prisoner!
Pinochet, prisoner!'' as they marched in downtown Santiago. The
ex-dictator's supporters burned British and Spanish flags in
protest, and Chile made a new effort to get Pinochet for trial at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Among those demonstrating in London was Teresa Villalobos, 49,
whose brother Manuel is among the estimated 3,000 ``disappeared''
who vanished and are believed to have been murdered by the Pinochet
regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crimes that happened in Chile under Pinochet were
unthinkable,'' said Villalobos, who had black and white photographs
of her brother and her cousin, who also disappeared, pinned to her
jacket. ``But there is a new climate about human rights, and I
think this is part of a campaign to build a better society.''
</P>
<P>
   Villalobos, who traveled from her home in Santiago to be present
for the ruling, said she was appalled by Thatcher's ringing defense
of Pinochet. Thatcher used her first speech at a Conservative Party
conference in nine years to accuse the government of Prime Minister
Tony Blair of collaborating in the ``political kidnapping'' of
Pinochet. Thatcher described Pinochet as Britain's ``only political
prisoner,'' and said it was a disgrace the way Britain was treating
its staunchest ally during its 1980 war with Argentina over the
Falkland Islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman has no humanity,'' Villalobos said of Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's legal saga here is a long and convoluted one. Last
October, British police arrested Pinochet as he recovered from back
surgery in a London clinic. They were acting on a warrant issued by
a Spanish magistrate who wants to try Pinochet for human rights
abuses committed during and after the 1973 coup.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the House of Lords, England's highest court of
appeal, ruled 3-2 that Pinochet did not enjoy immunity from
prosecution because he was a head of state. But that ruling was set
aside after one of the judges failed to disclose his links to
Amnesty International, one of the human rights groups seeking
Pinochet's prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   In March, another panel of Law Lords ruled that Pinochet must
face an extradition hearing, but that he was immune from
prosecution for crimes committed before 1988, when a United Nations
convention against torture took effect in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Even if extradited and convicted, Pinochet will not be
imprisoned because Spain forbids incarceration of anyone over 75.
But human rights advocates say his prosecution will set a precedent
and put other despots on notice that they will face international
justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision confirms that the world is becoming a smaller
place for people who commit atrocities,'' said Reed Brody, advocacy
director of Human Rights Watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
