<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1136 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-DENMARK-WIND-ART-NYT &LR;      10-08 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENMARK-WIND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENMARK MOVES AHEAD IN WIND POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAMSO, Denmark _ Imagine a Danish landscape: half-timbered
houses sagging at midbeam, farmlands sloping toward the sea,
crenelated church belfries with their masonry step notches marching
up the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays that's an incomplete portrait. Bringing it up to date
means making room for sleek, silvery towers with long-bladed
propellers on top.
</P>
<P>
   Danes are putting windmills _ or wind turbines, as the modern
versions are called _ all over their picturesque place. There are
small private ones in backyards, larger ones in open fields and
rows of giant industrial-strength ones standing single file in
shallow offshore waters.
</P>
<P>
   The move to wind power makes particular sense for Denmark, an
intensely ecology-minded country that is a low-lying assemblage of
407 islands and a large peninsula in one of the breeziest corners
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Wind power has also become a big business for Denmark. It
exports windmills to 35 countries and accounts for more than 50
percent of all the devices manufactured in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we decided 25 years ago that we wouldn't have nuclear
power, we had to ask ourselves, `What do we do now?' '' Soren
Hermansen said as he walked through a pasture behind his house to
show a visitor the windmill he and his neighbors own.
</P>
<P>
   Hermansen, called an energy adviser on his business card, has
returned to the island where he was born 40 years ago to help Samso
fulfill its designation as the chosen site for a 10-year government
project to convert an entire Danish community into one powered 100
percent by renewable energy. Samso won over four other finalists by
submitting a plan to live a decade from now on nothing but solar,
wind and biomass energy from organic waste and agricultural
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the venture turns on the participation of the
island's 4,400 inhabitants, which by law must be voluntary. No
problem in Denmark. Signs of people's concern with the environment
are anywhere you look.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhoods across the country have recycling centers full of
glossy field-green deposit boxes with stenciled instructions on
their sides identifying what you should put in them. To coax people
out of their cars, the country has set up more than 6,000 miles of
marked cycle routes, and in downtown Copenhagen there are
distinctly colored public bicycles activated by putting coins in
the handlebars to enable people to taxi themselves around.
</P>
<P>
   Products with red and white ``stats-kontrolleret ekologisk''
stickers take up more and more supermarket shelves, crowding out
the space left for foods that don't carry the state's additive-free
assurance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971 Denmark became the first European country to create a
Cabinet-level ministry dealing exclusively with the environment. It
now boasts that half of all waste is recycled and 80 percent of new
paper is made from used paper. Businesses pay a tax on their carbon
dioxide emissions, with the revenue going to finance various energy
conservation and efficiency plans.
</P>
<P>
   Magrethe Auken, 54, a member of the Danish Parliament, excitedly
interrupted a conversation about ecology to point out the window to
the parking lot below her office. ``Those spaces used to hold eight
cars,'' she said, ``but now they've been freed up to hold 80
bicycles. Tell me another parliament in the world that would do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The country's largest public works project, the 9.5-mile, $2
billion link between Copenhagen and the Swedish city of Malmo due
to open in July, was delayed for years by environmental concerns.
There were doubts about its effect on water flow from the Baltic,
and on the birds, frogs, ducks and seals that breed on a limestone
island in the straits separating the two countries. At considerable
added expense, an artificial landfill island was formed to enable
builders to tunnel under the sea and not disturb the fragile watery
environment.
</P>
<P>
   The Tivoli Gardens amusement park in Copenhagen is focusing its
promotion these days on its success in bringing its heating and
lighting systems under central control, converting its vehicles to
electricity, turning its kitchen waste into feed for 1,400 pigs,
monitoring the watering of its acres of flowerbeds and clearing up
its algae-choked lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go out to explain to people why moving to renewable
energy is a good thing,'' Hermansen said, ``it helps to make the
economic argument about saving oil costs, selling wind power and
getting government money. But there is a good feeling among Danes
about self-sufficiency and the environment I can play on, too.
Danes have a romantic attachment to the idea of leaving land
unharmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservation in Denmark not only benefits from high levels of
public support _ 80 percent of the country's windmills are owned by
individuals or cooperatives _ but also profits from the individual
ingenuity of people in places like Samso.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the earliest windmills on the island, still spinning away
15 years after being put up, were built by a local plumber. A
gardener, Kai Alexandersen, 69, proudly pointed out two solar
panels on the roof of his toolshed and the nest of tubes and pumps
carrying the gathered power to his house.
</P>
<P>
   How had he managed to create and install the elaborate system,
he was asked. ``With these,'' he said, extending his weathered
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ways the project aims to achieve its goal: improving
home insulation; centralizing community heating and focusing it on
wood chip furnaces and straw-burning stoves; creating biogas from
manure, organic waste and potato tops from the island's principal
farm product, and gradually converting the island's fleet of cars
and vans to electricity. People who agree to take these steps get
grants from the government to help pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes of powering all the vehicles and ferryboats with ethanol
were dashed when planners calculated that producing sufficient
rapeseed oil for the task would use up all the agricultural land on
the 17-mile-long island. Instead, Samso will deliver extra
wind-generated energy to the national grid to compensate for the
gasoline it burns.
</P>
<P>
   Wind energy today covers 7 percent of Danish electricity
consumption and will rise to 50 percent by 2030, according to the
Danish Ministry of Environment and Energy.
</P>
<P>
   This flat land of only 5.3 million people may be marginal to
many of the world's endeavors. But in terms of wind power
development, Denmark finds itself the hub of global activity.
</P>
<P>
   One person happy with Denmark's position at the center is Soren
Krohn, managing director of the Danish Wind Turbine Manufacturers
Association. ``The Danes,'' he said, ``were fortunate to be in the
right place at the right time with the right concept.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
