<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     10-08 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE ACQUISITIONS ROAD, STAY ALERT TO THE HAZARDS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was the best and worst of times in corporate
mergerville last week. On the one hand, investors were giddy over
MCI Worldcom's plan for a $130 billion all-stock merger with
Sprint, announced on Tuesday. Telecommunications stocks jumped on
the news of the gigadeal.
</P>
<P>
   One day earlier, though, a different merger hit the skids.
Mattel Inc., the toy giant with $4.8 billion in sales, stunned
investors with news that problems at its Learning Company
subsidiary, acquired less than five months earlier for $3.8
billion, would result in an after-tax loss of $50 million to $100
million in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This was a far cry from the $50 million that Mattel had expected
the division to earn in that period. The toy maker's stock plunged
30 percent that day, to $11.875. It ended the week at $11.8125.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel's woes illustrate the obvious but often overlooked fact
that not all corporate marriages are created equal. Some are wise;
others are breathtakingly foolish.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for shareholders in a combined company, it is not
always easy to tell whether an acquisition will succeed. But with
more mergers taking place _ the dollar amount of combinations
worldwide is up 24 percent from last year, according to Thomson
Financial Securities Data _ investors need to be on the lookout for
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, investors cannot always count on management to
uncover problems in a potential purchase, as the Mattel case shows.
When she announced the deal, Mattel's chairman, Jill E. Barad,
gushed, ``We are truly excited about the benefits to be realized
through the combination of our two great companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barad was not available last week to comment on those
benefits. A Mattel spokesman said that the company had done due
diligence on the Learning Company and that its problems came as a
big surprise.
</P>
<P>
   But Howard M. Schilit, president of the Center for Financial
Research and Analysis, said troubles at the Learning Company were
well-known for years. Mattel, Schilit said, ``bought a company that
had a lot of problems, and I don't think they did sufficient due
diligence before they bought it.''
</P>
<P>
   How can investors protect themselves from being bagged by a bad
acquisition? Two clues can signal problems, Schilit said, and both
were obvious enough for his company to issue a negative report on
Mattel last July.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign is a severe slowdown in sales growth at the
acquiring company, or even worse, a decline. Such a situation may
prompt management to make an acquisition because it will deliver a
quick boost to sales, not because it makes business sense.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel's revenues fell 8.1 percent in the March quarter of the
company's fiscal 1999 from the corresponding period a year earlier;
for the full year, they declined 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors should also examine the company being acquired. The
picture at the Learning Company was not pretty. In the March
quarter, revenue growth fell to 4.2 percent from levels above 25
percent in each of the previous three periods. And cash flow from
operations plunged from $28.2 million in the 1998 quarter to a
negative $42.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Schilit said, the Learning Company was a classic case
of an acquisition that would come back to bite shareholders. The
only question now is why Ms. Barad couldn't see the pig in this
poke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
