<HEADER>
A1153 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV10-NYT     10-08 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rara Avis at GM: A Director From Japan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Nobuyuki Idei, Sony's chief executive, was named to the
board of General Motors last week, he joined only a handful of
other Asian executives who are directors of United States
companies. Among the few are Goro Watanabe, vice chairman of Mitsui
Chemicals, who serves on DuPont's board, and Minoru Makihara,
chairman of Mitsubishi, who is on IBM's.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the corporate talk of globalization, big business
often leaves its multinationalism at the board-room door.
</P>
<P>
   John T.W. Hawkins, a managing director at Russell Reynolds
Associates, a headhunting firm in New York, says very few
executives are willing to cross the Pacific to attend frequent
board meetings. And given the turmoil in Asian economies, he added,
American companies have become even less willing to try recruiting
directors in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But companies are more likely to look to Europe, he said.
European directors can make a day trip out of a board meeting by
hopping on the Concorde, particularly if the company is based in
New York. No such snappy commutes are possible from Tokyo or
Seoul. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Reed Abelson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Whose Side Is He Really On? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The technology revolution reshaping Wall Street was the topic
for a daylong conference on Wednesday at Pace University in New
York City. But the ambient excitement about the new E-market was
not shared by the luncheon speaker, Alan C. (Ace) Greenberg,
chairman of Bear Stearns Cos.
</P>
<P>
   After amusing the crowd with homespun anecdotes about his
famously pithy office memos, Greenberg, who is 72, played down the
significance of online brokerage services and the advent of
electronic communications networks, or ECNs, the upstart trading
systems that are challenging traditional markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who owns a dog owns an ECN,'' Greenberg said, adding
that his firm wasn't jumping on that particular bandwagon. ``I
don't see the need for them.'' That may have come as a surprise to
the management of Strike, one of the new ECNs, whose big investors
include the Bear Stearns Companies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Diana B. Henriques &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a Buyout, Life After Lilco &QL;
</P>
<P>
   William J. Catacosinos, former chairman of the Long Island
Lighting Co., who left in July 1998 amid an outcry over his $42
million golden parachute, has another act to stage. This time, the
scene is Texas, the plot the first leveraged buyout of an electric
utility.
</P>
<P>
   At the now-defunct Lilco, Catacosinos abandoned the Shoreham
nuclear project after billions of dollars were invested, and
electricity rates on Long Island soared. Now, at age 69, he is
leading an investor group that is offering $585 million plus the
assumption of $434 million in debt for TNP Enterprises, owner of
the Texas-New Mexico Power Co., with 229,000 customers in Texas and
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Though leveraged buyouts and the resulting debt have been
regarded as too risky for utilities, deregulation is changing the
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Catacosinos and his group are getting close to completing the
deal after 98 percent of the shareholders approved the buyout late
last month. Federal and state regulatory approvals are still
needed. Catacosinos and his group have pledged that there will be
no layoffs. He has refused to comment further. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Agis Salpukas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Too Much Rest for This Driver &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Medical researchers, confirming what many suburbanites already
know, have reported that long-distance commuters suffer from
chronic sleep deprivation. But Thomas Purves, chairman and chief
executive of BMW's operations in the Americas, would like his
commute to be longer.
</P>
<P>
   Purves has a morning commute that many New Jersey residents can
only dream about: just a 10-minute drive, from Upper Saddle River
to Woodcliff Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the shortest commute I've ever had, and the pity of it
is I have the best car I've ever had,'' said Purves, who drives a
BMW 740i ($63,000 and provided by the company).
</P>
<P>
   A Scotsman who has lived in Europe for most of his career, he
moved to New Jersey this year. In the past, his commute stretched
to more than an hour. Now his biggest lament is, ``I can't
test-drive cars on the way home.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Robyn Meredith &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
