<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1158 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LAGARDE-LAWFIRM-ART-6     10-08 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAGARDE-LAWFIRM-ART-635(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD'S SECOND-LARGEST LAW FIRM HEADED BY WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ When Christine Lagarde found out she was soon to
become the top partner at Baker &AMP; McKenzie, the world's
second-largest law firm, she called friends all over the globe for
advice on what to call herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chairperson'' seemed to be a made-up word, she said. If she
shortened the title to simply ``chair,'' it would sound as if she
were becoming a piece of furniture. And one friend advised against
``chairwoman,'' surmising that some partners might vote for a man
next time, if only to have a ``chairman'' again.
</P>
<P>
   So Ms. Lagarde, who becomes the first woman to lead the
Chicago-based Baker &AMP; McKenzie, will be known as chairman, just
like her predecessor and the many men before him. Of the United
States' 20 largest law firms, Mayer, Brown &AMP; Platt is the only
other one with a woman in the top job.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lagarde, who is French, lives in Paris and speaks Spanish
and English as well as French. She said this week that she may have
had an easier time getting the top job at Baker &AMP; McKenzie, which
has offices in 35 countries and lawyers of dozens of nationalities,
than she might have had at other American firms not so dispersed
over the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our firm has to be extremely tolerant and open,'' she said.
``Diversity is part of us. I think a lot of law firms tend to be
more traditional, more clubby. Women are not so included in those
firms as they are in my environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it took half a century for partners at Baker &AMP; McKenzie
to choose a woman to lead them. The firm is celebrating its 50th
anniversary this year.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Lagarde's elevation to the top job is a sign that women
are finally moving into power at some major law firms, which have
been behind even their clients in corporate America at promoting
women into management's upper echelons. (She was formally elected
late Thursday by an overwhelming majority of the firm's 548
partners, 91 percent of whom are men.)
</P>
<P>
   Just within the last year or so, partners of at least five of
the top 100 U.S. law firms _ including Pillsbury Madison &AMP; Sutro of
San Francisco and Hughes Hubbard &AMP; Reed of New York _ have chosen
women to lead them. But these firms all have far fewer lawyers than
Baker &AMP; McKenzie's 2,487.
</P>
<P>
   Debora de Hoyos, a managing partner at Mayer, Brown, said:
``It's a simple fact of the passage of time. There are more women
now in the prime of their careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while only about 5 percent of law school graduates in
1970 were women, that figure is now closer to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lagarde, 43, also becomes one of the youngest partners to
manage Baker &AMP; McKenzie. She succeeds John Klotsche, now 57, who
was 53 when he took over.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lagarde said she believed women were now beginning to move
into higher positions because some clients were demanding it. More
corporations have hired women as corporate counsels, she said, and
in turn, those lawyers are asking that the teams of outside lawyers
they hire look more like their legal departments.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ms. Lagarde said, women at law firms now have at
least a few female colleagues as role models. She said that one of
hers was a female partner in Baker &AMP; McKenzie's Paris office who
had hired her in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the only female partner in the office at that time,''
Ms. Lagarde said, ``yet she was running the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker &AMP; McKenzie has also changed its compensation structure so
that women lawyers get three months' paid maternity leave, Ms.
Lagarde said. While she said she had no plans to change other
policies at the firm to help women, she added that she hoped her
election would help convince many of the firm's lawyers _ male and
female _ that women can excel in management as much as men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that I'm a she and not a he, that in itself is
helpful to a lot of female lawyers,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Baker &AMP; McKenzie _ the United States' largest law firm in number
of lawyers and, until the merger this summer of the British firm
Clifford Chance with various other firms, the world's largest as
well _ has had its share of scandals involving allegations of
sexual harassment and discrimination because of sex or sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, a secretary won more than $3 million in damages after
suing the firm, alleging that she had been sexually harassed by one
of the partners. Part of the film ``Philadelphia'' is said to be
based on the story of a Baker &AMP; McKenzie lawyer who claimed he had
been fired when he contracted AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Ingrid Beall, then a 65-year-old senior tax partner,
filed a lawsuit charging that she had been pushed aside in the firm
because of her sex and age. ``This is a firm that has the feeling
that women are second-class citizens,'' Ms. Beall said at the time.
``You are not supposed to be as good as they are.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Lagarde said that in her 18 years at the firm she had
never felt discriminated against because of her sex.
</P>
<P>
   She said she did remember one business deal she was working on
with a male lawyer at the firm. While both she and the other lawyer
were partners, she said, ``our clients were convinced that I was
his assistant. I never worked for them again.''
</P>
<P>
   An expert in employment and antitrust law, Ms. Lagarde has
worked for clients like Levi's, Great Lakes Chemical and the French
company Finacor. From 1991 to 1995, she was co-managing partner of
Baker &AMP; McKenzie's Paris office. In 1995, she was nominated to the
firm's executive committee, where she was the liaison for 11
offices in Western Europe. She served as chairman of the firm's
European regional council from 1997 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She became a partner in 1987 at the age of 31, younger than
average.
</P>
<P>
   As the mother of two boys _ Pete, 13, and Tom, 11 _ Ms. Lagarde
said she had learned to switch quickly between her roles of
high-powered lawyer and caring mother. She said that although she
has to be away from her children a lot because of her business
travels, she tries to make it up to them when she is at home.
</P>
<P>
   And she makes sure she calls the boys in the morning before they
leave for school and at night before they go to sleep, no matter
what time it is in the country where she is working. ``If that
means waking up at 2 a.m.,'' she said, ``then so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Lagarde will still be based in Paris, she will have
to spend a great deal of time either at the firm's Chicago base or
at its offices in New York, London, Moscow and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   When she, her husband and her sons are together on weekends,
they often travel to their country house in Normandy, where they
ride bicycles together or plant flowers and vegetables in a large
garden.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Eachran Gilmour, who runs a business in Poland,
said he was not surprised when he learned his wife would get the
top job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are more employable and reliable, and they're smarter,''
Gilmour said. ``Males have to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that neither he nor his wife had been left giddy by
her new status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't turn my head,'' he said of Ms. Lagarde's new title.
``It doesn't turn her head either. It's a job.''
</P>
<P>
   John Conroy, Baker &AMP; McKenzie's managing partner for its offices
in the United States, said Ms. Lagarde was a lawyer who ``puts
clients first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was selected on her merits,'' he said, ``but it's a
terrific bonus that she's a female.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lagarde's energy is apparent even in her choice of hotels
during her frequent business trips. As a former member of the
French national team of synchronized swimmers, she chooses only
hotels with pools, so she can squeeze in an early-morning swim.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what advice she would give to other lawyers who want to
run their law firms, Ms. Lagarde did not hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grit your teeth, because it is a matter of resilience, stamina
and energy,'' she said. ``And never try to imitate what the boys
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
