<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1162 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LABOR-SWEENEY-860(2TA     10-08 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-SWEENEY-860(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER SWEENEY, A RENAISSANCE FOR ORGANIZED LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When John Sweeney took the helm of the AFL-CIO four years ago,
the labor movement was spiraling downward. It was steadily losing
membership, politicians dismissed it as a toothless has-been, and
much of the public viewed it as an irrelevant dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, on the eve of the labor federation's
convention in Los Angeles, things have turned around big time for
big labor.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley are tripping
over each other to win the AFL-CIO's crucial endorsement for the
Democratic presidential nomination. Lawmakers are newly attentive
to labor's revived muscle as unions play a heavyweight role in
Congress, pushing for a patient's bill of rights and a higher
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Unionized workers at DaimlerChrysler and Boeing have hit grand
slams in their latest contracts. And in February, unions pulled off
their biggest organizing victory in six decades, organizing 74,000
Los Angeles health-care workers in one swoop.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Sweeney's preaching about the need to reverse
organized labor's slide in membership _ its ranks peaked at 21
million in 1979 before shrinking to a low of 16 million in 1997 _
unions expect to organize more than 500,000 new members this year,
more than five times the number the year Sweeney took office.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it seems, labor has so much cachet that doctors,
psychologists, graduate teaching assistants, limousine drivers and
even fashion models are rushing to join unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweeney has dramatically increased labor's visibility,'' said
former U.S. Labor Secretary Robert Reich. ``He's turned the AFL-CIO
into a more formidable political force. I haven't met anyone who
doesn't believe John Sweeney has been terrific for organized labor.
But having said that, the obstacles for labor are still very
large.''
</P>
<P>
   American unions are still in many ways swimming against the
tide. Globalization is putting downward pressure on union wages as
companies continue to close unionized factories and move work
overseas. The nation's recent explosion in jobs is concentrated in
small business and high technology, where unions have made little
headway.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America has become far more aggressive in battling
unionization drives, while Republican majorities in the House and
Senate continually propose hostile legislation.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not to mention the repeated corruption scandals,
which seem to turn organized labor's progress into two steps
forward and one step backward.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, many union officials acknowledged that if unions
did not reverse their membership decline, they would soon have
little power left. The reason: if only 15 percent of an industry
was unionized, unionized companies could make strong arguments that
they would be unable to compete with the 85 percent that was
nonunion if they were generous at the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   Today, unions represent 13.9 percent of the work force, down
sharply from 35 percent in the 1950s. Many economists say labor's
declining power is a major reason why wages for most Americans have
climbed more slowly than inflation since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney won the AFL-CIO's presidency after he and several other
union presidents conspired to push out his predecessor, Lane
Kirkland. They complained that Kirkland, who died last August,
seemed to pay more attention to helping workers in Poland than in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   From his first day as AFL-CIO president, Sweeney's top goal has
been to reverse the labor movement's decline in numbers and power _
and he recognized that, to do that, he had to rejuvenate labor's
oh-so-boring image and to form alliances across society.
</P>
<P>
   One of his biggest successes was creating Union Summer, a
program in which more than 1,000 college students worked as summer
interns, persuading many of them that improving the lot of workers
was a cause worth devoting their lives to. The AFL-CIO has set up a
program called ``street heat'' where scores of union activists in
more than a dozen cities instantly materialize for raucous
demonstrations during labor disputes.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual high-tech turn, the AFL-CIO is planning to make
computers and Internet service available to its 13 million members
at discounted prices, with an eye to tying workers closer together
and making it easier to mobilize them. With the push of a button, a
union president could e-mail tens of thousands of members to urge
them to e-mail Congress to push, say, for a higher minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And Saturday in Los Angeles, the AFL-CIO is kicking off a
campaign to cooperate with immigrant groups as part of an effort to
make labor focus more on immigrants' needs. The hope is to attract
more immigrants to unions and help improve the lives in bottom-rung
jobs like janitors, hotel maids and farm workers.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney has deliberately increased the movement's focus on
low-wage workers, after the AFL-CIO was perceived for years as
being preoccupied with labor's well-paid elite in auto plants and
steel mills. By focusing more on lower-rung workers, Sweeney has
improved the movement's moral stature, causing hundreds of
academics and members of the clergy to throw their support behind
labor in a way not seen in decades.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even some of his most vocal opponents grudgingly give Sweeney
credit. ``Ever since Lane Kirkland passed away this summer, we
heard how his work in fighting communism around the world is what
he will be remembered for,'' said Jeffrey McGuinness, president of
LPA, a Washington-based management association that represents 250
major companies. ``John Sweeney will be remembered for
reinvigorating the labor movement and getting back to basics. His
job is to make the labor movement grow again, and he is moving
aggressively in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the biggest change wrought by Sweeney is to get the
AFL-CIO and its member unions to focus far more on recruiting new
members _ the key to the movement's survival.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, unions on average spent less than 3 percent of
their budgets on organizing, but Sweeney has persuaded many unions
to raise that to 10 percent of their budget. The hotel and
restaurant employees' union now spends more than 30 percent of its
budget on organizing, while the union that Sweeney once led, the
Service Employees International Union, now spends 45 percent of its
budget on organizing.
</P>
<P>
   That is paying off. The service employees' union, which has more
than 400 full-time organizers, is expected to see its membership
jump by nearly 200,000 this year, to 1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Every few weeks this year, Sweeney has issued news releases
boasting of another impressive organizing win. After nearly a
century of trying, the Union of Needletrades, Industrial and
Textile Employees successfully organized 5,200 workers at six
Fieldcrest Cannon plants in Kannapolis, N.C. _ the heart of
anti-union country.
</P>
<P>
   In Puerto Rico, which recently gave its government workers the
right to join unions, about 66,000 public employees are expected to
vote to unionize this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   These developments make AFL-CIO officials optimistic that, for
the first time in decades, unions might be able to stop the fall in
the percentage of workers belonging to unions. To achieve that
goal, unions need to organize at least 500,000 additional workers,
with the net increase several hundred thousand less than that
because of plant closings and workers at some companies voting to
oust their unions.
</P>
<P>
   Some AFL-CIO officials say they hope to soon unionize 1 million
additional workers each year, but many labor experts say that may
be pie in the sky. The booming high-tech sector has resisted union
inroads, and unions still continue to lose nearly half of all
unionization elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first step to revitalizing the labor movement is stop the
shrinking, and I believe that's happened.'' said Richard Hurd, a
Cornell University professor of labor relations. ``Does this
translate into a revitalized labor movement that's on a permanent
upward track? The answer to that, is it's still premature to say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
