<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HMO09-COX     10-08 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democrats settle in for Senate healthcare battle
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The day after winning his four- year crusade to
overhaul the nation's managed healthcare industry, Rep. Charlie
Norwood (R-Ga.) was resting and readying for what will likely be an
even rougher battle: negotiations with Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   To turn legislation Norwood authored with Rep. John Dingell
(D-Mich.) into law, he must win over senators assigned to a
House-Senate conference committee, the special panel of lawmakers
that will resolve the differences between both chambers' bills.
</P>
<P>
   And there are many differences, but none as controversial as a
provision in the House bill that gives patients the right to sue
their health care plans. The Senate rejected that provision when it
passed its version of the bill in July.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood plans to win senators over in exactly the same tenacious
way that he defied the wishes of House Republican leaders and
convinced 67 Republicans to vote for his legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill say Norwood's dogged pursuit of victory
is one reason for its passage. House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt
(D-Mo.) said he doubted that the bill would have passed against the
powerful health insurance lobby, ``if it had not been for the sheer
passion of Charlie Norwood and John Dingell.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) said he has supported Norwood's efforts
from the start, because doctors have repeatedly told him the woes
of dealing with HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of House Republican meetings where the
``leadership made its preference known,'' Barr said. ``But this was
an issue that every member had to decide for themselves,'' Barr
said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about how he managed to defeat the House Republican
leaders, Norwood said that he did it the old-fashioned way: one
member at a time. He said he called, harangued and generally made a
pest of himself until he got their ear.
</P>
<P>
   He is likely to pursue the same strategy in dealing with Senate
negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood, a dentist, left at 6 a.m. Friday for a trip to Honolulu
with his wife, Gloria, where he will address a dental convention as
the keynote speaker. After a few days on the beach, his staff
predicted that he would return ``all fired up and wired to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood didn't waste much time basking in glory Thursday night,
either. Immediately after his bill passed 275-151, he already was
looking ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be a bloody war in conference to get this right, but
they can't stop Charlie Norwood,'' said Norwood, racing down a
hallway in the basement of the Capitol to yet another news
conference to declare ``victory for patients.''
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate leaders are expected to announce appointments
to the conference committee by the end of the session. But given
the complexity of the legislation, a final bill is not expected
until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood will face tough opposition not only from senators who
oppose allowing patients to sue their health plans. The health
insurance industry also is planning an ad and lobbying blitz,
arguing that allowing such suits would drive up the cost of health
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to take this to the American people,'' said Karen
Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health Plans,
which represents over 1,000 managed care plans. ``We will help lead
the conversation rather than react to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's senators are on opposite sides of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Max Cleland will support a growing coalition of
senators who want to approve the Norwood-Dingell measure, said Bill
Johnston, senior policy adviser to Cleland.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Paul Coverdell said he stands behind the Senate
version of the bill that passed this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I have some concerns about the managed care aspects of
the House bill, I am confident that the bill we ultimately agree to
will reduce the number of uninsured, protect an individual's right
to choose, prevent costs from rising, and guard against the
creation of a federal bureaucracy between patients and their
doctors,'' Coverdell said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
