<HEADER>
A1170 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-AUTO-SALES-$ADV10     10-08 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-AUTO-SALES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY HIGHER INTEREST RATES HAVEN'T FAZED AUTO MAKERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   (af)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Whenever the Federal Reserve raises short-term
interest rates _ or even hints that it might do so, as it did on
Tuesday _ economists issue warnings about the consequences for
rate-sensitive industries, notably automobiles and housing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite two quarter-point rate increases over the summer,
the auto industry is thriving. August and September were among the
best months ever for auto sales. The 1999 model year, which ended
on Sept. 30, broke a sales record set in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the industry's continued strength may indicate that rate
increases are just slow to have an effect. But some economists are
saying that the spread of retail incentives and leasing, and the
aggressiveness with which manufacturers are using them, are
allowing the industry to minimize the effects of interest rate
increases _ at least for a while, and as long as the increases are
fairly small.
</P>
<P>
   ``Car sales are not anywhere near as sensitive to interest rates
as they once were,'' said Cynthia Latta, the principal United
States economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, ``because manufacturers
will do anything to `move the metal,' as they say in the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Curtin, the director of consumer surveys at the
University of Michigan, said the rate increases last summer have
had no apparent effect on the public's interest in buying new cars
and light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear from our data that the entire impact of the recent
rate increases has been on the housing market,'' he said. ``While
we would normally say that interest rate changes affect
rate-sensitive sectors of the economy, that has narrowed greatly.''
</P>
<P>
   Auto makers softened the blow from rising interest rates during
the summer, mainly by using their auto financing subsidiaries to
subsidize new car loans and leases, offering rates as low as zero
percent for up to 36 months on some slow-selling car models.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Fed, the average rate for four-year auto loans
from banks rose to 8.44 percent in August, the most recent month
for which data are available, from 8.30 percent in the second
quarter. But the average rate charged by domestic and foreign auto
makers for loans of similar maturity fell to 6.28 percent from 6.56
percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Auto makers are also charging about 8.5 percent now for loans on
models with no incentives. But they have a much lower average than
the banks because of the many subsidized loans.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, subsidizing car loans is expensive for the auto
makers. While auto industry profits are high, they would be far
higher without them. The rising cost of sales incentives has pulled
down the stocks of General Motors, Ford Motor and DaimlerChrysler
by 20 percent to 30 percent since it became clear in early May that
the Fed would raise rates.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers can afford the incentives, because they are
essentially passing along the considerable cost savings they are
demanding, and getting, from parts suppliers, said David Bradley,
an auto analyst at J.P. Morgan. ``The auto makers have stepped in
and have cushioned the impact'' of rising rates, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Van Bussman, an economist at DaimlerChrysler, said discounts
were likely to remain widespread. Despite the auto market's overall
strength, no company wants to be the first to accept lower sales
and thereby lose market share, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lending arms of the big domestic and foreign auto makers are
in particularly good financial shape right now for a rate war. They
borrowed billions of dollars last winter, locking in low rates for
long terms.
</P>
<P>
   That has left auto loan rates less closely linked than usual to
the current rate for two-year Treasury notes, which leaped
11-hundredths of a percentage point last Tuesday, after the Fed's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The auto industry's rate resilience poses a potential problem
for the Fed, which has long followed the industry carefully. The
industry accounts for 4 percent of the nation's economic output,
and a much higher share of what used to be considered the
rate-sensitive portion of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Diane C. Swonk, chief economist at the Bank One Corp., said the
industry's new ability to accept higher rates might require the Fed
to raise rates slightly higher or faster than it would have
previously to slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   AlMOST nobody questions that a large rate increase, perhaps a
percentage point or more, would still hurt the industry. A big jump
would slow growth in incomes and employment while damaging consumer
confidence to the point that people would have less interest in
buying new automobiles, even with incentives available.
</P>
<P>
   Rate increases can also take as long as a year to affect the
economy, so the recent small increases could eventually catch up
with the auto industry. Higher rates have already slowed the pace
of mortgage refinancings. In recent years, many Americans have been
able to take out bigger auto loans because they have refinanced
home mortgages, reducing their monthly payments.
</P>
<P>
   Some auto executives, notably at DaimlerChrylser and Ford, have
nonetheless been suggesting lately that their companies are no
longer truly cyclical, and that they can remain profitable in an
economic downturn. But even economists who think that the industry
has begun moderating the effects of small rate increases say that
such views require considerable optimism.
</P>
<P>
   As Curtin put it, ``It's always at this point in an expansion
that an industry proclaims itself recession-proof.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
