<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-SAINTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Saints awaiting Williams dividends
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Ricky Williams signed with New Orleans, he and
his agent were ridiculed for allowing the Saints to hustle them.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-year, $16.2 million deal was criticized because it
doesn't include voidable years and because more than half of an
$8.84 million signing bonus is deferred until next year. But the
biggest complaint was that the contract was based on performance,
rather than potential.
</P>
<P>
   For the Heisman Trophy winner from Texas to earn the usual
compensation of other high draft choices, Williams will have to net
some of the contract's $52.2 million in incentive clauses, most of
which figure to be extremely difficult to attain.
</P>
<P>
   One incentive requires Williams, the NCAA's all-time leading
rusher, to average 1,600 yards in his first four seasons. Only two
players in NFL history have done it _ Terrell Davis and Eric
Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Williams says he isn't worried about the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're incentives,'' he said. ``That means if you do well,
you'll get them. If you don't do well, you don't get them. So
there's no concerns. They're supposed to be extras. If I get them,
great. If not, I still have my (signing) bonus and salary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy with the deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Through three games of his rookie season, the odds already are
stacked against him. Williams, 22, has rushed for 204 yards on 53
carries, an average of 3.8 yards per attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' slow start can be attributed mostly to injuries. He
left the opener against Carolina with a sprained ankle and didn't
finish a loss at San Francisco the next week because of an elbow
injury.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's 14-10 loss at Chicago, Williams rushed for a
career-high 84 yards. He seems to lack the breakaway speed that
helped him rush for more than 6,000 yards at Texas _ his longest
run with the Saints is 19 yards _ but he is running with more
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's feeling better,'' Saints coach Mike Ditka said. ``He's
not 100 percent by any means, but he's feeling better. I thought
his performance last week was pretty courageous, and he's a good
young man. Ricky doesn't worry too much about `breakout games' or
things like that. He just loves to play football.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams indicated this week that Leland Hardy, who negotiated
the controversial contract, no longer serves as his agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I don't think so,'' Williams said, when asked if
Hardy still represented him.
</P>
<P>
   However, Williams said he's still represented by No Limit Sports
of Baton Rouge, La., which is owned by rapper Percy Miller, a.k.a.
Master P.
</P>
<P>
   The contract and the hype surrounding Williams _ the Saints
traded their entire draft allotment to Washington to select him
fifth overall _ might be too much pressure to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everything in life that's worth anything, there's
pressure,'' Ditka said. ``When you have your first baby, there's
pressure, man. You've got to earn more money. There's pressure for
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a commitment that we wanted him, and once we made that
commitment we went ahead and did what we did,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter, because we were going to get bombarded by
all the experts, anyway. But the pressure's not on us. It's on him,
in the sense that he wants to be as good of a football player in
the professional ranks as he was in college.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
