<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-COURT-CAMPAIGN-FINANC     10-08 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT IS UNLIKELY TO ACT ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the Supreme Court on Tuesday, the justices
talked about a lot of things that seemed to be wrong with the
campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia lamented the time candidates must spend
on raising money. He also complained that the perception of
corruption in politics had not diminished since Congress set limits
on contributions in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist complained that unions got away
with more than business did. Justice David Souter said he shared
the view held by ``most people'' that ``someone who makes an
extraordinarily large contribution is going to get some kind of
extraordinary return for it.'' Justice Stephen Breyer spoke of big
contributors' ``owning'' candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But when the hour of argument was over, the nine justices
collectively left no impression that they meant to do much about
these problems. That may be just as well, considering how the court
mucked up a presidential election the last time it got in the
middle of one. In January 1976, in Buckley vs. Valeo, the court
ruled that the Federal Election Commission was improperly
constituted and gave Congress an implausibly brief 30 days to fix
things.
</P>
<P>
   After the law was repaired and the commission was reconstituted
in late May, most Democratic candidates had been starved of federal
matching money for two months. By then, Jimmy Carter, whose banker
friends lent him money on the assumption that the matching money
would ultimately be paid, had wrapped up the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Helping Carter, for good or ill, was far from the most important
thing the Buckley decision did. Concluding that campaign spending
amounted to free speech, the court held unconstitutional both the
spending limits set for federal candidates by the 1974 law ($70,000
for the House, for example) and the limits on how much wealthy
candidates could spend on their own campaigns ($50,000 for
president, $35,000 for the Senate, $25,000 for the House).
</P>
<P>
   As a direct result, spending in many contested House races will
top $2 million apiece this year as candidates spend most of their
waking hours dialing for dollars. And multimillionaire Steve Forbes
is bankrolling much of his campaign for the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Some justices would plainly like to take the logical path and
decide that restrictions on contributions impermissibly limit free
speech. Such a result might help some of the lesser-known
presidential candidates if they could find a suitable sugar daddy.
Breyer suggested that Ebenezer Scrooge might be good for $15
million.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, both sides of this argument assume that there are
real contribution limits now enforced by a functional Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the commission is a paper tiger, and the limits mean
something only at the early stages of a campaign, before party
money and independent expenditures start flowing.
</P>
<P>
   As one illustration, 40 of the ``Pioneers'' who have raised
$100,000 in $1,000 chunks for Gov. George W. Bush of Texas have
already moved on to the next stage, according to Common Cause, the
public-affairs lobbying organization. Through June they gave an
average of $50,000 apiece to the Republican Party, which in turn
can use it to help Bush if, in fact, he is nominated.
</P>
<P>
   Next week the Senate is scheduled to debate whether to ban these
unrestricted contributions to the political parties. The House did
approve a soft-money ban earlier this year, but there is stiff
opposition to the proposal in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Like their brethren on the Supreme Court, many members of the
House and the Senate agree that the current campaign finance system
is badly flawed. But they, too, are unlikely to do much about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
