<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECONOMY-ART-900&AMP;ADD-N     10-08 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMY IS SLOWING DOWN, REPORT INDICATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The energetic American economic machine may be slipping into a
slower gear, as job creation came to a halt last month and the work
force shrank for the first time since January 1996. But wages
continued to rise at a healthy pace, the Labor Department reported
Friday, keeping alive the potential for future inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Floyd, disrupting East Coast commerce in
mid-September, discouraged many employers from hiring. ``But
employment growth was weak even in those industries unaffected by
the hurricane,'' Katherine Abraham, commissioner of the Labor
Department's Bureau of Labor Statistics, said in a message to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Taking August and September together, only 95,000 new jobs were
created: 103,000 in August and then a loss of 8,000 in September.
That is a rather startling pullback from the 654,000 new jobs that
appeared in June and July _ and hardly justification for the
Federal Reserve to raise interest rates at its next policy meeting,
on Nov. 16, to contain inflation by slowing the economy. When they
met last Tuesday, the Fed policy-makers left rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American economy is slowing. The key question is how
much,'' said Nancy Lazar, a vice president at ISI Group, taking a
more pessimistic view of the September employment report than some
other Wall Street economists, who said more data was needed before
a trend could be identified.
</P>
<P>
   While the Labor Department's monthly survey of American
companies revealed the weak job growth, a separate survey of
households showed that the unemployment rate in September had
remained unchanged, at an unusually low 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bond market traders, uncertain whether to view the weak
employment report as a harbinger or an anomaly, left interest rates
unchanged. The stock market initially saw in the numbers evidence
that the Fed was unlikely to raise interest rates in November. In
response, the Dow Jones industrial average rose at the opening.
Then it fell, but finally finished up 112.71 points at 10,649.76.
</P>
<P>
   ``This number, which was expected to be a defining number for
the markets, only creates more confusion,'' Joel Naroff, an
economic consultant, advised his clients in an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The one aspect of the employment report that raised warning
flags was the wage number. Average hourly wages for production
workers below the rank of supervisor rose by 7 cents, to $13.37.
The 7 cents represented the biggest one- month jump in more than a
decade. But that was the only superlative. The percentage increase
_ .5 percent _ was no greater than in some earlier months this
year. And the 3.8 percent wage rise over the last 12 months is
roughly what wage growth for production workers has been all year:
firm but not yet firm enough to push employers into inflationar
price increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that would make the wage growth potentially
inflationary _and this is a big if _ is if productivity were to
slow from its present strong growth rate,'' said Lawrence Katz, a
Harvard University labor economist. A rising productivity rate has
meant that workers have produced more each hour on the job. The
added revenue from their output has paid, in effect, for their wage
increases.
</P>
<P>
   What Ms. Lazar saw in the employment report was evidence that
rising interest rates in recent months, as well as a flat stock
market, rising oil prices and a sharp drop in the number of
households refinancing mortgages, are beginning to take their toll
on the real economy. But the September employment report is the
first significant evidence of that toll. Elsewhere in the economy,
retail sales were strong in September, and so were industrial
production, home sales, consumer borrowing and auto sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly in 2000 we expect the economy to slow,'' said Martin
Bailey, chairman of President Clinton's Council of Economic
Advisers. ``But except for this report there is no other sign of
slowing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking an unusual step, the Labor Department estimated how many
additional jobs would have been counted if Hurricane Floyd had not
struck the week of the department's employment survey. The goal: To
head off speculation that September would have been a strong
employment month if not for Floyd. Without the hurricane, job
growth would have been only 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Including that 50,000, you can say that employment growth in
the third quarter was 175,000 a month compared with 210,000 a month
in the first half of the year,'' said Thomas Nardone, an official
at the Bureau of Labor Statistics. ``That is still slower growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobs disappeared in manufacturing, retailing, mortgage banking
and government. Employment remained unchanged in finance, insurance
and real estate. Jobs in the huge service sector _ office workers,
for example, and call center operators _ multiplied, as usual, but
only by 39,000, less than half the average monthly growth of the
last year. Trucking, the airline industry, construction and public
utilities also added jobs. Between the gains and the losses, the
total number of jobs in the nation declined in September to 128.91
million.
</P>
<P>
   While industrial production rose last month, manufacturing
employment fell once again, this time by 21,000 jobs. Over the last
18 months, manufacturing employment has shrunk by 532,000 jobs, to
18.4 million. To keep production up with fewer workers, companies
have resorted to labor saving technology and equipment, as well as
overtime for the remaining people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Overtime hours averaged a relatively high 4.7 a week in
September, unchanged from August. But other industries cut back
hours, and the net result for the private sector as a whole was a
slight decline in the average workweek, to 34.4 hours from 34.5 in
August.
</P>
<P>
   The overtime in manufacturing helps to explain the steady rise
in average hourly wages for production workers. Many of the people
displaced from these jobs, on the other hand, have probably moved
into lower-paying service jobs, economists say, helping to dampen
wage growth.
</P>
<P>
   In its monthly wage calculations, the Labor Department counts
only production workers, mainly in manufacturing, and not the wages
of nonproduction service workers. Nor does it include bonus
payments, which have been widespread across the labor force, but
are easier than wages to scale back when business declines.
</P>
<P>
   Viewing labor costs more broadly, Chris Varvares, a partner at
Macroeconomic Advisers, noted that total compensation per hour _
wages and benefits _ grew by 5.1 percent in the second quarter.
``Our forecast,'' he said, ``is that compensation will rise by more
than 4.5 percent in the third quarter, still high but not as
high.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
