<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1195 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CLINTON-CANADA-470(2T     10-08 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CANADA-470(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OPENS EMBASSY IN CANADA AS RELATIONS BETWEEN NEIGHBORS
REMAIN WARM 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ Friday, for the first time, an American president
traveled to a foreign nation and inaugurated an American Embassy.
It was fitting that President Clinton broke historical protocol in
Canada, a quiet partner that trades more with the United States
than any other country.
</P>
<P>
   The relaxed outdoor ceremony, with Parliament's landmark
Victorian bell tower mirrored in the glass-and-steel face of the
new embassy, seemed to reflect the easy relations between the two
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 years since a trade agreement was signed, trade
between the United States and Canada has doubled, now running over
$1 billion a day. In the 1990s, Canada has firmly established
itself as the largest source of imported energy for the United
States and the most popular foreign destination for American
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   In a joking mood on a sunny morning, Clinton cracked that Jean
Chretien, Canada's 65-year-old prime minister, was the only Western
leader ``who could still slalom on water skis with one of his
grandchildren on his shoulders.'' Noting that this was his fifth
visit to Canada as president, Clinton continued ribbing his
Canadian counterpart, saying: ``He also says if I come one more
time I have to start paying taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   The laughter faded at the end of his speech, when Clinton
appeared to stray beyond his prepared text, talking about ethnic
strife ``in the land of my forebears in Northern Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time they make an agreement to do it, they're like a
couple of drunks walking out of the bar for the last time,'' he
said of the on-again, off-again peace process between Protestants
and Catholics in Northern Ireland. ``When they get to the swinging
door, they turn around and go back in, and say, I just can't quite
get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The sparks around the president's joke provided news for
reporters hard pressed to find controversy in a relationship that
Americans take for granted: the world's largest trading
relationship crossing the world's longest undefended border. In
what may also be the world's smoothest relationship, this
cross-border commerce is expected to hit $410 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Less than one percent of our trade is subject to trade
action,'' said Raymond Chretien, Canada's ambassador to the United
States, a career diplomat who is also a nephew of the prime
minister. ``This huge trade goes so smoothly that it is
unnoticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with this quiet, north-south trade explosion, the United
States now exports more to Canada than to all the countries of
Western Europe. More goods cross between Ontario and the United
States than are exchanged between the United States and Japan.
Lloyd Axworthy, Canada's foreign minister, said: ``We do more trade
through Windsor and Detroit than the U.S. does with Japan.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Chretien was elected in 1993 on a platform of
skepticism about increasing economic integration with the United
States. Instead, he has presided over the fastest integration in
his country's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade between the U.S. and Canada has doubled in 10 years _
that is quite impressive when you think that we have been doing
business for more than 200 years,'' Gordon D. Giffin, the American
ambassador here, said in an interview. During the same decade,
world trade increased by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This trade boom has radically opened a country that once reveled
in its northern isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Since an auto pact was signed with the United States in 1965,
the portion of Canada's economy tied to foreign trade has tripled,
hitting 42 percent now. Measuring economic dependence on foreign
trade, Canada has climbed within the Group of Seven industrial
countries to second place, after Germany.
</P>
<P>
   For much of its history Canada has strived to create a cohesion
between east and west. But now each of Canada's 10 provinces trades
more with the United States than with the rest of Canada. In July,
87 percent of Canada's exports went south to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are seeing the Americanization of Canada, no doubt about
it,'' complained Peter S. Bleyer, executive director of the Council
of Canadians, a grass-roots nationalist group based here. ``Canada
is dramatically more integrated _ that is, dramatically more
dependent on the U.S. than we were a decade ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In the five years since Wal-Mart opened its first Canadian
store, the American chain has become the Canada's largest retailer.
Noting this march of American franchises across Canada's suburban
landscape, Bleyer lamented: ``We are becoming more and more made in
the image of our elephant neighbor to the south.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the wishes of economic nationalists, Canada's speeding
economic links with the United States is eroding popular support
for such icons of sovereignty as border posts and a national
currency.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, in a poll of 1,204 Canadian adults, 52 percent said
they were ``optimistic'' about globalization, and 39 percent said
that border posts between Canada and the United States should be
torn down, allowing trade and traffic to flow freely in both
directions. In the poll, conducted by Ekos Research Associates,
only 17 percent were pessimistic about the economic impact of
integration.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, in poll of 1,500 Canadians, half of respondents
predicted that the United States and Canada would have a common
currency in 10 years, 77 percent said in 20 years. In the poll,
conducted by the Angus Reid Group Inc., 37 percent said that
abolition of the Canadian dollar would be good for Canada's
economy. Over the last five years, the Canadian dollar has lost 12
percent of its value, a contraction popular with exporters but
frustrating to Canadian travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's openness is reciprocated on the other side of the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Americans made almost 15 million overnight visits to
Canada. Last year, the Chicago Council on Foreign Relations
commissioned a survey of 1,507 American adults for a ``feelings
thermometer'' about 25 countries. Respondents had the warmest
feelings for Canada (72 degrees) followed by Britain (69 degrees)
and Italy (62 degrees). Ranking in the mid-50s were Mexico,
Germany, Brazil, Japan, Israel, France and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Banking on these good feelings, academic specialists on
U.S.-Canada relations speculate that the next step toward fuller
integration could be a customs union _a European-style relationship
with common external tariffs and free internal movement of goods
and people.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and diplomats tend to be more cautious on
forecasting the evolution of North America's economic relations in
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``That dialogue is mostly in the press and among academics,''
Giffin said in interview, referring to talk of a North American
currency. ``I don't see it much among policy-makers in the U.S. or
Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Most governmental efforts are concentrated on the mechanics of
maintaining trade relations. In the last six months, disputes over
several trade issues have been eased: restrictions on Canadian
companies advertising in foreign magazines and declining salmon
stocks in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Friday ``an agreement in principle'' was announced over exchange
of defense and aerospace technology. In a move that threatened
Canada's $6 billion a year military industry, the United States
threatened last April to impose a licensing system on defense
exports to Canada if Canada did not tighten its controls. Friday,
Canada promised to tighten its export control system, creating,
with the United States ``a strong North American perimeter for
defense export controls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
