<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON STUDIES, SURVEYS AND PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reading, Writing, 'Rithmetic and Sniffles? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-school season is usually a bonanza for suppliers of
products like notebook paper, No. 2 pencils and crayons. But
Kleenex?
</P>
<P>
   As this year's back-to-school season winds down, Kimberly-Clark
reports that sales of its Kleenex brand facial tissue typically
increase about 17 percent for the July-to-September period. Why?
Apparently, school teachers around the country often include
Kleenex on the list of supplies that students will need to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know, it's been on school lists for years,'' said
Jim Peliotes, associate marketing director for the brand.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on that, Kimberly-Clark began promoting the
back-to-school season a few years ago. Since then, Kleenex, which
has about a 50 percent market share, has increased its share by
about 7 percentage points _ and by as much as 20 percentage points
in some markets during the back-to-school period. Traditionally,
the peak sales season for Kleenex sales is the cough-cold season
beginning in November.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Kimberly-Clark offered a ``value priced'' three-pack
of Kleenex, gave store displays to retailers and offered a special
mail-in promotion for a free gyroscope from Bill Nye, ``The Science
Guy,'' of PBS. Peliotes said the promotion helped build sales. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Patricia Winters Lauro
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
