<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEMINOLES-WARRICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARRICK WAITS AS FLORIDA STATE ADJUSTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The coalition assembled to tout Pete
Warrick's candidacy for the Heisman Trophy has been reduced to a
whimper overnight.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the Heisman coalition, as the campus group
calls itself, still plans to distribute more than 10,000 T-shirts
with the slogan ``(NU)9 in '99'' on them for Florida State's annual
war with the Miami Hurricanes on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   There is one pesky problem. Warrick will watch the game in
street clothes. He was suspended from the team after being charged
on Thursday with grand theft. Laveranues Coles, a fellow wide
receiver, was also charged with grand theft, but was kicked off the
team because of previous legal and academic problems.
</P>
<P>
   The two players are accused of buying clothes at a local
department store worth more than $400 and paying $21.40.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick's absence in particular could be telltale as FSU (5-0)
tries to maintain an unbeaten record when the Seminoles face Miami
(2-2).
</P>
<P>
   Other top games Saturday include Michigan at Michigan State,
Penn State at Iowa and Georgia at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, from Bradenton, Fla., turned down a multimillion-dollar
deal from the National Football League to return for his senior
season. He has been everything the Seminoles dreamed about, scoring
seven touchdowns, throwing for one score and averaging 101.6
receiving yards a game.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bowden, the FSU receivers coach, said there was no sense
trying to sugarcoat Warrick's absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete is a guy who can win a game for you on one play,'' Bowden
said. ``There was a certain confidence factor of knowing that you
had that go-to guy.''
</P>
<P>
   As singularly explosive as Warrick has been, and even though
some think the Hurricanes have been reduced to a mere tropical
depression, Miami's players seem to genuinely regret that he will
not play Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to go out and tackle people, anyway,'' defensive tackle
Matt Sweeney said. ``Heck, it might as well be a Heisman
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Bubba Franks said he had been rooting for Warrick to
be eligible Saturday, ``so nobody will have any excuses after we
win.'''
</P>
<P>
   Free safety Al Blades said: ``I want their best talent out
there. I don't want any excuses about this and that. Just like we
can't have any excuses. I feel we can play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Warrick, the Seminoles scrapped several plays
specifically designed to use his special skills, such as a pass off
a wide receiver reverse. But the Seminole coaches are more
concerned about what emotional damage, if any, this sobering
development might do to their hopes for a national title.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Overton, in charge of FSU's life skills program, part of the
school's academic support for its athletes, said she met with a
wide receiver Friday who viewed the charge against Warrick as
somewhat overblown and harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you think they made too much out of it?'' she responded to
him. ``Look, what you do on Saturdays is play a little throw and
catch, but there are always 83,000 people who think it's great. But
can you see that some people might think what you do is overblown
or given an exaggerated importance, just the way you think this
case is? I wanted him to get a little better perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hart, FSU's athletics director, who said on Thursday that
athletic talent did not put a person above the law, held out hope
Friday that Warrick would still be able to salvage his senior
season. Hart gave one disclaimer: if the charges against Warrick
remain a third-degree felony, he said, Warrick will likely not play
again for FSU.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
