<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-JUNKBONDS-ART-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUNK BONDS ARE QUICKLY IN A CRUNCH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass., Vt.)  (ART ADV: Graphic of fund flows of high-risk corporate bond funds
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday mornings have become a little ho-hum for Tim O'Hara at
the Golden Pear coffee shop in Bridgehampton, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara, managing director and global head of the high-yield bond
group at Credit Suisse First Boston, regularly runs into clients
there who are picking up cups of coffee. But these days, his
clients are glum. Money is getting harder for them to borrow, they
tell him. And when they can get it, it is more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the life these days of leveraged-buyout financiers _
that is, the group of Wall Street investors who borrow money to buy
troubled companies with the hope of shoring them up and selling
them later for a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The willingness of lenders to provide money for these deals at
reasonable rates is dwindling. And that is affecting these
financiers' ability to buy companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're waiting until next year,'' O'Hara said of the clients
whose high-yield bond issues he underwrites. ``They're not anxious
to spend a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the current crunch? For most leveraged-buyout specialists,
trouble began last July when Alan Greenspan, chairman of the
Federal Reserve, warned that the central bank would be willing to
put the brakes on the economy by raising interest rates and
tightening the supply of money available to borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   That sent a chill through mutual fund investors in high-yield,
or junk, bonds. They began pulling their money out of the funds
that specialize in such investments. As the pool of money to lend
contracted, interest rates on junk bonds rose two to three
percentage points, from roughly 9 percent to 11 percent to 12
percent to 14 percent, depending on the bond.
</P>
<P>
   That is making it more expensive for leveraged-buyout financiers
to borrow money. And to complicate matters, O'Hara said, some
lenders are not only demanding higher interest rates, but are also
asking for an equity stake of as much as 5 percent in smaller
companies involved in buyout deals.
</P>
<P>
   That makes borrowing money an even more expensive proposition
for the leveraged-buyout financiers, because it means sharing part
of their ultimate profit with the lenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they are forced to use money of their own, instead of
borrowing it,'' said Kingman Penniman, president of KDP Investment
Advisers in Montpelier, Vt. ``They don't want to do that, or worse,
give away a big piece of the company they are trying to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   What market watchers like Penniman have seen is the widening of
the spread, or the difference between yields on high-yield bonds
and on Treasury bonds. On April 30, Penniman said, 10-year
Treasuries were yielding 5.35 percent, while an index of high-yield
bonds averaged 9.11 percent _ a spread of 3.76 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, the spread had widened by nearly a full percentage
point, to 4.67, with the high-yield index averaging 10.7 percent,
compared with 6.03 percent on 10-year Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've only seen spreads this wide for a short time, during the
Russian default and the hedge fund debacle of last year,'' Penniman
said. ``It's way above what we've experienced historically.''
</P>
<P>
   Other concerns seem to be adding to the market nervousness,
notably the fears that Year 2000 computer glitches will cause
market disruptions that will play out detrimentally for bonds and
bond holders. The validity of those fears remains unclear, though
some lenders have warned customers that it will be difficult to
finance highly leveraged transactions near the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people talk about Y2K, I look at the equity markets and I
think, why aren't (italics)they(end italics) concerned?'' Penniman
said.
</P>
<P>
   To add to that, the default rate on junk bonds is climbing and
is now running ahead of last year's rate, further dampening
investor interest. As a result, bond investors are pouring their
money primarily into the market for higher-quality bonds that offer
more safety.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, smaller buyout shops will suffer the most.
Banks and other lenders have already put some of these customers on
notice. One leveraged-buyout professional, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, said he got a call last week from an executive at a
large lending institution, who told him that the bank was already
winnowing its list of ``preferred'' clients. (His company was still
on the preferred list, he said.)
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, well-known and respected buyout financiers like
Clayton, Dubilier &AMP; Rice are the least likely to be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation six months ago was that you could have
lesser-known companies get things done,'' said Bill Barbe, a
partner at Clayton, Dubilier. ``But now that is not as easy.'' As a
result, Barbe added, ``what will drive the market is quality
transactions of size.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
