</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTHCARE-715&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMOS LOBBY FOR PANEL TO HEAR PATIENTS' GRIEVANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Mich., S.D., Vt., Del., Tenn.)  (lb) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chief lobbyist for the United States' health
maintenance organizations, alarmed at the prospect of lawsuits
against HMOs, said Friday that her group would urge Congress
instead to pass legislation allowing patients to take their
grievances to an independent panel of medical experts.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbyist, Karen Ignagni, president of the American
Association of Health Plans, said the industry would also be
willing to accept a federal law imposing financial penalties on
HMOs that flout the decisions of an outside review panel.
</P>
<P>
   This represents a shift by the industry, which until now has
opposed new federal standards for managed care. The change was
prompted by the surprising House vote in favor of ``patients'
rights'' legislation on Thursday. Nearly one-third of House
Republicans joined Democrats in passing the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton insists that patients should be able to sue
health insurance plans for injuries caused by the denial of care,
and the House bill allows patients to file such lawsuits in state
courts. The Senate passed a bill to define patients' rights in
July, but it does not create any new right to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by the industry's defeat in the House, Ms. Ignagni said
Friday that she hoped to persuade Congress to require HMOs to set
up procedures for the independent review of their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, Ms. Ignagni discussed the industry's
strategy in the next stage of the legislative process. ``We will be
very aggressive in advocating external review of health plan
decisions,'' she said. ``We'd be willing to accept federal
legislation to that effect, with strong penalties for HMOs that
don't comply.''
</P>
<P>
   The House bill was drafted by Reps. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., and
John Dingell, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   John Stone, a spokesman for Norwood, said Friday that ``it's a
little late'' for HMOs to lobby for an appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the industry had come forward with this idea two or three
years ago, it would have received serious attention,'' Stone said.
``After several months of debate, members of Congress have learned
about the legal immunity of HMOs. The industry, in shock and panic,
has belatedly decided to concede some territory and cut its
losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Another major lobby, the Health Insurance Association of
America, is not ready to compromise. Charles Kahn III, president of
the association, said: ``We have never taken any public position
other than `Just say no.' We oppose legislation in this area at
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kahn said it was risky for insurance companies to indicate that
they could accept a requirement for independent review of their
decisions, because the industry's position would be just ``a
starting point for negotiations'' with Congress. In those
negotiations, Kahn said, ``it would be very difficult to get
legislation we could live with,'' because President Clinton and
many House members would insist on creating a new right to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ignagni said the HMO industry would strenuously oppose any
new right for patients to sue their health plans. And while the
industry is willing to accept some new Federal standards, she said,
it will oppose ``micromanagement'' of its day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ignagni said she could see some advantages to uniform
national standards set by the federal government. ``We can't
continue down the road of 50 states doing their own thing,'' she
said. ``You have to strive for some regulatory uniformity.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, lawyers have filed class-action lawsuits
against Aetna and Humana, alleging that they deceived consumers and
maximized their profits by degrading the quality of health care.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn said these lawsuits offered a preview of what to expect
under the House bill. ``Predatory attorneys would swoop in like a
bunch of buzzards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said Friday that the negotiations between the House
and the Senate would be very difficult. The two chambers have big
differences on specific provisions of the ``patients' bill of
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, for example, guarantees access to medical
specialists whenever it is medically necessary. The Senate bill
provides access to specialists only ``when such care is covered
under the plan.'' Democrats say this could render the protection
meaningless.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Senate Democratic leader, said
``We are ecstatic'' with the House vote on patients' rights. ``I
would hope that we could complete the conference and come back with
a good bill before the end of this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Republican leaders said they had other priorities and
would not rush to complete work on such complex legislation. An
aide to Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the assistant majority
leader, said the House-Senate negotiations would follow ``the
normal pace of Congress, the normal rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference committee will probably not begin serious work
until early next year, the Republicans said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said such delay would work to their advantage,
injecting the issue of ``patients' rights'' into the middle of next
year's election campaign season. Thursday's lopsided vote in favor
of patients' rights confirms the political potency of the issue,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   James Jordan, political director of the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee, said that Democratic candidates would use the
issue against three Republican senators who supported a limited
version of patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   The three Republicans, James Jeffords of Vermont, William Roth
of Delaware and Bill Frist of Tennessee, are all running for
re-election. Each of them played a prominent role in the Senate
debate on patients' rights in July.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords and Roth are chairmen of the committees that wrote the
Senate bill, and they beat back many Democratic efforts to expand
the definition of patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Frist, a heart surgeon, was particularly helpful to the
Republicans because he spoke as a medical authority. But Jordan
said Frist's position was contrary to that of consumer groups and
the American Medical Association, which favored more extensive
rights for patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
