<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  pennsylvania votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224. PLEASE
NOTE: THERE IS NO ATTENDANCE CHART WASHINGTON, Oct. 8 -- The
following chart shows how senators and representatives voted on key
bills and amendments within the last week. A ``Y'' means the member
voted for the measure; an ``N'' means the member voted against the
measure; a ``?'' means the member did not vote; and a ``P'' means
the member voted ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: WHITE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday rejected, 45 to 54, a bill to nominate
Missouri Supreme Court Judge Ronnie White to be a federal district
court judge. White, who had been tapped by President Clinton for
the position, is the first black judge on Missouri's state supreme
court. Supporters said White was fit for the nomination. Opponents
said White was not sufficiently favorable of the death penalty. A
``yes'' vote favors the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: AID
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday approved, 51 to 49, a $12.6 billion
foreign aid bill that President Clinton has threatened to veto
because it cuts $1.9 billion from his request. Supporters said the
amount of aid was sufficient. Opponents said the bill fails to fund
many important foreign aid programs. A ``yes'' vote favors the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) N Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) N Y
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: AG
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Oct. 1, the House passed, 240 to 175, a $69 billion
agriculture spending bill. The bill would provide $8.7 billion in
emergency funds for farmers reeling from bad weather and low
prices. Supporters said the bill should have provided more
emergency aid for farmers and that it failed to address
milk-pricing and trade sanctions issues. A ``yes'' vote favors the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: OPERATIONS
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday passed, 214 to 211, a $12.6 billion foreign
aid bill that President Clinton has threatened to veto because it
cuts $1.9 billion from his request. Supporters said the bill meets
foreign aid spending needs without dipping into Social Security
funds. Opponents said the bill fails to allot funds for the
implementation of the 1998 Wye River Middle East peace accords and
omits restrictions on aid to pro-abortion groups situated abroad. A
``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: TAX-BREAK
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday passed, 227 to 205, a bill to allow
citizens to create tax-free savings accounts to cover their medical
costs. The bill would also give tax breaks to those who buy their
own insurance and helps small businesses join together to buy less
expensive coverage. Supporters said the bill would help the 44
million uninsured Americans gain access to health coverage.
Opponents said the bill only helps the healthy and wealthy and
fails to addresss the needs of low-income Americans. A ``yes'' vote
favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: HMO1
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday rejected, 193 to 238, a bill, endorsed by
the Republican leadership, that would expand rights of patients
when dealing with their health maintenace organizations by easing
access to emergnecy room care and specialists and allowing them to
sue their HMOs under limited circumstances. Supporters said the
bill gives patients more rights without clearing the way for an
excess of lawsuits. Opponents said the bill's liability provision
was too limited. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   5) BILL NUMBER: HMO2
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 275 to 151, a bill that gives
citizens the right to sue HMOs that refuse to deliver adequate
medical coverage. The bill also eases access to emergency room care
and experimental treatments. Supporters said the bill would help
prevent HMOs from putting costs above the needs of patients.
Opponents said the bill's liability provision was too liberal and
could lead to an excess of lawsuits against both HMOs and employers
that provide health insurance. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4 5
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- --- ---
</P>
