<HEADER>
A1222 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBA-INDIANS-REDSOX-CO     10-08 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-REDSOX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Indians perched to send Olde Towne Team home
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Olde Towne Team is about to become olde news.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, they like to call the Boston Red Sox The Olde
Towne Team and before the leaves turn colors the Red Sox already
are one defeat away from packing away the equipment before they
barely took a whiff of postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   With a two games to none lead in the American League Division
Series, the Cleveland Indians need one victory in three possible
games to eliminate the Bosox and advance to the American League
Championship Series against the New York Yankees or Texas Rangers .
</P>
<P>
   The Tribe places the baseball in the meaty right hand of
Springfield native Dave Burba this afternoon in Fenway Park for the
possible coup de grace.
</P>
<P>
   Burba, wrapped in a heavy jacket, watched his teammates dissect
the Red Sox, 11-1, in Game 2 Thursday in Jacobs Field and remembers
turning to somebody to say, ``Hey, guys, save some digits (runs)
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Burba faced Boston only once this year and it wasn't pleasant,
even though he struck out eight in only five innings. He gave up
four runs, six hits and four walks in a 9-4 defeat in Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   That, though, is ancient history, something that happened April
24. Burba takes a 15-9 season's record with a 4.25 earned run
average to the mound against Ramon Martinez, an older and much
less-talented brother to Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not letting anything build up in me, telling myself I have
to win,'' Burba said. ``I'm just going to relax and pitch my
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the spectre of the 37-foot high left field wall, The
Green Monster, comes into play when he pitches in Fenway, Burba
said, ``Nope, no problem. I'm looking the other way. I can't let
the thought that a little fly ball might ricochet off the wall
enter my mind or you might change your way of pitching and some
line drives may bounce off it or some long fly balls may go over
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, if they tattoo the wall, at least I pitched my game,''
Burba added.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox haven't been tattooing anything. They've scored
three runs on 11 hits in two defeats and struck out 17 times.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Burba is pitching what could be the series clincher,
that, too, is something he won't permit to clutter his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to keep that out of my thoughts,'' he said. ``If I
start putting together a puzzle about what this game means, I put
pressure on myself, think too much. I don't need anything extra out
of the ordinary. . .just pitch the way I know how.''
</P>
<P>
   Burba formerly pitched the way he knows how the for the
Cincinnati Reds and was the scheduled Opening Day starter for 1998.
A mere hours before the first pitch, he was traded to Cleveland for
first baseman Sean Casey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy about coming here, it was just the timing,'' he
said. ``I was rooting for the Reds and I would have been happy for
them to make the playoffs. What I always liked about the Reds is
that even though they aren't a team of big salaries, every year
they battle you and it was fun to watch what they did this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds fell one victory short of making the postseason and
Burba played a role in their shortfall. On June 13 in Cincinnati,
he beat them, 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' he said with a broad smile. ``That's my job.''
</P>
<P>
   His job today is to put the Red Sox out of their century-long
misery. They've lost 18 of their last 19 postseason games and
haven't won the World Series since 1918 when a pitcher named Babe
Ruth won two games, including Game 1 by 1-0 over the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Boston manager Jimy Williams, trying to invoke The Bambino's
ghost, has carried a Baby Ruth candy bar in his pocket all season
for good luck and recalls the 1916 World Series when Ruth also
pitched a winning game when the Red Sox won the World Series over
the Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had room 1916 in the hotel in Cleveland,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
