<HEADER>
A1223 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDIA-ASSESS-ART-(TRI     10-08 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-ASSESS-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN INDIA, BACKER OF TOUGH ECONOMIC REFORM IS SURPRISE
WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Something amazing happened in Indian politics
in the elections that just concluded. In the large southern state
of Andhra Pradesh, the party that promised the biggest freebies
lost. And the politician who warned that there's no free lunch won.
</P>
<P>
   Congress Party candidates barnstormed with this come-on for
farmers: Vote for us and electricity will be free. Vote for us and
stop paying your bills right now.
</P>
<P>
   But Chandrababu Naidu, head of the regional Telugu Desam Party
and chief minister of the state, warned the crowds of farmers who
flocked to his rallies that free power would cost the state too
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cannot be done,'' he said. ``Don't believe their words.''
Almost as a consolation prize, Naidu promised his own more modest
giveaway programs.
</P>
<P>
   And it is Naidu's party that has swept to a landslide majority
in the state house and won 29 seats in the lower house of the
national Parliament, making it the second-largest partner in the
new Hindu-nationalist-led coalition that will soon be governing
India. Naidu won a seat in the state assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The larger question for India is whether Naidu's strategy for
economic growth will catch on in other states and in the nation's
capital. It combines cutbacks in subsidies with new spending on
education and rural development and an aggressive courting of
private investment.
</P>
<P>
   Yaswant Sinha, who was finance minister in the
Hindu-nationalist-led coalition that ran the country for the last
year and a half, said in a telephone interview Friday that the new
government would move forward with a ``second generation of
economic reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   It will quickly push legislation to open the insurance industry,
now a public monopoly, to domestic and foreign investors, he said.
The hope is that the money consumers spend to buy policies will
become a large pool of long-term capital that insurance companies
will invest in power plants, ports and other big projects.
</P>
<P>
   Sinha, who does not yet know whether he will be reappointed,
also spoke of the need for greater public spending on irrigation,
electricity and agricultural research to strengthen the rural
economy where most Indians make their living.
</P>
<P>
   And he said the new government will take politically painful
steps to scale back subsidies so it can free up money for these new
public investments.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The first test of the new government's resolve is already upon
it before it has even officially been sworn in.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, just two days after the last vote had been
cast in India's month-long national elections, the government
raised the subsidized price of diesel fuel, heavily used in
farming, by 40 percent to stanch huge losses to the government
caused by the soaring price of the fuel on the international
market.
</P>
<P>
   Already, two of the coalition's allies are howling in protest.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar situation earlier this year when one of the same
allies screamed, the ruling coalition blinked. The government had
raised the subsidized prices of wheat and rice that are mostly sold
to people who are not poor. Within days, the government had rolled
back the prices to the lower levels.
</P>
<P>
   But now the coalition has a bigger majority. Even if a couple of
smaller allies quit, the government would still have a working
majority in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to be done,'' Sinha said Friday of the diesel price
hike.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Moody's Investors Service this week upgraded its outlook on
India from stable to positive because the new government with its
stronger majority will ``be able to undertake more aggressive
economic restructuring during its term of office,'' it said in a
release.
</P>
<P>
   For decades after India gained its independence in 1947, the
economy was highly centralized and controlled by the state. The
government invested heavily in massive subsidies for fertilizers,
electricity, irrigation and fuel, but neglected primary education
and public health.
</P>
<P>
   Relative to other countries in Asia that achieved high rates of
economic growth and literacy and a rapidly rising standard of
living, India lagged behind.
</P>
<P>
   But in the early 1990s, in the midst of a severe
balance-of-payments crisis, India began to loosen the government's
hold on the economy and allow more competition. For several years
in the mid-1990s, growth rates topped 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last two years, the pace of economic change has
slowed and so has growth. In a country where the population of 1
billion still continues to grow rapidly, the economy must grow by
at least 7 percent just to generate enough jobs to keep pace with
the 10 million new people entering the labor force each year,
economists say.
</P>
<P>
   It is telling that the same elections in which Naidu, the
state-level economic reformer, was a winner, one of the losers was
Manmohan Singh, the architect of the India's first round of
economic reforms in the 1990s. Sing lost his first bid for an
elected seat in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Singh had a distinguished career as a high level civil servant.
He has a reputation for intellect and probity. But as a Congress
Party candidate for parliament, he did not have the natural
politician's knack for salesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Naidu, on the other hand, is the consummate pitchman. Actually,
when he talked Friday in a telephone interview about how to take
painful economic steps and still succeed in politics, he spoke like
a juggler who keeps many balls in the air.
</P>
<P>
   You can't just reduce subsidies and raise tax revenues, he said.
And you can't spend all your time convincing the Bill Gateses of
the world to set up shop in your state or the World Bank to invest
its billions in your projects.
</P>
<P>
   You also have to spend money on welfare programs that people
need to survive today. You have to invest in development programs
that will help them make a better living from their land. And you
have to figure out ways to make sure that the money the government
already spends on the basics _ schools, clinics, roads _ goes
further.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to appeal to investors all over the world,'' said
Naidu. ``Here in India, everything is possible. People thought that
if you talked about economic reforms, you would not get elected.
But if you do well, people will believe you and vote for you. I
have proved that now in Andhra Pradesh.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
