<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bengals never looked this way before
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ If you've been scratching your head while trying to
remember how long it has been since the Cincinnati Bengals played
this badly, you can stop scratching _ the answer is never.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three weeks, the Bengals have lost by 27 points to
San Diego (34-7), 24 to Carolina (27-3) and 28 to St. Louis
(38-10). This is the first trifecta of 20-point defeats in the
32-year history of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   And the 20 points total scored by the offense is the second
lowest ever for a three-game stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati will be reeling heading into Sunday's game in
Cleveland. The expansionist Browns are also 0-4, but that was to be
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to imagine they (the Browns) could look any
further off (from being a playoff contender) than we have,'' said
Cincinnati president/general manager Mike Brown. ``How could they?
I don't know of any team that's gone through what we've gone
through in the last three weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals have lost 14 of their last 15 regular season games
and coach Bruce Coslet will make at least two lineup changes for
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He announced on Monday that first-round draft pick Akili Smith
will replace Jeff Blake at quarterback. Later, he decided to make a
change at free safety, moving rookie Cory Hall ahead of three-year
starter Greg Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Coslet said he hopes Hall will bring ``consistency and
production'' to the position. ``We haven't been getting it done
there, so we made a change.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals haven't been getting it done at a lot of positions,
said tackle Willie Anderson. ``Check individual players and
sometimes you have to think, 'Are we good enough?' I'm trying not
to be harsh, but we're looking for answers to all those questions.
Maybe that's it. Maybe we're just not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals haven't been good enough for a long time. As they
head into Cleveland, they are 48-100 in the 1990s. With seven more
losses, they will have suffered through the most losing decade in
NFL history, supplanting the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, who were 45-106
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know if we lose to Cleveland, we'll become even more the
butt of ridicule,'' Brown said. ``While we seem to have pressed the
boundary on that, who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   RIVALRY RESUMES
</P>
<P>
   After the 1990 season, the Bengals had a 22-19 advantage in the
series with Cleveland. In the next five years, the Browns won eight
of the 10 meetings, including an active streak of seven straight.
</P>
<P>
   COATS ON PRACTICE SQUAD
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals on Friday signed guard Tony Coats to the team's
practice squad. A rookie from the University of Washington, Coats
had been waived from the 53-player roster by the Bengals on
Thursday. He was a seventh-round Bengals selection in the 1999
draft, and was on the inactive list for the first four games this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Williams writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
