<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAP-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE SCENES AT THE GAP, TROUBLING STATISTICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Gap Inc. losing its edge? When retailers reported September
sales on Thursday, the numbers were pretty good: an increase of 5.5
percent from a year earlier, according to the Goldman Sachs' retail
composite index. At Gap, sales rose even more than expected, 7
percent, news that nudged the stock up $1.1875 Friday, to $38.
</P>
<P>
   Behind that clutch performance, however, are some troubling
statistics. The entire 7 percent rise was powered by Gap's young
divisions, Banana Republic and Old Navy, each of which is expanding
at an explosive rate. But sales declined up to 4 percent in
September at Gap stores, which still account for roughly 35 percent
of the company's revenue. It was the sixth consecutive month that
the flagship chain had posted flat or negative sales. Gap Kids,
another division, has also been disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting trouble at Gap is a dangerous game. After all, the
retailer has stumbled before and each time swiftly regrouped,
coming back stronger than ever. But the landscape for Gap has
changed significantly in the last few years. Competitors have
become much more focused and are white hot. American Eagle
Outfitters, Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch and The Limited, which has been
resurrected from the dead, are all making successful assaults on
the younger end of Gap's customer base.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, Old Navy, the fun, lower-cost clothier begun
by Gap a mere five years ago, has become so popular so quickly that
it is challenging Gap stores' primacy. Gap does not break out sales
numbers for each division, but retail stock analysts estimate that
Old Navy contributes a third of Gap's annual $9 billion in revenue,
as much as Gap itself.
</P>
<P>
   Old Navy's connection with customers is a great retail triumph.
Still, the 1,021 stores under the flagship Gap name must start to
perform better or risk becoming dead weight. And the stock, while
down more than 25 percent from its July peak, looks rich to some
analysts unless the company can return to double-digit growth, for
which it needs the Gap stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors cannot ignore what is going on with the Gap
brands,'' said Richard Baum, who recently picked up coverage of Gap
Inc. for Credit Suisse First Boston by dropping his rating on the
stock from ``buy'' to ``hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Leroy Barnes, vice president and treasurer of Gap Inc., insists
that the current sales doldrums are little more than a blip in the
fashion cycle and mostly reflect how hard it is to beat the
double-digit growth Gap recorded in so many months last year. ``Gap
is up against tremendous performance of last year,'' he said. ``We
see this as a relatively short-term issue, and we do not have plans
for major change in long-term strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to argue with Gap's long-term strategy. Since Millard
Drexler took the helm in 1983, the company has transformed retail,
practically inventing the concept of a retailer as a brand _ as
opposed to just carrying clothing with a brand name. But Gap, which
aims to sell basic merchandise like T-shirts and blue jeans to a
very broad group of customers, is a ripe target for chains that can
tailor their presentation to a subset of those shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie and American Eagle speak with artistic precision to
college-age shoppers and the teen-agers who admire them. These two
retailers are small compared with Gap _ Abercrombie has some 200
stores with $815 million in total sales last year and American
Eagle has 400 stores with $587 million _ but each is growing at
stunning double-digit rates that clearly take a piece of Gap's
hide.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Leedy, executive vice president for marketing at
American Eagle, argues that his chain has a distinct advantage over
Gap, which is trying to be so much to so many people. ``Our store
environment is razor-sharp focused on that customer,'' he said,
pointing to details like music from the most recent Lilith rock
fair and couches for hanging out. ``I don't think that in their
environment they can present the lifestyle as well as we can,'' he
said of Gap.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of Gap's vulnerability is already showing up among
those early arbiters of cool, teen-agers. Last year, when Teenage
Research Unlimited, a Chicago-based market research firm, surveyed
2,000 people 12 to 19 years old on cool brands, Gap was No. 5 on
the list and the only retailer in the top 10. In a survey just
completed, Gap slid to sixth, a spot it shared with Abercrombie.
And it was right behind Old Navy, which ranked fifth. Survey
respondents also offered up bits of opinion that could be
devastating to Gap in the long run. ``They think of Old Navy as the
Gap but at lower prices,'' said Michael Woods, the research firm's
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Gap vigorously denies that Old Navy is stealing
Gap's thunder. Leroy, describing internal studies of openings of
Old Navy stores in Gap markets, said: ``After the first year, the
Gap store will do better than our projections, because Old Navy has
driven more customers into the market. We have not seen anything
like cannibalization.''
</P>
<P>
   But an executive who knows Gap's management says that Drexler,
the company's chief executive and spiritual force, is redirecting
his energies. Until last year, he had been enamored mostly of Old
Navy, but he is now convinced that Gap stores need his full
attention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
