A1241 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$A     10-08 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK STOCKS AND THE JINX OF FED CREDIT TIGHTENING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Rising interest rates are bad news for banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Every time the Federal Reserve starts to tighten credit
conditions, that nostrum is trotted out to explain why bank stocks
are suffering. But for the last two decades or so, the banks' big
problems have not been caused by rising rates.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Bank stocks have been suffering this year, in part
because investors have sold shares as the Fed has raised short-term
rates. After peaking in late April, a time when most folks thought
the Fed was friendly, the Keefe Bruyette &AMP; Woods Banks index has
fallen 15.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it may be a while before Wall Street's attitude
toward the sector sweetens. Lawrence W. Cohn, a bank stock analyst
and director of research at Ryan Beck Southeast Rearch in
Livingston, N.J., explained why last week. Here are excerpts from
that discussion: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why is this perception about rising interest rates being bad
for banks misplaced? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. That universally held misconception drives bank analysts
around the bend. And it goes back to the early 1970s, when after
roughly four decades of stable interest rates, this country went
through the first of several bouts of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In the postwar context the banking industry had never had to
defend itself against that, and banks got their clocks cleaned.
Traditionally, banks had never paid attention to looking at the
sensitivity of their balance sheets to rising rates. The experience
was very painful.
</P>
<P>
   In every succeeding rate cycle since then, and there have been
five, banks have gotten increasingly sophisticated in managing
risks by doing a variety of things, from repricing assets, changing
the mix of their liabilities to inventing various kinds of
derivative instruments that allow them to shift risk to someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   All of that has given the industry an ability to manage rate
risk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. But doesn't that perception explain why bank stocks have come
down this year? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A rise in interest rates is a big chunk of the reason, but
not all of it. There has been a real shift in attitude about where
we are in the economic cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's problems in the capital markets, coupled with the
Long-Term Capital crisis, began a view that the cycle couldn't go
on forever. And that has led to increasing concerns about asset
quality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Economic data don't support the thesis that the expansion is
nearing an end. And isn't the Fed raising rates to cool off the
economy? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We don't see any signs the economic cycle is coming to an
end. But we have gone through this before.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1988, when the economy was quite strong, bank stocks
acted quite poorly. The issue then was worry about the end of the
cycle when nothing indicated it was here.
</P>
<P>
   At some point this cycle will end, and when the market is
worried about that, things are tough. The thing that makes this
such an extraordinarily frustrating period for people in my
profession is that the stocks stay very cheap for a long period of
time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You mentioned concerns about asset quality. Are there areas
where banks are overextended? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We have already seen some of the excesses in the system.
Subprime consumer lending has gone through a terrible period, as
has credit card quality. But that has been improving now for more
than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, though, we don't see anything that would make the next
recession comparable to what the late 1980s was for the banks. When
it comes, the next recession will be sufficiently modest for the
industry that you will see a decline in earnings, but not much
else. If the market sees that modest effect, then you are finally
going to get a multiple on bank earnings that better reflects the
underlying growth of the industry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Absent a recession, can you see anything on the horizon that
would prompt investors to take a second look at the group? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A recession is the only thing that will cause the market to
reassess this situation. We had hoped that as the market saw the
better capital and reserve position of the industry, it would
recognize that banks were in better shape than during the last
recession, which for banks was the worst since the 1930s. But it
has not come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   At some point yields on these stocks will reach a point where
they start to create a floor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. For the past couple of years a good number of bank stocks had
a takeover premium built into their stock price. Merger activity
has slowed this year. Why? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The primary reason is the drop in stock prices. But it was
not possible that 1999 was going to be as active in the merger area
as 1998 was, because by any measure that was an exceptional year of
merger activity.
</P>
<P>
   Merger activity has picked up a little recently, and we still
expect a rush of activity as banks try and beat the 2001 deadline,
when pooling-of-interests accounting gets eliminated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there any stocks you like at this point, given the
market's sour mood on the group? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We think the place to be is those kinds of companies that are
less exposed to movements in interest rates from a perception
standpoint and from a business standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to companies with big processing or money
management businesses, like Bank of New York, Northern Trust, U.S.
Trust and Mellon Bank.
</P>
<P>
   We also like companies with solid dividends and the capacity to
grow those dividends. In that area, we like People's Bank of
Connecticut, which has been growing their dividend at a 20 percent
compound annual rate for the last five years. We think they can do
that for the next several years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So people should stay away from the big money center banks? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The money centers are stocks that will have the hardest time
making progress. At some point they will get so cheap they will
drag in value investors. But they are stocks that have had
substantial asset quality problems at the end of the economic
cycle. When they move out of institutional favor, as they are now,
it is hard for them to move higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
