<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERY BURNS HOT UNDER THE COLLAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Any spectators walking into the Bruins' workout Friday
were best advised to tiptoe or duck. The Bruins are off to their
worst start since 1965-66, only the seventh time they have begun
the season 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns was arguably in the worst mood he's been in
since joining Boston some two-plus seasons ago. Burns is a master
tactician at choosing his spots to use anger, pleading, and/or
humor to illustrate his points. Friday, though, he seemed genuinely
ripping mad.
</P>
<P>
   His No. 1 goaltender, Byron Dafoe, is sitting home in a contract
dispute, he no longer has last year's top checking center, Tim
Taylor, he's lost experience and depth in other areas, and he
doesn't have a center who can consistently (or even occasionally?)
win a faceoff. Add to that the fact Burns is having to audition
more players to figure out who can play in the league and who
can't, and it's obvious why tensions are rising.
</P>
<P>
   During practice at the Ristuccia Center in suburban Wilmington,
Burns peppered his language with expletives and other toxic
language for emphasis and was no less snappish when meeting the
media. These are not happy days, and perhaps what reflects an even
darker sense of foreboding is that it isn't going to get any
easier. The Bruins face Philadelphia Saturday night at the
FleetCenter, a dangerous proposition considering the potent Flyers
have scored zero goals in two games. They host the Colorado
Avalanche Monday afternoon and then embark on a six-game West Coast
swing that is always a colossal grind.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Rob Tallas, who was victimized in the Bruins' sloppy 4-3
loss to the Senators Thursday night, said the air around the team
is more like a depression than a tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of confidence,'' said Tallas. ``When
something goes wrong, the frown on the face says a thousand words.
The expressions are unbelieveable. Bad bounces are going to go
against us, but it's a matter of how you respond to them in the
positive. Rather than going after it, we're kind of waiting for it
to happen. I recall at Christmas last year we went through a time
like this. We got out of it. It's early in the season. But there's
such a cloud over this team now. I don't know if it's the Dafoe
thing or what.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns, who was as ornery and ill-tempered as ever seen in his
tenure in Boston, said he was somewhat encouraged by his team's
start in Ottawa. But turning a 3-1 lead into a 4-3 loss is
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started off much better with more grit and determination,''
said the coach. ``Everyone has got to get on the same page at the
end. We gave up some goals, took some penalties we didn't have to.
Some players have to play with emotion. We're not playing with
emotion. Skating is not good enough, there has to be emotion and
grit involved. It's tough to manufacture grit and size. It has to
come from within the heart. It's very difficult for a coach to make
a player that's not gritty into a gritty player. I think that's
their responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Anson Carter is one of those who has to improve.
Carter said he has felt a little out of the mix thus far due to the
Bruins' preponderance of righthanded shooting centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely can play better, that's for sure,'' said Carter.
``I haven't been getting the puck as much as I'd like it. All the
plays seems to be starting out on the left-wing side, and my job so
far seems to be creating space for other guys. In doing so, nothing
has been very effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to make plays with the puck as well as create
openings and so far the first three games, all I'm doing is
creating openings for other guys. A lefthanded center would help.
Then, his natural tendency is to pass to the right side and that
right away gets you more involved in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns would like to see Carter bear down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anson has got to play better,'' said Burns. ``Anson is one of
those guys that I know there's grit there. Anson's grit has got to
come out. He's got to show a lot more. Skating between the blue
lines is not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Don Sweeney, who has been through winning streaks to
losing streaks to everything in between, said it has been a tough
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only positive thing is we've gotten a little better each
game,'' said Sweeney. ``That doesn't say much. Obviously we've got
some areas we need to improve upon and that's as a whole. That's
not any one person, one play. We just need to do things a little
bit better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have teams chipping the puck in on us and pursuing it and
we need to do that. When we did that last year, we were very
successful and we need to realize that. Until we do, we're not
going to be successful. We're not a fancy hockey club. We've got a
couple of guys on this team who can stickhandle with the best of
them in certain situations. Otherwise, let's bread and butter it,
let's simplify things. Let's pick up the intensity and work
ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said the Bruins' first two goals against Ottawa were
classic examples of things the team needs to do more of.
</P>
<P>
   ``That speaks volumes right there,'' he said. ``You realize
that's how it's going to get done here. I just don't think we've
played good enough to win, to tell you the truth, especially the
first two games. It's not going to (get easier). Every night is a
test. Some teams bring more speed, some bring more size. You look
at the differential at the teams in the conferences with regard to
making the playoffs, it's slim margins across the board. Points
now, I hate saying it because we're 0-3, but they're equally as
precious now as they are in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   And so far, the Bruins don't have any.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
