<HEADLINE>
INDIANS NOT ONLY BETTER, THEY'RE CHEAPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give the Indians credit. They have a better 25-man roster than
the Red Sox, and only two of Boston's starters, Nomar Garciaparra
and Jason Varitek, could break into the Indians' starting lineup.
Yet the Indians payroll is $4.3 million less than Boston's. Here is
how the top 10 payrolls stacked up in major league baseball this
year:
</P>
<P>
   (! used as column separator)
</P>
<P>
   1. Yankees $89.5m &UR;  &LR; ! &UR;  &LR;  6. Atlanta $76.7m
</P>
<P>
   2. Baltimore $86.4m ! &UR;  &LR; 7. Texas $74.4m
</P>
<P>
   3. Los Angeles $85.7m ! 8. Arizona $74.3m
</P>
<P>
   4. Mets $79.6m  &UR;  &LR; ! &UR;  &LR; 9. Cleveland $72.5m
</P>
<P>
   5. Red Sox $76.8m  &UR;  &LR; ! &UR;  &LR; 10. Colorado $68.0m
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President/general manager Harry Sinden on the Bruins' 0-3 start:
``We have to start thinking more offense. They talk about needing
to play defense to win in any sport, and that's OK, if you can also
score. You can't win without scoring. At some point here we have to
think more about us scoring than worrying about the others guys
scoring. You need some kind of balance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter Warrick, the Florida State wide receiver suspended by the
team for allegedly being involved in grand theft larceny, would be
one the top three players taken in the NFL draft if it was held
today. And if no top college quarterback emerge, he could be No. 1.
Florida State plays LSU Saturday. Just before the season started,
Larry Foster, LSU's co-captain, was suspended after being arrested
for purse snatching . . . The call that took a touchdown away from
the Cleveland Browns last Sunday when they returned a Drew Bledsoe
interception was a bad one. A review of the film showed the
``holding'' was a joke and should never have been called. Much
worse than that had been going on all day, and the ``hold'' was a
one-10th of a second tug, rather than a takedown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next Reggie Lewis trial has been scheduled for the first
week of April 2000 . . . On Oct. 2, 1960, on the par-3 third hole
at United Shoe in Beverly, Mass., Paul Kelly of Kelly
Communications, which has put together many sports radio deals in
Boston over the years, got his first hole-in-one. On Oct. 2, 1999,
playing another par-3 third hole, Kelly collected his second
hole-in-one. When Kelly returned home to check the ball he had used
the first time, it was a Titleist 4, red. The second one was also a
Titleist 4, red. Knowing how tight Kelly is with a buck, his
friends would say he was still using the same ball if it hadn't
been mounted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notice what happens in the Miami-Indianapolis game Sunday. After
losing to Buffalo Monday night, head coach Jimmy Johnson ripped
into future Hall of Famer Dan Marino for turning the ball over four
times. Johnson said publicly that Marino had receivers open and
didn't get them the ball. TIn particular, Tony Martin had just two
catches. Reportedly, Johnson told Marino that if he throws one
interception this week, he is coming out of the game . . . Speaking
of Indy, the Colts will probably be the odd team out in the AFC
East when the new Houston franchise enters the league in 2002.
There will be eight divisions with four teams each, meaning one of
the current five in the AFC East will have to switch. Unfortunately
for Patriots fans, it figures to be Indy, which means we may not
get to see the potentially great Bledsoe-Payton Manning matchups of
the future on a yearly basis. Indy will probably be shipped to the
Central division. One team, perhaps Seattle, will be switched from
the AFC to NFC. There are only eight so-called West teams,
including St. Louis, and five are in the AFC. So one has to move .
. . Raiders owner Al Davis recommended at the NFL meetings this
week behind closed doors that the league consider eliminating all
intraconference games, setting up a Super Bowl where two teams
would not have played each other during the regular season, just
like the old AFL-NFL days. I'm all for that. There was a lot more
feeling in the early Super Bowl games when it was AFL vs. NFL.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The BTUFF group, Boston Terriers United For Football, put some
solid hits on John Silber and members of his administration who led
the charge to get rid of football three years ago, saying it was
too costly. The BTUFF newsletter contains these quotes: AD Gary
Strickler in Jan. '99: ``We dropped football primarly because of
cost issues. It's an issue how to spend our money and I don't think
Boston University wants to, or can afford to, spend $3 million a
year on one sport.'' However, BTUFF points out that in a November
1997 story in Boston Magazine, with figures taken from an Internal
Revenue Service report, BU's total sports budget was $2.6 million.
BTUFF also lists Silber's salary as chancellor at $604,212 a year
and points out in 1996, the year it dropped football, BU took in
$36 million more than it spent. Not bad for a non-profit
institution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Ted Johnson hopes to return to the Patriots' lineup
around Dec. 1, or sooner. ``I feel fine. I think what happened to
me (tearing tendons in both arms in two years) was a freak thing. I
read this stuff about being overtrained. How can anyone be
overtrained? When I come back my attitude is that what happened was
a fluke and isn't going to happen again.'' When the Patriots play
in Kansas City Sunday their top rookies, linebacker Andy
Katzenmoyer Center and Damian Woody, figure to get their biggest
tests thus far. Chester McGlockton will be playing in front of
Woody from time to time. And there's only one defensive lineman in
the league who is better than McGlockton _ Tampa Bay's Warren Sapp
_ when he decides to play. And reportedly he is playing hard this
year. Katzenmoyer will be going up against KC's version of the
Bermuda Triangle in center Tim Grunhard and guards Will Shields and
Dave Szott. They've played together for years and will show whether
the Patriots are vulnerable to an inside running game as some
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until Terry Glenn came along, Art Graham was tied with three
others for the Patriots' record for most catches in a game. Graham
made 11 receptions Nov. 20, 1966, against Kansas City, one of the
best defensive units ever assembled and the first AFL Super Bowl
representative. What made Graham's performance even more special
was that he played with stitches in his head after being involved
in a car accident earlier in the week, and before he didn't know if
he would even be able to put his helmet on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The death of Rod Shoate this week was not a shock, even though
he was just 46. Shoate, who played for the Patriots in the 1970s,
abused drugs most of his adult life and had two personalities. One
moment he was a nice guy and the next a jerk. The strangest thing
of all is that Shoate wanted to be a street person. When he got in
trouble after his playing days with drugs, some of his former
teammates reached out and helped him with money and jobs, but in
the end, he wanted to go back and live on the streets, which
ultimately cost him his life . . . Here's why major league baseball
is considering buying out two teams, namely Kansas City and
Oakland. Both teams are big financial losers in small markets,
which MLB teams have been supporting to the tune of $10 million a
year. These teams also get about $14 million a year from national
television contracts. They could be bought out for $200 million,
meaning in just four years, major league baseball would have enough
to pay for both teams and cut its losses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
