<HEADER>
A1267 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TA     10-08 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIES OF MISSTEPS HAS CAUSED GORE CAMPAIGN TO LAG, SAY INSIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT29 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Vice President Al Gore assembled his political
high command for a meeting at his residence at the Naval
Observatory last April 23, prospects for his presidential campaign
were looking good. Fund raising was on target. Polls showed him
comfortably ahead of former Sen. Bill Bradley for the Democratic
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But some of Gore's advisers, noting that Bradley seemed to be
making headway with disaffected Democrats and independents, urged
the vice president to take on the challenger before he gained
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   White House pollster Mark Penn wrote in a memorandum distributed
at the meeting and reviewed by The New York Times: ``Stop the free
ride for Bradley. His favorability is growing. And we are letting
him get his message out. The campaign must attack everything he
says and does.''
</P>
<P>
   When the group reassembled May 11, there was another memo from
Penn, this one recommending that campaign officials _ not surrogate
speakers _ attack Bradley directly. The suggested theme: ``All talk
_ no leadership. Big talk _ no ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   But after intense debates, Gore concluded that any mention of
Bradley would only give his rival more attention. Even Penn went
along with the consensus, according to many participants, persuaded
that Gore was safely ahead of Bradley in the horse-race polls. So
the vice president ignored Bradley for several months. Behaving as
if he were already the Democratic nominee, Gore saved his critiques
for the Republican front runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until last week that Gore uttered Bradley's name and
refocused his campaign on beating back Bradley. He replaced Penn
and other advisers. And now, several people who played influential
roles in the Gore operation say the failure to engage Bradley
sooner was a fundamental misjudgment.
</P>
<P>
   Several Gore advisers point to that as one of a string of
miscalculations, missed opportunities and simple misfortune that
resulted in a plight that they never anticipated: After entering
the presidential competition with the vast resources of the White
House and Democratic establishment behind him _ and more
institutional advantages than any candidate in modern times _ Gore
now finds himself in a harrowing battle for his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier on, the differences between the two could have been
painted in bright lights,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa, one of
Gore's leading supporters in Congress, ``and it would have been
much harder for Bradley to have gotten any traction.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has cast himself as the ``underdog,'' a maneuver that his
aides said was designed to diminish expectations even further.
Nevertheless, many of Gore's aides and advisers said they were
unnerved, if not panicked, by the state of the campaign. They
expressed hope that despite the fast-moving competition for the
nomination, there was still time for Gore, in the words of Roy
Neel, a confidant, ``to stop the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real dogfight for the nomination,'' said Neel, Gore's
first chief of staff in the White House. ``All campaigns go through
cycles of upheaval, dislocation and turmoil. It happens to the
best. But I would never have predicted this. I never did. I don't
even think Bill Bradley would have.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Gore has time to recover. He is still viewed by
Democratic leaders as the favorite for the nomination and enjoys
the aggressive support of President Clinton. Although Bradley is
pulling ahead in polls in crucial states like New Hampshire and New
York, Gore is still ahead in other important states like Iowa and
in national surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Gore declined to be interviewed for this article. But in more
than a dozen extensive interviews, people in the highest echelons
of his operation _ including current and former aides, outside
advisers as well as workers in the field _ described the internal
deliberations that led to his predicament.
</P>
<P>
   Past and present campaign officials are engaging in a frenzy of
post-mortems and recriminations; some are blaming everyone but
themselves for giving Gore inferior advice. But, in the end, they
conceded, a campaign is a reflection of its candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to be a great president, but he might not
be a very good campaign manager,'' said Lorraine Voles, Gore's
former communications director. ``That's not where his skills
really lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of reprimands, most of these people agreed on to speak
only if they were not identified by name.
</P>
<P>
   A senior campaign official, worried that Gore might not easily
recover, said, ``The thing that's most heartbreaking to me is he's
a solid, strong candidate who ought to be president for a million
different reasons.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rather than one misguided move, the Gore campaign's current
state results from what Neel described as ``a conspiracy of
factors.'' No one will ever know whether different decisions would
have left the vice president in a better position, or a worse one.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the interviews, people in the campaign cited several
things that _ in hindsight _ they would have done differently
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most fundamental, they said, was Gore's inclination
to mount a traditional, incumbent-style race from the White House.
Repeatedly, advisers said, he resisted pleas from some advisers to
break free from his formal role and present himself as a candidate.
Instead, Gore and others felt that if they could clear the field of
his most threatening rivals, notably House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, and act as if he were already the nominee, he could stay
above the political fray and easily capture the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Gore's advisers did not consider that the public might
not be eager for a traditional insider's campaign, particularly
after the impeachment and trial of Clinton. They said they had
conversations about locating the campaign headquarters in
Tennessee, but decided it would be too impractical for a vice
president who lives in Washington. And virtually no one, they said,
viewed Bradley as a political menace.
</P>
<P>
   Another miscalculation involved how the candidate was presented,
aides said. Gore was adroit at putting the mechanics in place, like
lining up endorsements and building campaign infrastructures in
Iowa and New Hampshire. But aides said the campaign did not devote
enough attention to explaining Gore and giving people a reason to
support him. ``His schedule became so efficient that it lost its
heart,'' said one ``We were putting out press releases of people
endorsing the vice president. But we didn't say why. It all became
about process.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some aides said, Gore was prone to micro-managing
his own campaign; it was initially run not by one strong manager
but by a series of people with varying responsibilities. As a
result, the operation was rife with disorganization, which led to
excessive spending. The organizational woes also made it harder for
Gore to raise money. Aides said the heavy spending was caused by
the campaign's determination to stage fancy (but costly)
presidential-style events _ and by an original reluctance from the
vice president to shed overpaid consultants. For example, the
campaign did not think twice about spending $800 for lighting at
outdoor events in the middle of the afternoon _ just so there would
be fewer shadows for the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With repeated staff reshufflings, the campaign also has been
plagued by turmoil and internal skirmishes. Gore's closest advisers
_ including Ronald Klain, who was chief of staff, and Robert
Squier, a media adviser _ have been supplanted by relative
newcomers. ``There was a long time when everyone was in charge _
and no one was in charge,'' said one top aide. The campaign's two
most important forces now are Tony Coelho, the former congressman
who took charge in May, and Carter Eskew, a media consultant.
</P>
<P>
   While Eskew is an old friend of Gore's, the vice president and
Coelho do not have a particularly deep history. That is a marked
contrast to the tightly-controlled Bradley and Bush operations,
which are run by people who have been close to the candidates for
years, and have been far more disciplined in putting forth campaign
themes and using resources.
</P>
<P>
   People involved in the Gore campaign credit Coelho for at least
taking charge and making decisions. And they credit Eskew for
forcing Gore to lace his speeches with gripping biographical
detail. Yet they complain that upheavals in leadership have left a
campaign that is still in turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there is Gore's image. Many advisers still recall _ and
they shudder when they do _ the news conference in March 1997 when
Gore defended his fund-raising practices in the 1996 campaign,
declaring repeatedly, that there was ``no controlling legal
authority'' that found he violated the law. They said that
performance, and subsequent incidents, have cemented a public
impression of Gore as a plodding, uninspiring politician.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the image problem, Gore's advisers said, was Gore's
self-deprecating stiff jokes. Several aides said they had told the
vice president for months, if not years, that the jokes had run
their course. But Gore continued to make it a constant theme until
the spring. Gore's advisers also said internal polls showed his
that image was damaged by his well-publicized boast in March that
he is the father of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Some problems were not of his making. The Lewinsky scandal, for
instance, froze the Gore campaign throughout 1998. Gore's aides
thought it would appear unseemly to start an overt political
campaign for the White House at a time when it would appear that
the vice president was distancing himself from Clinton's travails.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign started with this air of inevitability,'' Neel
said. ``But no one would have predicted Monica Lewinsky two years
ago. No one would have predicted that a single Republican would
rise out of a pack of nobodys and raise more than $50 million in
six or eight months.'' Gore has raised raised roughly $24 million;
Bradley, who took in more than Gore in the last last quarter, $18
million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two years ago, Gore seemed perfectly poised to
win the nomination. Month after month, he painstakingly courted
constituencies such as labor and Jewish leaders, and he toiled
behind-the-scenes to demonstrate that he had so much political
muscle that most of his rivals bowed out of the race, from Gephardt
to Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska to Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers eyed Gephardt as its greatest threat because he
could best compete for all of the institutional advantages that the
Vice President wanted, from fund raising to endorsements from
lawmakers and unions. Gore and his advisers were so preoccupied
with denying Gephardt any advantages _ he devoted much of last year
cozying up to the House leader _ that they took steps like hiring
his speech writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became such an obsession,'' said one adviser. Asked about
Bradley, the adviser said, ``I don't think anyone ever thought it
would be a big deal if he ran.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Gephardt announced in February that he would not run,
Gore and his people felt that the campaign was on track. ``When
people dropped out of the race, that kept us feeding on the idea
that Gore's got a good grip on things,'' said another top adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin said the campaign lulled itself into a false sense of
security. ``As vice president, you come into the race and you don't
see any real opposition out there,'' he said. ``All your polls are
good. The economy's great. Unemployment's low. The stars look all
lined up. I would fault the campaign for one thing: they put it
into fourth gear before he started out in first gear.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when Bradley made clear that he was running for president,
the Gore campaign took months to retool its strategy. The campaign
was in many ways modeled after Clinton's re-election bid: For as
long as possible, appear presidential and do not make it seem like
you are running for president.
</P>
<P>
   That is why when Gore formed a campaign organization and filed
papers with the Federal Election Commission, the move was announced
on New Year's Eve, so few people would notice. The campaign did not
even plan to launch Gore's showy announcement tour until this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They legitimately, though incorrectly, thought they could wait
to put a campaign together well into '99,'' Neel said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Bush's momentum _ as well as Bradley's _ led the
Gore campaign to move up its announcement to June. But many of
Gore's advisers now say the announcement tour was completely
fumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the campaign was preoccupied with the announcement
for two months and lavished enormous amounts of money on it. Even
so, the tour was marred by production failures. And Gore's decision
to use the occasion to chastise the president for the Lewinsky
scandal further hindered the vice president from establishing his
own identity. Several advisers said they regret that Gore spewed
out too many policy positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we needed to do was more forcefully give people a sense
of who Al Gore is and what's in his heart as opposed to what's in
his head,'' said one adviser. ``We began a little too cerebral with
issues. That was a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Gore's aides say the entire announcement tour was a
waste of time and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Announcing in June was a mistake _ it was too soon,'' said one
adviser. ``It was an overcompensation for an earlier mistake. He
had spent four months not being a candidate _ the perception was
the the only way to get out as a candidate was to announce. But we
spent the months of May and June doing nothing but getting ready
for the announcement. And we ended up getting mixed press from it
at a critical time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, a Gore supporter, said the
campaign's most daunting challenge now is to overcome its image as
inept. ``Everyone's telling horror stories _ whether they're true
or not, they catch on,'' he said. ``We have to turn this thing
around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
