<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-MUSEUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI, MUSEUM LOCKED IN FIRST-AMENDMENT BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- In Friday's courtroom battle between the Brooklyn
Museum of Art and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, one moment crystallized
the entire conflict.
</P>
<P>
   It came when federal Judge Nina Gershon asked the City Hall
lawyer, Leonard Koerner, if a mayor had the right to walk into any
museum sitting on city property, point to a painting he found
offensive, and say, ``Take that one off the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Koerner replied, if the painting is ``not consistent
with the mission'' of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   To the museum's advocates, Koerner's answer confirmed what they
have proclaimed: that Giuliani's threat to shut down the museum,
unless it closes a controversial show, poses a threat to the First
Amendment's guarantee of free expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``A First Amendment catastrophe,'' was how Floyd Abrams, the
museum's lawyer, described it.
</P>
<P>
   But in City Hall's view, the logic is equally clear: if art is
hung in a city-owned building that relies on heavy city subsidies,
there is a line of taste that cannot be crossed.
</P>
<P>
   If the art ``creates consternation in the community . . . there
is a point when you can interfere,'' Koerner said.
</P>
<P>
   The morning-long clash revolved around such basic questions as
whether First Amendment freedoms have limits and whether the mayor
can declare himself the one who sets those limits.
</P>
<P>
   After three hours of argument, Judge Gershon asked for more
documents next Thursday. She is expected to rule on the case
several days after that.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy started on Sept. 22, when Giuliani warned the
Brooklyn Museum that if it did not cancel an exhibit called
``Sensation,'' he would cut off its city subsidy, which amounts to
$7 million a year, one-third of the museum's operating budget.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit features several provocative works, including a
painting of the Virgin Mary decorated with elephant dung, which
Giuliani pronounced ``sick,'' ``disgusting,'' and
``anti-Catholic.''
</P>
<P>
   After the exhibit opened last weekend to record crowds, Giuliani
carried out his threat. The museum responded by suing the city and
the mayor for violating its First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has insisted that the First Amendment does not protect
public subsidies of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   But Abrams argued Friday that even when the city gives money to
a museum, its officials ``don't become the proprietors, they don't
become the moral censors.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Gershon pursued the point, telling Koerner that public
libraries are ``filled with works that are offensive to one group
or another''; does the city think it can pull books off the shelf
or shut the library down?
</P>
<P>
   Koerner never directly answered the question, but replied with a
question of his own: What if the Brooklyn Museum's directors turned
it into a museum of pornography? Would its lawyers argue ``that we
couldn't stop funding it because it's protected by the First
Amendment?''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams never directly answered that question, preferring to
build on Gershon's public library analogy. ``There are lots of
books that have done enormous harm,'' he said. ``The First
Amendment protects them.''
</P>
<P>
   He also cited a case in which the city of Miami ended its lease
with the Cuban Museum of Arts and Culture after the museum
displayed works by Cuban artists who supported Fidel Castro. The
city's lawyers noted that the exhibit offended many Miami
residents, and also argued the museum had violated its lease.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Supreme Court rejected these arguments, concluded
that the city had violated the museum's First Amendment rights, and
ordered it to restore the lease.
</P>
<P>
   In the Brooklyn case, too, the city's lawyers argue that the
museum has violated its lease, which states the museum must be
``accessible to the public and private schools.'' The lawyers say
the ``Sensation'' exhibit is ``clearly unsuitable'' for
schoolchildren; this violates the museum's mission of attracting
children; and so, the exhibit must be cancelled and the museum
evicted from its premises.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams ridiculed this argument, saying the lease does not
require the establishment of ``a childlike museum in which no one
can be angry, no one can be upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams then quoted a deposition in which deputy mayor Joseph
Lhota said one test to judge the suitability of art might be,
``Would I like my 8-year-old daughter to see it?''
</P>
<P>
   Some spectators in the packed courtroom laughed, and others
gasped.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Gershon asked Koerner if the city really was arguing that
all the museum's art ``has to be suitable for all ages.''
</P>
<P>
   Koerner replied, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   To the city, that's only being reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   To Abrams, the exchange was evidence that the mayor and his
aides have no standard of artistic ``suitability'' at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making it up as they go along,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
