u a BC-STATEFARM-FRAUD-NYT &LR;      10-08 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEFARM-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE FARM ORDERED TO PAY $1.19 BILLION IN DAMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A state judge in Illinois decided on Friday that State Farm
Mutual Automobile Insurance Co. had defrauded policyholders by
requiring that damages from automobile accidents be repaired with
lower-priced generic parts, and ordered the insurer to pay $730
million in actual and punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   A jury in the same court decided on Monday that State Farm had
breached its contracts with policyholders by having repair shops
use parts that were not authorized by auto manufacturers. The jury
ordered State Farm to pay $456.1 million, so Friday's verdict
brought the total damages from the case to $1.19 billion.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm officials had said on Monday that they would appeal
the jury verdict, and on Friday they vowed to appeal the decision
by the judge, John Speroni, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Rust, the chairman and chief executive of State Farm,
said in a statement that the generic parts were just as good as
factory-authorized parts and were mentioned in the company's
brochures and repair estimates. State Farm's practices are typical
of the insurance industry and comply with regulations in every
state, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers who filed the class-action suit against State Farm
in Williamson County Circuit Court in Marion, Ill., said that the
judge's ruling was needed to force the insurer to change its ways.
``It's a wonderful act on behalf of the policyholders,'' said
Trisha Littleton, one of the lawyers. ``It lets State Farm know
they can't get by with this any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The case was tried in two parts simultaneously _ with the
contract dispute decided by a jury and the fraud issue decided by a
judge. The Illinois law on Deceptive Business Practices requires
that fraud cases be tried by judges.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm announced on Thursday that it was temporarily halting
the use of replacement parts that had not been approved by
manufacturers, in response to Monday's jury verdict. Many
factory-authorized parts are not actually  &UR; manufactured  &LR; by
automakers, which buy them instead from independent auto-parts
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision on Friday, Speroni said that generic parts were
inferior to factory-authorized parts, and that the company had
committed fraud by promising parts that would restore cars to their
precrash condition.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of judicial displeasure that was confirmed by the size
of the verdict, the ruling strongly criticized the insurer's
business practices, particularly the fact that the insurer ``did
nothing to advise the State Farm policyholder of the inferiority of
the parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups have tended to side with State Farm, contending
that automakers overcharge for factory-authorized parts and that
generic parts are just as safe and have just as high quality.
Speroni questioned whether generic parts were as safe.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's verdict consists of $130 million for State Farm's cost
savings from the generic parts, plus $600 million in punitive
damages. The money is payable to all U.S. policyholders who had
automobiles repaired with generic parts between July 28, 1994, and
Feb. 24, 1998, except for some policyholders in Arkansas,
Tennessee, Illinois and California, where similar cases are pending
or have been settled.
</P>
<P>
   Because State Farm is owned by its policyholders, the verdicts
could eventually result in higher rates, although Murray Payne, a
company spokesman, said that the insurer would not make any
decision on rates until after its appeal was resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Littleton said that another class-action case would be filed
soon accusing State Farm of fraud involving repairs since Feb. 24,
1998, and that yet another case might be filed accusing big
insurers nationwide of conspiring to make generic parts seem as
good as factory-authorized parts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
