<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1277 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-GAME3-BOS &LR;      10-08 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GAME3-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX LICK THEIR WOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After an afternoon dominated by medical updates on
pitcher Pedro Martinez (better) and shortstop Nomar Garciaparra
(ouch), New England won't need a doctor to detect whether the Red
Sox season still has a pulse.
</P>
<P>
   A loss to the Cleveland Indians in the October twilight, and the
Red Sox will be first-round casualties in the playoffs for the
fourth time this decade and the fifth time in the last 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   A win would not only avoid a three-game sweep by the Indians,
bidding to return to the AL Championship Series for the fourth time
in the last five years, but will assure that the gates will be open
Sunday for at least one more afternoon in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back wins this weekend, and Pedro the Younger is
harboring hope that he would be available to pitch the deciding
game in Cleveland Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they got us the first night and got us the second
night,'' said Sox DH Butch Huskey during Friday's workout, ``but
there's no reason why we can't do that in this ballpark, then go
from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can happen. It might be the story of the year, if we can
pull it off. We have nothing to lose, everything to gain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, with Garciaparra sitting out the workout because of
recurring pain in his wrist, were encouraged by the news that
Martinez's back felt better than it had 48 hours earlier, when he
strained a muscle just below his right scapula (the wing bone),
just below his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling better, guys,'' said a cheerful Martinez, who
reported he slept 12 hours after taking a muscle relaxant the night
before. ``(Today) I'm going to test it, see how it feels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try, I'm going to try, do whatever I can to be
back. So far, good signs.''
</P>
<P>
   But before the Sox can even think that far ahead, they will turn
to Martinez's brother, Ramon the Elder, to pitch against Dave
Burba, who like Game 2 winner Charles Nagy features a good
split-fingered fastball to complement his hard stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez has been in this situation before. Against Jimy
Williams's Braves in 1996, he pitched eight innings and allowed
just three hits in a game that his former team, the Los Angeles
Dodgers, would eventually lose, 2-1. But that was before the
reconstructive shoulder surgery he underwent 15 months ago, and
before he was pressed into service in the Red Sox rotation because
Pat Rapp's infant son was born prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez has made just four starts for the Sox, winning
two of them, and pitched effectively against the Indians three
weeks ago in Cleveland, allowing three runs in 4 2/3 innings in a
no-decision. The Sox always figured their fate would ultimately
rest in the hands of a Martinez, but no one ever imagined it would
be Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   ``No better time for him to show up than this time,'' Pedro
Martinez insisted. ``Earlier, when I was struggling, (Bret)
Saberhagen and the other guys picked me up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, me and Saberhagen are gone, and Ramon is there to pick us
up. I have to pray to God and hope that he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Jason Varitek said it would help if the Sox, who have
managed just 11 hits (seven singles) in the first two games, took
the pressure off Martinez by scoring some runs off Burba, a 15-game
winner who faced the Sox just once this season and was not involved
in the decision in a 9-4 Sox win April 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first night, their guy (Bartolo Colon) pitched awfully
good,'' said Varitek, who struck out three times against Colon in a
3-1 Game 1 loss. ``I hate to tip my cap to any pitcher, but I have
to respect a pitcher after a game like that, especially as a
catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday (an 11-1 Game 2 loss), we were out of it before we
were in it. We hit some balls well yesterday, but either right at
people or people made good plays. But some good things started to
happen. I hit one ball I couldn't have hit any better (a line drive
caught by left fielder David Justice).''
</P>
<P>
   Harder to find positive signs in a 10-run loss than the negative
development that Garciaparra's right wrist was acting up again. The
Red Sox shortstop, who went eight days without playing in the
aftermath of being hit by a pitch by Baltimore reliever Alberto
Reyes, found that playing in back-to-back games this week took its
toll.
</P>
<P>
   While Jimy Williams put the rest of the team through its paces
Friday strictly for the benefit of the media _ he would have gladly
skipped the workout, but last year the Sox were fined because they
didn't practice when the league said it was mandatory _ team doctor
Arthur Pappas, a busy man, examined Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Pappas gave Garciaparra an injection of cortisone
after he said an MRI exam showed a bruised tendon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tendon is gliding within a sheath,'' said Pappas. ``When
there's a bruise, it's twice the size, and it doesn't like to move.
That's why it hurts like hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Pappas said the injury affects the side-to-side motion of
Garciaparra's hand, and is especially noticeable when Garciaparra
goes into the hole on a ball and makes an off-balance throw, and
when he swings and does not make contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he doesn't make contact,'' Pappas said, ``that's when
it's sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who wore a large ice pack on the wrist, underwent
treatment, which included anti-inflammatory medication. Garciaparra
said missing the workout ``was no big deal.'' Both he and Pappas
said there is little question he will play Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wrist is a little sore,'' said Garciaparra, who went
hitless in three Game 2 at-bats after hitting a home run and double
in Game 1. ``(Today), I'll go out and see how it feels. That's all
I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pappas said, Pedro Martinez felt much improved in the
48 hours since he strained a back in his muscle throwing a fastball
to Indians strongman Jim Thome in the fourth inning of Game 1, and
lasted just two more batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was able to go through his motion without major discomfort
at this time,'' Pappas said. ``The hope is (today) he'll play
catch, then we'll see how he is after that.
</P>
<P>
   The muscle strain is under the scapula, said Pappas, and it is
an unusual place for a pitcher to have injured himself. Pappas
suspects Martinez may have hurt it by overthrowing his fastball to
Thome. The pitcher feels it most, Pappas said, when his arm is at
full extension, just as he releases the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends how he throws (today),'' Pappas said. ``But it's
all very encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, meanwhile, are looking to close out the Red Sox in
a series in which they have made judicious use of the long ball _ a
two-run home run by Thome in the opener, a three-run homer by
Harold Baines, and a grand slam by Thome in Game 2 _ to complement
superb pitching and better defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood of the team is upbeat, obviously,'' manager Mike
Hargrove said. ``But we also know that the job's not finished.
Boston's not dead in the water. They have a good ballclub. I can't
emphasize that enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox met briefly in their clubhouse before taking the field,
but it was no time for inspirational, Remember the Alamo oratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no magic to how you win in the playoffs,'' Garciaparra
said. ``We played 162 games so far. Now you don't change a thing.
You go out and keep doing the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And hope you're still drawing a breath come morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
