u a BC-CPR-MYTH-BOS &LR;      10-08 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPR-MYTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHER DEBUNKS CPR AS LIFESAVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching ``ER's'' George Clooney resuscitate one patient after
another gives people unrealistic expectations of survival rates
from cardiopulmonary resuscitation, according to a Brandeis
University medical sociologist who believes the best use of CPR in
many cases is to buy time for loved ones to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Public education programs across the country long have advocated
and taught CPR as a way to keep alive someone whose heart has
stopped, by assisting his breathing and compressing the chest to
keep the heart going.
</P>
<P>
   But Stefan Timmermans, who has witnessed more than 100 emergency
room efforts to revive patients with CPR, the author of a book
titled ``Sudden Death and the Myth of CPR,'' said that because
survival rates are extremely low, the procedure should be looked
upon not so much as a lifesaver, but as a way to give the dying
person a few last minutes of consciousness with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Timmermans emphasized that he is not saying people should stop
learning CPR, since bystanders who witness someone dropping to the
ground with cardiac arrest are vital to efforts to keep the victim
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Chances of success are especially high when the victim's heart
is in ventricular fibrillation, meaning its pumping chambers quiver
irregularly and rapidly and do not forward blood flow. CPR often
buys time for defibrillation to save the victim's life.
</P>
<P>
   Timmermans said, ``It would be more appropriate to redefine
resuscitation as `defibrillation first-aid.'
</P>
<P>
   ``CPR, defibrillation, and the emergency medical system are sold
to the public as the key to saving all human lives,'' Timmermans
said.
</P>
<P>
   During the time won by emergency efforts, Timmermans said, the
victim's family should be encouraged to be at the side of the
victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regard CPR not so much a means of saving lives as a means of
`saving death,' making sudden death more dignified,'' Timmermans
said. ``It gives a temporary reprieve, long enough for family to
gather and have a few final moments with a patient.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason why CPR has been glorified in the United States is
because historically, physicians have seen death as a failure, said
Dr. James Adams, vice chairman of emergency medicine at Brigham and
Women's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has prevented us from helping patients with the dying
process,'' said Adams, who said that emergency physicians spend a
lot of time contemplating issues surrounding sudden death and how
to handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still do CPR aggressively on everybody, everybody,
everybody, unless those people express their opinions to the
contrary,'' said Adams. ``It has become a dying ritual, so in order
not to have CPR, we must ask for permission. Sometimes a patient
needs to hear that CPR is not going to be of life-sustaining
benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   A reason for low survival numbers after CPR is because its
application is so widespread, he said, and CPR was never intended
for all patients at the end of life, such as those with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other countries look at us curiously because we do apply it to
so many people at the end of life,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of people resuscitated is 65, Timmermans said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all physicians and health officials see the statistics for
survival of CPR-aided patients as gloomily as Timmermans does.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has been lauded as a city that has a particularly high
community survival rate after CPR, but Timmermans said that is
because officials there only counted patients with certain
conditions who collapsed in front of other people.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mary Fran Hazinski, who is on the committee writing CPR
guidelines for the American Heart Association, said that the low
survival rate numbers _ some in the single digits _ are misleading,
because they are an average of cities that have high survival rates
and those that have very low survival rates after CPR.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the survival rate from resuscitation efforts is 24
percent, said Richard Serino of the Emergency Medical Service.
Serino said that the rate has increased over the years, as a result
of education and putting more than 150 portable defibrillators in
buildings such as the John Hancock and the Boston Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians saw some disadvantages to Timmermans's suggestion
that families be present during resuscitation efforts. ``It can be
hard for the family to see the person nude, while we pump their
loved one like a piece of meat,'' said Dr. Peter Moyer, director of
emergency medical services at Boston Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer, who said that when his father died he realized that it
was important for his mother to know that everything had been
tried, said that at BMC, while he does not involve families in the
resuscitation efforts, he is not against doing so.
</P>
<P>
   In Orlando, Fla., Dr. Edgardo Rivera, associate medical director
for EMS in Orange County, Fla., said he asks families if they want
to watch the resuscitation efforts, and about 40 percent will
choose to stay and watch.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Rivera said, he had been working on a man for a long time
when he realized that the family was there. Rivera asked the son if
he wanted to watch. Right after the son rubbed the man's hand and
talked to him, his heart stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like the guy was trying to survive to see his son, to
say, `I want to see my son before I leave,' '' Rivera said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
