u a BC-AMA-EDITOR-APPOINT-1S     10-08 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMA-EDITOR-APPOINT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN MEDICAL ASSOCIATION NAMES JOURNAL EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Changes ``Wilkes College'' to ``Wilkes University in
Wilkes-Barre, Pa.'' in 14th graf)  
 (ATTN: Md., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT25 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a time of editorial turmoil for prestigious scientific
publications, The Journal of the American Medical Association named
a new editor on Friday _ the first woman and the first pediatrician
in its 116-year history.
</P>
<P>
   She is Dr. Catherine DeAngelis, 59, who worked for four years as
a nurse before going to college and then medical school. Dr.
DeAngelis is now a vice dean at Johns Hopkins University School of
Medicine in Baltimore and the current editor of the AMA's journal
Archives of Pediatrics and Adolescent Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. DeAngelis' appointment as the 15th editor of the Journal of
the American Medical Association comes as many scientific journals
are under pressure to increase income for the professional
societies and companies that own them.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. DeAngelis' predecessor, Dr. George Lundberg, was dismissed
last January, accused of publishing a paper on whether college
students think oral sex is ``having sex'' to influence President
Clinton's impeachment trial. The dismissal fueled a controversy
over the journal's editorial independence.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Dr. Jerome Kassirer resigned as editor of The New
England Journal of Medicine in a dispute with its owner, the
Massachusetts Medical Society, over the marketing of the journal's
name as part of the society's growing publishing empire.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. DeAngelis has a reputation as a no-nonsense editor and
administrator. At a news conference in New York on Friday, she was
asked whether she would have published the manuscript that led to
Lundberg's dismissal. She replied, simply, ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she had been given any guidelines about what
articles she could publish, she replied: ``You're joking; obviously
you don't know me. Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   To prevent another embarrassing episode similar to Lundberg's
dismissal, the AMA is creating a committee to evaluate Dr.
DeAngelis' performance each year and adjudicate any clashes between
the editor and the organization's executives.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. DeAngelis said she expected to develop a close relationship
with the committee and to consult members as ``an extra brain
trust'' on various issues, as editors often tap their editorial
boards.
</P>
<P>
   But while she said at first that she did not think such
consultations would pose a potential conflict of interest with
committee members _ who would be in a position to recommend her
continuation or dismissal _ she said in an interview later that she
might rethink her position, because she had not considered the
potential for such a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. DeAngelis, who has appended her own pithy comments to other
authors' papers in the pediatric journal, said she intended to
publish biting editorials in her new one.
</P>
<P>
   As a children's advocate, she said, she may publish more
scientifically acceptable articles on violence, lack of health
insurance for children, and substance abuse. Women's health may
also get more attention in her journal, she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dr. DeAngelis, who was born in Scranton, Pa., said that she had
wanted to become a doctor since the age of 4 but ``was told that
girls became nurses'' and that her family could not afford college
tuition. She worked as a nurse for a year at Columbia-Presbyterian
Hospital, where ``everyone told me that I was in the wrong
profession, and I looked at physicians making rounds and I knew I
was in the wrong profession.''
</P>
<P>
   She went on to receive degrees from Wilkes University in
Wilkes-Barre, Pa.; the University of Pittsburgh Medical School and
the Harvard School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``My background in nursing has made me a much better physician
and person,'' Dr. DeAngelis said.
</P>
<P>
   At Johns Hopkins she was instrumental in writing and
implementing a new curriculum that emphasizes learning from
patients outside the hospital, championed recruiting more women on
the faculty and received awards for her clinical teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. DeAngelis has a certificate in the business of medicine from
Johns Hopkins that should be helpful in running the 11 scientific
journals that she will oversee as chief editor of the AMA's
division of scientific information and multimedia. The association
says its publications bring in $54.7 million of advertising a year,
accounting for 25 percent of the annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   Income from publishing is crucial to the AMA because membership
has dropped. Thirty-four percent of doctors in the United States
are AMA members, down from 45 percent in 1988, the Chicago-based
organization said.
</P>
<P>
   Membership has fallen in part because the AMA was severely
criticized for endorsing home health products that it had not
tested, in a deal with Sunbeam. The AMA has paid $10 million in a
settlement for breach of contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
