<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ARATON-ART-NYT &LR;      10-08 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHILI DAVIS FINDS A HOLE AND HITS THE SPOT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was just a single in a deadlocked Game 2 of
another division series against the Yankees' playoff pets. It was
not the ninth inning, not the winning hit, not a perfect ending to
a major league run of two fruitful decades filled with hundreds and
hundreds of hits much more impressive than a measly ground ball
through the right side.
</P>
<P>
   This, obviously, could not be mistaken for Hollywood's 20-20
vision of a final Yankee Stadium bow. It was not Kevin Costner
looking marvelous on the mound, just Chili Davis ``fighting for my
life'' at the plate. It was Davis doing nothing beyond the norm,
applying himself as a professional hitter, plying his trade,
working the pitcher and later refusing to admit his job as a
ballplayer was almost done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about the future,'' he said after the
Yankees' 3-1 victory on Thursday night, using that unwelcome query
from the columnist with the Costner-contrived angle as a
springboard to the shower. ``I'm hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Hungry, if we may indulge ourselves, for a last hurrah.
</P>
<P>
   We won't know for a while if Davis will retire, as expected, or
how many clutch postseason hits remain in his bat, until the
Yankees complete their October business. But _ who knows? _ the
last one to savor might have come in the seventh inning of Game 2
against a tiring Rick Helling and the flailing Texas Rangers. The
game that most likely determined if the Rangers had a competitive
series in them, or would once again be a doormat on which the
Yankees would step into the second round, was still up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   The score was 1-1. Tino Martinez was on first, having led off
the home seventh with a walk. And here came Davis, 0 for 2 against
Helling, two strikeouts against a right-hander throwing all night
in the low- to mid-90s. More important, Helling was having pinpoint
location that was abetted by a plate umpire with a generous view of
the outside corner.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' 40th birthday awaits him next Jan. 17. With his
pinstriped shirt removed, the softness around the midsection is
hardly excessive for a designated hitter on the downside, but
obvious just the same. With the shirt on, with the bat in his
hands, more jarring has been the apparent slowing of Davis'
venerable swing. After a sizzling start this season, his average
after June 15 has hovered around .215.
</P>
<P>
   Though Davis did finish with 19 home runs and 78 runs batted in,
Darryl Strawberry got the Game 1 start. Of the two friends from
southern California, it is widely presumed that Strawberry has the
better chance of having his contract option picked up for next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, meanwhile, had begun to ponder going home to ride his
motorbikes, to play golf. Just not Thursday night, which might have
dragged into early Friday morning like a Mets game from Phoenix had
Davis not fought off a couple of the Helling fastballs that he had
twice struck out on, once looking.
</P>
<P>
   He fouled two off the other way, the ball looping into the
stands behind third. The count ran full. Davis dug in.
</P>
<P>
   ``All fastballs, two-seamers, with a little sink in them,'' he
said. ``He was trying to get me to hit it in on the ground, or get
another call. I wasn't going to let the ump ring me up again. I was
just trying to protect the plate, waiting for him to maybe make a
mistake, battling.''
</P>
<P>
   The foul-ball swings had not been promising, but Davis
understood that Helling was around 120 pitches for the game and was
due to put one in a place he could handle. It came on the 3-2
pitch, with Martinez, no Lou Brock, getting a jump. The ball was
down, but over the heart of the plate. Davis, bat speed be damned,
spanked it past Rangers first baseman Lee Stevens, into right, and
Martinez lumbered to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big base hit,'' Yankee manager Joe Torre called it, ``that
put us in position to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry jumped off the bench to greet Davis in the dugout as
Clay Bellinger went in to pinch-run. ``That's a perfect situation
for Chili,'' Strawberry said. ``Young pitcher who's tiring,
first-base hole to shoot for, and you know Chili's feeling no
pressure. Had that ball been up, he would've crushed it.''
</P>
<P>
   And that would have been more of a Kevin Costner moment.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, the table was set for Ricky Ledee to double in the
winning run. Roger Clemens' Game 3 pressure, Saturday night in
Texas, was gone. The Rangers, again failing badly in the realm of
timely execution, fell into an 0-2 hole like their cousins in
playoff misery, the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Texas annually seems to be an excellent example of why 90-plus
victories and a lineup decorated with run-producers are no
certification of quality baseball in this era of pitching-diluted
opponents operating on the cheap. At this level, winning and losing
are often determined in less-muscular and inelegant ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``All night, Helling was hitting his spots,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he missed. Davis found a hole. The Rangers are in one
the size of Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
