A1301 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      10-08 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  (ko) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: SCIENTOLOGY LOSES LICENSE
</P>
<P>
   A Moscow city court has revoked the license of the Church of
Scientology, saying the organization violated registration laws,
and perhaps tax laws, by listing bogus founders of the sect's local
branch. Tax police raided the sect's center this year. Scientology
officials said the revocation, which was applauded by the Russian
Orthodox Church, was politically driven.
</P>
<P>
   BELGIUM: BEEF DECISION DUE
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission in Brussels said it was examining a
four-inch-thick report that France had submitted to back up its
decision to maintain an embargo on British beef in breach of
European Union policy. The commission said its scientists would
have an initial evaluation of the report ready by Thursday. The
beef embargo was imposed three and a half years ago because of what
became known as mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: NEW COMPENSATION TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Further talks on compensation for people forced to work as
slaves in German industry under the Nazis will be held in Bonn on
Nov. 16-17, the government announced. An offer of $3.3 billion by
German companies was rejected at talks in Washington by lawyers and
representatives for the hundreds of thousands of survivors.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: ITALY SEEKS EXTRADITION
</P>
<P>
   Italy has requested the extradition of retired Gen. Manuel
Contreras, the former head of the Chilean secret police, on charges
that he gave the orders for a failed 1975 assassination attempt on
Chile's former vice president, Bernardo Leighton, and his wife, who
were living in exile in Rome. Contreras is already serving a
seven-year prison term in Chile for his involvement in the murder
of former Foreign Minister Orlando Letelier and an American
assistant in Washington.  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: JUDGES FACE DISMISSAL
</P>
<P>
   Continuing its purge of a judicial system described as corrupt
and inept, the National Assembly writing a new constitution has
announced that more than 100 lower court judges are to be removed
on charges of malpractice. The dismissals come after 22 other
judges were removed by the assembly, which in August declared a
judicial emergency, giving itself unlimited powers to intervene in
the court system.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: 4 TROOPS SLAIN
</P>
<P>
   A two-day clash between army units and left-wing insurgents near
a key oil field and pipeline has left at least four soldiers dead,
military authorities said. The fighting took place as efforts were
being made to repair the Cano Limon pipeline, which has often been
attacked by the National Liberation Army, the second-largest of
Colombia's guerrilla groups and a fierce opponent of government
policies encouraging foreign investment in Colombia's promising
energy sector.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: HONORED NOVELIST'S VIEWS
</P>
<P>
   Speaking after President Ernesto Zedillo draped him with a medal
honoring him as one of Mexico's distinguished intellectuals,
novelist Carlos Fuentes urged the government to combat injustice,
corruption and poverty as vigorously as it works to foster economic
growth. If the ancient Aztecs built monuments of stone,
contemporary Mexico should build its pyramids from the lamentations
of dirt farmers, kidnap victims and unemployed laborers, Fuentes
said.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: INDIANS DEFY VIOLENCE
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian Indian group, the Mi'kmaq of Burnt Church, New
Brunswick, has vowed to continue fishing for lobster out of season,
despite a week of violence that left dozens of lobster traps cut,
two Indians injured and a rash of suspicious fires that destroyed
pickup trucks, a white-owned house and an Indian religious shrine.
The violence came after the Indians interpreted a new Canadian
Supreme Court ruling on a 1760 treaty as allowing them to fish
commercially year round.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: GANDHI KILLERS TO HANG
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court rejected the appeals of four people condemned
to the gallows for the 1991 assassination of Rajiv Gandhi, the
former prime minister. They were found to have conspired in a plot,
directed by the leader of the Tamil Tiger guerrillas in Sri Lanka,
to kill Gandhi. A suicide bomber, Dhanu, blew up herself and Gandhi
just before he spoke at a rally in southern India.
</P>
<P>
   EAST TIMOR: GERMANS ON WAY
</P>
<P>
   The German parliament approved sending up to 100 soldiers to
help evacuate the sick and injured from East Timor. The plan was
approved by all parties with the exception of the small reform
Communist Party of Democratic Socialism. An initial deployment of
75 soldiers, of whom 20 will be medical staff members, will be made
next week, and two military transport planes will be sent to
Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
