<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1309 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV10-NYT     10-08 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK AT WORK BUT NEVER FAR FROM FAMILY  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Ill.)  (af) 
Patrice D. Samuels is a freelance writer who lives in New York
City. 
 By PATRICE D. SAMUELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three years ago, I closed my old black-and-white
laptop. My intention was to back off from my job as a freelance
financial writer for a few months so I could spend more time with
my children.
</P>
<P>
   Those few months stretched into a few years. Only now am I
returning to work.
</P>
<P>
   For some moms, the decision to leave the working life is the
hard part. For me, the hard part is going back. And I'm not alone.
``Increasingly, moms, and more dads, are facing re-entering the
work force,'' said Janet Chan, editor in chief of Parenting
magazine. ``The nature of two-career couples' lives is changing so
rapidly that these traumas occur almost regularly.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after I stopped work, my husband accepted a job near New
York City and left us in Chicago until our first-born, a son now 8,
finished his first semester of kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   I never did re-open my computer that fall. Instead, I sorted
through the huge accumulation of toys, clothes and equipment that
three children in three years had brought, packing some and getting
rid of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next six months, we moved five times, shuttling among a
hotel, my in-laws' house in New Jersey and a temporary apartment in
New York City before finally moving into our permanent Manhattan
home.
</P>
<P>
   As the months rolled by, it became clear that returning to work
was not an option. I lived from day to day, grappling with problems
like getting our then 2-year-old twins onto a bus with one hand
while holding their double stroller with the other. Occasionally, a
magazine or newspaper editor would call. I would always insist that
I would be back in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, things came together. I found a part-time baby sitter
and, for my son, a piano teacher and a neighborhood soccer league.
My daughters began nursery school.
</P>
<P>
   But my computer stayed shut. One day, a lawyer who was also a
mother asked me what I did for a living. As casually as I could, I
replied that I wasn't working at the moment. ``I keep hearing about
people not working,'' she said, as if she were pondering a puzzling
new form of body piercing.
</P>
<P>
   And so I started thinking about that space in my life where work
used to fit. But it seemed that that space had been swallowed up by
class plays, science projects and baseball practice.
</P>
<P>
   I felt like my son does digging at the beach. He loves to dig
near the tide where he can create a reservoir for the sand crabs
and tiny clams he finds. But the incoming tide always brings sand,
filling the opening as quickly as he can excavate. When I urge him
to move, he resists. He wants the water and the crabs.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the reservoir is the opportunity for work, while the
tide is my family and life, filling the space as quickly as I can
dig.
</P>
<P>
   I have become obsessed with finding out how working parents deal
with sick children, early dismissals from school and everyday
scheduling conflicts, like the time a birthday party for one twin
on the East Side of Manhattan overlapped with her sister's ballet
class and her brother's soccer practice on the West Side.
</P>
<P>
   My unassuming pediatrician confessed that she was forever
begging other parents to fetch one or another of her three
children. The woman in the waiting room with two of her three
children said she often ducked out of her office to pick up one of
her brood.
</P>
<P>
   The professional couple upstairs in our apartment building said
they had hired a full-time baby sitter even though their 6-year-old
girl was in school until 3 p.m. ``Sick kid insurance,'' the mother
explained.
</P>
<P>
   But what about things that can't be delegated? I remember a
neighbor in Chicago, a banker who went back to work shortly after
each of her three children was born. ``It gets much harder,'' she
said to me one night after my children, several years younger than
hers, had gone to sleep. ``Now I have to go upstairs and work on a
science project.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought to myself: Harder? How could a science project
possibly be harder than spending the day with three children under
5? Now I understand. It's one of those items that can't be assigned
to a baby sitter. The sitter can cart the child to speech therapy,
but you wouldn't have her hire the therapist _ or go to the book
fair or be class parent. Those tasks are part of the very reason we
have children; they are what we want to share with them.
</P>
<P>
   Now my twins are starting kindergarten and I have a new iMac. My
children look puzzled as I try to explain the new rules: You can't
interrupt me on the phone anymore, the baby sitter will be picking
you up more often and, by the way, you are going to Grammy's for
the day.
</P>
<P>
   But in my misery over having to set new limits, I remember
something that Janet Jackson, a Manhattan psychologist and friend,
once told me: My children may benefit from my going back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children learn to become more resourceful,'' she said. ``They
start to think of themselves as a family unit that can play
together. They have to rearrange how they relate to each other
because now they can't rely on mom to always come in and pull apart
a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she added, they may actually value their time with me
more.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chan, a working mother herself, suggested that parents
develop survival strategies. These include collecting phone numbers
of restaurants that deliver and being less high-minded about how
much television the children watch.
</P>
<P>
   My husband is supportive but nervous as I beg him to come home
``a little early tonight.'' He is bracing himself for lunch-hour
rushes to the school science fair that I can't attend because I am
on deadline. I am trying to find a space above the tide line where
I can create a reservoir of my own for work. But the tide always
beckons and my family will always draw me back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
