<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS READY TO MESS WITH TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Roger Clemens does not compete like other
pitchers, it has been said. Rather, the University of Texas alumnus
treats each outing like a football game against the hated
University of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens will take the linebacker mentality to the mound in Game
3 of the division series Saturday night. Clemens will be making his
first postseason start in a Yankee uniform, watched in his home
state by his ailing mother, other family and friends, with a chance
to close out the Texas Rangers in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be pumped up,'' said Joe Torre, the Yankee
manager. ``You'll see him talking to himself, yelling at the
umpire, yelling at the catcher. But that's what drives him.
Hopefully, he'll be able to keep his stuff focused and be able to
channel all that energy in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   That will be Clemens' challenge in Game 3, particularly in the
first and second innings. His emotions may be tougher to harness
than the Rangers' offense, which has batted .148 and scored a
single run in the first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Having won the first two games of the division series in Yankee
Stadium, the Yankees need only win one of the next three to advance
to the American League Championship Series and face either the
Cleveland Indians and Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill, the Yankees' right fielder, was forced to leave
Thursday's game because of bruised ribs that have affected his
breathing since he ran into a fence last weekend. If Game 3 had
been played early Friday, O'Neill most likely would have been
unable to participate, but the Yankees believe he will be in the
lineup Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has been getting messages from college buddies all week,
leading to the right-hander's start in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   When Clemens forced his trade from the Toronto Blue Jays last
spring, he spoke of how those closest to him encouraged him to go
to the Yankees and pursue a championship. This is what they have
been waiting for, the messages have said.
</P>
<P>
   Cognizant of his tendency to let his energy overcome his
command, Clemens threw three times since his last start on Sept.
30. The standard is to throw about 50 pitches in these bullpen
sessions. Clemens threw about 85 pitches in his last session
Thursday, according to Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching
coach, along with two standard-length sessions and all the jogging
and lifting he does.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens will take one last look at the scouting reports,
including those notes highlighted in yellow. He will talk aloud,
using a language all his own. ``It's a Texas drawl, with a little
Boston thrown in there,'' David Cone said. ``He talks real funny. A
lot of times I think he could use an interpreter.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens will review the tendencies of the home plate umpire _
John Hirschbeck, in this case, who usually calls a wide strike
zone. Clemens will do his sit-ups, about 200 in the estimation of
teammates. He will go through a series of stretches and sprints,
power his way through his warm-up pitches. And then he will stalk
purposefully to the Yankees' dugout and wait to pitch his half of
the first inning, a linebacker masquerading as a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's different when he pitches,'' Ricky Ledee said. ``He's
mean. Not toward us _ but just mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clemens: ``I just hope to be able to definitely channel a
lot of the adrenalin I'm going to have and settle in and throw
strikes and play our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi, the Yankee catcher, agreed that it will be
important to get Clemens through the first two or three innings,
when his emotions are peaking.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens tends to rush his pitching mechanics when he is excited.
When his front shoulder opens too soon, his fastball will fly high
and outside to left-handed batters, and his split-fingered
fastball, which usually has a north-south trajectory when it
reaches the plate, will move east to west.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed 20 runs in the first inning in his 30 starts, and 52
of the 101 runs he allowed this season were scored in the first
three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens comes into the game with a 1-2 record in the postseason,
a mark that does not reflect how well Clemens has pitched at times
in October. But as Bill Buckner learned, you can have a great
career obscured by bottom-line failure in the postseason. ``In some
respects, the postseason rap is a little unfair,'' Cone said.
``With that being said, I think he still feels this is a big
opportunity for him. I think this is a missing link for his
career.''
</P>
<P>
   When Clemens walked into the visitors' clubhouse Friday evening,
there already was an edge to his voice. Clemens asked about the
starting time for Game 3, his voice conveying frustration while he
mentioned that he had heard four or five start times.
</P>
<P>
   A clubhouse attendant went to call the Rangers' front office for
the precise schedule, and Clemens suddenly ticked off the forecast,
as if he was in constant contact with the National Weather Center.
``We're supposed to get rain tonight, and then it'll get clear, and
it's going to be 74 degrees and calm,'' Clemens said.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Clemens' first postseason game in four years, and
perhaps his best shot at obtaining that elusive championship he
craves. There can be nothing left to chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
