<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-DANCE-BAND-740(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMED CUBAN BAND IS SET TO PERFORM IN MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (Eds: Spelling of ``Issac'' in 4th graf is correct.) 
(lb) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In presenting the Cuban singer-songwriter Carlos Varela
to a group of listeners in Miami Beach last year, Maria Romeu said
she had bouts of panic during which she worried about his safety.
One of the first artists from Cuba to perform in hostile exile
territory, Varela tested the waters by singing then for select,
word-of-mouth-only audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small venues, out-of-the-way obscure locations, no
advertising,'' said Ms. Romeu, who has a marketing company here and
who promoted those appearances. ``That's not exactly how a promoter
generates revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   But Varela was a hit, and after he appeared here, more than a
dozen Cuban solo artists and bands trickled in to play more openly
to bigger crowds and dwindling groups of protesters, prompting the
occasional bomb threat _ and in at least one instance a Molotov
cocktail thrown at a club's front door _ but no major controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Headliners like Issac Delgado, NG La Banda, Chucho Valdes and
Francisco Repilado, the guitarist from the ``Buena Vista Social
Club'' documentary who is better known as Compay Segundo, helped
usher in what seemed like a new era of tolerance in an area where
bombings, assaults on concertgoers and public scorn had dissuaded
many Cuban performers from visiting.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, hostilities are at a peak once again with the
announcement that Los Van Van, Cuba's most popular dance band,
which has performed all over the United States but never in Miami,
is coming to town.
</P>
<P>
   The band is to play the Miami Arena on Saturday night, in what
promises to be a test for both freedom of expression in this city
and the shifting views within Cuban Miami, which, after successive
waves of immigration, encompasses people who vary in social class,
race, generation, politics and indeed musical taste.
</P>
<P>
   Los Van Van, arriving here for the next-to-last stop of a
28-city tour of the United States, Canada and Puerto Rico, have
stirred up passions partly because they are booked in a venue of
8,000 seats, which would allow by far the biggest audience yet for
Cuban artists here.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the concert is set within Miami, the seat of power
for conservative Cuban exiles, rather than the more liberal Miami
Beach, where almost all the Cuban artists performing in the area
have appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the band itself is a 30-year-old institution regarded
as Cuba's foremost cultural ambassador, which to detractors means
Fidel Castro's handpicked proxy. Even the name Van Van, derived
from a revolutionary slogan, grates on critics.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the concert first prompted Miami city officials to
impose requirements on the local promoter that led to two changes
of date and the moving of the event from one city-owned center to
another.
</P>
<P>
   The promoter, Debbie Ohanian, who said only city-owned arenas
were large enough to meet the expected demand for tickets, sought
help from the American Civil Liberties Union, which threatened to
sue if Los Van Van were in any way prevented from performing.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the band has cleared bureaucratic hurdles, exile
organizations are planning a large protest outside the Miami Arena
on Saturday night. Some callers to Spanish-language radio stations
have even vowed to videotape concertgoers as they enter the arena
so that the city's ``Communists'' can be identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last straw,'' Juan Perez Franco, president of
Brigade 2506, a group of Bay of Pigs veterans that is organizing
the protest, said of the concert. ``This is a provocation to exiles
and an insult to the memory of our martyrs.''
</P>
<P>
   But while older exiles shun Los Van Van as political envoys, a
growing population of more recent arrivals from Cuba, and many
young Cuban-Americans, welcome them as cultural envoys who help
satisfy yearnings for the homeland or for a connection with Cuban
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami Herald poll of Miamians last month confirmed a sharp
generational split on the issue among Hispanic respondents: Those
older than 50 opposed performances by musical groups from Cuba in
city-owned centers, 65 percent to 24 percent, while those under 50
supported such shows by 50 percent to 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The members of Los Van Van themselves say that denunciation by
conservatives here kept them from trying to perform in Miami
earlier, but that on visits to family and friends, they have found
an increasingly welcome climate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``These are different times,'' Cesar Pedroso, the band's pianist
and co-founder, said in a telephone interview. ``Everything
changes. This concert will be an encounter with fans of many years
who have not seen us since they left Cuba, and with the generations
who don't know Los Van Van personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the children of exiles supporting the band is the
42-year-old Ms. Romeu, who was brought to the United States as a
child, was reared in Chicago and became one of a handful of
promoters who have created the Cuban music scene here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about Cuba or Los Van Van,'' Ms. Romeu insisted.
``It's about a glorious music tradition. We talk about the First
Amendment and the extreme Cuban right wing, and nobody is talking
about the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Romeu's fervor for Cuban culture got her fired once, after a
leading Cuban exile group complained in 1994 to her employer, the
Spanish-language network of MTV, that she was using her office
there to help organize a private tour to Havana for a concert by
Varela. The network, MTV Latino, where Ms. Romeu was an assistant
to the managing director, said at the time that she had been
dismissed for using company resources for a personal matter.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Romeu, who has helped promote and produce Cuban artists'
performances around the United States since the late 1970s, says
she has no regrets. ``That was the beginning of a beautiful
thing,'' she said of her early support for Varela, whose Miami
Beach shows last year she describes as ``unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 250 sobbing people who knew every word of the songs,''
she said. ``Nobody said, `I hate you because you left.' Nobody
said, `I hate you because you're still there.' There was
unconditional reconciliation, and that is the single most important
thing that can happen to our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Cuban-Americans, including some younger ones, say that
even culture must be governed by the rule of law, in this case the
United States' economic embargo of Cuba. Miami's 44-year-old
Cuban-born mayor, Joe Carollo, said in an interview that he
personally opposed Los Van Van as ``Castro's premier band'' but
that in any event the city's interest in the concert was that there
be compliance with the embargo, which requires financial
restrictions on any cultural exchanges with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, city officials demanded that the concert's promoter
produce documentation from the U.S. Treasury Department certifying
that none of the money generated by the concert would go to the
government of Cuba. That documentation was obtained.
</P>
<P>
   The promoter, Ms. Ohanian, a Miami Beach nightclub owner who has
presented half a dozen Cuban artists over the last year without
incident, has been called a ``Castro agent'' on Spanish-language
radio stations here and picketed by small groups of protesters who
have shown up outside her club.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to the concert by Los Van Van, she is planning
to present Ibrahim Ferrer and Ruben Gonzalez, two stars from the
Grammy-winning ``Buena Vista Social Club'' album, at the Jackie
Gleason Theater in Miami Beach in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has to be the voice of the people who are tired of
all this,'' she said of the protests against Cuban performers.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Romeu, she said she was ready to bring Varela back
for a concert tour next year. ``I'm really committed to
disseminating this art,'' she said. ``Why can't I have a right to
it? We grow up hearing, `Cuba, Cuba, Cuba.' How can we not want to
hear Cuban music?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1332 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-VITAMINS-FRAUD-$ADV10     10-08 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAMINS-FRAUD-$ADV10-ART-(TRIMS)3TAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEARING DOWN   THE FACADE OF   `VITAMINS INC.' 
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT  
 (ATTN: Switzerland, Germany, Canada, Conn., Ark., Ala.)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scope of the conspiracy boggles the mind. For a full decade,
top executives at some of the world's largest drug companies met
secretly in hotel suites and at conferences. When federal
investigators were closing in, they moved to the homes of
high-level European executives.
</P>
<P>
   Working together in a coalition they brazenly called ``Vitamins
Inc.,'' they carved up world markets and carefully orchestrated
price increases, in the process defrauding some of the world's
biggest food companies, including Kellogg, Coca-Cola and Nestle.
</P>
<P>
   It was, in the words of Joel I. Klein, head of the Justice
Department's antitrust division, ``the most pervasive and harmful
criminal antitrust conspiracy ever uncovered.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, after the conspiracy collapsed, those involved agreed to
pay nearly $1 billion to settle federal antitrust charges, by far
the largest criminal fines in American history. Further penalties
could come in Europe and elsewhere. The companies involved have
pleaded guilty to the government's charges, but they have refused
to discuss details of the case beyond what the authorities
originally charged.
</P>
<P>
   Now, virtually every big vitamin maker in the world is on the
brink of agreeing to pay an additional $1.1 billion to resolve a
consolidated class-action suit brought by purchasers of bulk
vitamins _ the raw vitamin ingredients that go into everything from
cereal and orange juice to vitamin pills and chicken feed. The suit
alleges a wide variety of anti-competitive practices.
</P>
<P>
   How could a conspiracy on this scale ever be born, much less
survive a decade? How, in a global marketplace filled with
sophisticated buyers and sellers, could a group of multinational
corporations, largely from Europe and Asia, avoid detection for so
long?
</P>
<P>
   They did it, interviews with investigators and a review of court
documents show, with a sly mixture of corporate panache and tight
discipline _ nourished by a European tradition that encouraged such
anti-competitive practices. The big vitamin makers aren't talking,
except to say that they regret fixing prices and are working to
keep it from happening again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't dispute the facts and we've decided it is of no value
to unravel it. The situation is behind us,'' said Carolyn R. Glynn,
a spokeswoman at &UR;  &LR; Roche AG, which is based in Basel, Switzerland.
``We've paid dearly for it.''
</P>
<P>
   But even lacking chapter-and-verse corporate confessions, it is
still possible to piece together the outlines of this historic
swindle.
</P>
<P>
   It all began in 1989, when executives at Roche and BASF AG of
Germany began holding secret talks about price-fixing, government
investigators said. At the time, both companies faced pressure from
rivals and from the prospect of falling prices.
</P>
<P>
   Their solution was to agree, in secret, to carve up the vitamin
market and to recruit other big vitamin makers to come in on the
arrangement, like Rhone-Poulenc of France and Takeda Chemical
Industries, Japan's largest pharmaceutical company. Because these
companies have operations in the United States, this was a blatant
violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies seemed to be indifferent to the possibility
that the antitrust laws would be enforced,'' said Robert Silver, a
lawyer at Boies &AMP; Schiller, of Armonk, N.Y., who filed the first
class-action suit against the vitamin makers in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Roche was the ringleader. Its executives, federal investigators
say, organized the meetings, coordinated the price-fixing and
ordered documents destroyed. It wasn't just one Roche officer but a
succession of high-level executives who carried out the details of
the plot.
</P>
<P>
   The company had gone this route before. Roche's antitrust
problems date to the early 1970s, when it was fined by antitrust
officials in Europe for engaging in anticompetitive behavior in the
sale of two tranquilizers, Librium and Valium.
</P>
<P>
   Roche also faced litigation over the vitamin market in 1973
after Stanley Adams, a high-level executive in its vitamins and
fine chemicals division, sent a confidential letter to antitrust
officials at the European Commission in Brussels detailing what he
said was Roche's violation of European law in its dominance of the
bulk vitamin market.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Roche Versus Adams,'' his 1984 book, Adams said the company
regularly fixed prices. Roche would ``get together the major
vitamin and chemical producers and talk prices with them,'' he
wrote. ``Meetings were held, often in Basel. The manufacturers
discussed world prices for different vitamins and chemicals and set
a price which they all agreed to keep.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the vitamin price-fixing accusations were never proved,
and Adams himself turned out to be less than a savory character _
he was jailed in 1994 for plotting to murder his wife for the
insurance payoff _ the story he outlined turned out to be eerily
similar to the one government investigators described in the more
recent vitamin case.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, there were said to be meetings in Basel,
coordinated price increases and threats to smaller competitors. By
the 1990s, Roche, BASF and Rhone-Poulenc, which together controlled
more than 60 percent of the world's vitamin supply, formed a giant
price-fixing phalanx, the government said in court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Roche alone had revenues of $3.3 billion in the United States
while the conspiracy was running, and during that time, Justice
Department investigators say the conspirators gradually and
artfully raised the prices of raw vitamins, so as not to attract
notice. They also rigged the bidding process. The average price of
bulk vitamin A was $11.59 a pound in February 1990; in November
1998, it was $19.84 a pound, according to a study by the lawyers.
The Justice Department says that $5 billion to $6 billion in United
States commerce was affected.
</P>
<P>
   The vitamin conspiracy wouldn't be just a European operation for
long. In 1991, three Japanese vitamin makers _ Takeda, Eisai and
Daiichi Pharmaceutical _ joined in. A year later, prosecutors say,
the cartel included Lonza AG of Switzerland, Chinook of Canada and
as many as 10 other vitamin makers, including Ducoa. There are few
American companies involved in the production of vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   As the operation went global, there were regular meetings in
Switzerland, Germany and elsewhere with a varying circle of
participants, investigators said. The companies exchanged sales and
market-share data, illegally coordinated price increases and
decided, region by region, who would get what share of the market,
right down to the half percentage point, and even the penny, the
government said.
</P>
<P>
   There were also efforts to prevent cheating and regular ``budget
meetings'' to make sure everyone was on the same page, according to
the government's court documents. ``This was a very elaborate and
effective conspiracy,'' one high-level Justice Department official
said. ``The companies operated as if they were a single entity. And
they were very precise. It was greed, pure greed.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   The vitamin business is not unique.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, federal prosecutors have broken up three
international food and agriculture cartels that lasted for more
than a decade. The Justice Department says there are now 35 federal
grand juries hearing evidence about the possibility of other global
cartels operating in this country, affecting billions of dollars in
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a number of large mergers in food and
agriculture, as well as criminal price-fixing convictions earlier
this year against executives at the Archer Daniels Midland Co.,
some of the nation's leading antitrust lawyers say the legal
remedies now available may not be enough to thwart price-fixing
cartels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a one-time thing that has been rooted out,'' said
Kenneth J. Adams, an antitrust lawyer who joined the class-action
suit against most of the large vitamin makers. ``There's no reason
to believe this won't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although Justice Department officials say they have smashed the
cartel, even government prosecutors say they are astonished at what
took place over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the reign of I.G. Farben, the German chemical giant
that operated as a state-sponsored conglomerate in the 1930s and
1940s, has an international cartel so effectively and
systematically manipulated a world market.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say the secret vitamin pact may have grown out of a
corporate culture that encouraged collusion, and legal systems in
Europe and Asia that were then far more accommodating to
price-fixing than the American legal environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until recent times, European countries didn't have laws that
stopped cartels; in fact, they had laws that encouraged cartels,''
said George L. Priest, a professor of law and economics at Yale
University. ``But today, virtually every country is coming around
to the view that the more competition, the better the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   What the vitamin conspirators controlled was most of the world's
bulk vitamin production _ vitamins A, C and E, niacin and other
B-complex vitamins _ a $1 billion-a-year industry in raw vitamin
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   The big companies sell the raw vitamins to animal feed
operations, food and beverage makers, and pharmaceutical and
cosmetics companies, which turn the raw products into vitamin
tablets and even skin cream.
</P>
<P>
   America's largest food companies, which blend raw vitamins into
things like bread, rice and juice, said they were unaware of any
unusual pricing practices. ``They saw the price increases and
inquired about them,'' said Jonathan D. Schiller, another lawyer at
Boies &AMP; Schiller, which sued vitamin makers on behalf of big food
companies like Land o' Lakes, the butter maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the vitamin makers justified the increases by saying that
it was exchange rates or production cost increases,'' Schiller
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the animal feed industry, which bought huge amounts of bulk
vitamins, was more alert to the conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Vitamin producers shipped raw vitamins, often in powder form, to
a vitamin blender, or pre-mix operator, who then created a special
blend of vitamins that was sold to large farms and animal feed
operations, like the huge chicken farms of Tyson Foods, the world's
largest poultry producer.
</P>
<P>
   It had worked that way for decades, until the 1980s, when
vitamin makers saw the American pre-mix industry as a source of
additional revenue _ a way, some lawyers said, for the companies to
strengthen their hold on the world's biggest market for bulk
vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   BASF entered the blender market in 1986. According to lawyers
for the independent blenders, BASF and Roche later tried to destroy
small mixers with what the lawyers called predatory pricing.
</P>
<P>
   BASF executives declined to comment, but small pre-mix blenders
say BASF charged them high prices for raw vitamins while selling
blended vitamins directly to animal feed operators below cost, in
the hope of snuffing out their independent rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They threatened us,'' said Eugene E. Reed, a former vitamin
blender in Little Rock, Ark., who told investigators that in 1997
he sat in on a meeting in Atlanta with a BASF executive who made
threats against an American blender.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told a friend of mine: `You need to remove yourself or
you'll be forced out of the business.'''
</P>
<P>
   There were logical reasons for combining production and
blending, like getting to market faster. But lawyers involved in
the class action say the larger economic reason was simple:
eliminating competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``You squeeze out the guy in the middle,'' said Adams, the
lawyer for the pre-mix blenders. ``You vertically integrate, and
then you control both ends.''
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s, blenders and animal feed producers had grown
increasingly suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   Among themselves, they repeated tales of threats to small
blenders, and some vitamin customers complained about a lack of
competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did notice that the bids seemed to be unusually
consistent,'' said Les Baledge at Tyson in Springdale, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you went to a competing company they said the supply
wasn't available.''
</P>
<P>
   For the vitamin cartel, the beginning of the end may have been
signaled by the scandal at Archer Daniels Midland. In 1996, the
company agreed to pay $100 million to settle federal charges that
in the early 1990s executives had conspired with European and
Japanese companies to fix the prices of feed additives.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, it was the biggest international cartel ever
uncovered by federal prosecutors. One key Archer partner was Roche,
which agreed in 1997 to pay $14 million to settle criminal charges
that it helped fix prices for one additive, citric acid.
</P>
<P>
   The Archer case cracked open because of Mark E. Whitacre, an
Archer executive who secretly tape-recorded company executives
discussing price-fixing with rivals. Then came confessions from
other executives. During the investigation, Justice Department
officials heard Roche might have also been fixing prices in the
vitamin market.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no immediate confession on vitamins, partly
because there was no tape and no mole. When Kuno Sommer, head of
marketing in the vitamins and fine chemicals division of Roche, a
key participant in the meetings on citric acid, was questioned by
federal agents in March 1997, he denied that there was any
price-fixing in vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents later discovered, according to the government's
settlement documents, that before the 1997 interview, Sommer had
``met separately with at least two other high-level Roche
executives. At the end of those meetings, it was understood by the
individuals that if Sommer was asked about Roche's participation in
a vitamins cartel, Sommer would lie and deny that such a cartel
existed.''
</P>
<P>
   By that time, private antitrust lawyers had begun their own
investigation in hopes of winning a huge settlement. Among their
findings was a memo Sommer had written in September 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good experience with citric acid,'' Sommer wrote before a
meeting with Archer executives. ``Next opportunity B2. We think
it's worth that we explore all possibilities of cooperation. Let's
explore cooperation product-by-product.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1998, some of the nation's leading law fims joined the fray.
Cohen, Milstein, Hausfeld &AMP; Toll was investigating the case.
Lawyers at Boise &AMP; Schiller _ headed by David Boies, who is
prosecuting Microsoft for the government _ filed suit on behalf of
J &AMP; R Feed Services in Cullman, Ala., accusing large vitamin makers
of conspiring to fix prices. A year later, the Justice Department
brought its first price-fixing charges against Lonza of
Switzerland. Then the department turned to the biggest players.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the big three vitamin makers _ Roche, BASF and
Rhone-Poulenc _ denied the charges. Even when lawyers working at
Roche learned about the conspiracy in late 1997 or early 1998 and
directed that it be stopped, according to other lawyers involved in
the case, the cartel continued to operate. Meetings were moved to
executives' homes to avoid detection.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this year, Rhone-Poulenc broke ranks. It came
forward as part of an amnesty program, begun in 1994, that offers
leniency to the first company to cooperate in a federal antitrust
investigation. Some lawyers involved in the case say Rhone-Poulenc
was eager to appease regulators scrutinizing its pending merger
with Hoechst AG, the German pharmaceutical giant, which earlier
this year paid $36 million to settle federal charges that it had
conspired to fix prices on food preservatives.
</P>
<P>
   After Rhone-Poulenc's confession, the cartel's wall of silence
crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Roche and BASF stepped forward. So did a large group of Japanese
companies, which agreed last month to pay $137 million to settle
vitamin price-fixing charges. Roche was hit the hardest, though,
agreeing to pay $500 million to settle charges, equivalent to about
one year's revenue from its vitamin business in the United States.
Two Roche executives have been sentenced by federal courts to
prison terms of a few months. BASF paid $225 million and
Rhone-Poulenc avoided any fine.
</P>
<P>
   Partly as a result of those payments, the Justice Department's
antitrust division has already recovered $1 billion in all cases
this year, more than in the previous 30 years combined.
</P>
<P>
   Archer Daniels Midland ``was not the iceberg.'' said Klein, of
the Justice Department, ``it was the tip.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   What was it about vitamins that nourished a conspiracy?
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust experts say international cartels develop because the
right dynamics are in place. Most operate in concentrated markets
with few players, making it easy to coordinate pricing. They also
operate in businesses that require a big investment to enter.
Price-fixing commonly involves commodities, like paper or
chemicals, because generic products are harder to differentiate,
allowing conspirators to price uniformly. Vitamins were a perfect
fit.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there have been huge sanctions against the
conspirators, some experts worry that the penalties may not be
enough to prevent cartels from reappearing. Adams, the lawyer, said
the Justice Department ought to compel the breakup of the cartel's
American subsidiaries, because they have already killed off many of
their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Justice Department could have imposed structural relief to
inject competition,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   The vitamin cartel made billions of dollars, he said, often with
price mark-ups of 20 percent, far more than the cartel will repay
in criminal fines. ``That made it worthwhile,'' he said. ``Their
thinking was, A: You might not get caught. B: If you get caught,
you pay the ticket. Is this simply an expensive license to keep
stealing?''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department doesn't think so. Officials say the
agency has fulfilled its legal duty. They add that the antitrust
division does not have the authority to restructure foreign
companies and does not want to force them to break up American
subsidiaries. ``The penalties coupled with the jail time I think is
a far greater deterrent than structural relief,'' Klein said. ``I'm
confident that we've nuked this cartel.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, questions remain about whether the big vitamin makers,
which dominate the world market, will try again to raise profits
artificially. Even after the Archer Daniels Midland scandal and
government investigations into the vitamin market, investigators
say Roche continued to operate at the head of the cartel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically kept perpetuating it, basically saying it's
worth it,'' one Justice Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Roche was hit with big fines for being a repeat offender,
Roche executives say the conspiracy was carried out by a small
group of rogue executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will understand that this was not part of our
responsibility,'' Franz Humer, the chief executive, said at a news
conference in Basel after the settlement. ``It is certainly not
easy to understand the reasons for actions of employees who in
secrecy organized a conspiracy of this kind.''
</P>
<P>
   BASF executives said something similar, arguing that there is no
foolproof way to prevent another cartel from developing. ``There
will be no 100 percent guarantee that even with audits, everything
will be legal,'' Eggert Voscherau, a BASF board member, said in an
interview with The Chemical Markets Reporter in July. ``We cannot
set up a police state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
