<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STOP AND SMELL THE SOURDOUGH  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Money magazine has named San Francisco the
country's most livable city, which will come as startling news to
the people who die here.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine apparently is willing to overlook the fact that
we're in the middle of a thrilling race to see who can shut down
and destroy the city first _ the developers, Muni, the landlords,
the slumlords, the yuppies, the drifters, the junkies, the FBI, the
SUV warriors, the mayor, the mayoral wannabes, the meter maids, the
greedy, the needy, the undecideds, the triple-parkers or the
terminally cranky.
</P>
<P>
   But before you mock Money for its naivete, please consider the
possibility that the magazine got it right.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, if the livable-cities competition was the Miss
America pageant, all of the contestants would be pregnant, divorced
and chewing gum. Big cities have big problems.
</P>
<P>
   If San Francisco is falling apart, maybe it's falling apart more
slowly and more charmingly than other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, a glut of wealthy, successful people with too many
big cars want desperately to move to San Francisco and learn
humility at the hands of our four-star maitre d's. While this
invasion creates problems, it's also a sign that the city has some
redeeming qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Next time you're hurrying to the protest rally, stop and smell
the sourdough, the tortillas, the garlic, the tempura, the fish,
the fog and the roses.
</P>
<P>
   JESSE VENTURA: Bigger bag of wind than anyone imagined. The
human Whoopie Cushion.
</P>
<P>
   What were the people of Minnesota thinking when they elected the
guy governor? They should have pushed him on directly to the U.S.
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   BURNING DOWN the house: When that hotel on Valencia burned down
Monday night, the flames leapfrogged one building and singed the
Elbo Room, one of the Mission's fine cultural institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the day of week, the Elbo Room is a yuppie pickup
zoo or a homey neighborhood hangout, and the nightly live music is
the very soul of cutting-edge diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The bar reopened Thursday, but the upstairs music room will be
out of commission for another month or so.
</P>
<P>
   THE GRATE-ingness of the Raid-uhs: Stop me if you've heard this,
but Al Davis is talking about moving his Raiders back to Los
Angeles, a proven hotbed of NFL apathy.
</P>
<P>
   Davis says his team needs a full stadium in order to win.
Usually it's the other way around, but Al makes his own rules.
</P>
<P>
   If he needs a full stadium to inspire his gladiators, Davis
should give one of the Oakland high schools a call.
</P>
<P>
   They'd be glad to rent out one of their fields every Sunday. The
rental fee will help offset the cash shortage caused by the drain
from city coffers caused by the ludicrous deal the city cut to
bring back the Raiders four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Really, though, Al needs to take the Raiders back to Los
Angeles, where, dripping with diamond-and-silver jewelry, Davis can
be limo'd to the city's hippest restaurants, where he kicks back
with his Beverly Hills pals and bemoans the fact that his players
have gone Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The sooner Davis can get the Raiders back to Los Angeles, the
sooner the Oakland politicians can get to work on a new scheme to
bankrupt the city by luring the Raiders back to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   FUNNY THING IS, I like Al Davis. Sports aren't supposed to be
dull.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Al is the only Bay Area football team owner with no
felony convictions.
</P>
<P>
   DOWNTOWN OAKLAND, and Ray Peters spots a car with license plates
SKYDIVA, and a disabled placard on the dash.
</P>
<P>
   Wow! She parachutes, she sings, maybe she sings during
free-fall. How's that for not letting a disability keep you down?
</P>
<P>
   FROSTED: At the Rhinoceros Business Toastmasters Club, Harold
Lustig was honored for achieving the rank of Competent Toastmaster
(CTM). A beautiful cake was rolled out, inscribed: ``Happy Birthday
Jennifer.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Gravitt reports the mix-up, but has heard no report on
Jennifer's reaction to her cake: ``Congratulations Harold on your
CTM and good luck with your book on gay and lesbian financial
security.''
</P>
<P>
   CORRECTIONS (a regular feature of this column): The bridge of
the ship named San Francisco that is the memorial at Lands End is
not from the original vessel San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   There have been three.
</P>
<P>
   The first was a cruiser built in San Francisco and launched in
1890. The second was the warship heavily damaged during fighting at
Guadalcanal in 1942. San Francisco 3 is the submarine that will be
in Alameda for Fleet Week festivities.
</P>
<P>
   I also wrote about a Ford Wrangler? Wrong. It's Jeep Wrangler.
</P>
<P>
   And I should know that; I worked one summer as a wrangler on a
Jeep ranch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
