<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1336 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GENENTECH-GENENTCH_SF     10-08 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-GENENTCH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Genentech Stock Plunges  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shares of Genentech, the South San Francisco biotech leader, took a
pounding yesterday after the firm's Swiss parent said it would sell
as much as 17 percent of its stake to provide investors with a
greater supply of the much-in-demand stock.
<P>
   The surprise move sent Genentech's share price down $15.06 to
close at $157.75, a nearly 9 percent decline from $172.81 on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Roche Holding AG, the Swiss pharmaceutical giant that in June
scooped up the 35 percent of Genentech it didn't already own, will
turn a profit of about $3.4 billion when it sells as many 22
million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Although Roche's chief executive, Franz Humer, said in a
statement that the move is intended only ``to provide more
liquidity in Genentech shares requested by the market,'' analysts
see the company having a somewhat more selfish motive.
</P>
<P>
   Roche simply may be seeking to cash in on a 65-percent gain in
Genentech's share price since the stock was offered to the public
in July.
</P>
<P>
   Or the company may be adding to its war chest amid a slew of
lawsuits and fines related to a price-fixing scandal in the vitamin
market. Roche already has agreed to pay a $500 million fine to U.S.
authorities, and is facing a similar probe by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   A third scenario envisions Roche using proceeds from the stock
sale to acquire other biotech or pharmaceutical firms. In any case,
the European conglomerate will maintain a controlling 65 percent
stake in Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts weren't startled that Genentech's stock would lose some
ground after its big run-up in value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genentech is the granddaddy of biotech,'' said Alan Auerbach,
an analyst with First Security Van Kasper in Southern California.
``You've got a huge demand and a limited supply of shares.
Typically, when someone announces a (big sale of shares), you see a
drop in the stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Genentech also reported third-quarter earnings yesterday, but
the results were overshadowed by the Roche announcement and it's
not clear what impact they had on the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech posted a net loss of $62.8 million (49 cents per
share) compared to net income of $63.4 million (49 cents) a year
before.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding special charges and taxes related to Roche's
acquisition of Genentech stock, Genentech earned $66.9 million (51
cents) in the most recent quarter. That was way ahead of analysts'
average estimate of 40 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue in the quarter rose 10 percent, to $345.3 million, from
$313.9 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced a two-for-one stock split, effective
after Roche sells its shares. The two moves will effectively
quadruple the number of Genentech shares in circulation.
</P>
<P>
   While such developments should be catnip to investors, Robert
Toth, an analyst with Prudential Securities in San Francisco, said
the earnings news was offset by concerns about a pair of cancer
drugs that have largely fueled Genentech's recent advance.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes remain high that Herceptin, for treating breast cancer,
and Rituxan, for non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, will result in an eventual
windfall for the firm. But Toth said investors may be skittish
about product sales released yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Herceptin totaled $40 million in the first quarter and
jumped to $46 million in the second quarter, but registered slower
growth, to $47.9 million, in the most recent three-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Rituxan sales, meanwhile, came in at $57 million in the first
quarter and jumped to $74 million in the second quarter, but dipped
to $72.4 million in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech CEO Art Levinson thinks investors were overreacting to
the quarterly sales numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone thinks we're going to be growing sales of any
product at 50 percent every year, they're nuts,'' he said. ``At
some point, you can only be so fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Levinson speculated that investors were more worried yesterday
about Roche's stock sale than about the prospects for Genentech's
top two drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just asking themselves questions about the ability
of the public to take up the new shares,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Levinson added that the quadrupling of available shares likely
will have a ``neutral to positive'' impact on Genentech's stock
over the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the company has a healthy flow of products in its
pipeline. According to Levinson, Genentech now has three drugs (or
new applications for existing drugs) in Phase II trials, eight
ready for or in Phase III trials, and two others awaiting
regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   Phase I is when low-dose testing begins on a small group of
human subjects. Phase II involves a larger group and larger doses.
Phase III is the last round of testing prior to seeking a green
light from the government for commercial use.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech was founded in 1976 and has remained a dominant player
in the biotech industry. It makes drugs to treat a variety of
conditions, including cancer, heart disease and growth
deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
