u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-ASTROS-ART     10-08 0339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ASTROS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN'S BAT PUTS ASTROS ON THE EDGE OF AN ABYSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Batting heroics from Brian Jordan, fielding heroics
from Walt Weiss and managing heroics from Bobby Cox combined Friday
to help the Atlanta Braves beat Houston, 5-3, in 12 innings and
move one victory away from eliminating the Astros in the division
series.
</P>
<P>
   Driving in all five Atlanta runs, with a three-run homer in the
sixth and a two-run double in the 12th, Jordan was the star of Game
3 at the Astrodome. But Weiss saved the day for Atlanta with a
nifty play at shortstop in the 10th, and Cox resorted to using Greg
Maddux in relief and Kevin Millwood as a closer in order to put his
team up by 2-1 in the series.
</P>
<P>
   A victory by the Braves here in game four Saturday _ with John
Smoltz opposing Shane Reynolds, Houston's first-game winner _ would
advance Atlanta to the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's tie-breaking double came off Jeff Powell in the 12th.
The rally began with one out, when Otis Nixon singled to left
field. Bret Boone singled Nixon to second base. Chipper Jones
chopped out to third base, while Nixon and Boone advanced.
</P>
<P>
   With first base open, manager Larry Dierker of the Astros
elected to pitch to Jordan, rather than giving him an intentional
walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you walk him, you load the bases and you still get a pretty
good hitter up there in Andruw Jones,'' Dierker explained after the
game. ``If I'm pitching,'' the former 20-game winner went on,
``that's what I want to do _ pitch to him and make him hit a tough
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   So Powell pitched and Jordan hit a line drive down the right
field line that scored both runners. Cox then turned to Millwood,
who pitched a one-hitter in Game 2 on Wednesday, and the
right-hander retired Houston in order to end a memorable game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
