<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   S&AMP;P 500 GAINS 18 POINTS ON BARGAIN-HUNTING SPREE
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 18.38 points, or 1.39
percent, to 1,336.02, in reaction to a buying spree by bargain
hunters. The market was also responding to the mixed jobless report
for September. The unemployment rate remained at 4.2 percent last
month, but the report signaled that wages are rising at a
faster-than-expected clip.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average jumped 112.71 points, or 1.07
percent, to 10,649.76. The Nasdaq composite index increased 25.87
points, to 2,886.57.
</P>
<P>
   A LIMIT FOR COMPUTER TECHNOLOGY?
</P>
<P>
   A researcher at Intel contends in the journal Science that
computer technology is reaching a limit for how small silicon chips
can become. The limit would end a phenomenon known as Moore's law,
which says that every 18 months, the number of transistors that
will fit on a silicon chip doubles.
</P>
<P>
   FCC LOOSENS RULES FOR CABLE
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission has substantially loosened
the rules that have limited one company from controlling too much
of the cable industry. The decision clears the way for AT&AMP;T to own
more than a third of the United States' franchises offering
subscribers television, telephone and high-speed Internet services,
as well as own major interests in a number of major video producers
and television programmers.
</P>
<P>
   STATE FARM MUST PAY DAMAGES
</P>
<P>
   A state judge in Illinois has decided that State Farm defrauded
policyholders by requiring that damages from auto accidents be
repaired with lower-priced generic parts, and ordered the insurer
to pay $730 million in actual and punitive damages. Earlier in the
week a jury said the insurer breached its contracts with
policyholders by having repair shops use parts that were not
authorized by auto manufacturers. The new verdict brought the total
damages from the case to $1.19 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ROCHE TO CUT STAKE IN GENENTECH
</P>
<P>
   Genentech said Roche Holdings would reduce its stake in the
company to 65 percent from 82 percent by selling 20 million shares.
Investors sold on the news, driving Genentech's stock down
$15.0625, to $157.75.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZILIAN PRIVATIZATION DISRUPTED
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Minas Gerais state in Brazil, Itamar Franco, who
caused a currency crisis for the country in January, is trying to
sabotage a federal program to privatize state-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
   NATWEST DISMISSES CHIEF EXECUTIVE
</P>
<P>
   National Westminster dismissed its chief executive, Derek
Wanless, to try to regain investor confidence and thwart a takeover
bid by the Bank of Scotland. The move was expected because
investors had lost confidence in him after several failed attempts
to acquire other companies, including the British insurer Legal and
General Group.
</P>
<P>
   CRUDE-OIL PRICE FALLS ON SUPPLY DATA
</P>
<P>
   The price of crude oil fell $1.55, to $20.90 a barrel, capping a
15 percent decline for the week, following reports of small
increases in oil supplies.
</P>
<P>
   IBM SET TO CUT ABOUT 1,000 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   IBM plans to cut up to 10 percent of its personal-computer work
force, or up to 1,000 workers, in a cost-cutting effort to turn
around the division, which lost nearly $1 billion last year. The 5
percent to 10 percent reduction in the work force of 10,000 will
mostly affect marketing employees as the company consolidates its
staff for different brands.
</P>
<P>
   CANADIAN UNEMPLOYMENT RATE DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Canada's unemployment rate fell 0.3 percent, to 7.5 percent in
September, the lowest level in over nine years. It is the latest
piece of evidence that suggests Canada's economy is heating up.
</P>
</TEXT>
