<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1339 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-RAINBOW-RAINBOW_SFCHR     10-08 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAINBOW-RAINBOW </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 California's First Gay Chamber of Commerce Forms
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Loren Stein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Special to the Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Like any entrepreneur starting from scratch, Larry Rosen knew he
needed contacts to build his Redwood City law practice.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosen, who is gay, didn't want to go through the established
networking channels. ``As a gay businessman, I didn't feel
comfortable signing up with the Rotary Club, there's not a lot
there I can relate to,'` he said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney, who specializes in business litigation, had only
limited success jump-starting his business by putting ads in the
Lavendar pages _ the gay equivalent of the Yellow pages _ and
tapping a gay business organization for leads.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, he hit on the idea for a networking organization to
help gay and lesbian businesses.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of a few other business owners, he founded the
Rainbow Chamber of Commerce, the first gay chamber of commerce in
California and one of only a handful in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow Chamber of Commerce officially opened its doors last
June to gay and lesbian businesses in Santa Clara, San Mateo,
Alameda and Santa Cruz counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're saying is, we're a substantial business community,
we're here, and we want to be strong and effective,'' Rosen said,
the group's president. ``When we asked ourselves what type of
business group does the job best, the answer was a chamber of
commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   The group hopes the chamber designation will give it the
credibility it wants to improve business conditions for its members
as well as clout with public agencies. Such groups can be quite
effective. In San Francisco, for example, the gay business
community is well-represented by the 25-year-old Golden Gate
Business Association, the first professional organization founded
for gay, lesbian and gay-friendly businesses in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, there have been mixed opinions about the South
Bay's new gay chamber of commerce. Steve Tedesco, president of the
San Jose Silicon Valley Chamber of Commerce, which represents 2,000
members, has a hard time with the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little irritating that three people can get together
and call themselves a chamber of commerce,'' he noted. ``In my
opinion, it's really a trade association (with) like-minded people
coming together to solve their problems and not the problems of the
community at large.''
</P>
<P>
   He also argued that people aren't loyal to businesses because
they are gay-owned, but because they provide the best products and
services.
</P>
<P>
   Others don't see a problem with it. ``The traditional chamber is
more geographically based,'' said Dave Kilby, vice president of the
California Chamber of Commerce, which represents some 450 chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, name your favorite ethnic or minority group and there's
probably a chamber of commerce out there. It's the way of the
world. We've no problem with it and moreover, we've no authority
over it,'' said Kilby, noting the chamber name is not trademarked
and chambers are not required to belong to an umbrella
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly O'Brien, a Rainbow chamber member who owns Silicon Valley
Appraisal in San Jose, said the organization is definitely needed
to help build a professional community among gay and lesbian
business owners. She said that she personally feels less
self-conscious at gay-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to play the pronoun game,'' she said. ``It's
easier for people who are not completely out of the closet to
patronize gay and lesbian businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   With 17 businesses signed up so far, Rainbow chamber officials
are working to get the word out about their group.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of gay business people sitting on the sidelines
asking, `What are you going to do for us?''' Rosen said. '`Once
they join, and we reach critical mass, they'll see the results of
working together cooperatively.''
</P>
<P>
   The chamber, which is also open to supportive businesses and the
general public, hopes to get the backing of prominent local
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to go out and sign up the big players in Silicon
Valley: Hewlett-Packard, Apple, Sun,'' said Rosen. ``They need our
business and we need their support.''
</P>
<P>
   There's general agreement in the business community in the South
Bay that there is a large potential market for gay businesses.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, gay business owners and local activists believe the
time is ripe for the South Bay's gay community to begin flexing its
economic and political muscle.
</P>
<P>
   However, unlike San Francisco's gay community, which is
well-organized, highly visible and concentrated in a relatively
small geographic location, the South Bay gay community is diffused,
lacking a unified voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gay and lesbian business community has been invisible in
terms of political clout, which is really an arena chambers operate
in,'' said Barbara Jones, executive director of the Billy DeFrank
Lesbian &AMP; Gay Community Center in San Jose. ``The best thing about
the chamber starting is that it opens another door for building
alliances across many issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Gate Business Association, which has 300 members,
including Wells Fargo, Bank of America, Pacific Bell and PG&AMP;E, is
encouraging the efforts of the Rainbow Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   '`It'll help gay and lesbian business owners show mainstream
corporations that they're a viable part of the business
community,'' said Golden Gate president Thomas Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said the emergence of the South Bay's first gay chamber is
especially important because the region has traditionally been more
conservative. ``Gays and lesbians who work there are more afraid to
come out of the closet for fear of retaliation, against their own
jobs or their clients.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ray and other supporters of the chamber say that
conservative sentiment has shifted these days to a more tolerant
climate. They say young Internet and high-tech companies in the
region encourage creativity and tend to be more interested in an
employee's talents than his or her sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gillard, a chamber member and publisher of Out Now News
Magazine and Pipers Vision Marketing and Design in San Jose, said
that along with the group's more traditional functions, the new
group will be a forum to discuss problems of the gay business
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all share in the challenges facing gay business owners,
such as do we come out to our clients or not?'' Gillard said. ``We
need an environment that supports a dialogue on these kinds of
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow Chamber of Commerce joins six other official gay and
lesbian chambers in the United States. Three are in Texas; the
others are in Chicago, Phoenix, and Minneapolis. (The Greater San
Diego Business Association also refers to itself as the city's gay
chamber of commerce.) According to the heads of both the Houston
and Chicago chambers, there has been virtually no backlash or
opposition to their work.
</P>
<P>
   The Greater Houston Gay and Lesbian Chamber of Commerce was one
of the first chambers ``brave enough to use the name,'' said
founding president Coy Tow. ``We've had an overwhelmingly
supportive response,'' he said. Started in 1995, it now has 350
members, including Chase Bank, Shell Oil, and Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Boyer, co-chair of the 300-member Chicago Area Gay &AMP;
Lesbian Chamber of Commerce, said the chamber name ``has been a
huge benefit to us, it's immeasurable.''
</P>
<P>
   Other chamber presidents in the South Bay warn that there's hard
work ahead for the Rainbow chamber not so much because of its
novelty, but because it covers four counties.
</P>
<P>
   '`They'll have their work cut out for them, like any chamber,
but particularly because of their broad reach geographically,''
says Susan Frank, president of the Palo Alto Chamber of Commerce.
'`I wish them well.''  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
