<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-TEST-BAN-TEXT-2TAKES-     10-08 1802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-BAN-TEXT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND TESTING: FIVE SENATORS' VIEWS ON U.S. ROLE IN WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Del., Miss., Okla., N.Y.)   (with TEST-BAN-TREATY)  
(editors: selected excerpts may be used as sidebars) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following are comments from five senators during
the arguments presented Friday for and against the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEN. JON KYL, R-ARIZ. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to talk a little bit about a common thread of many of
the people who are in opposition to the treaty here, a common
thread of their remarks here this morning. And that is that it is
difficult for the United States to sustain our position as the
world leader, and many in the international community would find it
objectionable if the United States rejected the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty, and that this would hurt our ability to lead with
respect to proliferation of nuclear weapons. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The world community, which does not want the United States to
develop a ballistic missile defense, which doesn't want the United
States to do anything that would require an amendment to the A.B.M.
Treaty, and some of which is very much in favor of total nuclear
disarmament and has agreed to participate in this treaty only after
leaders promised them that this Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty would
be one of several key steps toward nuclear disarmament _ all of
those people in the world, I submit, are not people that we want to
make United States national defense policy. Their goals are not the
same as our goals.
</P>
<P>
   We have an obligation, as the leader of the free world, to
insure that our nuclear deterrent is safe and reliable. They don't.
</P>
<P>
   We may have to do things that they could never dream of doing,
including nuclear testing to insure the safety and reliability of
our nuclear stockpile. They don't have to worry about that. But we
do. . . .
</P>
<P>
   So I frankly don't care much if people around the world who
don't want us to defend ourselves against ballistic missile attack
are going to criticize us for rejecting a flawed, unverifiable,
ineffective C.T.B.T. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Just close with this point: The whole world thought that Ronald
Reagan was wrong, that he had left his senses when he said ``No''
to Mikhail Gorbachev at Reykjavik. They both talked about trying to
rid the world of nuclear weapons. But when Gorbachev said the price
of that agreement was that the United States would have to forego
the development of the Strategic Defense Initiative, Reagan said
no. All of the world leaders gasped except Margaret Thatcher. But
the rest of the world leaders gasped. They said, Mr. President, you
should reconsider that. And all of the arms control advocates said
this was a bad mistake for President Reagan to have said no.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it later transpires, George Shultz mentions the fact
that Mikhail Gorbachev told him that that was the turning point in
the cold war. That's when Gorbachev concluded that he could not win
the cold war. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan, in calling the Soviet Union the Evil Empire,
upset a lot of the world leaders. But he stood his ground. And
history has proven him correct. . . .
</P>
<P>
   SEN. TRENT LOTT, R-MISS.
</P>
<P>
   Just in the last two days, in hearings before the Armed Services
Committee and the Foreign Relations Committee, it's become apparent
that this treaty is flawed _ should not be ratified, now or in the
foreseeable future. When you look at the testimony of the country's
three nuclear weapons laboratories' leaders yesterday, it makes it
very clear that as far as safety and reliability without testing,
at this time we do not have the ability to make sure that they are
safe and that it should be, would be reliable if there was a need
for them.
</P>
<P>
   The headline even in The New York Times says, ``Experts Say Test
Ban May Impair Nuclear-Arms Safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. President, that is a fact, and that is a scary fact. Do the
American people want us to have nuclear arms that are not tested,
that are not safe? I don't think so. And so I think we need to be
very careful about going forward with a treaty that has the
problems that this treaty has now in terms of what it would do, the
fact that we don't have the ability to detect or verify what other
countries may be doing.
</P>
<P>
   Just this past week the C.I.A. said, you know, they couldn't
guarantee that they could detect low-level testing in Russia. And
then you add to that the testimony of the labs' experts. So we
should _ we should defeat this treaty. . . .
</P>
<P>
   SEN. JOSEPH BIDEN, D-DEL.
</P>
<P>
   I have real questions about my colleagues' concern about the
stockpile stewardship _ that it cannot work. Our scientists are the
best in the world. They know what they're doing. They define
scientific challenges that must meet the military performance and
reliability standards. And after defining these challenges, they
believe they can meet them.
</P>
<P>
   I believe they know what they're talking about. But I see one
problem. The one problem the stockpile stewardship faces _ now and
in the future _ that's the problem that some may not fund it. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I find it kind of interesting: the very people who stand up here
and say, as I happen to believe, that they have confidence that our
scientists in the future are going to be able to shoot out of the
sky, like a bullet meeting a bullet, incoming nuclear weapons over
the ocean traveling at multi-thousand miles per hour. And do it
with certainty and accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   They have faith in the ability of that to occur, but they don't
have faith in the ability of our scientists at the three
laboratories who say they are well on their way to doing that, to
be able to do what they say they need. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Let's be fair. You can't have it both ways. I would respectfully
submit: the ability to guarantee that MIRV nuclear warheads fired
in the hundreds or the thousands at the United States could be
blown out of the sky with impunity by a missile defense initiative
on our part is (a) greater scientific feat than what the stockpile
requires. . . .
</P>
<P>
   SEN. JAMES INHOFE, R-OKLA. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Senator from Delaware was talking about our allies. And I am
very sensitive to our allies. And our allies have signed this
treaty. ``So if our allies have signed this treaty, we've got to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I'm not concerned about our allies. I'm concerned about
our adversaries. I'm not at all concerned that Great Britain's
going to send a missile over the United States. I am concerned
about China and Russia and now North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   You know, right now, as we speak, the President is sending money
and making promises to North Korea so that they will not test a
missile that they have called a Taepodong 2 that will reach
Washington, D.C., from any place in the world, take 35 minutes to
get over here, and we don't have any defense against this thing.
And so those are the ones I'm concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Have they ratified this treaty? No.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not China, not Russia, not North Korea. . . .
</P>
<P>
   During one of the hearings, we had Secretary Cohen _ and let me
start off by saying there's no one I respect more highly than
Secretary Bill Cohen, our Secretary of Defense. . . . But I do have
to say this: That he has certainly changed his story since he was
in the United States Senate. I'm going to quote what Secretary
Cohen said in 1992, when at that time he was the most vigorous
opponent of a ban on nuclear testing that we had in the United
States Senate.
</P>
<P>
   This is Secretary Bill Cohen when he was a Senator: ``Many of
these nuclear weapons which we intend to keep in our stockpile for
the indefinite future are dangerously unsafe'' _ you want to put
that chart up _ ``are dangerously unsafe. Equally relevant is the
fact that we can make these weapons much safer if limited testing
is allowed to be conducted. So when crafting our policy regarding
nuclear testing, this should be our principal objective: to make
the weapons we retain safe. The amendment that was adopted last
week'' _ I'm speaking 1992 _ ``the amendment banning testing does
not meet this test because it would not permit the Department of
Energy to conduct the necessary testing to make our weapons safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, when I ask that question, there is some suggestion that
maybe we're talking about different weapons. But we're not talking
about different weapons. These are the nine weapons we're talking
about today. These same nine weapons were there in 1992, the same
ones that Secretary Cohen had alluded to. . . .
</P>
<P>
   SEN. DANIEL PATRICK MOYNIHAN, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   I was Ambassador to India in 1974 when the Indians set off what
they called a peaceful nuclear explosion. And they intended it as
such. In conversations with Prime Minister (Indira) Gandhi, she was
persuasive that they were not going to build a bomb. They simply
wanted to establish that they had the capacity to do so.
</P>
<P>
   It was a matter of prestige. It was a matter of reminding
Westerners that Indian physicists had been as much a part of the
great era of discovery at the turn of the century as had any
Europeans, and more than any Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades go by, a quarter century goes by, the Congress Party
with its universalist tendencies and professions has gone into a
minority. A new party, a Hindu party as it would call itself, the
B.J.P., came to power in March of 1998 and two months later, Mr.
President, India set off five, a series of five nuclear explosions.
That was followed almost instantly with Pakistan doing the same. .
. .
</P>
<P>
   Here an important distinction is to be made: In India, to its
great credit, the nuclear development is a matter directly under
the control of the Prime Minister and is not under the control of
the military. The Indian military have been very apolitical, kept
out of politics and have followed the civilian command from the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Not so Pakistan. The Pakistan bomb is in the armaments of the
Pakistan military.
</P>
<P>
   And here, sir, if I could make a point, in which I do not assert
absolute confidence but I believe this is a shared judgment: It's
not clear that Indian tests last year were successful. They
probably did not achieve a hydrogen bomb that they proclaimed. . .
. They want to test more. . . . They need to, as it were, show the
Pakistanis that they have the weapons that they've claimed to have.
</P>
<P>
   And in turn the Pakistanis will respond, and you have this
ratcheting up at the same time. Pakistan, not a stable country, not
a country with civil authority very secure, and an impoverished
country _ that country will be selling nuclear weapons. And sir,
they will be selling them to the Middle East. A Saudi prince who
has most recently visited Pakistan was shown nuclear facilities. We
have to expect this migration. It is ineluctable, unless we get
this treaty. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
