<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYBE FISHER'S PLAY WILL GROW ON JACKSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ Patience and three years of
dive-across-the-court dedication have put Derek Fisher in position
to be the Los Angeles Lakers' starting point guard. Three inches
might deny him that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   As the Lakers' most experienced point man and one of the team's
hardest workers, Fisher seems an obvious choice. It's why he was
given a seven-year, $24 million contract this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But coach Phil Jackson prefers his guards be about 6-4 or taller
to avoid having to switch defensive assignments or give up height
against the Gary Paytons of the league. Fisher and second-year
guard Tyronn Lue (6-0) could be, ahem, sold short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyronn and I were joking around about it yesterday, that we
won't grow four inches before the season starts,'' Fisher said
Friday at training camp. ``The only thing we can control is how
hard we play and what we go out there and do, and that's all we're
going to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it seems, so good. Jackson has singled out Fisher for
praise and remains noncommittal about the lineup. And for what it's
worth, during a halfcourt scrimmage earlier this week, Fisher
played on a unit with the other starters.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson is considering a backcourt of 6-7 Kobe Bryant and
6-7 Rick Fox and still hopes to have former Chicago Bulls guard Ron
Harper, who is 6-6, signed by the time camp ends Monday.
</P>
<P>
   History shows Jackson is open-minded. He played 6-2 B.J.
Armstrong in Chicago. And he said playing full-court defense can
balance out any height issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the coach asks me to do or needs from me that's what
I'm willing to do,'' Fisher said. ``That's just the way I've always
been.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher began last season as the starter, but coach Del Harris
had Derek Harper finish games, then made him the starter. Fisher
regained the starting job by the end of the season and showed
promise in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   All he wants now is a clear role, whatever it might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned that, over the years, the team's success is most
important, and wherever my role fits into that, I'm cool with,'' he
said. ``If they feel like with Ron (Harper)'s height and his
experience and knowing the offense, he needs to start, I'm fine
with that. I'll play behind this guy, he's got championship
experience. I'll continue to learn. This is only my fourth year. I
don't concern myself with all those things. As long as I know where
I stand.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Time to play: For the first time this week, the Lakers held a
fullcourt scrimmage, with referees, Friday night. As with all
practices, it was closed to the media, but the scrimmage promised
to be the best test yet of how proficient the Lakers have become at
running the triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be kind of crazy,'' Robert Horry said earlier in
the day. ``It's going to be kind of hectic. We're still getting it.
There's still things they're trying to get us to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Roster reduced: Rookie guard Melvin Levett, acquired from
Detroit in the Derek Harper trade, was released Friday at his own
request. Levett, a long shot to make the roster, wanted a chance to
win a job elsewhere, the team said.
</P>
<P>
   Had Levett made the team, the Lakers would have owed the Pistons
a second-round draft choice because Derek Harper is expected to
retire rather than play for Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' roster now stands at 18 players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
