<SLUG> BC-KOCH-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Koch lawsuit: Unlawful business practices or family squabbling?
 &HT;    By Fred Cohen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULSA, Okla. _ The latest courtroom battle between America's Cup
champion yacht racer William I. Koch and his brothers' $35 billion
company began here this week with testimony by former employees who
said they had systematically cheated producers that sold oil to
Koch Industries.
</P>
<P>
   William Koch, 59, filed the suit a decade ago against the
Wichita, Kan.-based company led by his two billionaire brothers on
behalf of the federal government and Indian tribes. The trial is
expected to last until December.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges Koch Industries falsified measurements during
the 1980s in 13 states to skim oil it bought from independent
producers.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement Monday, Plaintiffs' lawyer Roy Morrow
Bell of San Diego said Koch Industries stole a total of $230
million in oil over 10 years. A small part of that was produced
under federal and Indian leases, the only oil at issue in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chief trial lawyer, Clyde Muchmore of Oklahoma
City, said company's maximum damages are ``a few hundred thousand
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the company faces possible civil penalties of
$5,000 to $10,000 per month, per lease, for each time the jury
finds that the company wrongfully reported production to the
government. More than 2,000 leases and at least a three-year period
are involved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   William Koch, already worth about $650 million, according to
Forbes magazine, sued under a whistle blower-type law that allows
him to collect as much as a third of any award to the plaintiffs.
Both sides deny the case is primarily about money.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, it is about the process of determining how much
oil was in the tanks of producers the company bought oil from. On
another level, the parties say, it's about the reputation of the
nation's second-largest privately-held company and the family n
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1354 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KOCH-LAWSUIT-COX     10-08 1536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOCH-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Koch lawsuit: Unlawful business practices or family squabbling?
 &HT;    By Fred Cohen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULSA, Okla. _ The latest courtroom battle between America's Cup
champion yacht racer William I. Koch and his brothers' $35 billion
company began here this week with testimony by former employees who
said they had systematically cheated producers that sold oil to
Koch Industries.
</P>
<P>
   William Koch, 59, filed the suit a decade ago against the
Wichita, Kan.-based company led by his two billionaire brothers on
behalf of the federal government and Indian tribes. The trial is
expected to last until December.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges Koch Industries falsified measurements during
the 1980s in 13 states to skim oil it bought from independent
producers.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement Monday, Plaintiffs' lawyer Roy Morrow
Bell of San Diego said Koch Industries stole a total of $230
million in oil over 10 years. A small part of that was produced
under federal and Indian leases, the only oil at issue in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chief trial lawyer, Clyde Muchmore of Oklahoma
City, said company's maximum damages are ``a few hundred thousand
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the company faces possible civil penalties of
$5,000 to $10,000 per month, per lease, for each time the jury
finds that the company wrongfully reported production to the
government. More than 2,000 leases and at least a three-year period
are involved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   William Koch, already worth about $650 million, according to
Forbes magazine, sued under a whistle blower-type law that allows
him to collect as much as a third of any award to the plaintiffs.
Both sides deny the case is primarily about money.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, it is about the process of determining how much
oil was in the tanks of producers the company bought oil from. On
another level, the parties say, it's about the reputation of the
nation's second-largest privately-held company and the family name
of its founder.
</P>
<P>
   But to many observers within the industry, it is little more
than ``sibling rivalry on a very high financial level,'' said
Mickey Thompson, executive vice president of the Oklahoma
Independent Petroleum Association, a producers' group.
</P>
<P>
   Koch Industries calls the case part of an ``ongoing vendetta
against our company'' by William Koch, who was fired after a failed
attempt to wrest control from his brother Charles in 1980. William
sold back his shares, then filed a barrage of mostly futile
lawsuits against the company and family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``William Koch's history of unsuccessful litigation against Koch
Industries has thus far occupied the time of 27 state and federal
judges,'' the company said in a June press release.
</P>
<P>
   What gives the two sides room to continue arguing in this latest
case is the complicated and indirect way the amount of the oil in a
producer's tank is determined. An employee of the company buying
the oil takes about a half-dozen readings and measurements. The
information goes into a computer, which calculates the amount of
the oil and its value.
</P>
<P>
   The witnesses who testified for William Koch's side said they
routinely recorded measurements rounded or inflated to favor Koch
Industries _ unless someone was watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (would) intentionally write down something other than
what they see,'' plaintiffs' lawyer Bell said in his opening. ``And
they will tell you in their case that they call that adjustments.
(T)he adjustments is the skimming. They're taking oil off the top,
keeping it and are not paying for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Koch Industries' Muchmore agreed company employees made
adjustments. But he said the employees _ called ``gaugers'' _ who
took the readings always worked out any adjustments with the
``pumpers'' who managed the wells for producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the joint responsibility of the gauger and the pumper to
see to it that the measurements are acceptable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the gauger were to cheat, Muchmore said, the pumper would
catch him. ``He can check the oil before the gauger comes. He will
always check it after. He has the right to be there if he's
concerned about any problem with the oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Bell downplayed the amount of protection pumpers
provide. The opportunity to cheat ``is ever-present in the gas and
oil business because it's impractical, not economical, perhaps not
even reasonable, to check all the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma Independent Petroleum Association's Thompson said,
``There is a lot of trust in the way oil is bought and sold.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson agrees with Koch Industries that producers and
their pumpers would have caught any widespread cheating, and he
called William Koch's case a farce. ``If he's got a case, where are
the aggrieved producers lined up on his side? Where's the beef?''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson echoed Koch Industries' line that any producer who
thought Koch Industries was cheating had many other potential
buyers. ``There is huge, intense competition'' among oil
purchasers, Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Koch Industries remains a major purchaser nationally,
buying half a million barrels of day, it sold its pipeline
operations in Oklahoma and no longer buys crude oil in the state.
The plaintiffs acknowledge that any cheating by Koch Industries on
measurement ended in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Both those factors have diminished interest in the case here,
Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   The four Koch brothers inherited a fortune generated by the
second-biggest privately held company in the United States, after
grain giant Cargill. The low-profile conglomerate operates oil
refineries in Texas and Minnesota and pipelines and engages in
numerous other businesses, from cattle to asphalt to specialty
chemicals used in the manufacture of microchips.
</P>
<P>
   The last time William Koch squared off against the company, in a
federal case tried in Topeka, Kan., last year the amount at issue
was $2 billion. William and his older brother Frederick lost their
claim that the company had cheated them and other shareholders when
it bought their stock in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   In a story this summer, The New York Times shed new light on the
scope of that battle, reporting that investigators working for
William Koch had ``infiltrated'' the press corps to try to
influence coverage and posed as journalists to try to obtain
confidential information about Koch Industries.
</P>
<P>
   The story also reported that people working for William Koch
said they were followed and harassed by investigators on the
company's payroll.
</P>
<P>
   William's fraternal twin brother, David, is an executive vice
president of the company. He is closely allied with Charles, 63,
who lives quietly in Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   Though on opposite sides of the family fault line, both twins
have oceanfront estates in Palm Beach, Fla. William heads the West
Palm Beach-based Oxbow Corp., a privately held group of
international energy, engineering and real estate businesses.
</P>
<P>
   William is perhaps best known for winning the America's Cup
yacht race in 1992, at a cost to him of $68 million. He later sold
his three International America's Cup Class yachts and used the
proceeds to fund a foundation that provides grants to sailing
training programs.
</P>
<P>
   William has been active in politics, attending a 1998
fund-raiser for Vice President Al Gore and hosting this month a
$1,000-a-plate fund raiser for Ted Kennedy. That no doubt would
have horrified his father, Koch Industries founder Fred Koch, who
was a founding member of the John Birch Society.
</P>
<P>
   David, a supporter of conservative think tanks and foundations,
ran for vice president of the United States in 1980 on the
Libertarian Party ticket. Koch Industries was a major contributor
to the 1998 presidential campaign of Robert Dole, the Kansas
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Charles, who lives in Wichita, William and David appear
frequently with their younger wives in the Palm Beach society
pages, though never in photos taken at the same event.
</P>
<P>
   David and his wife, Julia, were among the ``new 400 of New York
society'' picked by Quest magazine in March 1998. Their base in New
York is a 14-room apartment facing Central Park, bought for $10.5
million from the estate of
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest brother, Frederick, has no connection to Koch
Industries. Unlike his siblings, who have collected engineering
degrees from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, he studied
English and Harvard and Drama at Yale. He spends much of his time
in Europe restoring castles.
</P>
<P>
   During a break in the second day of the trial, William Koch
dismissed the idea that he is obsessed with litigation against his
brothers and their company. He said he is suing to vindicate the
name of his father, the name he will pass down to his six children.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the week, when company spokesman Jay Rosser was asked
how much Koch industries has spend defending itself against William
Koch, Rosser said it was a substantial amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost to our reputation, though, is just as critical and
just as immeasurable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Cohen writes for The Palm Beach Daily News, Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
