<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OIL-PRICES-NYT &LR;      10-08 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL PRICES DROP MORE, BUT TREND IS SEEN AS TEMPORARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crude-oil prices fell nearly 7 percent Friday, registering a 15
percent decline for the week, after hitting a 33-month high the
previous week. The volatile performance reflected reports of small
increases in oil supply.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts cautioned, however, that the price drop appeared
to be premature and did not indicate fundamental changes in supply
or any lack of resolve by major oil-producing countries to keep
their cutbacks in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't find a fundamental reason why crude oil has dropped
like this,'' said Fred Leuffer, an oil analyst for Bear, Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   He said there was no evidence that the major oil producers were
easing up on their cuts, even though several surveys showed this
week that production among major countries of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries showed a small increase in output for
September.
</P>
<P>
   The increases were so minor, he said, that they could not be
considered evidence that producers were cheating on the cutback
plan.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that crude-oil prices would recover and could be as
high as $30 a barrel by the end of the year, because growth in
demand was strong while supplies have not been increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil for November delivery dropped 6.9 percent Friday in
trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, falling $1.55, to
$20.90 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Brent crude oil for November delivery fell $1.38, or
6.3 percent, to $20.70 a barrel on the International Petroleum
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The decline, Leuffer said, was related to concerns by oil
traders who have been looking for reasons to take profits, and thus
reacted to the failure of oil prices to go above the $25 level.
</P>
<P>
   Selling by speculative commodity funds has been a major reason
prices have dropped so suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   In such an atmosphere even the small increase in production by
OPEC nations last month had a big effect on the futures market.
</P>
<P>
   There was also concern among traders that Mexico, Saudi Arabia
and Venezuela, in their meeting next month in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia,
might decide to increase crude-oil production.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Tellez, the energy minister for Mexico, said Friday,
however, that the group would reaffirm its agreement of earlier
this year to cut crude-oil output by about 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That cutback and the recovery of demand, particularly in Asia,
have been leading factors in the doubling of crude-oil prices since
early last year.
</P>
<P>
   World inventories of oil have also fallen considerably while
demand has continued to be robust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
