<SLUG> BC-TEST-BAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADMITS DEFEAT, ASKS DELAY ON TEST BAN TREATY VOTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ President Clinton conceded temporary defeat Friday for
a global nuclear test ban treaty and condemned Senate Republicans
for playing politics on a critical issue.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton formally asked the Senate to postpone a ratification
vote just hours after the Senate opened debate on the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   A vote was set for Tuesday, but supporters remained far short of
the 67 votes needed for ratification. They remained hopeful,
however, that final consideration would be postponed either through
parliamentary delaying tactics or &UR;  &LR; with the consent of Republican
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The votes, said Clinton, ``are simply not there.'' The treaty
has the support of all 45 Democrats but only two of 55 Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the first of 154 world leaders to sign the treaty two
years ago, faced a major foreign policy setback by withdrawing the
test ban. Administration officials also fear the lack of
endorsement from the Senate will stymie ratification by other
nations, especially new nuclear powers India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, trying to keep the treaty alive, called on the Senate
to ``reach an agreement to delay the vote and to establish an
orderly process _ a nonpolitical, orderly process, to
systematically deal with all the issues that are out there and to
take whatever time is necessary to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president adamantly rejected demands by conservative
Republicans, led by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., chairman of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, that Clinton in writing request
the withdrawal of the treaty from the Senate calendar and pledge
not to seek another vote until Clinton steps down in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they want me to give them a letter to cover the political
decision they have made that this does severe damage to the
interest of the United States and the interest of nonproliferation
in the world? I don't think so,'' Clinton retorted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shouldn't tie the Senate up or themselves up in knots
thinking that some letter from me will somehow obscure from the
American people next year the reality that they have run the risk
of putting America on the wrong side of the proliferation issue for
the first time in 50 years,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart later tried to soften
Clinton's statement, saying ``his intention was not to rule out
sending a letter.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In Washington, meanwhile, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., who was still negotiating a possible postponement of the
vote late Friday with Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.,
suggested that Clinton efforts to delay a vote might be better
served if he would simply ``pipe down.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Joining the debate on the Senate floor, Lott said he found it
ironic that the president ``has been demanding (a vote on the
treaty) for two years'' and has now suddenly discovered ``that the
votes aren't there'' to pass it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's right,'' said Lott, who opposes it. ``This treaty is
not going to happen. It's not going to be ratified.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Lott said he was ``very worried'' that a postponement of the
vote would allow Clinton to use it for ``political purposes'' in
next year's elections against Republicans. Nonetheless, Lott told
reporters later that he was still willing to listen to arguments in
favor of a delay. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Daschle, calling the move toward a vote next week
``pigheaded,'' said if Lott refuses to put it off Democrats will
try to force a postponement by moving for a vote to put it aside.
Such a move would require the support of 51 senators to prevail,
but Daschle said he believes at least six Republicans will join
with the Senate's 45 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's comments on the floor sparked an angry outburst from Sen.
Joseph Biden, D-Del., the ranking Democrat on the Foreign Relations
Committee. Biden accused Lott of playing politics with the treaty
by scheduling a vote on it before the foreign relations panel ``has
even held one hearing on it.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; There have been limited hearings on the treaty before other
Senate committees in recent days. But foreign relations, Biden
pointed out, is supposed to have jurisdiction over arms control
matters. He suggested that Republican leaders had sought to avoid
hearings and a vote on the treaty until they were certain it would
not pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a break ... Come on,'' Biden shouted. ``This is a
stacked deck.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton: ``This whole thing is about politics. It's about:
`Burn us (supporters) in 1999, because we (GOP) are against a
treaty that 80 percent of the American people support; but please
don't burn us (GOP) again in 2000.' It's political,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty is intended to eliminate nuclear test explosions
worldwide. But opponents fear the United States would be unable to
adequately monitor low-level test ban violations by other nations
and would also be prevented from improving and modernizing its own
nuclear arsenal without the benefit of tests. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But supporters contend the treaty requires on-site inspections
and establishes 321 new monitoring stations around the world. They
also contend current technology &UR;  &LR;  allows the U.S. stockpile to be
tested through computer simulation instead of actual tests. The
United States has operated under a self-imposed test moratorium
since 1992. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
