<SLUG> BC-SMOG-PROBE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOG ERUPTION IN HOUSTON AREA PROMPTS PROBE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BILL DAWSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A suspicious eruption of high smog readings Thursday,
including the Houston area's highest in a decade, has prompted a
state investigation of local industries in a search for the cause.
</P>
<P>
   The day's highest measurement, recorded in nearby Deer Park, was
double the national health standard's maximum permissible level for
ground-level ozone, a respiratory irritant and smog's chief
ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   The health standard is a one-hour average reading of 125 parts
per billion (or ppb). The Deer Park reading of 251 ppb was in the
middle of a range deemed ``very unhealthy'' by federal officials.
It was the highest local ozone measurement since a 271 ppb reading
in 1989, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Deer Park reading, six other state and municipal
monitoring stations also measured ground-level ozone above the
health standard Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's readings above the standard on that day pushed it
ahead of Los Angeles as the U.S. metropolitan area with the most
1999 days with one or more ozone violations. In all previous years,
Los Angeles has recorded the highest number of violation days.
</P>
<P>
   In a possible prelude to next year's presidential race, Vice
President Al Gore criticized Gov. George W. Bush's environmental
record Thursday, citing Houston's ozone problem. A Bush spokesman
replied that Gore is an environmental extremist and said Bush has
worked to reduce pollution in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   State and local officials said Friday that the sequence and
timing of Thursday's high ozone readings prompt them to suspect a
chemical release, possibly from an industrial facility, as the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Ground-level ozone forms when certain air pollutants _ released
by vehicles, industries and other sources _ react in sunlight.
Varying weather conditions can promote or hamper ozone formation,
with the highest numbers often appearing miles downwind of emission
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Houston has recorded 44 days this year with at least one ozone
reading above the health standard
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not just a typical ozone day in Houston, Texas,''
Andy Saenz, spokesman for the Texas Natural Resource Conservation
Commission, said of the Thursday readings.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the episode has triggered ``a whole different level
of response'' by state officials, Saenz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find a smoking gun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their investigation, TNRCC officials will be checking
industries along the Houston Ship Channel, in the Bayport
industrial complex at LaPorte and in Galveston County to determine
if they were responsible for any major accidental pollution
releases that went unreported, Saenz said.
</P>
<P>
   Most major local industries are outside the city of Houston and
therefore beyond the investigatory jurisdiction of the city's
environmental officials.
</P>
<P>
   But Kathy Barton, spokeswoman for the Houston Health and Human
Services Department, said city officials will press the TNRCC to
conduct a vigorous investigation of the Thursday event.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Houston department's Bureau of Air Quality
Control thought the pattern of high ozone readings Thursday
possibly pointed to pollution from the Bayport complex as a cause,
Barton said.
</P>
<P>
   That complex of plants is located southeast of the state's Deer
Park ozone-monitoring station. Prevailing winds often blow from
that area toward Deer Park.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's high readings started showing up much earlier than
usual, helping prompt officials' suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, high ozone readings don't occur until the afternoon,
after pollutants have had time to react in the sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   But Saenz said the first reading above the health standard was
recorded at the Deer Park site at 10 a.m. CST. The excessive
readings continued there for six hours.
</P>
<P>
   The 251 ppb reading easily exceeded the area's previous highest
ozone reading in 1999, which was 211 ppb on Aug. 6 at an
industry-sponsored monitoring station in Texas City.
</P>
<P>
   Ozone levels measured at all city and state monitors on Friday
were below the health standard, according to preliminary readings.
</P>
<P>
   The TNRCC must submit a new ozone-reduction plan to federal
officials for approval later this year that lists new
pollution-control strategies that will bring Houston's ozone levels
below the health standard by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Although Houston's ozone problem has improved considerably since
the 1970s, government analysts disagree about whether it has
continued to improve more slowly since the early 1990s or is
staying about the same.
</P>
<P>
   Local government and business leaders, including Mayor Lee
Brown, Harris County Judge Robert Eckels and Ned Holmes, chairman
of the Greater Houston Partnership and chairman of the Port of
Houston Authority, have formed a coalition to help plot new
ozone-reducing strategies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
