A1364 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-ASTROS09-C     10-08 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ASTROS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves outlast Astros 5-3 in extra-inning thriller
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For all the October drama the Braves have staged this
decade _ from Sid Bream and David Justice, to Tom Glavine and
Lonnie Smith _ they have discovered new ways to muster up more.
</P>
<P>
   It may have only been the Division Series, but the Braves proved
the shortest and the most intense of the playoff series can mean
the most. With their 5-3 win over the Astros in a 12-inning,
four-hour-19-minute gut-wrenching marathon in what may prove to be
the second-to-last game ever in the Astrodome, the Braves redefined
themselves this postseason from nearly-out to a team on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go on and do something special,'' said John Smoltz, who
will pitch today against Shane Reynolds in Game 4, ``this game will
be remembered for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   A win like that had the Braves daring to look into their
postseason future and their postseason past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than `92, the seventh game of the NLCS against
Pittsburgh, all the great games we lost,'' Tom Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   But this one would be different, and the Braves knew it after
the 10th inning when John Rocker gave them a miracle, getting out
of a bases loaded no-out jam. He got an assist on the play of the
year by Walt Weiss on a grounder by Tony Eusebio that he fielded
and fired home for the second out. Brian Jordan took care of the
offense, giving new meaning to the term cleanup hitter by driving
in all five runs on a three-run homer and the game-winning double
in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kind of plays make you wonder,'' Chipper Jones said,
referring to Weiss. ``That maybe it was meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros and Braves played this game like their lives depended
on it. And in baseball terms, it did. They put on enough excitement
for an entire series for the pleasure and pain of 48,625
towel-waving Texans, just looking for a team to bust out.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was much obliged.
</P>
<P>
   He'd already taken Astros ace and NL Cy Young candidate Mike
Hampton deep on a three-run home run, only his second home run
since Aug. 15, to give the game its first dramatic turn in the form
of a 3-2 Braves lead in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I can start looking for pitches now,'' said Chipper
Jones, who was pitched around to bring Jordan up in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   With Larry Dierker holding onto closer Billy Wagner for
something that never came, Jordan drove a 1-2 Jay Powell pitch past
Jeff Bagwell and into the right field corner to score both Nixon
and Bret Boone, who had collected back-to-back one-out hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were facing the best,'' Jordan said. ``I just wanted
to go out and be aggressive and hope for the best. The best was
good enough tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
