<HEADER>
A1365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     10-08 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DUNSTON FINDS A HOME AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There were dramas and sub-dramas at Shea Stadium on
Friday night for Game 3 between the Mets and the Diamondbacks.
Before the game, Manager Bobby Valentine revealed that Orel
Hershiser was relegated to the Mets' bullpen. Valentine also
addressed disparaging comments about members of his team and staff
that had been attributed to him in a national magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The most disturbing news for Mets fans was that the slugger Mike
Piazza was out of the game with a bruised thumb and that Todd Pratt
would replace him.
</P>
<P>
   But for one family, the central drama was Shawon Dunston.
Dunston was playing center field for the Mets as the team played
its first playoff game at Shea in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Dunston played a key role in the Mets' victories over Pittsburgh
at the end of the regular season and in Game 1 of this playoff
series against Arizona. He ran down shot after deep shot to help
keep the Mets close until Edgardo Alfonzo won the game with his
ninth-inning grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a playoff game, but I'm going to look at it as
another game where I've got to go play hard and do the best I
can,'' Dunston said. ``I know it's a playoff game, but I let other
people think about that. I know what it is, but I don't focus on it
that much.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Mets played in the playoffs Dunston was
playing his fourth season in the majors with the Chicago Cubs and
was selected to the All-Star team. Life was good.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982 Dunston, a 19-year-old infielder from Thomas Jefferson
High School in Brooklyn, became the first player from the New York
area to be the No. 1 selection in baseball's summer free-agent
draft. He was selected by the Cubs. One scout said Dunston was
``the best-looking player I've seen in 30 years of scouting.''
Another called him ``the best overall player I've seen around in 20
or 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He was regarded as such a force: a third baseman with speed and
power. The Mets chose Dwight Gooden two picks later. When Dunston
was assigned to a minor league team in 1982, he predicted he would
make it to the majors in four seasons. He made it in three. ``I
just wanted to play baseball,'' he said. ``My goal was to make
$500,000. I didn't want to be a bonus baby. I just wanted to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 19, Dunston was projected as one of the best players New
York had turned out in 30 years. At age 36 he is a well-respected
player, a player the Mets desperately need to perform, especially
now that Piazza is injured. For 17 years Dunston has lived a dream.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 he played in the National League playoffs with Chicago.
Then came the injuries: a herniated disk in 1992; in 1993 back
rehabilitation reduced his time. He returned for 88 games in 1994
and played his 1,000th major league game that season.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995 he was back full time, but he was traded to San
Francisco after the season. He was stunned, but it was just the
beginning. He was traded back to Chicago in 1997, then was traded
to Pittsburgh near the end of the season, was traded to Cleveland
for the start of the 1998 season and to San Francisco midway
through that season.
</P>
<P>
   Dunston strained his left groin in 1996, had a concussion, two
fractures of the left eye orbit and fractured his cheekbone. He
rebounded in 1997 with the Cubs and had one of his best seasons in
the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're on one team, you're loyal, you play hard, you do what
you gotta do,'' he said. ``They tell you you can still play, then
they trade you. Then you go back to the same team. Then another
team trades you. You get picked up. They say: `We love you. We
aren't going to trade you.' Then they trade you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're old and you can be replaced. You can be moved out. But
six teams, that kind of bothered me.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of 1998 he was traded to St. Louis, and the Cardinals
traded Dunston to the Mets for Craig Paquette, a minor league
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I don't like is that I was with one team for 11
straight years and then the last three years I've been on six
teams,'' Dunston said. ``If someone would have told me that I'd
have played with six teams in two years, I would have said no. If
they would have done this to me earlier in my career, they really
would have heartbroken me.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Dunston's salvation has been his
versatility. In high school he was a third baseman. Shortly after
being drafted he was moved to short, where he played for 11
seasons. He has played second base, left field, right and now, for
the Mets in what may be the most critical stint of all, he is
patrolling center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a time and place for everything,'' he said. ``This
could be the time and the place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
