<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECS-ROUNDTABLE-ART-5TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEADER'S-EYE VIEW OF LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
(Eds: All questions should be italicized) 
(af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lawrence A. Bossidy spoke of the value of hiring
those who have failed. L. Dennis Kozlowski shook his head at the
``absurd'' valuations of Internet companies, while Charles B. Wang
talked about having dot-com envy. Shelly Lazarus defended the
$80-million-plus pay package that Hewlett-Packard recently awarded
its new leader.
</P>
<P>
   Early one Monday morning in late September, these four chief
executives _ Bossidy of Allied Signal, Kozlowski of Tyco
International, Wang of Computer Associates International and Ms.
Lazarus of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide _ gathered over coffee at The
New York Times to talk about leadership and how they do their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   All are featured in a recent book, ``Lessons from the Top: The
Search for America's Best Business Leaders,'' (Doubleday/Currency,
1999) written by Thomas J. Neff and James M. Citrin, two executive
recruiting consultants from Spencer Stuart in New York. Neff and
Citrin also joined the discussion, as did Reed Abelson, Alison
Leigh Cowan and Patrick J. Lyons of The Times.
</P>
<P>
   The four chief executives brought different perspectives to the
two-hour discussion. Bossidy, who has more than four decades of
business experience, helped turn around Allied Signal and is
currently merging it with Honeywell to create a company with $25
billion in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Kozlowski has guided Tyco through the purchase of more than 100
companies since he took over as chief executive in 1992. At
Computer Associates, one of the world's largest independent
software concerns, Wang managed the transition from founder to the
leader of a company with more than $5 billion in annual sales. And
while the agency that Ms. Lazarus runs is not an independent or
public company _ the London-based WPP Group acquired it in 1989 _
it has long been one of the most successful advertising agencies in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the discussion focused on the challenge of managing
people: the fierce competition for talented employees, the need to
communicate effectively, the growing demand for a healthier balance
between work and life outside the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   The four also frankly discussed compensation, and all noted the
importance of their own actions in conveying the values of the
companies they lead.
</P>
<P>
   Following are excerpts of the conversation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reed Abelson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making Their Mark  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kind of thoughts do you have about the legacy you're
going to leave behind? Is it just to have the biggest company? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY It isn't size that is as important to me as to have the
employee base be convinced that we were always willing to change a
lot of things, that the company had some edge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI We went out and did a reverse acquisition of ADT a
couple of years ago where we had to charge our shareholders capital
gains on the deal. It was a pretty unpopular decision with
shareholders and even with my board. I hope to exemplify leadership
in a way that we're willing to do things that are unpopular. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG I don't know if legacy is defined only in business. If I
could be remembered for something, it's probably how I raised my
kids and what (else) I did. As much as we think we're very
important, I think we forget there's probably somebody in our ranks
who thinks they can do it better and probably can do it better. Our
job probably is to make sure that they have the right values. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS I inherited a legacy, which came home very much to me
when David Ogilvy died. We had a memorial service, and thousands of
employees returned who hadn't worked for the company in 20 and 30
years because the emotional connection to what David founded was so
remarkable. So I see my job much more is to keep that alive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG Why wouldn't you make your own legacy? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS Well, because it's marvelous, because it's founded on a
set of values. It's not founded on a personality, on an individual.
And it's a set of values that are all about excellent people and
excellent work and all about recognizing individual contribution.
I've stayed for 28 years because I believe in all those things. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Success and Succession
</P>
<P>
   Q: The book ``Lessons from the Top'' is clearly a reflection in
time. As we approach 2000, what qualities and skills will your
successors need? &QL; 
BOSSIDY Trying to stay ahead of the game, trying to work with a
work force which is far more independent than it was when I started
and trying to be responsive and keep those organizations at the
leading edge will be the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, you could be a CEO 10 years ago and never have talked to
your employees. You talk to them every day now.
</P>
<P>
   This notion of CEO and COO (chief operating officer), which I
think is awful, will go in the next 10 years. It's a bad thing
under a set of circumstances that doesn't envision transition
immediately, because it separates two jobs that should be joined. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI I agree that the COO concept is a dangerous one in
most companies, because it really separates the CEO from the
operating groups. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
