u a BC-FOI-CONVENTION-TEXAS-     10-08 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOI-CONVENTION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BATTLES OVER DATA ACCESS SEEN AT FOI CONVENTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In Galveston, it was student test scores. In
Houston, it was government plans affecting the environment. In
Austin, it was closely guarded information about university
investments.
</P>
<P>
   All were official documents that eventually were made public,
but only after protracted and sometimes costly disputes with the
keepers of those records. That was the assessment of panelists
Friday at the annual conference of the Freedom of Information
Foundation of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans of battles over open records and open meetings said
they are accustomed to delaying tactics and intransigence by
secretive officials. However, they warned of new challenges posed
by privatizing government services.
</P>
<P>
   While public officials defended legal provisions that keep some
records sealed and meeting doors locked, open government advocates
said they will try again in the 2001 legislative session to improve
citizen access to information, including that from public-private
ventures.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's legislative session, the media were again
thwarted in efforts to clarify what records from private companies
may be scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was simple _ to follow the public dollar across the
aisle into the public sector,'' said M.J. Nicchio of the Texas
Daily Newspaper Association. The media's legislation was weakened
to include only major state contracts with private companies _
those worth more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   New legislation will be submitted in 2001, some of it sought by
state agencies that want to clarify how open government rules apply
to private contractors, Nicchio said.
</P>
<P>
   One consequence of the push for disclosure is that public
meetings have become ``very scripted, very choreographed, often
devoid of any controversial issues,'' said Tom Ricks, president of
the University of Texas Investment Management Co., the entity that
manages the university's multibillion-dollar investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's human nature, and I think it will also apply to our
meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   The investment company, which contends that its deliberations
sometimes warrant protection for competitive or proprietary
reasons, recently opened its meetings in response to public
pressure generated by the Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our directors will be much more cautious'' about
discussing managers, audits and other delicate matters because of
the risk of having it misconstrued or sensationalized in the
media,'' Ricks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my view is that (it) is to the detriment of oversight,
because it will drive certain issues _ particularly involving
critical self-evaluation _ underground.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle reporter R.G. Ratcliffe, whose reporting led
to policy changes at the investment company, said the public
deserves as much information as possible from entities like UTIMCO,
which handle taxpayer money and might be influenced by political
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The controversy that we had here is minor compared to some
that have occurred elsewhere,'' Ratcliffe said.
</P>
<P>
   While some participants were concerned about cutting-edge open
government issues, others said they faced challenges over just
applying established open-records law.
</P>
<P>
   Houston environmental lawyer Jim Blackburn said he struggled to
get information from the Port of Houston about its master plan and
about political advertising for a proposed container facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're running across in some of these governmental
agencies is pure obstructionist tactics. You simply have to
persevere.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
