<HEADER>
A1369 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-EXECS-ROUNDTABLE-2NDT     10-08 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECS-ROUNDTABLE-2NDTAKE-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: operating groups.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WANG You know, maybe by the traditional definition of what the
CEO or COO does, what their job function is, perhaps you can say
that. But maybe I'm fortunate. I know who the next CEO is: He's my
COO. But he doesn't really operate in that traditional sense. We do
things together. He happens to have the unfortunate task of doing
everything I don't like to do.
</P>
<P>
   If you asked him, he'd probably tell you he can run the company
better than I can. And I hope he feels that way, because that's
what makes somebody who should be the CEO.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS The thing that keeps me up at night is the scarcity of
talent. In my industry, we keep recycling the same eight people.
There's so much opportunity for young people now _ the world of the
Internet and start-ups and dot-coms, and 28-year-olds making $50
million overnight. The challenge for us is to figure out how to
keep those people long enough that they are ready to become CEOs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I think there's more talent than ever before. The
trouble is, it migrates to narrower places. A few years ago, if you
didn't go to a consulting firm, you weren't essentially in the
main. Now if you're not with a dot-com you're basically not allowed
to the party. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI There are 20-year-olds coming out of college now, and
out of graduate school, that are far brighter and have a far
greater perspective of the world than anybody did in my class. But
there's another thing that's happening, too: Really talented,
bright people are starting to question the life styles that are
involved in this kind of work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS Absolutely. I think we're going to have to get much more
flexible and open-minded about how we _ I don't even say employ
people _ but how we source resources. Because there are people who
are now saying, ``I'll give you X number of hours a week but I am
not signing up as a full-time employee.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give us an example of the flexible arrangements you
find yourself making? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS Well, we have a man who wants to live in Penelope,
Texas, where he has a ranch. I'd make him a creative leader in my
agency; he doesn't want to do that. He said: ``I will sell you 40
percent of my time. And I will also retain the right to refuse an
assignment if I don't want to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has done a brilliant job for us, absolutely brilliant. If I
can get five more of him, if I get a hundred more of him, I would
take them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY You've also got to be careful that the only people you
retain aren't those who are risk-averse and don't want to do the
dot-com situation. So I say to our people: ``Let's go get some
people from the dot-coms right now. They're failing every day. But
at least they showed the interest and the courage to take some
risks.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: So failure can be a good thing? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I used to hire real estate people. I always hired ones
that had failures. I wanted the person who had lost a lot of money
for somebody else to come work for me. You don't reward _ you don't
praise _ failure. But it can be a wonderful thing in terms of what
you learn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Even if the failure is very public?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I think every failure needs to be analyzed. Why? What
happened? And sometimes you've got to stand up, yourself, and say,
``I was a part of that and I have as much responsibility for it as
anybody does. Now, let's make sure we don't make that same mistake
again when we develop another product.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG I think what you've got to do is take the blame. I mean,
ultimately you give all the credit to your people and you take all
the blame.
</P>
<P>
   We tell our people we're no smarter than any other company in
the world. The problem with all the other companies seems to be,
they may spend five times the amount of time to make decisions,
spinning about what went wrong: ``It's really not my fault.'' And
all of that time could have been used to make decisions. So if we
could just cut out all the spinning, then we'd have that much more
time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI Any time you're going to try something, at whatever
level, there's always a risk of failure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY And if you study it for three months, or study it for a
day, probably the percentages are about the same. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Embracing the Internet
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: These days, one primary reason that chief executives seem to
fail and are shown the door is the Internet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI I don't see the Internet as being the demise of CEOs.
There are a couple of examples, maybe, but CEOs usually trip over
themselves. They make slow decisions or bad decisions or invest the
money in the wrong way or don't have a focus _ aren't quick out of
the box. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS I think the healthiest thing that's coming out of this
whole Internet phenomenon is that the good CEOs are rethinking the
whole way they go to the market.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not the Internet per se. I think that becomes sort of
like a distraction. But because you have this new capability _ this
new way to distribute, inform, communicate _ the good companies are
stepping back and saying, ``What does this mean about the whole way
we go to market?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY One of the things I try to do is get everybody in the
company involved on the Net in some way _ manufacturing people,
more outsourcing; purchasing people, more global sourcing. And you
can use it as a way to reinvent the company. You get a whole new
set of excitement; some new people come to the fore. You do some
things experimentally that you would never do otherwise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E-Communicating Pros and Cons
</P>
<P>
   Q: You all lead large organizations. How do you stay in touch
with your employees? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG Get a good COO! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY There's such a thing as the e-mail now. And you have an
easier time communicating with anybody than ever. You can issue
e-mails, you can get e-mails, all the time. And I think it's
essential that you do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS But I also think there's no substitute for
face-to-face. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I agree. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS Something happens when you are in the room with people
with whom you work, trying to solve a problem together or just
listening to them. And the e-mail becomes more meaningful after the
trip with the face-to-face. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI We have 140,000 employees in 80 countries. And it
takes a lot of face-to-face time, a lot of travel on my part, to be
able to articulate our goals and where we're going.
</P>
<P>
   But I really like showing up. You know, I really like being
there and being able to have a dialogue like this. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY If you aren't willing to communicate and if you're not
good at it, you're at a disadvantage. You have to do even more than
you've ever done before in whatever way you do it, but it's
something that you ought to do every day, someplace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1370 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-EXECS-ROUNDTABLE-3RDT     10-08 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECS-ROUNDTABLE-3RDTAKE-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: day, someplace.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI Employees are far more willing to critique _ openly
critique _ the CEO than ever before. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY That's better than having it only in chat rooms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS I agree. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG I don't have e-mail. I force my people to get in touch with
me. And it takes an effort. And it must be important, then, too.
</P>
<P>
   And I travel a lot. Once a year we also bring all our field
people together for what we call a kickoff. We spend a week of
basically bringing them all up to date on what's happened. But as
you get bigger, you still have to force the issue of thinking
small, because otherwise you end up in a bureaucracy that can choke
you. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fair Play in the Numbers Game &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about that other constituency: the institutional
investors, the analysts? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG My COO deals with Wall Street. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI I spend 10 percent of my time communicating with
investors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY One of the things I think CEOs do is understand who your
constituents are, and one of them is share owners. You've got
customers, you've got employees, you've got suppliers, you've got
share owners, you've got communities in which you live. You've got
to spend time with all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does paying attention to the share owners make you too
short-term at times? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI You absolutely have got to deliver what you promised
in the short term. And you've got to have a strategy in place
worrying about two years from now. I pretty much know what the next
year and a half will look like and have a forecast in place that
I'm very confident in. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS I'm actually sitting here thinking this is probably the
only benefit of having been acquired hostilely by an English
company.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have seen very good managements run into trouble when they
surprise analysts. But then, maybe truly good managements never
surprise analysts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY You're better off to run it on the basis that you avoid
those surprises to the fullest possible extent.
</P>
<P>
   NEFF You could probably get away with one surprise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI I don't agree. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY No. The price is immediate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI Yeah. You miss earnings by a penny and you can lose $3
billion of market value the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Doesn't that increase the temptation to have a little bit in
the back pocket to make sure you're going to make your numbers? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI It increases the temptation of making sure you give
appropriate guidance (to Wall Street) as to where you think you're
coming out.
</P>
<P>
   You can't manage earnings. There are very specific accounting
rules and SEC rules now that preclude one from going that route.
But it really is terribly important to have good communication and
good visibility of your own businesses, so that you can become, and
are, and continue to be a predictable company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG I don't know if you really can be that predictable. There
are a lot of things beyond your control. We do so many deals a
year. Some of them can slip by a few days. You don't know until
almost the _ actually, till the last day of the quarter, many
times. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: You see a company that makes its numbers for 15 years in a
row. Do you suspect they're just lucky enough to be in a very
predictable business, or do you suspect that the chief executive is
good at making the numbers? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI I think they're good. I think companies like GE are
good. They're well-run companies. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That Urge to Merge &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: This is a golden age for mergers. Do you see that changing? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I think it depends on two things: What's the interest
rate environment and what's the stock market going to be?
</P>
<P>
   I think there's benefit to being big. To Charles' point, I think
you want to be as big as you can and run it as small as you can, as
a way to be quick. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI When interest rates fluctuate, pricing usually comes
down on companies to be acquired and you're more inclined to use
some combination of stock and cash in those deals. I would expect,
for any horizon I can see, a Tyco that would continue to be quite
active. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY Dennis, let me ask you a question. What's going to
happen to your view if pooling (of interests, a method of
accounting for mergers) is eliminated? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI I think what we attempted to do with Raychem _ where
we could have pooled Raychem and shown another penny or two a share
but where we used half stock and half equity _ is the kind of deal
that you're going to see going forward. However, part of the
proposal is showing earnings before the amortization of goodwill.
Then you have the best of all worlds. And there are so many
unintended consequences of poolings, limitations that the SEC puts
on you _ not being able to sell off things that you don't want to
have, on the purchase of your own stock _ I think it's almost a
good thing that poolings will be eliminated. It will protect us
from ourselves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I agree. I think there's going to be a lot of furor
expressed on the potential elimination, but I don't think at the
end of the day it's going to have much impact.
</P>
<P>
   A Brave New World? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does this unprecedented period of prosperity herald a ``new
economy,'' or are you afraid that it's got to end pretty soon? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG I think we are in a new economy. I think we've gone through
this kind of industrial age, the marketing age, and now we're
really in an information age. And I think the people we call the
knowledge workers are expected to have more information and make
decisions faster. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI It's a true global economy now, too, that just didn't
exist five years ago, where you're buying and selling on a
worldwide basis, and your competitor now may be in Indiana, or your
competitor may be in Brazil, or your competitor may be in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the information technology that you have available to you
now allows you to see a lot of things on a real-time basis that you
weren't able to see five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the business cycle gone? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI No, probably not. In business, as far as I know it,
the good times get bad and bad times get good. Maybe there are
longer cycles now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I think, too, there's another factor, which doesn't mean
that markets won't, over time, change.
</P>
<P>
   I think the U.S. has a big competitive edge now. We have taken a
lead in the information technology. We've taken the lead in
Internet. I don't say that we're destined to always have that
advantage, but I do think in the last number of years we've moved
faster than the Europeans, we've moved faster than the people in
the Far East. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
