<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDING FOR MENTALLY ILL, RETARDED RESOLVED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A $30 million budget shortfall that threatened
to slash services to the mentally ill and retarded in Texas has
been resolved through next August, the agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can say that we are deeply pleased and gratified that we
have the funding necessary to ensure that clients continue to
receive services,'' said Laurie Lentz, spokeswoman for the Texas
Department of Mental Health and Mental Retardation.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said $6.4 million will be transferred to the agency
from a social services fund overseen by the Texas Health and Human
Services Commission. Along with other steps, such as prepaying
leases and cuts in administrative spending, full funding has now
been restored through the end of August 2000.
</P>
<P>
   News that the budget shortfall had been resolved for the current
fiscal year came as the state auditor's office released a report
confirming the earlier announced shortfall. The audit said the
mistake occurred largely from clerical errors, including a $16.2
million data entry error.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Garnet Coleman, D-Houston, said Friday the immediate
crisis, which threatened to cut services and highly touted
``new-generation'' anti-psychotic drugs, appears over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can take care of the first fiscal year probably without any
pain,'' he said. ``We still have to deal with the second fiscal
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers familiar with the problem had assumed that an
additional $30 million budget shortfall would occur in the second
year of the two-year funding cycle.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lentz said that's unlikely. She said steps taken this
year to achieve more efficiencies and better collections from
private insurers will go a long way toward resolving the agency's
budget woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really kind of feel like this puts us on pretty solid
ground for next year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   MHMR Commissioner Karen Hale said the agency intends to
implement recommendations from the state auditor to ``prevent
future problems.'' She also thanked other state social services
agencies for helping with the mental health agency's crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate we can use similar measures to address FY
(fiscal year) 2001 in a way that will not affect client services,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
