 NEW YORK: Far East.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: So higher price-to-earnings ratios are justified? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I think on a global basis, yes. You know, markets are
smart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the Internet valuations? Do you all wish you had
dot-com at the end of your company's name? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI No. Some of it is absolutely absurd. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG I wish we had dot.com.
</P>
<P>
   We do so much business on the Internet, but traditionally, the
perception has been that we are a plumbing company, what's behind
it. Our software manages the largest Web sites in the world, and we
have more security software than any other independent software
company. And yet our valuation is not a dot-com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS Once you relax the profit requirement, you know, it's
very different. And we have clients coming in who are new dot-com
companies who say, ``We have an advertising budget of $70 million,
$80 million,'' and you sort of press them on the economics.
</P>
<P>
   I just saw where Etoys today is going to invest 70 percent of
their sales last year in advertising in the next three months. I
mean, it's madness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY But you know, therefore, that's going to stop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS It's got to stop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY But I do think that the medium will continue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom, what percentage of your placements have been Internet
placements in the last 12 months? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEFF In terms of current assignments in the U.S., it's into the
double digits. It's probably approaching 15 percent, currently. So
we've had over 100 active search assignments for Internet CEOs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Many a brilliant marketing campaign aims to familiarize the
public with these new Internet names. What about the companies that
possess the old great names? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS Well, I think they have an advantage if they use it.
Sears, which is one of our clients, as a name for the old catalog
company, as a place that you trust to get merchandise, is
brilliant. But they've got to get onto it or Amazon.com is going to
become the retailer of the year 2000. I mean, because I don't think
they're stopping at books. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG I really believe that an established business should look
at a hybrid type model instead of thinking of this as a separate,
distinct silo. Imagine if you could get on line, buy books and at
the end of your whole order, you have a choice: send it to me or go
drive through a drive-through window at Barnes &AMP; Noble and pick up
my package. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY And yet, it's ironic that because of Amazon.com, Barnes
&AMP; Noble's got a better household recognition than ever before. So
the question is: Can you capitalize on that? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Chief as Superstar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last week George Shaheen surprised all of us by jumping from
Andersen Consulting, which he ran with an iron fist, to the Webvan
Group, the Internet grocery vendor. Out of his mind? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI He has the opportunity to make a whole lot of money
over there, from what I've read. So, you know, it's like the risk
somebody pointed out before: if he has a shot at $100 million or
thereabouts, it's probably a reasonable place to go. And he's
probably a pretty capable executive, so it's a risk worth taking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do the media exaggerate the extent to which the CEO is the
company and the company is the CEO? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI I've thought about that a lot, and I think the
difficulty you have is it's hard to talk about a company _ that
Allied Signal did this or Tyco did that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I think you ascribe brilliance too soon. I mean, you
take a Jack Welch (of General Electric) for 20 years _ he deserves
it. He's come through good and bad times and always has done well.
But I don't think you should do it in terms of a year or two. I
mean, you might want to see them season a little. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about CEO compensation? There is some concern that while
the market's been doing wonderfully, CEOs have made out more than
handsomely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY The press had something to do with that. They didn't
like salaries and bonuses, so they said, ``You ought to put more of
your income at risk.'' And so the corporations did, and now they're
complaining about that.
</P>
<P>
   But when I get asked in my own audiences, I say: ``I make a lot
of money. And take on a lot of risk.''
</P>
<P>
   And then I say, ``Our savings plan is up $2.5 billion since I
came.'' That doesn't mean just me _ the whole company has made a
lot. And the people who own the stock in the company make a lot of
money. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI I do not receive one single penny of bonus unless my
earnings per share grow over 20 percent a year. However, I do start
accruing restricted shares of stock, and I make an awful lot of
money in the stock. We pay taxes on that, and our compensation is
totally in line with the shareholders. And one could look at it and
say, yeah, we truly are overpaid, but a lot of it's been the
appreciation of the stock market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG It's been noted that I got a $600-and-some million grant.
But people don't realize this was a plan that was approved by 86 or
87 percent of the shareholders. If we brought a value of $18
billion to shareholders, I would think then we'd earned a bonus. It
was a five-year plan with a seven-year tail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI You got a $600 million grant? I'm glad I'm not your
shareholder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I wouldn't mind being your adopted kid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS I had a fascinating conversation last week with someone
who was absolutely outraged by Carly Fiorina's pay package (when
she recently signed on at Hewlett-Packard). And I said, ``Yes, but
why would she have come otherwise?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's often said that at a certain level it no longer matters
how much any of you make, that you would be doing just as good a
job for $100 million less or $20 million less. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI Yeah, all my meals are paid for, for as long as I'm
around. So, I'm not working for that any longer.
</P>
<P>
   But it does make a difference in the charities I ultimately
leave monies behind to, and it's a way of keeping score. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY Hewlett-Packard doesn't have a habit of going out and
paying exorbitant salaries, so they wanted her (Ms. Fiorina) to run
the company, and that's what the market was, and she got the market
price. How can you be critical of that? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS I don't even know her, but I think she would have
considered herself foolish if she left all that money on the table.
Why would she do that? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Setting an Example &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do employees and other stakeholders in the companies look to
activities outside the executive suite as signals about the chief
executive's leadership and values? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG I think charity is a personal thing. We also recognize the
company is also a member of the community and the world at large.
What I try to do is encourage my people to give. If you're an
employee of CA, if you give $1, CA will match $2 for it. So this
way we really push them to give more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I think, though, there is an issue as to how much time a
CEO should spend doing other things.
</P>
<P>
   I think you're hired to run the company. That doesn't mean you
should be ignorant of what's going on in Washington, but you ought
to go down there selectively as opposed to weekly.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
