<SLUG> BC-EXECS-ROUNDTABLE-5THTAKE-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 NEW YORK: to weekly.
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't think you can get involved in a whole bunch of
charities. I think you can get involved in a charity and then spend
some time, and influence it, and try to make it better. But the
more I see CEOs fragment their time doing a lot of other things, I
think, the less successful they're going to be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS I'd like to answer your question in a somewhat different
way, because I think I'm always asked these questions about balance
and how do you retain women.
</P>
<P>
   How I spend my time and how I communicate my own values and my
own priorities does have a very significant impact on the employees
in my company. So that when I stay out for three months for
maternity leave, I am well aware that that makes it all right to
take maternity leave.
</P>
<P>
   And if the CEO isn't going to the school play, and the CEO is
canceling his vacation, and the CEO is not coming home to be at his
6-year-old's birthday party, well then, the rest of the company
knows how they're supposed to behave. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: We still haven't seen too many cases of women with small
children running large organizations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG Why is it different for women? I raised my three kids. One
of them is 28 years old. And I raised them while I was building
Computer Associates. Now I have two more kids. One's 6 and one's 1
year old. I go to the school play. I'm the one that goes to the
parent-teacher conference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: There is a widely cited statistic that two-thirds of the men
who work, are married and have children, have wives who stay at
home, but hardly any working wives with children have stay-at-home
husbands.
</P>
<P>
   WANG My wife works. She works for CA. She has 4,000 people
reporting to her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI So she is your successor?
</P>
<P>
   WANG No, she's not. She's too nerdy! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I've had nine children. There's no reason why you can't
be president and do a lot of the things as the kids grow up. I did.
</P>
<P>
   And I do think the hardest deal in the world is for a woman to
have two or three young kids, to work when their spouse works. That
is just physically exhausting. That takes a toll after a while. And
I don't know what we in business have done yet to be able to
resolve that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI We've tackled it a little differently in the last
couple of years, where we've put about 8,000 of our managers
through diversity training, approaching all types of issues, from
creating a culture where a man or a woman can work from the home,
to being much more flexible in their abilities to make
contributions to a company, to being supportive of maternity leaves
before Congress mandated them. And I think you really need to do
that, because if not, you're going to eliminate an awful lot of
talented people out of your pool of resources. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAZARUS The smart CEO has to do that. Why would you give up 50
percent of the population when talent's a scarce resource? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSSIDY I tell people: ``Don't come in here on Saturday and
Sunday unless something special is going on, because all you're
going to do is become a bore. I mean, do something, music or
whatever you like, but for heaven's sake, grow.'' They'll say,
``How many Sundays do you work?'' I work a couple of Sundays a
year, only because something special is happening. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the one thing about being a chief executive that you
would change with a wave of your hand, if you could? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOZLOWSKI I'd probably eliminate the jet plane, so that we
wouldn't be expected to be in so many different places so often.
Jets have really destroyed civilization. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANG One thing is, don't perceive us CEOs as some kind of higher
order of human beings. I really want to work with people and not
have a meeting where everybody is, ``He's here, so I've got to be
on a different kind of behavior.'' I wish they would just relax.
</P>
