<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMPHIS-MAYOR-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMPHIS MAYOR RE-ELECTED BY SURPRISINGLY WIDE MARGIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ After one of the most raucous and highly
contested election campaigns in this city's history, voters have
given Mayor Willie Herenton a third term by a surprisingly decisive
margin.
</P>
<P>
   Herenton, who became the first black mayor of Memphis with a
narrow victory in 1991 and was re-elected handily with no serious
competition in 1995, triumphed again on Thursday with 45.7 percent
of the vote, in a field of 14 challengers.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a Memphis mayoral election, the top two
contenders were black, with the City Council chairman, Joe Ford,
Herenton's closest competitor, drawing 25.1 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Analysis of returns from precincts throughout the city suggested
that Herenton's support cut across racial lines in this city of
650,000 people, 55 percent of whom are black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this election means in part that the evolution in race
relations in Memphis continues to improve,'' said Marcus Pohlmann,
a political science professor at Rhodes College. ``I don't know
whether we're ready to bury race as a factor in this city. I
suspect not. But this election showed that you continue to have a
significant number of whites who appear to be comfortable voting
for an African-American. And that is a change.''
</P>
<P>
   In his victory speech, Herenton said: ``We must have a spirit of
unity that crosses race, politics and economics. That is what is
going to move Memphis on to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   The margin of Herenton's victory in this election _ a
nonpartisan process, although the winner and the runner-up were
both Democrats _ surprised many here. Ford was considered the
mayor's most formidable opponent throughout the race, not so much
because of his own political record after five years on the City
Council as because of his family name.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ford's brothers, Harold E. Ford Sr., was Tennessee's
first black congressman and served 11 terms in the House before his
son, Harold Jr., replaced him three years ago. Another brother of
Joe Ford serves on the County Commission, and yet another is a
Tennessee state senator.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the mayoral race, Herenton called the Fords a
political machine that was ``not healthy for the body politic.''
But Joe Ford's resounding defeat has some calling into question the
family's longtime hold on power here.
</P>
<P>
   Pohlmann said the Ford family ``might have given the illusion
that they have more clout than they actually do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think many people might have overestimated the Ford family's
control in the black community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Steven Etheridge, a nonpartisan political
pollster, said he did not think the outcome of the election
signaled that the Fords' power had much diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be overstating it,'' Etheridge said. ``It is very
circumstantial. I think the black community did not want to run the
risk of eliminating a strong black mayor by voting for Joe Ford and
so letting a white candidate win.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Thursday's result has brought speculation about the
viability of Harold Ford Jr.'s ambition to run next year against
Bill Frist, one of the state's two Republican senators.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ford, who has already made a preliminary tour of the state, was
involved in one of the nastiest flare-ups of his uncle's mayoral
campaign, in which he and other Ford supporters accused a Herenton
campaign worker of pulling a gun on them when they were putting up
Ford yard signs. Ford also recorded radio commercials attacking
Herenton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to understand,'' Pohlmann said, ``why a sitting
congressman would risk alienating Democratic Herenton supporters by
getting himself involved in what was essentially a Democratic
primary.''
</P>
<P>
   In one bright spot for the Fords, yet another member of the
family, Edmund Ford, easily won the City Council seat that his
brother Joe vacated to run for mayor. That seat has been held by a
Ford family member since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Lawler, professional wrestler turned politician, finished
a distant third in the mayoral race, with 11.7 percent of the vote.
Lawler had hoped for a Jesse Ventura-style jump from the wrestling
ring to the political arena, but his candidacy faltered, especially
after he was indicted on charges of attacking a police officer this
spring in a dispute over parking at the airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
