<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS CASTRO FACES END OF REIGN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, basking in the
embrace of the political organization of his brother, Gov. Jeb Bush
of Florida, on Friday lambasted a favorite bogeyman of the Sunshine
State GOP, Cuban President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   The two sons of former President Bush put on a warm display of
mutual admiration before the Texas governor dropped a spirited
denunciation of Castro into his regular presidential stump speech
for a crowd of several hundred supporters at the Florida Republican
convention.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination, labeled Castro a ``revolutionary relic'' who faces the
end of his 40-year Communist rule. Bush indicated he could not
foresee lifting U.S. economic sanctions on Cuba as long as Castro
remains in power.
</P>
<P>
   After making his standard observation that freedom is the United
States' greatest export, Bush launched what was apparently the most
extensive public comments of his presidential campaign about the
Marxist regime of the island nation 90 miles off the Florida Keys.
</P>
<P>
   ``This freedom must be spread throughout all the Americas. This
freedom is meant for all of our neighbors. And this freedom is
meant for Cuba,'' Bush said, setting off whoops of approval in a
crowded hotel ballroom where some of his backers stood for more
than an hour to await his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must and we will keep the sanctions against the Castro
regime until there is freedom of speech in Cuba, until there is
freedom of press in Cuba, until there is freedom of religion in
Cuba,'' Bush said. ``We will keep those sanctions until justice is
restored, political prisoners are set free and the exiles are
welcomed home.''
</P>
<P>
   Most foreign policy analysts believe few if any of those
conditions are likely to be met as long as Castro remains in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today Cuba is ruled by a revolutionary relic at war with time
and at war with his people,'' Bush said. ``But history has always
disposed of tyrants, and Castro's day is coming. Cuba will be
free.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Cuban population has been a relatively reliable
supporter of Republicans since the waves of exiles began fleeing
Castro's regime in the early 1960s. More recently, however, younger
Cuban-Americans have been less faithful to the GOP than their
elders.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Florida co-chairmen of the Bush presidential campaign
announced Friday by Jeb Bush was U.S. Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart of
Miami, a Cuban-American political leader.
</P>
<P>
   Also among the group were Lt. Gov. Frank Brogan, Secretary of
State Katherine Harris, Senate President Tony Jennings and House
Speaker John Thrasher.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the lineup of GOP power assembled by the Florida
governor, the Texas governor told reporters before the rally: ``I'm
glad I was such a kind older brother.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed to detail how he would win Florida's primary in
March and carry the state's 25 electoral votes in November 2000 if
he's the nominee, candidate Bush said: ``I'm going to do everything
he tells me to do (pause), for the first time in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texan said _ with a grin _ that he had not even scratched
his brother off the list of prospective vice presidential running
mates, a line-up that almost certainly will include other
Republican governors. Earlier this year, the Bush brothers said
they would not consider being running mates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
