<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE THUMB HURTS, AND SO DO SOME WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Piazza got his left thumb in the way of a baseball; Bobby
Valentine lodged his foot in his mouth _ again. Steve Phillips, the
Mets' general manager, called the latter ``an ill-timed fire,'' but
he declined to compare its potential impact to the Piazza ailment.
</P>
<P>
   In the context of the New York Mets playing the Arizona
Diamondbacks on Friday night and trying to win their division
series, Phillips was asked before the game which was the more
ill-timed: the inflammatory reaction Piazza had to a cortisone shot
for his thumb, or Valentine's comments about his players and one of
his coaches as quoted in a Sports Illustrated article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Phillips said, obviously opting not to answer, ``I have
feelings about it. But I don't feel my feelings have to be shared
with the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Mets were trying to generate another winning streak
that would catapult them into the National League Championship
Series, they encountered trouble and distraction. Neither could
help.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's thumb and his forced absence from the third game of the
tied series undoubtedly would have a greater impact. A team doesn't
lose its starting catcher and No. 1 home &UR; - &LR; run hitter and run
producer without noticing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' Al Leiter, the Mets' scheduled starting pitcher
for Saturday afternoon's Game 4, said before Friday night's game.
``Crazy stuff like this happens where you don't expect something
from somebody. I hope Todd Pratt is the hero tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, the seldom-used reserve, replaced Piazza in the lineup.
There apparently is no substitute for common sense. Otherwise, why
would a manager say to a reporter for a national, or any,
publication that he has ``about five guys in there right now who
basically are losers''?
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said the article contained two inaccuracies, but he
didn't deny that he made that particular statement. He said he
would talk to his players about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might just say if any shoes fit, wear them,'' he related,
standing at the batting cage during batting practice. ``If not,
don't worry about it. I don't think anybody will worry about it.
It's an issue because it's New York and Bobby Valentine. Otherwise
it's a nonissue. Everything that's said there has been said a
thousand times about teams and players. It's no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But managers don't usually say it about their players, certainly
not when they're trying to get to the playoffs. ``I'm supposed to
call the editor and tell him when to write the story?'' Valentine
said when he was asked about the timing.
</P>
<P>
   But he has tried to play editor before. In spring training this
year he objected to an article in The New York Times in which Todd
Hundley, the Mets' former catcher, spoke harshly of his former
manager. Valentine complained that there was nothing new in
Hundley's comments and that the only reason for writing it was that
the reporter had a vendetta against him.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine doesn't need anyone raising questions about him; he
does the best job of that himself. For example, a couple of weeks
ago, after he said that he shouldn't return next season if the Mets
didn't reach the playoffs, he described the remark as spontaneous.
His wife said earlier this week that they discussed it the night
before.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips this year has periodically had to put out brush fires
that Valentine lighted. ``We've had a lot of timing issues this
year,'' the general manager said. ``The timing's not great, but at
this point it's irrelevant.'' In other words, the comment was in
print; nothing to be done to delete it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope,'' Phillips said, ``is we can avert a distractive
state from the players and that it won't distract them and they'll
be able to focus on what we're trying to do.'' He added a minute
later: ``I think that Bobby is an emotional person. It's part of
what makes him very good at what he does and at times it's the
thing that gets him in trouble with the things that he says.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips added that he ``would rather be getting fired up that
Rick Reed's going to pitch a great game tonight and we're going to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's presence in the lineup would very likely have aided
that endeavor, though in the first two games he had twice as many
strikeouts (four) as hits (two). Buck Martinez, a former catcher
turned broadcaster, said disclosure of the thumb injury put
Piazza's hitting problems in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Catching pitches with an injured thumb, Martinez explained,
``tears you up,'' adding: ``Now it becomes a factor because it's
your power hand on the bat. You think back on it and it explains
itself. The bad sliders he swung at against Todd Stottlemyre _ you
think about starting the bat because you know it's going to bark a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza said he hoped the inflammation would subside sufficiently
so he could play Saturday, but Martinez said catching Leiter would
not be beach volleyball for Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``His ball sinks so much and you get in between turning it this
way and turning it that way,'' Martinez said, moving his hand back
and forth as if he were catching pitches. ``It's tough to get
over,'' he added about the injury. ``You don't get over it real
quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it takes people time to recover from Valentine's
comments, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
