<SLUG> BC-CANYON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND CANYON FLIGHT BILL GUTTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - Noise restrictions at the Grand Canyon, caps on the
number of air-tour flights, and a curfew on flights at sunrise and
sunset could all be gutted under a bill pushed through the Senate
this week by Arizona Sen. John McCain.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aides to the Republican presidential candidate said the bill is
intended as a ``shot across the bow'' of the Clinton
administration, which Mc Cain maintains has dragged its feet in
establishing rules for so-called ``quiet technology'' aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and members of the Clinton administration
believe that industry-backed ``quiet technol ogy'' is not the
answer to restoring periods of silence to the Canyon, but McCain
has supported it as a way to make the skies there less noisy
without banning air flights alto gether.
</P>
<P>
   John Raidt, the McCain campaign's policy director, tried to
reassure critics, saying McCain ``is not going to let something go
into law that would end up making the Canyon noisier.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Arnberger, superintendent of Grand Canyon National Park,
joined environmentalists Oct. 8 in warning that the measure will
have the unintended consequence of gutting years of work toward
establishing McCain's own long-sought goal of returning ``natural
quiet'' to the nation's most popular natural attrac tion.
</P>
<P>
   Late Oct. 5, in an amendment to a bill reauthorizing the Federal
Avia tion Administration, McCain re quired the agency to define
what is a ``quiet aircraft'' within nine months.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure says that if the agency fails to do this, ``any
aircraft shall be considered to be in compli ance.''
</P>
<P>
   Aircraft that are deemed to be ``quiet'' could run an unlimited
number of flights and fly during the sunrise/sunset curfews
established as a result of McCain's landmark 1987 Grand Canyon
Overflights Act.
</P>
<P>
   McCain press secretary Nancy Ives said the amendment would apply
only to aircraft that replaced existing planes and helicopters in
the fleets of the nearly two dozen firms that fly tours over the
Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   But because all aircraft would be deemed ``quiet,'' both
environmen talists and park officials say, the air-tour industry
could swap out aircraft at random and be in compli ance with the
law.
</P>
<P>
   There is no such thing as a quiet airplane or helicopter,
according to Superintendent Arnberger.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's measure presumes, incorrectly, that quieter
aircraft will reduce noise at the Canyon, Arnber ger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not silent. They're just less noisy, and they are
noisy,'' Arnber ger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This amendment allows a free-for-all for all aircraft over the
Grand Canyon so long as they meet some definition for quiet
aircraft,'' the superintendent said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bassett, president of the U.S. Air Tour Association, a
Maryland lobbying group that represents 55 air-tour and related
firms, including most that fly over the Grand Can yon, said he was
aware of McCain's amendment, but he refused to dis cuss it.
</P>
<P>
   Bassett's group has worked to ensure that the federal agency
maintains control of the airspace over the nation's 52 national
parks, fearing that the National Park Service would ban all air
tours if given the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Raidt, who has worked as McCain's environmental policy point-man
for more than a decade, said the sena tor's passage of the 1987
Overflights Act, which bans aircraft below the rim and restricts
them to certain flight corridors, ``is the flagship of John
McCain's environmental re cord.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain would do nothing to jeopar dize that legislation, Raidt
said, noting that it was McCain who proded the Justice Department
in recent years to seek fines from air-tour operators who had
refused to pay hundreds of thousands of dollars in park-tour fees.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists have called McCain the Canyon's
staunchest defender in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Rob Smith of the Sierra Club wonders why McCain is
pushing the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wording of the amendment virtually eliminates all the
progress made so far since 1987,'' he said. ``The only ones who
would hear a quiet Canyon would be those who hike at midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Aircraft that employ quiet tech nology simply produce noise for
up to nine miles in every direction, instead of 16 miles, Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal in most of the Canyon should be to listen to the
Canyon, and not to airplanes.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
