<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-DISPARITY(TRIMS     10-08 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISPARITY(TRIMS)-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CHINA'S BOOM, RURAL POOR FEEL A WIDENING GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALI, China _ In a crumbling mud-brick house, nestled against
the untidy heap that holds her family's entire wardrobe, Zheng
Xingrong defines her life with a series of emphatic negatives.
</P>
<P>
   How often do your children eat eggs or meat? ``Never!'' Do you
have a radio or television? ``No!'' Is your 14-year-old daughter in
school? ``No!'' Does your 8-year-old boy have any toys? ``None!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we have no money, we don't dare to have any dreams,''
said the 40-year-old woman, whose family is one of the poorest in a
destitute farming village north of the Yellow River in Shandong
province.
</P>
<P>
   Only three hours away by car, in Hongyuan village, near the city
of Jinan, Li Huazhu, 45, and his wife Chen Xuerong, 39 _ farmers
until a few years ago _ proudly show off the former gas station
site they just bought with cash. It will house their expanding
company, which makes precision-ground granite slabs to export for
industrial use.
</P>
<P>
   Their 17-year-old son has some very big toys _ a videodisc
player and a motorbike _ and their 18-year-old daughter is in
nursing school. Ms. Chen dreams of the day, not so distant, when
they can buy a car and build their own two-story house. ``No,'' her
husband interjects, ``a three-story house!''
</P>
<P>
   Between one family's despair and another family's dreams lies a
serious new problem for China, the rapid growth in economic
disparities. In the booming 1990s, yawning gaps opened between city
and countryside, between the developed coast and the isolated
interior, between upper and lower classes in the cities and, as
these two families illustrate, between richer and poorer villages.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   No one knows the extent to which popular resentment of
inequality may be a source of unrest in a country that is already
struggling with slowed growth, high unemployment and bitterness
over official corruption. But the trend itself is striking.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   From comparative income equality in the mid-1980s, China in the
last decade has suddenly emerged as one of the most unequal
countries in Asia, surpassing countries like India and Indonesia,
according to reports by the World Bank and others. China's
disparities surpass those of the United States and Western Europe,
though they do not approach the extremes of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mounting inequality and its possible consequences, both for
social and economic stability and for continued growth, have become
central issues of policy debate and scholarly research,'' said Hu
Angang, an economist at the Chinese Academy of Sciences, and Wang
Shaoguang, a political scientist at the Chinese University of Hong
Kong, in their new book, ``The Political Economy of Uneven
Development: The Case of China'' (M.E. Sharpe).
</P>
<P>
   Still, public debate inside China about the growing disparities
remains muted, in part because the official line remains that
economic trailblazers will pull up everyone else and that the
government is fully addressing any problems.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades ago, as China switched from Mao Tse-tung's failed
socialism toward a more open, market-oriented economy, some rise in
inequality was expected and even desired. Deng Xiaoping, mastermind
of the reforms, famously said, ``Let some prosper first, so that
others may follow.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic loosening produced blistering growth and,
especially in the early years, widely shared improvements. The
climb from penury for hundreds of millions of rural people through
family farming and the spread of rural industry has been one of
modern China's greatest feats.
</P>
<P>
   But few anticipated the surging disparities of the 1990s, as the
top urban and rural groups sped ahead. One study, by Dwayne
Benjamin and Loren Brandt of the University of Toronto, found rural
inequality as great as in the feudal 1930s, although at higher
levels for all.
</P>
<P>
   Today, these scholars found, it is access to nonfarm jobs in
rural and township industries or the cities, rather than grossly
skewed land-holdings, that has allowed some to forge ahead. Rural
areas nearest to cities _ like Hongyuan village, outside Shandong's
capital, Jinan _ have done especially well.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, rural economic growth has fallen far behind
that of the cities _ and is likely to keep sputtering without major
changes in policy, economists say, because agriculture is in a rut
and many rural industries are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, there is evidence that progress against the most severe
poverty slowed during a period of fantastic national growth. Since
the late '80s the reduction of rural poverty ``was far less than it
would have been had the growth in rural income inequality been
avoided,'' conclude Carl Riskin of Columbia University and Azizur
Khan of the University of California in a study being published by
Oxford University Press.
</P>
<P>
   Still trapped at rock-bottom today are some 124 million Chinese,
living below the World Bank's poverty standard of $1 a day in per
capita income. According to the government's more stringent
definition, there are 42 million Chinese below the poverty line.
Whatever the definition, China's poorest people are concentrated in
crowded, eroded mountain lands in the south and the north and in
pockets elsewhere, like the region of poor soils and little
industry around Bali.
</P>
<P>
   Now, too, an urban underclass is emerging for the first time in
recent history, mainly unemployed workers and elderly people with
minimal pensions and no prosperous relatives to help out.
</P>
<P>
   The government has special policies to aid the poor and reduce
inequality, including small welfare payments for destitute city
dwellers, rural anti-poverty projects and incentives for investment
in inland provinces.
</P>
<P>
   But harming the rural areas in particular are two policies that
seem unlikely to be reversed any time soon: the tight controls on
the ability of villagers to move to cities and compete for jobs,
and a national policy of self-sufficiency in grain, under which
farmers are forced to grow grains when they often could make far
more growing fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
