<HEADER>
A1390 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-SCNOTE-LADN     10-08 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SCNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN RAAPHORSE SICK OF BEING HOT TOPIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ USC quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst has not
always fared well in hot weather but expects to change that trend
today.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Van Raaphorst experienced flu-like symptoms before
the season opener with Purdue, when the field temperature reached
118 degrees. He also experienced nausea and was forced to sit out
most of the Florida State game.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst said he's sure he won't suffer a relapse today
against Arizona, because his family doctor said anti-cramping pills
caused his nausea.
</P>
<P>
   Others are not so sure. USC does not endorse the use of
anti-cramping pills except in extreme cases, which would not
include Van Raaphorst. There is still speculation that Van
Raaphorst's problems were psychological.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Van Raaphorst is confident he will be healthy
against the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of that stuff, I'm good to go,'' Van Raaphorst said.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett said he plans to use more players today
because the kickoff temperature is expected to reach 95 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to play some guys and give guys a break,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the expected changes is to use freshman tailback Sultan
McCullough more to keep starter Chad Morton fresh.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hostile crowd: USC linebacker Zeke Moreno has never played in
Arizona Stadium, but that doesn't mean he isn't familiar with the
atmosphere on game days. Moreno came here to watch his brother,
Moses, play quarterback for Colorado State against the Wildcats in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the way the fans can be because we had on Colorado
State shirts and stuff. It's a hostile place,'' Moreno said. ``The
only memory I have is my brother playing there.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State won 21-16.
</P>
<P>
   __ Seeking help: Because Hackett has never faced Arizona, he
asked his assistants for even more input than usual this week.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator Hue Jackson coached at Arizona State and
California before coming to USC in 1997. Offensive line coach Steve
Greatwood spent most of his career at Oregon, and tight ends coach
Steve Morton was at Washington before being hired by Hackett last
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very fortunate that we've got three people that have
played against this defense many times before,'' Hackett said. ``So
I'm sitting back and listening to them. I'm going to rely heavily
on them.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Controversial call: Washington State is bitter about losing
to Arizona two weeks ago 30-24 on a clearly botched call on the
last play of the game, when wide receiver Bobby Wade ``caught'' a
42-yard Hail Mary touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   What made the play particularly galling to Washington State is
that side judge Jerry Gastellum, who made the call, is from Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   __ Some weaknesses: Arizona's unimpressive start can be
explained by one key stat: The Wildcats' defense is allowing 5
yards per carry.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State, Texas Christian and Stanford exposed this weakness,
rushing for 262, 224 and 214 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear about missed tackles,'' Hackett said. ``I don't know
how a great defense starts missing tackles, but I don't buy that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-DISPARITY-ART-2     10-08 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISPARITY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BALI: and vegetables.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bali, a village of 300 families and 1,300 people, is in a county
that authorities only last year declared to have been lifted above
the official government poverty line, set at a per-person income of
about $220 a year.
</P>
<P>
   A large group of residents, gathered in front of Ms. Zheng's
home, laughed on hearing about that official milestone. ``An entire
family here doesn't earn $220,'' one man said, and that includes
money brought home by migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
   In all the village, just three people have bought motor scooters
and about 70 percent of families have small black-and-white
televisions. The mud and straw homes have floors of packed earth.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that perhaps the farmers do not fully calculate the
value of their subsistence crops, but other signs point to an
insecure, nearly hand-to-mouth existence. Each family has less than
an acre of land to farm, and the soils, cropped with wheat and then
corn every year, are salty and low-yielding.
</P>
<P>
   Each year every family must hand over 100 kilograms _ about 220
pounds _ of grain, close to half their produce, to the local
government, residents said, in payment of obligations they are not
sure about. For most families, the remaining grain provides just
enough to eat through the year, with some of the wheat traded for a
paste made from freshwater shrimp. There is rarely any surplus left
to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Families owe another $15 in various fees each year, residents
said, and must also pay other fees for every child in school.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that keeps families here going is the money
earned by men who spend a few months each summer _ leaving when the
corn is knee-high and returning at harvest time _ working in
highway construction around the city of Tianjin or along Shandong's
prosperous coast. There, they can save about $60 each month.
</P>
<P>
   One reason why Ms. Zheng's family is especially bad off is that
her husband has asthma and has not been able to earn much in
distant labor. He does not go to the clinic, she said, ``unless he
has really serious trouble breathing,'' because it costs $5 a
visit.
</P>
<P>
   The family keeps six chickens and a pig in the front yard, but
all eggs and meat must be sold, and day after day they eat either
bread and shrimp paste or boiled turnips.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zheng's brother-in-law, 34-year-old Luo Huicheng, thought he
had a way to break through last year when he saw low prices for
feed grains and good prices for pork. Encouraged by county
agricultural agents, in July of 1998 he borrowed $2,100 to build
concrete sties and buy 30 pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, hundreds of thousands of other farmers around
China had the same idea and in a classic cycle, overproduction
caused pork prices to plummet. In front of his empty sty, Luo
described his feelings earlier this year, as he watched prices fall
below his costs, and then fall more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt so helpless,'' he recalled. ``I'd built the sty. I'd
bought the pigs. I just wished they would hurry up and grow!'' He
sold the pigs for $600, and worked at construction jobs to start
repaying his loan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
