<HEADLINE>
TROJANS CAN'T AFFORD TO GET LOST IN DESERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; TUCSON, Ariz. _ The loss to Oregon was devastating. The victory
over Oregon State somewhat embarrassing. But through those two
less-than-desired results, USC is surviving and clinging to its
preseason goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a long way to go to get to the Rose Bowl, but we're
making small steps at this point,'' USC tailback Chad Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 22-ranked Trojans will take a giant leap today when they
face Arizona at 12:30 p.m. The only mystery is whether it will be a
step forward or backward?
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot lose again if we want to go to the Rose Bowl,''
Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   A couple weeks removed from their triple-overtime loss to
Oregon, the Trojans (3-1, 1-1) are hitting the road again, needing
an elusive victory in a hostile stadium to keep their aspirations
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to explain what kind of game this is. We've
played on the road, played our hearts and (thrown) it away,'' USC
coach Paul Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Trojans need to finally earn a road victory
instead of collectively shaking their heads afterwards, which
usually happens on these excursions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to the point of the year where a team should take
shape,'' Hackett said. ``For the most part, we're getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Now all that is left is to prove it. Morton, who gained a
career-high 153 yards last weekend, believes he has figured out
where the Trojans' fortunes rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the (offensive) line that will determine how far the team
goes,'' Morton said. ``I think it's up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a key area, all right, because the line remains in flux.
A finally healthy Trevor Roberts is gaining ground on starter Brent
McCaffrey at left tackle, and left guard is being filled by
sophomore Faasea Mailo because starter Donta Kendrick has a badly
sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   At center, senior Matt McShane is expected to play an entire
game because starter Eric Denmon has been slowed by tendinitis in
his knees. Denmon returns today, but McShane will get most of the
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the offensive line to pick up where it left off last
year, but it took a while to get going and that's just the
process,'' Hackett said. ``We saw a spark in the (Oregon State)
game where we're going to be a pretty good running team &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; . If
we can get the running game going, I'm going to be very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Did someone say excited? That's something few people have been
in Tucson since late August, when Arizona took a 41-7 thumping from
Penn State and saw its national-championship hopes evaporate.
Nearly everything else was lost following a stunning 50-22 setback
to Stanford three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, (the expectations) probably weren't realistic,''
Arizona coach Dick Tomey said. ``I knew we were overrated a little
bit, but I hoped we would rise to the occasion and play over our
heads, and we haven't done that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats (3-2, 1-1) still have a chance to make it to the
Rose Bowl, which is why this game is so important.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have had a week off, they've worked on fundamentals and
they'll probably play like gangbusters,'' Hackett said. ``I think
we're going to play the best team we've played this year. They were
slated as the favorites and I don't think that information was too
far off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
