<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-WORLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web may be found in tiny places
 &HT;    By Heather Cocks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The technology driving the Internet's next big growth
spurt may be as tiny as the tip of a match.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fall 1999 Internet World conference, which wrapped up
here Friday, a handful of companies pushed what they believe is the
next big advance in Internet computing _ tiny World Wide Web
servers embedded in clothing, jewelry and even household
appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the post-PC age,'' proclaimed Jack Powers of the
International Informatics Institute, an Internet-related research
company. ``The Internet is expanding off the desktop and leaking
into the fabric of our lives. We'll be immersed in connectivity.''
</P>
<P>
   And that full Internet integration can happen without the
clutter of clunky servers. Powers described a minute,
matchtip-sized Web server that, when built into any device, can
create smarter appliances empowered by the rich content available
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The IPic technology, designed and used by University of
Massachusetts researchers, is just a piece of the puzzle. Powers
described a future in which the processors already present in
things such as cars, watches and security systems connect to the
Net. Service providers such as GoAmerica are giving Web access to
wireless phones and tiny handheld computers, and researchers say
home appliances are a logical next step in using the power of
information to enhance functionality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make these devices smarter,'' said Michael Nelson,
chief executive of emWare Inc., which makes software that runs
Internet-enabled devices. ``We just need a server that can talk to
the Web _ we don't need to cram a Pentium in there.''
</P>
<P>
   At a forum showcasing so-called smart appliances, Powers
introduced a prototype of a Web-enabled microwave oven.
</P>
<P>
   A scanner lets the oven read barcodes, which it uses to
recognize a product and download cooking instructions. On a 10-inch
touch-screen on the microwave door, the computer chip creates a
shopping list, helps create recipes or lets the user navigate the
Web. It also performs limited online banking functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``These appliances have to be simple, with an application that's
appropriate to the context in which they exist,'' said Stephen
Emmott of NCR Knowledge Labs, which designed the prototype. ``The
kitchen is a hub of activity and information, but people don't want
a whole PC in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Allegro Software Development Corp. used a small Lego house to
show what Internet connectivity could do for home security.
</P>
<P>
   By embedding Web servers in motion detectors and other home
security features, a homeowner who is traveling can use any PC to
alter the frequency and times that lights turn on and off, and
track any motion inside their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone's really watching a house, they notice if the same
lights come on like clockwork every night,'' said Edward Steinfeld,
who handles Allegro's marketing.
</P>
<P>
   There's already a growing core of interest in Internet-embedded
appliances and other systems.
</P>
<P>
   About 27 million Americans would buy Internet-enabled devices if
they were available today, up 31 percent from last year, according
to online market research company Cyber Dialogue Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Of that 27 million, a surprising 54 percent log onto the
Internet only rarely, if ever, the study showed _ something
researcher Thomas Miller said stems more from a fascination with
gadgets than with the Web itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want things that are cool but easy to use,'' Miller
said. ``That poses new challenges for the industry. People want
fun, not complexity or big, heavy Web servers.'' During futuristic
fashion shows during Internet World, InfoCharm Inc. showcased
prototypes for badges and headsets that offer hands-free Internet
and e-mail access. Some sets included Web viewing tools that attach
to glasses, one-handed keyboards and keypads built into the fabric
of a shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, InfoCharm wants to create a wireless, wearable Web
device that's as much an afterthought as jewelry and watches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at clocks _ they used to fill buildings until someone
started making them smaller and smaller,'' said Russ Hoffman, an
InfoCharm hardware engineer. ``At first people balked at wearing a
clock, a machine, on their arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, everyone wears them as necessary accessories.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Cocks writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
