<SLUG> BC-BOX-ALI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALI WINS, BUT FIGHT ISN'T THE GREATEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERONA, N.Y. _ With her father sitting ringside on Friday night
at the Turning Stone Casino ballroom, Laila Ali, the youngest
daughter of Muhammad Ali, stepped into the ring to continue the
legacy. And just like her father, Laila Ali made quick work of her
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Ali, making her boxing debut, knocked out April
Fowler with a left-right combination at 31 seconds of the first
round and then stood over Fowler, yelling for her to get up and
fight.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same pose that her father struck when he stood over a
fallen Sonny Liston in their rematch in 1965 in Lewiston, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Laila Ali posed for pictures and then leaned through
the ropes and got a kiss from her father, who smiled proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali entered the ballroom about 45 minutes before his
daughter stepped into the ring. He arrived to a great ovation. He
walked slowly to his seat at ringside, the tremors from Parkinson's
disease making his gait unsteady. He was accompanied by his wife,
Lonnie, and Laila's sister Hana.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica, Laila's mother and Ali's third wife, sat on the
opposite side of the ring. Veronica and Muhammad Ali were divorced
when Laila was 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali's presence created a huge buzz in the building and
overshadowed his daughter's ring debut. But it also indicated that
he was throwing his support behind her, even though he does not
agree with her desire to box.
</P>
<P>
   Ali sat expressionless as his daughter entered the ring draped
in a long white robe. He kept eyeing her opponent warily. But there
was no reason to.
</P>
<P>
   When she is not training, Laila Ali runs a nail salon in Los
Angeles. She hit upon the idea of boxing for a living a year ago
when she went to the L.A. Boxing Gym to work out.
</P>
<P>
   Ali said she was not athletic as a child. She never played
sports, although she said she believed she had inherited her
father's boxing ability. But she said she was tough, and frequently
fought to protect herself and her older sister, Hana. She said she
was not worried about getting popped in the face or having her nose
bloodied.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed she had very little to fear in that regard, heading
into her debut bout against Fowler. Fowler, 27, is a divorced
mother of two from Michigan City, Ind. She doesn't have an amateur
background, but she had three fights in the Tough Woman contest.
</P>
<P>
   In her first professional bout Fowler was stopped in first round
on a technical knockout. She was knocked down twice before the bout
was stopped. That was 18 months ago. She said she kept training,
waiting for a fight. But she appeared to be pudgy around the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   Before the fight Ali had said that her opponents would be
surprised by her power and her boxing ability. She said the most
frustrating thing at this early stage of her boxing career is that
she is unable to execute the things that she wants to do in the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   There was no way to tell exactly what skill level Ali has, based
on her performance against Fowler, who closed her eyes when she
threw a punch and turned her head when Ali was throwing jabs at
her. Ali managed to land a couple of stiff jabs as Fowler ran
around the ring. But Fowler flopped so fast that it was pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no tapes of her,'' said Michael Acri, the promoter,
who admitted that Fowler was bad. ``There was no way of knowing.
All I knew is that she had one pro fight and three Tough Woman
fights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
