<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-METS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mets pound Diamondbacks 9-2
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ The New York Mets blew open the League Division
Friday night with an unproven and delicate maneuver: park Mike
Piazza's pantaloons on the pine.
</P>
<P>
   Weird science. With their catcher sidelined by a sore left
thumb, the Mets turned merciless, strafing Arizona for 11 hits and
a 9-2 victory on the kind of night that breaks a lesser club's
spirit. The Diamondbacks responded by committing three errors and
walking eight. With a two games-to-one lead, New York sends out Al
Leiter this afternoon to nail down an NLCS berth for a wild card
team most left for dead two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   New York salted it away with a six-run sixth, which reliever
Darren Holmes set into motion with a pair of walks. Rickey
Henderson dropped an RBI single into shallow right and after
Edgardo Alfonzo was intentionally walked to load the bases, John
Olerud greeted reliever Dan Plesac with a two-run single for a 6-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton, the ninth man to bat in the inning finished it
off with a two-run single off Dan Plesac as the Diamondback bullpen
allowed seven base runners and four hits for the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets made such big noise without Piazza, who was scratched
earlier in the day after his sore left thumb ballooned from a
cortisone injection. Piazza, who hits 40 homers with 124 remains
questionable for today's Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona starter Omar Daal was lifted after giving up six hits
and three runs in four innings and the move paid an immediate
dividend. Pinch-hitter Turner Ward made the first postseason hit of
his 10-year career count with a two-run homer in the fifth to close
the gap to 3-2. The runs represented the first Mets starter Rick
had surrendered in 14 innings, dating back to Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   New York increased its lead to 3-0 in the third, which Edgardo
Alfonzo fueled with a lead-off double. John Olerud then dumped an
opposite-field single into left to bring in Alfonzo. Two batters
later with runners on first and third, Robin Ventura beat out a
potential double-play ball with the aid of an Andy Fox throwing
error, bringing Olerud in from third for the third run.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' first response to missing Piazza was this: Benny
Agbayani, hitting fourth in Piazza's place. walked to lead off the
second. Two hitters later, Pratt, starting at Piazza's catcher's
spot, milked a walk after being down 1-2 in the count to keep the
inning alive. Then No. 8 hitter Rey Ordonez recorded his second RBI
of the LDS sent a grounder through shortstop for a 1-0 New York
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
