<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-HURRICANES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' TOP LINE FINDS ITS OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To Ranger fans, it was starting to seem like an
eternity. To Theo Fleury it was just a three-game drought.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury, the Rangers' new 5-foot-6-inch sparkplug, who scored 40
goals last season for Calgary and Colorado, was confident he would
score more this season. Plenty more.
</P>
<P>
   But through his first three games as a Ranger, he did not have
even a point. On Friday night Fleury scored his first goal and set
up two others, and the Rangers blew past the Carolina Hurricanes,
3-1, at Madison Square Garden for their first victory of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury scored the Rangers' final goal at 10 minutes 43 seconds
of the final period; Petr Nedved (three assists) and Adam Graves
(one goal, one assist) combined for eight points, as the Rangers
outshot the Hurricanes, 37-17. Goaltender Kirk McLean, playing for
the injured Mike Richter (back), turned in his second consecutive
solid performance.
</P>
<P>
   But the more encouraging news was the emergence of the Rangers'
top line. That news was tempered, however, by an apparent right
heel injury to Nedved, who was hit by a Mathieu Schneider slap shot
with just over eight minutes remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved skated off, and then attempted to skate during the next
two breaks in action. Finally, Nedved retreated to the Rangers'
dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are already without Richter (who has a slightly
protruding disc), left wing Valery Kamensky (stress fracture, right
forearm) and Tim Taylor (concussion). Their offense is fragile, and
without Nedved, it might become punchless, even with Fleury, who
chopped a loose puck over Carolina goaltender Arturs Irbe for a 3-0
lead Friday night, out on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes' style is that of a counterpuncher, but they
never punched back Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina _ which was playing without left wing Gary Roberts, who
has a left shoulder strain, and without unsigned center Keith
Primeau _ opened in its trademark defensive shell. The trap is
intended to lull an opponent and produce a mistake. It had worked
for the Hurricanes, who came into the Garden 2-0-0 after shutting
out the Philadelphia Flyers, 2-0, on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers, who came in without a victory, played like the
much hungrier team.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes did not record their first shot on goal against
McLean until 5 1-2 minutes had been played. By the end of the first
period, the Rangers had 18 shots to Carolina's four. Halfway
through that period, the Rangers' top line of Fleury, Nedved and
Graves became a strong unit on each shift.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury, Nedved and Graves had not recorded a point through the
Rangers' first three games. The drought ended 17 minutes 28 seconds
into the first period, when Fleury and Nedved set up defenseman
Stephane Quintal for the game's first goal.
</P>
<P>
   The play started in the Rangers' zone. After a long battle for
the puck along the boards, Quintal flipped the puck over Carolina's
Jeff O'Neill to trigger a Rangers' rush. Fleury and Nedved moved
through the neutral zone, creating a 4-on-3 situation. Moving along
the left-wing boards, Fleury carried the puck into the offensive
zone as Nedved hustled down right wing to set up a screen. Fleury
caught Quintal, who was the trailer along the right wing, and hit
him with a pass through the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Quintal sent a wrist shot from the right faceoff circle over
Irbe's right shoulder. The goalie, who was screened by Nedved,
never saw the puck until it was in the net. Quintal had his first
goal as a Ranger, Nedved his first point of the season and Fleury
his first point as a member of the team.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rangers had a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was more of the same. Even the Rangers'
dormant power play contributed something, with Fleury acting as the
catalyst.
</P>
<P>
   With Marek Malik in the penalty box serving a double-minor for a
high stick that caught John MacLean in the face, the
Fleury-Nedved-Graves line clicked less than a minute into the
penalty. Nedved carried the puck through the neutral zone before
hitting Fleury on right wing at the blue line. Fleury skated down
the wing and fired a pass through the right circle for Graves, who
was cruising down the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Graves knocked a modified one-timer _ it was more of a shovel
motion than a swing _ past a helpless Irbe at 13:36 of the second
period for his first goal of the season. Fleury and Nedved each had
their second assist. The Rangers had scored more than one goal for
the first time this season. They outshot the overmatched Hurricanes
by 31-10 over the first two periods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
