<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL LANDS IN NEW YORK AS KNICKS ISSUE A FINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ On the same day the New York Knicks took
disciplinary action against Latrell Sprewell for his mysterious and
unexplained absence from training camp, the unpredictable guard
surfaced in the New York area Friday afternoon when he checked into
the same hotel he lived in last season.
</P>
<P>
   He had apparently spent the previous three days on the road,
driving from Oakland, Calif., to his hometown, Milwaukee, and on to
Westchester County, N.Y., according to two people close to Sprewell
with knowledge of his travel plans.
</P>
<P>
   If so, this partly explains why the Knicks had been unable to
reach him this week. On Friday they began to fine Sprewell for each
of his unexcused absences from practice.
</P>
<P>
   After almost 48 hours of no word from anyone associated with the
player, the two people close to Sprewell said that his agent,
Robert Gist, called late Friday. But as of Friday night, it was
unclear whether Sprewell would attend the final day of camp on
Saturday. The Knicks return home after a workout here in the
morning and resume training on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, the Knicks' tolerance for Sprewell's behavior
was continuing to dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, you have to take disciplinary action,'' general
manager Scott Layden said. ``And so I'm just going to leave it at
that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday and Tuesday, Sprewell was excused from practice to be
in court for a civil lawsuit that had been filed against him in
California. After the jury awarded the plaintiffs $105,000 on
Tuesday _ an amount far short of the $3.5 million they had
reportedly been seeking _ Sprewell's agent told Layden on Wednesday
afternoon that his client was on his way to Milwaukee but would be
in camp by Wednesday night or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As day five of camp passed on Friday, Sprewell was still a
no-show. If the Knicks decide to fine Sprewell from Wednesday on,
his wallet could be as much as $25,000 lighter, according to league
rules. Last April, when the Madison Square Garden president, Dave
Checketts, fined Sprewell $25,000 for the critical remarks of his
agent, the apparel company that Sprewell endorses, And 1, picked up
the tab.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Sprewell's reason for failing to communicate with the
Knicks this week, it is doubtful it will appease a team that grew
weary of the distraction his disappearance caused. But, as coach
Jeff Van Gundy pointed out, pro athletes are not your average
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few employees, except on Wall Street and in professional
sports, make more money than the people they supposedly work for,''
Van Gundy said. ``I'm just saying we can't apply real-world logic
to the NBA. I'm not going to get into a war of words. Discipline is
important. He's important to our team. Disciplinary actions are
obviously going to take place. What I want to do more than anything
is to get it resolved so we can get on with the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks would like to get on with the sleek style of play
Sprewell was such a big part of last season. But in his absence,
the team has been unable to experiment with Sprewell and Allan
Houston in a big backcourt. The team also has not had a chance to
get in the same comfort zone it had as it made its run to the
finals last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing much different than last year,'' said Van
Gundy, whose team's first exhibition game is Tuesday. ``But in
preparation for the season, we have to start strong. Our guys have
to be focused on the first 13 games where 10 of them are on the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are already going to be undermanned without Patrick
Ewing and, potentially, Chris Dudley. Ewing has said he will not
play until the tendinitis in his Achilles' tendon has eased, and
Dudley cannot run, because of a knee he sprained this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really thinking in terms of lineups,'' Van Gundy said.
``I'm just thinking about how to put our team together so we can
play well right off the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell is an integral part of that plan. But his disappearance
this week has left the team in a bad position. He was always a bit
eccentric in his ways, but Sprewell's recent behavior has left some
question about whether the team wants to invest up to $70 million
in him with a contract extension. Throughout this week, his
commitment to the organization has been suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discipline is an important part of any team,'' Van Gundy said.
``It's really an important part of this team. This is not about
making an example of anyone. But you do the right thing. You do
what you're supposed to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
