<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCADV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALIOTTI TRIES TO DOWNPLAY RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Oregon defensive coordinator Nick Aliotti isn't
sure what he'll feel when he enters the Rose Bowl this evening to
face his former team, but pain and anger are good bets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kept my feelings at bay,'' Aliotti said. ``They probably
still haven't gone away, how I feel about the situation. With time,
I'm sure they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliotti was UCLA's maligned defensive coordinator last season _
the man who oversaw the nation's 99th-ranked defense, the man
criticized publicly by Bruins coach Bob Toledo, the man UCLA fans
blame for the collapse at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo eventually asked Aliotti to return for the 1999 season,
although he wanted Aliotti to simplify his intricate system and
tweak it to UCLA's personnel. Despite Toledo's offer, Aliotti
sensed his support and credibility had disappeared. When the Oregon
job opened _ Aliotti and Ducks head coach Mike Bellotti are close
friends _ he bolted.
</P>
<P>
   His relationship with Toledo is damaged, perhaps beyond repair.
Both men have downplayed tonight's meeting, saying it's a game
between Oregon and UCLA, not Toledo and Aliotti, not a former boss
and his embarrassed assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Believing what they say is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be frank about this,'' Toledo said. ``Nick Aliotti was
not fired from this staff. He left on his own accord. That's all
I'll say about it this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliotti claims he has prepared for UCLA as he prepared for USC.
That, too, seems to contradict the laws of human emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't used, haven't said anything about me being at
UCLA,'' Aliotti said. ``I'm sure the players know it, but I haven't
approached it any differently. It's been a matter-of-fact week.''
</P>
<P>
   More intriguing than the Aliotti-Toledo matchup is Aliotti
against UCLA offensive coordinator Al Borges: They are second
cousins and close friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't given this much thought,'' Borges said. ``I'm
trying to get in his head, just like I try to do with every guy.
But I feel bad it didn't work out for him here, both for him and
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Borges grew up in Salinas, Aliotti in Pittsburg. They were
childhood acquaintances but did not become close until adulthood.
(They missed each other as Oregon assistants by one season.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really Al against me,'' Aliotti said. ``It's the
Oregon defense against the Bruin offense, but I think I could beat
Al in a footrace.''
</P>
<P>
   How will the coaching triangle affect tonight's game? Aliotti
knows UCLA's offense and its personnel, but he won't know the
called play. UCLA knows Aliotti's coaching technique but not the
Ducks' system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense is not what (Aliotti) ran here,'' said Toledo,
who was Oregon's offensive coordinator from 1983-88. ``But he knows
our personnel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0392 </DOCNO>
