<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE'S FUTURE AS A YANKEE IS UNCLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBA-YANKEES) 
(mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ David Cone ponders the future of his baseball
career, knows there is the sort of lingering uncertainty that he
had hoped to finally shed after signing with the Yankees, and grows
exasperated. Cone knows that he could be pitching for the Yankees
for the last time, knows it so well that he brought up the
possibility Friday and then rambled on about it for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   There was a mixture of anger and angst and confusion and
comprehension in Cone's voice as he talked about his failure to
deal with the likelihood that he will not return to the Yankees
next season. While general manager Brian Cashman stressed that the
Yankees had not made any decisions for 2000, Cone has heard enough
speculation about his precarious future that he spoke like a player
who feels he may be done in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, more than ever, I realize this is a unique opportunity,
it may be the last one,'' Cone said. ``I've said before that it
might be my last chance to pitch in the playoffs. ... This year, I
think I can honestly say that this may be my last chance to pitch
in the playoffs with the Yankees. Now, more than ever, I realize
that.''
</P>
<P>
   As Cone sat near the entrance to the visitors' clubhouse at the
Ballpark in Arlington, he was still trying to understand everything
he was uttering. He signed a one-year, $8 million contract last
November, forgoing the opportunities for a multiyear deal with
another team, and has long professed a strong desire to finish his
career with the Yankees. Friday, Cone retracted his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that I was pretty idealistic in making those
statements,'' said Cone, who will start Game 4 of the division
series on Sunday night, if there is one. ``Now I'm much more
realistic and understand anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have budgetary concerns involving Derek Jeter,
Mariano Rivera, Andy Pettitte and Jorge Posada, all of whom are
guaranteed to receive raises next year, and with Paul O'Neill's
$6.5 million option likely to be exercised. They would also like to
inject Ed Yarnall, a promising and inexpensive left-hander, into
the rotation. These are some of the reasons Cone, who would
obviously want a raise, too, feels expendable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about whether I feel like I still fit in and whether it's
still a good fit and whether the organization feels like they might
be able to plug my spot with someone else,'' Cone said. ``There are
a lot of variables involved.''
</P>
<P>
   It was shocking to hear Cone, the player who is more influential
than anyone else in the clubhouse, wonder if he still fits in with
the Yankees. Cone was told that the remarks made it seem apparent
that an official in the organization had said something to him
about the direction the Yankees were headed in 2000. When Cone was
asked if this was true, he paused, looked at the carpet and said:
``Um, I'd rather not get into that. I'll leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman seemed surprised and disappointed that Cone did not
express these concerns to him and vowed to meet with the pitcher to
remind him how critical he is to the Yankees. The general manager
said he had given Cone no insight about the muddled future, but
almost all of team's decisions emanate from Tampa, Fla., anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to know where you're going to be working and
what you're doing,'' Cashman said. ``Since he's been so superhuman,
maybe we've been a little guilty of taking him for granted and not
realizing that he needs to be told how we feel about him.''
</P>
<P>
   After Cone tossed his perfect game against the Montreal Expos on
July 18, he was 10-4 with a 2.65 earned run average and said that
he was ``the best pitcher in the league this side of Pedro''
Martinez. Cone wondered how far he could have plummeted since then
and blamed himself for allowing his emotions to influence his
performances. He went 2-5 with a 4.28 ERA after the perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   Cone earned his reputation as a mercenary who bounced from team
to team, but now it seemed as if he was trying to say that he
wanted to remain with the Yankees and did not want to start over
with another team.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees do not re-sign Cone, the Mets and the Orioles are
two teams that would be interested in the 36-year-old. Cone has
indicated to friends that he would seriously consider returning to
the other New York team, meaning that he might finish his career
with the Mets instead of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't rule it out,'' Cone said. ``At this point, I have
to put all these issues to the off-season. I got to try and just
put them away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
