<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1500 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TEX-EDUCAITON-COX     10-08 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-EDUCAITON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two banks, not one, will handle $20 billion school fund
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The State Board of Education's decision to hire
two banks instead of one to manage the $20 billion Permanent School
Fund could cost taxpayers $1.2 million in interest, according to a
Texas Education Agency analysis.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the 15-member board _ ignoring the advice of
financial experts who some members argue should be relied on more _
voted in May and July to hire two banks to oversee the funds
instead of a single bank recommended by the TEA financial staff.
</P>
<P>
   While the $1.2 million in potential earnings is tiny when
compared with the $700 million that the fund generates annually,
the action suggests another misstep by the board and its governance
of the school fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly adds to the concern that the board continues to
shoot itself in the foot,'' said Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount
Pleasant, chairman of the budget-writing Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff is among lawmakers who are considering replacing the
elected board with an appointed one, in part because of recent
decisions the board has made regarding the school fund. Ratliff
promised that his committee will pay special attention to the
Permanent School Fund in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   State Street Bank of Boston was hired to be the custodian of the
$20 billion Permanent School Fund and Citibank was hired as the
securities lender for the fund.
</P>
<P>
   A custodian is responsible for overseeing a fund's assets while
a securities lender oversees loans by one broker to another.
Typically, banks or financial institutions discount their fees when
they are hired as both the custodian and securities lender.
</P>
<P>
   Bundling those services in the bank recommended by the TEA staff
_ Northern Trust _ would have generated $5.5 million for the school
trust fund after the bank deducted its handling fees, records show.
That is $1.2 million more than what the TEA staff projected the
fund would earn by splitting services between Citibank and State
Street, or about $4.3 million after fees.
</P>
<P>
   State Street was chosen by the board because it offered a bigger
discount than Northern Trust in its bid to be custodian, TEA
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank was ranked last by the TEA financial staff among the
four financial institutions that bid for the combined custodial and
securities lending business; Northern Trust Company of Chicago was
ranked first, records show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, we are paying a lot more,'' said Will Davis, a
Democratic board member from Austin who opposed hiring separate
banks and who has been a dissenting voice on recent board decisions
regarding the massive school fund. ``That's because we have two
firms performing duties instead of one firm performing duties.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Board Member Richard Watson, a Republican from Gorman,
voted against Northern Trust because he said he was not convinced
that Northern's bid was more beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not necessarily convinced Northern Trust would have ended
up providing more money to the fund,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   The board's action follows several controversial decisions it
has made in recent months regarding the school trust fund,
including hiring a financial consultant who was fighting fraud
charges by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission. A federal
judge later cleared Russell W. Stein, senior vice president for
Everen Securities' Houston office, of all charges.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Attorney General John Cornyn said he still is
reviewing a request by State Board of Education Chairman Chase
Untermeyer to investigate the board's hiring of a dozen private
investment firms, which manage about $7 billion of the school
fund's investments.
</P>
<P>
   Some board members say that six of the firms have misdirected
the public's money into unauthorized accounts or tried to win
contracts via gifts to board members or staff.
</P>
<P>
   A review of the May and July board meeting minutes shows that
two key members, Republicans Bob Offutt and David Bradley,
persuaded their colleagues to split services rather than combining
services at one, as the TEA financial staff recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Offutt _ a San Antonio dentist _ chairs the board's finance
committee, which makes recommendations about the Permanent School
Fund. Bradley, a Beaumont insurance agent, is vice chairman of the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Offutt and Bradley were unavailable for comment Friday. But
board minutes and other documents show that the decision to reject
Northern Trust was based in part on information provided by
Austinite Brian Borowski, an informal adviser to Offutt and Bradley
who has financial management experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Borowski) was invited by some of my colleagues to counter
the mathematical analysis of the (TEA) staff, and that persuaded a
majority to go with Citibank,'' Untermeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the TEA staff analysis, Northern Trust was the
second-lowest bidder for the combined custodial and lending
securities services. But the staff preferred it over the lowest
bidder, Citibank, because Northern's technology and accounting
services were deemed superior to Citibank's.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Untermeyer said the TEA financial staff was
dissatisfied with the level of service Citibank supplied as the
custodian bank to the school trust fund. Citibank, with a large
corporate division in San Antonio, has been both the custodian and
the securities lender for the school trust fund since 1995. The TEA
staff was satisfied with Citibank's performance in securities
lending.
</P>
<P>
   A. Phillips Brooks writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
