<DOCNO> NYT19991008.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1502 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FBO-STEARNS-NFL-COX     10-08 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-STEARNS-NFL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Players did not invest with Stearns, attorney says
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (a) General news and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Jason Spencer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A Los Angeles attorney who invested $5.5 million
with Austin, Texas resident Brian Russell Stearns disputes federal
authorities' claims that the money may have come from NFL players.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a DFJ investment and no NFL players were
involved,'' Robert ``Bobby'' Caron, an attorney and one-time player
agent now working with DFJ Italia, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Caron said the money he wired to Stearns' bank account last May
belonged to him and a small group of private investors, including
DFJ Italia Chief Financial Officer Robert Winter.
</P>
<P>
   DFJ Italia, in Irvine, Calif., specializes in making financial
investments for professional athletes and produces movies for cable
television stations, Winter said.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns promised the investors a substantial payoff in a short
amount of time, Winter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He explained to us a bond deal he had and how we could make
100 percent of our money in 30 days,'' Winter said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI and Internal Revenue Service agents arrested Stearns at his
$2.2 million Lake Austin home last month and charged him with
defrauding a Georgia investor of $3.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Through his attorney, Laird Palmer of Mason, Stearns has denied
any criminal wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   In his sworn affidavit used to obtain the search warrant for
Stearns' home, IRS agent James Neff accused Stearns of operating a
scheme in which Stearns would use money from one investor to pay
other investors, creating the impression he was successfully
investing their money in secret bond markets. As collateral for the
investments, Stearns created fraudulent bonds and bank documents
indicating he had access to millions of dollars, the document
states.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Stearns defrauded investors of more than $31 million
from March 1998 through last July and spent their money on his
home, a pair of jet airplanes, a helicopter and other expensive
items, according to the document.
</P>
<P>
   In his sworn statement, Neff wrote that he ``could not find any
instances where Stearns invested the money he received from
investors into the type of securities and/or bonds that he
guaranteed the investors. Stearns did use the money to purchase
substantial personal assets. . . . In many instances, as soon as
Stearns deposited investor funds into his checking account, he
would expend the funds on personal items.''
</P>
<P>
   Neff added that he had not determined where the $5.5 million
Caron sent Stearns came from, but stated that he ``believes that
the source of the money is coming from NFL players.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI began looking into Caron and DFJ Italia's business
dealings when Lawrence Sweeney, an NFL senior investigator, told
them several current and former members of the Arizona Cardinals
and Cleveland Browns had put money into a DFJ Italia investment
that guaranteed a 24 percent monthly return, the federal document
states. Players who invested with DFJ Italia include Browns
offensive lineman Lomas Brown, Cardinals defensive tackle Eric
Swann, tight end Johnny McWilliams and Larry Centers, a running
back now playing with the Washington Redskins, according to the
document.
</P>
<P>
   Other Cardinals players who considered investing with DFJ Italia
were receiver Chad Carpenter and retired offensive lineman Duval
Love, the document states. Love now works for DFJ Italia soliciting
players to invest with the company, Winter said.
</P>
<P>
   Winter said he met Stearns last May and was immediately
impressed with the 29-year-old's extravagant jet-setting lifestyle
after spotting him in a Sunset Strip nightclub with Hollywood stars
Henry Winkler and Oscar winner Cuba Gooding Jr. Winter said he also
spotted Stearns at Hugh Hefner's Playboy mansion.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in New York earlier this week indicted
Stearns on a charge that he conspired to commit wire fraud to
obtain $26 million from a pair of foreign investors. In 1994,
Stearns pleaded guilty to grand theft by stealing about $20,000
from members of his Maryland National Guard unit and was placed on
five years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities additionally are looking into the
possibility that Stearns may have defrauded more than 100 residents
of the Hill Country town of Brady of as much as $5 million in his
alleged investment scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Spencer writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
