<HEADER>
A1504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-INDIANS-BAINES-NY     10-08 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-BAINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIETLY AND CONSISTENTLY, BAINES JUST KEEPS HITTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There are plenty of guys in major-league uniforms who
are older than Harold Baines, but most are coaches and managers.
Only 10 players are older than Baines, and only three are still
around for the postseason. And few players of any age are hitting
the baseball any better than Baines in this first round of the
playoffs. Life might not begin at 40, but Baines' career is
continuing at that age at a remarkably consistent pace.
</P>
<P>
   In seven at-bats in two games as designated hitter for the
Cleveland Indians, Baines has three hits, one of them a home run.
He helped the Indians win both games, and they can clinch their
best-of-5 division series over the Boston Red Sox when they meet on
Saturday in Fenway Park. Should the Sox extend the series, game
four would be here on Sunday and game five would be in Cleveland on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older you get, the more you appreciate all the hard work
that it takes to get to the playoffs,'' said Baines, who was
acquired in a trade with Baltimore on Aug. 27. ``In my case, I'm
coming over from a team that struggled most of the year, so I'm
very happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning of game two on Thursday at Jacobs Field,
Baines hit Bret Saberhagen's first pitch for a three-run home run
to increase Cleveland's lead to 6-1, the decisive moment of the
game. Saberhagen said it was a good pitch, a fastball low and away.
Baines, called a professional hitter by teammates and rivals, said
he was looking for a pitch in that zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, you just learn certain situations what type of
pitch you think you're going to get,'' Baines said. ``That means
you are going to get it 80 percent of the time. I'm a zone
hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hart, the Indians' general manager, knew how Baines hit
when he got him for two minor-league pitchers. He is approaching
milestones of 400 home runs and 3,000 hits. But Hart said he was
also attracted by Baines' subtle and intangible qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to be in a situation where you need a big hit,'' Hart
said. ``Some guys like it, some guys don't. This guy wants it. You
know the other team doesn't want to have to pitch to him in a tight
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an opinion shared by Sandy Alomar, the Cleveland catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I saw him come to the plate, I go, `Oh, man, here
comes this dude again,''' Alomar said. ``He's so hard to get out.
He's a very, very, very good hitter. When you have a Harold Baines
on your team, you feel a sense of relaxation.''
</P>
<P>
   A left-handed batter, Baines hit .312 in the regular season with
25 home runs and 103 RBIs, close to career bests in each category.
His greater value may come in the next round, if the Indians and
Yankees advance to play for the pennant. Yankee Stadium's
right-field fence is an inviting target for left-handed batters
with power.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Elias Sports Bureau, Baines has batted .386 in
his career against David Cone and .317 against Roger Clemens.
Against Yankees pitching over two decades, Baines has a .286
average with 27 home runs and 119 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Yankees were a factor in his transfer to Cleveland,
Baines said, ``I think that is a great part of the reason I am
here.'' And Hart fought back a smile as he said the Yankees were in
the ``back of my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates and managers speak of how Baines' personality affects
the mood in a clubhouse. Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove said
Baines ``brings a unique professionalism to our ball club'' because
he carries himself the same way when things are going good or bad.
``He is always on an even keel,'' Hargrove said. ``I don't want to
say mild mannered, but very consistent. Our younger players see
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar, the 33-year-old catcher, said Baines is ``not a rah-rah
guy'' but one who ``speaks the truth'' and is willing to share his
wisdom when asked.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thome, the 29-year-old first baseman who has two home runs
this series, said Baines' ``bat does a lot more talking than he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His approach to the game is great,'' Thome said. ``He's a guy
that really never shows much emotion. And when he hit that home
run, I saw the smile on his face when he crossed home plate and
that was great. That was awesome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
