<HEADER>
A1513 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-SPRINT-BRAND-KAN &LR;      10-08 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-BRAND-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE NAMES ARE THE REALM OF THE ACQUIRER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When Bernard J. Ebbers, William T. Esrey and
top lieutenants from MCI WorldCom and Sprint Corp. sat down to
hammer out what to call their soon-to-be merged companies, it was a
brief debate.
</P>
<P>
   Ebbers, chief executive of MCI WorldCom, and Esrey, chief
executive of Sprint, decided the new name would be WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of corporate branding experts from around the United
States mostly lamented the choice, including Ira Bachrach, who
tagged the new moniker pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want it to mean the world of communications or worldwide
communications,'' said Bachrach, president of San Francisco-based
NameLab Inc. ``But it's just a dumb word that doesn't mean anything
_ it's just a name, like Fred.''
</P>
<P>
   What Ebbers and his team should have done, according to Bachrach
and other branding experts, was set aside their egos and call the
new company Sprint. That name has energy, vitality, speed, even
humanness.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be unprecedented for the conqueror to take on the
conquered's name. Earlier this year, for example, NationsBank
completed its purchase of Bank of America and then retained the
better-known Bank of America name.
</P>
<P>
   Besides settling on a corporate name, merging companies have a
myriad of other marketing decisions to make, including which
products to market under which names.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Sprint's product line uses the Sprint name, such as
Sprint PCS and its local and long-distance services. MCI,
meanwhile, markets products both under its name and others that
don't mention MCI, such as its 10-10-321 dial-around service.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing experts called Sprint one of the strongest and most
distinctive brand names in the telecommunications industry, an
industry populated with ``techs,'' ``teles'' and ``coms.''
</P>
<P>
   A study in the summer by International Data Corp., based in
Framingham, Mass., showed Sprint the second most-recognized name in
the telecommunications industry, behind only powerhouse brand AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   That same survey found that MCI, the one-time No. 2 brand name
in the industry, had dropped to 11th after it was attached to
WorldCom. WorldCom bought MCI last year.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, said Tim Kiersted, senior analyst for
International Data who is based in Austin, Texas, WorldCom vaulted
from 33rd most-recognized to 11th once it married MCI.
</P>
<P>
   Kiersted said it was likely the Sprint and the MCI product
brands would drop in rankings once they were no longer attached to
their current corporate names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I have to wonder how they're going to build in and
blend their portfolio of names under this scenario,'' Kiersted
said. ``The question is do they try to continue to build them as
separate but strong brand names?''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the issues Sprint and WorldCom will talk about once
the Department of Justice, the Federal Communications Commission
and other regulators bless their union, said Tom Weigman, Sprint's
senior vice president, consumer market strategy and communications.
Completing the merger could take a year to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Already, however, the two have struck several agreements,
including one in which MCI WorldCom has the rights to sell Sprint
PCS service under the WorldCom name.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Weigman is sure of, based on comments from Esrey and
Ebbers, is that the Sprint and MCI names will live on in some form.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have both stated their intent to use all the brand
names,'' Weigman said. ``What we're thinking about now is how we
might want to approach those issues....We have a number of thoughts
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Weigman was hesitant to talk about marketing plans, because the
two companies must wait for regulatory approval before discussing
these issues together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually anything is conceivable,'' Weigman said.
``Accelerating growth and what makes compelling strategic sense at
that point is what will drive the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom marketing executives could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The company will have several models to follow as it works
through those issues, said Steve Rivkin, a corporate branding
expert based in Glen Rock, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   There's the GE model, in which most every part of the company,
from $2 light bulbs to $2 million jet engines, are GE-branded.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Procter &AMP; Gamble model, which has thousands of
products, none of which is called Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   In between there's the 3M approach, where some products such as
transparent tape have the 3M brand and others such as Post-it notes
are stand-alone products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me the Sprint and MCI names should be preserved
and used as fighting brands against existing strong competition,''
Rivkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Bachrach is leery of any plan that would use a bunch of
different brand names under one corporate umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you want to maintain more than one identity?''
Bachrach said. ``Instead of being one very large thing, it divides
you into two smaller things in a world where arguably, the larger
you are the better the vendor you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bachrach even theorizes that the Sprint name would have had more
clout on Wall Street and, more important, on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Rivkin also says it is sad that WorldCom executives chucked the
Sprint name from the corporate holding company. But he's not
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Rivkin recalls one incident in which the company being bought
insisted its name be retained. The acquirer said if that happened,
it would lower its bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Do you want to tell your shareholders they're
getting less for their stock but their name is being preserved or
do you want the money?' '' Rivkin recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a righteous world, yes, the new company probably should
have been called Sprint,'' Rivkin said. ``But given the reality of
corporate egos, they probably didn't give it more than a
milliseconds' worth of thought. History is written by the winner _
the acquirer decides.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
