<HEADER>
A1518 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PINOCHET-EXTRADITE-1S     10-08 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-EXTRADITE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGLISH MAGISTRATE SAYS PINOCHET CAN BE EXTRADITED TO SPAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS reaction in Chile in 5th graf)  (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A London court ruled Friday that Gen. Augusto Pinochet
of Chile can be extradited to Spain to stand trial on torture and
conspiracy charges.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy chief magistrate of the Bow Street Magistrates Court,
Ronald Bartle, said that ``all the conditions are in place'' for
the transfer of the former Chilean dictator from London to Madrid
to face one charge of conspiracy to torture and 34 charges of the
torture of individual Chileans.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been a number of dramatic court decisions since
Pinochet's arrest a year ago, Friday's was the first to be based on
the crimes he is accused of rather than simply on the legality of
his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet was excused from appearing in the packed chamber
because of his failing health. But in a defiant statement read by
Clive Nicholls, his chief lawyer, he protested his innocence and
said he was the victim of a political conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   In Chile, rights advocates and relatives of Pinochet-era victims
celebrated while Pinochet's allies expressed bitter disappointment,
but the country's reaction to the ruling was generally muted. There
were small competing marches around Santiago, but they were
peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers have 15 days to decide whether to appeal to the High
Court, and in the likely event that they do so, the case could
continue on through many more months of legal maneuvering and end
up returning to England's highest tribunal, the Law Lords of the
House of Lords, where it has already been through two extended
judgments.
</P>
<P>
   Even after all the appeals have been exhausted, Home Secretary
Jack Straw must make a final decision on whether Pinochet, 83,
should be sent to Spain. That decision, too, is subject to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's lawyers declined to say what their next course of
action would be, but Fernando Barros, a Chilean professor who leads
the general's support group in London, said there would be an
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In getting Pinochet excused from court Friday, his British
doctor testified Wednesday that he had suffered two small strokes
in September and that he was disoriented and ``giddy'' much of the
time. The state of his health is not an issue during the appeal
process, but it will be a critically germane one if and when the
time comes to determine his fitness to go to Spain and stand trial.
One option open to Straw would be freeing Pinochet on compassionate
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bartle on Friday stressed that his ruling and the four days of
hearings held in the court in September were focused not on guilt
or innocence but only on whether the extradition papers were in
order and the charges were extraditable offenses under British law.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It cannot be too strongly emphasized that these proceedings
are not conducted for the purpose of deciding the guilt or
innocence of Senator Pinochet in respect of the allegations made
against him,'' he said in his decision. `` Nor would a finding on
my part, that the request of Spain should be complied with, be any
indication whatever that I have formed a view as to his guilt or
innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, who gave himself the title of senator for life in an
effort to grant himself immunity from prosecution, said in a
statement: ``I declare that I am not guilty of the crimes of which
I am accused.'' He continued: ``Spain has not produced a single
piece of evidence which shows that I am guilty. Not only that, I
believe that Spain has not properly investigated any of the these
crimes and Spain does not even have jurisdiction to try me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said Spain was acting ``in violation of the sovereignty of
Chile'' and that ``It has long been clear that my extradition is
politically motivated and is being pursued clearly for political
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Alun Jones, the British lawyer representing the Spanish
government, said he had nothing to say in response to the Pinochet
claims, telling the court that there were already enough ``strident
voices'' surrounding the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a rally in Pinochet's behalf at the Conservative Party
conference in Blackpool on Wednesday night, former Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher argued that he had been the victim of a
``judicial kidnap'' in circumstances ``which would do credit to a
police state.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Pinochet supporter, the former Conservative Chancellor
of the Exchequer Norman Lamont, argued that the British
government's longtime contention that the arrest and detention of
Pinochet was a judicial and not a political matter had been
undermined by a comment by Prime Minister Tony Blair in which he
called the former Chilean dictator ``unspeakable.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the Labor party convention in Bournemouth 11
days ago excoriating the opposition Conservatives as being out of
touch, Blair called them ``the party of fox-hunting, Pinochet and
hereditary peers _ the uneatable, the unspeakable and the
unelectable.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressing the point Friday, Barros said Blair's scornful comment
had been an unacceptable intervention in the case. ``That makes
this null and void,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's judgment, Bartle turned aside defense lawyers'
objections to the submission of the 35 cases outlined by Baltasar
Garzon, the Spanish judge who assembled the case against Pinochet.
The original charges against Pinochet at the time of his arrest in
London last Oct. 16 included allegations of kidnapping, murder and
genocide in the disappearances of more than 3,000 people dating to
1973, the year Pinochet seized power in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A decision by the Law Lords in March drastically reduced the
number of cases and limited the relevant period to after December
1988, the date when Britain adopted the international torture
convention making torture abroad a crime punishable in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   That meant that only two of the original charges, the conspiracy
count and a single torture allegation, survived from the original
extradition request. Over the summer Garzon added 33 new cases to
the application, and in Friday's ruling Bartle approved their
inclusion. ``The further material, objected to by the defense, is
in my view supplementary to and in amplification of the conduct
alleged against Senator Pinochet, namely his involvement in acts of
torture and conspiracy to commit such acts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision also appeared to give prosecutors some leeway to
get around that strict date. They would be able to cite
disappearances of people in the 1970s on the basis that these acts
were undertaken to commit ``mental torture'' on relatives and
survivors that continued into the period after 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not this was intended by the regime of Senator
Pinochet is in my view a matter of fact for the trial court,''
Bartle said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors also gained the right to introduce evidence of
events before the crucial date as part of their effort to prove
that Pinochet was guilty of a long-running conspiracy to torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magistrate's ruling will allow the Spanish prosecutors to
show that Pinochet created a repressive state apparatus that relied
on torture, that he was fully aware that torture was being
practiced systematically and that he never once punished anyone who
committed torture,'' said Reed Brody, advocacy director of Human
Rights Watch in New York, in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet has been living in a London suburb under police guard
since leaving a hospital in December where he was recuperating from
back surgery. He was arrested at the request of Garzon, who made
his case in the course of studying atrocities committed during the
so-called dirty wars in Latin America in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The case has wound its way through English courts and already
secured a valuable legal victory for the human rights movement _
the finding that former heads of state do not enjoy immunity from
arrest and prosecution for crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
