<HEADER>
A1522 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     10-08 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, IT WORKS FOR THE CUBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A gavel crashes down as the most important people
in the Los Angeles Dodgers front office take their seats at a
blond-wood conference table.
</P>
<P>
   ``This postseason meeting of the marketing and promotions
department will please come to order. Bertleson, kindly remove the
Diamondbacks cap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a difficult year for all of us. The team
finished in third place and the organization took a few hits from
the letter writers and talk-show callers. To put it bluntly, fans
don't love the Dodgers as much as they used to. Our challenge is to
devise an advertising strategy to win them back, lest we start next
season with a bunch of empty suites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Graziano wouldn't like a bunch of empty suites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Um, Bertleson, you missed a memo during your recent vacation.
I'll fill you in later. Anyway, let's go around the table and share
our ideas for a 2000 advertising plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got one. How about this for a slogan? `The Dodgers: We Do
Our Best for You 161 Times a Season.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``The season is !ital!162 games.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that. Now tell the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got one. `The Dodgers: We Spell Fun
G-R-U-D-Z-I-E-L-A-N-E-K!' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a mouthful. But I'll write it down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got one: `Dodgers Baseball: You'll Come for the Hot Dogs,
You'll Stay for the Beer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different, anyway. Parlato, do you have any thoughts?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How about: `What Else Are You Going to Watch, Our Pro Football
Team?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, people, I think we're on the wrong track here. Perhaps
we should think in more general terms about an overall approach
instead of trying to write a catchy slogan. If we come up with the
right !ital!message, the words will fall into place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir?''
</P>
<P>
   ``McGrotto, what's in that box?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A few items that might suggest an approach.''
</P>
<P>
   He holds up a new gray T-shirt bearing the words, ``Chicago
Cubs, World Series Champions, 1908.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They sell this at Wrigley Field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very funny, McGrotto, but what does it have to do with
the Dodgers?''
</P>
<P>
   McGrotto holds up an orange-and-black lapel pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Croix de Candlestick _ these Latin words say, `I
Came, I Saw, I Survived.' The Giants used to hand them out to fans
who stayed to the end of extra-inning night games. It was their way
of poking fun at their own ballpark. Fans ate it up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was clever of the Giants. But McGrotto, we're the
Dodgers!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bear with me. Who recognizes this book?''
</P>
<P>
   He holds up an old, dog-eared paperback.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Jonathan Livingston Seagull'? '' someone guesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. It's called `Can't Anybody Here Play This Game?' It's
about the 1962 Mets and it was a bestseller. People loved to read
about the foibles of a last-place ballclub. Think about all the
books written about the Red Sox _ `Curse of the Bambino,' `One Out
Away,' `One Strike Away,' `One Grounder Away,' `One Warning-Track
Fly Ball Away' . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``McGrotto, will you please get to the point?''
</P>
<P>
   He props up a black-and-white publicity mug shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it's Lou Grant!'' someone says fondly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it's Joe Garagiola, and he parlayed funny stories
about a thoroughly mediocre catching career with some of history's
worst teams into popularity as a sportscaster, game-show host and
author. Anyone see what I'm getting at here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That we should sell more T-shirts, buttons and paperbacks?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not exactly. My point is that in baseball, you don't have to
be a winner to be popular with the public. The game has a long
tradition of lovable losers. The Dodgers were lovable losers back
in Brooklyn and now people yearn for the days of `Dem Bums.' The
Cubs sell out!''
</P>
<P>
   ``So you're saying we should market the Dodgers as lovable
losers?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll never be a better time. We could give away `Wait Till
Next Year' shirts on opening day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does McGrotto's idea strike anybody as too weird?''
</P>
<P>
   Bertleson speaks up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only problem I see is that our baseball people could mess up
our whole strategy by fielding a winning team next year.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, everybody has a good laugh and goes to lunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-99 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
